<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARKET (Moved in ``f'' category &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-ASSESS (Undated) _ A news analysis on what is going on in
the stock market. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Three graphics have been sent to NYT graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-RESPONSE (Washington) _ Can there be, and should there
be, a coordinated international response to the widening
international economic crisis? The Clinton administration tried to
protect the American economy from the crisis in Asia with a series
of firewalls, but the Russian crisis broke through. Now the
strategy seems to be changing. The favored option of the moment
seems to be reducing interest rates both here and abroad. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-RUSSIA (Undated) _ Ripples from Russia's economic crisis
are rapidly spreading through other world financial markets, as
Citicorp, Bankers Trust, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Barclays and
Nomura Securities joined the growing list of companies reporting
heavy losses on their Russian business. By Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-FED (Washington) _ When faced with a Latin America that
could no longer pay its debts during the summer of 1982, the
Federal Reserve cast aside its tight-money policy and cut interest
rates. When faced with a stomach-churning stock market drop in
October 1987, the Fed acted quickly to pump more money into the
financial system. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has be
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OBRIEN-NOVEL (New York) _ The tortures of Tim O'Brien, who hasa
new novel coming out. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-BIRCH (Hollywood) _ The screenwriter Mark Steven Johnson
tlks about ``Simon Birch.'' By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd on sex and money in the
news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BROWNS (Cleveland) _ The awarding of the Cleveland Browns
franchise is a unique bazaar: an auction for what is fated to be
the highest price ever for a sports team, one that could double the
$311 million paid this year for the Los Angeles Dodgers. The scope
of the bidding orgy _ featuring millionaires and billionaires,
stars like Bill Cosby and Jim Brown, Cleveland's great fullback,
and bidding rationales like civic duty and a pained conscience _
captures many of the dimensions and dynamics of modern sports
business. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Open: Steffi Graf makes her return. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-HUDSON-VALLEY (New York) _ The Hudson Valley as breadbasket
for the city: Over the past 20 years, the area has undergone an
agricultural renaissance _ small farms are producing everything
from cattle to artichokes, peaches to heirloom potatoes _ and it is
all because of the city's demand for premium local ingredients for
chefs and greenmarkets. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT4,5) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-HUDSON-RESTAURANT (Undated) _ For 30 years, Sophie and Joseph
Parker have been the Hudson Valley's best-kept secret, running a
little restaurant with the attention and perfection that
distinguisihes the best in the French countryside. By William
Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-HIDDEN-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ The annoying trend of
restaurants that have no signs or any other way of telling that
they are restaurants. They're all in bleak places _ Bond Street, 2
Seven 7, Lot 61, Moomba _ so not it's not bad enough that you have
to stumble down a dark, slightly menacing street, but then you have
to look for light shining out the cracks around the black curtains.
By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT8,9) have been sent to NYT photo clients.).
</P>
<P>
   NY-WINE-PRIZE (Undated) _ A 1997 Johannisberg riesling made by
Chateau LaFayette Reneau, a boutique winery in Hector, N.Y., on the
southeastern side of Seneca Lake, has been chosen the No. 1 wine in
New York State.
</P>
<P>
   GRILL (Undated) _ On the grill: After a summer's worth of
burgers, three terrific alternatives: Vietnamese ground pork
patties, tingling with chilies and aromatic with lime leaves and
lemon grass and wrapped in lettuce leaves, Turkish ground lamb
laced with cumin, and Southwestern turkey burgers with chipotle
pepper. parsley and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   RATATOUILLE (Undated) _ The long list of ingredients in a
typical recipe for ratatouille or the vowel-clogged French word
itself? Actually, the preparation and the pronounciation share the
same rule: keep the components distinct. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
