<HEADLINE>
UCLA FRESHMAN CATCHES ON FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Freshman receiver Jon Dubravac's surprising
three-month climb may culminate with a spot on the Bruins' depth
chart.
</P>
<P>
   A Denver native, Dubravac spent the summer in Westwood, working
with strength coach Kevin Yoxall, playing catch with quarterback
Cade McNown and learning the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   The results are apparent: Dubravac is one of the few freshmen
ready for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here over the summer helped me 100-fold,'' he said. ``It
was the opportunity to run around and get a feel for the offense
and the routes and what I need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Mullen High in Denver, Dubravac was one of UCLA's
least-publicized recruits. He had scholarship offers from 20
schools, including Michigan, Northwestern and Washington. But with
five returning receivers, the Bruins expected Dubravac to redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they can't keep him off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good possibility he'll play as a freshman,'' coach
Bob Toledo said. ``We're very impressed with his athletic ability
and he has less drops than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubravac is the third-string split end, behind Brad Melsby and
Brian Poli-Dixon. He may spend time as the backup slot (third)
receiver, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very important to me to play (this season),'' he
said. ``There's a big difference between redshirting to get a feel
for what's going on, and the opportunity to do it. If you can play
immediately, it gets you on the fast track.''
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt status: Injuries and performance may dictate otherwise,
but it appears at least five of the 24 true freshmen will play.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback DeShaun Foster, nose guard Ken Kocher and linebacker
Robert Thomas are expected to contribute immediately. A sprained
ankle has slowed Kocher's progress, and Thomas is playing with a
heavily wrapped broken hand that hinders his tackling.
</P>
<P>
   Dubravac and cornerback Julius Williams are improving rapidly
and may play. Heralded cornerback Lovell Houston, another Denver
native, has not practiced because of a strained quad and probably
will redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Either guard Mike Saffer or offensive tackle Blake Worley will
play, but not both, Toledo said. A shoulder injury has limited
Saffer's practice time this week.
</P>
<P>
   Paying respects: Fred Andrews, an offensive tackle for UCLA in
1952, died Saturday in Bakersfield of an apparent heart attack. He
was 65. Services will be held Thursday at 1:30 p.m. in Church of
the Recessional at Forest Lawn in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Walendy update: Starting fullback Craig Walendy (allergic
reaction to bug bites) probably will not be ready in time for Texas
on Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost past that point,'' Toledo said. ``It would be a
bonus if he's there, but we're not planning on him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
