<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELEASE STILL BOTHERS FIELDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Cecil Fielder has found a new home with the Indians,
but he's still ``puzzled'' about his release from the Anaheim
Angels. After all, he says, it's not often the leading RBI man on a
first-place team gets released in August. Fielder had 17 homers and
68 RBI for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't come up with something,'' he said. ``I can
only go on what they told me. (Dave) Hollins has a salary for next
year, they wanted to bring the kid (Troy Glaus) up and move Hollins
to first base. That came out of (manager Terry Collins') mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did what they had to do. The only thing that (ticked) me
off was saying I wasn't doing this or that in certain situations,
or I can't run the bases. That's baseball, they knew what they were
getting when they signed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielder has struggled with the Indians. He was 1 for 17 until
getting a two-hit game Sunday. Now, he's batting .167 (4 for 24)
with the Indians with no RBI and eight strikeouts. He said the time
off before signing with Cleveland hurt him. Fielder was designated
for assignment by the Angels on Aug. 5 and signed with Cleveland
Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost almost two weeks then had to get up and get going
again. It was rough,'' he said. ``The whole month of August was a
wash.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of seats: The Angels are in a pennant race. They know it,
but it seems their fans either don't know or don't care.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three home games of the season, Sept. 21-23 vs.
second-place Texas, the Angels have sold between 18,000 and 23,000
seats. The three games prior to the Texas series, Sept. 18-20 vs.
Seattle, the team has sold 28,000-39,000 seats. Why?
</P>
<P>
   The series vs. Seattle is 1) on the weekend, 2) includes a
fireworks show and 3) includes fan appreciation day.
</P>
<P>
   Promotions: The Angels clubhouse got a little more crowded
Tuesday, as the club added pitchers Mike Holtz and Jason Dickson,
and infielders Justin Baughman and Chris Pritchett from triple-A
Vancouver. Catcher Charlie O'Brien, pitcher Steve Sparks and
outfielder Reggie Williams jumped from Double-A Midland.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks and Williams never actually left the Angels but were
temporarily taken off the roster to make room for Ken Hill and
Gregg Jefferies. O'Brien was acquired in a trade July 30 from the
White Sox but hadn't been able to play because of a broken thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jarrod Washburn, who went 5-2 with a 4.38 ERA in 10
starts for the Angels earlier this season, is expected to be called
up soon. The Angels want him to get another start for Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Rosters may be expanded to as many as 40 players. The Angels
have 32.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, a left-handed reliever, had been sent to Vancouver on
Aug. 3 to regain a feel for his curveball. He says he has found it,
as well as an appreciation for the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last day in Vancouver there was this naked guy running
across the field,'' Holtz said. ``Then he went back in the stands
and sat down in his seat and watched the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not: O'Brien won't say his thumb is completely healed,
only that he can play with it. He played five games for Midland to
get ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been a whole lot of fun,'' said O'Brien, who hit
.262 with four homers and 18 RBI for the White Sox. ``Especially
when this team is fighting for a pennant.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's biggest asset is his ability to call a game and handle
pitchers. O'Brien is expected to get his first start with the
Angels on Friday against the Royals in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Fan support: The crowd at Jacobs Field Tuesday night was 43,184,
their 281st consecutive sellout. With tonight's game, the Indians
will surpass three million in attendance for the third consecutive
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
