MacKENZIE OUT FOR SEASON 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC tailback Malaefou MacKenzie will miss the
remainder of the season after being diagnosed with a torn anterior
cruciate ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie, a sophomore, will redshirt this season and have three
years of eligibility remaining. He is scheduled to undergo surgery
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say? That's football,'' MacKenzie said. ``All
things happen for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie injured his knee on an awkward play in the third
quarter against Purdue, when his foot got stuck in the turf during
a 2-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   ``My weight went one way and my knee went the other,'' MacKenzie
said.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie gained 28 yards in seven carries against Purdue. He
gained 332 yards last season, including 104 against Nevada-Las
Vegas, when he became just the third true freshman to start at
tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more than a football player,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said. ``He is a real leader. His leadership, his work ethic and how
he threw himself into learning the offense were outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett compared the injury to the one safety Grant Pearsall
suffered, which caused him to redshirt last season.
</P>
<P>
   With MacKenzie out, Hackett said Petros Papadakis would become
the No.2 tailback behind starter Chad Morton. Jabari Jackson and
Frank Strong will back up Papadakis.
</P>
<P>
   Strong, perhaps the most impressive back in training camp, seems
to have dropped down slightly because he is a true freshman _ at
least according to Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank hasn't done anything before,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, neither had Carson Palmer, so Hackett could likely
revise the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback update: Hackett stressed again that Mike Van
Raaphorst is the starter and Palmer will remain the backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I don't want to do is not develop a young
quarterback because I'm so hung up on (who) the starting
quarterback (is),'' Hackett said. ``What Mike went through at
Washington last season (a 27-0 loss), I don't want to put Carson
through that. Mike recovered well, and some never recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas rests: Hackett said freshman quarterback Jason Thomas
will stay off his injured ankle for 10 days, without any practice
or running, to see if the scar tissue surrounding his left ankle
can heal. If not, Hackett said Thomas might undergo arthroscopic
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   That means Quincy Woods is back at No. 3 quarterback, although
Woods practiced only at wide receiver Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
