<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' PITCHING SLAMMED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Danny Patterson sat quietly with a pained look on his
face. Smashing his foot against the side of his locker only
emphasized the frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious I just don't have the stuff I had before the
surgery,'' Patterson said. ``It's there one day and gone the next
10. ... Nothing is working.''
</P>
<P>
   John Burkett dressed and bolted the clubhouse quickly, an exit
almost as fast as his first-inning performance in a 12-8 defeat
against the Detroit Tigers last night. He left behind teammates
sitting glumly in the visitors' clubhouse of Tiger Stadium, many of
them wondering if the Rangers will have enough pitching to catch
the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels lost last night, 7-6, against Cleveland, leaving the
Rangers still trailing by 2 1/2 games in the American League West
race. But that didn't alleviate many people's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough time right now,'' outfielder Juan Gonzalez said.
``If you don't have pitching, everything is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it would take to get a winning streak going, first
baseman Will Clark said, ``It isn't hard to figure that out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't get pitching last night. Instead, Burkett
gave up four runs in the first inning to kiss away a 3-0 lead, and
the bullpen was torched for seven runs in the final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson took the brunt of the carnage, giving up a grand slam
to shortstop Deivi Cruz in the seventh and two more home runs to
Juan Encarnacion and Damion Easley in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, who underwent off-season surgery to repair a rotator
cuff, has allowed 11 home runs in 53 1/3 innings this year. He
allowed just three in 71 innings last year, including none in the
first 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's location,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``Maybe it's
velocity, but the radar guns say it's the same speed as last year
before he got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager was as frustrated as his reliever. He had no
illuminating explanations other than stating the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is you can't win giving up 12 runs, no matter how
much offense you have,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense gave Burkett three runs to work with,
including a two-run homer by Clark. But the lead disappeared
quickly. Burkett, pitching on three days' rest, faced nine batters
and seven reached base on five hits and two walks, one intentional.
He was pulled with two outs, the shortest outing of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was right down the middle,'' catcher Ivan Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine and newcomer Tony Fossas, who struck out three of the
four batters he faced, kept the Rangers close, and they pulled even
at 5-5 in the seventh on two Detroit errors.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't stay that way long. It was disaster by committee. Tim
Crabtree gave up a double to Luis Gonzalez and a single to Gabe
Alvarez. Eric Gunderson walked Paul Bako. Cruz broke the tie by
crushing an 0-1 pitch over the left-field fence for his first
career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   The two home runs in the eighth made it 20 in the past 32 games
allowed by Rangers relievers. They also have a combined 5.56
earned-run average in their past 37 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do have the fifth-fewest relief appearances by a
team in the American League, which makes Oates believe they are not
tired from early-season overuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that has anything to do with it,'' Oates said.
``Nobody has come to me and said they were tired. If they are,
we're in deep trouble because we haven't overused anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Explanations were hard to come by last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the major-league level, you can't outscore people every
night,'' Oates said. ``You've got to get people out. At the
beginning and the end, we didn't pitch well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
