<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BULLPEN FALTERS; SEATTLE'S DELIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARINERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Short of forcing Ken Griffey to play blindfolded, Lou
Piniella to manage without his cap, or Jay Buhner to use Rogaine,
the Red Sox could not have had the Seattle Mariners at a greater
disadvantage Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The game came down to a battle of bullpens, which for the
Mariners is tantamount to telling their bus driver (no relation to
Heathcliff Slocumb) to leave the motor running.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday the Red Sox bullpen, which was ranked No. 1 in the
American League, turned sloppy at the first scent of September,
giving up five runs in the seventh and eighth innings in a 7-3 loss
to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   While a crowd of 28,150 at Fenway Park was reduced to amusing
itself with college cheers practiced by this year's crop of
incoming freshmen, the Sox bullpen disintegrated with four hits,
three walks, a wild pitch, and a costly throwing error by Derek
Lowe, who had inherited a 3-2 lead from Pete Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   After a leadoff walk to Buhner and a line single by Russ Davis
off third baseman John Valentin's glove, Lowe threw away Dan
Wilson's bunt in the two-run seventh. It was his fourth error of
the season and the 16th committed by a Red Sox pitcher _ a figure
exceeded only by the Mariners (23) and Dodgers (17).
</P>
<P>
   Making the error all the more frustrating was that the
6-foot-6-inch Lowe, who has joked about his lack of athleticism but
was an all-state basketball player in high school, has been working
overtime on his fielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was out there a half an hour yesterday and a half an hour
today,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``We must have gone over
the same play he saw tonight about 15 or 20 times. He's slow
reacting to balls hit at him. We're trying to make him quicker when
he steps off the mound and quicker on making his throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have him out there every day until he gets it right.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sinkerball pitcher who either generates ground balls or
finds another line of work, Lowe recognizes that his glove is more
than just an ornament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to be able to field my position,'' he said. ``Field
bunts, cover first. You're going to be handling the ball so much as
a ground-ball pitcher, you have to be able to field or it's going
to hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as harmful was the eighth inning, another artistic disaster
in which newly recalled David West walked Griffey on four straight
pitches, uncorked a wild pitch to Edgar Martinez, and allowed an
RBI single to David Segui. With Segui taking second on a rare
overthrow by center fielder Darren Lewis, the Mariners went on to
score twice more on Davis's bloop single and Wilson's double off
Carlos Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two leadoff walks, the bunt play, the little things hurt us
tonight,'' Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the maligned Mariners pen, the league's most adept at
coughing up leads, protected this one with 2 2/3 innings of
scoreless work from Jose Paniagua and Mike Timlin, Paniagua's test
of fire coming when he coaxed a pop fly from Nomar Garciaparra with
the bases loaded to end the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture for the Sox, the damage was contained, as
their closest contender for a wild-card spot, the Texas Rangers,
also ran into late-inning blues and fell, 12-8, to the Detroit
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Sox' margin at eight over the Rangers and nine
over the Blue Jays, who have won five straight to make a faint
appearance on the radar screen. A four-game set in Toronto is just
ahead for the Sox, beginning Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The big picture was of little consequence to Schourek, who has
known nothing but losing since coming to the Red Sox but was in
line for his first win when he left with a 3-2 lead after six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek weathered a bases-loaded, no-out jam in the first that
yielded just one run and a 441-foot homer by Buhner in the second
that clocked the light stanchion well above the Coke bottles,
dropped into the screen, then bounded onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners hit a couple of more deep balls off Schourek that
not only remained under radar range but were caught, one by a
leaping Lewis in front of the center-field wall in the fourth. But
they managed just two more hits off Schourek, singles by David Bell
in the third and Griffey, who went the other way against the shift,
in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   A measure of satisfaction for a job well done?
</P>
<P>
   ``A small one,'' Schourek said. ``Obviously, it's another outing
I've made that we've lost. I don't think we've won yet when I've
been on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. It's five times and counting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
