<HEADLINE>
MARLINS EXEC INTERVIEWS FOR GM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Hughes, the Florida Marlins director of
player personnel, closed out the first round of interviews for the
Los Angeles Dodgers' GM position by meeting with the club on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there were seven candidates for the job, which is
expected to be filled by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will conduct follow-up interviews next week while
the club is on the road in Arizona and San Diego. Fox's baseball
people Chase Carey and Peter Chernin will be involved in the second
round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers president Bob Graziano and club chairman Peter O'Malley
were the point men in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins' GM Dave Dombrowski, considered the front-runner, will
be part of the second round, as will Cincinnati GM Jim Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Yankees GM Bob Watson, the only African-American
candidate, also will be back. National League president Leonard
Coleman has spoken on behalf of Watson, who also is being
considered by the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The final candidate is Baltimore assistant Kevin Malone. He was
the former general manager with Montreal after Dan Duquette went to
Boston at the end of the 1993 season. Duquette replaced Dombrowski,
who left the Expos to join the expansion Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The three who did not make the cut _ Hughes, Atlanta's Dean
Taylor and the Mets' Omar Minaya _ were well regarded, but did not
have GM experience.
</P>
<P>
   One trivia note: Minaya, who interviewed Sunday, was the
long-time Latin America coordinator for the Texas Rangers and
signed Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa for $3,500 in 1986 out of the
Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Antonio Osuna, who learned Monday he needs
season-ending surgery, will have the procedure Tuesday at Centinela
Hospital Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna's absence was not the only reason minor league callup Mike
Judd pitched two innings in Monday's 8-3 loss to the New York
Mets.Left-handed reliever Mark Guthrie is expected to miss a week
after complaining of soreness in his pitching elbow. Guthrie,
second to Scott Radinsky (58) in appearances with 52, hasn't
pitched in a week.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous four outings, Guthrie allowed nine hits and five
runs in 51/3 innings. Guthrie is earning $1.6 million in the final
season of a multi-year contract and is not expected back.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back: O'Malley appears to be mending fences in what is
expected to be his final year with the club. Fired manager Bill
Russell was a guest in his box Monday and Russell now is headed to
Taiwan to represent the Dodgers in clinics with a local
professional team. Russell and the Dodgers' three fired coaches _
Reggie Smith, Mark Cresse and Goose Gregson _ will be part of the
annual November fantasy camp in Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's father dies: Marvin Sheffield, the father of Dodgers
right-fielder Gary Sheffield, died Tuesday in Tampa, Fla., of
throat cancer. He was 50. Sheffield, who learned earlier in the day
that he will miss the rest of the season with a severely sprained
left ankle, flew to Florida on Tuesday night. Sheffield will be
wearing a removable cast for the next four to six weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
