<SLUG> BC-LOVEBOAT-LAUNCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE BOAT'S' JULIE OPENS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MELISSA SCHMITT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There they were Tuesday. Doc, Isaac, Captain
Steubing, Vickie and the woman who made cruise director the career
of choice for girls of the 1970s, Julie.
</P>
<P>
   Real and in the flesh, the crew of the 1970s hit TV show ``The
Love Boat'' came together for a reunion at Ray Art studios in
Canoga Park that was really a chance for the UPN network to
publicize its show, ``The Love Boat: The Next Wave.''
</P>
<P>
   The first episode of the new season is a reunion of the old cast
with the new, set for broadcast Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   So there they were standing on the bottom stair leading into the
pool area of the Pacific Princess. Right up close. And Julie was
wearing one of her wonderful pale blue gowns with spaghetti straps.
Just like she did in the late '70s and early '80s, when teen-age
girls thought life could be no better than that of the cruise
director on the Pacific Princess.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Princess, where love was ``exciting and new'' every
week. Where every week the crew invited you to ``come aboard, we've
been expecting you.''
</P>
<P>
   Life couldn't get any better for a teen-age girl baby-sitting
three kids for a buck an hour and a pizza if the parents were rich.
``Love Boat'' was the high point of Saturday night. Julie was the
picture of glamour and career. She put cruise director on the
career map of girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you wised up,'' said Lauren Tewes, the actress who
played Julie.
</P>
<P>
   Tewes took a few minutes to sit down and talk about life after
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's been 20 years, Tewes looks the same. Short blond
hair, pretty blue eyes. Same sweet, quiet girl. Still uncomfortable
in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   Tewes' life hasn't been all that simple.
</P>
<P>
   After a well-publicized battle with cocaine in the '70s, Tewes
made her way to Seattle, where she married actor Bob Nader and
began a career as a stage actress.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband has been diagnosed with Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tewes said, she is turning her efforts toward gaining
public awareness for Lou Gehrig's disease, which has no known cure.
</P>
<P>
   Tewes said after the filming of the reunion show, she will
return to Seattle and her ailing husband.
</P>
<P>
   And hopefully she'll find a way to set her course for adventure,
her mind on a new happiness.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
