<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-RETAIL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITANIC' VIDEOS SAIL OFF SHELVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The fans can't get enough.
</P>
<P>
   That's the early conclusion after the video version of
box-office megahit ``Titanic'' went on sale at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' said Kelly Haynie, manager at a Blockbuster
outlet in Northridge that offered a ``Bon Voyage'' party with gifts
and coupons. ``I was expecting no more than 15 or 20 people, and we
had more like 150. People started to line up at 10:30 (p.m.).''
</P>
<P>
   Many stores stayed open until 2 a.m., then encountered more
buyers when they reopened. Haynie said her store was selling 10
copies an hour and had already asked the studio to restock the
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Video's Tarzana outlet drew about 40 customers between
midnight and 1 a.m., then reopened at 8 a.m. -- two hours earlier
than normal. ``It's amazing that people were here in the middle of
the night when they could get the video today,'' store manager Nick
McCauley said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even stores that didn't participate in the midnight madness drew
impressively. Workers at Circuit City stores in Northridge and Van
Nuys each found several dozen customers in line when the doors
opened Tuesday morning, possibly drawn by the $16.99 discount price
for the two-tape set.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary figures indicate ``Titanic'' -- with a worldwide box
office topping $1.8 billion -- should become the top live-action
video ever in the U.S. market, topping the 17 million units sold of
``Jurassic Park'' and ``Independence Day.'' Paramount Studios
shipped more than 20 million copies; Video Store magazine, citing
an unnamed distributor, reported recently that the total topped 23
million.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster announced it had presold 1 million copies at $24.99,
while Best Buy sold 50,000 copies between midnight and 2 a.m., when
its stores closed. To stock its 289 stores, Best Buy bought enough
copies to fill 25 53-foot-long trucks, said spokeswoman Laurie
Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people lining up as early as 9:15 last night, and some
of our stores had several hundred people,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount spokeswoman Dorrit Ragosine reported no problems with
stores breaking the 12:01 a.m. embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been completely enthusiastic,'' she said. ``It's
been a complete home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry tracker Barbara McNamara of Alexander &AMP; Associates said
the video will post strong sales for several weeks before dropping
off, then could see a resurgence as the holiday shopping season
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HN     09-02 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The Comets are WNBA champions _ again.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the littlest one was there Tuesday night to lead them to an
80-71 victory over the Phoenix Mercury in the third and deciding
game of the 1998 WNBA Championship Series at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   There's no discounting the contributions of Cynthia Cooper, who
for the second time was chosen the championship Most Valuable
Player. She had 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes, quiet most of the night, rose when it counted
most. Swoopes had 16 points and in the final seven minutes came up
with a huge blocked shot, an assist and a fast-break layup within
the span of 32 seconds to help seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson was there with 18 points, six rebounds and a pair
of 3-pointers that helped subdue the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Kim Perrot, more than any Comet, who had the
consistent effect for 40 minutes that made Phoenix coach Cheryl
Miller's guarantee of a championship win over the Comets back in
July nothing more than hot air that drifted into the desert night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim Perrot's had two bad games,'' said Coach of the Year Van
Chancellor, ``and to come back like this is unbelievable. The `Big
Three' (Cooper, Swoopes and Thompson) are going to get all the
publicity. But poor little ol' Kim, she was right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her to get me just one rebound. She went out there and
got three (among) those giants there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   A non-factor through most of the first two games of the
best-of-three series, Perrot shook the rust off her game Tuesday
and contributed 13 points, five rebounds and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   With the Comets, who built a 10-point lead in the first half,
ahead 73-67 with 2:21 left, Perrot on three consecutive missed
field-goal attempts by the Mercury knifed through to grab the
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We most definitely had to turn it up a notch (on defense),''
Perrot said, ``but there was never a moment of doubt. We've been
through that all year. We got together as a team and said, `Hey,
they're going to make some runs. All we had to do was hold on. We
held on and came up with some key rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Comets, their 27-3 record attracting
expectations that helped make the 1998 playoffs pressure-packed
from beginning to end, survived their toughest of challenges this
season.
</P>
<P>
   True to their promise of the day before, the Comets roared out
of the gates at the start and mounted a 10-point lead in the first
half, only to have it melt under a heavy Mercury siege at the start
of the final period.
</P>
<P>
   And with 16:51 remaining, a fast-break layup by forward Umeki
Webb, one of many by Phoenix, had the Comets trailing 41-39 for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   But true to another pre-game vow, the defending champions
weren't going to allow anything to stand in their way of a second
crown. They had been galvanized by a 74-69 win in overtime Saturday
during which they trailed by 12 points with 7:24 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   They were duty-bound Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the best games I've ever seen, and I'm so
proud that we won our second championship in a row,'' Chancellor
said. ``Thank God for great players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is good. And they're playing good right now. I don't
want to play them again. This is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I've been resurrected, so to speak. The good Lord won
one for me Saturday night. The players won one for me today, so I'm
a lucky guy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Comets down 47-45, Perrot had two free throws and
followed that with a 3-pointer off an assist from Swoopes (one of
six) as the Comets took the lead for good 50-47.
</P>
<P>
   Twice over the next seven minutes, the Mercury rallied behind
Michelle Griffiths (game-high 24 points) and pulled to within a
point. But on each occasion, someone in Comets white was there with
an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Leading only 60-59 following a Griffiths layup that came off a
Perrot turnover, Perrot gained redemption by returning the favor on
the other end.
</P>
<P>
   When Bridget Pettis tossed in a bucket to cut the Comets' lead
to 62-61, Swoopes, fouled by Brandy Reed, nailed a pair of free
throws to build the lead back to 64-61.
</P>
<P>
   During the timeout that followed, Chancellor had instructions
for his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole timeout at that time was,'' he said, ```We've got to
find somebody who can guard somebody.' We made a defensive
adjustment. We were allowing them to go down the middle. So we told
them to push the Mercury to the sidelines, cut a few passing lanes,
step it up defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that's where we won the game, with a gallant,
valiant defensive effort by Kim Perrot.''
</P>
<P>
   The names of Cooper, Swoopes and Janeth Arcain might have been
added. Cooper, who had 13 of her 23 points in the first half,
forced reserve Toni Foster into a turnover. On the other end,
Arcain took a pass from Swoopes and converted for a 66-61 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On Phoenix's next possession, Swoopes blocked Reed's shot.
Swoopes would complete the series by taking a pass from Thompson
and making a fast-break layup that put the Comets ahead 68-61.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mercury wasn't done. First, Jennifer Gillom (20 points)
cut the advantage to 69-65. Then, after Thompson's follow shot made
it 71-65, Griffiths converted in transition to trim it back to
71-67.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last hurrah for the Mercury, which finished second
to the Comets in the Western Conference race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was,'' Miller said, ``they made their shots. That's
what you want to do in a championship game, make the shots, make
the ones that count. And they did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of that stretch when the Mercury briefly led in the second half,
then again found itself playing catch-up, Miller said: ``We traded
baskets for a while. But when there were key shots to be made, they
did that; they were able to get into transition and make some easy
baskets that way. We made some good plays down the stretch, trying
to get to the rim, trying to get some calls (from the officials).
That didn't happen. That's just the way the ballgame went.''
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes after Griffiths' basket trimmed the lead to four
points for the final time, Swoopes made four straight free throws
to put the Comets ahead 77-67.
</P>
<P>
   The workers at Compaq Center perched in the rafters, then busied
themselves preparing the blizzard of red-white-and-blue confetti
that fell throughout most of the postgame ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheryl made some big-time free throws,'' Chancellor said,
``some big-time shots, big-time rebounds. She's a big-time player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That blocked shot, she ran over one of our players to get to
it. That's the second game in a row she's done something like that.
She's a player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets led 25-15 in the first half following a 3-pointer by
Thompson. The Comets were ahead 32-26 at intermission. But with
five points from Gillom stoking a 15-7 run, the Mercury came back
to take the lead 41-39 at 16:51 of the final period.
</P>
<P>
   But this night, it would hardly be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through a lot of ups and downs this season,'' Cooper
said, ``just like a lot of teams do, and we made a lot of
sacrifices as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is special. I didn't think before that this championship
would feel as special as the first one, but when that buzzer
sounded, I felt so many emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes all of it worth it. I would definitely say this
one was sweeter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
