</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT DENIES NEW YORK CITY'S BID TO BAR HARLEM RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, inserts throughout) (sw) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Complying with a federal court order, city officials
and organizers of the rally billed as the Million Youth March
briefly put aside weeks of vitriol on Tuesday night to hammer out
conditions for the event, which will take place on Saturday as
organizers had hoped but in a much smaller swath of Harlem and for
a much shorter time.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came hours after a federal appeals court ruled
that the rally could take place in Harlem on Saturday, despite
efforts by the city to block it. But the court ruling significantly
curbed the scope of the event, reducing the proposed duration to 4
hours from 12 and the number of blocks to 6 from 29.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, by a divided three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan, balanced the free-speech
rights of the event's organizers against the concerns of city
officials, who said they feared that it could be too large to
manage, particularly when the city's police force will be taxed by
other Labor Day weekend events.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claimed victory on Tuesday night, after
representatives of the organizers met with city lawyers to hammer
out final conditions. They agreed that the rally would take place
from noon to 4 p.m. on Malcolm X Boulevard, from 118th Street to
124th Street. Organizers also agreed that there would be no
entertainment or music and no vending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only wanted a few things, and by God's grace, we have
everything we wanted,'' Khallid Abdul Muhammad, the rally's lead
organizer, told reporters after the meeting. Asked about his
original requests for 12 hours and 29 blocks for the rally,
Muhammad described them as negotiating tactics. ``Sir, in
negotiating for the Million Youth March, we set up the parameters
broadly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the potential for disturbances on Saturday, Muhammad
said, ``If the policemen are courteous and kind and respectful to
us, then we must return that respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that Mayor Giuliani's police will riot on
this day,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hess, the city's corporation counsel, said Muhammad's
declaration of victory was merely ``a spin they have to put on
it.'' He portrayed the court-imposed limits as a triumph for the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the court's ruling was the acknowledgment by lawyers
for the organizers that they expect only 50,000 people, which is
significantly lower than previous estimates of 150,000 to three
million.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Wareham, one of the lawyers, attributed the drop to the
``climate of terror'' that he said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had
created by consistently referring to the event as a ``hate march.''
Muhammad has promoted the rally as an expression of strength and
unity by young black people, but he has peppered his comments with
the sort of antiwhite and anti-Semitic remarks for which he has
repeatedly been criticized.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, which supported the plans for the rally, said the
court's decision to let it go on was ``a win for the First
Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The court decision signaled the latest and perhaps final clash
between the city and Muhammad over his plans for a rally in Harlem,
one that he said would attract entertainers, gang members
interested in ending lives of violence, and thousands of young
black people from around the country. But specifics have been few,
and he has had to compete with a larger rally, the Million Youth
Movement, also taking place this weekend, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has repeatedly denounced the rally and all those who
might participate. His comments have prompted several leaders in
Harlem to criticize him as insensitive, and provided Muhammad with
an opportunity to spice his familiar rhetoric with suggestions that
invited gang members might fail to contain themselves if the police
try to stop the event.
</P>
<P>
   The city's efforts to block the event, and to offer an
alternative time and place _ Randalls Island on Sept. 19 _ were
undercut last week when Judge Lewis Kaplan, of Federal District
Court in Manhattan, ruled that the city's denial of a rally permit
for the Labor Day weekend was unconstitutional and based on
arbitrary interpretations of city regulations.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that the city had enough police officers ``to
deal with whatever problems of congestion, emergency action,
overcrowding and fire risk may arise'' during a 12-hour rally that
would stretch 29 blocks along Malcolm X Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the appeals court majority, Judges Jon Newman and
Fred Parker, upheld the lower court's decision to issue an
injunction allowing the event to take place in Harlem on Sept. 5.
But they argued that the ``invalidity of a permit regulation cannot
automatically entitle a plaintiff to hold its event precisely as it
wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the two judges found fault with Kaplan's assessment
of the city's ability to respond to the rally, saying that the
lower court's decision ``exceeded the scope of its allowable
discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Richard Cardamone joined his colleagues in agreeing that
the organizers had a right to hold the rally, but in his written
decision, disagreed with the modifications. The smaller scope of
the rally, he said, could have the counterproductive results of
increasing congestion and ``the risk of confrontation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
