<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA SUMMIT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service moved the following package of
stories relating to the summit meeting in Moscow and the political
and economic turmoil in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUMMIT (Moscow) _ President Clinton delivered a sober
lecture to Russian leaders and the Russian people Tuesday about the
hard realities of capitalism and the price of international support
for relief from Russia's current financial crisis. In meetings with
President Boris N. Yeltsin and the temporary caretakers of Russia's
paralyzed political and economic institutions, and in a speech to
students at a Moscow university, Clinton warned that there is no
easy escape from the financial catastrophe that has closed banks,
left millions of workers unpaid and caused the collapse of the
government. By John M. Broder. (1stLd)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ While anxiety over Russia's deepening
economic crisis spread, acting Prime Minister Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin said Tuesday that he would form an acting government
without waiting for parliamentary approval. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RESCUE (Undated) _ Plan A, a $23.6 billion program
courtesy of the IMF, failed in less than four weeks. Plan B, a
devaluation and debt moratorium cobbled together by young Russian
reformers, collapsed within days. Neither prevented investors from
fleeing or citizens from turning every ruble they have into
dollars. So what options are left for restoring financial
stability? By Slyvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SCENE (Moscow) _ As Muscovites defied a cold rain to
methodically pick grocery shelves clean of goods they expect will
soon disappear, President Clinton stood Tuesday morning in the oval
office _ Boris Yeltsin's marble-and-bronze, oval-shaped study in
the Kremlin _ and pushed the heel of his hand onto the top of a
fat, round loaf of Russian bread. Each time the bread bounced back.
``Amazing,'' Clinton told Yeltsin. ``Kind of like you.'' So he
hopes. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMS (Moscow) _ During the frigid days of the Cold War,
American satellites watched for the fiery launching of Soviet
missiles, a sign that the United States might soon be under nuclear
attack. Now that the nuclear standoff is over, the United States
has found a new use for its warning systems. It plans to employ
them to alert the Russians about missile launches around the world.
On Wednesday, President Clinton and President Boris N. Yeltsin plan
to sign a new accord under which the former antagonists will
instantly share data about the launch of ballistic missiles and
space boosters. By Michael R. Gordon. (1stLd)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
