<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES PITCHES DODGERS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A month off meant everything to Ismael Valdes. Two
days did not help Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes pitched seven scoreless innings Tuesday night in his
first start since July 27, but Shaw continued to struggle in the
Los Angeles Dodgers' 3-2 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who blew four save opportunities during a six-day stretch,
allowed a mammoth home run to Bobby Estalella on the first pitch of
the ninth inning but retired the final three hitters to preserve
the victory for Valdes before 28,199 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (10-9), sidelined since July 27 with a strained left side
muscle, was activated before the game, but did not appear bothered
by the layoff.
</P>
<P>
   He limited the Phillies to five hits and two walks in seven
innings. He struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable. I had no pain in my injury at all,''
Valdes said. ``But I started to have some blisters in the fourth
inning. I just wanted to go pitch by pitch and inning by inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Dodgers, who just dropped three of four to the
Mets, have an abundance of starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Glenn Hoffman has elected to use a six-man rotation. He
moved Carlos Perez into tonight's game against the Phillies and
dropped Darren Dreifort to Friday's series opener against the San
Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody deserves to be taken out right now,'' Hoffman said.
``(Dave) Mlicki and (Brian) Bohanon have been great. And now
Ismael. It's a strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, however, remains a trouble spot, as does the entire
bullpen. After allowing big late-inning homers to Andres Galarraga,
Andruw Jones and Edgardo Alfonzo in the past 10 days, Shaw gave up
a 447-foot drive to Estalella that cut the Dodgers' lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But he held on to record his 39th save overall and 16th with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Charles Johnson's two-run homer in the seventh, the
Dodgers might not have closed out the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   The club already is without set-up man Antonio Osuna, who
learned Monday that he needs season-ending surgery to remove bone
chips in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   And left-hander Mark Guthrie is expected to miss a week with a
tender elbow. He hasn't pitched since Thursday against Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies and Dodgers entered August with a chance at the
wild card. But Philadelphia went 11-20 and the Dodgers 11-18 during
the past month and both dropped from the race.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the two teams were left to play out the string.
</P>
<P>
   While Valdes was breezing through the Phillies order, the
Dodgers didn't get their first hit off starter Paul Byrd (2-2)
until the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros doubled off the wall in left-center with one out,
moved to third on an infield single by Bobby Bonilla and scored
when Phillies shortstop Desi Reliford misplayed Matt Luke's
grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, who failed to crack Atlanta's vaunted starting rotation a
few years back, has pitched well since he was promoted two weeks
ago from Triple-A. He had complete-game victories in his first two
starts before getting roughed up by San Diego on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It remained 1-0 until the seventh when Jerry Spradlin took over
for Byrd. With one out, Mark Grudzielanek hit a sharp one-hopper
off Spradlin's pitching hand for an infield hit and Johnson
followed with his 17th homer.
</P>
</TEXT>
