<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MARKET TURMOIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service moved the following package of
stories on the day after the market suffered the second-largest
point drop in the Dow ever.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The stock market Tuesday regained more than
half of the value it lost on Monday as trading volume set a record.
Traders and stock-market analysts said that big institutions, like
pension funds and insurance companies, took the lead in Tuesday's
buying, picking through big and small stocks that had been leveled
by Monday's selloff. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-ASSESS (Undated) _ The smoke from the stock market
shootout of the last five trading days finally began to clear
Tuesday. As the Dow Jones industrial average rallied to close up
288.36 points, or 3.8 percent, investors began to ask: Where do we
go from here? By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-RUSSIA (Undated) _ More financial firms report losses
from Russia. By Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-IMF (Washington) _ The deepening worldwide economic
crisis has widened the gulf dividing Republicans over whether to
approve new financing for the International Monetary Fund. Congress
appeared certain to increase IMF financing when lawmakers left on a
monthlong recess in August. But as the Senate resumes business this
week, and the House due back next week, the new financing is now
teetering on the brink with each day's gloomy financial news. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-BUYBACKS (Undated) _ Are companies announcing stock
buybacks? By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-SHORT (New York) _ How short-sellers fared in the
volatile market. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-VOLATILITY (Chicago) _ Trading in options and futures and
what that is doing to market volatility over all. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   CT-MARKET-MOOD (Greenwich, Conn.) _ The mood in Connecticut's
Fairfield County, whose suburban fortunes are closely tied to Wall
Street. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-VENEZUELA (Caracas) _ With investment holdings flying out
of this country, market analysts around the world widely agree that
Venezuela's economy has been crippled by an overvalued currency,
government inteference in monetary policy, and irresponsible
spending that relies too heavily on oil revenues. Many Venezuelans,
however, beg to disagree. Their political mood seems to be swinging
in precisely the opposite direction. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARKET-LIFESTYLE (New York) _ A brief look at whether New
Yorkers, who are more dependent than others on the stock market's
fortunes, are beginning to rethink spending.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-FED (Washington) _ When faced with a Latin America that
could no longer pay its debts during the summer of 1982, the
Federal Reserve put aside its tight-money policy and cut interest
rates. When faced with a stomach-churning stock market drop in
October 1987, the Fed acted quickly to pump more money into the
financial system. Does that mean the central bank will now feel
compelled to bring rates down? Don't count on it. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MARGINS (Undated) _ Are brokerage firms, especially
Internet firms, experiencing capital problems? By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-RESPONSE (Washington) _ Can there be, and should there
be, a coordinated international response to the widening
international economic crisis? The Clinton administration tried to
protect the American economy from the crisis in Asia with a series
of firewalls, but the Russian crisis broke through. Now the
strategy seems to be changing. The favored option of the moment
seems to be reducing interest rates both here and abroad. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
</TEXT>
