<HEADER>
A4208 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LA     09-02 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Anaheim Angels have played well enough to make
their own breaks lately, but Tuesday night the breaks went to the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the Indians won it 7-6 on Mark Whiten's one-out RBI
single in the bottom of the ninth before a sellout crowd of 43,184
at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   The winning rally was set up on a chopper by Manny Ramirez off
pitcher Rich DeLucia's glove for a single and continued when David
Justice hit a liner that appeared to go right through first baseman
Darin Erstad's glove into right field.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ramirez dived back into first on the play, right fielder
Garret Anderson had a chance to throw Ramirez out at second, but
his throw was wide.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Sexson failed in an attempt to bunt the runners over, but
it didn't matter. Whiten singled to left field on a 1-2 pitch from
Omar Olivares to win it. Indians reliever Steve Reed (2-2) got the
win over DeLucia (2-5).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Angels have won five of nine on the trip
to maintain their 2{-game lead over Texas. But they also know
there's a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the month of September,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``You talk about the postseason, this is where pennants are
won and lost. You play five months to get here, and you can lose it
in five days. Obviously, this is when it counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they learned anything from '95, it's how to play in this
month.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire game seemed to be like the ninth inning for the
Angels. Whiten's chopper up the middle in the second inning should
have been a double play, but it deflected off pitcher Chuck
Finley's glove and went into left field for an RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, the Indians' Omar Vizquel hit a grounder to third
with the bases loaded and one out. Third baseman Troy Glaus would
have had a play at the plate, but he bobbled it and could only get
the out at third, allowing a run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the fifth inning, center fielder Jim Edmonds overran a
ground-ball single by Ramirez. Edmonds took his eye off the ball
when he looked up to see Joey Cora, who was running hard to second
and had Edmonds thinking he might go to third. It went for a
two-base error and another Indians run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Edmonds said. ``The grass is cut two different
ways and (the ball) moves. I probably shouldn't have charged the
ball as hard as I did, I didn't need to. It went right under my
glove and probably cost us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those nights,'' Collins said. ``That's why
you've got to catch it. It's another example why defense is so
important. Maybe Roger Clemens can pitch without any defense, but I
don't know if anybody else can.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley couldn't Tuesday, but he wouldn't blame anybody but
himself. He gave up five runs and nine hits in 41/3 innings, his
shortest outing since being knocked out of the game by a line drive
in Kansas City on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the time of year to have a couple of bad starts,''
Finley said, referring to Tuesday's game and his previous start
last week against the Yankees. ``But you also have to look at the
fact they need me just as badly the next start. So you move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied from deficits of 3-0 and 5-3 to take a 6-5
lead on Gregg Jefferies' two-out, two-run bloop single in the
sixth. However, the bullpen couldn't hold the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holtz, who had been sent to the minors Aug. 3 to rediscover
his curveball and was recalled Tuesday, came in to face Justice
with runners on first and second and nobody out in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-2 pitch, Justice threw his bat at a breaking ball out of
the strike zone but got enough of it to bloop it into shallow right
field for a game-tying, RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the pitch where I wanted to put it,'' Holtz said. ``I
was mentally and totally ready. I was geared up all game for a
situation like that. I made my pitch, and nine times out of 10 I
get him out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
