<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIT PLAYERS BEGIN MARINER AUDITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Randy Johnson. Joey Cora. George Karl. Nate McMillan.
Sam Perkins. Chris Warren.
</P>
<P>
   The local casualty rate in the pro-sports-hero dodge is
unusually high in 1998, and four months remain.
</P>
<P>
   At least, the Seahawks appear to have reloaded. The Sonics? They
may never play again.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners?
</P>
<P>
   Well, pay attention this week. Nearly all the replacements will
be here by about Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Giomar Guevara. David Bell. Carlos Guillen. Mac Suzuki. Brett
Hinchcliffe. Freddy Garcia. David Holdridge.
</P>
<P>
   Your 1999 Mariners. More or less.
</P>
<P>
   You gotta learn these guys.
</P>
<P>
   For the first September in the last four, there's no scoreboard
watching. No jolt from a stretch drive rent-a-vet. No anticipation
of an Angels' choke, or a Rangers' wilt.
</P>
<P>
   What's left is a September the way it was for the first 18
years; the way it's been for baseball's two dozen also-ran clubs.
</P>
<P>
   A kiddy parade.
</P>
<P>
   A difference for the Mariners is the club has three major groups
to impress in the final month: Potential ticket buyers for an
expensive new ballpark; Ken Griffey Jr., and Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   All three need to see that the Mariners' beleaguered, bashful
tycoons, the Shytys, are not trying to sneak a fire sale past their
partners in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike what happened in Cleveland and Denver, where new parks
arrived with upswings in team fortunes, the Mariners risk being in
a deep swoon by the time the new yard opens July 15.
</P>
<P>
   That will make the blue skies/green grass honeymoon exceedingly
short and do little to inspire Griffey and Rodriguez, whose
contracts expire in 2000, to lock up early with long-term
extensions.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to acquire immediate help in exchange for Johnson
was the final signal from the bosses that the 1998 season was being
written off.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's trade of Cora was not nearly as hopeless, and actually
portends modest hope, since serviceable talent was received in
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   A market for a 33-year-old second baseman who often misplaces
first base was believed non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mariners get lucky, Bell will be a near-equivalent to
Doug Strange in 1995, a solid utility bench guy who can play
multiple positions and pinch-hit decently. If they don't get lucky,
they haven't lost anything, which is more than can be said about
almost every other development this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entering the season, we thought we had a club that would stay
in the hunt for a division title, but it didn't work out,'' Woody
Woodward, the VP for baseball operations, said Tuesday. ``In
looking ahead, we had to make changes at a few positions. We've
moved Joey to a playoff club and gave him a chance to succeed,
while using the opening to take a look at a number of our young
infielders.''
</P>
<P>
   One among Bell, Guevara and Guillen will be Cora's replacement.
If third baseman Russ Davis continues to be Dr. Strangeglove, one
of the young guys will replace him. Among position players, that's
the likely limit of change.
</P>
<P>
   As long as they can induce first baseman David Segui to extend
his Seattle stay, the Mariners aren't going to add vets to the
regular lineup. Neither are they likely to seek an ace to replace
Johnson, nor a top closer, although a free-agent pursuit of a cheap
No. 4 or No. 5 starter is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership made intentions clear in July when it became known the
1999 player payroll would be little different than this year's $53
million. Mariner president Chuck Armstrong was quoted as saying his
charge next year was to achieve ``positive cash flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was said about winning, or a World Series, or staying up
with other teams with new stadiums. Increased revenues from the new
park will go not to new free agents, but to raises for current
players and to the owners' checking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward did indicate that further bailouts on expensive veteran
contracts was probably over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel there are certain veterans who are very productive
and are important to the club's future,'' he said. The guess on the
higher-priced names on that list includes Segui, Edgar Martinez,
Jay Buhner and Dan Wilson, plus pitchers Jeff Fassero, Jamie Moyer
and Billy Swift.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily because they are cheap and available, the farm-system
kids called up for Tuesday's roster expansion to 40 players will be
the fillers for the Mariners' numerous holes.
</P>
<P>
   None of them are close to sure-fire, but given the success the
club had this year in the journeyman free-agent pool that produced
Tony Fossas, Pat Listach and Glenallen Hill, the Mariners are as
well off to try to coax their own camels through the eye of a
needle instead of someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   So now that the pressure is off to love these guys, here's the
first submission for the 1999 club slogan: ``We Might Get Lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, it won't make the Yankees stop dead. But it's hard to tap
your feet and hum to ``Positive Cash Flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
