<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANIAGUA'S PERFORMANCE PLEASES M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Mariner manager Lou Piniella talked about
right-handed reliever Jose Paniagua Tuesday night,
what-might-have-been crept into the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he had been here all year,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua might not be the entire remedy for a bullpen turnaround
the M's need next season, but his value continues to increase. It
reached another level at Fenway Park when he bailed starter Jamie
Moyer out of a seventh-inning bind, and then worked a scoreless
eighth inning as Seattle handed the Boston Red Sox a 7-3 loss
before 28,150 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has found a new home,'' Mariner pitching coach Stan
Williams said. ``He's done a great job for us everytime he has
pitched. His pitches have good location and he keeps them down.''
</P>
<P>
   On a night when Jay Buhner blasted a towering 441-foot home run
off the light standard in left field _ above the Green Monster and
three huge coke bottles _ and David Bell had a productive game as
the leadoff batter, Paniagua was instrumental in Seattle winning at
Fenway for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, closing in on the American League wild-card playoff
spot, fell behind 4-2 in the seventh when the Mariners scored two
runs off reliever Derek Lowe, whose throwing error on Dan Wilson's
sacrifice bunt scored Buhner. Bell delivered the go-ahead run with
a grounder to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams surprisingly conceded the go-ahead
run. He undoubtedly expected his team to pull out another
come-from-behind win. They've done it 41 times this season.
</P>
<P>
   The M's were beaten twice this season at Fenway because of
ninth-inning collapses.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua retired John Valentin on a pop-up to first baseman
David Segui and walked Mo Vaughn on a full-count pitch to load the
bases, but retired Nomar Garciaparra on a fly ball to Buhner in
shallow right field.
</P>
<P>
   Although the walk to Vaughn put the potential run in scoring
position, Stan Williams said he liked Paniagua's approach to facing
the dangerous Red Sox first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He challenged him, and that's what you want to see,'' Williams
said. ``Even on the full-count pitch, he never gave in. He didn't
walk Mo because he was pitching around him. He walked him pitching
aggressively and there is nothing wrong with that. I like the kid's
makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners added three insurance runs in the eighth inning.
Wilson, returning to the lineup after missing nearly six weeks with
torn ligaments in his left ankle, contributed a run-scoring double
in the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't miss a beat,'' Piniella said. ``We tested him with
some pitches in the dirt, but he held up well.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua has made eight relief appearances, allowing one earned
run in 91/3 innings, stranding five of the seven runners he
inherited.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Mike Timlin pitched the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked Darren Lewis leading off, many Mariner fans
watching at home probably had flashbacks to April 10. The Mariners
took a 7-3 lead into the ninth inning but didn't retire a batter as
Boston scored seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing two straight balls to Valentin, Timlin got a
visit from Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan told me I was rushing and I wasn't getting on top of the
ball,'' Timlin said. ``I slowed it down after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin bounced into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first game we've won here (this season),''
Piniella said. ``We let a couple get away that we should have won.
But, we got almost seven innings from Jamie, excellent relief from
Paniagua and Timlin and won a ballgame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
