<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-02 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WITH their she-peat complete, I have a request. Might the Comets
play the Quest?
</P>
<P>
   Houston's twice WNBA champions vs. Columbus' twice American
Basketball League champions is the only way to settle the issue of
``Who's No. 1?'' in the world of women's hoops. But because it
never will happen, of course, such a Super Bowl of ladyball, we're
simply going to have to make a judgment call here.
</P>
<P>
   I've decided to vote for the Comets. How about you?
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA's second season ended Tuesday night the same as its
first one had, with the Comets up there soaring among the stars,
looking down upon the hoi polloi. Having risen, Phoenix-like, from
the brink of defeat in overtime against Phoenix on Saturday after a
Game 1 loss, they claimed a second title _ 80-71 _ that was at once
far easier and infinitely harder than the historic first one.
</P>
<P>
   Three in a row, and I suppose we'll have to start calling them a
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   This team, blessed with two superstars and a season's worth of
experience playing together behind it, was clearly better than last
year's. You can't be a whole lot cleaner than 31-4, even if you are
the Bulls. But internal pressures over the course of the longer
season created challenges that coach Van Chancellor never had to
confront with everyone joy-riding through the giddy inaugural run.
</P>
<P>
   In '97, with most of the Comets returning from overseas exile,
the women were delighted just to be back in front of friends,
family and cheery English-speaking fans who didn't fling sharp
objects at them on the court. But in '98, reality set in.
Inevitably, egos and jealousies collided. Soap-opera scripts
evolved. Feelings got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Comets became the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Right down to the Clutch City script and, ultimately, the
back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, we must give coach Van the Man a promotion. With two
rings and one stomach bloated with antacids, he's now the WNBA's
emperor, not a mere Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were dead in the water Saturday,'' he said. ``But
the good Lord won one for me Saturday, and the players won one for
me tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chancellor offered considerable assistance. He X'd and O'd
rings around the Mercury's Cheryl Miller, who dresses like a
gangster and exhorts like a preacher but doesn't bring much to the
table when the heat is on and short-notice strategic decisions must
be made.
</P>
<P>
   She failed as a coach and as a prognosticator. Guess that ``bad
boy'' (championship) of hers won't be going back to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had no answers for the Comets' late charge in Game 2,
when the mercurial Mercury couldn't cling to a 12-point lead with
seven minutes left. And her brain froze up again down the stretch
in Game 3, after an early second-half spurt twice provided
two-point leads, the latter with 13:49 left.
</P>
<P>
   Later, her jaws wouldn't work, either. Apparently, she had flat
trash-talked herself out, judging by the plethora of sullen
one-word responses to reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Miller's defense, she was up against a superior
opponent _ and a superior player. Collectively, the Mercury had no
answer for Cynthia Cooper, the repeat Most Valuable Player who
contributed a typical monster night, scoring 23 points and
assisting six times. Coop's sublime game is a cut above the rest
despite her 35 years. We in Houston have been blessed by her
presence.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheryl Swoopes, a lass of 27, showed signs late that the
Comets will indeed be her team soon, as was originally ordained by
the WNBA's talent-seeding procedures. Although pregnancy and the
birth of her son, Jordan, limited her role to bit-part status last
season _ she rode the bench in the second half of last summer's
championship game _ she lately has begun to resemble the Madam
Legend she made herself at Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   With the Comets up only 62-59 and less than eight minutes to go,
she swished two of her nine free throws, then dished a beautiful
assist through a tangle of bodies to Janeth Arcain underneath.
Finally, she administered a brutal facial to Brandy Reed, after
which she outran the Mercury to the other end, taking a feed from
Kim Perrot for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Sheryl swooped to conquer. The Mercury was pretty much
toast there.
</P>
<P>
   The sold-out Compaq Center screamed its approval and never did
settle down thereafter, erupting as riotously at the close as any
Rockets crowd has. Given the labor stalemate threatening the coming
NBA season, that might have been the last gasp of hooping and
hollering we'll witness in the building for a while.
</P>
<P>
   So who's got next? Perhaps the Comets, if the boys and their
bosses can't make peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
