</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES' NEW PUNTER HAS APPOINTMENT IN TEMPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He will punt for the University of Washington on
Saturday night in Tempe, Ariz., in front of 72,000 boisterous fans
and 11 Arizona State special-teams mercenaries who will figure he
can't handle a rush.
</P>
<P>
   This is a far cry from his first college football game, and Ryan
Fleming knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' he said. ``I'm so excited, I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Fleming, 6-foot-3 and 180 pounds, can't tell you much
about his first college game. He wasn't even there. He was sitting
in the school library, brooding, at St. Olaf's College in
Northfield, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, an Irish Catholic out of Seattle Prep, had offered up
his 3.8 grade point average and 1,300 SAT score to Notre Dame, and
been rejected. So he settled on St. Olaf's, a Lutheran school
outside the Twin Cities, in a state peopled by relatives from both
sides of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Son of the UW department chairman in biostatistics, Fleming had
been a soccer player who burned out, finally joining the Seattle
Prep football team as a senior. He had a modest season punting for
a good team, averaging only 32 yards.
</P>
<P>
   He tried out for the St. Olaf's football team and soon found
himself outkicking the No. 1 punter, a transfer from a Division 1-A
school. Then the time came for the bus trip to Luther College in
Decorah, Iowa, and Fleming was left home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out it was by accident,'' he recalls. ``They left my
name off the (travel) list.''
</P>
<P>
   With a radio plug in his ear, Fleming sat there that Saturday in
1996, trying to study but unable, mad at the injustice that
grounded him. His time would come, though. Three games into the
season, he became the No. 1 punter and averaged a league-record
42.2 yards on a 2-8 team that played Augsburg and Carleton and
Gustavus Adolphus in the quaint, NCAA Division III Minnesota
Intercollegiate Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Half a continent away, Tom and Joli Fleming had season tickets
at the University of Washington. They were witnessing what a lot of
people have noticed about Husky punting. It comes and goes, mostly
goes. In no season in the 1990s has Washington averaged as much as
40 yards, even in the glory years.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the season ended, I thought about checking out
Washington,'' Fleming said. ``I thought I should just give it a
try. If I came here and didn't like it, I could always come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Huskies were skeptical, but desperation begets
open minds. As UW coach Jim Lambright puts it, ``You're not ready
to throw your hands up and jump and cheer because you've got
somebody that's gonna save your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington liked Fleming's flexibility and thought it might have
something. Fleming competed evenly in the spring with scholarship
punter Sean O'Laughlin, who since last season was married and had a
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fleming) tested out better than Sean, ran better, which
showed more commitment,'' Lambright said. ``Everything you were
weighing gave the pluses back to Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how Fleming might handle a low snap or a
thunder rush from a Sun Devil who might leak free. But Lambright is
convinced the Huskies at least will learn one thing from St.
Olaf's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make sure,'' Lambright smiled, ``that he's on the
plane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
