<HEADER>
A4229 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS &LR;      09-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ You measure milk by the quart, gas by the gallon, steel
by the ton.
</P>
<P>
   And in the National League, you measure everything and everybody
against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker did after
last year's playoff wipeout and concluded that his team couldn't.
Measure up, that is. Not against the Braves. At least, not without
elevator shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious way to get a lift up there with the big boys would
have been to engage in an arms race. Spend the big money, go for
the big names, and try to assemble enough strength in the biceps
department so that in a return postseason engagement with Atlanta,
the Astros no longer would have to feel as helpless as Pee Wee
Herman in an arm-wrestling match with Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Two words: Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight in the rubber game of the playoff preview, the Braves
finally get a taste of their own medicine when the Grand One takes
the mound against Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is an equally valid reason for the Braves to feel
just the slightest bit concerned about another meeting with the
Astros in the postseason, it is because Hunsicker correctly
concluded that it would not have been prudent to try to fight fire
with fire against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using barrels of Drayton McLane Jr.'s cash to bring
in pitching talent, Hunsicker chose to bolster the offense, and it
is the most solid, potent every-day lineup in club history, as much
as Johnson, that makes the Astros a threat to play deep into
October.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's 6-4 loss notwithstanding, this now is an Astros
team to be feared and not only on the nights when Johnson pitches.
</P>
<P>
   After using a six-single rally in the ninth inning that chased
John Smoltz and produced their 41st come-from-behind win Monday,
the Astros spotted the Braves a couple of homers by Chipper Jones
and Javy Lopez for a 4-1 lead and did battle back to tie the game
at 4-all against Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we fell behind the second time, I still thought we
had a chance,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``And we did hit a lot
of balls hard in the late innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, ask the Braves if they feel confident that they can
outscore this Astros team 16-5 in a cavalier three-game sweep. Ask
them if they expect the killer breeze from a combined .054 batting
average by Craig Biggio, Derek Bell and Jeff Bagwell to be all
they'll feel this time around from Houston bats.
</P>
<P>
   Not with Moises Alou playing like the National League MVP and
not with an overall Astros lineup that is deeper than an honors
philosophy class.
</P>
<P>
   In this year of Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and the homer, don't
forget that it is the Astros who lead the NL in runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our most most glaring weakness a year ago was being too
dependent on Jeff Bagwell to drive in runs,'' Hunsicker said.
``Sure, we could always use pitching. Everybody always can. But it
was more prudent, I think, for our club to spend our money on
getting another RBI man in the middle of our lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to be willing to acknowledge, in our position as
a mid-market club, is that you're always going to be an underdog to
a team with deep resources like Atlanta. While I believe that
pitching is the cornerstone to most championship teams, we're just
never going to be able to stack up talent in that area like the
Braves. They can keep throwing money out there, good after bad, if
that's what it takes. That's just a fact of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fact is that these Astros would not be this deep, this
solid across the board if they had re-signed free-agent starter
Darryl Kile. For though the deal to bring in Alou was made two
months before Kile's decision to run for the hills of Colorado,
keeping him likely would have meant giving up key parts of the team
in order to keep the budget in balance.
</P>
<P>
   It still says here the Astros' bid to re-sign Kile was a
public-relations ploy to keep the locals happy. Their true
intentions all along were to come up just short in the bidding, let
him go and spend the money in a wiser fashion, on players who could
help every day. It was a shrewd move and the right one. Now look
where it has gotten them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tie up 40 percent of your salary in pitching, you might
not have an offense strong enough to do the job,'' Hunsicker said.
``If your pitchers can't match up game-for-game with the Braves _
and they're the best, the yardstick _ then you still lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way, by solidifying our offense, we've given ourselves a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The season series is 4-4. Total runs are 27-26.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Randy Johnson. That's the Braves, a year later, holding
their breath.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-UNIT-MADDUX-HNS &LR;      09-02 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-UNIT-MADDUX-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Pitching matchups of this caliber usually are reserved
for opening day or the playoffs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This certainly isn't April, but it might feel a little bit like
October tonight when Randy Johnson and Greg Maddux do battle at
Turner Field. On paper, it's an attraction more cuddly than the
Beanie Babies the Braves are giving away.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some confusion regarding the authenticity of some
Beanie Babies, but there's no doubt about Johnson vs. Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   This is the genuine article.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux is quite simply the best pitcher of his generation,
having won four Cy Young Awards and anchoring perhaps the best
starting rotation in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson might very well be the most dominant lefthanded pitcher
ever to take the mound. He intimidates hitters with his 6-10 frame,
menacing stare and fastball that reaches 98 mph on the radar gun.
</P>
<P>
   At approximately 6:40 p.m. CDT, the job of being a big-league
hitter will be about as desirable as that of a crash-test dummy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be awesome,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio
said. ``You're talking about two of the best when you talk about
Randy Johnson and Greg Maddux. When I used to watch Randy on TV, I
just thought he was a chucker (a hard thrower), but he has an
excellent idea of how to pitch, just like Maddux. They're both
great pitchers. It's going to be fun for the fans and players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are very familiar with Maddux, who is 17-8 with a
2.12 earned run average against them in his career. However, most
of the Braves will be facing the Big Unit for the first time.
Johnson's last start against the Braves was May 7, 1989 _ 20 days
before the Montreal Expos traded him to the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just another major-league pitcher that we have to try to
go out there and beat,'' Braves center fielder Andruw Jones said.
``We just have to see what he's got. We can't get scared by the
name `Big Unit.' We just have to wait for our pitches and hit
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easier said than done, and Johnson has the numbers to
prove it. Since joining the Astros in a July 31 trade, Johnson is
5-1 with a 1.17 ERA. He has allowed only 31 hits in 46 innings
while striking out 61 batters, including 16 in his last outing.
</P>
<P>
   It's reasonable to assume some of Johnson's success could be
attributed to the fact he's facing a lot of hitters who never have
looked down the barrel of his rifle-like left arm. Then again,
Johnson hasn't seen most of his new opponents, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who it's an advantage for,'' Jones said. ``I
guess we'll just have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Those looking ahead to the postseason already are
second-guessing Astros manager Larry Dierker for allowing Johnson
to face the Braves tonight, the theory being it would give them a
chance to get a feel for him in anticipation of a possible playoff
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Randy wasn't pitching here,'' Biggio said. ``I think it
would be better if they didn't get to see him. But on the other
hand, Randy's stuff is nasty enough that you could see it as many
times as you wanted, and you still might not be able to do anything
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``I never gave it thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox is glad he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather see the guy,'' Cox said. ``I don't think it's the
most important thing in the world, but at least you'll know how
he's throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two games of the Astros-Braves series attracted an
average of 32,526 fans to Turner Field, but the marquee pitching
matchup and the Beanie Babies giveaway will help tonight's crowd
easily surpass that figure. Braves officials are expecting a crowd
in excess of 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy was a big deal in the American League, and he's a big
deal over here, too,'' Cox said. ``People want to see him, and I
want to see him, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
