<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES TOP METS, 9-8 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Mike Piazza could not save the New York Mets from
falling out of the National League wild-card lead for the first
time since Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza ripped a three-run homer on Tuesday night off Dan Miceli,
who had gone 20 straight outings without allowing a run, capping a
furious seven-run rally in the seventh inning that wiped out a
five-run Padres lead.
</P>
<P>
   Any hope of keeping pace with the Cubs vanished when Turk
Wendell allowed a game-tying two-run home run to Steve Finley with
no one out in the seventh, and then Dennis Cook forced in the
go-ahead run by walking Quilvio Veras on a full count with the
bases loaded and one out, giving San Diego a wild 9-8 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Piazza's heroics _ and those of role players such as
Matt Franco, Jay Payton and Jorge Fabregas _ in the end, the Mets
(76-62) had fought all the way back for naught. And, after
splitting the first eight games of this nine-game West Coast swing,
they still have one more to play here before they can head home for
a much-needed day off.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had not entered of September with a legitimate shot at
the post-season since 1990. Not until Tuesday, that is. But after
Greg Vaughn blasted his 46th and 47th home runs of the season off
Hideo Nomo just as Tony Gwynn came off the disabled list to go 3
for 3 with a pair of runs batted in, the Mets were in danger of
dropping behind the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Mets, who had sleep-walked through the first six
innings against a 29-year-old rookie named Stan Spencer, who was
making just his second major league start, erupted in the seventh
against Spencer and Miceli to erase a 6-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo followed his best outing as a Met with a dismal
performance, while the Mets' hitters were equally ineffective
against Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer held the Mets hitless for four and one-third innings
before Lenny Harris singled. Spencer then allowed a solo homer to
Edgardo Alfonzo with one out in the sixth and another to Brian
McRae leading off the seventh. The homer was McRae's career-high
20th of the season to go with his 20 stolen bases. After Harris
followed with a double to deep right center, Spencer was done for
the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who replaced John Olerud, singled Harris home from third
on a two-out, 1-2 count off reliever Dan Miceli to pull the Mets
within 6-3. The fun was just beginning. Payton, on the first pitch
of his first major league at-bat, singled to left to move Harris to
second. Alfonzo walked to load the bases. And up stepped Fabregas
to pinch-hit for Mel Rojas, in what had been Olerud's spot.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it looked as if Mets Manager Bobby Valentine had
given up on the game too soon by making a triple switch on defense
with his team trailing by 6-1 heading into the sixth. But Valentine
has faith in his role players. And Fabregas, like Franco had before
him, would reward that faith.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 1-2, in the count, he grounded a two-run single into right
to make the score 6-5. With runners on first and second, up stepped
Piazza, who has been carrying the Mets for almost a month now.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza had come into the game hitting .273 with runners in
scoring position as a Met. According to the Elias Sports Bureau,
Piazza was hitting only .224 with men in scoring position through
Aug. 16. Since then, he had been 9 for 21 (.429) with 2 homers and
14 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Piazza drilled a 2-1 pitch from Miceli into the seats
in right center field for his 27th homer of the year and a
short-lived 8-6 New York lead.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's homer ruined what had been a sparkling outing by
Spencer. In all, the 29-year-old right-hander was charged with
three runs and five hits in six-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres had made it easy on Spencer by knocking Nomo around
for five runs on five hits in the right-hander's four-inning stint.
Nomo was coming off a complete-game, three-hit victory in San
Francisco six days ago. But he walked the first batter he faced,
Veras, a portent of bad things.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Gwynn, who had missed San Diego's last 18 games with
an inflamed left Achilles' tendon and was playing for the first
time since Aug. 12. When Gwynn went on the disabled list, he was on
a 19-for-37 tear, which had lifted his average from .303 to .323.
And on the first pitch the eight-time National League batting
champion saw from Nomo, Gwynn doubled to right off Harris' glove
for a 1-0 Padres lead.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Vaughn _ whose stellar season has been lost in
the race between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa to break Roger Maris'
single-season home run mark _ drilled a 1-2 offering 439 feet to
left field for a two-run homer and a 3-0 lead. It was his 47th of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo responded by walking the next two batters he faced, before
somehow escaping the inning without further damage. But Vaughn led
off the third with his second homer of the night, a 393-foot shot
to left. And then Chris Gomez led off the fourth with a double, was
sacrificed to second and scored on a Veras sacrifice fly. It was
5-0 San Diego, and Nomo's evening was just about finished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
