A4244 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-02 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Astros rookie pitcher Scott Elarton learned another
major-league lesson Tuesday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``First loss I just don't want to get used to it,'' Elarton said
following a 6-4 setback to the Atlanta Braves at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The blame didn't fall completely on Elarton, who allowed the
Braves' go-ahead run in the sixth after the Astros had rallied from
a 4-1 deficit to tie the game. Sean Bergman lasted only four
innings, surrendering four runs on seven hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get that far behind (Atlanta) and hope to beat
them,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``But we did get back to
tie it. Even after we got back behind, I thought we hit the ball
well and put some pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the sixth, Elarton (1-1) sandwiched walks to
Andruw Jones and Curtis Pride around a Michael Tucker popout. Ozzie
Guillen broke the 4-4 tie with an RBI single just over the head of
second baseman Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go through some struggles. It's really the first
time I've struggled since I got here,'' said Elarton, called up
from Class AAA in June for two starts before earning a permanent
spot on the club in the bullpen. ``Eventually, it's going to
happen. I'll work through it, and next time out I'll get back to
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make the perfect pitch (to Jones), maybe too nasty.
I usually don't walk a whole lot of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio gave the Astros an early lead with a leadoff home run off
Braves starter Denny Neagle (14-11), his fourth to begin a game
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The game remained 1-0 until Bergman ran into trouble in the
fourth. After allowing several hard-hit balls earlier, he served up
a pair of home runs four batters apart. Chipper Jones led off the
inning with his 32nd home run of the season to tie the game at 1.
Andres Galarraga walked, Ryan Klesko singled, and Javy Lopez
smashed a three-run homer to left field _ his 32nd of the season _
to put the Braves ahead 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros and Braves have split the first two games of this
series and stand 4-4 for the season. If there's a silver lining for
the Astros in facing Greg Maddux tonight, it's that Eddie Perez
will catch for the Braves in place of Lopez, who has terrorized the
Astros this year and has seven home runs and 13 RBIs in his last
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, who continues to struggle after going 1-2 in five
starts last month, has allowed nine runs and 15 hits in his last 9
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in trouble most of the night,'' Bergman said. ``I got
some double-play balls to get out (of some jams) early. The fourth
inning I made a couple of bad pitches that hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   As bad as things appeared on the surface, the resilient Astros,
who scored three times in the ninth to win Monday's series opener,
staged yet another improbable rally against Neagle. In the fifth,
Bill Spiers tripled Biggio home and scored on Derek Bell's
groundout. In the sixth, Ricky Gutierrez tripled and scored the
tying run on Carl Everett's grounder.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind in the bottom of the sixth, the Astros
squandered a golden opportunity in the top of the seventh after
Bell reached on an error and Moises Alou walked. With one out and
Odaliz Perez on the mound, Dierker inserted pinch hitter Mitch
Meluskey, who grounded into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he opted not to use Sean Berry as a pinch hitter at
the time, instead saving him in anticipation the Braves would bring
in John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Rocker would come in late in the game,'' Dierker
said. ``Mitch walked 85 times and hit .350 down there (at New
Orleans). He's a tremendous on-base hitter. And here's a guy
(Perez) in his first big-league game, and he's already wild. I
thought there was a chance he might walk him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
