A4253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT     09-02 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
 
TOO NICE, TOO PERFECT TO COME TRUE AGAIN  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the history of major league baseball, no pitcher
has ever pitched two perfect games, so who could have thought on
Tuesday night that David Wells would pitch his second one in three
and a half months? The Oakland A's, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about it in the dugout, no doubt about that,''
Jason Giambi, the Oakland first baseman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Giambi is the reason Wells lost his chance for a historic second
perfect game. After the New York Yankees' guileful left-hander
retired the first 20 batters he faced, Giambi poked an 0-2
curveball to center field for a single.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Blowers would lead off the next inning with another single,
but it was Giambi's hit that burst Wells's magical balloon and
ended his quest for history.
</P>
<P>
   That's what this Yankees season is all about: history. Every
step they have taken this season either makes history or puts them
closer to making more history. Securing their 99th victory with a
7-0 decision over the Athletics, the Yankees on Wednesday night can
reach No. 100 sooner than any team has in major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of even more history lies beyond that victory.
But all of the victories the Yankees could amass this season would
not have matched the pitching of two perfect games by one pitcher.
In fact, two perfect games by the same pitcher might have exceeded
the remarkable feat of two hitters breaking the home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Wells had pitched to only 27 members of the
Minnesota Twins at the Stadium on May 17, the Athletics feared they
could join the Twins in the ignominy of not putting a man on base
against the same pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had great stuff, unbelievable stuff,'' Giambi said.
``Everything and anything was working. He was pitching me in with
fastballs and throwing me curveballs that had a late break. His
fastball was running in hard. It was the best stuff I've ever seen
him have definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   But after he threw strikes to Giambi with his first two pitches
with two out in the seventh inning, Wells threw a curveball up in
the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit if off the end of my bat,'' Giambi said. ``I just
happened to get good placement. When I started running down the
baseline, I saw where I hit it, the placement on it. I knew it was
up the middle enough that it would get through.''
</P>
<P>
   What did he think as he saw it fall in for a hit? ``Thank God,''
he said, letting out the same kind of sigh he probably released
when the ball hit the ground in center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics were relieved that they did not become Wells'
second perfect victims, but they did not appreciate the pitch calls
of the plate umpire, Jim McKean. In fact, their catcher, A.J.
Hinch, and their manager, Art Howe, got themselves thrown out of
the game in the sixth inning by expressing their opinions of what
they felt was McKean's expanded strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Howe especially believed McKean might help Wells get the perfect
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I voiced my displeasure,'' Howe said. ``I had
numerous complaints about the size of the strike zone the first
half of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager referred to the strike zone as ``very generous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomer's so good he doesn't need help,'' Howe said. ``But I
don't want to detract from his performance. It was outstanding. He
pitched a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinch, who said he has good relations with umpires because he is
behind the plate with them all the time, said he didn't intend to
get himself ejected after he took a third strike, making him one of
seven batters who went down that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole situation was built around frustration,'' Hinch
said. ``You've got 40-plus thousand people standing up cheering.
Wells is pitching a perfect game. I've battled him. I was deep in
the count. I had just fouled off a tough pitch. I felt the ball was
inside. There was a lot of frustration out of a lot of avenues. I
just snapped.''
</P>
<P>
   He also snapped his bat, slamming it against the ground and
winding up with a broken weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean for it to break,'' Hinch said. ``I slammed it
down maybe a little harder than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The catcher said he didn't remember McKean having such a big
strike zone, then added: ``But I don't know that we've faced a
pitcher like Wells that continually threw in there every time. If
the umpire's going to give you any liberty at all, he put it in
there nine out of 10 times. Who do you blame, the umpire or David
Wells?''
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson, who has a long history of disputing umpires'
strike calls against him, took called third strikes his first two
times at bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a hitter, you feel you know what a strike is and
what isn't a strike,'' Henderson said. ``He was calling a different
ball game. He was giving him a lot of pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Henderson saying McKean was helping Wells pitch a perfect
game? ``It helps,'' he said, ``but Wells is a great pitcher. You
can't take anything away from him. All he can do is throw the ball
in the location where he hits the spot. Then it's up to the umpire
to make the call. He was just doing what he thought was right. He
got the strike and stayed there. He kept painting that same spot,
the ball inside, the ball outside. The umpire was with him so he
kept putting it where he was calling a strike. He didn't have to
put the ball over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   If Wells had been forced to put the ball over the plate,
Henderson said, it might have been a different game. But he
nevertheless credited Wells with a fine performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the advantage, but I also felt he didn't need the
advantage,'' the veteran leadoff hitter said. He's such a great
pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Wells succeeded in retiring another seven batters without
allowing a hit or a base runner, he would have become an immortal
pitcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
