<HEADER>
A4333 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-RAILSIDER-HNS &LR;      09-02 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RAILSIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL PACKAGE OFFERS ITINERARY CHOICES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ The basic two-day Rocky
Mountaineer rail package works this way:
</P>
<P>
   Early morning departures are scheduled, roughly on alternate
days (with no Saturday departures), in each direction: eastbound
from Vancouver, British Columbia; westbound from Calgary and
Jasper, Alberta. All passengers travel between Vancouver and
Kamloops, British Columbia; the train is split between Kamloops and
the Alberta destinations. The only stops en route are for crew
changes; passengers must remain aboard.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 percent of the passengers choose the Vancouver-Banff
itinerary (585 miles). About 25 percent continue from Banff to
Calgary (another 82 miles) or travel between Vancouver and Jasper
(550 total miles).
</P>
<P>
   Overnight accommodations in a Kamloops hotel or motel _ with bus
transfers _ are included in the basic fare.
</P>
<P>
   While not inexpensive, the excursion is more affordable than
ever for Americans, thanks to the current favorable exchange rate
between the U.S. and Canadian dollars ($1 equals about $1.50). Two
service levels and price structures are offered:
</P>
<P>
   _ Easily the most popular is the line's Signature Service.
Assigned seats are provided in standard, single-level but spacious
cars that carry about 50 passengers each with one attendant. Each
car has picture windows and a small platform. A selection of cold
breakfasts and lunches are served both days airline-style at seats
(but the comfort level equals or surpasses most airlines'
first-class sections).
</P>
<P>
   One-way Signature Service costs through September, based on
double-occupancy and including four meals and the Kamloops lodging,
are $468 U.S. per person between Vancouver and Banff or Jasper and
$516 U.S. Vancouver-Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers can cut significantly into that cost by converting and
paying in Canadian funds; the Vancouver-Banff fare, for instance,
is $585 Canadian, which equates to about $390 U.S.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rocky Mountaineer's Goldfleaf dome-car service _ available
between Vancouver and Banff or Calgary but not to Jasper _ offers a
top-of-the-line experience. Views are more expansive from the upper
level. And with one dome car situated at the rear of the train
between Kamloops and Banff, its outdoor platform becomes a popular
gathering place.
</P>
<P>
   Four attendants, three dining personnel and a Dome manager cater
to Goldleaf passengers. Hot meals are served in the lower-level
dining room, and an elevator is available for passengers unable to
negotiate steep spiral staircases.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast options include Alberta steak and eggs, eggs Benedict
and a heaping Mountaineer platter that features smoked salmon,
fresh fruit, Belgian waffles, sausage, eggs and potatoes. Gourmet
luncheon entrees are preceded by soup or salad. Calgary-bound
passengers are provided dinner just before arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Goldleaf passengers also are given dinner vouchers (valued at
about $20) to use at their Kamloops hotel. Unlike Signature
Service, whose participants are allowed only carry-on luggage in
Kamloops, luggage is trucked and placed in hotel rooms prior to
check-in.
</P>
<P>
   Snacks and all nonalcoholic beverages are complimentary in both
categories; wine, beer and cocktails can be purchased. (Goldleaf
passengers are offered complimentary wine at lunch.)
</P>
<P>
   Goldleaf Service double-occupancy costs through September are
$868 U.S. between Vancouver and Banff and $948 U.S. between
Vancouver and Calgary. By paying instead in Canadian currency
($1,085 and $1,185, respectively), those costs can be reduced _ at
current exchange rates _ by about $150 U.S.
</P>
<P>
   One-way fares in both categories are about $80 lower for October
departures, and discounts are available for round-trip journeys.
Because only one hotel is involved, single supplements cost only
about $50.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers share a smoking car (the only place on the train
where smoking is permitted). Special-interest groups can reserve
cars outfitted to host weddings, corporate receptions, lecture
tours, seminars and other events.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen departures in each direction are scheduled in
September. The final 1999 departure is Oct. 15 from Vancouver. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Before or after the train journey, Rocky Mountaineer Railtours
also offers a wide range of group or independent tours by bus,
minivan, car or motorhome. Some combine all three train segments
with land packages in British Columbia and Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   Tours range in length from three to 11 nights. Costs vary widely
depending on the scope and hotel categories chosen: September
prices start at $836 U.S. ($1,045 Canadian) for a three-night,
four-day excursion that includes one night each in Vancouver,
Kamloops and Banff; prices start at $2,128 U.S. ($2,660 Canadian)
for an 11-night, 12-day circle trip that allows three nights each
in Banff, Jasper and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, to request a brochure or make
reservations, contact a travel agent or call 800-665-7245. On the
Internet, access http://www.rkymtnrail.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
