<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 04:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4334 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-RAIL-HNS &LR;      09-02 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE CANADIAN SPLENDOR FROM A TRAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Their colorful names merely hint
at the splendor of each panoramic vista on display from the upper
level of the Rocky Mountaineer's glass-enclosed dome carriage:
</P>
<P>
   Hell's Gate. Suicide Rapids. Rainbow Canyon. Jaws of Death
Gorge. Salmon Arm. Kicking Horse River. Three Sisters Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get ready to look to the left in one mile,'' an attendant
encourages as the train twists through the Canadian wilderness.
``At eye level, we'll pass a huge osprey nest atop a telephone
pole. Mama probably will be out in search of food. But look
closely, and you'll see a baby in the nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, and don't forget to keep watching for those fuzzy little
things. You never know when we'll come upon a bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Care for cheese, crackers and a glass of wine to tide you over
until lunch is served in the dining room downstairs?'' another
attendant is asking at your seat. She goes on to explain that
today's midday repast, in this ``Goldleaf Service'' dome car, will
require a choice from among six entrees, including fresh British
Columbia salmon and roasted Alberta Angus beef striploin.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. First, a brief history lesson:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, at Monte Creek, or Ducks Station, as it was known at the
time, Billy Miner _ the greatest train robber ever _ made his
biggest mistake.'' The first attendant again has the audience at
rapt attention. ``Billy robbed the wrong train. Got only $15 and
some liver pills. He was captured for an $11,500 dead-or-alive
reward and sent to prison in Kamloops.''
</P>
<P>
   The travel experience doesn't get much better than this. At
least not for those who appreciate gorgeous scenery, wondrous
wildlife, caring service, stellar cuisine, rich tradition and a
tinge of adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Only passengers addicted to a midday nap likely will be
disappointed by this Rocky Mountaineer Railtours two-day excursion,
which operates from early May to mid-October (with tentative plans
for additional Christmas-season trips) in either direction between
Vancouver, British Columbia, and Banff or Calgary, Alberta _ or
between Vancouver and Jasper, Alberta, on a partially different
route.
</P>
<P>
   Close your eyes, even for an instant, and risk missing the
majesty of a waterfall as it cascades seemingly forever down a
mountainside; the spunk of expert rafters who tumble almost
out-of-control over boulder-strewn rapids swirling just beyond the
train windows; or the how-dare-you-invade-my-natural-habitat,
point-blank stare of an elk or moose or bighorn sheep languishing
near the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   On carriages in two price categories _ the white-gloved Goldleaf
Service and more economical Signature Service _ an open-air viewing
platform, varying in size, enhances unrestricted viewing and
photography angles.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 optional land packages also are available. Among
temptations beyond the train departure and arrival cities:
enchanting Victoria, the year-round Whistler resort and the
Okanagan Valley wine-growing region in British Columbia; and Banff,
Lake Louise and the Columbia Icefield in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocky Mountaineer has revitalized passenger train travel
through some of North America's most spectacular countryside _ on
tracks that offer testimony to the courage, perseverance and
brilliance of 19th-century railroad pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   The stories from that era, all given new meaning during this
fascinating journey, are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers relive:
</P>
<P>
   _ The foresight of Canadian Pacific Railways president William
Van Horne who, in spearheading development of a rail line through
uncharted territories almost 120 years ago (and plotting the first
CP hotels as convenient rest stops along the route), declared, ``If
we can't export the scenery, we'll import the tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The sacrifice made by hundreds of laborers, including many
Chinese, who perished while bringing the project to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   _ The pride in driving the last spike of the Canadian Pacific at
Craigellachie, British Columbia, marking completion of Canada's
first transcontinental railway on Nov. 7, 1885, and in completing
the rival Canadian Northern (now Canadian National) route 30 years
later. (Today, the Rocky Mountaineer uses tracks owned by both
companies.)
</P>
<P>
   Almost as remarkable is that prior to this decade, few
modern-day travelers had the opportunity to visually appreciate
these engineering masterpieces. Or a landscape of steep and narrow
canyons, roaring rivers, crystal-clear lakes, valleys blanketed by
wildflowers and _ even in late-summer _ snow-capped mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1988, scheduled passenger trains inexplicably covered most
of the region only at night. For two subsequent years,
government-owned VIA Rail experimented with daylight service; then,
proposals were accepted toward turning the project over to private
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The first privately operated Rocky Mountaineer rolled out of
Vancouver on May 27, 1990. Its annual growth rate is now 25 percent
to 30 percent, according to a company spokesman, but don't fret
about getting a seat at the last moment: As bookings increase,
train carriages are added; on Sept. 12, 1996, a Canadian record was
established when 37 cars carried 1,100 passengers, and
blue-and-white Rocky Mountaineer engines routinely pull 20-25
carriages in midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Only a portion of the route _ between Kamloops and Calgary or
Jasper _ actually winds through the Rockies. But except for about
two hours departing (or approaching) Vancouver, scenic wonders
abound. A 16-page guide placed at each seat includes maps,
anecdotes and highlight listings that correspond to mileposts
situated beside the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the journey between Vancouver and Kamloops winds along
the walls of the Fraser and Thompson river canyons. During late
summer, bright red salmon are observed making their way eastward to
the Adams River spawning grounds. For about 10 miles, the train
proceeds through Rainbow Canyon, so named because minerals in the
rocks reflect a rainbow of colors and give the rocks a painted
look.
</P>
<P>
   At Hell's Gate, about 120 miles from Vancouver, more than 200
gallons of water per minute surge through a 110-foot-wide gorge.
Just as magnetizing is the Jaws of Death Gorge 30 miles to the
east.
</P>
<P>
   Even more riveting is the Kamloops-Banff segment, during which
the eastbound Rocky Mountaineer follows lovely Shuswap Lake, passes
through Sicamous _ dubbed the ``houseboat capital'' of Canada _ and
Craigellachie, then climbs into the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Train attendants provide background on many landmarks, including
Salmon Arm, a popular retirement center 60 miles east of Kamloops
and so named because spawning salmon once were so abundant that
settlers pitch-forked them from the river to use for fertilizer on
their fields.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Salmon Bay Nature Enhancement Reserve is home to more
than 150 species of birds and waterfowl. But a trip earlier this
month brought a sobering perspective: On this particular day,
forest fires were ravaging the area, forcing the evacuation of
thousands of residents. Train passengers, temporarily restricted to
indoor viewing to avoid smoke inhalation, watched as seaplanes
scooped into the lake and took on water to douse the flames.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 miles to the east, the train slows to a crawl _
``Kodak speed,'' an attendant describes the pace _ over Stoney
Creek Bridge, an architectural marvel that spans 484 feet and
hovers 325 feet above the creek bed.
</P>
<P>
   Also mesmerizing is the 30-mile journey _ including seven river
crossings _ through Kicking Horse Canyon, another challenge for
rafters.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the Continental Divide in the heart of the Rockies,
the Spiral Tunnels intrigue, too. The Lower Spiral, tunneled
through Mount Ogden, turns 230 degrees, covers 2,922 feet and
emerges 56 feet higher than its entrance. The Upper Spiral, through
Cathedral Mountain, turns 250 degrees, covers 3,255 feet and
emerges 50 feet higher than its entrance.
</P>
<P>
   No tunnel vision is allowed, though: not on one of the world's
most scenic train rides.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
