<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-10GAMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ten games that could decide the national championship
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TENNESSEE AT SYRACUSE
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5 at Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the best place for new Tennessee quarterback Tee
Martin to get his first start. It will get very loud and the
Syracuse defense will come after him. The Orangemen beat the last
SEC team (Florida) that dared visit the Carrier Dome. If Martin can
survive this trip with his confidence intact, he'll be ready when
Florida comes to Knoxville on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO STATE AT WEST VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5 at Morgantown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   A dangerous game for the Buckeyes, who are ranked No. 1 in both
of the major preseason polls. Ohio State is loaded again with 16
returning starters and great depth. But West Virginia has 17
starters returning, including running back Amos Zereoue, a Heisman
Trophy darkhorse. Fans and media are billing this as the biggest
home game ever at West Virginia. Ohio State's national championship
train could get derailed before it gets out of the station.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON AT ARIZONA STATE
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5 at Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   If Arizona State survives its opener against the Huskies, the
Sun Devils could run the table to the Pac-10 championship and earn
a spot in the Fiesta Bowl. That game, conveniently, will be played
on Arizona State's home field in Tempe. It will be the first game
back for Arizona State quarterback Ryan Kealy, a freshman
All-American in 1997, since he suffered a late knee injury last
season.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA AT TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 19 at Knoxville
</P>
<P>
   As always, the winner of this one has the edge in the SEC East
and remains in the hunt for the national title. Tennessee likes its
chances at home even without Peyton Manning. Florida, which tunes
up with The Citadel and NE Louisiana, should have all its
quarterback problems ironed out by then. The Vols have not beaten
the Gators since 1992. It will be a prime time (8 p.m.) showdown on
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   LSU AT FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 10 at Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Florida went into Baton Rouge ranked No. 1 and left
beaten and embarrassed 28-21 by an inspired LSU team. That loss,
plus the one to Georgia in Jacksonville, ultimately cost the Gators
a shot at their fifth straight SEC title. Now Florida gets the
Tigers in the Swamp in what could be a preview of the SEC
Championship game in December. Two years ago LSU came to
Gainesville and was trounced 56-13.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON AT NEBRASKA
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 26 at Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were the last visiting team to win in Lincoln and
this will be the first big test for new coach Frank Solich. A year
ago Nebraska traveled to Seattle and trounced Washington on the way
to the national championship. If Brock Huard stays healthy, this
time could be different for the Huskies. But don't bet on it.
Nebraska has won 42 straight home games since Washington last
visited.
</P>
<P>
   NEBRASKA AT KANSAS STATE
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 14 at Manhattan, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   If both teams stay undefeated, this will be the biggest football
game ever played at Kansas State. Both could be ranked in the top
five and a ton will be on the line. Nebraska has won 29 straight
games over the Wildcats and handed K-State its only loss in 1997, a
56-26 thumping. The Wildcats have 18 starters returning and
Nebraska is breaking in a new coach. If Kansas State doesn't beat
the Huskers this year, it never will.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA AT FLORIDA STATE
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 21 at Tallahassee
</P>
<P>
   The Gators knocked Florida State out of a chance for the
national championship by upsetting the Seminoles last year in
Gainesville. Bobby Bowden still hasn't gotten over it and his
Seminoles will be out for revenge. It will not be a game for the
faint of heart. Two years ago Florida State beat the Gators in
Tallahassee in a very physical game. The winner of this one will be
sore, but probably headed to the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN AT OHIO STATE
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 21 at Columbus, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   If both of these teams are still undefeated, the tension factor
in the Ohio State camp will be off the charts. The Buckeyes of John
Cooper have been one of the nation's top programs in the '90s
except for one glaring weakness: They are 1-8-1 in their last 10
meetings with Michigan. With the Buckeyes so high on everyone's
list, Ohio State fans just can't have their heart broken one more
time by the Maize and Blue. Or can they?
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA STATE AT ARIZONA
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 27 at Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Arizona State still had an outside shot at an
Alliance bowl when it was stunned at home by the Wildcats 28-16 in
the regular-season finale. This time the Pac-10 championship and
even a spot in the national championship game could be on the line
for the Sun Devils. Arizona returns 15 starters and has won four of
its last five meetings with Arizona State. Wildcats coach Dick
Tomey is in the last year of his contract and may need to win this
one to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
