<HEADER>
A4520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-ACC-SPOT-COX     09-02 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-ACC-SPOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC: FSU dominates, AGAIN
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After watching Florida State toy with the Atlantic Coast
Conference for the last six years, respected Virginia defensive
coordinator Rick Lantz is convinced it's not only overwhelming
physical talent that has made the Seminoles such a dominating force
in the league, as well as the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of Virginia's goal-line stand that resulted in a
1995 upset of the Seminoles _ to date their only conference loss
against 47 wins _ Lantz pointed to his own team's lapses as an
example of what the rest of the ACC must avoid if anyone hopes to
contend with Florida State consistently. After a big win at home
over Georgia Tech in November, the complacent Cavaliers got upset
at N.C. State and squandered a bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a letdown,'' Lantz said. ``Our concentration that week
of practice was not on getting ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The week before, Florida State calmly handled the hype of a game
at North Carolina, the first involving two ACC schools ranked in
the top five, and by a 20-3 score flattened the listless Tar Heels,
who have made the most strides in emulating Florida State's
athleticism. The matchup circled by ACC watchers nearly a year
before quickly turned into another methodical destruction in a
league that seems as far from being competitive at the top as when
FSU joined in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's talent is unquestioned again, as the Seminoles
are aiming to make another run at the national championship. But
after earnestly recruiting bigger and stronger athletes, their
rivals are seeing that cultivating a hard mental edge _ one sharp
enough to pull off a major upset at the very least _ may prove to
be just as difficult and important a hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap has closed physically, but Florida State has learned
how to win big games everywhere it plays,'' Lantz said. ``You have
to learn how to go into hostile stadiums and win. That's why they
win a lot of games the rest of us would have a hard time winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, using that talent to wear down the gamest opponents
is a supreme advantage. The Seminoles didn't put away Clemson until
the fourth quarter at Death Valley last year, finally getting a
90-yard punt return for a touchdown from the explosive Peter
Warrick, who blazed past weary Tiger defenders, setting in motion a
35-28 victory. The victory erased doubts that the Seminoles weren't
up to snuff and sent Clemson into a psychological swoon that took
most of the season to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we felt we should have won that game,'' Clemson
coach Tommy West said. ``There are teams in our league who have a
lot of good front-line players. But they've (Florida State) got
backups who could be frontline players. You lose a game by seven
points the way we did and it takes a lot out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's George O'Leary felt the same thing in Tallahassee
later in the year in a valiant first-half showing that couldn't
hold up over 60 minutes. Warrick's circus catch for a touchdown
near halftime broke a scoreless tie as well as the Yellow Jackets,
who suffered a 38-0 drubbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap is closing, but it's really about an attitude you have
to have about winning,'' O'Leary said. ``Do your kids believe they
can beat them?''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, the Seminoles must replace six
defensive starters, including ACC player of the year Andre
Wadsworth. Also gone are All-ACC quarterback Thad Busby,
All-America receiver E.G. Green and offensive lineman Tra Thomas, a
first-round NFL draft choice. Incredibly, they should be even
better and perhaps as fast a team as coach Bobby Bowden has ever
fielded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we lose in our league would be better for the league,
but not necessarily for Bobby Bowden,'' he said. ``Last year, North
Carolina was the best team we played. And Virginia always has given
us a great game. They've showed it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether Virginia's upset will become a museum piece or the
blueprint for genuine ACC parity won't be clear for perhaps a very
long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's improving, but there's always Florida
State,'' Duke coach Fred Goldsmith said. ``People in our conference
were closer to beating them than Miami was last year. But we don't
sit around and talk about closing the gap. Y'all are the ones doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
