<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-AROUND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE FOOTBALL PREVIEW: New coalition guarantees title game
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good friend of mine, we'll call him Tom, can always find a
cloud behind every silver lining. Give Tom a $40,000 Mercedes and
he'll complain if the cigarette lighter doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   It's people like Tom who are complaining about the new Bowl
Championship Series, the latest version of the dearly departed Bowl
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series _ made up of the Fiesta, Sugar,
Rose, and Orange bowls _ will guarantee that the two top-rated
teams in the country will meet in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4 for the
national championship. You might not agree on who those two teams
are, but the winner of that game will be the national champion.
After the Fiesta Bowl, you won't have to wait for the polls to be
released at O-Dark-Thirty the next morning to know who the champion
is.
</P>
<P>
   Tom doesn't like the Bowl Championship Series because he still
wants a playoff in Division I football. Get over it!
</P>
<P>
   A playoff is a good sports-bar conversation. But the reality is
that we're about five years and several billion dollars away from
even having a serious discussion about a playoff. Let's solve this
Y2K thing before we worry about a college football playoff, OK?
</P>
<P>
   He also complains about the new Bowl Championship Series formula
to determine the two teams which will play in the national
championship game. Instead of relying solely on the polls, which
are simply the opinions of the voters, the Bowl Championship Series
formula also will factor in strength of schedule and other
components to make the selection less subjective.
</P>
<P>
   You may not like or appreciate the process, but on Jan. 4 two
teams will play for all the marbles in Tempe, Ariz. And you will
like that.
</P>
<P>
   A few other things to ponder before the games begin:
</P>
<P>
   Milestones
</P>
<P>
   _ Penn State coach Joe Paterno needs only two victories to
become only the fourth Division I-A coach to win 300 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas running back Ricky Williams is 1,928 yards short of
breaking Tony Dorsett's all-time Division I-A rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   _ This will be the first season since 1941 that Grambling takes
the field without Eddie Robinson as its head coach. Doug Williams,
a former Grambling quarterback and Super Bowl MVP, takes over.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the first time since 1972, Nebraska will not have Tom
Osborne on the sidelines. Osborne retired with 255 wins in 25 years
and captured three national championships in his final four years.
Frank Solich is the new guy.
</P>
<P>
   _ This will be the WAC's last year as a 16-team conference.
Eight teams (Colorado State, Utah, BYU, Air Force, New Mexico,
UNLV, Wyoming, San Diego State) will break off in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On the hot seat
</P>
<P>
   These guys will spend time looking over their shoulder:
</P>
<P>
   _ Brad Scott is essentially starting over in his fifth season at
South Carolina. Not good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike DuBose will still be the coach at Alabama next year
whatever happens in 1998. But after going 4-7 in his rookie season,
the heat is really on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tommy West got a contract extension but is still hearing from
Clemson fans who want to compete for the ACC championship again.
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping the Heisman
</P>
<P>
   Williams gets an early boost _ we'll call it the ``Peyton
Manning Bump''_ by coming back. He will be the strong preseason
favorite, but here, in no particular order, are the others who will
contend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Daunte Culpepper, QB, Central Florida: Scared Nebraska to
death last year at Nebraska. Might be the most talented player in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Faulk, RB, LSU: With Cecil Collins gone, Faulk will have
to carry the load.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Couch, QB, Kentucky: Will put up some gaudy numbers again
but needs to cut down on his interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cade McNown, QB, UCLA: I'm not big on left-coast QBs, but this
guy is tough.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Bishop, QB, Kansas State: Going back to his JUCO days,
Bishop is 35-1 as a college quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
