<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-COACH-HOW2-COX     09-02 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-COACH-HOW2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College coaching strategies
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JIM DONNAN,
</P>
<P>
   HEAD COACH,
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   ``THE DOUBLE SPLIT''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Donnan believes that one way to handle excessive defensive
pressure is with multiple formations that keep the other team
guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to give them enough stuff outside of your base
offense so that they aren't comfortable running their base
defense,'' Donnan says. ``By moving your people around, you hope to
slow them down and eventually get some mismatches.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan's ability to mix up his formations and keep a nationally
ranked defense off balance played a major role in Georgia's 37-17
upset of No. 6 Florida last November in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   On this play, which is usually run near the goal line, Georgia
goes to the line of scrimmage in a basic formation with two tight
ends. Before the ball is snapped, both tight ends split wide,
forcing the cornerbacks to cover them man-to-man. Also before the
ball is snapped, the flanker goes in motion from the left side to
the right.
</P>
<P>
   On the snap, the tight end on the right side goes right at the
cornerback and breaks his route inside and to the left. If the
cornerback goes with the tight end, the flanker should be open in
the end zone. If the corner goes with the flanker, he'll be taken
out of the play and the tailback should be open out in the flat
with only a linebacker to beat for the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you try to show them something complicated and then
run something easy,'' Donnan says. ``You can't be predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   STEVE SPURRIER,
</P>
<P>
   HEAD COACH,
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   ``THE FADE''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, LSU brought its version of the high-pressure
defense to Florida's Ben Hill Griffin Stadium. Coach Steve Spurrier
and quarterback Danny Wuerffel were ready.
</P>
<P>
   LSU's cornerbacks tried to pressure Florida's receivers with
tight coverage while bringing maximum pressure on Wuerffel.
Spurrier responded with his favorite play against pressure: ``The
Fade.''
</P>
<P>
   The play is simple but the execution must be precise. On the
snap, the two Florida receivers run straight toward the
cornerbacks, make slight outside turns, then go racing down the
sidelines. The quarterback takes only a three-step drop and throws
the ball even before his chosen receiver has gotten any separation
from his defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing the defensive coaches hate to see is the ball
getting out of there,'' Spurrier says. ``So we believe in getting
the ball up in the air and giving our receivers a chance to make a
play.''
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Florida led 42-6. In the second half, LSU's
shell-shocked defense began using six defensive backs, and the
Gators responded by running the football. When it was over, Florida
had 635 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier took particular joy in that one. Earlier in the week,
LSU defensive coordinator Carl Reese had gone on ESPN and
diagrammed how his high-pressure defense would work against the
Gators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess we won't have too many opposing coaches giving chalk
talks any more,'' Spurrier said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   BILL OLIVER,
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   COORDINATOR,
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN
</P>
<P>
   ``A DEFENSIVE BACK'S DREAM''
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas morning 1992, Bill Oliver sat in his office
hatching a plan. In just seven days, his Alabama defense would go
up against No. 1 Miami and quarterback Gino Torretta in the Sugar
Bowl. The national championship was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver decided to try to confuse Torretta with a series of
unusual formations that included as many as seven defensive backs.
Many times it appeared that the Crimson Tide had 11 defensive
players on the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to never let him get comfortable,'' Oliver says.
``We wanted him to be guessing on every play.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen times during the game Oliver showed Torretta a
formation with seven defensive backs. One of those plays determined
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 20-6, Torretta had his team in a shotgun formation.
Alabama pulled all 11 of its players to within a yard of the line
of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Torretta changed his protection, preparing for an all-out blitz.
But on the snap, eight Alabama defenders backed into pass coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Torretta threw into the teeth of the coverage. George Teague
intercepted and returned the ball 31 yards for a touchdown. Alabama
went on to win the game 34-13 and the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who became Auburn's defensive coordinator in 1995, used
some of the same principles to confuse Peyton Manning at times in
last season's SEC championship game against Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Manning looked confused at times but was able to make enough
plays for the Vols to win 30-29.
</P>
<P>
   BOBBY STOOPS,
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   COORDINATOR,
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   ``BLITZ OR BAIL OUT?''
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Bobby Stoops faced a problem. His Kansas
State defense was giving up too many yards, despite what he thought
was a good collection of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great corners and safeties and pretty good guys at
linebackers,'' Stoops says. ``But people seemed to be doing what
they wanted to against us.''
</P>
<P>
   So Stoops decided to take advantage of his team's athleticism at
defensive back and linebacker to put greater pressure on the
quarterback and the line of scrimmage. Stoops brought his
linebackers closer to the line of scrimmage, even to the point of
putting one over the tight end. The cornerbacks would play tight on
the receivers, and the strong safety also would get closer to the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to stop the run by putting one more man up there
than they can possibly block,'' Stoops says. ``If everybody does
their job, they shouldn't be able to run it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was an additional wrinkle. From that formation,
Stoops' defense was in position to bring a maximum blitz on the
quarterback every play. Sometimes, they would blitz. Sometimes,
they would fake it and drop into pass coverage, what coaches call
``bailing out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to keep the quarterback guessing,'' Stoops says.
</P>
<P>
   The concept worked. By 1995, Kansas State led the nation in
total defense. In 1996, Stoops was hired as defensive coordinator
at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
