</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-DREAM-COX     09-02 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-DREAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE DREAM TEAM: South boasts a bevy of precious players
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In their private moments, coaches dream of what it would be like
to have the perfect player at every position _ one who meets or
exceeds all of the physical and mental standards to excel, without
flaw or weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coaches are particularly guilty of it. As college
defenses have become faster and more sophisticated over the past 15
years, coaches have been searching for athletes with just the right
qualities to make those defenses work. Once in a great while, just
the right athlete comes along. When that happens, it is coaching
nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been lucky to have coached some great ones,'' said
Auburn's Bill Oliver, recognized as one of football's leading
defensive gurus. ``And when I had a great one, I thanked the Lord
for it every night. It's amazing how smart those guys can make you
look.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches interviewed had some very specific ideas about what
kind of athletes are best-suited to play the various defensive
positions. If they could design the perfect athletes, they would be
something like this:
</P>
<P>
   CORNERBACK
</P>
<P>
   With the evolution of faster defenses, which puts more pressure
on the secondary, it has become one of the glamour positions in
college football. The best cornerbacks, according to the coaches,
range in height from 5-11 to 6-2 and rarely weigh more than 190
pounds. They don't have to have blazing speed, but they must have
quickness in both their hands and feet. They also must have good
hand-eye coordination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found that guys who were great basketball or baseball
players in high school make the best corners,'' said Bobby Stoops,
Florida's defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   For most coaches, the best pure corner in recent memory is
Florida State's Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver takes issue. He turned Antonio Langham into an
All-American in 1992 and 1993 when he was defensive coordinator at
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Antonio, you could set up your defense and literally take
half the field away,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Both made the coaches' All-Southern Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, the safety was a quasi-linebacker who was
counted on for run support and very limited pass coverage. As
offenses have become more sophisticated and are spreading the field
with as many as four wide receivers, the big, slow safety went the
way of the dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is too fast now, so we had to take those old safeties
and make linebackers out of them,'' said Carl Torbush, head coach
and former defensive coordinator at North Carolina. ``Today, a
safety doesn't have to be as fast or as good a cover guy as a
corner. But he better be close, or you'll get burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Good safeties, say the coaches, can be a little bit bigger than
corners and go over 200 pounds. They have to be fast enough to
cover receivers deep but a good enough tackler to run up and make a
stop on the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Bennie Blades (6-0, 215) was one of the first of these
new safeties when he won the 1987 Jim Thorpe Award, which goes to
the nation's best defensive back. He and two-time Clemson
All-American Terry Kinard are the Dream Team safeties.
</P>
<P>
   OUTSIDE LINEBACKER
</P>
<P>
   These men have become the raptors of college football. They must
be big enough, usually in the 230-240-pound range, and strong
enough get rid of a 280-pound pulling guard and make the tackle.
They also must be fast enough to chase down running backs and wide
receivers and, occasionally, cover those guys deep.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of great ones have roamed Southern football in the modern
era, including Jessie Armstead and Darrin Smith of Miami, Sam
Cowart of Florida State and Wilber Marshall of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy probably needs to be the best athlete on your team,''
Stoops said.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly was true at Alabama from 1984-1986 when Cornelius
Bennett was a three-time All-American. He was the 1986 Lombardi
Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and two-time All-American Aundray Bruce of Auburn get
the spots on the coaches' Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE LINEBACKER
</P>
<P>
   Before speed became such an important factor in the game, the
inside linebacker did not need to be particularly fast. He was
primarily responsible for run support inside the tackles. Today's
inside linebacker might be called on to pick up a running back
going out for a pass and follow him all the way down the field.
Today he's got to have size _ about 6-3, 240 _ and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted our guy to be the kind of athlete that nobody would
challenge,'' said former Miami Hurricanes coach Jimmy Johnson, now
with the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had its fair share of great ones in the middle, including
Ray Lewis and Micheal Barrow, but the Dream Team spot goes to
Marvin Jones of Florida State. Of all the players drafted at
Florida State, Jones was the highest pick, as the Jets' took him
fourth in the 1993 draft. As a junior, he had 111 tackles and won
the Butkus and Lombardi awards.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE END
</P>
<P>
   The ends have one mission in the new, speed-oriented defenses:
To meet each other in the backfield as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have got to be strong, but it's more important that
they be quick enough to get around blocks,'' Stoops said. ``Their
job is to get into the backfield and cause as much damage as fast
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical defensive end is about 6-4 and can range anywhere
from 240 to 270 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them to be big enough to take on the offensive tackle
every play, but I'll never sacrifice speed for size,'' Torbush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama had what many consider the best pair of defensive ends
on one team in 1992 when Eric Curry and John Copeland led the
Crimson Tide to the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys set the tone,'' Oliver said. ``They were something
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry gets one of the slots on the Dream Team, while the other
goes to Miami's Greg Mark, the school second all-time sack leader
with 34 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE TACKLE
</P>
<P>
   In previous generations, the defensive tackle could be big and
slow. His job was to clog up the middle and grab anybody who
happened to run by. No more.
</P>
<P>
   Today's defensive tackle can tip the scales near 300 pounds, as
Florida's Ed Chester and LSU's Anthony McFarland do. But they also
have to be fast enough to get into the backfield and pressure the
quarterback when opponents pass.
</P>
<P>
   When opponents run, tackles must be strong enough to stuff their
blockers and slow down the development of the play. The newer
defensive schemes rely on the tackles to shut down the run in order
to allow the linebackers and defensive backs room to take advantage
of their speed and make big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our tackles are playing well, there is a good chance we're
going to control the line of scrimmage,'' Stoops said. ``That's
where it all starts.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of dream defensive tackles to choose from.
Miami had two great ones in Russell Maryland and Warren Sapp.
Auburn's Tracy Rocker was an Outland Award winner. But Virginia
Tech's Bruce Smith (Buffalo) and Tennessee's Reggie White (Green
Bay) have been to the most Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   THE COACHES' ALL-SOUTHERN DEFENSIVE DREAM TEAM
</P>
<P>
   _ DE _ Eric Curry, Alabama, 1990-92
</P>
<P>
   _ DE _ Greg Mark, Miami, 1986-89
</P>
<P>
   _ DT _ Bruce Smith, Virginia Tech, 1981-84
</P>
<P>
   _ DT _ Reggie White, Tennessee, 1980-83
</P>
<P>
   _ OLB _ Cornelius Bennett, Alabama, 1983-86
</P>
<P>
   _ OLB _ Aundray Bruce, Auburn, 1984-87
</P>
<P>
   _ ILB _ Marvin Jones, Florida State, 1990-92
</P>
<P>
   _ CB _ Deion Sanders, Florida State, 1985-88
</P>
<P>
   _ CB _ Antonio Langham, Alabama, 1989-93
</P>
<P>
   _ S _ Bennie Blades, Miami 1985-87
</P>
<P>
   _ S _ Terry Kinard, Clemson, 1979-82
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mention
</P>
<P>
   _ DE _ John Copeland, Alabama; Art Still, Kentucky; Andre
Wadsworth, Florida State
</P>
<P>
   _ DT _ Warren Sapp, Russell Maryland, Dan Stubbs, Miami; Tracy
Rocker, Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   _ MLB _ Jeff Davis, Clemson; Micheal Barrow, Ray Lewis, Miami
</P>
<P>
   _ OLB _ Darrin Smith, Jesse Armstead, Miami; Sam Cowart, Derrick
Brooks, Florida State; Wilber Marshall, Florida
</P>
<P>
   _ CB _ Terrell Buckley, Leroy Butler, Florida State
</P>
<P>
   _ S _ Jarvis Williams, Florida; Jake Scott, Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
