<HEADER>
A4525 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-SEC-EAST-COX     09-02 3371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-SEC-EAST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE FOOTBALL PREVIEW: SEC East capsules
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   GATORS
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 39,500.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 10-2, 6-2 SEC (T-2nd, East); beat Penn State 21-6
in Citrus Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 6, defense 6.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Steve Spurrier is 83-16-1 in eight years at Florida,
138-48-2 overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: Florida will win its fifth SEC championship in
the past six seasons because the Gators will field their best
defense in 1998. No team in America has a better front seven on
that side of the ball. Whether Florida will contend for the
national championship depends on the development of an offense,
where some questions persist. Either Doug Johnson or Jesse Palmer
must become a consistently productive quarterback. Spurrier doesn't
need to spend the season juggling the two and dealing with a
quarterback controversy every day. He also has to find a top
receiver from a group of young talented ones.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   7 Junior Doug Johnson, who was in and out of Spurrier's doghouse
last season, is recovering from shoulder surgery. Sophomore Jesse
Palmer, who has limited experience, will start early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   8 Fred Taylor is gone, but in his place will be senior Terry
Jackson, who sat out last season with a knee injury. Jackson is the
emotional leader of the offense and one of the most versatile
players around.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   7 Jacquez Green departed with a year of eligibility remaining,
so a big-play receiver must step forward.One of a group of talented
sophomores could fill that role. Nafis Karim and Travis McGriff are
dependable.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   9 Eight linemen with starting experience return, led by tackle
Zach Piller and guard Ryan Kalich, three-year starters on the left
side. A couple of newcomers, Notre Dame transfer Leon Hires and
redshirt freshman Kenyetta Walker could push for playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   10 No team in the country can match the front four of tackles Ed
Chester and Reggie McGrew and ends Willie Cohens and Tim Beauchamp.
But the four guys backing them up are almost as good.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   9 Defensive coordinator Bobby Stoops did some juggling in order
to get his three best guys _ _ Jevon Kearse, Mike Peterson and
Johnny Rutledge _ on the field. Kearse is one of the most
impressive physical specimens in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   7 Strong safety Tony George moves to corner, where he will make
a lot of plays. He won't be missed at SS, as Rod Graddy has emerged
as a future star. Teako Brown is back at free safety after
intercepting six passes last season.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   7 Practice had barely started when punter Robby Stevenson landed
in Spurrier's doghouse. He might lose his job to freshman David
Wasielewski or walk-on Josh Korn. Placekicker Collins Cooper also
will be challenged by the freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   10 Florida missed out on its fifth straight SEC championship in
1997, but Spurrier and his staff won 10 games and upset No. 1
Florida State. With Spurrier calling the plays and Stoops running
the defense, this is one of the nation's strongest staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   7 There are two breathers _ The Citadel, NE Louisiana _ to open
the season, but the two biggest games _ Florida State and Tennessee
_ are on the road. It will be difficult for the Gators to win both
of them.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   VOLUNTEERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 25,489.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 11-2, 7-1 SEC (1st, East); beat Auburn 30-29 in
SEC championship game; lost to Nebraska 42-17 in Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 8, defense 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Phillip Fulmer is 54-11 in six years at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: Life must go on without Peyton Manning, and it
will quite nicely in Big Orange country. As strange as it sounds,
the offense actually could be better under junior quarterback Tee
Martin, a more versatile player than Manning. The line has matured,
as has tailback Jamal Lewis of Atlanta. Just about all the concerns
come on the defensive side of the ball, where six starters are
gone. The key is the month of September, when the Vols face
Syracuse and Florida. If the Vols win both of those, they could run
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   7 Martin earned the confidence of the Tennessee players by
leading a touchdown drive against Nebraska in the Orange Bowl.
Martin had a very good spring practice. But he must stay healthy,
because there is no experienced backup.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   10 Lewis was a freshman All-American after rushing for 1,364
yards and has returned faster and stronger after a summer of hard
workouts. He'll be the workhorse, but he'll get some help from
underrated fullback Shawn Bryson.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   9 Marcus Nash is gone with his 76 catches, but the Vols still
have the SEC's best one-two punch in Jeremaine Copeland (58
catches) and Peerless Price (48 catches). Price finally is back at
full speed after an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   10 Center Trey Teague is the only starter not returning, so the
Vols might have to do some juggling to get their five best players
on the field. Tackles Cosey Coleman and Chad Clifton are serious
talents.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   6 The Vols will find it difficult to replace tackle Bill Duff
and end Jonathon Brown. And it didn't help that five defensive
linemen missed spring practice because of various injuries. Two key
questions to be answered: Can end Shaun Ellis recover completely
from a spring car accident? Can tackle Billy Ratliff stay healthy?.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   7 Al Wilson moves to the middle and will be one of the SEC's
best against the run. If Eric Westmoreland comes back fully from a
knee injury, he'll join Raynoch Thompson to give the Vols two good
ones on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   6 Only one starter returns, but cornerback Dwayne Goodrich is a
good one. Experience gives Steve Johnson the edge at the other
corner, but he will be pushed. Sophomore Deon Grant has a lock on
free safety, but Fred White of Griffin will have to work to hold on
to the strong safety position.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   8 Jeff Hall is a three-time All-SEC kicker and apparently has
solved the back troubles that bothered him early last season.
Punter David Leaverton has one of the nation's strongest legs but
must learn to kick under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   9 Fulmer has won 50 games in the past five seasons, and now he
has an SEC championship. That should quiet some of the critics.
Beating Florida this year would quiet the rest of them.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   6 Tennessee must open at Syracuse, never an easy place to play.
After a week off, Florida comes to town with a five-game winning
streak against the Vols. Tennessee also has to visit Auburn and
Georgia in its first five games.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   BULLDOGS
</P>
<P>
   72
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Athens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 30,149.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1997 record: 10-2, 6-2 SEC (T-2nd, East); beat Wisconsin 33-6
in Outback Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 4, defense 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Jim Donnan is 15-8 in two years at Georgia, 79-29
overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: The Bulldogs took a huge step back to
respectability last season with their first 10-win season since
1992 and their first win over Florida since 1989. Donnan and his
staff followed that up with a top-five recruiting class. With the
losses of quarterback Mike Bobo, running back Robert Edwards, and
all-purpose receiver Hines Ward, it's hard to see Georgia repeating
last season's magic. But if the Bulldogs get better than expected
play from one of their young quarterbacks and if one of the running
backs turns into a top player, they could make some noise in the
SEC East.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   6 Freshmen Quincy Carter and Nate Hybl have a real chance to
play early, with redshirt freshman Daniel Cobb still uncertain
while he takes blood thinners. Jon England and Mike Usry have taken
snaps but have done little with them.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   8 Olandis Gary and Patrick Pass have had their moments, but
neither has proved he can be the featured back. The X-factor is
Jasper Sanks, the top signee of 1997, who was in prep school last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   6 Senior Tony Small (26 catches) is the guy everybody hopes will
step up. Michael Greer has shown a knack for getting open and
making big catches. The group will be helped by the occasional use
of cornerback Champ Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   8 After this season, tackles Matt Stinchcomb and Chris Terry
both will be playing on Sunday. Georgia needs some rebuilding in
the middle, but Steve Herndon and Jonas Jennings should be good at
the guards. The key is center, where Miles Luckie needs to come
through in replacing Brad Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   9 Georgia is deeper and more talented here than it has been in
more than a decade. Ten lettermen, all good, are fighting for four
positions. Marcus Stroud and Antonio Cochran will handle the ends
while senior Emarlos Leroy will have a big season at nose guard.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   7 Gone are Greg Bright and Brandon Tolbert, who combined for 75
starts the past four seasons. Orantes Grant (81 tackles) is back at
his outside spot, and sophomore Adrian Hollingshed should land
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   8 Bailey is an All-America corner and free safety Kirby Smart
will make some All-SEC teams. Senior Glenn Ford can handle the
other corner.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   5 Placekicker Hap Hines struggled as a sophomore, and the hope
is that he'll regain his freshman form. If he doesn't, sophomore
Chad Holleman will push him. Punter is an even greater concern with
a host of players, including some walk-ons, battling for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   9 Jim Donnan's program got a huge shot of credibility last
season. In wins over Florida and Georgia Tech, Donnan proved he can
call plays with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   6 Mississippi State goes off the schedule and a road game with
LSU comes on. Georgia also has to play LSU and Tennessee in
consecutive weeks in October. Trips to Kentucky and Auburn could be
dangerous in addition to the Florida game in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY
</P>
<P>
   WILDCATS
</P>
<P>
   66
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 24,378
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 5-6, 2-6 SEC (5th, East).
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 9, defense 6.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Hal Mumme is 5-6 in one year at Kentucky, 70-33-1
overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: There's no mystery about what Kentucky must do
to take its program to the next level, which would be a bowl bid.
The Wildcats must improve a defense that was dead-last in the SEC
in points allowed, giving up 32.91 per game. All too often, that
defense negated the best efforts of quarterback Tim Couch, who led
the Wildcats to 31.64 points per game, third best in the SEC.
Kentucky should make some strides, having signed 19 defensive
players last February. How big the strides will be remains to be
seen. Kentucky should move ahead of South Carolina to fourth in the
SEC East.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   9 Couch broke or tied 17 school and 10 SEC passing records with
3,884 yards last season. Now he must reduce his 19 interceptions
and show that he has matured as a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   7 The Wildcat backs are better than most folks know. Derek Homer
averaged 5.7 yards per carry while Anthony White averaged 5.6.
White also caught 59 passes out of the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   8 Craig Yeast caught everybody's attention last season when he
grabbed 73 passes for 873 yards. Kevin Coleman (52 catches) is also
a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   8 Four of five starters are back but the Wildcats will miss
guard John Schlarman, the leader on that unit. The good news is
that Kentucky will start five seniors, led by tackles Jonas Liening
and Kris Comstock.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   5 Kentucky recruited five defensive ends in hopes of improving a
front wall that was simply terrible a year ago. The tackles, Marvin
Major and Mark Jacobs, are respectable but there is a lot of work
to do at end.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   5 Jeff Snedegar returns after posting 97 tackles last season but
he needs some help. Dennis Johnson, the USA Today high school
defensive player of the year last season, will start at outside
linebacker. Other freshmen may be needed here as well.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   4 The good news: FS Willie Gary of Valdosta is back after
earning freshman All-America honors from The Sporting News. Now the
bad news: Gary is Kentucky's best and most experienced player in
the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   7 Punter Jimmy Carter rarely gets a chance to boom one because
Mumme prefers to keep opponents from returning kicks. Still he
averaged 40.2 yards. Seth Hanson won't get that many field-goal
tries because Mumme knows his team must score as many points as
possible to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   8 Mumme has made a smooth transition from Division II football
and has shown he can call plays with the big boys. He kept his
staff together and wisely went out and recruited some defensive
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   5 The first three games against Louisville, Eastern Kentucky and
Indiana are all winnable. But then the Wildcats play three of the
next four on the road at Florida, Arkansas and LSU. There is also a
road trip to Tennessee to finish the season. The SEC home games
with South Carolina, Georgia, Mississippi State and Vanderbilt will
determine if Kentucky has a winning season.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   GAMECOCKS
</P>
<P>
   57
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 26,346.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 5-6, 3-5 SEC (4th, East).
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 7, defense 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Brad Scott is 22-22-1 in four years at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: Scott made a painful discovery in 1997. He spent
four years trying to install the fast-break offense he used so
effectively at Florida State. Then he learned the offense is only
effective if backed up by a superior defense. South Carolina's
defense was anything but, finishing 10th in the SEC while giving up
24.82 points per game. So in this fifth season in Columbia, Scott
has junked that offensive philosophy in favor of a power running
game to hopefully control the ball and keep his defense off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   7 Anthony Wright returns after a severe knee injury in the ninth
game last season. Redshirt freshman Phil Petty is the backup, but
true freshman Keith Matkins of Charlotte is too talented not to get
a look.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   7 Troy Hambrick has rushed for 885 yards in his first two
seasons and will be the power back, with speedy Boo Williams giving
the team a change of pace. Dependable Steve Mixon will handle the
fullback job.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   7 Zola Davis has had an up-and-down career, but he still needs
54 catches to become the school's all-time leading receiver. That
won't happen because sophomore Jermale Kelly is the main man after
catching 10 touchdown passes a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   4 Things are so bad that Jamar Nesbit, an All-SEC tackle, may be
moved to center. Andray Spearman, a returning starter at tackle, is
the only other person who has played on the offensive line, which
will be filled out by redshirt freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   5 End John Abraham is a talented player, but he's not going to
get a lot of help from the cast of characters that return. Matt
Marsters will play the other end, but he's a bit small.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   5 There is some talent here, but most of it is young. OLB Corey
Atkins (77 tackles), is the lone veteran. Marco Hutchinson played
as a true freshman and Darion Hutcherson enrolled last January.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   6 This was going to be the bright spot on the defense until 11
days ago when safety Arturo Freeman, an All-SEC preseason pick, was
knocked out for the season with a knee injury. So the Gamecocks
will have two new safeties to play with veteran corners Homer
Torrance and Kevin Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   7 Placekicker Steve Florio is dependable after hitting nine of
13 field goals last season. Punter Courtney Leavitt settled down
after a shaky start to his career and averaged 40.9 yards per kick.
Williams led the SEC in kickoff returns last season with a 29.3
average.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   6 Scott is feeling some serious heat as it appears Kentucky has
surpassed the Gamecocks in the SEC East pecking order. Scott
brought in two new offensive coaches, Chuck Reedy and Woody
McCorvey, in hopes of turning things around.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   3 A nightmare. The traditional brutal finish _ Tennessee,
Florida and Clemson _ is still there. The Gamecocks also have to
play the first nine weeks of the season without a break. After four
straight home games to open the season, they play five of the final
seven on the road.
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT
</P>
<P>
   COMMODORES
</P>
<P>
   56
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 10,000
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 3-8, 0-8 SEC (6th, East).
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 7, defense 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Woody Widenhofer is 3-8 in one year at Vanderbilt,
15-39-1 overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: Last season Vanderbilt proved defense will keep
you competitive, but it won't win a lot of games. The Commodores
led the SEC in defense (277.09 ypg) and were ninth nationally but
did not win a conference game. The problem was a truly awful
offense that finished 11th in the conference (275.45 ypg).
Widenhofer went out and hired Steve Crosby, who has 21 years of NFL
experience, as his new offensive coordinator. Crosby installed a
new one-back, pass-oriented offense in the spring. Now the
Commodores must recruit enough talent to run it.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   3 The Commodores have six reasonably talented quarterbacks, but
none of them has ever played a college down. Junior Hi Lewis should
be the starter, but he could be pushed by a true freshman like 6-6
Sean O'Connor, an all-state player from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   5 Jared McGrath turned some heads as a freshman with 491 yards
rushing and will get some help from highly regarded redshirt
freshman Rodney Williams. This position was good enough to move
sophomore Jimmy Williams, the team's leading rusher last season, to
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   4 Todd Yoder (21 catches) and Tavarus Hogan (20 catches) are the
proven veterans, but they will get some help from redshirt freshman
Adam Ditto, who made a bid to start when he caught nine passes for
200 yards in the spring game.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   6 Four starters are back with five other lettermen to provide
some depth. Tackles Clay Condrey and Raminite Byndom have taken
their lumps over the past two seasons and should finally be ready
to play with the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   7 The inside play will again be solid with the return of Ryan
Aulds, a freshman All-American last season. If end Alphonso Harvey
can stay in shape, it will again be tough to run against the
Commodores.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   7 All three starters are gone, including All-SEC Jamie Duncan.
Redshirt freshman Jamie Winborn takes over for Duncan in the
middle. Matt Stewart and Lamont Turner will handle the outside
spots but will be pushed by talented youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   9 Despite the loss of All-SEC corner Corey Chavous, the group
will still be very, very good. Corner Fred Vinson will be an
all-conference player and Jimmy Williams, a former running back, is
a star in the making at the other corner.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   4 Punter Joe Webb needs to improve on his 38.9 average as a true
freshman, particularly if Vanderbilt is going to struggle on
offense. John Markham hit eight of 13 field goals as a true
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   7 Widenhofer, a former defensive coordinator for the Pittsburgh
Steelers, has done a masterful job of upgrading the program with
defense. Now he has to get the offensive problems ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   4 The Commodores open with two straight road games at
Mississippi State and Alabama. They finish with Florida, Kentucky,
and Tennessee. Winning non-conference games with Duke, Western
Michigan and TCU is imperative.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
