</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-SEC-SPOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC: Gators are team to beat
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most fun things about the beginning of a new college
football season is that all the questions finally start getting
answered. After endless months of speculation in print and over the
air, reality rules the day.
</P>
<P>
   In no conference are there more offseason questions than in the
SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Take the quarterback position. Only three SEC teams _ Kentucky,
LSU, and Arkansas _ will enter the fall secure in their starting
quarterback. The others still have questions, because of
graduation, injury or ineffectiveness. It could make for a wacky
year, league coaches say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the league is like this, you'd just better hold on,''
Georgia coach Jim Donnan said, ``because anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the other intriguing questions being asked as
the SEC begins its 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Can the SEC be as good this year as last year?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but in a different way. Last season, four SEC teams spent
some time among the top 10, and three (Florida, Tennessee, Georgia)
finished there. Two others (Auburn, LSU) finished in the top 13.
The conference might not be as strong near the top, but it could be
better in the middle and near the bottom. The SEC had seven teams
that were bowl-worthy last season, and that number could be eight
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Can Tim Couch win the Heisman Trophy?
</P>
<P>
   He can, but he probably won't. Couch put up great numbers _
3,884 yards, 37 touchdowns _ but the Wildcats need to have a
winning season to give him a shot. Couch threw too many
interceptions (19) last season. But here's an early indicator.
Kentucky could go to Florida on Sept. 26 with a 3-0 record. If
Couch puts up some impressive numbers, even in a loss, he could be
in the Heisman race all year. If Couch gets hammered, he could be
out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Can Florida get back to the SEC championship game?
</P>
<P>
   Count on it. For the first time last season, the SEC held a
championship game without the Gators, whose losses to LSU and
Georgia sent Tennessee to Atlanta. Sitting at home in December did
not set well with Steve Spurrier. He has put his players and his
staff on notice, so expect the Gators back at the Georgia Dome on
Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Who's this Nutt coaching for Arkansas?
</P>
<P>
   Houston Nutt is 35 years old and light years ahead of his
predecessor, Danny Ford, on the enthusiasm scale. Ford and Arkansas
parted ways because he got tired of athletics director Frank
Broyles looking over his shoulder. Nutt, a former Arkansas
quarterback, has been given the job of his life and has infused the
program with his energy. With 20 starters returning, the Hogs could
be the surprise team in the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Will this be the year that Tennessee finally beats Florida?
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Vols beat the Gators was 1992 and Phillip
Fulmer was the interim coach for the ailing Johnny Majors. Since
Fulmer became the full-time coach in 1993, Tennessee has lost only
11 games, but five have been to Florida. This season, the Vols get
the Gators before a full house at Neyland Stadium. Florida has some
questions at quarterback. Won't matter: Gators will make it six in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be the most improved player in the league?
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that Jamal Lewis returned for his sophomore
season in the best shape of his life. With Peyton Manning gone,
Lewis will be the main man in what will be another good Tennessee
offense and should surpass the 1,364 yards he gained as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama was 4-7 last year but hasn't had two straight losing
seasons since 1956-57. Is the Tide going to be that bad again?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and here are three reasons why:
</P>
<P>
   _ In the spring, Alabama installed a new passing offense that it
doesn't have the personnel to run. Coach Mike DuBose admits the
offense is geared for recruiting over the long haul. It will make a
lot of mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defense was supposed to be the bedrock of the team, but
Alabama has lost its best player, end Chris Hood, to academic
problems. Linebacker Steven Harris also is gone. A lot of young
players remain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alabama's non-conference schedule is the toughest in recent
memory, with BYU, East Carolina and Southern Miss. On the
conference schedule, Kentucky goes off and Florida comes on. Not a
very good trade.
</P>
<P>
   LSU again has the best talent in the Western Division. Any
chance they can't win the West?
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Last year, the Tigers upset No. 1 Florida 28-21, which
should have been a springboard to the division championship. Turns
out the Tigers and their fans couldn't handle success. They were
still celebrating when Ole Miss came to Baton Rouge the next week
and beat them soundly, 36-21. This season, the Tigers have to
travel to Auburn, Florida, Ole Miss and Arkansas with a
quarterback, Herb Tyler, who struggles with consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be the surprise player in the league?
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Carter has not played any kind of football in two years.
But Georgia's freshman quarterback appears to be a rare combination
of speed, strength and smarts. He'll struggle early. All young
quarterbacks do. But by late October, everybody in the country will
be talking about this guy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
