</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-SEC-WEST-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE FOOTBALL PREVIEW: SEC West capsules
</P>
<P>
   LSU
</P>
<P>
   TIGERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 25,879
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 9-3, 6-2 SEC (T-1st, SEC West); beat Notre Dame
27-9 in Independence Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 9, defense 8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Gerry DiNardo is 26-9-1 in three years at LSU, 45-34-1
overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: The offseason was a costly one for the Tigers,
who are looking for their first SEC championship since 1988. LSU
lost RB Cecil Collins, who had All-America potential, after his
arrest on assault charges. Two starters in the secondary, Chris
Beard and Clarence LeBlanc, were also removed from the team after
violating team rules. Despite those losses, LSU still has the
potential to be a top-10 team if a few things fall into place. LSU
was good enough to win the West last season but couldn't handle
success after upsetting No. 1 Florida. This should be DiNardo's
breakthrough team.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   7 Herb Tyler is 23-5 as a starter who has shown flashes of
brilliance, as he did in a win over Florida, only to crash and burn
the following week, as he did against Ole Miss. Week in and week
out, his play will set the tone for the offense. If he goes down,
there is no experienced backup.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   10 The departure of Collins still leaves the Tigers with Kevin
Faulk, an All-America candidate, and Rondell Mealey, who was the
MVP of the Independence Bowl. There is even more depth here with
senior Kendall Cleveland and sophomore fullback Tommy Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   7 The top four receivers from a year ago return, led by Larry
Foster (43 catches) and sophomore Abram Booty (35 catches). There
is some young talent that will provide some depth, but the Tigers
could use a few more big plays at this position.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   8 The Tigers lost a couple of good ones in guards Alan Faneca
and Adam Perry, but this group should still be strong, thanks to
three returning starters, including All-SEC center Todd McClure.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   8 New coordinator Lou Tepper will use a 3-4 alignment and move
Anthony McFarland from tackle to nose tackle, where he should have
a good season. Redshirt freshman Jarvis Green will handle one of
the ends.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   8 The new alignment will use four linebackers and the Tigers
have a pair of good ones inside in Joe Wesley (105 tackles) and
Charles Smith (78 tackles). Senior Arnold Miller has been moved
from end to outside linebacker and will do well.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   6 With Beard and LeBlanc gone, some shuffling is in order, but
there is still some talent. FS Mark Roman was a freshman
All-American two seasons ago and senior cornerback Chris Cummings
started all 12 games last season. Senior Raion Hill can play both
safety positions and will replace Beard at SS.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   6 The Tigers can't be as good because they lost the nation's
best punter in Chad Kessler and his 50.3-yard average. Danny Boyd
takes over at placekicker, which has been a real sore spot the past
few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   8 Throughout the troubles in the offseason, DiNardo has
maintained control of the program. This is his fourth season in
Baton Rouge and by far his most talented team.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   5 The Tigers have six home games instead of the usual seven.
They also drop Vanderbilt and pick up Georgia. There are also trips
to Auburn, Florida, Mississippi, Notre Dame and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI STATE
</P>
<P>
   BULLDOGS
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Starkville, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 13,577
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 7-4, 4-4 SEC (T-3rd, West).
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 7, defense 4.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Jackie Sherrill is 41-37-2 in seven years at
Mississippi State, 146-82-4 overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: The Bulldogs came very close to a great season
in 1997 but lost their last two games to Arkansas (17-7) and
Mississippi (15-14), which knocked them out of the SEC championship
game. They were also passed over for a bowl bid with a 7-4 record.
This year, Mississippi State plans to make amends. The Bulldogs are
capable of going to a bowl if a couple of things fall into place.
First, Mississippi State must get more production out of the
quarterback position. Secondly, the defense has to recover from
losing seven starters.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   4 As a junior, Matt Wyatt simply didn't meet expectations with
only six touchdowns and 15 interceptions. He continues to be pushed
by junior Rob Morgan and redshirt freshman Wayne Madkin, the best
athlete in the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   8 James Johnson ran for 1,069 yards and 12 touchdowns last
season. He will be counted on even more heavily than a year ago
when he had almost half (217) of the team's 441 rushing attempts.
Senior fullback Dennis McKinley is a very strong player.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   6 Senior Kevin Prentiss (20 catches) did not realize his
potential a year ago because of nagging injuries. Split end Kevin
Cooper was a junior college All-American two years ago but suffered
a knee injury. He could do big things now that he is at 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   8 Four starters return, including three that weigh over 325
pounds. Senior center Eric Allen is the lightest of the bunch at
288 pounds, but he is also the best.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   6 All four starters are gone, including some big-time players in
end Greg Favors and tackle Eric Dotson. But coordinator Joe Lee
Dunn got a lot of playing time for his backups last season. Tackles
Kevin Sluder and John Hilliard played in every game and nose tackle
Kenwoynne Smith has played in 27 career games.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   7 Junior Barrin Simpson returns after posting 104 tackles at
inside linebacker last season. Senior Bert Keys, a junior college
transfer last season, moved into the other spot to replace Dereck
Rush, the team's leading tacker from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   7 Cornerback Kendall Roberson is a very dependable cover guy and
will be joined at the other corner by Anthony Derricks, who
coverted from free safety. Strong safety Tim Nelson of Atlanta is
good tackler.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   10 Nobody in the SEC can match the daily double of punter Jeff
Walker (45.5 avg.) and placekicker Brian Hazelwood (16 of 26 field
goals).
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   7 Sherrill was on the hot seat last season after two consecutive
poor ones. He was rewarded with a four-year contract extension and
was able to keep his entire staff together. He has a winning record
(41-37-2) in seven years at Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   5 The good news is that the Bulldogs get Auburn, Alabama and
Arkansas at home. The bad news is they have only five home games
and tough road trips to Oklahoma State, LSU, Kentucky, and Ole
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN
</P>
<P>
   TIGERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Auburn, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 21,500
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 10-3, 6-2 SEC (T-1st, West); lost to Tennessee
30-29 in SEC championship game; beat Clemson 21-17 in Peach Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 7, defense 9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Terry Bowden is 46-12-1 in five years at Auburn,
110-47-2 overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: The Tigers came within one point of winning the
SEC Championship last season but there are some hurdles to overcome
if they are going to get back into the race. First there is a
schedule that includes three top-10 teams (LSU, Tennessee,
Florida), a top-20 team (Virginia) and two tough road trips
(Mississippi, Mississippi State) in the first six games. With the
departure of quarterback Dameyune Craig, Bowden will install a more
conservative, run-oriented offense.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   7 Redshirt sophomore Ben Leard takes over after serving a
two-year apprenticeship under Craig. Leard is a solid player but
will not be asked to make the big plays of his predecessor. Meiko
Collier is the backup should Leard go down.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   6 Sophomore Demontray Carter is bigger, faster and stronger than
a year ago. If he shakes his fumbling habit, Carter could be a
big-time back. Juniors Rusty Williams and Markeith Cooper are
capable but don't have the qualities of a featured back.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   7 Karsten Bailey returns after catching 53 balls a year ago, but
fortunes at this position were hurt when Robert Baker was kicked
off the team for legal problems. Clifton Robinson and Errick Lowe
will get a chance to win the other job.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   7 The Tigers had to rebuild here a year ago but now it will pay
off as four of five starters return. Tackle Jeno James leads a
group that must change its mindset from passing to running.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   9 This will be the strength of the team as All-SEC end Jimmy
Brumbaugh (74 tackles) returns after an injury-filled 1997. He'll
get plenty of help from NT Charles Dorsey and end Leonardo Carson.
The only question here is depth.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   7 Inside linebackers Takeo Spikes and Ricky Neal combined for
260 tackles last season. Both are gone. The Tigers may need some
junior college help at this position. The outside linebackers, Ryan
Taylor and Quinton Reese, are back and are dependable players.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   8 Strong safety Martavious Houston was kicked off the team for
breaking rules, but the Tigers will still be good in the secondary.
Free safety Brad Ware, who has eight pickoffs over the past two
seasons, returns, as do corners Larry Casher and Antwoine Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   5 Auburn lost one of the nation's best kickers in Jaret Holmes,
who hit 14 of 17 field goals and averaged 42.9 yards per punt last
season. Jeremy Zills will be the punter and Rob Bironas has the
edge at placekicker.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   8 Bowden has won 46 games in five seasons at Auburn, so he must
be doing something right. This season will be a real test as the
Tigers change style on offense and could struggle early because of
the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   3 Few teams anywhere open the season with seven straight
opponents that won seven or more games in 1997. If Auburn can come
out of that stretch 4-3, it should be thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI
</P>
<P>
   REBELS
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 12,542.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 8-4, 4-4 SEC (T-3rd, West).
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 6, defense 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Tommy Tuberville is 19-15 in three years at Ole Miss.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: After two years of NCAA sanctions, the Rebels
are finally approaching their full compliment of 85 players on
scholarship. The future looks bright but there is a concern for
this team, which has only five seniors on scholarship. There are
several things the Rebels must do if they want to go to their
second straight bowl game. Sophomore quarterback Romaro Miller must
get comfortable running the offense. Running back John Avery, a
first-round draft choice, is gone and somebody must step up to fill
that void. Finally, a defense that lost three great linebackers
must find somebody who can make a play.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   6 Miller was one of the nation's most highly recruited high
school quarterbacks two years ago. He has all the skills to be a
great one.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   7 The Rebels can't be as good with Avery gone, but there is
talent in Deuce McAllister (402 yards), Tony Cannion (210 yards),
and redshirt freshman Joe Gunn.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   7 Rufus French (43 catches) is the nation's best tight end. Wide
receivers Corey Peterson and Grant Heard combined for 75 catches
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   8 Junior tackle Todd Wade, center Matt Luke, and sophomore guard
Terrence Metcalf can play for anybody. Junior Tutan Reyes and
sophomore Keydrick Vincent will fill the other spots.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   5 Both ends, Andre Harrison and Johnny Jones, are gone. As a
result, Derrick Burgess (49 tackles as a true freshman) has been
moved from tackle to end. Junior Michael Boone will man the other
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   6 Brock Kreitz, Nate Wayne and Walker Jones combined for 252
tackles last season. They are all gone. But a star is on the rise
in junior Armegis Spearman, who had 43 tackles as a backup. Al Rice
and Walt Hill are good but lack experience.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   7 Three of four starters return but one of them, SS Ronnie
Heard, has been moved to outside linebacker. Former free safety
Timothy Strickland (79 tackles) was moved to corner and joins Gary
Thigpen as the starters. JUCO transfer Kenny Woods won the free
safety job in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   5 Reagan King averaged 41.0 yards per punt last season while a
pair of redshirt freshmen _ Donald Juneau and Bill Sinis _ are
still battling for the placekicking job. Losing Avery really hurts
the return game. He averaged 24.2 yards on 13 kickoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   9 After turning down the job at Arkansas in the offseason,
Tuberville was able to keep his entire staff together. He did a
masterful job getting the Rebels to a bowl last year and knows how
to get the most out his players' ability.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   6 The Rebels drop Tennessee and pick up South Carolina in the
SEC rotation. The non-conference games with Memphis, SMU, and
Arkansas State are all winnable. With the exception of Georgia, the
toughest SEC games (Auburn, LSU, Mississippi State) are all at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS
</P>
<P>
   RAZORBACKS
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Fayetteville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 16,590
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 4-7, 2-6 SEC (T-5th West).
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 10, defense 9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Houston Nutt is beginning his first season at Arkansas;
35-23 overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: After reaching the SEC championship game in
1995, things tailed off decidedly in Danny Ford's final two years
in Fayetteville. But Ford's staff did recruit well. As a result,
Nutt takes over a program filled with SEC-caliber athletes. First,
Nutt must do something about the anemic running game, which
finished last (56.5 ypg) among Division I's 112 schools. That
should happen with a stable of good running backs and a veteran
offensive line. Defensively, there is more than enough talent to
compete with the best of the SEC. .
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   6 Clint Stoerner set a school record for passing last season
(2,347 yards), but if he has to throw that much, the Hogs will be
in trouble. There is, however, no proven backup.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   7 If Madre Hill and Chrys Chukwuma have fully recovered from
their injuries, Arkansas will certainly improve its running game.
Rod Stinson (413 yards) and Eric Branch (251 yards) return to
provide depth.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   6 Three of the top four receivers are back, but it will be hard
to replace Anthony Eubanks, who set school records for receiving
yards, receptions, and touchdown catches. Still, there is talent in
sophomore Anthony Lucas (27 catches) and junior Emanuel Smith (28
catches).
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   7 The Hogs are strong up the middle with guards Russ Brown and
Brandon Burlsworth, who made several preseason All-SEC teams, plus
center Grant Garrett. Arkansas needs better play from its tackles,
who struggled against some of the SEC's quicker defenses last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   7 The front-line players, led by nose guard Melvin Bradley, are
solid but the Razorbacks have got to find some depth. Bradley has
led Arkansas in tackles the past two seasons and will get help from
Ryan Hale and D.J. Cooper up front.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   8 In addition to J.J. Jones, Harry Wilson, Jamel Harris and
Quenton Caver, outside linebackers C.J. McLain and Bryan Smith have
been reinstated to the team after being suspended late last season.
All these guys can run and can hit.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   7 Seven of the top eight secondary players are back. Senior Zac
Painter moves over from cornerback to the newly created rover
position. Jeromy Flowers and Kenoy Kennedy are very dependable
safeties. The Hogs could be a little undermanned at corner, which
could cost them.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   4 Not a whole lot went right last season and this still looks
like a weakness. Arkansas was 12th in the SEC in kickoff returns
and 11th in punt returns. Placekicker Todd Latourette has limited
range, and Arkansas is still in search of a punter.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   5 Nutt, an Arkansas native, was 22-3 at Murray State and brings
a new level of enthusiasm to Fayetteville. He still has to learn
about life in the SEC, however.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   5 The non-conference games with SW Louisiana, SMU and Memphis
are all winnable. Florida goes off the schedule and Kentucky comes
on. But after four straight home games to open the season, five of
the Hogs' next six are on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA
</P>
<P>
   CRIMSON TIDE
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Tuscaloosa, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 4-7, 2-6 SEC (T-5th, West).
</P>
<P>
   _ Starters returning: Offense 3, defense 7.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Mike DuBose is 4-7 in one season at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998 outlook: Only one Alabama coach in history, J.B. ``Ears''
Whitworth, has posted two consecutive losing seasons. DuBose could
be the second if he doesn't create some magic. He started by
replacing four assistant coaches and installing a BYU-style passing
attack which he really doesn't have the personnel to run. DuBose
says he's committed to the passing game so that Alabama can recruit
the necessary athletes to compete with Florida and Tennessee on a
consistent basis. Defensively, the Tide has been hurt by a pair of
academic losses, end Chris Hood and linebacker Steve Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks
</P>
<P>
   5 Senior John David Phillips is a converted safety who has shown
a tendency to turn the ball over. Redshirt freshman Andrew Zow is a
better athlete but has never played. Incoming freshman Tyler Watts
is talented but will be burdened by unrealistic expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs
</P>
<P>
   6 Two years ago, Shaun Alexander ran for a school-record 291
yards against LSU. Last season he was good, but not great, running
for 415 yards. Fullback will be solid despite the loss of 22-game
starter Ed Scissum as Montoya Madden and Dustin McClintock return.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers
</P>
<P>
   6 The return of Michael Vaughn, who missed the 1997 season with
back surgery, and Calvin Hall, a starter last season, gives this
group a chance. Quincy Jackson is back after leading the team with
29 receptions as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   6 Left tackle Chris Samuels and center Paul Hogan are the only
two starters that return, but several players are back who had
signficiant playing time like tackle Will Cuthbert and guards Jason
McDonald and Griff Redmill.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   7 The front wall took a huge blow earlier this month when end
Hood, a strong All-SEC candidate, was declared academically
ineligible. Kenny Smith moves from end to tackle and should be an
inside force. Junior Jamie Carter and redshirt freshman Sam
Matthews will also be strong at tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   7 This position took a hit when Harris, who had 45 tackles in 11
games last season, was ruled ineligible because of academics.
Sophomore Travis Carroll started four games at in the middle as a
true freshman. Steve Stanley and Trevis Smith are solid veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   7 Fernando Bryant is one of the nation's best cornerbacks and is
primed to have a very good season. Antoine Hunter will fill the
other corner spot in place of Deshea Townsend.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   6 Punting is fine as senior Daniel Pope returns after averaging
43.1 yards per kick. In 1997 Alabama used three different kickers
on field goals and four on extra points, so this season the
position is wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching
</P>
<P>
   5 By his own admission, DuBose made a ton of mistakes as a
rookie coach. He has replaced four assistants and vowed to get more
closely involved with every aspect of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule
</P>
<P>
   3 Houston and Louisiana Tech go off, BYU and East Carolina come
on. On the SEC side, Kentucky goes off and a home game with Florida
on Oct. 3 comes on. The road games at Arkansas, Tennessee, LSU and
Mississippi State are all problems.
</P>
