<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-SPEED-COX     09-02 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-SPEED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE PREVIEW: Defenses evolve to keep up
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a movement that changes the world begins with one
quiet act of desperation. So it was for college football when Jimmy
Johnson became head coach at Oklahoma State in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had taken over a perennial Big Eight whipping boy. He
was searching for a way _ any way _ he could compete with the
Nebraskas and the Oklahomas of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we couldn't get the top player _ the player who had it
all,'' said Johnson, now head coach of the NFL's Miami Dolphins.
``So we had to sacrifice something. We decided to sacrifice size
and went after the player who had great speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson didn't know it at the time, but that decision began the
most significant shift in college football philosophy in the modern
era. Johnson took his emphasis on speed to Miami in 1984 and, on a
more visible stage, won 52 games and a national championship in
five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Johnson left Miami for the Dallas Cowboys in 1989, a
game that had relied on size and strength since World War II had
been taken over by speed, speed and more speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we wanted to do was find a way for little people to beat
big people,'' said Johnson, who was in the top 10 four of his five
years at Miami. ``It also gave us a chance to be aggressive and the
players loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Johnson's success at Miami, the switch to speed
on defense methodically made its way across the college football
landscape. Many coaches jumped on the bandwagon when it became
obvious that this was the direction in which the game was headed.
Some, however, had to be pushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different people caught on at different times during the '80s
and '90s,'' said Carl Torbush, the head coach at North Carolina.
``Those who were slow to change eventually got tired of getting
their brains beat in. You either got faster or you got your butt
fired.''
</P>
<P>
   As college football approaches the next century, the offenses
remain more sophisticated and wide-open than ever. But this much is
clear: You're not going to win a national championship without a
fast _ make that a very fast _ and aggressive defense.
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that Michigan and Nebraska, which shared
the national championship last season, were ranked No. 1 (206.9
ypg.) and No. 5 (257.3 ypg.) nationally in total defense. In fact,
each of the top five teams in total defense (Michigan, North
Carolina, Florida State, Kansas State, Nebraska) finished the
season ranked in the top 10. And their defenses had one thing in
common. They were built around players who, if nothing else, could
run like the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest change I've seen in football since I started
coaching,'' said Bobby Stoops, the defensive coordinator at
Florida. ``Today, if you can put enough fast people together on
defense, you've probably got a chance to compete. If those people
are big and fast, you've got a chance to win every game you play.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Journal-Constitution visited several of the
nation's top coaches and got their views on how defensive speed has
changed the game of college football in the 1990s. Some of them had
to learn the hard way but all of them learned: There is no
substitute for speed.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Osborne, Nebraska
</P>
<P>
   Osborne was in his 16th season as a head coach and had won 158
games when the Cornhuskers lost to Florida State 31-28 in the 1988
Fiesta Bowl. The following year, the Cornhuskers lost to Miami's
national championship team 23-3 in the Orange Bowl. A trend had
begun.
</P>
<P>
   From 1988-94, Nebraska lost seven straight bowl games, six of
them to Miami or Florida State. Year after year, Osborne was asked
why his teams would win the Big Eight title in a breeze and then
fall flat in the bowl to a team from Florida. The answer was
simple. It was speed. Or, in Nebraska's case, the lack of it on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always asked us why we didn't recruit speed like Miami
but, believe me, we tried,'' said Osborne, who retired last season
after 25 years as coach. ``We eventually got some of those kind of
players and changed our defensive philosophy so that the whole
group could run better.''
</P>
<P>
   With vastly improved speed on defense, Nebraska won three
national championships (1994, 1995, 1997) in Osborne's last four
years as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say it made a difference,'' said Osborne,
who retired with 255 career victories.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Spurrier, Florida
</P>
<P>
   One of Osborne's national championships provided a painful
lesson about defensive speed to Florida's Steve Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier's Gators were 12-0 and ranked No. 2 after the 1995
regular season. Their Fun 'N' Gun passing attack seemed to be the
perfect counterpunch to the Nebraska option attack.
</P>
<P>
   But those who picked the Gators didn't count on one of the
fastest defenses in Nebraska history. By game's end, Nebraska had
sacked Florida quarterbacks seven times, held the Gators to
minus-28 yards rushing and posted a 62-24 thrashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game I asked my offensive line coach what he liked
to run against those guys,'' Spurrier recalled. ``He said 'nothing'
because they always seemed to have an extra man up there. I
understood what he meant.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing Nebraska, Spurrier learned that if he was ever
going to win a national championship, he would have to have a fast,
dominating defense like the one that had destroyed his beloved
offense.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1996 season, Spurrier hired Stoops away from Kansas
State as his defensive coordinator. Stoops implemented a defensive
philosophy that emphasized speed and aggressiveness above all else.
That season, Florida won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden,
</P>
<P>
   Florida State
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, Florida State has posted 11 consecutive seasons of
10 victories or more. The Seminoles have finished in the top four
of the final Associated Press poll in each of those years.
</P>
<P>
   But people forget that Bowden's program was struggling, at least
by his standards, in the early 1980s. The Seminoles were 6-5 in
1981 and 7-4-1 in 1986, the year before they started this
unprecedented run.
</P>
<P>
   So what changed?
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a defense and we got faster,'' said Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Bowden hired Mickey Andrews as defensive coordinator
and gave him marching orders to put some faster athletes on
defense. He was aware of what Johnson had done at Miami _ all too
well. Johnson beat Bowden in four out of their five meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became pretty obvious that we weren't going to get where we
needed to go until we learned how to stop people,'' said Bowden.
``And the only way to stop speed on offense is with more speed on
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, when Andrews had his system in place and the
athletes he needed to run it, Florida State is 118-15.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Torbush, N. Carolina
</P>
<P>
   Torbush became North Carolina's defensive coordinator in 1987
but in 1994 he reached a pivotal moment in his career. North
Carolina had hung on to beat Duke 41-40 in the regular-season
finale. In the Sun Bowl, his defense had blown a 31-21 lead late in
the fourth quarter and the Tar Heels lost to Texas 35-31.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Mack Brown was not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became apparent to me that we better get better or old
Torbush was going to be gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina did an about-face on its defensive philosophy by
adding speed and aggressiveness. Brown promised Torbush he would
get as many fast athletes as he needed for his side of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. In 1995 North Carolina led the ACC in defense (267.3
ypg.) and was sixth in the nation. The past two seasons the Tar
Heels have ranked second nationally in total defense. In 1996 and
1997, they won 21 games and posted consecutive top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   And when Brown left for Texas, Torbush was named head coach at
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you could say I kind of like this speed thing,'' said
Torbush.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
