<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-ACC-ALLCONF-COX     09-02 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-ACC-ALLCONF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC SCOUTING REPORT
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ TEAM ON THE RISE: After missing a bowl game for the first time
in five years, Virginia is restocked for another run at the best in
the ACC. QB Aaron Brooks thrived under offensive coordinator Sparky
Woods. The Cavaliers' strength is defense, where Antonio Dingle,
Wali Rainer and Anthony Poindexter have All-America talent.
Upsetting Florida State is a longshot, but Virginia could be in the
running for a major bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   _ TEAM ON THE DECLINE: After losing the likes of Raymond
Priester, Anthony Simmons, Nealon Greene and Tony Horne, Clemson
has to regroup with a diminished, although respectable core that
will carry a heavy burden. A new quarterback and running game will
have to come through early and the defense must find a leader to
replace the invaluable Simmons for the Tigers to match a 7-5
season.
</P>
<P>
   _ TOUGHEST SCHEDULE: Playing without a breather for its first
nine games, Clemson has the unenviable task of taking to the road
against Virginia, North Carolina and Florida State between Sept. 19
and Oct. 17, a slate preceded by an intriguing visit from Virginia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   _ EASIEST SCHEDULE: Considering the talent gap in the ACC,
Florida State shouldn't have much trouble reasserting its
dominance. Both North Carolina and Virginia have to come to
Tallahassee, and non-conference foes Texas A&AMP;M, Southern Cal and
Miami are coming off subpar seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ GAME OF THE YEAR: Given that Florida State will likely rule
the roost yet again, Virginia's home encounter with North Carolina
on Nov. 14 could determine second place. The Cavaliers will have
just returned from playing the Seminoles, while UNC's turn at FSU
will have come Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   _ UPSET OF THE YEAR: If Georgia Tech's mastery of Virginia in
Atlanta two years ago can be repeated on Oct. 17, it might be just
the midseason boost for the Yellow Jackets during some very rough
sledding on the schedule. Tech plays host to Florida State the
following week and also has a road game at Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   _ FRESHMAN OF THE YEAR: One of the most celebrated prep
two-sport stars in recent years could fill a variety of roles in
his debut season. North Carolina's Ronald Curry will serve as the
backup quarterback behind Oscar Davenport and is slated to be the
punt returner. The Tar Heels have the luxury of providing him with
some seasoning before he tangles with fellow rookie Luke Huard next
season to replace Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   _ PLAYER(S) OF THE YEAR: Defense has ruled in the ACC, where
Florida State defensive lineman Andre Wadsworth was tapped as the
league's best player. North Carolina cornerback Dre' Bly could very
well take honors in his junior, and probably final, season. Florida
State's Peter Warrick is an All-American candidate at running back
and as a punt returner, and his electrifying big-play ability are
unmatched.
</P>
<P>
   _ COACH ON THE HOT SEAT: Mike O'Cain got a contract extension to
remain at N.C. State, as did Tommy West at Clemson, and no other
ACC coaches appear to be in any imminent danger. Fred Goldsmith of
Duke and Wake Forest's Jim Caldwell have been given long leashes to
bring their their respective programs to life, but bad seasons
could set ominous tones next year. Ditto at Maryland, where
second-year-man Ron Vanderlinden is under duress to make some
substantial strides toward what appears to be an even greater
rebuilding task than what he inherited last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
