<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-CHANGE-COX     09-02 2183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-CHANGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teams are likely to keep moving as leagues seek best possible TV
deals
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In May, eight members of the 16-team Western Athletic Conference
suddenly announced that they were mad as hell and they were not
going to take it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The language was couched in professional terms but, in essence,
eight of the strongest schools in the WAC said they were tired of
being held back by the weak ones. They would bolt and form a
yet-to-be named conference in the fall of 1999. WAC commissioner
Karl Benson, at home recovering from eye surgery, got the news in
an afternoon telephone call from the president of Colorado State:
``Hi Karl. Sorry you're hurting, buddy. Just wanted to let you
know. We are outta here!''
</P>
<P>
   The news sent shock waves through college football. ``I'm
assuming it got everybody's attention, because it sure got ours,''
ACC commissioner John Swofford said. ``I think people were
wondering 'Could that ever happen to us?'''
</P>
<P>
   This all-too-public temper tantrum began a debate that continues
as we approach the 1998 season. Was the breakup of the WAC:
</P>
<P>
   A: An inevitable consequence of an ill-conceived conference that
covered nine states and four time zones?
</P>
<P>
   Or . . .
</P>
<P>
   B: The first noticeable tremor of a major shakeup that will hit
the sport early in the next century?
</P>
<P>
   According to a group of key college football officials, the
answer is B. In fact, they say, the question is no longer if there
is going to be another major conference realignment but when.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's going to happen,'' SEC commissioner Roy Kramer said.
``We can see the signs like everyone else. So we're doing our
homework and trying to be prepared. Then when it happens, hopefully
we can make an intelligent decision on what we should do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's view was echoed by several other conference
commissioners interviewed by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. They
do not want to be caught off guard when the rumbling starts.
</P>
<P>
   `Economics and politics'
</P>
<P>
   That conferences already are preparing for college football's
equivalent of The Big One probably surprises most fans. On the
surface, the game appears to be in pretty good shape.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season, Division I teams set an all-time attendance
record of 27,565,959 _ an average of 42,085 per game. The total
attendance was almost 1 million more than the previous best mark.
</P>
<P>
   _ This season marks the debut of the new Bowl Championship
Series, which will guarantee that the two top-ranked teams _ based
on a formula _ will meet in the Fiesta Bowl for the national
championship. It's not a playoff, but it will be the closest thing
college football has ever had to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although concerns remain about the overall health of the
22-game bowl system, seven of them drew their biggest crowds last
season. Thanks to a new deal with ABC, which will broadcast all
four games in the Bowl Championship Series _ Fiesta, Orange, Sugar,
Rose _ the system will pump a record $127.3 million back into
college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface, things are looking pretty stable right now,''
Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese said. ``Do I think they are
going to stay that way? Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that the coming upheaval, as with
most of the changes that have taken place in the past 15 years,
will be driven by television.
</P>
<P>
   All of the major conferences have multiyear network deals that
are scheduled to run out during the early part of the next century.
As the renewal dates of those contracts draw near, each conference
will begin negotiating to try to increase _ or at least maintain _
its share of those finite television dollars.
</P>
<P>
   That's where expansion comes in. A conference's television
dollars are determined by how many viewers it can deliver to the
networks on any given Saturday. So if one conference expands in an
effort to increase its numbers, the others risk losing their share
if they don't react.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has to do with both economics and politics,'' Big
Ten commissioner Jim Delany said. ``You have to maintain your power
to negotiate with the networks, but you also have to keep yourself
strong within an organization like the NCAA. So you have to stay on
top of things like this. You can never afford to be passive.''
</P>
<P>
   Started with Big Ten
</P>
<P>
   To understand how the process probably will work, go back to
December 1989, when the Big Ten extended an invitation to Penn
State to become its 11th member. The Big Ten already was the
nation's most powerful television conference, delivering the large
markets in Detroit, Cleveland and Chicago. With Penn State, it
added the eastern markets of Pittsburgh and Philadelphia to that
list.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State would not begin Big Ten play until 1993, but the move
brought about an immediate chain reaction:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1991, the SEC added Arkansas, which left the Southwest
Conference, and South Carolina to become a 12-team conference split
into two six-team divisions.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACC had a huge internal battle before taking Florida State
as its ninth member.
</P>
<P>
   _ With Penn State no longer available, the remaining Eastern
independents _ Syracuse, Rutgers, Pittsburgh, West Virginia,
Temple, Virginia Tech and Boston College _ persuaded Miami to join
them in forming the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, another television event created the next wave of
change. The SEC broke away from the College Football Association
television package to cut its own five-year, $125 million deal with
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The other conferences then began scrambling for their own TV
deals. In the process, the Southwest Conference, which had been in
business since 1914, dissolved and sent its four strongest schools
_ Texas, Texas A&AMP;M, Texas Tech, Baylor _ to merge with the Big
Eight and form the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the WAC, sensing it was going to be left out in the
cold, took in three refugees from the SWC and pulled in several
others in what was essentially an act of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``And just think,'' Tranghese said. ``All of that happened with
just one move by the Big Ten. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Are Irish Big Ten bound?
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure exactly when the next wave of conference
realignments will begin, but they agree that the Big Ten again will
get the ball rolling.
</P>
<P>
   When the Big Ten made Penn State its 11th team, it was a given
that the conference eventually would add a 12th member and go to
divisional play, as the SEC, Big 12, Mid-American and WAC do. The
SEC title game generates almost $450,000 annually for each of its
12 schools. In the next century, when such economic pressures as
Title IX, which requires equal athletic opportunities for women,
grow greater, the schools will not be able to ignore any source of
income.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten has made it clear that it wants Notre Dame, the
greatest of all television teams, to become that 12th member.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, it was inconceivable that Notre Dame would give
up its 100-year status as an independent. For one thing, the Irish
already have the best television deal: NBC televises every home
game, and the school gets all of the money. That contract runs
through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past two months, the Big Ten and Notre Dame have
been exchanging information, giving the school a sense of what
membership would be like. Notre Dame officials now concede that
joining the Big Ten would not necessarily bring about the major
financial hit it had feared. That, say those familiar with the
process, is a major concession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We once thought it was a pretty significant disincentive
financially,'' Notre Dame athletics director Mike Wadsworth said.
``It's certainly not so obvious as we thought it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame officials will continue to study the question and
some time next year will make a recommendation to the school's
administration. For the first time, it seems possible that Notre
Dame could join the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   If it happens, the Big Ten would become college football's
version of the 600-pound gorilla, able to dominate in its
negotiations with the networks. That is, if everybody else stands
pat. Which, of course, they won't.
</P>
<P>
   What's likely to happen
</P>
<P>
   Based on a number of interviews with officials around the
country, here is a possible sequence of events once Notre Dame
joins the Big Ten:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Big East, the weakest of the six conferences in the Bowl
Championship Series, will find it difficult to renegotiate its
television deal with CBS.
</P>
<P>
   With the decline of Miami, which was supposed to be its football
anchor, the Big East has struggled for respect on the field. Last
season the league's non-conference record was 13-20. Against
non-conference teams with winning records, it was 3-15.
</P>
<P>
   If the Big East takes a hit on its television package, the
strongest members will grow tired of being held back by such woeful
programs asRutgers (0-11 last season) and Temple (3-8). Some of
them will look for a new home and find it _ in the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   _ But the ACC will have another major internal fight on the
subject of expansion. The non-expansion folks don't want to do
anything that would further divide ACC basketball tournament
tickets, the most precious commodity in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   _ However, the conference has a new commissioner and several new
athletics directors who will see the writing on the wall. Its
current TV contract with ABC expires in 2005. Without expansion,
the dollars on the next contract could be significantly less.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACC will pass on such schools as West Virginia and
Virginia Tech, which make the most sense geographically. Instead,
it will add Boston College and Syracuse to expand its television
clout up the Atlantic coast. To get an even stronger presence in
Florida, it will add Miami.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pac-10 has had a long-standing invitation for Texas and
Colorado to join. That invitation will be extended again. Texas
will decline again, but Colorado will accept.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado makes no secret of its desire to get out of the Big 12,
a group of schools with which it has little in common. Colorado, in
fact, does most of its recruiting in California.
</P>
<P>
   Texas will have to say no because the state legislature won't
allow the Longhorns to go off on their own and leave the other
state schools behind.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Pac-10 will look for another strong football school
with West Coast ties and take BYU as its 12th member.
</P>
<P>
   _ With Colorado gone, the Big 12 will invite SMU to return to
the fold after its exile to the WAC in 1995. That move would give
the conference a bigger share of the Dallas market.
</P>
<P>
   _ The SEC will think seriously about inviting Texas and Texas
A&AMP;M in order to compete with the Big Ten's blockbuster package.
Ultimately, however, the conference will stand pat, confident that
its current strength will weather the storm. In May, the 12 SEC
members divided a record $58 million from television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our athletics directors are pretty smart. They certainly know
how to do math,'' Kramer said. ``They know the money we make is
more divided by 12 than divided by 14.''
</P>
<P>
   SEC expansion still isn't out of the question, because of the
Big 12 situation.
</P>
<P>
   After the WAC and the Big East, the Big 12 is on the shakiest
ground. Since the conference began in 1996, it has been wracked by
dissension between the old Big Eight members and the Texas schools,
who think they are treated like second-class citizens. The Big 12
forced out Steve Hatchell as commissioner earlier this year and
still doesn't have a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   If the league splits, the SEC will rethink its position on the
two Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   The new look
</P>
<P>
   When the dust finally settles, college football will look
significantly different:
</P>
<P>
   _ There will be five major conferences _ ACC, SEC, Big Ten, Big
12, Pac-12 _ and each will have 12 members. Each will negotiate a
multiyear deal with the networks, and, as a result, those 60
schools will control an even larger percentage of television
revenue than they do now.
</P>
<P>
   _ The second-level conferences _ the Great Eight (the WAC
secessionists), Mid-American, Conference USA, Big West _ will have
to scramble for regional-television exposure, which does not pay
the big bucks. As the TV revenue for these schools goes down, so
will their ability to compete at the highest level of the sport.
The gap between the haves and the have-nots will grow wider each
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ After absorbing Big East refugees West Virginia, Pittsburgh
and Virginia Tech to form a 14-team league, Conference USA will
make a push to be included as a member of the Bowl Championship
Series. It will fail.
</P>
<P>
   With the new television contracts in place, things will be
peaceful in college football once more. For a while, at least.
</P>
<P>
   But as the new contracts approach their ends, schools again will
get the itch to improve their situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that after the next series of realignments, things
should be pretty calm for a while,'' Kramer said. ``But I wouldn't
bet on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
