<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-CONFERENCE-PREV-C     09-02 2180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-CONFERENCE-PREV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Haves and have-nots
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A look at some of the teams, players and matchups to watch this
season in the major college conferences.
</P>
<P>
   BIG TEN
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: Joe Tiller delivered in his first season at
Purdue, giving the Boilermakers their first winning season (9-3)
since 1984. The sophisticated passing attack he brought from
Wyoming has been a hit with recruits. Two more recruiting classes
like the last one and the Boilermakers could start scaring people
at the top of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: This probably will be Hayden Fry's final
season at Iowa. Fry turns 70 in February and opponents are starting
to use his age against the school in recruiting. Hawkeye fans might
be ready for a change: Iowa had difficulty selling 2,000 tickets to
the Sun Bowl game against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Another reason for Fry to retire after this
season: The Hawkeyes open at Nebraska in 1999. Fry will turn the
program over to a younger man to take on that challenge. Florida
defensive coordinator Bob Stoops is on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has the talent to win the national championship, but
will likely need to win at home against Michigan Nov. 21 to keep
the critics off coach John Cooper's back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: LB Andy Katzenmoyer, WR David Boston and DB
Antoine Winfield, Ohio State; RB Anthony Thomas, Michigan; RB
Sedrick Irvin, Michigan State; RB Ron Dayne, Wisconsin; LB Brandon
Short, Penn State; DL Jared DeVries, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Michigan at Notre Dame, Sept. 5; Ohio State at
West Virginia, Sept 5; Michigan State at Michigan, Sept. 26; Penn
State at Ohio State, Oct. 3; Penn State at Michigan, Nov. 7;
Michigan at Ohio State, Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (6): Ohio State, Michigan, Penn State,
Wisconsin, Michigan State and Purdue. Northwestern, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   CONFERENCE USA
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: Tommy Bowden performed nothing less than a minor
miracle in his first season at Tulane. When Bowden arrived, the
Green Wave had won only five games in the previous three seasons.
In 1997, it was 7-4 overall with the only conference loss to
champion Southern Miss. Tulane returns 10 starters from an offense
that set 26 school records. If Bowden stays a couple more years,
the Green Wave could win the conference. But that's a big if.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: It's hard to believe that in this decade,
Louisville played Alabama in the Fiesta Bowl _ and won. Ron Cooper
was let go after winning just six games in his final two seasons,
and on comes John L. Smith, who was an offensive guru at Utah
State. The Cardinals will be fun to watch, but they still have one
of the nation's worst defenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Two years ago, Houston went to the Liberty
Bowl. Last year, the Cougars dropped to 3-8, and two of the wins
were by three points or less. Coach Kim Helton promises the program
will turn the corner soon. This season would be a good time to
start.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: QB Chris Redman, TE Ibn Green, Louisville;
RB Ketric Sanford, Houston; WR Sherrod Gideon, DL Adalius Thomas,
Southern Miss; DL Marquis Bowling, DB Mike McKenzie, Memphis; QB
Shaun King, RB Toney Converse, WR JaJuan Dawson, Tulane; OL Brian
Uhl, DB/KR Tinker Keck, Cincinnati
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Southern Miss at Penn State, Sept. 5; Kentucky at
Louisville, Sept. 5; Texas A&AMP;M at Southern Miss, Sept. 19; Southern
Miss at Tulane, Oct. 3; Southern Miss at Alabama, Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (2): Southern Miss, Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   BIG EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: West Virginia appears ready for a breakthrough
season after finishing 7-5 and losing in the Carquest Bowl last
season. Heisman Trophy candidate Amos Zereoue and quarterback Marc
Bulger head an explosive offense. The Mountaineers could contend
for the national championship this season.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting bottom in a 47-0 loss to Florida State last
season, Miami is working its way back to respectability. After a
5-6 season in 1997, the Hurricanes finally were free of NCAA
sanctions and able to sign a full recruiting class. Running back
Edgerrin James leads a talented backfield. Coach Butch Davis has
turned down several offers to leave Miami. He knows the 'Canes
aren't far from being good again.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: Rutgers was 0-11 last season, which was Terry
Shea's second as coach. It doesn't figure to get much better. Shea
says he's optimistic about 1998, but that's not based on talent.
Getting good players to visit Piscataway, N.J., isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Syracuse is good enough to win the Big East
but must open the season with consecutive games against Tennessee
and Michigan. The Orangemen also face a stiff test with consecutive
games against West Virginia and Virginia Tech in November.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: QB Donovan McNabb, WR Quinton Spotwood,
Syracuse; RB Amos Zereoue, LB Gary Stills, West Virginia; RB
Edgerrin James, LB Dan Morgan, Miami.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Ohio State at West Virginia, Sept. 5, Tennessee at
Syracuse, Sept. 5; Penn State at Pittsburgh, Sept. 19; Florida
State at Miami, Oct. 10; Miami at West Virginia, Oct. 24; Syracuse
at West Virginia, Nov. 7; Miami at Syracuse, Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (4): West Virginia, Syracuse, Virginia Tech, and
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   WAC
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: SMU went 6-5 in Mike Cavan's first year and put
the rest of the conference on notice. The Mustangs weren't the most
talented bunch in the Mountain Division, but they played hard every
week. Cavan followed up by putting together an impressive
recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: TCU is coming off its worst season (1-10) in
17 years, and it looks as if things will get worse. Dennis
Franchione took over for Pat Sullivan as coach and has changed just
about everything, from the offense to the demands of the offseason
program.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Tulsa is 4-12 in the WAC and 6-16 overall
since joining the league three years ago. Coach Dave Rader has been
at Tulsa for 10 years, so it might be time for a change.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: RB Damon Washington, OG Anthony Cesario,
Colorado State; QB Jon Denton, UNLV; QB Graham Leigh, New Mexico;
DL Pene Talamaivao, LB Phil Glover, Utah; RB Ronney Jenkins, BYU;
DE Kabeer Gbaja-Biamila, San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Colorado State at Michigan State, Aug. 29;
Colorado State at Colorado, Sept. 5; BYU at Alabama, Sept. 5;
Arizona State at BYU, Sept. 12; SMU at Arkansas, Sept. 19; Colorado
State at Air Force, Sept. 17; Colorado State at Rice, Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (4): Colorado State, Utah, BYU, Rice.
</P>
<P>
   BIG 12
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: It won't show this year, necessarily, but Texas
is on the way back under new coach Mack Brown. Brown, unlike
predecessor John Mackovic, speaks the language of the Longhorn
state and has a knack for luring great high school players to his
program. Give Brown two more recruiting classes like the most
recent one, and Texas will be knocking on the door of a Big 12
title.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: Colorado went 10-2 in Rick Neuheisel's first
two years as coach before dropping to 5-6 last season. Something is
missing in this program, and it might be talent. The Buffs simply
haven't been doing a big-time job in recruiting as they did under
Bill McCartney.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Oklahoma could set a dubious school record in
1998 by posting its fifth straight losing season. The Sooners are
3-8 and 4-8 in John Blake's two years and have looked bad doing it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: RB Ricky Williams, Texas; QB Michael Bishop,
Kansas State; DE Michael Rucker, QB Bobby Newcombe, Nebraska; RB
Dante Hall, LB Dat Nguyen, Texas A&AMP;M; RB Darren Davis, Iowa State;
QB Corby Jones, Missouri; RB De'Mond Parker, Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Texas at Kansas State, Sept. 19; Washington at
Nebraska, Sept. 26; Nebraska at Texas A&AMP;M, Oct. 10; Texas at
Nebraska, Oct. 31; Nebraska at Kansas State, Nov. 14.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (6): Kansas State, Nebraska, Texas A&AMP;M,
Colorado, Oklahoma State, Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   PAC 10
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: Southern California coach Paul Hackett has yet to
prove he can get it done as the head man, but he inherits a team
with 15 returning starters and most of the tough games at home.
Given the surrounding talent base, USC should be a Top 15 team
every year. This season, the Trojans begin the long march back.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: Washington State had its 15 minutes of fame
last season, as it rode quarterback Ryan Leaf all the way to the
Rose Bowl. Only five starters return, and the Cougars return to
reality. Four years after advancing to the Rose Bowl, Oregon finds
itself fighting to remain in the upper half of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Dick Tomey is in the last year of his
contract at Arizona. The Wildcats saved him last season by winning
their last four games, including an upset of Arizona State. That he
didn't get a new deal speaks volumes. Arizona will begin the season
in the Top 25, but will face a tough stretch in October with
consecutive games against Washington and UCLA and the season finale
against Arizona State. Things will be tight in Tucson this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: QB Cade McNown, OT Kris Farris, UCLA; RB
J.R. Redmond, Arizona State; CB Chris McAlister, Arizona; LB Chris
Claiborne, CB Daylon McCutcheon, USC; DE Andre Carter, California;
QB Brock Huard, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Washington at Arizona State, Sept. 5; USC at
Florida State, Washington at Nebraska, Sept. 26; Arizona State at
USC, Oct. 3; Washington at USC, Oct. 31; UCLA at Washington, Nov.
14; Arizona State at Arizona, Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (5): Arizona State, UCLA, USC, Washington,
Arizona. Oregon is a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   MID-AMERICAN
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: Western Michigan, 2-9 in 1996, posted the
nation's best turnaround in 1997 with an 8-3 record in Gary
Darnell's first year as coach. Fifteen starters, including nine on
offense, return in 1998. The Broncos are expected to give Toledo a
run in the MAC's West Division.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: In the early '90s, Bowling Green was the class
of the league. Now, the Falcons are struggling with a 7-15 mark the
past two years. Coach Gary Blackney is trying to save things by
bringing in six JUCOs and some older players from Canada. It
doesn't look good.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Herb Deromedi, who won 110 games in 16
seasons as coach of Central Michigan, hand-picked friend Dick Flynn
to take over the program when he retired in 1993. Flynn won a MAC
championship in 1994 but the Chippewas have struggled since. They
were 2-9 last season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: QB Chad Pennington, WR Lavorn Colclogh,
Marshall; DL Jon McCall, WR Reggie Allen, Central Michigan; QB
Kareem Wilson, Ohio; LB JoJuan Armour, DB Paris Johnson, Miami; WR
Eugene Baker, Kent State. QB Chris Wallace, Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Marshall at Akron, Sept. 5; Western Michigan at
Toledo, Sept. 19; Ohio at Western Michigan, Sept. 26; Miami at
Marshall, Oct. 3; Marshall at Ohio, Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (1): Toledo will beat Marshall in the MAC
championship game and get the league's automatic berth in the Motor
City Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENTS
</P>
<P>
   _ On the rise: Central Florida put a major scare into some
big-time programs last season, thanks to the heroics of quarterback
Duante Culpepper. Now, the Golden Knights are thinking bowl game.
The program was rocked by the forced resignation of coach Gene
McDowell after the cell-phone scandal, but new coach Mike Kruczek
has held things together well.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the decline: Southwestern Louisiana has never been great
but usually was competitive. That is no longer the case: Last
season, the Rajun' Cajuns were 1-10, and they don't figure to get a
whole lot better. Coach Nelson Stokley has been there 12 years and
definitely is feeling the heat.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the hot seat: Central Florida's Kruczek inherited a very
good team with one of the nation's best quarterbacks. He turned
down a three-year deal to be an offensive coordinator in the NFL
and has only a one-year agreement with UCF.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Davie has had to deal with several off-the-field problems
during the off-season, including an embarrassing trial involving
former assistant Joe Moore. It will be interesting to see how the
Irish handle adversity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players to watch: QB Daunte Culpepper, CB Reginald Doster,
Central Florida; TB Autry Denson, LB Kory Minor, Notre Dame; QB Tim
Rattay, Louisiana Tech; WR Marty Booker, NE Louisiana; TB Lucious
Foster, UAB; WR Brandon Stokley, SW Louisiana; RB Bobby Ray Tell,
Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best games: Notre Dame at Michigan, Sept. 5; Central Florida
at Purdue, Sept. 19; Central Florida at Auburn, Nov. 7; Louisiana
Tech at Texas A&AMP;M, Sept. 12; Louisiana Tech at Auburn, Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going bowling (2): Notre Dame, Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
