<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-GRAMBLING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doug Williams tries to reinvigorate Grambling
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he replaces living legend Eddie Robinson on the Grambling
sideline, former G-man Doug Williams wants to make one thing clear
to fellow alumni and friends:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to realize that I won't be trying to walk in
Coach Rob's shoes. What he did won't be duplicated,'' Williams
said. ``But this is a new era, and I just hope me and my staff have
the opportunity to do our thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who coached at Morehouse College in Atlanta last
season, returns to his alma mater as the second coach in school
history. Robinson, who stepped down after his last two teams had
posted 3-8 records, started football at Grambling in 1941.
Fifty-five seasons and 408 victories later, Robinson reluctantly
left his once-proud program.
</P>
<P>
   What Williams has inherited for his first season on the scene of
his collegiate heroics is a team thin on talent and short on
experience. He estimates that as many as seven freshmen could
start, perhaps all four in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're no longer reloading here like we once were,'' Williams
said. ``Realistically, we're rebuilding, and we've got to take our
lumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten starters return, but Williams is not convinced that all 10
will start this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've moved some guys around, from offense to defense, and
defense to offense,'' he said. ``Some of them may not be out there
(as starters).''
</P>
<P>
   Williams does think he has linebackers and two transfers capable
of running his offense. One is former Arkansas quarterback Lajun
``Pete'' Burks (6-2, 195), and the other is Lionel Hayes (6-4,
225), who transferred from Southern.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest suit, however, could be the coaching staff. It
includes former NFL star Sammy White (receivers coach), former
Grambling quarterback Matt Reed (quarterback coach), former
Pittsburgh Steeler Tyrone McGriff (offensive line) and three from
the Morehouse staff, including defensive coordinator Todd Bowles, a
Washington Redskins teammate of Williams.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year as a coach in the Southwestern Athletic
Conference, the league in which he passed for 8,411 yards as a
player (1974-77), Williams will be one of four new coaches in the
league. Ron Dickerson, who was fired after five years at Temple,
has replaced Houston Markum at Alabama State, former Louisville
coach Ron Cooper is the head coach at first-year conference member
Alabama A&AMP;M and Dr. Johnny Thomas, a former coach who put that
profession on hold for several years while he sought a doctorate,
is the new man at Alcorn State.
</P>
<P>
   None of those coaches is expected to guide their teams into
contention for the SWAC title, which Southern or Jackson State has
won four of the last five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Arkansas-Pine Bluff coach Lee Hardman, whose team went 8-3
last year and has been picked to finish third behind Southern and
Jackson State, said, ``I think the new coaches coming in are going
to be a plus for the conference, because they come in with new
ideas. They can only heighten our programs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Conference: With one of the
toughest defenses in Division II last year returning almost intact,
Albany State has an excellent chance of winning its sixth straight
SIAC championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were 11-0 before losing 22-21 to Carson Newman in the
second round of the '97 NCAA Division II playoffs. A repeat
probably hinges on how effectively freshman Jamal Robinson can
replace Purvis Jackson at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Valley State, with junior quarterback Renotto Solomon and
tailback LaVorris White, might have improved enough on both sides
of the ball in coach Kent Scholfield's second year to be in the
championship race from start to finish. Morris Brown is also
expected to compete for the title.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference: Hampton University has been
picked to repeat as champion in Joe Taylor's seventh season as
coach. The Pirates will have to replace their top three receivers
and leading rusher Charles Jackson (1,138 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Florida A&AMP;M was the choice for second but will have to see if
former Southwest DeKalb High product Michael Morand is an adequate
replacement for Oteman Sampson, who passed for 3,292 yards and 25
touchdowns for the 9-3 Rattlers last year. Hampton and FAMU play
the critical game, Sept. 5 in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Howard University, led by quarterback Ted White (6-4, 220), who
during the past two seasons has thrown for 5,455 yards and 54 TDs,
could challenge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Central Intercollegiate Athletic Conference: After the
remarkable 1997 run by Livingstone, the nation's smallest Division
II school, the CIAA probably returns to the hands of Virginia
State, which had won the two previous titles.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference that dropped to nine teams with Norfolk State's
move to the MEAC, Virginia State returns 55 lettermen, including
all-stars Antonio Hawkins at quarterback (1,550 yards, 17 TDs),
Desmond Thornton at wideout (44 catches, 601 yards) and linebacker
Eugene Brown (12 sacks).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
