<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABC push leads to bowl game shove
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems like ages ago, but earlier this decade ABC was not only
the big dog of college football but network television's only dog
in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Except for those mavericks at Notre Dame, who dared to split
from the pack and cut a separate deal for their home games with
NBC, ABC was the sole national carrier on ``free TV.''
</P>
<P>
   But then the College Football Association fell apart, and CBS
moved deftly to acquire the SEC and Big East. ABC had to look on
with envy when CBS positioned itself to carry the national
championship game of the Bowl Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   However, ABC held a trump card to the effectiveness of the Bowl
Alliance because that setup did not include the Big Ten, Pacific-10
and Rose Bowl. ABC also would point out that its package continued
to win the ratings battle, consistently drawing numbers that were
25 percent higher or more than CBS' and NBC's.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for a network that always considered college football as
one of its main identities, it grated on ABC that a rival had
snatched the high-profile SEC and could claim the so-called
national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But last year's situation with Michigan and Nebraska provided
ABC the impetus needed to get behind closed doors and emerge with
the Bowl Championship Series, which encompasses every conference
and theoretically should yield a true version of No. 1 vs. No. 2
for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ABC reportedly paid $80 million for the rights to the Bowl
Championship Series, which will rotate the national championship
game among the Fiesta, Sugar, Orange and Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite often the networks are accused of dictating events, and
quite often that's simply not true,'' ABC publicist Mark Mandel
said. ``But in this case, we were the prime player. The Bowl
Championship Series would not have happened without ABC's
involvement. Any other network couldn't have pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous system was flawed because it did not have the
Rose Bowl. It took creativity and hard work by ABC to (persuade)
the Rose Bowl to be a part of this. It's not a perfect system. This
is not a perfect world. But it is a guarantee of a national
championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS, although barely visible in the postseason picture now with
only the Sun Bowl, is not ready to concede that guarantee to its
rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is a farce,'' CBS studio analyst Craig James
said. ``It's not what college football fans want. I was talking
playoff system before this, and I'll always talk playoff system.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS studio host Tim Brando said, ``The spin on the Bowl
Championship Series is they want to protect the bowls. But the
bowls are not doing fine. Kansas State was not as deserving as
North Carolina or UCLA last year, but Kansas State went because it
would bring 30,000 people to the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a marketing standpoint, the title Bowl Championship
Series suggests more than one game. Simply because we had a
Nebraska vs. Michigan scenario last year doesn't mean it will work
that way this year.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the game coverage, not much has changed from a year ago.
Keith Jackson and Bob Griese return as ABC's No. 1 team, as do Sean
McDonough and Terry Donahue for CBS and Ron Franklin and Mike
Gottfried for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will make its debut in college football with the Cotton
Bowl, while Fox Sports South again will pick up Raycom's ACC
package at noon for the Atlanta market, while also airing games
from the Southern Conference, Conference USA, Big 12 and the
Pac-10. WATL (Channel 36) will carry Jefferson-Pilot's SEC schedule
at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has revamped its Notre Dame team, with Dick Enberg returning
to the play-by-play role. He will be joined by Pat Haden, who is in
his first year with NBC after eight years with TNT on the NFL.
Before, Haden worked for CBS as college football game analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
