<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-HIGHFIVES-COX     09-02 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-HIGHFIVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL High Fives
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Really good games
</P>
<P>
   Some ``don't-miss'' NFL games that will justify the purchase of
a satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Tampa Bay at Green Bay (Sept. 13): If Tampa Bay is to be a
real contender, it must beat the Packers at Lambeau.
</P>
<P>
   2. Denver at Washington (Sept. 27): Redskins' new tackles, Dana
Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson, get a shot at Broncos RB Terrell
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   3. San Francisco at Green Bay (Nov. 1): Niners get chance to see
if they are for real or just kings of the sorry NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   4. Kansas City at Denver (Dec. 6): One of the best rivalries in
the NFL. Game could determine division championship and playoff
seedings.
</P>
<P>
   5. Pittsburgh at Jacksonville (Dec. 28): Series is tied 3-3, and
the average margin is 3.3 points, with three of the last four
meetings decided in the final two minutes or overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Good gets
</P>
<P>
   Some teams made excellent veteran acquisitions during the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   1. OG Kevin Donnalley (Miami): Coach Jimmy Johnson needed a good
blocker, and he got one.
</P>
<P>
   2. RB Curtis Martin (N.Y. Jets): If he's healthy, and that's a
big if, given his track record, former Patriots star will provide
Bill Parcells the tough inside slasher he wants.
</P>
<P>
   3. DT Dana Stubblefield (Washington): Coming off a 15-sack
season, and Washington paid ($9.9 million) because of it.
</P>
<P>
   4. WR Bert Emanuel (Tampa Bay): Brings big-play potential to Buc
passing game and should become go-to guy for erratic Trent Dilfer.
</P>
<P>
   5. DE Hugh Douglas (Philadelphia): Gives the Eagles their best
outside rusher since DE William Fuller departed in free agency in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   On the rise
</P>
<P>
   Terrific players who are known only to the hardest-core fans.
</P>
<P>
   1. DT Travis Hall (Atlanta): His trademark ``Mormon Maneuver''
rush move has helped him notch 16 1/2 sacks the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   2. OG Ron Stone (N.Y. Giants): Skeptics snickered when the
Giants signed the restricted free agent to a $2.069 million-a-year
deal in '96, but he's developed into a very physical in-line
blocker.
</P>
<P>
   3. OT Jonathan Ogden (Baltimore): Has allowed only three sacks
in two seasons and drives off on running plays better than he used
to.
</P>
<P>
   4. SS John Lynch (Tampa Bay): Sometimes a liability in coverage,
but his strong suit is run support and big hits.
</P>
<P>
   5. LB Mo Lewis (N.Y. Jets): Former University of Georgia player
has played well at all three linebacker spots during his career.
</P>
<P>
   Big hitters worth watching
</P>
<P>
   Open-field defenders who increase concussion rates and insurance
premiums:
</P>
<P>
   1. SS Rodney Harrison (San Diego): Plays the run like a
linebacker and hits bigger than his size.
</P>
<P>
   2. MLB Ray Lewis (Baltimore): Loves to knock off tight ends
coming across the middle. Actually has knocked himself out with
some tackles.
</P>
<P>
   3. ILB Earl Holmes (Pittsburgh): Has good speed and gets into
hitting position quickly.
</P>
<P>
   4. SS Lawyer Milloy (New England): Makes receivers fear him in
the intermediate zones. Has great timing.
</P>
<P>
   5. OLB Jamir Miller (Arizona): Doesn't blitz as much as he once
did but loves a running start before hitting high and driving his
shoulders into opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Terrific tutors
</P>
<P>
   The best assistant coaches, coordinators excluded, no one knows
about.
</P>
<P>
   1. Andy Reid (Green Bay/quarterbacks): Replaced Steve Mariucci
as confidant for Brett Favre. If Mike Holmgren leaves the Packers,
offensive coordinator Sherm Lewis probably gets the job, but Reid
will get some consideration.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bill Kollar (Atlanta/defensive line): Coaching skills are
sometimes overshadowed by legendary growling at practices, but he's
developed into a top assistant.
</P>
<P>
   3. Joe Vitt (Philadelphia/linebackers): Great knowledge in the
``back end'' of a defense and has been very creative in developing
blitz and coverage packages.
</P>
<P>
   4. Kent Stephenson (Pittsburgh/offensive line): Tough-minded and
intense, and Steelers linemen have come to reflect that style.
</P>
<P>
   5. Jim Mora Jr. (San Francisco/secondary): There's no doubt his
name helped get him a job, but in 12 seasons ``J.R.'' has
demonstrated his own expertise.
</P>
<P>
   They love the game
</P>
<P>
   These players would consider playing for free.
</P>
<P>
   1. DE Chuck Smith (Atlanta): Plays with passion. Gives no
quarter and expects none.
</P>
<P>
   2. MLB Ted Johnson (New England): The epitome of what the old
4-3 middle linebackers used to be.
</P>
<P>
   3. OT Ross Verba (Green Bay): Got into a brawl in his first camp
practice as 1997 rookie and immediately earned the respect of QB
Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   4. MLB Ed McDaniel (Minnesota): An overachiever who doesn't know
when to quit; combines intensity with survival instincts.
</P>
<P>
   5. DT Wayne Martin (New Orleans): Rarely gets Pro Bowl
consideration, but he plays the game clean and hard on every snap.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
