<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4542 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-LOWFIVES-COX     09-02 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-LOWFIVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOW FIVES
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Really bad games
</P>
<P>
   These games are for friends and relatives only.
</P>
<P>
   1. Jacksonville at Chicago (Sept. 6): The Jaguars could
represent the AFC in Super Bowl XXXIII. The Bears could have the
first selection in the 1999 draft. The point spread in Las Vegas is
in double-digits.
</P>
<P>
   2. New Orleans at Indianapolis (Sept. 27): Archie Manning's son
plays against his old team. Mike Ditka goes against former Saints
coach Jim Mora. Great storylines in the Big Easy; terrible game for
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   3. St. Louis at New Orleans (Nov. 15): A chance for one of these
NFC West dregs teams to get a victory.
</P>
<P>
   4. Buffalo at Cincinnati (Dec. 6): Both teams probably will be
already eliminated from playoff contention, and the wind will be
howling off the Ohio River. Great reasons to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   5. Kansas City at Oakland (Dec. 26): This used to be one of the
NFL's big rivalries. But the Chiefs have won 15 of the last 17.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeting fame
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks who could lose their starting jobs by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   1. Gus Frerotte (Washington): The four-year veteran is right
behind coach Norv Turner on the Redskins' hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Glenn Foley (N.Y. Jets): The player anointed by coach Bill
Parcells hasn't started and finished with a victory since playing
at Boston College in '93.
</P>
<P>
   3. Tony Banks (St. Louis): Banks hasn't progressed, and coach
Dick Vermeil is losing patience.
</P>
<P>
   4. Billy Joe Hobert (New Orleans): The only reason coach Mike
Ditka likes him so much is that he's the best of a sorry lot.
</P>
<P>
   5. Erik Kramer (Chicago): He already has a history of injuries,
and it won't be easy to stay healthy behind the Bears' shaky
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Really hot seats
</P>
<P>
   Coaches who are high on the endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   1. Ray Rhodes (Philadelphia): His act _ an incredible temper and
a vocabulary that would make some sailors blush _ has worn thin on
players and management.
</P>
<P>
   2. Kevin Gilbride (San Diego): GM Bobby Beathard apparently is
skeptical now about whether Gilbride can succeed.
</P>
<P>
   3. Dennis Green (Minnesota): Forget that the Vikings have been
in the playoffs five times in six seasons; new owner Red McCombs
will want his own man.
</P>
<P>
   4. Dave Wannstedt (Chicago): Wannstedt got total control when he
was hired, but poor drafts are hurting him.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mike Ditka (New Orleans): Never mind the new, three-year
contract extension; the Big Easy will be through with Iron Mike by
the end of this season, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Slip-sliding away
</P>
<P>
   Potential members of the Hall of Fame who stuck around too long.
</P>
<P>
   1. CB Rod Woodson (Baltimore): He's getting beaten by receivers
who shouldn't be on the field with him.
</P>
<P>
   2. DE Reggie White (Green Bay): The greatest sackman in history
is known more now for anti-everything statements.
</P>
<P>
   3. RB Thurman Thomas (Buffalo): One of the finest all-purpose
backs in recent history has been reduced to just one purpose,
third-down receiver, in his 11th season.
</P>
<P>
   4. DE Leslie O'Neal (Kansas City): Will be with his third team
in four seasons, and snaps should be limited primarily to obvious
passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   5. RB Emmitt Smith (Dallas): The workhorse pace of averaging
324.4 rushes a season during his career finally caught up to Smith
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Direct deposits
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most inexplicable free-agent signings of the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   1. DT Ray Agnew (St. Louis): Despite starting just two games in
two seasons, Agnew got a four-year, $8.1 million deal with a $2
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   2. QB Neil O'Donnell (Cincinnati): The usually thrifty Bengals
coughed up a signing bonus of $3.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   3. CB Larry Brown (Minnesota): Good thing the corner-thin Vikes
have only $100,000 in up-front money invested. Brown is slow.
</P>
<P>
   4. DE Gabe Wilkins (San Francisco): He got a $4.5 signing bonus,
but he hasn't practiced yet and won't play until at least
mid-September because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   5. OG Lester Holmes (Arizona): Cardinals paid $11 million for
four years, with a signing bonus of $3.5 million, to an average
blocker.
</P>
<P>
   Bad acts
</P>
<P>
   These people are acting phat but wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   1. WR Michael Irvin (Dallas): Irvin (left) has come to exemplify
the seamy side of the Cowboys, with scissors-wielding incident the
latest. But that's no problem for coddling owner.
</P>
<P>
   2. LB Bryan Cox (N.Y. Jets): Hard to believe that Bill Parcells
will put up with Cox's temper tantrums and lack of control.
</P>
<P>
   3. Owner Al Davis (Oakland): The once-brilliant Davis is living
in a time warp.
</P>
<P>
   4. LB Bill Romanowski (Denver): Way over the edge, even for the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   5. Analyst Joe Theismann (ESPN): Giant ego. Doesn't do his
homework. A master of the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
