<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-PREDICTIONS-COX     09-02 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-PREDICTIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Len Pasquarelli's NFL Preview
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFL writer Len Pasquarelli rates the league from top to bottom.
Power ratings in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   1. GREEN BAY (77.5): Free-agent talent drain puts more pressure
on QB Brett Favre and offense, but three-time MVP is still league's
best playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   2. JACKSONVILLE (77): Probably best overall depth in NFL, and
Jaguars veterans are tired of playing second fiddle to Pittsburgh
in AFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   3. KANSAS CITY (75.5): Only question is suspect running game,
with tailback by committee. The defense, No. 11 in 1997, is even
better this year.
</P>
<P>
   4. DENVER (75): Preseason injuries and offensive-line
uncertainty create some slippage, as QB John Elway stages his
``Farewell Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   5. TAMPA BAY (74): People love to take shots at owner Malcolm
Glazer, but where were all those geniuses when Tony Dungy couldn't
get a job?
</P>
<P>
   6. PITTSBURGH (73.5): Lost some free agents again but retained
director of football operations Tom Donahoe and coach Bill Cowher,
two keys.
</P>
<P>
   7. SAN FRANCISCO (73): Not nearly as good as advertised.
Division is so weak, though, Niners could win 11-12 games just by
showing up.
</P>
<P>
   8. WASHINGTON (72): Management laid out $16.4 million for two
new defensive tackles. This is the season QB Gus Frerotte must show
maturity.
</P>
<P>
   9. MINNESOTA (71.5): Offense rates as one of the league's most
explosive. Defensive coordinator Foge Fazio again will need some
smoke and mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   10. N.Y. GIANTS (71.5): Roster better than a year ago, but a
killer schedule probably translates into fewer victories for coach
Jim Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   11. MIAMI (71): Terrific athletes but few big stars on defensive
side. Will QB Dan Marino be content in a new offense designed to
run the ball?
</P>
<P>
   12. DETROIT (71): Best thing embattled QB Scott Mitchell can do
is keep handing the ball to RB Barry Sanders and get out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   13. NEW ENGLAND (71): Coming off sloppy training camp, and
second-year coach Pete Carroll already is rumored to be on the hot
seat.
</P>
<P>
   14. TENNESSEE (70.5): Intriguing offensive talent, certainly on
fringes of playoff contention. Chances hurt by overall strength of
division.
</P>
<P>
   15. N.Y. JETS (70.5): No denying Bill Parcells is a genius. But
it's hard to imagine making the playoffs with Glenn Foley or Vinny
Testaverde at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   16. CAROLINA (70): Ownership deemed 7-9 record of '97
unacceptable and spent NFL-record $27.32 million this year to sign
veteran free agents.
</P>
<P>
   17. SEATTLE (70): A lot of talent on both sides of the ball.
With Mike Holmgren and George Seifert in the wings, coach Dennis
Erickson needs playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   18. ATLANTA (70): Break-even year very likely, nine victories a
possibility, if offensive line opens some holes and protects QB
Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   19. DALLAS (68.5): Atrocious drafts of past three years catching
up to aging roster, and lack of depth is a problem for rookie coach
Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   20. CINCINNATI (68): Should score plenty of points no matter who
plays quarterback. Young linebackers must grasp exotic zone-blitz
scheme quickly.
</P>
<P>
   21. ARIZONA (67.5): Rampant optimism would be more justified if
the offensive line and safety situations were more settled than
they are.
</P>
<P>
   22. OAKLAND (67.5): Has some of the NFL's most talented pure
athletes, but first-year coach Jon Gruden will find out football
isn't a track meet.
</P>
<P>
   23. BUFFALO (67): Rudimentary design of first-year offensive
coordinator Joe Pendry means fewer mistakes but also few points.
</P>
<P>
   24. BALTIMORE (66.5): Defense in particular has young, promising
players. Still, coach Ted Marchibroda could be gone by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   25. PHILADELPHIA (65.5): Only two years after winning 10 games,
the Eagles have fallen on hard times. Coach Ray Rhodes probably
will be bounced.
</P>
<P>
   26. INDIANAPOLIS (65): Even when the rookie quarterback is named
Peyton Manning, there are going to be the typical rookie mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   27. SAN DIEGO (64): An interesting team because of QB Ryan Leaf,
but there figures to be a major front-office housecleaning at
season's end.
</P>
<P>
   28. NEW ORLEANS (64): The TV cameras will stay on Mike Ditka,
who could become the first coach to spontaneously combust on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   29. ST. LOUIS (63): Have looked pitiful in camp. Fans are booing
every incompletion by QB Tony Banks, and coach Dick Vermeil might
throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   30. CHICAGO (62.5): Should be known as the ``Monstrosities of
the Midway.'' The spiral continues for once-proud franchise now in
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs
</P>
<P>
   NFC DIVISION CHAMPIONS
</P>
<P>
   Washington, Green Bay, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   _ NFC WILD CARDS
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, New York Giants, Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   _ AFC DIVISION CHAMPIONS
</P>
<P>
   Miami, Jacksonville, Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   _ AFC WILD CARDS
</P>
<P>
   Denver, Pittsburgh, New England.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUPER BOWL XXXIII
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay over Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
