<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-NFCCENT-CAP-COX     09-02 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-NFCCENT-CAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC Central capsules
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY PACKERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Mike Holmgren is 73-36 in six seasons with the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 13-3, first in NFC Central (lost in Super Bowl
XXXII).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: CB Doug Evans (FA), DE Gabe Wilkins (FA), OG Aaron
Taylor (FA), RB Edgar Bennett (FA), FS Eugene Robinson (FA), OT
John Michels (injury), P Craig Hentrich (FA), WR Don Beebe
(retired), QB Steve Bono (trade), DT Darius Holland (trade).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: DE Vonnie Holliday (D-1), RB Raymont Harris (FA),
DE Vaughn Booker (trade), CB Terry McDaniel (FA), FS Pat Terrell
(FA), DE Jonathan Brown (D-2), LB Antonio London (FA), DE Eric
Curry (FA), OT Matt Willig (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Despite its free-agent defections the past three
years, Green Bay remains formidable with three-time MVP QB Brett
Favre. When RB Dorsey Levens gets to camp, the skill part of the
offense will be intact. Defensive coordinator Fritz Shurmur might
have to rotate a lot of people in his front seven, particularly on
the line.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY BUCCANEERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Tony Dungy is 17-17 in two seasons with the Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 10-6, second in NFC Central (wild card, lost in
NFC semifinal round).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: RB Errict Rhett (trade), TE Jackie Harris (FA), OG
Jim Pyne (FA), LB Rufus Porter (cut), FS Melvin Johnson (trade), DE
Eric Curry (FA), P Sean Landeta (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: WR Bert Emanuel (FA), WR Jacquez Green (D-2a), FB
Lorenzo Neal (trade), OT Jason Mathews (FA), CB Brian Kelly (D-2b),
QB Jeff Brohm (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: With great depth, team speed and athleticism, Dungy
has closed the gap between the Bucs and Packers. The one-time
doormat franchise should go deep into the playoffs. The biggest
questions still revolve around QB Trent Dilfer, who needs to begin
taking advantage of the upgraded players on offense. WRs Emanuel,
Green and Reidel Anthony can stretch any defense. On defense, DT
Warren Sapp, LB Derrick Brooks and CB Donnie Abraham are among the
NFL's best young players at their positions.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA VIKINGS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Dennis Green is 57-45 in six seasons with the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 9-7, fourth in NFC Central (wild card, lost in
NFC semifinal round).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: CB DeWayne Washington (FA), LB Jeff Brady (cut),
DE Fernando Smith (cut), OG Scott Dill (cut), LB Ron George (cut),
CB Leonard Wheeler (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: WR Randy Moss (D-1), CB Jimmy Hitchcock (trade), PK
Gary Anderson (FA), LB Bobby Houston (FA), CB Larry Brown (FA), DE
Kailee Wong (D-2), CB Ramos McDonald (D-3), QB Jay Fiedler (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: If the Vikings can stop somebody, they could be one
of the NFC's most dangerous teams. The creativity of defensive
coordinator Foge Fazio is underrated. He relies on an aggressive
scheme that emphasizes takeaways, and FS Orlando Thomas, if
healthy, is an opportunistic playmaker. QB Brad Johnson appears to
have recovered from neck surgery and began throwing better late in
camp.With WRs Cris Carter, Jake Reed and Moss, few secondaries will
be able to match up.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT LIONS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Bobby Ross is 9-8 in one season with the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 9-7, third in NFC Central (wild card, lost in
first round of playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: C Kevin Glover (FA), DT Mike Wells (FA), LB Reggie
Brown (injury), KR Glyn Milburn (trade), TE Pete Metzelaars
(retired), CB Corey Raymond (cut), LB Antonio London (FA), DT Shane
Bonham (FA), SS Van Malone (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: LB Allen Aldridge (FA), DT Dan Owens (FA), LB Rob
Fredrickson (trade), OG Jim Pyne (FA), CB Terry Fair (D-1), QB
Charlie Batch (D-3), WR Germaine Crowell (D-2).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The pressure is on erratic QB Scott Mitchell, much of
it from an impatient Ross. The spectacular RB Barry Sanders goes
after 1,500-plus yards for the fifth time in a row. Mitchell must
overcome his inconsistency in big games. A revamped linebacker
group will upgrade the overall defense, but the biggest improvement
should come from the continued development of second-year CBs Kevin
Abrams and Bryant Westbrook.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO BEARS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Dave Wannstedt is 37-45 in five seasons with the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 4-12, fifth in NFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: RB Raymont Harris (cut), LB Bryan Cox (cut), DE
Alonzo Spellman (cut), FB Tony Carter (FA), RB Rashaan Salaam
(cut), WR Ricky Proehl (FA), OG Todd Burger (FA), KR Tyrone Hughes
(cut), KR Glyn Milburn (trade), OG Chris Gray (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: RB Curtis Enis (D-1), DT Mike Wells (FA), DT Shawn
Lee (trade), RB Edgar Bennett (FA), FS Tony Parrish (D-2), FB Ty
Hallock (FA), LB Rico McDonald (FA), C Olin Kreutz (D-3), LB Andre
Collins (FA), OG Mike Zandofsky (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Most observers who saw the Bears in preseason are
convinced they are legitimate contenders for the No. 1 overall pick
in the '99 draft. The club seems to lack direction, certainly is
shy on talent and is paying the price for some of Wannstedt's worst
draft decisions. New vice president Mark Hatley might be able to
put Humpty Dumpty back together again, but he'll probably have a
new coach manning the glue jar.
</P>
