<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanders still going strong at age 30
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long dash into the history books is probably only two good
seasons away for Barry Sanders, certainly no more than three.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders, the brilliant Detroit Lions running back who has
used his trademark elusiveness to climb to within shouting distance
of Walter Payton's all-time rushing mark, cannot dodge an obvious
question as he enters his 10th pro season.
</P>
<P>
   Can the best pure runner the NFL has ever seen defy history at
age 30, a chronological turning point at which even great backs
have gone into a steady downward spiral? Even as Sanders was
blowing out the candles on his birthday cake the week before
training camp opened, he was blowing off the notion he is suddenly
going to decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't age just in one year or in one day,'' said Sanders,
who needs 2,949 yards to pass Payton's rushing record. ``In my
workouts, games, whatever, I don't feel any different. Unless folks
are lying to me, no one else sees any difference, either. The
(drop-off), it seems to me, is more a gradual thing anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But in the 78-year history of the NFL, no player in
his 30s ever has won a rushing title. Only a dozen backs aged 30 or
older have rushed for 1,000 yards. Dallas tailback Emmitt Smith,
eight months younger than Sanders, is a prime example of how the
production of workhorse runners can slip as they approach 30.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's 1,684 yards in 1984 is the most ever gained by a
30-something runner. But coaches will be surprised if Sanders, who
has run for 1,500 yards a record four straight times, doesn't
demolish that mark. Just two workouts into camp, coach Bobby Ross
had seen Sanders sidestep would-be tacklers enough to realize that
the team's offensive meal ticket remains the premier back in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't lose anything from the end of last year to this
camp,'' Ross said. ``Then again, I hadn't expected him to.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sanders joined Eric Dickerson and O.J. Simpson as the
only backs to rush for 2,000 yards in a season, his 2,053 yards the
second-most ever. Dickerson ran for 2,105 yards in 1984 and then
slipped to 1,234 the following year. Simpson's total fell by 878
yards the season after he went for 2,003 yards in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders isn't predicting another 2,000-yard campaign, but he's
not imposing limits on what he feels he can accomplish in '98. ``I
think,'' he said, laughing, ``I'm maybe still good enough to play
in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   BARRY SANDERS' RUSHING RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Year Team G GS Att. Yds. Avg. TD
</P>
<P>
   1989 Team 15 13 280 Yds. Avg. 14
</P>
<P>
   1990 Team 16 16 255 Yds. Avg. 13
</P>
<P>
   1991 Team 15 15 342 Yds. Avg. 16
</P>
<P>
   1992 Team 16 16 312 Yds. Avg. 9
</P>
<P>
   1993 Team 11 11 243 Yds. Avg. 3
</P>
<P>
   1994 Team 16 16 331 Yds. Avg. 7
</P>
<P>
   1995 Team 16 16 314 Yds. Avg. 11
</P>
<P>
   1996 Team 16 16 307 Yds. Avg. 11
</P>
<P>
   1997 Team 16 16 335 Yds. Avg. 11
</P>
