<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giants hungry for second chance
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because those who ignore the past are destined to repeat it, New
York Giants coach Jim Fassel wouldn't allow his young team to
easily forget its painful postseason collapse of 1997. So when
training camp opened this summer, there were frequent reminders
from the scholarly looking Fassel of how the Giants squandered a
nine-point lead against Minnesota in the final 2 1/2 minutes of a
first-round playoff defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the old line about how tomorrow is promised to no
one?'' said linebacker Jesse Armstead, the emotional leader of the
NFL's best young defense. ``The feeling around here is that none of
us can wait for another shot, (because) it won't happen the next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' critics think that shot might be a long time coming.
They contend New York's success resulted from an easy 1997 schedule
and suggest the Giants sneaked up on opponents in a season when the
NFC East was the weakest it has been in years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants were undefeated in intradivisional play and could
be ready to surprise again this year. A tough schedule could keep
Fassel's team from matching its 10 victories of a year ago, but
players and coaches insist the Giants are more solid than they were
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are actually pretty psyched that teams will be out
gunning for us,'' said quarterback Danny Kanell, who must improve
if New York is to advance past the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Kanell improves, a defense that is solid at every
position will carry the team. A front four led by end Michael
Strahan and tackle Keith Hamilton is imposing; its starters
averaged 8.2 sacks last year. Armstead is an emerging star.
Cornerback Phillippi Sparks is strong.
</P>
<P>
   The season-ending injury to cornerback Jason Sehorn is
devastating, however, and top pick Shaun Williams, normally a
safety, is being asked to work some at corner.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, which helped New York to a league-best plus-25
turnover differential, doesn't have a starter as much as 30 years
of age. Little wonder the Giants insist the stunning loss to the
Vikings was more a beginning than an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be around for several more years,'' said strong
safety Sam Garnes. ``So people better get used to that idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
