<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers can toss Rice against defenses
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Even before Jerry Rice sustained a severe
knee injury in the 1997 season opener, San Francisco 49ers rookie
coach Steve Mariucci had decided his debut season would feature a
back-to-the-future twist.
</P>
<P>
   So when Rice went down on Aug. 31, Mariucci re-emphasized, even
more than he had planned, a physical running game and increased use
of the screen pass. It served the 49ers well, as they ranked 12th
in total offense and fifth in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, the NFL's career leader in touchdowns, is healthy again in
his 14th season. His return will allow Mariucci to transform his
play-calling from fundamental to fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many possibilities for us,'' said quarterback
Steve Young, who benefited from the conservative approach last year
to stay healthy enough to start 15 games, his most since 1994.
``The plan is to be more wide-open.''
</P>
<P>
   That likely means an increase in three-wide-receiver sets, with
Rice joining Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes, the youngsters who
stepped up big in 1997. The 49ers historically haven't featured the
three-receiver alignment much; instead, they relied on packages
that made clever use of the tailback and often kept the tight end
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of Stokes and Owens, who both possess the size the
Niners always have stressed at the position, will serve as a
catalyst for change. Stokes had 58 catches for 733 yards and four
touchdowns, and Owens had 60 catches for 936 yards and eight TDs.
There are plans to use Rice in the slot position, where single
coverage is dictated. If the running attack continues to struggle
behind a makeshift line, Mariucci might rely heavily on the three
wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The three receivers should present a tough physical matchup for
any secondary, and the three men know it. Stokes is 6 feet 4, 223
pounds; Owens is 6-3, 217, and Rice is 6-2, 196.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many teams with three corners good enough to
cover us all,'' Owens said. ``We're going to have some fun with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
