R.W. McQuarters (D-1), DE Gabe Wilkins (FA), QB Ty Detmer (FA), OT
Jamie Brown (trade), SS Lance Schulters (D-4), TE Irv Smith (FA),
DT Shane Bonham (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: If a team could win a division by default, it might
be the 49ers. They aren't as talented as in the past, but it might
not matter in the NFC West. The biggest problems for San Francisco
are up front. The offensive line is unsettled, and the defensive
line will play at least the first two games undermanned. Look for
more three-wideout sets from Mariucci.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINA PANTHERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Dom Capers is 27-23 in three seasons with the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 7-9, second in NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: LB Sam Mills (retired), OG Greg Skrepenak (cut),
FS Chad Cota (FA), DE Gerald Williams (retired), DT Greg Kragen
(retired), TE Walter Rasby (FA), OG Matt Elliott (FA), LB Andre
Royal (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: DT Sean Gilbert (FA), CB Doug Evans (FA), FB
William Floyd (FA), offensive coordinator Gill Haskell (Green Bay),
DE Jason Peter (D-1), FS Brent Alexander (FA), OG Corbin Lacina
(FA), LB Ernest Dixon (FA), WR Donald Hayes (D-4).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Owner Jerry Richardson deemed '97 unacceptable and
spent a league-record $27.325 million on veteran free agents. The
defense will have at least six and maybe eight new starters, but
age is a concern at outside linebacker. QB Kerry Collins seems
comfortable with the new West Coast offense, but the running game
has looked awful. The line is fairly average, and one-time
undrafted free agent RB Fred Lane will have to show he's not a
flash in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA FALCONS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Dan Reeves is 7-9 in one season with the Falcons and
156-122-1 in 17 NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 7-9, second in NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: WR Bert Emanuel (FA), DT Dan Owens (FA), C Roman
Fortin (cut), QB Jim Miller (FA), OT Matt Willig (FA), DE Anthony
Pleasant (cut), OT Antone Davis (cut), DT Nathan Davis (retired),
LB David Brandon (cut).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: WR Tony Martin (trade), FS Eugene Robinson (FA), LB
Keith Brooking (D-1), WR Keith Crawford (FA), C/OT Dave Widell
(FA), CB Randy Fuller (FA), WR Tim Dwight (D-4b), OT Corey Louchiey
(FA), QB Steve DeBerg (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: One of Reeves' strengths is his ability to keep a
game close and give his team a chance to win late. During the
second half of last season, the Falcons began making
``crunch-time'' plays to win those close games, and they have to
build on that experience. The offensive line is a concern again,
especially right tackle. Coordinator Rich Brooks established a much
sounder defense in '97 and maybe can add some wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS SAINTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Mike Ditka is 6-10 in one season with the Saints and
118-78 in 12 NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 6-10, fourth in NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: CB Eric Allen (trade), LB Winfred Tubbs (FA), DE
Darren Mickell (retired), TE Irv Smith (FA), RB Mario Bates (FA),
WR Randal Hill (FA), SS Anthony Newman (FA), QB Heath Shuler
(injury), WR Daryl Hobbs (cut).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: OT Kyle Turley (D-1), WR Sean Dawkins (FA), FS Chad
Cota (FA), RB Lamar Smith (FA), CB Tyronne Drakeford (FA), TE Cam
Cleeland (D-2), LB Andre Royal (FA), LB Kevin Mitchell (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Zaven Yaralian gets his gritty defense to play hard
every week, and he designs some creative blitzes to take advantage
of the quickness of OLB Mark Fields. If DE Joe Johnson continues to
hold out, though, DL will be thin. No matter how well the defense
performs, it won't be good enough, because the offense still lacks
a top-shelf quarterback and enough playmakers. If QB Billy Joe
Hobert is the best you have, it's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS RAMS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Dick Vermeil is 5-11 in one season with the Rams and
62-62 in eight NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 5-11, fifth in NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: DT Bill Johnson (FA), DE Leslie O'Neal (cut), LB
Robert Smith (cut), C Bern Brostek (retired), WR Keith Crawford
(FA), QB Mark Rypien (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: LB Eric Hill (FA), WR Ricky Proehl (FA), DE Grant
Wistrom (D-1), RB Greg Hill (FA), DT Ray Agnew (FA), RB Robert
Holcombe (D-2), QB Steve Bono (trade), DT Joe Phillips (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Rams have talent but don't play well in games.
It's clear something is missing and that talent isn't enough. Word
is that players are grousing about Vermeil's extra-long practices,
and some veterans want out. The guy Vermeil soon may want out is QB
Tony Banks, whose maturity level and leaderships skills have yet to
catch up to his talent. Jim Hanifan is the league's premier
offensive-line coach, but he hasn't been able to put together a
solid enough group. The defense simply has too many underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
