<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-SIZE-COX     09-02 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-SIZE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bigger players at all positions: An expanding league trend
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From a burgeoning database of 80,000-plus athletes, Dr. Frank I.
Katch, a professor of exercise science at the University of
Massachusetts, has arrived at a startling conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   By the 2007 season, offensive linemen in the NFL will average a
whopping 6-feet-8 and 300 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The thick research files that threaten to engulf Katch's
on-campus office and his home in Amherst, Mass., aren't the only
things expanding in the NFL's universe. This advice for equipment
managers leaguewide: Start ordering up the size-XXXXL practice
pants before the rush begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tracked growth since the 1920s, and you can identify
certain periods where it's on an upswing and others where it levels
off for a while,'' said Katch, who has served as a consultant for
several NFL teams. ``In the early '80s, it was relatively flat.
Now, we are back on the rise again. It makes you wonder if there's
a limit to `big' in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The league that was founded at a Canton, Ohio, automobile
showroom in 1920, is being re-created by a Big Bang Theory all its
own: If you're big and like to bang people around, an NFL training
camp probably has a spot for you.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1980, the league had no 300-pound players. This
year, 361 of the 2,493 players who went to training camps _ nearly
15 percent and an average of 12 heavyweights per team _ weighed 300
pounds or more. At least three dozen players weighed more than 340.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played (at 6-7, 291), it was like I was some kind of a
freak,'' said former defensive tackle Dave Butz, who played 16
seasons before retiring in 1988. ``Now, teams might not give me a
second look.''
</P>
<P>
   Size is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I couldn't hold up at anything less than (the 320 pounds)
I am,'' Washington defensive tackle Dan ``Big Daddy'' Wilkinson
said. ``You get those big, ol' (offensive) guards hanging on you,
and you better be pound for pound with them. I mean, those are some
big (people) there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at the so-called ``skill'' positions, average height and
weight has increased dramatically in the past two decades. Starting
quarterbacks in 1998, for instance, are an inch taller and 16
pounds heavier than their counterparts were in the 1980 season.
Ryan Leaf, who weighed 261 pounds at combine workouts last spring,
wondered what all the fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   There are similar increases for wide receivers and cornerbacks.
On the offensive and defensive lines, the gains are substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The ``all-size'' team, a lineup compiled by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and comprising the biggest veteran starters at
each position, features an offense averaging 282.6 pounds and a
defense that averages 268 pounds. Thin, certainly, is not in.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cases, just because you're bigger doesn't mean you're
necessarily better,'' said Chet Fuhrman, the conditioning
coordinator for the Pittsburgh Steelers. ``But with us seeing so
many 320-pound guys nowadays who can move so quickly, . . . that
axiom might not be true anymore in the NFL. Yeah, it's become a
`bigger is better' league.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran coach Bill Parcells and former New York Giants general
manager George Young once espoused a shared brainchild known as the
``Planet Theory.'' It held that there is a finite number of
large-bodied individuals on planet Earth and shame on the personnel
director who passed one by. For years, the ``Planet Theory'' shaped
Giants draft classes, Young at one point taking six offensive or
defensive linemen in the first round in a 10-year stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Now the ``Planet Theory'' is reshaping the entire league.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson, who long has favored speed
over size, brought to camp this year 16 players who weighed 300
pounds or more. Parcells also had 16 in his New York Jets camp. The
New York Giants had a league-high 19. Just five of 30 teams brought
fewer than 10 to camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's a big man's game, certainly,'' Johnson said recently
between training camp practices. ``You can't ignore what's gone on
with size just in the last 10 years alone.''
</P>
<P>
   League personnel directors spent much of the summer driving by
giant billboards that touted the movie ``Godzilla'' and declared,
``Size does matter.'' Most of those talent scouts chuckled quietly
at the advertising. ``Hey, we could all have signs like that in our
scouting offices,'' Oakland Raiders personnel man Ken Herock said.
</P>
<P>
   What surprises some people is that The Big Boom continues,
despite the fact the Denver Broncos received so much publicity just
seven months ago for taking Super Bowl XXXII without a single
300-pounder on their offensive line. The victory seemed to
reinforce the notion that leverage, not tonnage, is the most
essential element in line play.
</P>
<P>
   That's true only to a certain extent, said St. Louis Rams
assistant coach Jim Hanifan, one of the premier offensive line
coaches in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What everyone thought,'' Hanifan said, ``is that we'd all run
out and start beating the bushes for 280- or 290-pound linemen.
Uh-uh. All it meant when the Broncos won was that we'd now look at
the smaller guys a little different, that's all. But if you're
asking, 'Do I want a 280-pound guy with quick feet or a 310-pound
guy with the same kind of feet' _ well, brother, that's a
no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Dallas guard Nate Newton looked like a Slim
Fast poster boy after shedding 75 pounds from his 350-something
frame. In recent days, however, Newton admitted he might have
overdone it. Former Atlanta Falcons offensive tackle Lincoln
Kennedy, now with the Raiders, went to camp at 325 pounds, the
lightest he has been since high school. He decided to bulk back up
to about 340 because he felt too weak at the lower weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be a place for the great player, no
matter what he weighs,'' said Arizona Cardinals defensive line
coach Joe Greene, the Pittsburgh Steelers' Hall of Fame tackle.
``Look at (John) Randle or (Warren) Sapp. They're dominating
tackles, and they don't play at 300. But if you're going to play in
the 270s or 280s, you have to be exceptional anymore just to hang
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of Hall of Fame selectors two weeks ago, all-time
middle linebacker Joe Schmidt, who played at 222 pounds for 13
seasons, argued emotionally that size has replaced skills in the
NFL. He might have a point. Katch fears that without post-NFL
counseling, most 300-pounders are headed for physical disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants 'bigger, bigger, bigger,' and it can be
dangerous,'' Katch said. ``For all their claims in the NFL,
steroids still aren't totally under control. The coaches don't want
to hear about it, and the players won't talk about it, but there's
still a lot of underground stuff going on. It's like size has
become the prize, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Katch, who once worked for Washington, told the story of a
tearful Butz coming to him and explaining his reluctance to accept
Redskins coach George Allen's demand that he bulk up to 305 pounds.
``He cried, literally,'' Katch said. ``He said to me, 'I think
about my weight every single day.' And that was years ago, before
this craze for bigger. Like I said before, you wonder where it's
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to Madison, Wis., is where. That's the home of the
Wisconsin Badgers, a team that features Aaron Gibson. A senior
offensive tackle, Gibson is an All-Big Ten player. He is projected
to be among the top five players selected in the 1999 NFL draft.
And he regularly plays at almost 400 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
