</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-SIZE-LB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LINEBACKERS: 276-pounder gives chase to passers and receivers
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATROBE, Pa. _ There are 115 defensive linemen projected as
starters in next weekend's NFL regular-season openers, and
linebacker Levon Kirkland outweighs 32 of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers star entered the league in 1992 at 240
pounds. Six years and 36 pounds later, Kirkland sees his status as
one of the bulkiest linebackers in league history as worth the
weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I can still run, and I think I can, it gives our
defense a lot of flexibility,'' he said. ``There are certain things
we can scheme around my size and ability and not have to substitute
to do them. Certainly, I'm a better player now than I was (at 240
pounds).''
</P>
<P>
   That he went from huge to hulking wasn't necessarily planned by
Kirkland, who spent his rookie season playing on special teams. But
years in the weight room at Three Rivers Stadium, combined with
offseasons spent at home in Lamar, S.C., feasting on his mother's
fried chicken, eventually added up.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 NFL combine workouts, Kirkland ran the 40-yard dash
in 4.88 seconds. While the Steelers don't clock their veteran
players annually, linebackers coach Mike Archer estimated
Kirkland's current time probably isn't much over five seconds. The
quickness allows Pittsburgh to keep the seventh-year veteran, who
recently signed a new contract that makes him the NFL's
highest-paid linebacker, on the field for third down.
</P>
<P>
   The past two years, Kirkland's versatility netted him six
interceptions, nine sacks and a dozen passes defensed. On the first
two defensive series of last year's AFC title game, Kirkland, who
played at Clemson, had two solo tackles, a quarterback pressure off
an inside blitz and an interception. In his team's Super Bowl XXX
loss, he had 10 tackles, a sack and a pass defensed.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland is regarded by Steelers fans as the team's best inside
linebacker since Hall of Famer Jack Lambert retired after the 1984
season. Lambert also could cover the tight end but did so while
weighing 212 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You expect (Kirkland) to muscle you,'' Denver tight end
Shannon Sharpe said. ``What you don't expect is that he'll hang
with you 15 yards up the field _ but he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   The unassuming Kirkland is part of a trend of growing
linebackers bigger. As recently as 15 years ago, just a handful of
linebackers in the NFL weighed 240 pounds. This season, seven
linebackers weigh at least 255, and the average weight for starters
now is more than 230 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 0905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-SIZE-QB-COX     09-02 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-SIZE-QB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUARTERBACKS: QB's have gotten bigger and stronger as well
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ His critics, including several who can be
identified in the New England locker room, say Drew Bledsoe must
toughen mentally before the underachieving Patriots can claim their
first Super Bowl victory. Because he disagrees with the assessment,
and wouldn't know where to find a gym that specializes in mental
calisthenics, Bledsoe spent the past few months girding himself
physically for the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Probably harder than in any other spring, the five-year veteran
hit the weight room. The result is a well-toned quarterback better
prepared to deal with a pass rush. And Bledsoe is not the only
quarterback suddenly more conscious of conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the past two seasons, Miami's Dan Marino has
attempted to slow the aging process by working with a personal
trainer. Always a weight-room guy, Jeff George of Oakland recently
got into a power-walking program. Tampa Bay's Trent Dilfer became a
regular on the weight machines this year, to shed soft fat and
improve muscle mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too long ago, I'm sure it was almost (sacrilegious) for a
quarterback to be pumping (weights),'' Bledsoe said during a spring
minicamp. ``But you take so many big hits now at the position . . .
that you have to be prepared to withstand them. Everybody at every
other position is bigger now, and you're seeing bigger
quarterbacks, too. I mean, look at (Ryan) Leaf. The guy is huge; he
looks like a linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf sent personnel directors into apoplexy when he arrived for
the NFL combine seven months ago at a whopping 261 pounds. He is 20
pounds lighter now, and during preseason looked like a sequoia with
legs when he dropped into the pocket. If he isn't yet the prototype
at his position, Leaf certainly is a sneak preview of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL likes quarterbacks who are ``tall in the pocket,'' but
that scout euphemism is a bit inaccurate. What coaches really
prefer is a sturdy passer, and statistics indicate that the league
leans heavily toward passers who have a better chance for
durability.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the 28 starting quarterbacks averaged 6-feet-2 1/2 and
205.3 pounds. Phil Simms (6-3, 216) and Terry Bradshaw (6-2, 215)
were considered physical tough guys and the heaviest quarterback
weighed 220. The average height of the 30 starters for this season
has increased only an inch over 1980, to 6-feet-3 1/2. But the
average weight has increased to 221.7 pounds, and 14 passers weigh
225 pounds or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, in a league where the battle cry is 'Get the
quarterback' and everybody wants to see a lot of sacks, it's a
matter of survival,'' Bledsoe said. ``It's one thing to take the
hits, but the biggest thing is being able to get up from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
