</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-SIZE-WR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battles taking place at higher level
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 11 months after the fact, each of the players still
recalls the head-to-head confrontation on Oct. 19 as the equivalent
of a championship title fight that just happened to be surrounded
by a football game.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner, Detroit Lions four-time Pro Bowl performer Herman
Moore, 6 feet 4 and 210 pounds and probably the most physical wide
receiver in the NFL. In the other, Jason Sehorn, the New York
Giants' emerging star, and at 6-2 and 212 pounds, the prototype for
the bigger-is-better cornerback philosophy that is pervading the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (was) a knock-down, drag-out afternoon,'' Moore said
about his matchup with Sehorn for more than half of the Lions' 65
offensive snaps in a 26-20 overtime defeat. ``He is a strong guy
who can dominate you with his raw strength. He is one of the best.
But, really, we're seeing these gigantic cornerbacks almost every
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore caught seven passes in the game, but only two against
Sehorn. The corner had a key pass defensed and seven
tackles.Defensive coordinators urgently seeking Sehorn wannabes are
acting in response to the offenses. About eight years ago, it
became fashionable for teams to draft bigger wide receivers. The
success of such pass-catchers as Moore, Michael Irvin and Jake Reed
triggered the predictable countermove: long, lean cornerbacks to
cover them.
</P>
<P>
   Giants defensive coordinator John Fox said the trend toward
bigger corners has a back-to-the-future flavor. The seven pure
cornerbacks in the Hall of Fame averaged just under 6 feet 2 and
198.4 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts going onto college campuses now check out safeties as
would-be cornerbacks, if possible. The standard rationale _ that
cornerback is easier to learn as a rookie _ is only half the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get (wide) receivers reaching up and just plucking
the ball away from a tiny corner, you have to do something about
that,'' Philadelphia defensive coordinator Emmitt Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   So in his second year with the Eagles, coach Ray Rhodes drafted
Notre Dame cornerback Bobby Taylor (6-3, 216) to help his defense
match up better with the big wideouts in the NFC East. A year after
that, he signed ``transition'' free-agent corner Troy Vincent (6-0,
194) from Miami. For all the talk of size, though, the bigger keys
are still strong hands and quick feet, Sehorn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to turn and run deep with those guys,''
said Sehorn, who will miss the 1998 season with a knee injury.
``But the overlooked element is hand strength. If you can get your
hands on (a receiver) and redirect him, it's half the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
