</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-TVCOLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBS return causes ripples in TV lineups
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When CBS stepped into the NFL negotiations with a check for $4
billion for the AFC package, and Disney followed by giving ESPN the
green light to pay $4.8 billion for the entire Sunday night cable
package, it meant viewers would need a scorecard to keep up with
all the movement among the announcers.
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, there has never been a season for change like
this one. The biggest involves CBS returning to the NFL, a move
that ousted NBC and set off a chain of events that would introduce
new faces and put some old faces in new places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't start with a blank sheet,'' CBS executive producer
Terry Ewert said. ``We played the what-if game ... if we got the
NFL back. We looked at over 130 resumes and inquiries and reviewed
close to 60 demo tapes. Although we've looked to upgrade
operationally and technically, we knew we had a good infrastructure
to resume our NFL coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But CBS turned to NBC's talent roster for its No. 1 announcing
team. Both Greg Gumbel (play-by-play) and analyst Phil Simms left
NBC to ride in the lead chariot for CBS. Armen Keteyian was then
lured from ABC to join them as a sideline reporter.
</P>
<P>
   For Gumbel, the decision to return was easy, because it was
during his first stint at CBS from 1989-94 that he secured his
place as one of sport television's top talents. Simms said his
decision was a no-brainer, too, while Keteyian jumped at the chance
to do the NFL. On paper, it looks like CBS has compiled a winning
combination for its No. 1 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes there is a tendency to try and reinvent the wheel.
But we do not want to lose sight of the fact people just want to
watch football,'' Gumbel said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Simms: ``The biggest thing is: Let's just don't mess it
up. This is a great game for TV, so keep it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Verne Lundquist, who returns to CBS after a three-year stint
with Turner, joins analyst Randy Cross and reporter Michele Tafoya
on the No. 2 team. The other teams include Kevin Harlan-Sam Wyche,
Gus Johnson-Steve Tasker, Ian Eagle-Mark May and Don Criqui-Beasley
Reece.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS pregame show is expected to receive the most scrutiny.
Only host Jim Nantz and reporter Bonnie Berstein (from ESPN) are
experienced. The three analysts, Marcus Allen, Brent Jones and
George Seifert, are rookies in network television.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps CBS felt compelled to go with a totally new look because
of the imposing competition from ESPN's ``NFL Countdown,'' which
added an extra half-hour and former Bills quarterback Jim Kelly to
the formidable cast of Chris Berman, Tom Jackson, Sterling Sharpe
and Chris Mortensen. And Fox's star-studded lineup got stronger
with charismatic Cris Collinsworth joining Terry Bradshaw, Howie
Long and James Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled for Jim Nantz, but it will be tough for anybody
to get rhythm with three guys who have not been in that environment
before,'' Fox executive producer Ed Goren said. ``Jim will not have
an asset like we had with Terry Bradshaw, who was experienced in
the studio setting and took Howie and J.B. under his wing. If Nantz
had that kind of anchor, it would make it easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ewert: ``We know we are going against two great pregame
shows. But we wanted to come up with an alternative that would be
contemporary and newsy with a certain hard edge. All three of our
analysts have broadcasting experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brent and George did sports talk, and Marcus had his own show
in Kansas City. They are not new to the red light going on.... We
are going to surprise some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Another surprise was Frank Gifford's resignation from ``Monday
Night Football.'' Gifford will join Berman on an abbreviated
pregame show, but Boomer Esiason will take his place beside Al
Michaels and Dan Dierdorf. Judging by the preseason telecasts, the
transition will be a smooth one.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth could also be used to describe ESPN's move to a three-man
booth on ``Sunday Night Football,'' with Paul Maguire joining Mike
Patrick and Joe
</P>
<P>
   Theismann. Initially, Theismann voiced his preference for a
two-man booth, but was singing a different tune after a couple of
preseason telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egos always take a back seat because the single most important
element is the game,'' Theismann said. ``I didn't have an
expectation going in, but that first broadcast felt like we had
been working together forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, CNN's ``NFL Preview'' moves to 10 a.m. to get the
jump on the pregame competition, while HBO's long-running ``Inside
the NFL'' stood pat with Len Dawson, Nick Buoniconti, Jerry
Glanville and Collinsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
