<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-AFCEAST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins fulfilling J.J.'s need for speed
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The man's gait is reminiscent of an Olympic
speed-walker, and he talks with the rat-a-tat precision of a
Gatling gun.
</P>
<P>
   Have a beer with Jimmy Johnson, and he will chug-a-lug a
Heineken over ice before your mug is half-empty. When it comes to
falling in and out of love with a rookie, no one in the NFL does it
faster.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder, then, that in the bigger-is-better universe of
the NFL, the Miami coach likes a bit of contradiction? He knows
that size is good. But speed, Johnson decided long ago, is what
kills offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first thing Jimmy looks at, especially on
defense,'' Dolphins director of football operations Bob Ackles
said. ``If you can't run, you can't play defense for Jimmy. It's
that simple. He really is a speed freak.''
</P>
<P>
   The revamped Miami defense certainly reflects Johnson's
preference.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding 320-pound tackles Tim Bowens, who finally ended a
long camp holdout, and Daryl Gardener in the front seven are lean
and athletic players. The first four ends on the depth chart
average 262.8 pounds. Except for Zach Thomas in the middle, the
linebackers look more like tight ends. The emphasis in a reshuffled
secondary is on ``ball skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Taylor, who struggles to keep his weight above 250 pounds
but who can run around blocks and get upfield, is one of Johnson's
favorites. A thin frame kept Taylor on the 1997 draft board until
the third round, long enough for Johnson to ignore his lack of bulk
and focus on the player's quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Jimmy is that he doesn't worry about the
packaging,'' Taylor said. ``If you're an end who can make plays,
he's the last guy who's going to say, `Yeah, but he's a little too
skinny.' He talks all the time about dictating (to the offense)
with speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The blueprint, tweaked slightly from Johnson's championship days
in Dallas, could dramatically improve a unit that ranked No. 26
last season. After a preseason loss to Johnson's team, Washington
Redskins players noted the difficulty they had holding blocks
against the slippery Dolphins defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want play-makers, and that means across the board, not just
at the so-called skill positions,'' Johnson said. ``Give me a bunch
of guys who can redirect, knock the ball loose, scoop it up and run
it in . . . and I'm happy. I think we have more of those kinds of
players now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
