<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 09:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRO-AFCWEST-CAPS     09-02 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRO-AFCWEST-CAPS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC West capsules
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY CHIEFS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Marty Schottenheimer is 97-56-1 in nine seasons with
the Chiefs and 143-87-1 in 14 NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 13-3, first in AFC West (lost in AFC semifinal
round).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: RB Marcus Allen (retired), RB Greg Hill (FA),
offensive coordinator Paul Hackett (Southern Cal), DE Vaughn Booker
(trade), FS Kevin Ross (retired), WR Lake Dawson (cut).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: DT Chester McGlockton (FA), WR Derrick Alexander
(FA), DE Leslie O'Neal (FA), OT Victor Riley (D-1), DT Darius
Holland (trade), FS Melvin Johnson (trade), RB Rashaan Shehee
(D-3).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Chiefs have finished first or second in the
division all nine seasons under Schottenheimer but haven't made it
to a Super Bowl. Even the true believers who pack Arrowhead Stadium
on Sunday are focusing on the coach's subpar playoff performances.
The Chiefs almost certainly will make the '98 postseason. How far
they go probably will depend on how well Jimmy Raye's new offense
clicks. The tailback-by-committee situation could be troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER BRONCOS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Mike Shanahan is 37-16 in three seasons with the
Broncos and 45-28 in five NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 12-4, second in AFC West (wild card, won Super
Bowl XXXII).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: OT Gary Zimmerman (retired), DE Alfred Williams
(injury), OG Brian Habib (FA), LB Allen Aldridge (FA), QB Jeff
Lewis (injury), OT Jamie Brown (trade), CB Tim McKyer (cut).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: WR Marcus Nash (D-1), DE Marvin Washington (FA), SS
Eric Brown (D-2), DE Anthony Smith (FA), C Courtney Hall (FA), WR
Justin Armour (FA), DE Martin Harrison (DE), QB Brian Griese (D-3).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: After taking 15 years to win his first Super Bowl, QB
John Elway could go 2-for-2. Even without Zimmerman, the talent
level is high, and RB Terrell Davis, the offensive hub, is a unique
runner. Shanahan is savvy enough to prevent any letdown the Broncos
might suffer after capturing Elway's holy grail. But his defensive
staff might not be able to compensate for a shaky front seven. The
Broncos spent much of camp looking for a middle linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE SEAHAWKS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Dennis Erickson is 23-25 in three seasons with the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 8-8, third in AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: C/OG Kevin Mawae (FA), RB Chris Warren (cut), RB
Lamar Smith (FA), SS Bennie Blades (retired), LB Winston Moss
(retired), OT James Atkins (FA), FS Tim Hauck (FA), DE Martin
Harrison (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: RB Ricky Watters (FA), C Kevin Glover (FA), LB
Anthony Simmons (D-1), LB Darrin Smith (FA), RB Ahman Green (D-3),
OG Brian Habib (FA), FS Mark Collins (FA), OG Chris Gray (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Erickson almost certainly needs a playoff berth to
save his job. Seattle should be aided by the hiring of Pete
Rodriguez, a top-flight special teams coach, who will be asked to
solve the club's glaring problems in the kicking game. The defense
is quick, with LB Chad Brown and DE Michael Sinclair pressuring
from outside. The secondary doesn't play up to its talent. On
offense, QB Warren Moon likes to spread the field, but he'll be
more content this year to hand the ball to Watters.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND RAIDERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: John Gruden is in his first season as an NFL head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 4-12, fourth in AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: DT Chester McGlockton (FA), CB Terry McDaniel
(cut), LB Rob Fredrickson (trade), DE Leon Bender (deceased), OG
Lester Holmes (FA), DE Anthony Smith (FA), QB David Klingler (cut),
CB Larry Brown (cut).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: CB Eric Allen (trade), CB Charles Woodson (D-1a),
OT Mo Collins (D-1b), WR Terry Mickens (FA), SS Anthony Newman
(FA), FB Jon Ritchie (D-3), PK Greg Davis (FA), SS Louis Riddick
(FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: A typical Raiders team, with speed and playmakers at
skill positions. Unfortunately, the defense, last in the league
last year, won't improve enough, even with new blood at cornerback.
The defenders at ends and linebackers are average, and Oakland will
</P>
<P>
   surrender lots of points again. The Raiders will score some,
too, with QB Jeff George benefiting from the coaching of Gruden.
The former Atlanta starter had a terrific '97 season, which was
overshadowed by the defensive collapse.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO CHARGERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Kevin Gilbride is 4-12 in one season with the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 4-12, fifth in AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: WR Tony Martin (trade), WR Eric Metcalf (trade),
DT Shawn Lee (trade), QB Stan Humphries (retired), RB Gary Brown
(FA), RB Aaron Craver (cut), LB Patrick Sapp (trade), QB Jim
Everett (retired), OG Joe Cocozzo (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: QB Ryan Leaf (D-1), RB Natrone Means (FA), OT John
Jackson (FA), OG Aaron Taylor (FA), offensive line coach Joe Bugel
(Oakland), LB Gerald Dixon (FA), C Roman Fortin (FA), quarterback
coach June Jones, WR Mikhael Ricks (D-2), DT Jamal Williams
(supplemental draft).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Chargers might not win much more than last year,
but Leaf will make them more compelling to watch. He has superb
size and arm strength, and Jones will be a steadying force. A
youthful receiving corps could slow Leaf's progress, but Charger
defense ranks as a greater concern. San Diego has almost no pass
rush, and the secondary gets exploited as a result. Look for a
shakeup at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
