<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER  
 IT'S NEVER TOO EARLY TO BOOK HOLIDAY TRIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Over the years, we have spent the year-end holidays sightseeing
London, cruising on board the Mississippi Queen, seeing the
Rockettes perform in New York City and cheering on the Northwestern
Wildcats in Pasadena, Calif., during one of their two Rose Bowl
appearances in half a century. Wherever we go during the holidays,
we find other mature travelers who also choose to celebrate the
season on the road.
 &HT;    The lure of a holiday trip is not the same for everyone. For
some mature travelers, it's a way to let succeeding generations
develop their own Christmas customs. For other travelers, family
members may be few or far-flung.
 &HT;    For especially large families, central destinations such as
Nashville's Opryland can offer a place to gather without hassle or
stress. And, of course, for the inveterate traveler, it's a way to
see favorite places in a new way _ all dressed up for the season.
 &HT;    Now is the time to book holiday tours or cruises. Because of
their growing popularity, people who wait too long to make
reservations are likely to be disappointed.
 &HT;    Travel company catalogs feature holiday tours to places such as
Branson, Mo., San Antonio, Texas, Williamsburg, Va., the Christmas
markets in Germany, San Miguel de Allende, Mexico and Vienna,
Austria. Other possibilities include Kenya wildlife safaris and
Caribbean, Mediterranean or Pacific cruises.
 &HT;    Here is a sampling of great places and tours for your holiday
trip:
 &HT;     _ Saga Holidays,  which packages tours just for those 49-plus,
has a special Christmas in London tour for singles and a Danube
River Christmas cruise. Also on its menu of holiday destinations
are old favorites such as Palm Springs, Calif., and San Antonio,
Texas. Many of its trips do not require a single supplement.
 &HT;    The London tour features a walking tour of Dickensian London,
Christmas Eve with caroling and an evening at the theater. The
price, which includes round-trip airfare, is $2,149 from New York
or $2,349 from San Francisco. For more information, call (800)
343-0273.
 &HT;     _ Holland-America  offers 11 different itineraries for holiday
cruises ranging from seven to 16 days, with new ports of call at
Puerto Quetzal, Guatemala; Hualtulco, Mexico; and Virgin Gorda and
Tortola, British Virgin Islands.
 &HT;    Holiday cruises feature caroling, an international crew choir
and a visit from Santa. Seven-day Christmas cruises, double
occupancy, start at $1,381. Call your travel agent or
Holland-America Cruises at (206) 281-3535.
 &HT;     _ Gerhard's Odysseys' annual Christkindles (Christmas) Markets
Tour  highlights Germany, Austria and French Alsace. There are two
1998 departure dates _ Nov. 27 and Dec. 4. The price is $1,440 per
person, double occupancy. Call (503) 223-2402 for details.
 &HT;     _ Maupintour's Top 40 Holiday Treats  start in November with
Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade in New York City and conclude with
Fiesta San Antonio in April.
 &HT;    Based in Lawrence, Kan., Maupintour offers a Traditional Irish
Christmas, cruises on the Danube and Nile, a Yellowstone Christmas
Wonderland, a New England Country Christmas and a Kenyan Wildlife
Holiday, among other holiday vacation. You can call (800) 255-4266
for brochures or visit their Web site at www.maupintour.com.
 &HT;     _ Smithsonian  offers Christmas study programs in the Tyrol
region of Europe, Prague, Czechoslovakia, and Canterbury and
London, England. The 10-day Prague program, for example, leaves
Newark on Dec. 18 and includes tours of the Jewish Quarter,
Christmas Eve at an Old Town church and a musical performance after
Christmas dinner.
 &HT;    The price is $4,480, double occupancy, with round-trip airfare
from Newark. For further information, call your travel agent, visit
the Web site www.si.edu/tsa/sst or call (202) 357-4700.
 &HT;     _ Travcoa's  44th anniversary catalog lists more than 40 exotic
luxury Christmas tours of Africa, Egypt, India, the Orient, South
Pacific, Central and South America and Mexico. For specific
brochures, call your travel agent or (800) 992-2004 (outside
California), (800) 992-2003 (inside California).
 &HT;     _ Sanborn's Viva Motorcoach Tours of Mexico  offer great
variety, from San Miguel de Allende to Oaxaca and Veracruz. Many of
the itineraries are repeated year after year because of their
popularity.
 &HT;    A five-night tour of San Miguel, for example, is offered for the
eighth time this year, departing from Texas' Rio Grande Valley on
Dec. 22. Stops will include San Luis Potosi, Guanajuato and
Matehula as well as San Miguel, where tour-goers will greet
Christmas morning taking a tour of this popular retirement haven
for North Americans. The price per person, double occupancy, is
$357. Call (800) 395-8482.
 &HT;     _ Colonial Williamsburg,  with more than 50 years of special
holiday activities under its belt, offers decoration tours, open
houses, musical programs and holiday feasts from Thanksgiving
weekend through Jan. 3. New this year is Felicity in Williamsburg _
that is, Felicity Merriman, the fictional character from The
American Girls Collection of books and dolls.
 &HT;    A complete vacation package for two adults and two grandchildren
costs $230 per family per night. Day packages are also available at
$69 per adult and $54 for children under 12.
 &HT;    Midway between Richmond and Norfolk, Williamsburg is served by
Amtrak as well as the airports at Richmond, Norfolk and Newport
News. Call (800) 501-0057 for details.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
 &HT;     (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 The Mature Traveler Newsletter  
