<P>
   STOCK MARKET REACTION BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   DOW-STOCKS _ The Dow Jones industrials were firmly in positive
territory at midday after swinging widely in frenetic morning
trading, following a fierce sell-off Monday. In the first 65
minutes of trading, the Dow moved to a gain of 143 points at 7,682,
then dropped as low as 7,400, down 138 points, then climbed
decisively back into positive territory. ``This brings a new
definition to the word `volatility,' '' said Bill Meehan, chief
market analyst at Canter Fitzgerald. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-BEAR _ A look at how this bear market _ if in fact it is one
_ is different from past bear markets. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET. WITH TIMELINE
</P>
<P>
   DOW-PSYCHE _ A look at the psychology of the market. How much of
the drop/gain is being driven by real factors and how much by
emotion and fear. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-TECHSTOCKS _ For months, analysts have been screaming that
many of the tech stocks are way overvalued. The hammering some of
the less stable stocks took Monday is just what needed to happen to
get thoses shares back to a price more connected to the companies'
actual prospects. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-BELLSOUTH _ Where is the money going that's coming out of
high-flying tech stocks? Some of it is going into tech sompanies
that, in fact, have profits and identities other than wobbly tech
stocks. BellSouth, for example, went up during the big decline, as
did some other utilities. Tech or no, they are perceived as safe.
(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-INTERNET _ A look at what sites investors turned to on the
Web in seeking the latest developments on the stock market. Also, a
look at which sites offer the best info. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-RETIRE _ Last year, politicians were talking about letting
people invest some Social Security money in goverment securities or
stocks. Bob Dart updates that story. (Dart, Cox Washington Bureau)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-MORTGAGE _ A look at the direction of metro mortgage rates,
which are now around 6.5 percent for a 30-year fixed. (Harte,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ Trying to calm the turmoil in the U.S. stock market,
President Clinton today cited a continued strong job market and a
balanced federal budget and said ``we believe our fundamental
economic policy is sound.'' Clinton added his voice to the U.S.
administration's efforts to reassure nervous investor after
Monday's dramatic declines on Wall Street. Noting that he had
consulted with Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin en route to Russia
on Monday, Clinton told students at Moscow State University that
market gyrations are not unexpected. (Deans, Cox News Service) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS _ Will Tuesday be a repeat of Monday, or will bargain
hunters move in and drive the bears away? (Bohman, Dayton Daily
News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MEASUREMENT _ The growing importance of Web measurement. A
comparison of the two top Web measurement firms, Atlanta's Relevant
Knowledge and New York-based Media Metrix. Will include analyst
commentary on Web measurement and if it's developed to a point
where the information is both accurate and useful. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER BUSINESS NEWS
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST _ MINNEAPOLIS _ Northwest Airlines started handing out
layoff notices Tuesday and said many of its 50,000 employees could
be sent home as a strike by pilots reached its fourth day. In
Washington, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater urged both sides
to start talking again. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTRADE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A look at a growing pastime
that, like gambling, can make the player a lot of money or clean
him out. It's day trading in the stock market, where players head
to personal computer parlors and buy and sell stock all day. We
visit locations in Boca Raton, Fla., and West Palm Beach, Fla.
(Pounds, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PAXSON2 _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Developments from Day 2 of
PaxNet. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP-COMPUTERS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Mark Martich set out to
replace his 6-year-old home computer this spring and wound up in
the middle of the biggest trend to hit the personal computer
industry in years. He bought a PC for $499. (Ladendorf, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS/GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP-COMPUTERS-DELL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. says
it doesn't sell sub-$1,000 personal computers because its customers
don't want them. Instead, Dell has targeted knowledgeable buyers
who want high-performance computers for high-end computer games,
image processing, desktop video conferencing and processing
computer video clips. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
WITH PHOTOS/GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP-COMPUTERS-LIST _ Winners, losers and survivors in the
computer industry. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
WITH PHOTOS/GRAPHICS.
</P>
