<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SILVER-LINING03-COX     09-02 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILVER-LINING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monday's 512-point fall produced good bargains in solid
companies
 &HT;    By Michael Utley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Domestic stock markets' free fall Monday, August 31, and partial
recovery Tuesday proved that at least one cliche has some cachet:
The dark cloud over the markets does indeed have a silver lining.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when the market fell a staggering 512 points, veteran
money managers figured, hey, it's a buying opportunity. The lurking
bear produced some pretty good bargains in solid companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great silver lining is that you get a chance to buy stocks
at much lower prices,'' said Carl Domino, a money manager at West
Palm Beach-based Carl Domino Associates, with more than $2 billion
under management. ``You're getting more money for your investment
dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one of the most popular stocks in America,
Microsoft Corp., was selling as high as $118 a share in mid-July,
but on Monday savvy investors could snap it up for $96. On a
typical trade of 100 shares, that's a savings of $2,200. Plus, the
stock moved up to $101.25 Tuesday, a gain of $525 on those 100
shares bought Monday.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's Corp., another perennial favorite, was going for $74
a share in early July, before falling to $56 on Monday. That
translates to a savings of $1,800 on a 100-share buy. The stock
closed Tuesday at $60.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors should use (a down market) as a buying opportunity
for good, quality companies that are market leaders, especially in
consumer staples, health care and financial services,'' said Thomas
Doak, a broker with the Lake Worth office of Edward Jones, a St.
Louis-basedcq investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average bear market lasts only eight months and fully
recovers in an average of 13 months,'' Doak added, ``so if you are
a long-term investor and have realistic expectations, you need not
worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the stocks you bought before a correction most likely
are going to take a temporary hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That money you've already invested is now worth a lot less,''
said Alex Bigelow, branch manager at the West Palm Beach office of
St. Louis-basedcq A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. And anybody looking for
a bargain, Bigelow said, needs to keep in mind that lower prices
don't necessarily translate into a great buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because stocks are cheaper right now doesn't mean they
are a better value,'' he said. ``You still have to do the
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important benefit of the recent drop in stock
prices is that it brings a dose of reality to a market that has not
had a bad year in nearly a decade, market players said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of correction is healthy,'' said Barbara Trebbi, a
senior vice president with Boca Raton-based Ivy Management Inc.
``It's unrealistic to think stocks could continue to trade at such
high (price-to-earnings) ratios. . . . So I think this should
provide the foundation for the next move up.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Raborn, a money manager at Delray Beach-based Raborn &AMP; Co.,
with $120 million under management, urges his clients not to
``panic'' when inevitable corrections shake the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market has compounded at 11 percent since 1926,'' he
said, reciting a well-worn pitch. ``At these levels, the Dow will
exceed 30,000 by the year 2010.''
</P>
<P>
   That's usually enough to convince most people.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
