<P>
   BBN-CERABINO-COLUMN _ Mark McGwire, the man who is our ticket to
fame and fortune _ or at least a 20-second interview on the evening
news _ is swinging the bat, way down there on the field, and we can
visualize it all. We can imagine the ball springing off his bat and
landing here among us, the antlike minions who will undoubtedly
tear each other limb from limb to get a McGwire home run ball.
(Cerabino, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BBB-MCCOY-COLUMN _ Said Sammy Sosa after his game and before
McGwire's game, ``I know he is going to come back and take the
lead. That's that I want him to do. As I say, Mark is The Man. I'm
pulling for Mark. He is my idol.'' Sosa was right on . . . again.
Not only did McGwire recapture the lead with his 55th homer that
August 30th, he hit it farther in the heavy, muggy St. Louis night
than Sosa did in Denver . . . an estimated 501 feet. That's the way
it keeps happening. (McCoy, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
