<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-TRADERS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day traders make their living on edge of stocks' movement
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ If any investor can stand up to the
gut-wrenching swings of this week's volatile stock market, it's a
day trader like Andy Friis.
</P>
<P>
   Don't talk to Friis about price-to-earnings ratios or order
backlogs or any other traditional gauge of a company's health. It's
more information than he needs to know. Friis lives for
``movement,'' how a company has traded in a period of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of a new breed of investor who earns his daily bread
by squeezing fractional profits from each share he buys and selling
as a stock rolls in one direction or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the guys don't even know what the companies make,''
Friis says.
</P>
<P>
   Friis trades from a computer terminal at Broadway Trading Co.,
one of several shops in the area where day traders access stock
markets electronically. Broadway operates out of a second-floor
office in a bank building in Boca Raton where rows of tables
crowded with computers fill two rooms of mostly young men.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when markets plummeted, day traders were doing their
best to follow the first rule of day trading _ minimize loss. It
wasn't easy, Friis says. Many were trying to pull their cash out of
the market. If they were smart, they had already taken short
positions _ betting that stocks would go down _ and could watch
unemotionally as the panic ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would come to an end but it never did,'' Friis
says.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders will buy and sell stocks in keystrokes _ sometimes
in seconds, often in minutes but most certainly in hours. Holding a
stock all day would be considered unusual.
</P>
<P>
   A day trader might buy 1,000 shares of a stock, watch it go up
by a sixteenth, then an eighth, and finally by a fourth before
selling it. He pays the shopkeeper 2 cents a share on the trade and
pockets $210.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can all happen in a matter of two or three minutes,''
says Chris Perry, a day trader at On-Site Trading Inc. in West Palm
Beach. ``We're trying to get quarters, or halves, or
three-eighths.''
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's stock slide, many held onto their money and
waited for one of two trading respites when some stocks leveled
off. They bought into the market briefly or took a short position
in anticipation of a deeper drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these guys caught a bounce in a stock. But it got a
little rough,'' Broadway Manager Glenn Disort said. ``Nobody threw
anything. But I had to tap a couple of guys on the shoulder and
say, 'breaking your keyboard isn't going to help anything.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although day-traders can trade on the New York and other
exchanges, The market of choice for day traders is the Nasdaq Stock
Market. There are two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First is volatility. Day traders play stocks that move up and
down in great volume, and the Nasdaq is heavy in technology stocks,
a mercurial sector that often suffers from mood swings.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if the trader operates on the Nasdaq, he can act, in
effect, like a market maker, an investment house that buys and
sells stock and helps to maintain its price in the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders don't care if the market goes up or down. They'll
jump in on any trend in a stock's movement. Even so, the
requirement that a stock must have an uptick before a trader can
take a short position makes trading on the long side a bit easier,
Disort said.
</P>
<P>
   Friis' plan for Tuesday was to short stocks in an anticipated
upward swing at market opening before it began to slide again. ``I
won't enter on the long side until the market shows signs of
strength,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On-Site Manager Jack Polsky said one key to day trading is going
with the flow, or following a short-term trend in a stock's price.
The other is minimizing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Disort, Broadway Trading's manager, preaches discipline in
either direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a rule that you will not lose more than 25 cents a
share, you have to stick to the rule,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Friis lost money on Monday even though three-quarters of the
traders at Broadway made a profit, Disort says. ``Nobody expected
the selling in droves,'' he lamented. ``When the trend goes in one
direction _ up or down _ it's hard to stay on the right side.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry is a former broker; Friis a former floor clerk on the
American Stock Exchange. But not everyone has stock-trading
background. A former surgeon, gas-station owner and Motorola
engineer also are day-traders.sure, and lots of other people in
other occupations are too. but what makes these special? were they
people who were there today???
</P>
<P>
   After the 1987 crash, the Nasdaq began the small-order execution
system, or SOES, so individual investors could make trades of 1,000
shares or less automatically rather than go through an investment
middleman. Day traders have even been described a SOES (pronounced
sose) bandits in the past because of their lightning quick use of
the electronic trading systems.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders also avoid small-cap stocks because they aren't
traded in enough volume for changes in price _ up or down _ to gain
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can just walk in and sit down at a terminal in a
day-trading office. Traders are required to plunk down a sizable
chunk of cash to draw from. At Broadway, $75,000 is the minimum; at
On-Site, it's $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done. Friis let one stock ride up $18, and made
$18,000 but he also let one slide a little too long and lost
$10,000 after it fell $10 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Even on a dismal day like Monday, as the market fell more than
500 points, day traders were clicking away.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of guys are doing okay, made over $10,000. But
everyone is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general mood was amazement. Most of these guys haven't
seen something like this,'' Disort said.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as there's momentum, there's opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most momentum traders are long traders but in a market like
this, you have to go short,'' Disort said of the practice of
gambling on certain stocks going down. ``What is there to take
long?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
