<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptists who came Second beg to differ
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would somebody please pass the crow?
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to apologize to the multitude of churchgoers I
inadvertently eliminated from existence in my column recently.
</P>
<P>
   That's the last time I'll ever joke around about how you never
see a Second Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   See, like an idiot, while writing about the Texas high school
football ranking system, I mentioned how Americans love to be No. 1
and hate coming in second. And that, I said, explains why nobody
ever names their church the Second Baptist Church. It's always the
First Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I could try to weasel out of this by claiming I stole
this joke from former Boston Globe columnist Mike Barnicle. But the
fact is, I didn't realize how many Second Baptist Churches there
are until y'all called me up to tell me about it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that. There's at least one Third Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did make a mistake; now you're talking to Third,'' said
Rev. Larry Davis, associate pastor of the Third Baptist Church in
St. Louis, Mo. ``I get questions and remarks about Third Baptist
all the time. They wonder what happened to First and Second.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering about Fourth, Davis added that the Fourth
Baptist Church in St. Louis is still there, although Fifth Baptist
is no longer around. But Third Baptist in St. Louis will celebrate
its 150th anniversary in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But let's forget about who's on First and what's on Third for a
second and talk about Second. As in Second Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   There are Second Baptist Churches all over Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're scattered throughout the state,'' said Dale Gore,
executive director of the Austin Baptist Association.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there are Second Baptist churches in Lubbock,
Corpus Christi, La Grange, Odessa and San Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Second Baptist churches call themselves second because
they came along second, after First Baptist, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   But Second Baptist in Dallas got the name because it was founded
on Second Avenue in 1912, said Betty Proctor, church secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that we were trying to be second behind First
Baptist,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And just because you're called Second Baptist doesn't mean
you're playing second fiddle. According to the Union Baptist
Association in Houston, last year the Second Baptist Church in
Houston had 24,334 members, compared to 21,169 for First Baptist in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Curious about how widespread this phenomenon really is, I called
New York and asked the operator for the number of the Second
Baptist Church. She wanted to know which one I was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have multiple listings for Second Baptist churches,'' she
said. Multiple, as in eight churches in New York with the words
Second and Baptist as part of their names.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the New York phone directory, there's just one
listing for a Dew Drop Inn.
</P>
<P>
   You know you've got a lot of Second Baptist churches when you
outnumber the Dew Drop Inn 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how I missed seeing all these Second Baptist
churches, but it makes me wonder: Ever notice how you never see a
Ninth Baptist Church around these parts?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column for the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
