<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMN: Lessons in charisma
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c: 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Out of view of the television cameras, President
Clinton should give charisma lesson to President Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton knows better than anyone that the secret to maintaining
a strong following is charisma, certainly not character.
</P>
<P>
   Charisma coupled with a good economy blinds people to a
multitude of character flaws. No one knows this better than
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While he's at it, Clinton also can teach Yeltsin to blame his
troubles on a vast outside conspiracy, perhaps masterminded by a
man named Starrsky.
</P>
<P>
   Without immediate help from Clinton, Boris Yeltsin is a dead
duck in Russia. At this point, Yeltsin's political career can be
salvaged only if he develops a nationwide cult following strong
enough to discount all the man's obvious defects.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for Yeltsin, Clinton is the right man for that job. After
all, Clinton has been on the verge of turning the Democratic Party
into a cult for the past six or seven years.
</P>
<P>
   If a cult is defined as a group of people who blindly follow an
unscrupulous charismatic leader, then that description comes
uncomfortably close to the power Clinton holds over his devoted
followers.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, it's nearly impossible to explain why so many good,
intelligent Americans could not see that they were being held
spellbound by an obvious scoundrel.
</P>
<P>
   Like successful cult leaders, Clinton has shown an uncanny
ability to manipulate people to serve his interests. And from
Clinton's actions, it's easy to see that his interests seldom rise
to a level higher than himself. Clinton first, right or wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Cult leaders always invent powerful enemies bent on the
destruction of the selfless leader and his faithful flock.
</P>
<P>
   Evil outside forces combined with the cult leader's charismatic
believability convince beguiled followers to ignore clear and
convincing evidence that their leader is telling them lies they
want to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, his companion enabler and a host of enchanted acolytes
vigorously blame their troubles in a vast right-wing conspiracy, an
anti-Arkansas conspiracy or an out-of-control independent counsel,
who, by the way, Clinton could fire.
</P>
<P>
   Like any good cult leader, Clinton has made a career out of
telling people what they want to hear. From the beginning, Clinton
has been willing to lie, invent and shift positions to manipulate
the support he needs to obtain and maintain personal power.
</P>
<P>
   A telling indicator of both his charisma and his total lack of
scruples came during his 1992 presidential campaign after poll
watchers told him he needed to beef up his support among Jewish
voters.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, Clinton was standing before 500 surprised members of
the Council of Jewish Organizations of Borough Park, a Hasidic
stronghold in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I become president,'' he said, ``we will keep a glatt
kosher kitchen in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't do it, of course, because he didn't mean what he said.
He looked his audience in the eye and lied.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's admission that he ``misled'' people when he looked the
nation in the eye and emphatically said, ``I did not . . . have . .
. sexual relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky'' could surprise
only those people who had been deluded by Clinton's characterless
charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's history of mendacity and manipulation is obvious to
anyone not caught in his spell.
</P>
<P>
   Most politicians have unfulfilled campaign promises. But
thankfully few politicians are so devoid of personal convictions
that they go out of their way to tell purposeful lies to the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that even Clinton can save Yeltsin's job. And if
Clinton gets many more cracks in his charisma, he will be defrocked
by his own flock.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
