<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Program like a morning hug for Glades tots
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Used to be that Sam King the kind-hearted custodian would come
around to the back of the new elementary school in Belle Glade, and
there they'd be.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen or 20 of the little squirts. Waiting outside the gate.
Rain or shine.
</P>
<P>
   Sweltering heat. December cold spell. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   And Sam would usher the little guys inside, or, at the very
least, he'd bring them around and let them stand inside the gate,
under the roof of the bus port where the drivers drop off kids each
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't have the heart to let those kids stand outside,''
said Juanita Malone, assistant principal at Belle Glade Elementary
School.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, these weren't middle schoolers or high schoolers
standing out there at 6 a.m. These were itty bitty kids, many of
them too small to cross a road alone. We're talking 5-, 6-,
7-year-olds, dropped off at school before the sun was up.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? Many parents in the Florida Glades _ some of them
field workers _ have to be at work early. Very early. And they have
no place to drop their kids at that time of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes our parents go to work at 5 o'clock,'' Malone said.
``They know it's safe here, so they would just bring them to
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it worried Malone to death. What if some kid got lost?
What if a fight broke out and someone got hurt? What if, what if,
what if?
</P>
<P>
   But all that is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Three schools in the Glades are getting grants from the Quantum
Foundation to start what will be called the Glades Before School
Care Program.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Nikolopoulos, director of development for the Boys and
Girls Clubs of Palm Beach County, says they will take the $338,210
and start morning programs at three schools _ Belle Glade
Elementary, Glades View Elementary and Pioneer Park Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Quintero, 27, falls into the ranks of these working
Glades parents. She's a little different because she was able to
move back her hours at the Wellington hospital where she works. But
that meant she lost precious work hours _ and precious money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to increase my hours and increase my pay,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The grant is new, it was just approved last week, so officials
haven't decided when the program's going to start and exactly who's
going to staff it. But Nikolopoulos says they want someone
bilingual who will start the kids off with a little exercise in the
morning _ ``Some of these kids are still half asleep,'' she said _
give them breakfast and help them with homework.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time you wake up late and it's 7:15 and you're
rushing around making Pop-Tarts and packing lunches and telling the
kids to hurry, hurry, hurry, take a minute to stop and think about
those little guys out in the Glades. The ones Sam the custodian
treats with kindness each morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real thrust of this program is education,'' says
Nikolopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's that.
</P>
<P>
   But me, I like the part about bringing little kids in out of the
dark and giving them a hug and a hot breakfast, all before the sun
comes up.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
