   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS_ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ALLMAN-GRAVES _ As the Allman Brothers Band continues its week
of five shows at the Fox Theatre, a look at the controversy
involving the graves of Allman Brothers Band members Duane Allman
and Berry Oakley in Macon's Rose Hill Cemetery. We talk to Berry's
sister Candace Oakley, at the center of the dispute, about what
she's planning now that city has taken down a chain link fence
around the graves, which like rock graves around the world are
usually littered by fans. Talk with fans in Macon headed for the
Allmans shows, and sketch in brief various Allman factions in town.
photo of Oakley at the graves. (SoMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   REM-ALBUM _ NEW YORK _ Interview with R.E.M. in New York, with
Michael Stipe, Pete Buck and Michael Mills talking about their new
album ``Up'' due out Oct. 27. The band talks about why they're not
touring behind this album (don't feel like it), what Warner Bros.
thinks of their mellow, New Age-y musical departure (they, uh, love
it). More details. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE _ The problem? Many parents in Florida _ some of them
field workers _ have to be at work early. Very early. And they have
no place to drop their kids at that time of day. (Minor, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DECOUPAGE _ What others might see as a useless, cardboard box,
Evelyn Holmes envisions an endless world of decoration. She sees
pictures and colorful paint, lace and ribbon. Decoupage has been
around since the 17th century, when the French began using the
technique to spruce up somewhat homely furnishings, such as hat
boxes. (Mays, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DECOUPAGE-TIPS _ Following are pointers to help decoupage
novices: (hints follow). (Mays, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNING-COLLECTION _ Pushing through the 1,500-pound bronze
double doors, visitors might think they've stepped from the
confines of Waco, Texas, into a museum somewhere in the midst of
Europe. Perhaps one of Waco's unintentionally best-kept secrets,
the library houses the world's largest collection of poetry and
materials of world-famous poets Robert Browning and his wife,
Elizabeth Barrett Browning. (Mays, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-COMMUTE _ AUSTIN _ Lured by the prospect of a quick trip
to San Antonio's Riverwalk or a less stressful commute to work,
about 50 Austin-area residents sat down recently to start
brainstorming about commuter rail. ``Texas has always been
literally a car-driven state,'' said Claudia Parker, who attended
the meeting. ``There's just a need for alternatives.'' The idea
behind the brainstorming session was to determine what some of
those alternatives were, and how a commuter rail line from
Georgetown to San Antonio might become a reality. (Hiott, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TOWN-DIES _ THE AREA FORMERLY KNOWN AS GOLFVIEW, Fla. _ It can
be argued this place died a few years ago when most of its longtime
residents left or a few months ago when boarded-up houses first
outnumbered occupied ones. Recently, though, the long demise of
Golfview, Florida, became final and official. (Bennett, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
