<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Teen dad is dilemma in flesh
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Sex education in the 1990s. Here is the egg. Here
is the sperm. Put the two together and here is what they create in
approximately nine months:
</P>
<P>
   A visit from Child Support Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere this week a boy in his teens is learning that
reproduction is a lot more than arrows and ova. Under welfare
reforms still in the toddler stage, a mom who seeks federal
assistance must declare the name of the father. Once identified, he
is approached to declare paternity. If he refuses, the government
takes him and his blood sample to court. Paternity established, a
pencil-thin neck is fitted with a monster yoke.
</P>
<P>
   The obstetrician has this word for the laboring teen mom:
``push.'' Now, the government has this word for the teen dad:
``pull.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the latter player, Pamela Wilson has her own word for a
society trying to make the best out of what happens when teens have
children: ``firmth.'' It's the wedding of ``firm'' with ``warmth.''
</P>
<P>
   Society could stick with the ``firm'' alone. It could be as cold
as Siberian winter. But Wilson, a Washington-based expert on
getting teen fathers to act responsibly, isn't just talking about
child support in a fiscal sense. She's talking about co-parenting,
even when parents don't cohabit.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was speaking to concerned citizens in a public forum
following a daylong seminar with professionals sponsored by Planned
Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Although society does some reasonable things to help teen moms
get on their feet and do what's best for their children, teen
fathers are treated either as irrelevant or as the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   We are well aware of the deadbeat dad, he who has money but
won't share it. In the case of teen fathers not even out of school,
Wilson points to something else entirely: the dead-broke dad.
</P>
<P>
   Under tough welfare reforms, you can wallop that turnip with
sadistic intensity and still not get child support that will matter
in the short run or in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   If society wants to make the best of such a bad situation, says
Wilson, it must find ways to warm these young people to the task
facing them. It must provide them with job training, support
groups, counseling.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes after them like the ATF executing a warrant, many
do what little boys do. They hide.
</P>
<P>
   A teen father is a dilemma in the flesh: You want him to start
helping out with child support. But do you want him dropping out of
school to do it? Surely not. That's lost earning power, not to
mention all else lost for the sake of earning the quickest buck.
And yet it happens all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The other dilemma is about the extent to which a teen dad should
be involved in his child's life. In the ideal world, of course,
wedding bells would ring before the twinkle of a mom's eye. In the
real world . . .
</P>
<P>
   Some of offspring of teen dads grow up with suitable fathers
when their mothers marry suitable life partners. Others don't. And
in those fatherless homes incubate so many of society's more
serious ills, including teen fatherhood, a cycle prolonged.
</P>
<P>
   Involving the dad can work. Waco resident Joan McClary, in the
audience at the forum, was a teen mom. She said that the father of
her child has played an important role, including caring for the
child while she went to college. She's a physician now.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in earning power or in nurturing potential, or in the
essential ingredients that make humanity wondrous and complex, the
teen dad is raw material society doesn't want to squander.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
