<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHEM03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anthem charges premiums to subsidize rural Ohio
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One option for Anthem to keep its Medicare HMO in some less
profitable rural and suburban counties is to charge new monthly
premiums to Anthem Senior Advantage members in Montgomery County.
</P>
<P>
   Sources outside the company said Anthem is considering a
proposal that would include monthly premiums of about $40 for
beneficiaries in Montgomery and certain outlying counties, who
currently pay no premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Those premiums would be a legal way to subsidize the lower
federal payments all Medicare HMOs receive for covering residents
of outlying counties, said the top regional Medicare HMO
administrator. But the federal government will not increase its
reimbursement rates for those counties.
</P>
<P>
   For every dollar the government pays a Medicare HMO to cover a
Montgomery County resident, it pays 83 cents in Greene County and
89 cents in Miami County. That kind of disparity was a main reason
Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield announced last spring it would
discontinue the Medicare HMO Dec. 31 for about 20,000 Ohio
customers in 22 rural and suburban counties.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem says it is reconsidering that decision, but officials
declined to discuss whether or how much of a premium there might
be, which counties it plans to retain for coverage or any other
details on the proposal it is preparing.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is settled about Anthem's plans, stressed Michael
Gessel, a spokesman for U.S. Rep. Tony Hall, D-Dayton, but he said
Hall ``expects the final decision to be fair to residents of
Montgomery County, and he would certainly be very upset if
residents of Montgomery County were not treated equitably.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the four Medicare HMOs in Montgomery County currently
charge premiums. But even at $40 a month, Senior Advantage is a
better value than beneficiaries can find in a traditional Medigap
supplement, said Bob Thimmes, president of the Miami Valley Health
Improvement Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't cut any benefits, that's not too bad,'' Thimmes
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration would have to approve
any proposal from Anthem and would streamline the approval process,
said Bette Weisberg, HCFA's regional HMO administrator in Chicago.
Nov. 1 is the deadline for all Medicare HMOs to notify
beneficiaries of changes in fees and coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Weisberg called it ``very likely that there will be either fewer
benefits or more of a premium'' in at least some of the 15 counties
where Anthem planned uninterrupted Medicare HMO coverage. She said
Medicare HMOs can change fees and benefits year-to-year under any
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The Xenia attorney representing discontinued Anthem Senior
Advantage members in a class-action lawsuit said he hoped Anthem
would remain in all Ohio counties it planned to leave, even though
that would make the suit irrelevant before lawyers were paid a
dime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything we can do to get these people's health care back
would be great,'' Charles Rowland said. If Anthem decides to retain
Senior Advantage coverage in only selected counties, he said he
would continue the lawsuit on behalf of any discontinued members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to complain if we have to pay $40 a month for
our insurance,'' said Becky Howe, the Senior Advantage member in
Piqua who organized grass-roots opposition to Anthem's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Howe said she believed most of the thousands of people she has
talked to would also tolerate slight increases in Senior Advantage
co-payments, currently $5 for a doctor visit, $25 for an emergency
room visit, $5 a month for generic prescription drugs and $15 for
brand-name drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But from Howe to U.S. Rep. David L. Hobson, R-Springfield, there
has been strong agreement that the best solution would be to
consider uniform HCFA reimbursement rates throughout metropolitan
regions instead of county by county.
</P>
<P>
   The only way HCFA can bypass its county-by-county rate
structure, said Weisberg, is if a governor requests a single
reimbursement rate throughout a state. Such a request would include
lowering the rates in urban counties as well as raising them in
less-populated counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have to be budget-neutral, so that's why that hasn't
been popular,'' said Weisberg. No state has made such a request.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense to do it by metropolitan areas,''
Thimmes said. As he pointed out, the reimbursement rate disparity
has prompted United HealthCare, Aetna and Pacificare to announce
they will discontinue Medicare HMOs in other regions across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've probably got similar problems around the country,''
Thimmes said, ``simmering right below the surface that haven't
bubbled out yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
