<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECOUPAGE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decoupage: Found objects are turned into art
 &HT;    With sidebar, DECOUPAGE-TIPS
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What others might see as a useless, cardboard box, Evelyn Holmes
envisions an endless world of decoration.
</P>
<P>
   She sees pictures and colorful paint, lace and ribbon. Holmes is
a crafter who's taken on the old art of decoupage _ a craft that
involves cutting out decorated pieces of paper and affixing them to
a solid-surfaced item to create a display.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started doing it because it's simple,'' she said. ``It
doesn't take a lot of time to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two or three years, she's turned dozens of
ordinary items into attractive accents for the home. Using scrap
art, magazine clippings, prints from napkins and wrapping paper,
Holmes decoupages Easter baskets, birdhouses, papier-mache boxes,
candles and candle holders.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her items can be found at Brazos Craft Mall in Waco,
where she rents a small booth to sell her artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just mostly do it for the fun,'' she said. ``It's fun taking
a magazine clipping or something from a napkin or wrapping paper
and making something someone would buy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Decoupage has been around since the 17th century, when the
French began using the technique to spruce up somewhat homely
furnishings, such as hat boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Today's decoupaging process isn't as complicated or
time-consuming as it was in the old days, said Holmes, who's been
creating various home crafts for about 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can still do it the old way with layers and layers of
finish and sanding between each layer so it would be real smooth,''
she said. ``But you probably wouldn't want to do that unless you
(were decoupaging) furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's decoupaging process basically involves cutting out
pictures and gluing them down with decoupage glue or another type
of sealer.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any item can be dressed up with decoupage, Holmes said _
glassware; bottles; any type of wood, metal or paper boxes; tea
pots; birdhouses; shelves, books; picture frames; flower pots, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Local craft and discount stores carry the necessary products for
decoupaging products _ decoupage glue and medium-bristled brushes.
And also items that encourage crafters to use their imaginations _
decoupage prints and papers, doilies, papier-mache boxes, pressed
flowers, foil kits to add foil accents, kits to add 3-D effects,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use your imagination and just about anything will work,''
Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
