<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAXSON-RATINGS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PAX TV gets higher-than-expected ratings on its first day
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new PAX TV network officials were was in seventh heaven,
uplifted by strong overnight Nielsen ratings for the first day of
the network's programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great ratings. Great Day America. Great Day Bud,'' said Paxson
Communications Chairman Lowell ``Bud'' Paxson, playing off the name
of an original talk show PAX TV is airing.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's seventh TV network, which promises family friendly
programming without sex and violence, posted an average weighted
1.4 rating for prime-time programming in its markets measured by
Nielsen Media Research. Network executives have said they need to
average a 1 rating to be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Palm Beach market, PAX TV drew a 2.4 rating for
prime-time programming, meaning that 14,244 homes with televisions
in this market were watching Paxson Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 1.4 is incredible,'' Paxson said.''It's a lot of people.''
Paxson said iIt's a mass audience that the network can deliver to
advertisers as well as introduce to the networks original
programming during the weekend and in the daytime.
</P>
<P>
   Each rating point represents 1 percent of households with
television sets. Nationally, there are 99.4 million TV households
in the nation and 593,480 in the West Palm Beach market.
</P>
<P>
   While Paxson was elated, The numbers had Paxson staffers
psyched, but industry watchers cautioned against putting too much
weight on the initial numbers.
</P>
<P>
   One media buyer said he didn't expect to look at the ratings for
a while. ``To watch the first day, the first week, even the first
month is probably not fair to them and more than a little premature
to be making judgments as to how well they're doing,'' said Allen
Banks, who oversees media buying for advertising agency Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The overnight Nielsen ratings were collected in 31 markets in
which PAX TV broadcasts. A national sample was not available.
Paxson averaged the ratings in its markets, weighting each market
to reflect its number of TV households to arrive at a 1.4 rating
nationally. That compares to the national ratings for the week of
CBS, which were 6.9; ABC, 6.4; NBC, 7.3; FOX, 5.3; WB, 2.3 and UPN,
1.5, according to Nielsen spokeswoman Anne Elliot.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson did not release market specifics. But in the West Palm
Beach market, at 4 p.m., PAX TV aired Hogan Family, which drew an
average 0.7 rating. That went up against NBC's Oprah Winfrey, with
a 8.6 rating and ABC's Jerry Springer, with an average 4.5 rating.
UPN's rating was 0.6 in the time slot for Sweet Valley High.
</P>
<P>
   In prime time in the West Palm Beach market, PAX TV'sTouched by
an Angel reruns averaged a 2.2 rating; CBS's Cosby reruns received
7.8; NBC's Princess Diana special, 10.7; The Kickoff Classic
football game featuring the Florida State Seminoles on ABC scored a
7.8; Fox's Melrose Place took 8.2 and UPN's In the House took a
1.4.
</P>
<P>
   One media buyer said he didn't expect to look at the ratings for
a while. ``To watch the first day, the first week, even the first
month is probably not fair to them and more than a little premature
to be making judgments as to how well they're doing,'' said Allen
Banks, who oversees media buying for advertising agency Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson Communications owns, operates or is affiliated with 95
broadcast stations that can reach up to 76 million households with
television sets in the nation. Not all the stations are up and
operating yet. Paxson also has several deals with cable companies
to air its network where it has no broadcast stations.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen's Elliott said the rating service is still determining
whether PAX TV meets all the criteria to be a full network.
Specifically it's looking at whether Paxson reaches 70 percent of
the TV households, she said. Paxson, however, said his network has
proved to Nielsen it does.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kuzio, an analyst with KDP Investment Advisers, called the
showing ``pretty impressive.'' His company has been forecasting an
average 0.7 rating for the year, a number Kuzio called
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how much of it is a `new-thing factor,' '' Kuzio
said, adding that he'll wait to see the ratings for a month or so
before reconsidering his forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
