<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-NUKEDUMP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate poised to approve Texas' nuke dump deal
 &HT;    By Christi Harlan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Senate is expected to approve an agreement
allowing Maine and Vermont to ship nuclear waste to Texas, despite
last-minute lobbying by people who live near the proposed West
Texas dump site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we're going to have some strong opposition (to the
waste agreement), but it's an uphill fight,'' said Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., the lead opponent of the agreement in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday on the U.S. Capitol grounds, where
he was surrounded by about 15 Texans holding posters protesting the
waste agreement, Wellstone said their fight has been hampered by a
lack of support from President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and
other members of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone said he has heard ``precious little'' from an
administration that ``says it's focused on environmental justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the president's and vice president's support,''
Wellstone said. ``We need for them to speak out.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor his staff had made a public statement about
the waste agreement as of Tuesday. But a White House official
speaking on condition of anonymity told The Associated Press on
Tuesday that a veto is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's vote is the last legislative action needed to seal
the agreement, known as a compact, which will allow Maine and
Vermont to ship low-level radioactive waste _ including pieces of
dismantled nuclear power plants _ to Texas for long-term storage.
The two states would pay Texas $55 million. The House has already
approved the compact, which does not specify a site for storing the
waste.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' two senators, Republicans Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey
Hutchison, support the compact. Both have said they're following
the wishes of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, former Gov. Ann Richards
and the Texas Legislature. In a statement Tuesday, Hutchison also
noted that the compact has been approved by governors and state
lawmakers in Maine and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe the federal government has a mandate to
nullify a contract signed by three state governors and ratified by
their legislatures,'' Hutchison said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Austin, said Tuesday that the ``Senate
should say 'no' to this final action to allow our state to become a
dumping ground for radioactive waste and say 'yes' to protecting
the citizens of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature has approved a site near Sierra Blanca in
Hudspeth County for the waste dump, but that plan became less
certain in early July when state examiners recommended that the
site be rejected because of concerns that the area's geology and
because the economic impact of the dump had not been adequately
addressed. Those two issues drove Tuesday's protest and lobbying
effort in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The geological study should include a look at what leakage from
the waste site might do to underground water supplies and the Rio
Grande, said state Rep. Norma Chavez, D-El Paso, and Sierra Blanca
resident Bill Addington _ two of the Texans who met Tuesday with
Senate staffers in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be a hanging offense to poison a man's well in
Texas,'' Addington said.
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact on Sierra Blanca, a mostly Hispanic
community about 90 miles southeast of El Paso, has stirred
Wellstone's passion against the compact. ``This isn't just a Texas
issue,'' he said Tuesday. ``This is a national civil rights
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone's work against the waste agreement earned him honorary
Austin citizenship last October from the Austin City Council and
gratitude Tuesday from state Rep. Lon Burnam, D-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not fair to dump on us (in Texas), and I thank Senator
Wellstone for serving as my senator,'' Burnam said.
</P>
<P>
   The state agency in charge of developing the waste site, the
Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste Disposal Authority, has taken
issue with the examiners' report in a formal res
</P>
</TEXT>
