r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLPHINS-STUBBS03-COX     09-02 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-STUBBS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stubbs likes familiar feeling of fast team
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Daniel Stubbs has a need for speed . . . from his
linebackers, cornerbacks and safeties.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs, the Dolphins' veteran defensive end, has prospered most
when he's played on a defense that's terrorized running backs who
dared turn the corner. Stubbs was a staple on the legendary
University of Miami teams that chased down and pulverized
ballcarriers. And his best season in the NFL was when he started 15
games for the Cowboys, whose defense followed the Hurricanes'
blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stubbs feels he's back on a football freeway, with no speed
limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised how much speed we've got now,'' Stubbs said.
``Just like at UM and the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator to the Hurricanes of the mid '80s, the
Cowboys of the early '90s and the Dolphins of the late '90s is
coach Jimmy Johnson, who prefers speed over size.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aggressive style has helped us and we've been able to
utilize our athletic talent and we'll be able to make more plays,''
Johnson said of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's relationship with Stubbs dates back to 1983, when
Johnson recruited Stubbs out of Red Bank (N.J.) Regional High
School. At the time, Stubbs was a linebacker. But those were the
years when Johnson would turn safeties into linebackers and
linebackers into defensive linemen to use their speed.
</P>
<P>
   Since gaining All-America status at Miami, Stubbs has had a
checkered NFL career, playing for five teams in nine seasons, and
even being released by Johnson late in 1991, 19 months after he
acquired Stubbs in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   But with Jason Taylor's injury and Stubbs' excitement over the
improved defense, he's hoping for a spark to his 33-year-old body.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to start, you want to battle, but you don't want to
do it because somebody gets hurt,'' Stubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs will line up for his first regular-season start in almost
two years Sunday at Indianapolis if Taylor's knee _ injured in last
Friday's pre-season finale _ does not heal in time.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs' 1997 season ended Aug. 31, when he tore a tendon in his
right knee. Before that, he had never missed an NFL game, a string
of 129 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got bored and anxious to play,'' Stubbs said of the nine
months of rehabilitation. ``You want to see what you can do and
after mini-camps you (realize) the knee is not everything that you
thought and you're wondering when it will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   By training camp, Stubbs was fully recovered physically, but
started having doubts mentally. He watched as Johnson sifted
through his stable of defensive ends, giving most snaps to rookies
Kenny Mixon and Lorenzo Bromell, and Taylor, a second-year player.
He started hearing rumors about trades, and worst of all, his job
being in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to prove I can play,'' Stubbs said. ``And I got lumped
into the group that played last year. I wasn't part of the problem.
I played one game and I come back and (hear) I can't play against
the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to prove to myself and prove to the coaches that I
can still play and make plays in the backfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Taylor and Bromell (sprained left knee) were not injured
Friday, Stubbs' job appeared safe. Johnson enjoys the luxury of
having five ends _ Taylor, Mixon, Stubbs, Bromell and Trace
Armstrong _ and finally has a defense that brings back memories of
the glory days at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has the components and the parts he's been talking
about,'' Stubbs said. ``We're so aggressive in the secondary our
safeties can run and, boom, make a stop. People aren't going to get
around the corner like they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Copeland, Harper visit camp: The Dolphins worked out wide
receivers Horace Copeland and Alvin Harper on Tuesday. Neither
player was signed and Johnson said he doesn't expect to add a
player to the active roster this week.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland played at the University of Miami and was released
Sunday by the Buccaneers after five seasons. He had 33 catches for
431 yards and one touchdown in 13 games last season. Harper, a
seven-year veteran, caught two passes for 65 yards for New Orleans
last season. He played for Johnson for three years in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Miami brought back defensive tackle Antoine Simpson
and signed Andy McCullough, placing both on the practice squad.
Simpson, a defensive tackle, was released last Tuesday. McCullough,
a wide receiver, was a seventh-round draft pick of the Saints this
year. . . . Guard Scott Shaw, the Dolphins' fifth-round pick who
was released last Tuesday, has found a home in Cincinnati, which
expects him to play this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
