<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-TAKE     09-02 1960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to the lifeboats from the Titanic that were
dropped off at the White Star Lines' New York dock by the
Carpathia? Are they still in a museum somewhere?
</P>
<P>
   A: No one knows exactly what happened to the 13 Titanic
lifeboats that were brought to New York by the first ship to reach
the survivors, said Scott Andrews of Titanic International, but
it's certain that none are now in any museum. The lifeboats taken
aboard by the Carpathia were hauled to the second floor of the New
York pier where they were kept until after hearings into the
Titanic's sinking were over, Andrews said. After that, it's not
known for sure where they ended up.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that they might have been used by White Star Line
on a Titanic sister ship, the Olympic, Andrews added. A photograph
taken after the 1912 disaster shows ``quite a few'' lifeboats in
the water next to the Olympic, and they may or may not have been
from the Titanic. The Olympic's stokers had gone on strike over the
issue of insufficient lifeboats, so in order to get the ship back
into service, extra lifeboats _ possibly some or all of those from
the Titanic _ had to be brought onboard. After the Titanic sank,
however, its name was removed from the lifeboats, so it would have
been impossible to identify them ever again.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been collecting Princess Diana stamps from around the
world since her death. Does the U.S. Postal Service plan to issue a
commemorative for her?
</P>
<P>
   A: No such U.S. stamp is planned. The first of the Postal
Service's 12 guidelines for subject selection is the main reason,
according to Postal Service spokeswoman Sandra Harding in
Washington: ``It is a general policy that U.S. postage stamps
primarily will feature American or American-related subjects.'' And
another guideline specifies that no postal item will be issued
sooner than 10 years after the proposed subject's death. So even if
an exception is made to feature Diana, a British citizen, it
woundn't happen for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last year at Mother Teresa's death it was reported that she
was one of only a few people in the world granted honorary U.S.
citizenship. Who were the others?
</P>
<P>
   A: Before Mother Teresa received the designation in 1996,
honorary U.S. citizenship had been conferred only three times
before: on British leader Winston Churchill; Swedish diplomat Raoul
Wallenberg, believed to have saved at least 20,000 Jews from the
Nazis; and Pennsylvania founder William Penn and his wife, Hannah.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was air conditioning invented? A recent letter to the
editor said that if Southerners gave up everything Yankee, they'd
have to give up air conditioning, because it was invented in the
North. I thought a Dr. Gorrie in Apalachicola, Fla., developed it
in the 1850s.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's difficult to pinpoint a ``first,'' because the concept
of trying to cool hot air has been around since ancient times, when
Egyptians, Greeks and Romans used wet mats to cool indoor air. In
1838, David Reid, an English scientist, provided the British House
of Commons with a system to ventilate and humidify the air, and in
the mid-1800s, John Gorrie, the doctor you mention, invented a
cold-air machine for hospital rooms. In 1897, Joseph McCreery of
Toledo, Ohio, received a patent for the type of spray now used in
air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   The forerunner of present air conditoning systems was developed
in 1902 by a Northerner, Willis Haviland Carrier of Buffalo, N.Y.,
for a Brooklyn printer trying to align color inks on paper. Perhaps
this is what the letter writer meant by saying ``Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of heat and humidity conditions, Southern textile mills,
such as the Chronicle Cotton Mill in Belmont, N.C., were among the
first users of his new system, starting about 1906. Carrier's ``dew
point control,'' an air conditioning unit based on the principle
that cooled air reaches saturation and loses moisture through
condensation, solved static electricity problems at the mills. The
first refrigeration system with centrifigual chillers made its
debut in 1924 at the J.L. Hudson Department Store in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that two Spanish climbers fell to their deaths on Mont
Blanc, bringing to 10 the number of climbers losing their lives on
that same mountain within a week's time. What happened to cause so
many deaths so quickly?
</P>
<P>
   A: Recent high-altitude rains have made the 15,750-foot
mountain, on the border of France and Italy, dangerously slick,
authorities in Chamonix, France, said. The most recent victims fell
several hundred yards on the icy northern approach to the peak a
few hours after they reached the summit. Several other climbers
have been ``gravely injured'' in falls in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Those of us observing low-fat diets have trained ourselves to
read nutrition labels. Why are they not required on breads and
certain other products prepared and sold in the deli sections of
grocery stores?
</P>
<P>
   A: Only processed foods made in large quantities are required to
have nutrition labeling, said Connie Crawley, nutrition and health
specialist at the University of Georgia Extension Service. Anything
made locally in small volume is exempt.
</P>
<P>
   You can voice your concern to the deli or store manager, and if
enough people do so, the stores may put labels on these daily
items. But as Crawley observed, analyzing a food for its nutrition
content isn't cheap, and they may be reluctant to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: CVS pharmacies seem to be popping up on everywhere lately.
Where did this company come from all of a sudden?
</P>
<P>
   A: CVS isn't new, but its recent growth has been dramatic. The
first CVS opened in 1963 in Lowell, Mass., under the name Consumer
Value Store. The merger of CVS and Peoples Drug in 1990 allowed CVS
to leap into major new markets, according to the company. On May
29, 1997, CVS Corp. completed its acquisition of Revco, making CVS
the largest drugstore chain in the United States based on store
count: nearly 4,000 properties in 24 states. And on March 31, 1998,
CVS expanded further when it completed its acquisiton of Arbor
Drugs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, CVS expects to dispense about 12 percent of all
retail prescriptions in the United States, the company says. Based
in Woonsocket, R.I., CVS Corp. expects to have operating revenues
this year exceeding $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was Bill Clinton ever a Boy Scout?
</P>
<P>
   A: Profiles of Clinton before the 1992 election reported that he
was a Boy Scout into high school.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We always hear a lot about Andersonville, the Civil War
prison camp in South Georgia where many Northern soldiers died. I
understand a prisoner of war camp in Delaware was just as
notorious, but no one ever mentions that. Do you have any
information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Andersonville gained its reputation because as many as 33,000
Union prisoners at a time were crowded into a log stockade that
enclosed only 16 1/2 acres. As many as 13,000 men died there in
seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as you say, there were prisons in the North where
Confederate soldiers were confined in miserable conditions. At Fort
Delaware, on Pea Patch Island in the Delaware River, up to 8,000
prisoners were held on a site so marshy and muddy that the
overcrowded barracks sank to the point of falling over. More than
300 prisoners died even before a smallpox epidemic broke out;
statistics after that weren't kept.
</P>
<P>
   Among the worst used by the Union were Alton Prison, in
Illinois, where severe overcrowding and bad sanitation produced a
smallpox epidemic that raged for weeks. It was estimated that
several thousand Confederates were buried on a nearby island in the
Mississippi River. At Camp Chase, near Columbus, Ohio, 10,000
Confederates were jammed into facilities intended for half that
many; prison laborers were forced to build improved barracks and
more secure fences for their own confinement. Elmira Prison in New
York was another disaster. By May 1865, it held 12,122 Confederate
prisoners on 40 acres. Accounts showed that hundreds of prisoners
developed scurvy and 2,917 prisoners died.
</P>
<P>
   Other Northern prisons included Ohio Penitentiary; Old Capitol
Prison in Washington, D.C.; Point Lookout (Md.), the largest prison
in the North; and Rock Island Prison in the Mississippi River
between Rock Island, Ill., and Davenport, Iowa. At war's end,
26,500 Southerners and 22,600 Northerners had died in prison camps.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a program about World War II on the History Channel, the
narrator kept referring to German U-boats. What does the U stand
for?
</P>
<P>
   A: Think of underwater. A U-boat was a German submarine, from
the German word Unterseeboot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard about a sugar substitute, Splenda, which I believe
was developed from sugar cane and is available in Canada. Do you
have any information about this product?
</P>
<P>
   A: Made by Johnson &AMP; Johnson, sucralose (sold under the brand
name Splenda) was approved by the Food and Drug Administration in
April. Johnson &AMP; Johnson had applied for approval in 1987. Said to
be 600 times sweeter than sugar, the low-cal sweetener, which
indeed is made from sugar cane, has been available in Canada since
1991. Q: Could you explain the difference between probation and
parole?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probation falls under the judicial branch of government.
Judges may impose a probated sentence in lieu of, or in addition
to, prison time, explained Scheree Lipscomb of the State Board of
Pardons and Parole. Let's say a person is convicted of a crime and
is sent to prison. When the prison term is completed, he (or she)
is released to the sentencing court jurisdiction to begin serving
probation. If the person violates probation terms, the judge can
revoke the probated sentence and send the person back to prison.
The parole board isn't involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The judicial system isn't involved in parole matters, Lipscomb
said. Parole deals with prison time. For certain types of offenses,
and adhering to rules requiring a minimum amount of time to be
served, the parole board can allow an inmate to serve a portion of
the prison time in the community. The board maintains authority
over the inmate until he reaches the expiration date of the time to
be served in prison. If he violates parole, the board returns him
to prison to continue serving the original sentence.
</P>
<P>
   If a person is serving a split sentence _ prison time followed
by probation _ he completes his parole time before being
transferred to probation supervision.
</P>
<P>
   There are 230,000 people on probation currently in Georgia,
including people guilty of misdemeanors who are under private
supervision, Lipscomb said, and just under 20,000 people on parole.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the public be able to buy independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's report to Congress on the investigation of President
Clinton, or if not the entire report, at least a summary of it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The entire report probably never will be released to the
public, said Michelle Morgan of the House Judiciary Committee. One
reason: It would contain grand jury material. However, it's
possible that an executive summary may be released to the public,
she added. At this point, it's not certain when or if that will
occur, and there's no precedent, because an independent counsel has
never reported to Congress, Morgan said. If a summary is made
available to the media, you'll know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
