<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-COMMUTE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin area keeps brainstorming on commuter rail
 &HT;    By Debbie Hiott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN -- Lured by the prospect of a quick trip to San Antonio's
Riverwalk or a less stressful commute to work, about 50 Austin-area
residents sat down recently to start brainstorming about commuter
rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has always been literally a car-driven state,'' said
Claudia Parker, who attended the meeting. ``There's just a need for
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the brainstorming session was to determine what
some of those alternatives were, and how a commuter rail line from
Georgetown to San Antonio might become a reality.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was the second of three scheduled this week by a
team studying commuter rail feasibility. The team includes
representatives of the state Transportation Department, Austin-San
Antonio Corridor Council, Austin and San Antonio transit
authorities and metropolitan planning organizations, Bexar and
Travis counties and the cities of Austin and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The final meeting this week is at 6 p.m. today at the San Marcos
Activity Center, 501 E. Hopkins St. in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   Business and community members along the Austin-San Antonio
corridor have long been discussing a proposal to run a commuter
train along the existing Union Pacific railroad tracks, which run
primarily in the MoPac Boulevard (Loop 1) median in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Hackley of Carter &AMP; Burgess, the consultant team heading up
the study, said the Austin-San Antonio corridor will have a
population in 2020 of 4 million, twice the population of the region
in 1990. Traffic on Interstate 35 between the two cities has
increased at a higher rate. On an average day 200,000 vehicles
cross Town Lake on the interstate in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those attending Tuesday's meeting didn't need to be
convinced about the need. When participants broke into three groups
to discuss specific ideas about commuter rail, they pointed out
some of the benefits: faster travel, easy access to shopping,
tourism, better air quality, safety, improvements to the
environment, reduced stress and more time for travelers to do the
things they enjoy while commuting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people read the paper or study while driving, but it'll
be safer on the train,'' said Pierre Riom.
</P>
<P>
   The groups also brainstormed over some of the biggest unanswered
questions about commuter rail, such as who would pay for it.
Participants suggested public-private partnerships, joint
development agreements, car and gas taxes, local economic
development sales taxes and I-35 tolls.
</P>
<P>
   Those suggestions will be incorporated into the commuter rail
feasibility study, which will be released in a draft by
Thanksgiving. An early ridership study will be ready in September.
Additional public meetings will also be held before the study is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
