NYT-09-02-98 1048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4707 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-TAKE     09-02 2025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED: Q: Will the public be able to buy independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's report to Congress on the investigation of
President Clinton, or if not the entire report, at least a summary
of it?)
</P>
<P>
   Q: House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt was quoted as saying
President Clinton was elected by a ``big majority.'' Did Clinton
actually receive a majority of the popular vote?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Clinton obviously received more votes in 1992 than George
Bush, and more in 1996 than Bob Dole, but in neither presidential
election did Clinton receive more than 50 percent. So in fact he
didn't receive a ``majority,'' which is defined as ``more than half
the total number.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the particulars of the major party candidates in the
two elections:
</P>
<P>
   1992: Clinton/Al Gore, 44,908,233 votes (43 percent); Bush/Dan
Quayle, 39,102,282 (37.4 percent).
</P>
<P>
   1996: Clinton/Gore, 45,628,667 (49.2 percent); Dole/Jack Kemp,
37,869,435 (40.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, by the way, was not the first president who failed to
receive a majority of the popular vote. He was the 16th in that
category.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Hurricane Opal is often overlooked in reports of hurricane
damage, but didn't it cause a great deal of destruction in the
Southeast?
</P>
<P>
   A: Opal, which came ashore east of Pensacola, Fla., on Oct. 4,
1995, was indeed destructive, slamming along Florida's beaches for
120 miles before moving northward into Georgia. It caused at least
$1.8 billion in damage to insured property in Florida alone. Opal
killed at least 19 people in Florida, Georgia, Alabama and North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know that not all the victims of the Holocaust were Jewish.
For example, I understand that many Jehovahs Witnesses were killed
by the Nazis, too. Can you list the numbers, or approximate
numbers, of victims by category?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sources differ considerably. There's no ``absolute, knowable
single set of statistics,'' said Mary Ann Leonard, a librarian at
the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington. The best
information, she told Q&AMP;A, comes from a report compiled in 1996 by
Sybil Milton, former senior historian at the museum. Rather than
dealing with specifics, Milton's report lists ranges of victims to
take into account the differing numbers in other sources, Leonard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the approximately 11 million people who died during the
Holocaust, Jewish victims were believed to number up to 6 million.
Soviet prisoners of war were as many as 2.3 million. More than 1
million Polish victims were identified. Estimates of other
categories: Gypsies, 250,000 to 500,000; mentally or phsyically
disabled, 200,000 to 250,000; Jehovahs Witnesses, about 10,000
imprisoned, of which about 2,500 died in prison camps; and
homosexuals, 5,000 to 12,000 arrested, with the mortality rate
unknown but believed to be at least 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Other victims, with no specific numbers or ranges assigned,
included people identified by Nazis as communists, socialists,
trade unionists, Free Masons and various political and religious
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   If you have access to the Internet, the Holocaust Memorial
Museum's site _ www.ushmm.org _ is a valuable resource.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We continue to see photos of President Clinton and his dog,
Buddy. What happened to his cat, Socks? Does Socks still live at
the White House?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, Socks ``sure is a resident'' of the White House, a
spokeswoman at the first lady's press office told Q&AMP;A. Although
Buddy got to go on the Clinton family's recent Martha's Vineyard
getaway, the first feline didn't. He stayed in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Socks, by the way, shouldn't be called the president's cat; he
belongs to Chelsea. Both the president and Hillary Rodham Clinton
are said to be allergic to cats.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can people, including members of the media, stay in areas
in the path of a hurricane when a mandatory evacuation has been
ordered?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no general rule applying to every area and every
case, according to the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
Decisions on evacuations _ and even the definition of what
``mandatory'' means _ are up to local authorities in affected
areas, and can vary from county to county, even from sheriff to
sheriff, a FEMA spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   As to news media representatives remaining in the path of a
storm, a FEMA spokeswoman said local authorities in affected areas
probably consider that the benefit of getting information out to
the public outweighs any potential risk to reporters and camera
crews.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know Ronald Reagan had been divorced before he became
president, but isn't it true that Gerald Ford also was divorced?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ford's only marriage was on Oct. 15, 1948, to Elizabeth
Bloomer Warren, said Donna Lehman of the Gerald R. Ford Library in
Ann Arbor, Mich. Elizabeth Warren, known as Betty, was a
35-year-old divorcee, which may explain the confusion. Her first
husband was William Warren, a furniture salesman in Grand Rapids,
Mich. They were married in 1942, divorced in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read several times that there may be some problems with
getting water and other necessary items in the future because of
computer and other problems, including Y2K on Dec. 31, 1999. I want
to store enough water to last six months. What is the proper way to
do this, and what type containers should I use?
</P>
<P>
   A: To store water for long periods, clean glass or plastic
food-grade containers are recommended. For the best taste, use
glass. The water should be boiled for 10 minutes and stored at room
temperature in a dark place.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A three-judge federal panel in Washington has ruled that the
Census Bureau's plan for statistical sampling violates 1957 and
1976 laws governing the census. Will you explain what statistical
sampling is, and how it works?
</P>
<P>
   A: In this case, statistical sampling would be something like a
public opinion poll. It would supplement, but not replace,
traditional head counting, which is accomplished with forms mailed
to residential addresses. Opponents of statistical sampling point
to the Constitution, which requires the federal government to
conduct an ``actual enumeration'' every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Under statistical sampling, the Census Bureau would employ three
sets of samples. In the first, it would send counters to one in 10
of the 6 million residential addresses said by the Postal Service
to be vacant. Normally, census forms are not sent to those
addresses, but studies have shown that at least 11 percent of the
homes said to be empty were, in fact, occupied. After the counters
checked these presumably vacant residences, it would use the number
of people actually living in them to estimate the population in
other housing units nationwide that were thought to be vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau also would check a proportion of residences
from which census forms had not been returned. And it would conduct
a random nationwide sample to check for accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about storms in the Pacific. What is the
hurricane or typhoon season there? Do storms ever cause problems
between Hawaii and California or Baja California?
</P>
<P>
   A: The tropical cyclone season in the western Pacific is never
quite over, but varies greatly in intensity. Every year, conditions
east of the Philippines send a score of violent storms howling
toward Asia, but it is worse from June through October. Southwest
of Mexico, eastern Pacific storms develop during the spring and
summer. Most die at sea as they move over colder ocean waters, but
there are destructive exceptions when storms occasionally curve
back toward Mexico. It's not the norm, though.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about a California columnist who
supposedly was fired for writing, the day after President Richard
Nixon died, that he was a ``wretched, wretched man''?
</P>
<P>
   A: The incident involved Matt Coker of the Daily Pilot in Orange
County, Calif., who minced no words after Nixon died. In a column
the day before Nixon's funeral, Coker called the former president
``a paranoid liar who did irreparable harm to these United States .
. . these same media that helped facilitate his downfall are now
giving teary-eyed eulogies to this wretched, wretched man. . . .
Goodbye and good riddance.''
</P>
<P>
   After hundreds of readers complained and some canceled their
subscriptions, the Daily Pilot apologized and printed a front-page
item criticizing Coker's view. Editor William Lobdell, who had
approved the Nixon column, said: ``We try not to be mean-spirited
and vicious in our columns. I try to bend over backwards to let a
columnist have his say. But the minute I saw it in print, I knew it
was a mistake.'' Coker no longer is writing a column, but at last
report remained on the staff as arts editor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article about the E. coli outbreak listed safety
tips for avoiding this bacteria. One was to drink carbonated
bottled water when traveling in areas where the water quality is
uncertain. Why is it important that the water is carbonated?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not because carbonation itself makes the water better
for you, according to Connie Crawley, nutrition and health
specialist at the University of Georgia Extension Service. The only
reason it's recommended is that if you ask for bottled water in
some areas of the world, you may get a previously opened bottle
that has been refilled with tap water _ exactly what you're trying
to avoiod. If you ask for carbonated water, and open the bottle
yourself, you can tell by the fizz that it hasn't been tampered
with.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible for a president to serve two consecutive
terms, then be out for a term, and then return for another two
terms?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It's possible for a person to serve for more than two
terms only if one succeeds to the office of president and serves
less than two years of the departed president's four-year term,
then is elected two times on one's own. But serving two terms, then
staying out for a round or two, and trying again, is not permitted
under the 22nd Amendment to the Constitution, which reads: ``No
person shall be elected to the office of president more than twice,
and no person who has held the office of president, or acted as
president for more than two years of a term to which some other
person was elected president, shall be elected to the office of the
president more than once.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it known why the suspected Islamic terrorist financier
Osama bin Laden is so anti-American? When the Soviets invaded
Afghanistan, both he and the United States supported the
mujahedeen. Why the change?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's true that throughout the 1980s, the United States and
bin Laden were on the same side against the now-collapsed Soviet
state, but bin Laden made no secret that he saw secular, powerful
Washington as an infidel just as much as Moscow. However, his first
priority was Moscow, which invaded Afghanistan in December 1979 to
prop up a communist government.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of religious edicts faxed to the outside world from
his suspected hideout in Afghanistan, bin Laden has laid out his
case against the United States: Its soldiers protecting oil in his
homeland, Saudi Arabia, are desecrating Muslim holy sites with
their very presence; its power has emasculated Arab countries,
turning them into client states; and its friend is Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In February, bin Laden helped form the World Islamic Front for
Jihad Against Jews and Crusaders, a coalition that brought together
two Egyptian militant groups, two Pakistani groups and a
Bangladeshi group. ``We _ with God's help _ call on every Muslim
who believes in God and wishes to be rewarded to comply with God's
order to kill Americans and plunder their money wherever and
whenever they find it,'' read one of the group's statements.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
