 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 400 - September 2, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To publish any of the special ``separate buy'' articles listed
below, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81. e-mail: nyt &LR; calva.net
ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 400 -- September 2, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. HOW MUCH OF POLITICS IS ENTERTAINMENT? Have we reached the
point where the line between entertainment and news is blurring?
Like entertainment, politics is increasingly part of the
easy-listening background music of the time. More and more,
politicians play to the camera. There's nothing entertaining about
Bill Clinton's plight since the Monica Lewinsky story broke in
January - and yet the entire spectacle has more in common with mass
entertainment than with serious politics. By David M. Shribman.
From The Boston Globe Magazine. 2,500 words. 2. ASHLEY JUDD Ashley
Judd has grown up now and is a movie star. It wasn't always that
way. In this interview she recalls her life before she hit the big
time in Hollywood with a number of films, including ``Kiss the
Girls'' (1997.) Judd's star power shines through. The director of
her new film ``Simon Birch'' marvels that she is ``vivacious,
strong and sexy,'' and Interview magazine has called her ``a young
Elizabeth Taylor.'' By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo. 3.
CINDY CRAWFORD GRABS ATTENTION WITH SPECIAL ON SEX In the first
result of a three-year development deal she recently signed with
ABC, supermodel Cindy Crawford is going on TV for an hour-long
special program to talk about .... sex. ``I'm not a journalist or a
sex expert, but I'm curious about sex,'' Crawford says. In this
interview she says she would act in movies again only under the
right circumstances, after the failure of her debut ``Fair Game''
(1995.) The 32-year-old cover girl (ancient in modeling circles)
does worry about getting old and is already obsessing that her
knees are starting to droop ... By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words +
photo. 4. SPIELBERG BASHES INTELLECTUALS Steven Spielberg's film
``Saving Private Ryan'' has one false and creepy note, writes
Nicholas Lemann. From SLATE. 500 words. 5. FOR MATT DAMON, FAME
MEANS PROTECTING HIS PRIVATE LIFE Matt Damon is riding high at the
box office with the success of ``Saving Private Ryan.'' His latest
film is ``Rounders,'' about card sharks. But now that he is truly a
star, he has learned the hard way to keep his private life low key.
In this interview Damon discusses the new movie as well as his
turnabout on private topics - after he told Oprah Winfrey about his
break up with actress Minnie Driver. He also talks about the
lengths to which he goes in acting, including Robert De Niro-like
physical changes. In Damon's case, he goes on diets for some of his
roles, once losing 18 kilos. By Jeanne Wolf. (N/A England.) 1,400
words + photo. (Cartoon of Matt Damon by Vance Lehmkul also
available.) 6. ROSEANNE JOINS THE RANKS OF TV TALK SHOW HOSTS Watch
out Oprah! Roseanne is coming to host talk-show television. When
last heard of, she had just left TV with a bang, abandoning her hit
sitcom ``Roseanne'' with a few last potshots at ABC, people who
worked with her and Hollywood in general. Now with ``The Roseanne
Show'' she is claiming to be the perfect talk show host : ``I've
got five kids by three different men .... I came from a trailer
park ...''. If the show is a hit, she can expect to earn around $50
million a year. By David Kronke. From TV Guide. 1,400 words + photo
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
NOTES ON THE NON-CRITICS Reviewers have a stake in keeping up the
pretence that most films are worth reviewing, writes Jacob
Weisberg. Were they to acknowledge that 95 per cent of what comes
out of Hollywood is rubbish, there wouldn't be much left for most
of them to do. Critics should address the larger question of why
Hollywood thinks so little of today's film audience. From Slate.
1,000 words. 8. PRINCESS DIANA : FASHION STATEMENTS James Fallon
reports on a new book ('Diana : Her Life in Fashion' by Georgina
Howell) on how designers perceived Princess Diana. ``Princess Diana
absolutely was not a fashion leader,'' Howell says, ``but she used
fashion as a language to get her message across to her public, and
I believe it made her one of the great communicators of the
century.'' From Women's Wear Daily. 700 words. 9. LEELEE SOBIESKI :
TEEN ANGEL She's worked with Tom Cruise, Nicole Kidman and Stanley
Kubrick, but Leelee Sobieski is still a wide-eyed 16-year old. She
is in the latest Merchant Ivory production, ``A Soldier's Daughter
Never Cries,'' playing an American girl who comes of age in Paris
and the U.S. in the '60s and '70s. Interview by Julie L. Belcove.
From W Magazine. 1,500 words + photo.
</P>
