<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Sept. 2, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ON-LINE-TRADING (San Francisco) _ Popular on-line trading sites
say stock market turbulence has sent record numbers of individual
traders to their keyboards. The on-line trading sites seem to have
handled the crush well. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   STOX-RETIREMENT (San Francisco) _ By the size of the headlines
shouting stock market free fall, you would think that
retirement-minded investors like Carol Covington of San Francisco
would be cowering in a corner, but she's still as bullish as they
come. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GRAFFITI-CAR (Albany, N.Y.) _ Tom Mosquera, an aspiring
constitutional lawyer, has taken the practice of free expression
through bumper stickers a little farther down the road. With a
black marker taped to the front of the windshield and the First
Amendment written on the hood, Mosquera's 1982 Volvo is now a
mobile marketplace of ideas. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERFLY-EXTINCTION (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Karner blue butterfly
is slowly losing its fight to survive in the Albany Pine Bush
Preserve, one of the species' last remaining natural habitats in
the United States. The killer: humans. The latest tool of
destruction: the all-terrain vehicle. By PAUL ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TUSCANY (Volpaia Italy) _ Lightning flickered across the Tuscan
sky. Thunder crackled and boomed off medieval stone towers. As
heavy drops spattered the piazza, we dashed across rain-slick
cobblestones to the sanctuary of the village's only restaurant. It
was one of the many good fortunes we encountered walking through
the Chianti hills, through vineyards full of plumping grapes and
dark forests sheltering wild boar. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   With: TUSCANY-INFO
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MINT (Albany, N.Y.) _ This summer I gave in to the mint
dominating our herb garden. Instead of cursing the aggressive
plants as they enacted hostile takeovers of small pockets of soil
set aside for basil, oregano and thyme, I decided to embrace the
mint, one sprig at a time. The results have exceeded expectations.
By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In San Francisco, you don't need
a ticker to know which way the stock market is going. You just need
to watch bartenders. While I was having a plate of perfectly fried
calamari at Farallon restaurant, I told bartender Patrick Dunn that
the Dow Jones had bounced back from its big drop. ``That explains
why I've been selling so many martinis and so much champagne,'' he
observed. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
