<HEADER>
A4762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX     09-02 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW I SPENT MY BALTIC VACATION: Estonia beats Russia, hands down
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLINN, Estonia _ I'm like most Americans traveling in foreign
countries. I recognize only two languages: English and gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the words on the pocket of the Estonian border
guard's uniform took the form of a warm welcome, especially after
traveling in Russia:
</P>
<P>
   ``Border Guard,'' it said _ in English!
</P>
<P>
   He even looked rather like an American, tall and handsome in a
sort of Clint Eastwoodiness fashion, and not at all Slavic.
</P>
<P>
   I would have thought otherwise of the people of the Baltics _
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, with Russia bordering to the east
and Poland to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Not so. Estonians are of Finnish heritage. Latvians and
Lithuanians, closer cousins in language and tradition, are of
German lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Tallinn, Estonia's capital, on the northern edge of the Baltic
Sea, is only 30 minutes by air from Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans have to look twice to find the Baltic States on
the map. Often we confuse them with the Balkans _ Serbia, Croatia
and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   What all I didn't know until I arrived:
</P>
<P>
   _ The people call themselves Balts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The tradition of Christmas trees may have originated here, as
early as the 1500s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christian religion is prevalent. You'll find Lutheran,
Orthodox, Baptist, Methodist and Catholic churches.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Estonian currency is the Kroon, valued at about 14 to the
U.S. dollar. Prices are reasonable. A first-class hotel room in
Tallinn is about $100 a night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Old Estonian superstition: If you eat in the dark, your
children might grow up to be thieves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Geographically, Estonia is about the size of Louisiana, 45,000
square miles. The similarity doesn't end there. A favorite holiday
dish is Verivorst, blood sausage. Old Cajuns would feel much at
home.
</P>
<P>
   So did I.
</P>
<P>
   Tallinn is a clean, safe and beautiful city of slightly more
than 400,000 population, almost Disney-like with its Old Town
sector dating back some five centuries. The parks are lovely and
numerous.
</P>
<P>
   You find English spoken most everywhere, and people couldn't be
nicer, though a bit reserved. Blame that on their Finnish culture.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, one of the most popular pastimes for Estonians is to
go into the woods and sit under a tree.
</P>
<P>
   I seldom saw a police car or heard a siren. Evening time is
quiet time for Tallinn. The order of the day seems to be
orderliness.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that in World War II Estonia had its own unit of the
SS fighting alongside the Nazis against the Soviet Red Army. The SS
veterans, in staging a recent reunion, are a great embarrassment to
the current democratic government seeking membership in the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltics suffered equally under Nazi and Soviet occupation.
In just one day in 1944, Red Army air strikes leveled more than 10
percent of Tallinn's Old Town.
</P>
<P>
   The end of World War II was only the beginning. During the first
year of Soviet rule, Estonia lost 60,000 of its citizens, exiled to
Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltic States broke away from Russian dominance in the early
1990s as the Soviet Union crumbled. Nowadays, it's not so easy
being Russian in Estonia, although they make up 32 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Russians feel they are being treated as second-class citizens.
Indeed, citizenship in the new Estonia is difficult for Russians to
obtain. For instance, they have to be able to speak Estonian.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians, even those born here, never bothered to learn
Estonian. They expected everyone else to speak their language, if
you can imagine such an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
