<SLUG> BC-GRAFFITI-CAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW STUDENT PUTS THE PEDAL TO THE MEDAL FOR FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When it comes to defending the right of free
speech, Tom Mosquera lets his car settle the case.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquera, 32 and an aspiring constitutional lawyer, has taken
the practice of free expression through bumper stickers a little
farther down the road. With a black Magic Marker taped to the front
of the windshield and the First Amendment written on the hood,
Mosquera's 1982 cream-colored Volvo is now a mobile marketplace of
ideas _ open for anyone to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very popular with the lesbian crowd, apparently,''
Mosquera said this week, pointing to messages like ``Lesbians
rule'' and ``Mary loves Joan'' scrawled on the sides of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look _ `Down with liberals.' Isn't that ironic? They should
try to find a conservative with a car like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the politics of the vehicular graffiti, Mosquera
doesn't care. Only about a quarter of the messages are political,
anyway. Many have to do with legalizing marijuana. Some promote the
Bible. Most are simply reflections of the progressive residents in
Mosquera's Hudson Park neighborhood, where the car is quickly
becoming a local _ albeit transient _ landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquera, who is in his first year at Albany Law School, said he
got the idea after watching a debate on flag burning and people who
opposed that form of expressive opinion. On July 9 _ the date is
written atop the Volvo's grill _ Mosquera dedicated the car he
bought in 1996 for $2,500 to demonstrating free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it was to remind people that a car like this
couldn't exist in China,'' said Mosquera, whose thinning hair swept
into a ponytail belies his twentysomething grunge attire. He
aspires to someday work for the American Civil Liberties Union or a
similar nonprofit activist organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea is to get people to think. A lot of people have
opinions, but not a lot of people actually think. I was curious to
see what people would write.''
</P>
<P>
   The results have run across the gamut:
</P>
<P>
   ``Drive locally, pollute globally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``'98 Led Zepplin!! Nothin' left to do but Smile, Smile,
Smile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love cops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get pulled over, this one might come in handy,'' Mosquera
said, pointing to the latter message, written just below the
driver's seat window.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the messages toe the line. Racial epithets and
profanity are quickly covered with spray paint. The Volvo gets
edited on a daily basis, and the painted-over spots outnumber its
patches of rust.
</P>
<P>
   Whether graffiti-makers will try to spread the word to other
cars is another concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people choose to write on their own cars, that's one thing.
If it does start to spread, that's something we'd have to address
with the police,'' said Hudson Park Neighborhood Association
President Colleen Ryan. The neighborhood has recently been looking
at enforcing issues like picking up garbage or cleaning up after
dogs, but ``so far that hasn't included people who write on their
cars,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of characters in this neighborhood who are
involved with making it a better place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Mosquera's marker has yet to be stolen or used on
another car. How long he will continue to use the Volvo as a
pontificating point remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to do this in some upscale community, it would
probably get towed,'' Mosquera said with a grin. ``Here, no one's
ever said `You're an idiot' for doing this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
