<HEADER>
A4831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-JAMAICA-$ADV0     09-02 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-JAMAICA-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BEYOND JAMAICA'S POSH RESORTS: ANOTHER SIDE TO PARADISE
 &HT;    With photo placed in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Sept. 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica _ ``Crime's so bad they'll cut off your arm to
get a nice watch,'' warned the American businessman seated beside
me during a nearly two-hour flight from Miami to Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   It was an ominous beginning to what was supposed to be a quick
business trip to paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Often I'd heard Jamaica, the Caribbean's largest
English-speaking country, touted as a succulently green island,
where honeymooners munch on mangoes for breakfast at posh hotels
while gazing at blooming hibiscus plants and palm trees dripping
with coconuts.
</P>
<P>
   This island of 2.5 million people welcomed 1.9 million tourists
last year, many of whom were undoubtedly charmed by the country's
azure waters and mountains that look as high as heaven.
</P>
<P>
   And it is true that the scenery in many parts of this
Connecticut-sized nation is spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another side to Jamaica that lies beyond the high
walls of all-inclusive resorts.
</P>
<P>
   I found, for example, that driving through this capital city was
like driving through the worst slums of Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Children in tattered clothing live inside squalid shanties with
corrugated tin roofs in neighborhoods where rancid fruit stands and
closet-sized liquor stores are fixtures and the only
sanitary-looking structure is a Texaco service station.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is like El Salvador after the war except that there
wasn't any war in Jamaica,'' exclaimed a dumbfounded official at
the U.S. Embassy here.
</P>
<P>
   But what the country has suffered from is an economy in
shambles.
</P>
<P>
   When most of the world was enjoying an economic boon, Jamaica's
economy was shrinking by nearly 3 percent in both 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that even Haiti -- the Western Hemisphere's
poorest country -- has a better-performing economy than Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Just the sheer unreliability of everyday life offers a peephole
into the downturn's effect on average citizens.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  With many manholes uncovered, walking down a sidewalk can be
precarious business.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A sign in Montego Bay claims Kingston is 190 kilometers away;
another says 122.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And, in a country that sees rain almost every afternoon, many
people are without water 12 hours a day thanks to broken pipes that
allow an estimated 60 percent of the water supply to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to blame for the country's devastating recession is a
massive government debt that has choked off any chance at
development. Interest rates of 40 percent have slowed investment.
And, as an unemployment rate now at nearly 20 percent has grown, so
has its dark shadow -- crime.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 murders were reported here last year, a rate
fueled primarily by a thriving drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There're few places doing as poorly as Jamaica,'' laments
Charles Ross, executive director of the Private Sector Organization
of Jamaica. ``And, we expect another year of negative growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The government points to inflation of 9 percent in 1997 -- the
first single-digit increase in a decade -- as a resounding
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   It has also managed to forestall a spectacular financial-system
collapse by taking over 50 percent of all the banks and financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the government of Prime Minister P.J.
Patterson has increased the number of public-sector employees by 11
percent when most other Caribbean governments have trimmed bloated
bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   Economists agree that the only thing keeping Jamaica's economy
afloat today are $800 million in remittances the island receives
each year from the 2 million or so Jamaicans who're living
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what has average Jamaicans scratching their heads is
that, in a country strapped for cash, the government promised each
member of its soccer team, dubbed the Reggae Boyz, a two-acre
building plot and a low-cost home loan after it won a place in the
World Cup final late last year.
</P>
<P>
   And they're still baffled over the Jamaican Tourist Board's
decision last year to spend hundreds of thousands of dollars to
commission what it had hoped would be the world's largest
inflatable soccer ball as part of a promotional scheme only to have
it rejected by the Guinness Book of Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to wonder what the government is thinking,''
pondered Gerald Hamilton, a taxi driver.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Jamaica used to be one of the more prosperous
islands in the West Indies, and the preferred playground of
celebrities like Bette Davis and Rudyard Kipling.
</P>
<P>
   Even today the most popular saying on T-shirts here is ``Smile
Mon -- No Problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a problem on this lovely island -- an economic
crisis -- and until it's solved, this no-problem getaway offers
visitors very little to fantasize about.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
