<HEADER>
A4840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUSCANY-INFO-HNS &LR;      09-02 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUSCANY-INFO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU GO: TUSCANY AND UMBRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guidebooks: ``Walking and Eating in Tuscany and Umbria,'' by
James Lasdun and Pia Davis (Penguin Books; $16.95). In addition to
providing historical information, the book also contains data on
bus connections, restaurants and accommodations, as well as
information on other walks in Tuscany and Umbria. Lonely Planet has
just released ``Walking in Italy,'' which describes a different
three-day walk through the Chianti hills.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation: At a bookstore in Siena I bought two topographic
maps; neither was terribly useful. The verbal description of the
route in the guidebook was reassuringly precise, although once or
twice I was thrown off course briefly due to the rerouting of farm
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Logistics: We started from Siena, took an express bus to
Florence and one of the frequent local buses to Greve, the starting
point. The walk has two alternative ending points. We chose
Vagliagli over San Sano because bus connections back to Siena were
much more frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: ``Walking and Eating'' lists hotels along the
route. From a purely logistical standpoint, some may be more
convenient than the ones where we stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after the walk we stayed at Hotel Chiusarelli, Viale
Curtatone 15, Siena, Italy; phone: 011-39-577-280562; fax:
011-39-577-271177. $74 a night for two, not including breakfast.
Clean, quiet, located near the Chiesa di San Domenica and the bus
station; a good place to leave excess clothes and other gear during
your walk.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get a room in Greve at the start of the walk, we
stayed at the Relais Fattoria Valle, Case Sparse 56, Panzanon
Greve, Chianti, Italy; phone: 011-39-55-852-482. $90 a night for
two, including breakfast. A stately, restored 19th-century Tuscan
villa about 15 minutes by local bus from Greve. Note: limited, if
any, English spoken.
</P>
<P>
   In Parco San Michele there's only one place to stay: Villa San
Michele Hostel, Parco Naturale de San Michele, Greve, Italy; phone:
011-39-55-851034. All rooms are $63 a night for two, including
breakfast. Ask for room No. 3 _ it's by far the nicest.
</P>
<P>
   Between Volpaia and Radda we stayed at Azienda Il Pruneto, Loc.
Il Pruneto 37, Radda in Chianto, Italy; phone: 011-39-577-738013.
Cost: 120,000 lire ($68.50) per night for a double room, not
including breakfast. A farmhouse in a spectacular location.
</P>
<P>
   Also between Volpaia and Rad da, Podere Terreno, alla via della
Volpaia, Radda in Chianti (SI), Italy; phone: 011-39-577-738312;
fax: 011-39-577-738400. Rooms are 140,000 lire ($80) per person per
night, with half board (breakfast, dinner and wine). Minimum
two-night stay. Those not overnighting there may book dinners
separately for 45,000 lire ($26) if space permits. Phone before 10
a.m. the day you plan to dine.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat: In Siena, Grotta del Gallo Nero, Via del Porrione
67, Siena; phone: 011-39-577-284356; serves authentic dishes from
medieval recipes. Multicourse menus, including wine, are $22 to $33
per person.
</P>
<P>
   In Panzano we had a superb dinner at Trattoria Oltre il
Giardino, Piazza Bucciorelli, 42 5022 Panzano, Chianti, Italy;
phone: 011-39-571-310483. Dinner for two, including wine, came to
$48.
</P>
</TEXT>
