<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GRAFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS HAVE ALWAYS LOOTED STATE FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Allegations by foreign bankers that the Russian elite
has systematically plundered more than $33 billion in international
loans came as little surprise to those familiar with the country's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials of Credit Swiss First Boston bank claimed
that members of the so-called ``oligarchy'' _ high-flying Russian
business executives and bankers close to the Yeltsin regime _ had
siphoned the immense sum into their own pockets, helping to account
for the plunge of the ruble and the political crisis now
threatening Russia.
</P>
<P>
   If true, the charge is an echo of similar looting that has
occurred through the centuries. The czars regularly provided choice
morsels from the state coffers to their supporters. Little
differentiation was made between public funds and private money.
Indeed, in the final analysis, all property was considered to
belong to the czar, to do with as he wished.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the current crisis erupted, President Boris Yeltsin
was reported to be following the old tradition, helping his cronies
to become Russia's new tycoons. One of them, banker Boris
Berezovsky, is said to be so wealthy and powerful that Yeltsin
seldom makes a move without his advice _ in much the same way the
czars relied on the favorites they had raised to positions of
influence.
</P>
<P>
   If Yeltsin did bankroll his friends, he didn't have to look all
the way back to the czars for a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-five years of Soviet government legitimized the lack
of scruples,'' according to historian Robert Vishnogradov of
France's National Research Council, a government-funded think tank
here. ``The rule of law did not exist under the communists. This
has made it easier for the post-communist era to be lawless.
</P>
<P>
   ``State property was considered easy pickings for theft in
Soviet times,'' Vishnogradov said. ``It has been hard for Russians
who grew up under communism to shake that view. It is a widespread
notion that if you don't steal from the state, others will _ and
will take your share.''
</P>
<P>
   At the highest levels of government and finance, the same casual
attitude is often found, he noted. It helps to explain the large
number of wealthy people who have emerged in just a few years
although Russia itself remains a poor and backward country, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theft has simply become one way _ a frequent way _ to make
money,'' Vishnogradov said. ~``The fact is, nobody holds it against
you if that is how you get rich. Rather, they envy you for being
clever enough to do it and get away with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
