<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With TEENS-CONSTITUTION.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A telephone survey of 600 teenagers between 13 and
17 found that more could correctly answer entertainment questions
than questions about current affairs. The margin of error is plus
or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   1.8 percent knew: Who is considered the father of the U.S.
Constitution? (James Madison)
</P>
<P>
   58.3 percent knew: Who is the father of the computer company
Microsoft? (Bill Gates)
</P>
<P>
   2.2 percent: Who is the Chief Justice of the United States?
(William Rehnquist)
</P>
<P>
   94.7 percent: Who played the Fresh Prince of Bel Air on
television? (Will Smith)
</P>
<P>
   12.2 percent: What's the name of the town where Abraham Lincoln
lived for most of his adult life and which he represented in
Congress? (Springfield)
</P>
<P>
   74.3 percent: What's the name of the town where Bart Simpson
lives? (Springfield)
</P>
<P>
   21.2 percent: How many U.S. senators are there? (100)
</P>
<P>
   81.2 percent: How many brothers are there in the musical group
``Hanson''? (3)
</P>
<P>
   32.7 percent: Who is currently Speaker of the House in the U.S.
Congress? (Newt Gingrich)
</P>
<P>
   89.8 percent: Who stars as the father of the house in TV's
``Home Improvement?'' (Tim Allen as Tim Taylor)
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Luntz Research Companies for the Nation Constitution
Center. August 1998
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
