<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-02 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING UP WITH THE DOW JONESES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In this city you don't need a ticker to know
which way the stock market is going. You just need to watch
bartenders.
</P>
<P>
   While I was having a plate of perfectly fried calamari at
Farallon restaurant on Tuesday, I told bartender Patrick Dunn that
the Dow Jones had bounced back from its big drop the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``That explains why I've been selling so many martinis and so
much champagne,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to love this town. The high rollers go to one of our
finest restaurants and get tanked on Moet to celebrate the stock
market not tanking.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market ever crashes, they'll just drink cheaper
stuff. Any excuse to have a pop in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   I don't usually have lunch at Farallon, but I was wondering what
the rich people were doing.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I was wondering about the large portion of the
Bay-area population who sell things to rich people.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch Tuesday, Farallon was filled with beautiful people.
Business types smiled and laughed over chef Mark Franz's grilled
pike with caper aioli. An impeccably tailored young woman took a
table for one near the window for an intimate lunch with her cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market completely folds, will it please take cell
phones with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the restaurant business goes, the stock market can
have an effect,'' said Farallon's operations manager, Nick Peyton.
``People become a little more value-conscious. Not that they stop
going out. They'll just say, `I'm not going to get the Peter
Michael Chardonnay at $75, I'll get something cheaper.'''
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask me who Peter Michael is. I never saw his stuff in
Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   Peyton, who has been in the restaurant business since the 1960s,
says every economic dip hurts. ``I was at the Ritz Carlton in 1991
when there was a downturn after the Gulf War, and it had a profound
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the rich and not-quite-so-rich have lost some
money on paper in recent weeks, but they aren't selling pencils and
they're still buying Jaguars and Land Rovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I can't believe how steady our clients are,'' said
Gordon Blackstock, sales manager of British Motor Car Distributors
Ltd. ``We're so consistent. We sell 20 to 30 Jaguars every month
and 30 to 35 (Land) Rovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackstock said that no matter what the stock market does, his
clients buy luxury cars at that pace, among them the gorgeous new
Jaguar convertible priced at $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   Salesman Craig R. Perry, who was closing a deal, said his
customers don't waste time listening to market news because they're
in for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, ``I guess it's better to worry about
the market than to worry about a bomb coming in your window, as in
other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Business was brisk at the San Francisco Gun Exchange. Never
fear. Customers weren't arming themselves to take to the hills in
case of national collapse. They were arming themselves for dove
season, duck season, deer season and elk season.
</P>
<P>
   Co-owner Bob Posner said he has a beautiful handmade Purdy
shotgun that a customer had imported from England for $60,000 and
never used. Posner said he should have no problem selling it. ``I'd
have people lined up for this gun at $30,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The rich are different from you and me. Their idea of a bargain
is buying a $30,000 gun so they can sit in the cold and shoot a
duck they can get at Farallon for about 20 bucks _ already cooked,
and better than their personal chefs can prepare.
</P>
<P>
   At Neiman-Marcus, jewelry saleswoman Marci Halabis said business
was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the crossroads of the world,'' she said from behind
the counter in the front of the store. Some architect friends saw
her and came in to say hello. Halabis, who is studying massage,
gave one friend a quick hand massage.
</P>
<P>
   That's another thing about San Francisco. Buy jewelry at
Neiman's in Dallas, and you won't get a hand massage. Well, here
you have to be an old friend of Marci Halabis, but she has a lot of
friends after 13 years selling jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   She said she has money in a 401(k), but she doesn't worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm above ground,'' said this practical Michigan native. ``As
long as I'm alive and can make decisions, I'm OK.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the American attitude. Never mind what the rich people
are doing, or how much Bill Gates or Larry Ellison have lost on
paper. We're an optimistic people.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look on the bright side. Optimism sure beats pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   I was so optimistic I even took a close look at that Jaguar
convertible (hey, I play Lotto), and invested in a glass of wine
futures at Farallon. You don't have to be rich, and it makes an
hour of the present quite wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the Municipal Railway, all leading San Francisco
indicators are up. I ran into the Brown twins, Vivian and Marian. I
said hello and asked them what they thought of all this stock
market hullabaloo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an investor,'' Marian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have that kind of money,'' Vivian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good news, is it?'' Marian said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I don't know. I was smiling, just because they had put
their money into duplicate suits and hats of the brightest yellow
imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   This is San Francisco, and we have better things to look at than
jagged falling lines on a graph.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
