<SLUG> BC-BUTTERFLY-EXTINCTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE BUTTERFLY FACES A NEW MENACE: ALL-TERRAIN VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Karner blue butterfly is slowly losing its
fight to survive in the Albany Pine Bush Preserve, one of the
species' last remaining natural habitats in the United States. The
killer: humans. The latest tool of destruction: the all-terrain
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The azure-winged butterflies, about the size of a 25-cent coin,
are being threatened by burly ATVs illegally churning through the
property, Pine Bush officials say.
</P>
<P>
   As they pop wheelies and spin doughnut-shaped grooves into the
earth, ATV riders are also mowing down the wild blue lupine, the
only plant that Karner caterpillars eat, Preserve Steward Joel
Hecht said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you impact the plant, you're going to directly impact the
Karner blue butterfly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate New York was once home to hundreds of thousands of the
flying blue lepidoptera, which were first identified in 1949 and
named after the now-extinct village of Karner. Now there are only a
few hundred in the Pine Bush. The northern Saratoga County town of
Wilton also is home to a significant Karner Blue buttery
population. They live in the state-owned Wildlife Preserve and
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Once found in 12 states, the butterflies remain only in Indiana,
Minnesota, New Hampshire, New York and Wisconsin, preserve
ecologist Neil Gifford said. The species is listed by the federal
government as endangered.
</P>
<P>
   ATVs aren't permitted in the 2,400-acre Pine Bush, said Joseph
Hess, the lone New York Department of Environmental Conservation
forest ranger patrolling the preserve. But morning and weekend joy
riders ignore posted signs.
</P>
<P>
   Though ATVs have long been a scourge of the Pine Bush, the
problem has become so severe that officials decided to hold a news
conference Tuesday near a sand dune freshly engraved with ATV
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get people to ride responsibly,'' Hess said.
Meaning: Stay off Pine Bush property.
</P>
<P>
   ATVs aren't the only threat to the Karner blue. Shrinking open
space and the lack of rejuvenating scrub fires also have hurt,
Hecht said.
</P>
<P>
   Pine Bush officials are trying to maintain the population of
Karner blues by protecting what lupine-laden land there is as a
breeding ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without intervention, they will be lost,'' Gifford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
