<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-CHASIDIC-NYTSF &LR;      09-02 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-CHASIDIC-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST CHASIDIC LEADER WAS BORN 300 YEARS AGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In 1971 I moved across the country from Brooklyn to Lomita,
Calif., an area where few Jews lived. I was sent by the Chasidic
leader, Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson, the Lubavitcher Rebbe, to
establish a Chasidic Jewish community for the South Bay.
 &HT;    Being Chasidic means our family customs and lifestyles are
different. On the Sabbath married men wear a long jacket called a
kapota, which looks like a Prince Albert tuxedo, and distinct black
fedoras. We don't work on the Sabbath, and we keep the many other
customs of Orthodox Jews.
 &HT;    One Sabbath morning as I was walking to the synagogue, a Chevy
convertible drove past me. The driver hit his brakes, got out of
the car and ran over to me. I was startled and frightened.
 &HT;    ``Hey, Padre, are you Jewish?'' he asked.
 &HT;    I said, ``Yes.''
 &HT;    ``Padre, are you a Chasid?''
 &HT;    I said, ``Yes.''
 &HT;    ``If that's the case, you must be from the happiest people in
the world,'' he said. Then he asked to shake my hand.
 &HT;    ``My name is Jose Rodriguez and I come from Mexico. I took a
college course called social anthropology. In studying the Jewish
people I was told by my professor about a group called Chasidim.
'Chasidim are the happiest people in the world,' he said. 'No
matter what happens to them their deep faith in God keeps them
happy.'
 &HT;    ``So, Padre, when I drove by I thought it couldn't be possible
that a Chasid would live so far away from his people. When I saw
that you had a beard, a black hat and a long black coat, you fit
the description of my textbooks and I realized that, yes indeed,
you must be a Chasid. So, amigo, let me wish you good luck.''
 &HT;    He saluted and off he went. The encounter gave me a wonderful
feeling.
 &HT;    Sept. 9 will mark a great day in the Chasidic movement. It is
the 300th anniversary of the birth of the first Chasidic leader,
Rabbi Yisroel Baal Shem Tov -- Master of the Good Name.
 &HT;    Rabbi Yisroel, living in the Carpathian Mountains in Eastern
Europe, launched a movement called Chasidism. It captured the
attention of millions of Jewish people. Within the initial 150
years of the movement six million Jews adopted this lifestyle. It's
been said that more than half of Eastern Europe were followers of
the Chasidic movement.
 &HT;    Rabbi Yisroel's mother died when he was born and his father, a
saintly man, addressed the 5-year-old boy before his death and told
him, ``Yisroel, have no fear of anyone except God.''
 &HT;    As a child Yisroel spent much time in the forest, observing
nature. He wasn't known to be a brilliant student; as a matter of
fact, he was different from most children. The young Yisroel was
definitely plugged into a different spiritual source.
 &HT;    The elders of the town tried to bring him back to the school;
however, Yisroel defied them and lived his own lifestyle. He
befriended many of the simple people. As he grew older he brought
joy and happiness to the poor and oppressed. One of his greatest
attributes was a joyful attitude to life and all sorts of people.
 &HT;    For 30 years Yisroel traveled from town to town where he
introduced the people to the concept of self-worth and happiness.
Everything, he claimed, had a purpose, whether good or seemingly
bad. The main thing was to have faith in God and to obey his
commandments happily. If you are happy with your lot in life, then
God will be happy with you. Our Father in Heaven hates sadness and
rejoices when his children are joyful. He had a saying, ``It is
man's duty to always live joyfully while serving God through prayer
and the study of Torah.''
 &HT;    You can well imagine the opposition of the scholars toward this
man's philosophy in saying that the main thing was to be happy when
worshiping God. This meant that the ignoramus could be just as
happy as the scholar. They thought maybe the scholars would not be
respected for his learning.
 &HT;    According to the Baal Shem Tov, all men were created equal, some
more learned than others, but when it came to joy there was no
monopoly. As a result, a schism was created within the Jewish
people.
 &HT;    To the gentiles of his era, the Baal Shem Tov was extremely
kind. He extended his patience and understanding to those in need.
Tradition tells us how he learned the mysteries of roots and herbs
from a gentile peasant whom he had saved when he was sick. As a
gift the peasant gave the Baal Shem Tov the secret healing powers
found in herbs and shrubs.
 &HT;    According to the Baal Shem Tov, every event in the physical
universe, even that of a leaf twirling from a tree, has a purpose.
 &HT;    Once there was a scoffer of the Baal Shem Tov who decided to
follow a leaf which was twirling across a street. He followed the
leaf over many blocks until it stopped. ``Ha,'' said the man to
himself, ``the leaf stopped for no purpose.''
 &HT;    He bent down and looked under the leaf and sure enough there was
a dying baby worm baking in the heat of the day. Now this little
leaf was providing the worm with shelter, thus ensuring that the
worm would not perish.
 &HT;    This idea of God loving everybody and everything having a
purpose was novel. The new movement flourished. People who followed
the Baal Shem Tov were called Chasidim -- pious ones -- for they
respected everything and considered that everything created in the
world has worth and is divinely given.
 &HT;    Next week, hundreds of thousands of Jewish people worldwide will
celebrate the birth of this Chasidic leader. During this period
people will speak about the many different Chasidic movements that
have flourished and branched out due to the encouragement of this
man.
 &HT;    In a way, the Baal Shem Tov is a great emancipator of the soul.
His lessons revived and rejuvenated the individuality of every
single person in this world. Our society could use the message of
worshiping God with joy.
 &HT;    If we had a generation of joyful people, what a wonderful world
it would be. Through joy any person can follow his religious
instinct and immerse himself in helping the world become a better
and safer place.
 &HT;    Within the many Chasidic movements, it has been the Chabad
Chasidic movement that has balanced the modern world and ancient
Jewish religion. Today there are over 3,000 Chabad centers spanning
the globe and continuing the work started by the Baal Shem Tov.
Thousands of young and old rabbis carry out his work in trying to
bring Godliness and goodness to the world, all inspired with joy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1998 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
