r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LINE-TRADING-HNS &LR;      09-02 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LINE-TRADING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE BROKERAGES SURVIVE A HECTIC DAY WITHOUT TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Popular on-line trading sites say stock market
turbulence has sent record numbers of individual traders to their
keyboards. But unlike one hectic trading day last year when sites
buckled under demand, the electronic brokerages appear to be
handling the recent crunch.
</P>
<P>
   Though exact numbers were not available, Monday's white-knuckle
market ride most likely set records for on-line trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was our largest single day,'' said Ken Squire, a
spokesman for ETrade, the No. 2 on-line trading broker behind San
Francisco-based Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.'s ESchwab site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday, we hit a volume record,'' said a spokesman for
Ameritrade, another heavily advertised on-line trading site.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab spokesman Tom Taggart said that after the numbers were
tallied, ``we're sure it will be a record-setting day.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when the Dow Jones industrial average fell 512
points, on-line stock traders were nervous. During the 554 stock
market free fall last Oct. 27, on-line trading sites collapsed
under the load of users rushing to check out and trade on their
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had some capacity issues,'' Taggart said, ``but we all
also learned from those times.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard lesson. Following last year's market drop, ETrade
was hit with a class-action lawsuit for allegedly failing to live
up to its promise of reliable, efficient trading. That suit is
still pending in a California court. In addition, the Securities
and Exchange Commission investigated the World Wide Web trading
failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had real trouble then,'' said Jonathan Squire, a
spokesman for CyberInvest, a San Diego-based clearinghouse for
on-line trading and financial services. ``It was total chaos for a
moment or two.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem affected the entire industry as investors
deluged brokerages house with trade orders, questions or concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even people trying to reach their brokers with their phones
had trouble getting through,'' Squire said. ``But from what we
hear, things went a lot better this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's troubles have not dented the on-line brokerage
business. According to Taggart, as of July, ESchwab had $132
billion in its on-line trading accounts. Taggart added that on-line
trading accounted for 52 percent of all trades executed by Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's growing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
