<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEN AND NOW, RECIPE GIVES MAYONNAISE THE LAYERED LOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lori Vara writes, looking for a recipe for a layered salad. The
one she remembers included lettuce, mushrooms and peas and perhaps
some grated cheese and egg. It's topped with ``some sort of
mayonnaise dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The original recipe was re-created by the home economists at
Kraft (gotta find more ways to use that mayonnaise). Over the
years, the recipe has evolved and been updated.
</P>
<P>
   The first recipe is very similar to the original. The second
recipe is from the home economists at the Hawaiian Electric Co. and
puts a fusion twist on the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAYERED SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1 head iceberg lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound bacon, crisply fried
</P>
<P>
   1 large sweet onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large cucumber, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   6 ounce package of frozen green peas, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   In a glass bowl, place shredded lettuce. Cover with a layer of
cucumber, then onion, then peas, then mayonnaise. Top mayo with
bacon and cheese. Refrigerate overnight, and serve. Make sure the
lettuce is on the dry side, however, or the salad will get runny
and will not be as good.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 244 calories, 21 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 28 milligrams cholesterol,
376 milligrams sodium, 76 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ISLAND LAYERED SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   1 medium head lettuce, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 bell pepper, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   3 stalks celery, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can water chestnuts, sliced
</P>
<P>
   10-ounce package frozen peas, blanched
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound bacon, cooked and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   4 hard-cooked eggs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Crumbled won ton chips (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Oil-and-vinegar salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   In a large glass serving dish, layer lettuce, bell pepper,
onion, celery, water chestnuts and peas. Sprinkle with the 2
tablespoons sugar. Combine sour cream and mayonnaise; spread evenly
over salad. Combine Parmesan cheese, garlic powder and pepper;
sprinkle over the salad. Sprinkle with bacon, eggs and chips. Cut
tomatoes into wedges, dip in salad dressing and arrange around edge
of the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 418 calories, 35 grams fat, 15
grams carbohydrates, 13 grams protein, 126 milligrams cholesterol,
556 milligrams sodium, 74 percent of calories from fat. Requests:
</P>
<P>
   A reader would like a recipe for an Irish potato cake. She
remembers the cake as being chocolate and including fruit, pecans,
coconut and, perhaps, dates.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader would like to replace a recipe her mother cut
from the Amarillo newspaper about 30 years ago. It's a peanut
butter fudge that includes chunky peanut butter and whole large
marshmallows and is made in an electric skillet.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
