<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPE-ANN-ARTIST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTRAIT OF AN ARTIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKPORT, Mass. _ Harold Rotenberg, 93, applied his opening
fusillade of paint to canvas like a child discovering fingerpaint.
His subject was ``Motif No. 1,'' the fishing shack dressed in bouys
that coaxes artists to this harbor like lobsters to bait.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The building is barn-red. But Rotenberg was attacking with
streaks of cadmium yellows and oranges, brushes splayed and
tortured, paint flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got to start with a gold base,'' Rotenberg was saying, more to
himself than his observer dodging paint. ``With time, the gold will
come through, the painting will brighten, and the picture will only
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in an image, is Harold Rotenberg: time-ripened, determined
to capture on canvas the midday shadows and impatient sunsets that
signal summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   The ratio of artist to linear shoreline foot may be no greater
in Cape Ann than in Marblehead, Newburyport, Small Point, Maine, or
a dozen other New England coastal enclaves that get visually sliced
and diced each summer.
</P>
<P>
   But most artists aren't painters in their nineties whose work
hangs in the Isreali Parliament and Boston Museum of Fine Arts.
Rotenberg _ seemingly tireless, a dreamer, and a backseat driver of
some repute, according to his wife, Charlotte _ is a man who can
expound at length on the colors of air in a shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in his eighth decade in the neighborhood, Rotenberg
agreed to share his perch, opening the door to a favorite hangout
(he tends to save time by closing doors with a much blasphemed
cane). He unsheathed his brushes to look anew at one of New
England's most painted icons, Motif No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick,'' said Rotenberg as he continued splashing first
colors on the canvas, gaze fixed on the horizon, ``is to see and
feel the atmosph...''
</P>
<P>
   He interrupted himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, look at all the air in front of that rock!''
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg lives outside Orlando, but comes to Rockport several
weeks each summer to visit his daughter Judi, a painter and owner
of the Judi Rotenberg Gallery on Newbury Street and the Square
Circle Gallery in Rockport. It was behind the Rockport Gallery, on
a patch of lawn secreted away from the throngs of tourists plying
the area, that the elder Rotenberg was scrutinizing the color of
shadow...
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadows,'' he continued. ``Shadows are as important as the
base tones on a piano.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes into it, his painting was beginning to look _ more
accurately, feel _ like the landscape before him, lobster boats in
the foreground, the granite pier with its grandstanding shack, the
outer harbor cluttered with sailing yachts capped by a granite
headland taking shape in splotches of color, not lines. This was
Rockport, but it was also a painting of 11:22 a.m. sunlight on a
New England day in late August.
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg is the son of an Attleboro clothing merchant who
taught his children the beauty of art and music. Lofty start _ but
it was lust for the sculpted female nudes created by his older
brother Frank that nudged him toward a career in art.
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg attended the Boston Museum School, then, as now,
affiliated with the Museum of Fine Arts, and taught for several
years in the ``settlement houses'' for the poor that were located
in Roxbury, the West End, and the South End. On weekends he would
take the ferry to Provincetown or Rockport, renting a room for $5
weekly and painting landscapes with the 2-inch-wide blade of a
putty knife. Color then, and now, went on in rich globs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color gives form. So all you have to do is add composition,
and you've got a painting!''
</P>
<P>
   Some other Rotenberg truisms:
</P>
<P>
   ``God is so good. I thank him every day, every minute. He pours
in atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to see a painting in a frame. The frame is clothes,
the painting a naked woman. She's more interesting with a dress
on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes two to make a painting. One to apply the paint, the
second to hit you over the head when it's done so you don't ruin
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, since school days Rotenberg has been coming to
Rockport seasonally, and now he and his wife live with Judi and her
family during visits. He is so much a local fixture in his
captain's hat and trim, parted beard that a film crew producing ``A
Love Letter'' the other day paid Rotenberg $40 just to stay put on
a bench while the action unfolded around him.
</P>
<P>
   His fears at age 93?
</P>
<P>
   ``None.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear time, and I thank God for every minute because when I'm
gone, I will miss all of this,'' he said with a hand sweeping the
shadows and sunlight. ``Sometimes I wake up at night and just paint
pictures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
