<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD ON EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Schadenfreude'' is a German word for the undeniably human
trait of taking pleasure in the misfortune of others.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of it going around these days. It's nasty if it's
your misfortune, and can be delicious, in small doses, if it's your
enemy who's on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   If the American government of 10 years ago had been informed
that the Russian government was imploding, Russian soldiers were
begging kopecks for food in the shadow of the Kremlin, the Russian
banking system had collapsed, the ruble was turning to rubble, and
there was no painless way out of the economic calamity visited upon
the nation by ruthless and selfish oligarchs of low morals and
lower intelligence, the White House of that era would have been in
ectasy.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan's crowd feared the Russians above everything, and
quadrupled our national debt in a headlong military buildup that
spawned a 600-ship Navy, more nuclear submarines than we could
possibly use, Stealth bombers at $2 billion a copy, as well as the
infamous $680 toilet seat and the hammer that cost the Pentagon
almost as much.
</P>
<P>
   If you gave Reagan the prostrate plutocracy that is Russia
today, the Gipper and his gang would have overdosed on
schadenfreude. In the Cold War era, which covered most of the
half-century between World War II and this morning, news of a
rubbery ruble, a weakened Kremlin, a toothless Russian Bear, would
have quickened heartbeats and encouraged stock markets in the free
world.
</P>
<P>
   A vast, brooding colossus of a country that had lost 18 million
dead to the Nazis, that had slaughtered much of its own officer
corps and imprisoned many of its finest intellects and artists, was
much to be feared by the West.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes all the more incredible the spectacle of an American
president landing in the Russian capital in the midst of a Moscow
meltdown _ and trying his damnedest to keep his opposite number
from crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Boris Yeltsin is barely functioning. An ailing
alcoholic who behaves erratically, is out of business by lunchtime,
and cannot conduct a meeting for more than an hour, the Russian
president seems to be on his last legs, physically, mentally,
psychologically, symbolically. But there's not even a micro-trace
of schadenfreude aboard Air Force One, or in the clucking of the
camp followers of journalism. Because the US policy of engaging
Russia, defanging Russia, selling stuff to and buying stuff from
Russia, of loaning large sums and promising more, this all worked _
too well.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists used to joke about how the dumb capitalists would
sell them the rope with which to hang capitalism. ``We will bury
you'' was another Cold War yuk. Nikita banging his shoe at the UN
was ludicrous, until he went to the nuclear brink with Kennedy over
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Now that communism destroyed itself, capitalism tried to come to
the rescue. Perhaps not as swiftly and as skillfully as we might
have. But the Russians keep screwing up. Unlike the Poles, who took
their bitter medicine and started to get better quicker, the
Russians have screwed around, and won't do the hard things, like
pay taxes, or obey the traffic rules of global markets.
</P>
<P>
   The US kept prodding the International Monetary Fund to throw
more billions into the furnace, to keep Russia stable. But the
world's Big Five leaders have all got problems. Clinton is hounded
from Martha's Vineyard's pillar to Moscow's post by Republicans
demanding his resignation or impeachment for dallying with a
20-something femme fatale.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's problems are about a thousand times more grievous than
Clinton's, but his Communist majority in the Duma hamstrings any
move he makes. Clinton's conservative Republicans and Yeltsin's
combative Communists conspire to render both men less effective in
time of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Keizo Obuchi is impotent to tackle the bad-bank-loan
hangover that paralyzes the world's second-biggest economy. China's
Jiang Zemin heads a shaky, unelected government of oligarchs who
have just mishandled the worst flooding in decades, with dire
implications for the food supply of one-quarter of the earth's
people. Helmut Kohl faces an election this month that will likely
find him booted out of office. That's the lineup of the world's
five most important economies. Not exactly Murderer's Row.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to stem the sort of panic that caused stock
markets around the world to quake, Merrill Lynch took out full-page
newspaper ads, headlined ``Putting the world into perspective.''
After a tour of the crumbling market horizons, the giant brokerage
firm concluded: ``In all these regions, we believe the markets are
increasingly looking for clear and decisive leadership, and that it
must come from key public policy makers.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no echo of agreement from the editorial pages, or
from the Congress. Clinton's personal conduct with an intern looms
larger in the media than any need for sound elected leadership. The
Republicans won't fund the IMF or give Clinton anything but the
most grudging cooperation. When it comes to Monica vs. monetary
policy, the media and Congress seem to prefer the young lady in the
beret.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
