<HEADLINE>
PRINCESS DI _ A SHOT AT FIRST CELEBRITY SAINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's said that every baby boomer can remember where he or she
was when John F. Kennedy was shot. I have no idea. But I remember
precisely where I was when I learned that Princess Diana had died
in a car crash. My father-in-law mentioned it just before breakfast
on the porch of my wife's lakeside cottage in New Hampshire. We all
thought he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, Diana obtrudes in my daily life. No small amount
of marital tension attended ``our'' decision _ my wife's decision _
to rise at dawn and watch the Westminster Abbey funeral. Though no
fan of Diana's (I've been a Prince Charles man all along, and have
the clips to prove it), I did find the service, crooning and all,
to be quite moving.
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening year, Diana has impinged on me again and
again. I visited Paris this spring and found myself reading
graffiti (why, Alex?) at the makeshift shrine erected near the site
of the fatal crash. And I was the first Globe staffer to obtain the
ceremonial in memoriam Dianae plastic margarine tub released in
England. When I mentioned it in a column, a Globe editor insisted I
show her the actual object, by way of fact checking. And then she
made off with it. Such is life at the Great Metropolitan Newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Now it seems that Diana may be with us ... forever.
</P>
<P>
   Who first bruited the notion that Diana might live on as a
saint? Pope John Paul II dropped a hint last summer in his
condolence message to Queen Elizabeth: ``The Holy Father has
offered prayers summoning her to our Heavenly Father's eternal
love.'' (Uh ... what about the Sixth Commandment?) In his recently
published analysis of women and theology, ``The World According to
Eve,'' Cullen Murphy quotes a feminist theologian saying that
Jesus' mother Mary ``cannot be a model for the New Woman.'' Murphy
notes that ``for a brief period in 1997 it seemed as if the
theological model for the New Woman might be Princess Diana.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. All the signs are there. The hawking of the relics.
The scholastic dispute over the Last Words. The suggestion of
``healing powers,'' put forward on television Monday night by
Diana's socialite pal Lucia Flecha de Lima. The three shrines: the
Alma underpass in Paris, the island at Althorp, and _ yes _
Harrods. The Althorp shrine bears a cross, and the following
inscription: ``Whoever is in distress can call on me. I will come
running wherever they are.'' The Gospel of Mark meets James Taylor
... I dig it.
</P>
<P>
   None of this Diana worship sits well with the Church of England,
of which the late princess was a nominal communicant. Wary of the
``cult'' of Diana, Lord Coggan, the retired archbishop of
Canterbury, condemned Diana's ``loose morals'' and branded her a
``false goddess.'' The bishop of Hull took to the airwaves earlier
this week to announce that ``the Church believes that the dead are
with God.'' The implication being: And they should stay there.
</P>
<P>
   One English publication has even dared to ask the toughest
question of all: Is Diana indeed with God? Writing in Prospect
magazine, a ``theologian'' named Philip Nobile examines her case.
(Can this be my old friend Phil, the former Penthouse editor? The
same! He tells me he made his theology bones at Holy Cross. But I
digress ...) Phil casts a cold eye on Diana's chances: ``The
argument for heaven, is, I am afraid, weak ... even the `cleansing
fires' of purgatory is a long shot.'' Roman/Anglican doctrine, Phil
concludes, ``leaves little room for optimism in Diana's case. But
that tells us more about the chilling core of Christianity than
about the ultimate worth of a young, kind, and sometimes foolish
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Eloquently stated. But it turns out there is hope. There is a
movement called Christians for the Cloning of Christ that wants to
engineer a Second Coming using genetic material from the Shroud of
Turin. So let's bring back Lady Di. For the right price, that
charming brother of hers will be willing to sell some DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Then she _ and we, her public _ can start the fairy tale all
over again. And who knows? Maybe this time she will live happily
ever after.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
