<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY MARKET SHOULDN'T DISCOURAGE RETIREMENT SAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Given the size of the headlines about the sharp
fluctuations in the stock market, it would come as no surprise if
retirement-minded investors like Carol Covington of San Francisco
cowered in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than hiding, she's still as bullish as they come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not shaking in my boots,'' said Covington, a
self-employed curator and art dealer. ``I just feel like if you are
invested in a good company, it is still a great place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tarica, who retired from Chevron Corp. last year at 54,
turned his company stock over to Gary Pollock at Bay Isle Financial
in San Francisco and was out playing tennis Tuesday when some
retirees might have been apoplectic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have faith in our economy that it is not going to tank,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there is nervousness in the land this week. On Monday,
the Dow Jones industrial average _ the leading stock market
indicator _ plummeted 512 points or six percent. Despite a healthy
comeback after Monday's free fall, the market has lost much of the
gains it made this year.
</P>
<P>
   The skittishness explains why retirement plan investors on
Monday moved money at more than 4 1/2 times the normal pace,
pulling about $142 million out of stocks and putting it into
fixed-income investments and cash.
</P>
<P>
   It's prudent, as one nears retirement, to have a conservative
strategy and not be at the mercy of the market, Pollock said. But
the extraordinary range of client requirements and risk tolerance
means there's no such thing as one retirement investment plan that
fits all.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Colette Norman, a librarian at the College of San
Mateo, who is organizing an investment club for herself and about
20 working women, and will be investing for her retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some stocks are still good buys,'' she said. ``We'll start
investing when the market hopefully is on an upward swing.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a discernible level of stock market panic among
people at or near retirement age, it's hard to find. For one thing,
many financial planners have correctly advised clients to make
portfolio adjustments to prepare for market volatility. Few have
heard from any anxious investors in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   Investment adviser Barbara Rosenblum of Rosenblum, Silverman and
Sutton in San Francisco said people should expect occasional
corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every few years you go through these external-driven events,
whether it be Russia or Japanese banks refusing to recognize their
loses or turmoil in the White House. They will pass. Will we have
more pain? Probably. Is this the end of the world? Absolutely not.
Will you feel like a fool a year from now if you sell securities
today? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are talking about long-term taxable money and about
people who need to rely on this money,'' Rosenblum said, ``it is
absolutely gross stupidity to dump out a bunch of stocks and buy
them back a week from now and pay taxes on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollock said investors close to retirement might have
three-fourths of assets in more conservative quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lighten up on small cap. Lighten up on international stocks.
But don't worry,'' he said. ``The broad market is down
substantially from mid-July, but it was the 50 or so largest
companies that came down in the last couple of days that is causing
all this. There is good value out there and I do not see interest
rates or inflation as being of great concern _ and that's two out
of three legs of the market, with corporate earnings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
