<HEADER>
A4999 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-02 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVO, PORTLAND, ORE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. -- In Beijing, Chinese officials are admitting
their environmental mistakes. Clear-cutting timber near the Yangtze
River, they acknowledge, created runoffs of rainwater and huge
floods. As soldiers piled up sandbags, officials issued a formal
apology.
</P>
<P>
   The American habit is not to apologize, but to move on while
correcting past mistakes. In the hub of this continent's timber
industry, Portland today is livable and walkable because the city
undid mistakes, then developed a habit of undoing them.
</P>
<P>
   The 450,000 residents of the nation's 30th largest city, as well
as the almost 2 million in its metropolitan area, are heirs to a
sophisticated land use and transportation policy begun by a native
of Massachusetts, Tom McCall, elected governor in 1966. To save the
Willamette River from environmental depredation, he envisioned
parkways similar to what his grandfather, Governor Samuel Walker
McCall, recommended to the Massachusetts Legislature in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Like his grandfather, McCall was a Republican. In other states,
``land use'' is regarded as a Bolshevik plot. But here the respect
for Oregon's majestic mountains and the mighty Columbia River also
extends to the built environment. Today, thousands enjoy the Tom
McCall Waterfront Park, where cars once roared along a major
highway, blocking off downtown from the river.
</P>
<P>
   In civic design, success breeds success. Portland is planning a
similar park on the west bank, between the Willamette and I-5.
</P>
<P>
   To move people, Portland has invested heavily in mass transit.
The city's new convention center is on the West Side near the
sports arena in the Rose Quarter. Trolley service departs
frequently from downtown and the ride is free. In the summer and
fall, antique open-air trolleys cross the 1912 Steel Bridge, with
commentary from conductors like Frank Weiler: ``Skidmore Fountain,
built in 1888, for man, horse and dog. ... Old Town district, site
of cast-iron and terra cotta buildings from the 1890s.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown's architecture is robustly Richardsonian and
Sullivan-esque. Because land use policy has stymied the bulldozer,
ad agencies are moving into old warehouses in the newly named Pearl
District.
</P>
<P>
   The city is celebrating a new West Side trolley line the way
Boston is anticipating the finish of the Big Dig. ``It's a very big
deal,'' says former Governor Barbara Roberts. ``We have 18 miles of
light rail that run from the city east and we're about to open
another 18 miles going west. It will be one of the most significant
movement of people, particularly during rush hours, that has ever
occurred. Portland is one of those cities that has gotten better
instead of worse. Our growth, instead of destroying the city, has
enhanced the community. The thing that's made the difference is
politicians not being afraid to take on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's triumph has been East Side, West Side and bipartisan.
In seeking federal funding, Les AuCoin, a former congressman,
recalls that the West Side line's ambitions lengthened when he won
a seat on the House Appropriations Committee. A Republican senator
from Oregon already chaired the Senate panel. ``If Mark Hatfield
had to do it alone,'' he says, ``I don't know how short that track
would have been, maybe half the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time this city left a major decision to chance was in
1845, when it was still an anonymous settlement 78 miles east of
the Pacific Ocean. Two New Englanders, Asa Lovejoy and Francis
Pettygrove, flipped a coin for the naming rights. Lovejoy, a
Bostonian, lost and Pettygrove named it after his hometown of
Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Portland takes to heart what Tom McCall said of the
first effort to rescue the Willamette: ``This great environmental
triumph could prove to be a Pyrrhic one if we don't keep the
pressure on. It won't stay clean if we languish in the admiration
of our own handiwork.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
