<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUDIST-RESORT-ART-BOS     09-02 1632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDIST-RESORT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT RESORT ENCOURAGES THE BARE MAXIMUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, Conn. _ Michelle is sitting in a green wooden beach
chair completely as God made her 15 years ago, talking about tan
lines. Or lack thereof. ``We have Teva lines,'' she giggles.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle's feet have the white strips that come from wearing
sandals and nothing else. So do most of the hundreds of undraped
folks, from toddlers to octogenarians, who flock to the Solair
Recreation League's woodsy hideaway at the end of a narrow dirt
road in the state's ``quiet corner'' just south of the
Massachusetts border.
</P>
<P>
   Each summer since 1937, Solair's members, most of whom live
within a two-hour drive, have passed through the big wooden gate,
doffed their clothes and gamboled unencumbered and unabashed among
the resort's 350 acres.
</P>
<P>
   They sun themselves beside the lake and the heated outdoor pool,
working on the nudist's classic head-to-toe bronzage. They hike
along Bare Trail, swatting insects seeking a fleshy feast. They
play volleyball and shuffleboard, they marinate in the hot tub,
they circle their chairs for wine-and-cheese before the Sunday
exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come up here and we have a community,'' says Phil, who
brings his wife and daughter up from New Haven. ``It's almost
secondary that we don't wear clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the whole idea of Solair, which bills itself as a family
nudist resort, is to be naked. Most of the nearly 300 full-time
members, who pay $1,333.50 a season (per couple) are social nudists
year-round, and many belong to the American Association For Nude
Recreation, whose 50,000 members are ``clothed when practical,
unclothed when possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Solair's members will toss on a shirt when they're frying their
breakfast bacon or when their shoulders are burned pink from the
sun, and the women will wear a sports bra on the tennis court and
shorts during certain feminine days. But most of the time they're
nude right down to their sandals, day and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We notice when you're wearing clothes,'' says Michelle, who
has been coming to nudist resorts since she was 4. ``We don't
notice when you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny weekend day, Solair's spacious grounds are filled
with 400 or more bare bodies strolling and lolling, gardening,
paddling canoes, tooling around on golf carts and standing in line
at the canteen for knockwurst-and-sauerkraut sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that you can do clothed, Solair's members do naked,
although they usually sit on towels for sanitary reasons. Bathing
suits actually are banned on the beach, not that anyone would ever
wear them. ``They're nasty,'' testifies Michelle. ``They're sticky,
you get sand in them ... Once you go without, you just can't go
back.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Solair's community (nobody inside the gate has called it a
colony for years) believes that nude is natural. If it was good
enough for Adam and Eve....
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, people forget to put their clothes back on when
they leave,'' chuckles one father, who brings his family down from
Oxford, Mass., every weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the gate, it is easy to forget that the rest of the world
wears tops and bottoms and looks askance at those who don't. So
most of Solair's devotees will happily reveal everything but their
real names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say most of our members are in the closet,'' says Billie
Carlson, a retired ob/gyn nurse and grandmother who serves as
Solair's membership director.
</P>
<P>
   There are still too many bosses, clergy, relatives, and
neighbors who think nudists are a shameless bunch of libertines who
are anything but natural. ``People have been raised to think the
only time you should be nude is to have sex or take a shower,''
Carlson says.
</P>
<P>
   So except for a handful of full-timers like Carlson (``I'm not
ashamed of it'') and her husband, Ed, most of the nearly 700 people
who come to Solair regularly will give only their first names, if
that, to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know lots of people who don't want their last names used, or
don't want any mailings,'' says Butch, an engineer from
Massachusetts who belongs to the community with his wife, son, and
daughter, and says his friends, relatives, and customers all know
he's a nudist.
</P>
<P>
   People on the outside tend to have odd notions of what goes on
inside. ``They think it's one big orgy,'' says a mother, laughing.
In fact, Solair is approximately as erotic as Water Country.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone is naked, the mystery and titillation that come
from concealment vanishes. Every bulge and blemish is out in the
open. Like most nudist resorts, Solair is filled with average
people with average shapes. The American Association For Nude
Recreation estimates that only 5 percent of its members have
``exemplary bodies'' and that a third have surgical scars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pluck 100 random shoppers out of Kmart and defrock them and
you would have roughly the same physical spectrum, from perky to
paunchy, from strapping to sagging.
</P>
<P>
   Solair's members are doctors and housewives and teachers and
policemen and artists and real estate agents. ``We're a
cross-section,'' says Carlson. The folks inside the big wooden gate
aren't much different from those outside. They just go through a
lot more towels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All there was in the beginning was the woods and a lake filled
with leeches and snakes. Solair's pioneers slept in tents, cooked
outdoors, and used a plank and a pail for a toilet. They didn't
bother with electricity until 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first came here there was one light in the whole
camp,'' remembers one member, who joined four decades ago. ``The
shower was two 55-gallon drums on top of the canteen. The first
people in got the hot water, where it was warm from the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Solair is a cooperative ``cottage resort'' whose full-time
members reside in everything from trailers to upscale houses,
throwing on clothes to go out for groceries. Some are snowbirds who
head south once the leaves fall. Others make weekend pilgrimages
year-round, skating and skiing (usually clothed) in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Solair has cabins and rooms and trailers for vacationers, plus
campsites with R/V hookups. A two-story pavilion provides a hot
tub, sauna, rec room, showers, and toilets. A roofed outdoor picnic
area serves as a dining hall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Though the resort has made some concessions to the outside
(such as street signs, so fire engines and ambulances can find
their way around), Solair remains a refuge for those who want to
shed the world beyond the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone asked me, what did you think of the bombing in
Sudan?'' Butch says. ``I had no idea about the bombing. I'd been
here all week.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still an Edenesque innocence to Solair, whose members
seem to assume that the world's stresses, dangers, and temptations
can be shed along with their clothes. Parents let their kids wander
about unsupervised. Teenaged girls stroll nonchalantly past
middle-aged men. ``I'm naked,'' one of them shrugs. ``So, what's
the big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Life inside the gate is casual, unhurried, collegial,
deliberately family-oriented. Parents pull chairs around in a
circle and bring out chips and dips and drinks. Teens, who have
their own rec room, horse around on the raft, shoving each other
into the water. Kids frolic on the swings. Grandmas, some of them
wearing makeup and jewelry, sun themselves by the pool.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The things that go on here are the same things that go on at
any other resort,'' says Phil's wife. ``That isn't something that
people who don't come here would understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Solair offers pig roasts and talent shows and scavenger hunts
and dances. There's even a camp song (``When the weekend comes
around, they all wonder where we run...''), but everyone's
forgotten it.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers are welcomed as kindred spirits _ as soon as they
remove their clothes. ``We follow kindergarten rules here,'' says
one member. ``Get along in the sandbox.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the outside world does not follow kindergarten rules, and
Solair's campers understand that. So prospective members, who must
be interviewed by different members on each of four visits, are
carefully screened to weed out unsuitables.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask them how they got interested in social nudism,'' says
Billie Carlson. ``Have they been to other resorts? Are they
married? Does their wife know? How does their family feel? What's
their idea of what goes on here?''
</P>
<P>
   Solair's members have concluded, some of them from unpleasant
experience, that most outsiders have the wrong idea of what goes on
here. Though pollsters found that 40 million Americans had gone
skinny-dipping (and that was in 1985), most people think social
nudism aberrant, at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``A neighbor's daughter asked our daughter where she was going
for the weekend, and our daughter told her,'' one father says.
``The neighbor wouldn't let her daughter play with our daughter
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   So the members, especially teenagers, are careful about what
they tell to whom. ``I told one friend, and she told people at
school,'' says Michelle, who won't give her real name. ``But I'm
such a good pretender that nobody believed her. `Can you imagine me
going to a nudist camp?' I told them. `Knowing my family? No
way.'''
</P>
<P>
   There is the inside and the outside, Michelle says, ``and you
don't mix the inside with the outside.'' Outside Solair's gate are
those who'll skinny-dip but won't go naked, who can't separate
nudity from sex, who are uncomfortable in their own skins. Inside
are those who have stripped life to its bare essentials. By their
Teva lines shall ye know them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
