<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      09-02 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE JETER'S HEAD; FLIPPING OVER MOVIE WIGS; OD'ING ON RITALIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the eyes of the baseball world are fixed upon the
McGwire/Sosa home-run derby, there's been another riveting hardball
spectacle this summer.
</P>
<P>
   I speak of the extraordinary constellation of talent at the
shortstop position. Has there ever been a trio to match Nomar
Garciaparra of our own Red Sox, Alex Rodriguez of the Seattle
Mariners, and Derek Jeter of the New York Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   In this month's GQ, Peter Richmond tries to get inside Jeter's
head. Richmond finds baseball, and only baseball, there; like
Nomar, Jeter lives for the game, and like Nomar, he is a
less-than-scintillating interview. But that's OK. We can never be
reminded enough that when it comes to athletes, they are what they
do, and being a scintillating interview is not what they do.
Besides, Jeter has other virtues: He doesn't swear (!), he gives to
charity, he signs autographs for anyone who asks, and he insists he
did not, rumors notwithstanding, ever take erstwhile girlfriend
Mariah Carey to a strip joint.
</P>
<P>
   The conceit of Richmond's piece is his admitted attempt to
shoehorn Jeter into his own personal cosmology, which stars the
23-year-old shortstop as the latest in a line of quietly noble
Yankees _ Mel Stottlemyre, Ron Guidry, Don Mattingly _ who act as
counterweights to the man Richmond clearly sees as evil incarnate:
George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond goes so far as to hope that Jeter's innate goodness
will somehow stop the dastardly Steinbrenner from abandoning Yankee
Stadium. It will touch a chord with Bostonians who fantasize about
saving Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the last episode of ``Seinfeld'' was a dud, but hey, so
was the entire final season of the show, so it shouldn't have
surprised anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The best reason to keep tuning in during the sitcom's lengthy
swan song was the sprightly malice Julia Louis-Dreyfus brought to
her portrayal of Elaine Benes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as we prepare to embark on the first ``Seinfeld''-free TV
season in a decade, Louis-Dreyfus is getting on with the rest of
her life. She talks about it in the current issue of Movieline, or
rather, she tries to, in the face of a jarring inquisition by
writer Martha Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   To her credit, I guess, Frankel eschews the puffball questions
and sycophantic stance toward her subject that ensnares most
writers of celebrity profiles. The problem is that Frankel seems to
think that she and her calculatingly ``shocking'' questions to
Louis-Dreyfus are the stars of the story. The effect is simply
annoying, not eye-opening.
</P>
<P>
   Better by far is Joe Queenan's amusing analysis of some of the
more preposterous wigs in movie history. Queenan claims that a
character's wig is a tipoff as to whether he or she will perish
before the movie is over; the worse the wig, the cloudier the
character's future.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Queenan writes: ``One highly noticeable thing in wig
movies is that the characters themselves are often stunned by the
wigs they confront. ...Armed with a disorienting pageboy in
`Richard III,' Olivier is able to befuddle his rivals and seize
control of England just by prancing around and fiddling with his
bangs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Photo celebrates its 20th anniversary with, among other
things, founding editor Sean Callahan's recollection of the last
years of photojournalist Margaret Bourke-White.
</P>
<P>
   A glamorous figure in her prime, Bourke-White was alone,
virtually friendless, and struggling with Parkinson's disease by
the time Callahan was dispatched to her Connecticut house on a
mission of mercy in 1970 by an editor at Life magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The woman known as ``Maggie the Indestructible'' did not ask for
pity. She did accept Callahan's help, however, in finding a way to
use her old photographs as a way to raise money for her medical
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bourke-White had not spent much time exhibiting her
photographs or making fine prints, her old photos were in poor
condition, according to Callahan. He describes the friendship that
grew between them as he helped her assemble her life's work for a
book (``The Photographs of Margaret Bourke-White'') while he
regaled her with tales of ``Eisie'' (Alfred Eisenstaedt) and her
other colleagues at Life. Her speech hindered by Parkinson's,
Bourke-White was forced to communicate with her eyes. The symbolism
is not lost on Callahan.
</P>
<P>
   Though he doesn't say so, it's clear that he and the
compassionate editor at Life may have helped rescue Bourke-White's
legacy for a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The use of Ritalin, a drug for treating attention deficit
disorder, has increased by an astonishing 700 percent since 1990,
much of it prescribed for children.
</P>
<P>
   In a thought-provoking essay in the fall issue of DoubleTake,
Lawrence H. Diller, a specialist in behavioral pediatrics, warns
that our ``obsession with performance'' has led to an over-reliance
on Ritalin as a means of ``medicating away'' shortcomings in
parenting, education, and managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Diller writes: ``To give medication for a condition whose chief
trait is the failure to perform up to one's potential _ or to
manage one's life efficiently _ crosses the line, in my view,
between treating a disorder and enhancing a particular aspect of
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever stood outside a burning building and marveled at
those whose sense of duty propels them inside, you shouldn't miss
Rick Bass's terrific piece on firefighters in the September Men's
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Bass tags along with an old high-school buddy who's now a
volunteer firefighter in Texas. His friend once thrived on
disorder, but now he leaves his house in the middle of the night to
join the fight to restore order from blazing chaos. In describing
the changes in his friend and his own reactions to the ``awful
animal'' of fire, Bass emerges with a story equally rich in
you-are-there detail and psychological insight.
</P>
<P>
   He tells us how the insides of a firefighter's nostrils become
caked with carbon during an especially hot fire, and how the
fragments tumble out of their noses for days afterward. He tells
how firefighters trapped by flames can create a ``water curtain''
by cutting a slit in a fire hose.
</P>
<P>
   But Bass also goes deep into the heart of what makes a
firefighter tick: ``that they yearn, have a need bordering almost
on addiction, to feel life deeply sharply. They also want to do
good, for any of a million different reasons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
