<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-ACZEL-BOS &LR;      09-02 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ACZEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATS PROF FINDS FAME AS A WRITER: WHAT ARE THE ODDS ON THAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.  R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amir Aczel, quiet, 50ish, professor of statistics at Bentley
College, was leading the simple academic life until he decided to
write offbeat books. His clear explanation of how taxpayers can
decrease their chances of being audited by the Internal Revenue
Service _ ``How to Beat the IRS at Its Own Game'' _ sold only
fairly well, possibly because most people think they haven't a
prayer of beating the old, unfriendly IRS.
</P>
<P>
   He was already an established textbook author, but that was
drudgery. ``General nonfiction editors have influence on your
work,'' he summed it up, ``but textbook editors tell you what to
do. Writing general books is much more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   His premise was simple. The IRS uses probabilities to allocate
its scarce resources, betting that audits of certain kinds of tax
returns will turn up more deliquencies than auditing other types
will. And he spelled out what to look for.
</P>
<P>
   Then Aczel wrote another book, a history of the origin and
solution of the most famous theorem (certainly not the most
important, but the most intriguing) in pure mathematics. And
somehow, ``Fermat's Last Theorem'' spent months on the New York
Times bestseller list. It surely was purchased by some people who
would have trouble passing Algebra 101, but who were intrigued by
the mystery of it all.
</P>
<P>
   If you had tried to sell a book about Fermat to a major New York
publisher, it would have been like selling suntan lotion to a
death-row inmate. ``Fermat's Last Theorem'' was published by a
small press house, and its surprising success brought Aczel a New
York-style contract (from Harcourt Brace) for his latest work, a
history of speculation on life in the universe and a short course
in the statistics needed to set up the problem and calculate the
odds.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he didn't set out to write a book about the prospect
of other intelligent life forms in the universe. He wanted to write
a book on polling techniques. He has, on occasion, turned his
business statistics students at Bentley into a polling operation.
``We set up a phone bank at Bentley to predict the outcome of the
'92 election,'' Aczel recalled. They used ``the usual system,
calling random phone numbers in all the states and asking the
person who answers the phone who they voted for,'' he explained.
``But we used a more sophisticated statistical technique to
estimate the margin of error than the commercial pollers do. We hit
it much closer and just as fast as the networks, with a margin of
error of less than 2 percent.'' But nobody wanted a book about
polling.
</P>
<P>
   Quite by accident, Aczel got interested in the techniques of
carbon-dating archaeological specimens. The carbon dates (which
depend on the kinds of radioactive carbon atoms in the sample) are
always expressed as a probability, such as: ``Two thousand years
before present, plus or minus 750 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistic the daters used,'' Aczel continued, ``was not as
powerful as some new ones, and I started recalculating the carbon
dates with a new method _ it happens to be called `bootstrapping' _
and was able to narrow the plus-or-minus by quite a bit.'' And that
got him interested in the island of Santorini, a Mediterranean
caldera, or exploded volcano, with a civilization buried under
volcanic ash, a sort of gigantic Pompeii, and a classic place for
radio carbon dating of everything from food to clothing to human
remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Aczel sighed, ``no one wanted a book on Santorini.'' By
this time, three years ago, he was working with an editor at
Harcourt Brace, whom he had found by walking into a Harcourt Brace
office with a copy of ``Fermat's Last Theorem'' and requesting to
speak to an editor. (Writing is like horse racing; track record is
everything.)
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't want a book on polling, she said `no' on
Santorini.'' What she wanted was for someone to pick up a project
that the late Carl Sagan had started. She wanted a book on the
probability of life out there, and here was Amir Aczel, professor
of statistics. The match was made.
</P>
<P>
   The new book, ``Probability 1,'' due out late this month, very
much resembles ``Fermat's Last Theorem,'' which amounted to a
short, clear, history of mathematics from the Greeks to the French
Enlightenment, before moving on to the proof of Fermat's theory.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Aczel starts with the earliest theories, in the
classical Greek era, that suggested that because there were so many
stars out there, surely there was someone else out there. Then,
just to make sure the reader is following the argument, Aczel
supplies a brief, but believable, history of cosmology, the Big
Bang, the formation of galaxies, solar systems, and the beginnings
of life.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for under a hundred pages. ``I think I am in the habit
of explaining the basics, that comes from writing textbooks, and
teaching introductory statistics.'' But that would appear too
modest, since some very bright people are incapable of teaching
elementary statistics to students. It is a gift.
</P>
<P>
   Having summed up the history of the ideas and the scientific
knowledge of the universe, Aczel turned, under his editor's
prodding, to the statistical part, to calculating the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sum it up,'' Aczel remarked, ``it is pretty simple. If
there are an almost infinite number of stars, which is certainly
the case, then even if the chance of life happening by the random
joining of atoms to make up a DNA molecule, or something that works
like replicating DNA on Earth, is almost infinitely small, it still
works out to be almost certain that somewhere out there is
something intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   As he noted, with every better telescope, we find more galaxies,
each with trillions of stars, so the almost infinite number of
planets around this almost infinite number of stars, even when
multiplied by an infinitely tiny chance of life starting comes to
one. And in statistics, one is unity, one is the whole shooting
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probability 1'' includes a brief history and clear explanation
of the whole idea of listening for a signal from space. Aczel is
kind, but not sympathetic. ``I was intrigued,'' he said, ``that
when the federal government stopped funding the listening posts,
the private donors that came up with the money were all computer
people: David Packard, Bill Gates. I wonder what they thought the
first message from outer space was going to be, an order for a
billion PCs with Windows 98?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he concluded, ``we should worry about this planet. I
would be surprised if they got a signal, ever. And what will we
they do with a signal that's going to be from billions of light
years away, which means it is billions of years old? Not much, I'm
afraid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
