<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNING-BRODERBUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVING A MORIBUND BRODERBUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where in the World is Carmen Sandiego?
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere lately, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the once-popular educational computer game have
languished in the past year as its parent company, Broderbund
Software Inc., lost its way in the competitive field of consumer
software.
</P>
<P>
   But Learning Co. Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., which acquired
Novato, Calif.-based Broderbund and its stable of well-known
software titles this week for $290 million in stock, says Carmen is
going places again.
</P>
<P>
   The company Tuesday outlined an aggressive plan to revive Carmen
Sandiego and the rest of Broderbund's best-known software brands _
a strategy that could help it become a billion-dollar player in the
home software market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always easier to revive a successful brand than create a
new one,'' said Kevin O'Leary, president of Learning Co.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the company's new marketing campaign, ``Broderbund
is back,'' is to return the Broderbund name and its portfolio of
software brands ``to the level of performance that the most coveted
equity in the consumer software industry should have,'' O'Leary
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Carmen Sandiego, Broderbund's best-known brands include
KidPix, The Print Shop, Arthur and Family Tree Maker. But the
company's share of the education software market has declined
steadily over the past few years, falling from 11 percent in 1996
to less than 6 percent in the first half of this year. Sales of its
6-year-old Carmen Sandiego brand have also collapsed. Last year, it
sold 176,000 copies. Through the first half of this year, it sold
only 37,500 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Learning Co. has a proven track record that leads
them to believe it can revive Broderbund's software portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management has demonstrated that they know how to make
acquisitions, especially ones where there is solid content. And
with Broderbund, there are some really solid brand names,'' said
Steven Frankel, managing director of Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Through a string of 14 acquisitions over the last four years,
Learning Co., formerly known as SoftKey International Inc., has
built itself into the nation's largest maker of education software,
with about 33 percent of the market, according to PC Data, a market
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Learning Co. has the size, the scale and the muscle to
boost what really had been the flagging fortunes of the Broderbund
line, and I think we'll see this work out to be a very synergistic
merger,'' said Stephen Fleming, a San Francisco-based analyst with
BankBoston Robertson Stephens. ``I'm very bullish on the outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund's existing brands will get a quick boost under
Learning Co. simply by getting more sales exposure.
</P>
<P>
   As the top maker of education software, Learning Co. can use its
distribution clout to get more retail shelf space for Carmen
Sandiego and the other Broderbund brands, O'Leary said. The company
will also push Broderbund titles through its school and
direct-marketing programs and its international sales channels _
areas where Broderbund has not been as strong.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-quarter of Learning Co's. software revenues are
generated overseas, while Broderbund sells very little
internationally, O'Leary noted.
</P>
<P>
   But the real revival of Carmen Sandiego and the rest of the
Broderbund portfolio depends on how well Learning Co. can mesh its
own software development teams with those of Broderbund to extend
existing product lines.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund had been slow to introduce updated versions of its
most-popular products, which contributed to its decline in the last
year, analysts said. ``They had some good hit products, but they
just got kind of lazy,'' said Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said Learning Co. will accelerate new product
introductions by ``pouring'' popular Broderbund characters such as
Carmen Sandiego into existing technology from Learning Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had to start from scratch every time you created a new
product line, it would be cost-prohibitive,'' O'Leary said.
Instead, consumer software companies can add new characters or
storylines to existing development ``engines'' _ the code that
provides the basic technology on which the game is played.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company can speed development time and
drastically reduce its costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although layoffs are expected as a result of the acquisition,
O'Leary said it was too early to speculate how many people will
lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was completed late Monday, after terms were approved
by shareholders of both companies. The votes were overwhelming,
despite the fact that as a result of Monday's big stock market
plunge, the value of the deal was only $290 million, instead of the
$420 million that had been anticipated when it was first announced
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Tanny, Broderbund's vice president of marketing, took a
philosophical look at the poor timing of the deal for her company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now make our bets with Learning Co. stock and hope that
that goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Learning Tuesday fell 1 5/8 to 16 1/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
