<HEADLINE>
NCAA SAYS LEBLANC AMONG THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER   AND SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Field hockey star Shannon LeBlanc, a graduate of UMass-Lowell,
has been named the Massachusetts winner and nominee for the NCAA's
Woman of the Year Award.
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc, an Amesbury native who now works in the athletic
department at Arizona State, was captain of the field hockey team
at UMass-Lowell for three years and holds the school records for
career points and points in a season. She was also a two-time
Coaches Association Division 2 All-American and a National Academic
all-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in complete shock,'' LeBlanc said in a statement. ``This
is a reflection on UMass-Lowell and its athletic program and
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten finalists will be named later this month, and the winner
will be announced at a dinner in Indianapolis in October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ultimate champions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the ultimate indeed for Boston-based Lady Godiva when it
won the World Ultimate Frisbee Championships last month by
defeating Japan, 19-10, at the National Sports Center in Blaine,
Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been walking around saying, `I'm a world champion!'''
said team member Anne Adams of Concord. ``Not many people can say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who has been playing ultimate since 1980 when she was a
student at Carleton College in Northfield, Minn., was one of 20
women who capped a perfect week for Lady Godiva. The team went 10-0
during the weeklong tournament, outscoring its opponents, 175-59.
Although it has won the last three national championships, this is
the 12-year-old team's first world title and it follows a
heartbreaking loss to Sweden in the final two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had their sights on this goal for two years,'' Adams
said of the victory. ``In the past, the US had been so dominant,
but when we went to Sweden, we found the rest of the world had
caught up. We trained really hard this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams isn't kidding. For six weeks leading up to the tournament,
Lady Godiva practiced six hours a day every Saturday and Sunday.
The payoff, in addition to the team trophy and gold medal she now
has hanging above her kitchen sink, came when she got home after an
eight-day absence for the championships and her oldest daughter, 3
1/2-year-old Sarah, proclaimed, ``Mom, I call you champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Lady Godiva will defend it US crown at the National Ultimate
Championships in Sarasota, Fla., Oct. 22-25.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Attention, soccer coaches
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Are you a soccer coach? If so, check out the lineup for the
Women's Soccer Foundation Coaches Symposium Sept. 13 at Wheaton
College, the day after the US women's national team faces Mexico at
Foxboro Stadium in the first game of the US Women's Cup. Focusing
on teaching coaches how to better train, develop, and inspire
female players, the day will be highlighted by a training session
with members of the national team and their coach, Tony DiCicco.
Marla Messing, president of the Women's World Cup Organizing
Committee, will also speak. For information, call 508-285-5699.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
