<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PRODUCTION-CHIEF-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWEEEPING SHAKE-UP FOR BOEING BRASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In one of the most sweeping shake-ups of top
management in the 82-year history of The Boeing Co., Ron Woodard,
head of the company's ailing commercial airplane division, has been
replaced with one of the company's brightest stars and a favorite
of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Two other top executives in the commercial group, including
Harry Arnold, executive vice president of airplane development,
also are out as part of the reorganization in which Alan Mulally,
now head of the company's defense and space group, takes over for
Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   Several other executives in the commercial group have been
reassigned and still more management changes are expected as
Mulally completes his own team and reshapes a division that caused
Boeing last year to take its first operational loss in a
half-century.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes don't stop there. Boeing's defense and space
headquarters in Kent, Wash., is history, eliminated as the company
formed two new units with separate presidents for each. One group,
for space and communications, will be based in Seal Beach, Calif.
The other, for military planes and missiles, will be based in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization leaves about 200 people at the former Kent
headquarters uncertain about their jobs. Most are expected to end
up in other positions within Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   After denying rumors for months that any heads would roll over a
recurring series of production problems that have battered Boeing's
image, its bottom line and its stock price, Chairman Phil Condit
personally asked Woodard, a close friend, to resign and replaced
him with Mulally, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally is generally considered by those inside and outside
Boeing to be Condit's heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mulally who directed the development of Boeing's 777.
Since that successful project, the 53-year old senior vice
president has gotten high marks while running the company's vast
defense and space business in the wake of last year's acquisition
of McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Condit's face-to-face meeting with Woodard on Sunday came after
Condit and other executives learned of new cost overruns at the
company's commercial operations in Wichita, as well as a reserve to
cover the overruns, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Condit could no longer protect his friend and decided
Wood-ard had to go, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's board of directors met Monday and, with Woodard
present, accepted his resignation. After adjourning, Condit was
silent about the pending shake-up, but announced the board had
authorized the world's largest aircraft maker to repurchase as much
as 15 percent of its common stock in a bid to boost its share price
from its lowest level in more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives then quietly began preparing to officially
announce the development early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have experienced unsatisfactory financial performance with
our commercial airplane operations,'' Condit said in a statement
released before the stock market opened. ``Our expectations are
that commercial airplane operations produce significant,
double-digit operating margins. We concluded there must be
significant changes in the composition of the management team at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said Condit and President Harry Stonecipher would have no
comment other than the official statement.
</P>
<P>
   Stonecipher will take over as the company's acting chief
financial officer while a replacement is sought for Boyd Givan.
Givan, whose ouster was apparently sought by Stonecipher and
announced two weeks ago, officially retired Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old Woodard, who has worked for Boeing for 32 years
and is widely considered one of the world's best airplane salesmen,
has been offered an unspecified job within the commercial group, a
Boeing spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's considering his options,'' the spokesman said. Both
Condit and Stonecipher personally asked Woodard to stay on in the
new position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no expectation that Woodard will take the new job,''
one person close to the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Woodard who told reporters late last summer, when the
production problems were publicly revealed, that Boeing had only
``stubbed its toe'' as it attempted to crank up production to
record levels in the face of airline demand for new planes.
</P>
<P>
   But industry analysts were taken by surprise by the extent of
the commercial division's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Since last fall, Boeing has taken about $3 billion in charges
related to its assembly line production snags, mostly with the next
generation 737.
</P>
<P>
   There have been calls by many analysts for Woodard's head, and
Condit has been under increasing pressure to make a change. But the
Boeing chief executive continued to stand by Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   That changed more than a week ago with the discovery of the new
problems in Wichita. The problem apparently involves ``a
significant number of parts that were not accounted for on a cost
basis,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   The figure could be as much as a couple of hundred million
dollars, but should not change the range of the company's recent
projected earnings, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding another problem might have been the last straw,'' the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street Tuesday, Boeing's shares rose 2 1/8 to close at
33 1/16 as the broader market recovered 288 points from a nearly
513-point drop on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace analyst Wolfgang Demisch of BTAlex. Brown, said Condit
was forced to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholders have suffered brutally,'' he said. ``The company
is responding to the distress of the shareholders and holding
people accountable. But the shareholders don't really care who's in
charge, as long as results are achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Demisch said Mulally is well regarded: ``He has more energy than
any two people I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts also said Mulally was the best person to replace
Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job with the 777 and perhaps he can now bring
that same magic to the entire commercial group,'' said Peter
Aseritis, aerospace analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this like a baseball team. If the team plays poorly,
you can't fire the players. You fire the manager. And Boeing's
commercial team has played poorly the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do any worse, so why not make a change. Boeing has
totally screwed up. They have lost market share. They have
alienated their customers. How much worse can they do? So why not
change managers and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Two executives are replacing Mulally in the reorganization of
the defense and space group. James F. Albaugh will head the new
Space and Communications Group in Seal Beach, and Michael M. Sears
will head the Military Aircraft and Missile Systems Group in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial group, Arnold, who has been in charge of
airplane development, resigned and Dan Heidt, executive vice
president of airplane components, retired as part of the overhaul,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Thomas Schick, Woodard's deputy, was offered another
position in the group. His new duties are still being discussed and
will depend on whether Woodard decides to stay, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In an internal management information bulletin Tuesday, Boeing
said three executives in the commercial group have been reassigned
to a ``special project'' and will report to Stonecipher ``to
develop an easily understood and highly visible management
reporting system.''
</P>
<P>
   The three are Fred Howard, executive vice president of business
resources; Rick Swindler, vice president of finance; and Molly
MacFarland, vice president of human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally's new top management in the commercial group includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Jamieson, who now leads the 737 and 757 programs. He will
have full profit and loss responsibility for the 717, 737, 757,
MD80/90 and MD-11 airplane programs. Dick Pearson, who heads the
Long Beach Division, will report to Jamieson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Morris, who now leads the company's rotorcraft operations
in Philadelphia and Mesa, Ariz., will assume profit and loss
responsibility for the 747, 767 and 777 programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Mitchell, executive vice president of airplane programs,
will have responsibility for airplane components and procurement
activities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Walt Gillette will lead engineering and product development.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Carson, who handled business resources within
Information, Space and Defense Systems, will serve as the
commercial group's chief financial officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
