<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVE TO FIND A WAY TO KEEP DAVIS IN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Think what would happen if you were able to
rearrange the Broncos. Let's say you took them out of Denver, sent
John Elway to the same retirement ranch that Gary Zimmerman is on
right now, scolded Shannon Sharpe for clowning against the Patriots
in 1996, and completed your makeover by dressing the Broncos in the
garb of the sorry Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Quick question: What would you have?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunate answer: A team that would still have Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   We are well past the introduction stage with Davis by now. On
Monday night, the Patriots will play the Broncos for the fourth
consecutive season. The previous three games have had two
consistent themes: The Patriots have been trounced and Davis has
been permitted to run as if he were in his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the stat that tells you the Patriots haven't beaten
the Broncos since 1968. If in our rearranging game we could go back
to '68, the Patriots would win again and again; Davis wasn't on the
planet then.
</P>
<P>
   You would think the following would be a foolish statement: The
only way to stop Terrell Davis is to tackle him. But that remark
makes a lot of sense to Pete Carroll, who has sat in dark rooms all
summer, watching tapes dated Oct. 6, 1997 _ the last time Davis ran
over his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go back and look at that film and there's a lot of
mistakes happening,'' the coach said Tuesday. ``They're subtle
mistakes, where we get cut off on a block and a hole opens up; not
so much assignment mistakes but just physically not being exactly
where we need to be. And (the Broncos) call for you to be very
precise about your positioning and deployment of your defensive
guys. You can't make up for mistakes on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots probably know that better than any team in the
league. Tuesday, Carroll was told that the Broncos are averaging
170 yards rushing in their last three meetings with the Patriots.
After jokingly saying, ``I'll remember to bring that up about the
running game,'' Carroll said the mission is to stop the Bronco
running game. But there's a catch to that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stop it may mean that they get 130,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So can we safely say that Denver is now Davis's team and not
Elway's?
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has a $59 million contract,'' said Chris Slade.
``You'd think he has some say in what goes on around there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Perhaps you have noticed a trace of sarcasm in the
comments of Slade and Carroll. Well, simply put, the Patriots are
annoyed with all the Denver talk. The frustrating thing for them is
that they won't be in a position to silence it _ maybe _ until
Monday night. They also know there is only one way to stop all the
squawking. ``We gotta win it,'' Carroll said. ``That's how you put
it all to rest.'')
</P>
<P>
   Outside linebacker Slade will be one of the men on Terrell
Patrol. He and his teammates know that shutting down Davis is not
like shutting down other great backs. The difference is that the
Broncos run an intricate zone blocking system. Sometimes they go
with the traditional man-vs.-man approach. At others, they will
block an area rather than a man. Davis has the option of running
toward the lane of his choosing. It is the ultimate Door No. 1, No.
2, or No. 3? approach to running.
</P>
<P>
   That's why new starter Chad Eaton believes that the easiest way
to control Davis is to upset the order of the offensive line
because, Eaton says, ``Some of the holes are so big that you and I
could run through them.'' But if commoners were to run through such
a hole, Eaton and Slade and Willie McGinest could floor them with
an arm tackle. Not so with Davis. He is featured in a commercial
that shows him lugging the tire of a sport-utility vehicle around
his waist. Ordinary people don't do that. He doesn't fall to the
turf easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running game is the key,'' Patriots linebacker Ted Johnson
said. ``I've been saying that for three years.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference this year, all the Patriots agree, is that their
defense is better now than it was in October. You will not hear
them talking about any adjustments to Steve Sidwell's scheme. They
do not say anything about needing time to learn and work out the
glitches. They tell you they know what they are doing. They tell
you that they are ready to play. They don't have to tell you the
secret information that is passed among them in team meetings and
on game plans. Loosely translated, the information amounts to this:
Tackle Terrell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
