<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST MASSACHUSETTS FIRMS GAIN GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a day makes.
</P>
<P>
   Most public stocks in Massachusetts followed the market's lead
Tuesday, rallying to recoup at least a part of the ground they lost
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Local banks, like Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston Corp.,
and Internet companies like CMG Information Services Inc. and Lycos
Inc. bounced back with mostly solid gains. Other winners on the
rebound: top shelf high-tech companies like EMC Corp., selected
retailers including Talbots Inc. and a smattering of special
situations.
</P>
<P>
   But there were disappointments too. Some stocks, particularly
those that had been trying to recover from previous setbacks or
uncertainty, continued to sink. Tuesday Polaroid Corp., Learning
Co., and Parametric Technology Corp. all slipped a second day.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a question of how broadly stocks rallied. The
Bloomberg Massachusetts index, which includes many smaller
companies, was up 2.05 percent for the day but advancing stocks
outnumbered losers by barely a 3-to-2 ratio. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index gained 3.86 percent and winners swamped losers by better
than 3-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   The most valuable company in the state, Gillette Co., has
actually come out of this week's early skirmishes ahead of the
game. It advanced 3 3/4 to to 44 7/8 after just a fractional
decline on Monday. But Gillette shares, which have a total value of
$50 billion, have slipped 28.1 percent from their July high in a
market worried about the company's ability to grow in an uncertain
global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts bank stocks were the biggest and broadest group of
local winners Tuesday, recovering at least part of Monday's losses.
Beyond the giants, smaller banks such as UST Corp. of Boston jumped
back.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston actually gained more ground than it had lost on
Monday, but the stock had fallen sharply the previous week on
worries about the company's big business in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   But bank stock prices, which are closely tied to the condition
of the economy, could remain volatile as investors continue to sort
out the impact of emerging markets, interest rates and currency
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are in the economic slowdown camp for 1999, earnings
estimates are too high as of today and there would be pressure on
these stocks,'' said analyst Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Anthony.
``But if the early estimates for 1999 hold up, bank stocks are
cheap today.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Internet stocks, few had been clubbed as hard on
Monday as CMG, an Andover company that invests in start-ups and
helps them grow. Among its success stories: Lycos Inc. and the
recently public Geocities.
</P>
<P>
   CMG was slammed by 23.8 percent in Monday's session because its
future is so dependent on how the stock market welcomes new
Internet businesses it cultivates. CMG's recovery Tuesdaystill left
the stock down 16 percent on the week.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos itself was trimmed by 8 3/16 on Monday but posted one of
Tuesday's best local rallies, gaining back 5 1/16 to 26 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks of every kind had rebounded Tuesday, but
analysts said it might only be a temporary recovery for the
companies known for their boundless promise and paltry profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be characterized as a dead-cat bounce for now,''
said Ullas Naik, a Boston-based Internet and electronic commerce
analyst at First Albany Corp., using the market slang for a brief
stock rebound following a big downturn. ``Right now, it's just a
reaction from the prior day's 500-point (Dow) drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Software services companies, a fast-growing industry that writes
custom programs and provides high-tech support to their corporate
clients, also staged a comeback Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Technology Partners Inc. advanced by 3 7/8 to 36 3/8,
Tuesdayovershadowing Monday's decline of 2 15/16. Keane Inc. of
Boston, down 5 11/16 on Monday, gained back 2 1/8 to 44 1/8.
Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   Many of this week's two-time losers were trying to shake off
problems or doubts. Polaroid, off 7 3/16 to 27 1/8 in the last two
days, is down 44.3 percent so far this year. Investors waiting for
a promised sales recovery read bearish news in Barron's over the
weekend, quoting a Polaroid short-seller.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of software firm Learning Co. have been cut in half since
July as investors worry about slowing demand for the its titles.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric Technology, considered a leader in its software
field, has plunged a shocking 71 percent since it missed earnings
expectations in July. It couldn't buy a break this week, falling in
both sessions by a combined 2 1/32 to 9 29/32.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
