<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-FUNDS-BOS &LR;      09-02 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-FUNDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND HOLDERS STAND PAT, BUT CAST WARY EYE ON MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shaken by Wall Street's gyrations but not moved to
jettison their investments, mutual fund shareholders kept a
generally steady footing Tuesday amid the Dow's rebound.
</P>
<P>
   But by many accounts, fund investors, a driving force behind the
Dow's recent gains, appear to harbor an increasingly wary view of
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Fund companies reported a flurry of calls from worried
shareholders throughout the morning, with phone traffic subsiding
later as the Dow Jones industrial average rallied 3.8 percent after
Monday's 6.4 percent rout.
</P>
<P>
   Many individual investors hastened to shift money from stock
funds into money market or bond funds, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   A few cashed in and withdrew their investments. Others saw a
buying opportunity and picked up funds focused on large-company
stocks that seemed a bargain after the Dow began the week with its
second-largest one-day point drop ever.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Tuesday's rebound, which saw a record 1.2 billion shares
traded on the New York Stock Exchange, appeared to come from
computer-driven trading programs run by professional asset managers
handling money for large institutions, rather than by America's
individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   Institutions were mainly behind Monday's sell-off, too. But so
were smaller mutual fund firms, executives with large stock option
packages, traders who are market makers in particular stocks, and
some individual investors, according to Laszlo Birinyi Jr. of
Birinyi Associates, an investment research firm in Greenwich,
Conn., that monitors trading patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw twice as much selling in smaller trades (of 10,000
shares or less) as in larger ones,'' Birinyi said. Smaller-sized
trades are usually carried out by smaller investors.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund ownership has more than quadrupled in the past 12
years, as the investing boom has brought Wall Street to Main Street
and helped fuel the Dow's rise. More than 47 percent of all US
households now own at least one fund, while the number of equity
and bond fund accounts has tripled over seven years to 135.7
million, according to the Investment Company Institute. With mutual
funds holding at least 19 percent of all US corporate stock, and
individual investors accounting for more than two-thirds of that
total, market watchers care deeply about how average investors
behave during market swings.
</P>
<P>
   But hard numbers detailing fund investors' trading patterns
often take at least several days to compile. As of yesterdsay, many
firms had not yet counted sales of new funds, cash withdrawals from
funds, and transfers of money from one type of fund to another.
Independent tracking firms will not have estimates on flows until
the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a picture is emerging amid anecdotal evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sentiment seemed to be that investors were sticking to
their strategies'' and not cashing out of long-term mutual funds,
Fidelity Investments spokesman Scott Beyerl said. While some
investors switched assets from stock funds into less risky money
market and bond funds Monday and Tuesday, and a few pulled out
completely, Fidelity had taken in more money over the past two days
than it had lost, Beyerl said. Still, Fidelity, the nation's
largest fund firm, pressed into service a record 3,700 staffers
Tuesday to man telephones to take calls from concerned investors
and brokers.
</P>
<P>
   At John Hancock Funds, phone calls increased 35 percent Monday
before subsiding to half that Tuesday. Redemptions were slightly
above average, but exchanges of stock fund assets into safer money
market funds were running six times above average, spokeswoman
Susan B. Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Tuesday's market rebound appeared to have been
fueled by institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   At the Vanguard Group, withdrawals on Monday from the company's
popular Vanguard Index 500 fund had turned into small positive
inflows Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Financial Services reported continued high volumes
of calls from investors after a brutal day Monday, when calls
spiked by one-third. About 500 investors cashed out of their funds
on Monday, while an equal number shifted stock fund money into more
conservative investments.
</P>
<P>
   Redemptions rose 15 percent above usual levels during the last
two days, according to the company. But the company had sold $80
million to $100 million worth of funds a day over the same period,
spokesman Jerry Potts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
