<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-VENTURE-BOS &LR;      09-02 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILLING EFFECT SEEN FOR VENTURE CAPITAL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After five rambunctious years in which entrepreneurs often
boasted of being offered more cash to start up their companies than
they could possibly use, the venture capital business is earthbound
again.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Howard Anderson, the president of The Yankee Group and a
general partner at Battery Ventures in Wellesley, Mass., bluntly
put it:
</P>
<P>
   ``All those companies that end in `-onics' or `-yzx' _ companies
that can't make it through the spellchecker'' _ are going to have
trouble raising capital in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Few among the Boston area's venture capital specialists were
ready to say that the important Massachusetts technology economy is
in imminent trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But amid world financial turmoil and Wall Street chaos, even
optimists among them were admitting the landscape they helped build
along routes 128 and 495, an ever-changing incubator where ideas
grow into companies, is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is basic: Just as the stock market has cooled its
ardor for start-up companies that offer more promise than profits,
so are venture investors taking another look at who will get their
money, and when.
</P>
<P>
   There's still plenty of capital available to back good ideas.
Only the best ideas, however, are going to get that money in coming
months and years. Investors who once had money burning holes in
their pockets are examining proposals more critically. And those
who have been hit hardest have less left to put into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel investors'' _ people who have made millions on earlier
high-risk investments and have enjoyed plowing their profits back
into similar ventures _ are now raising their standards. ``Those
folks probably have gotten hit the most'' in the recent downturn,''
said Robert J. Crowley, executive vice president of the
Massachusetts Technology Development Corp., a venture fund.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, young companies, already embarked on business plans
that count on raising needed cash through public stock offerings
within two or three years, are finding fewer bidders.
</P>
<P>
   High on this list are Internet-based companies, which often can
develop their software cheaply but need big doses of money for
marketing programs that are still slow to deliver revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But with the market's recent gyrations, this crowd, long
accustomed to battling among themselves for investor interest, now
faces new competition as share prices in dozens of still-promising
companies that went public between 1995 and 1997 have fallen to
half or frequently less, than their offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Venture fund managers that know bargains when they see them are
actively shopping for the best of these _ diverting funds that
might otherwise put into early-stage start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, often outspoken where others pull their punches, said
a prolonged market downturn could be especially damaging to a
Massachusetts economy that depends heavily on a continuing stream
of new companies developing and exploiting new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are the new kid on the block, unless you've got
something that is very good, the venture funds are going to say
`take a hike,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Following a year that saw $12.7 billion in venture funds plowed
into hundreds of startup companies nationwide, Anderson said the
venture capital industry now expects to invest no more than $12.5
billion in 1998, and about the same in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there will be about one-third fewer start-ups next
year,'' he said. And scores of other companies that might have been
expecting second-round or third-round venture financings to
continue their work ``are not going to be able to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all will fail, he added. Some may be able to sell out to
either competitors or better-heeled companies, in the same way that
West Coast telecommunications companies have been snapping up
Massachusetts startups to build their own empires.
</P>
<P>
   Even entrepreneurs who prove themselves strong enough to grow on
their own may still have to pay an additional price to get the cash
they need, by ceding more control to their investors.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies continue to be the most vulnerable in
this arena, said R. John Fletcher, chief executive at Fletcher
Spaght Inc. of Boston, because they typically generate almost no
revenues during the several years that it takes to develop their
products.
</P>
<P>
   Many venture specialists see rough waters ahead also for
Internet-based companies, which over the past two years have ranked
alongside telecommunications companies as the fastest growing
technology industry sector in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet deals are going to have to show more promise of
revenues'' before they can count on venture capitalists for help,
said Crowley, whose fund gets its money from both public and
private sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those companies make a great story, but behind them are a lot
more traditional investment opportunities, (firms) where people are
trying to build sustainable companies,'' Fletcher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (downturn) has been a wakeup call,'' says David Barry,
senior editor at The Private Equity Analyst, an investor
newsletter. ``Venture capitalists and companies thinking of going
public had better be sure their ship is in fine shape when they do
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Anderson: ``This is going to sort out the wheat from the
chaff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
