<P>
   RUSSIA-CLINTON _ MOSCOW _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
wrapping up a two-day summit with President Bill Clinton, said
Wednesday that his politically paralyzed nation is determined to
stay the course to democracy and a free economy. Clinton held out
hope for expanded western investments but emphasized ``there is no
short cut'' for Russian reform. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LEWINSKY _ MOSCOW _ Eight time zones from Washington and
behind the thick Kremlin walls, President Clinton could not shake
``Monica-gate.'' Clinton broke his silence on the Monica Lewinsky
scandal to tell the world he had said enough about his mistake and
had no plans to make a formal apology. ``I have acknowledged that I
made a mistake, said that I regretted it, asked to be forgiven,
spent a lot of valuable time with my family in the last couple of
weeks and said I was going back to work,'' Clinton said in response
to a question at the closing press conference of his summit with
President Boris Yeltsin. Braced for the questions he knew would
come, Clinton and his White House staff sought to use the world
stage of the U.S.-Russian summit to present the president as a man
too busy to worry further about the controversy that has dogged him
for seven months and raised the possibility of his impeachment.
(Holmes/Deans, Cox News Service). (With Washington reaction).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 6 p.m . EDT. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-GROOVE _ MIAMI _ Angered about a comment linking Haitians
to AIDS in a popular summer movie, Haitian-Americans are pushing
for a boycott if they don't get a public apology. In the movie,
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' the main character has an
affair with a Jamaican. When her two sisters question her about it
later, one asks if he used a condom ``because those people have a
history of AIDS.'' The other says ``No, that's Haiti, Miss
Manners.'' Haitians say the dialogue has unleashed painful memories
of a time when the U.S. government branded Haitian-Americans as
AIDS carriers and barred them from donating blood. What hurts
Haitians even more is that the film was written and directed by
blacks. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 3 p.m. EDT in both the (i)
International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-JAMAICA _ KINGSTON, Jamaica _ ``Crime's so bad they'll
cut off your arm to get their hands on a nice watch,'' the American
businessman sitting next to me on the airplane warned. It was an
ominous beginning to the start of a four-day trip to Jamaica, an
island that's long conjured up images of peaceful beaches and
picturesque waterfalls. But there was nothing peaceful or
picturesque about the Jamaica I encountered. Driving into the
capital of Kingston from the airport I passed children in tattered
clothes. liquor stores no bigger than closets, and slums that
reminded me of the worst parts of Haiti. Later I learned that
Jamaica, the largest English-speaking island in the Caribbean, is
on the verge of economic collapse. Experiencing an astounding three
years of negative growth rates, Jamaica's economy is performing
worse than any other economy in the hemisphere, even Haiti's.
(Emling, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TUTU-QA _ Q&AMP;A with the Rev. Desmond Tutu on South Africa's
experience with the Truth and Reconcilliation Commission and what
he plans to do at Emory University. (Graham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SERBS _ Muslims aren't the only Bosnians refugees who have
resettled in Atlanta. There are Serbs here as well. Last week, a
Serb who lives in the metro area was accused of having tortured
Muslims and Croats during the war in the former Yugoslavia in 1992.
There are two groups of Serb refugees in the United States. Some
are married to Muslims - being in a mixed marriage makes them
targets for persecution. Others are Serb refugees who were forced
out of the Krajina region of Croatia by Croatian soldiers in 1995.
The Serbs in Belgrade wouldn't take them and instead sent them to
Kosovo, where they are now fleeing. Local resettlement agencies say
Serbs and Muslims live here together peacefully now, but that may
be because they don't ask each other too many questions. (Kurylo,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
