<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO PRAISES MEXICO'S ECONOMY DESPITE SETBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A tired, dour-looking President Ernesto Zedillo
urged Mexicans to stay the course and accept his financial and
economic reforms during his fourth state of the republic message.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, there was little good news in Zedillo's speech,
which lasted nearly 100 minutes Tuesday night, and the president
rarely was interrupted by applause in the crowded federal Chamber
of Deputies, where he asked Mexicans to continue working to ensure
a brighter long-term future.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his brightest news was that the economy managed to grow
by 5.2 percent despite a year in which oil prices fell by more than
30 percent; world financial markets were rocked by crises in Asia
and Russia; and Mexico was hit with unprecedented natural
disasters. Oil counts for nearly 40 percent of Mexico's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo devoted more time to his controversial bank bailout
program than to any other topic.
</P>
<P>
   The bailout would commit public funds to buying up nearly $62
billion in bad bank debt, staving off what Zedillo termed an
imminent collapse of the Mexican banking system.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has been bitterly attacked by opposition politicians
and faces a rocky road in the upcoming legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has foreseen and informed you that the actions
necessary to return the banking system to health necessarily imply
substantial costs,'' Zedillo said during his televised speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an enormous cost if you take into consideration the
other uses to which the resources could be put. But with
everything, the cost we foresee is less than the result of allowing
the collapse of the banking system, or simply of having acted
slowly and indecisively,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said the federal government didn't have a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only responsible path was to take the measures necessary
to resolve the banking problems, as high as the political costs
might be to the government. I did it and I don't regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 3 million Mexicans turned out to vote Sunday in a
non-binding referendum on the bank bailout plan. The referendum was
sponsored by the center-left Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Early results released by the PRD Monday showed that less than 1
percent of those voting supported Zedillo's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The center-right National Action Party, or PAN, has proposed an
alternative plan it says would lower the bank bailout's cost to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Zedillo seemed to hint at a willingness to
compromise, saying: ``I am confident that with the proposals
presented by the federal government and the political parties
represented in this congress we soon will have a legal mechanism
that will provide the security our banking system needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said falling oil prices prompted three rounds of budget
cuts during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's federal budget counted on a world oil price of more
than $15 per barrel, he said. Instead, that price has plummeted to
just over $10 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to 1997, more than $3.5 billion will be lost; in
short, about 1 percent of our anticipated gross domestic product in
1998,'' Zedillo said. ``We chose to confront the price drop by
adjusting our spending measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Global weather patterns slammed Mexico hard during the past
year, Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Pauline devastated Acapulco and the coast of Oaxaca
last October, killing hundreds and causing billions of dollars in
damage to roads, housing and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The unpredictable El Nino weather phenomenon caused record
droughts in most parts of the country, killing livestock and
cutting harvests. Parched watersheds caught fire and millions of
acres of forest and brushland were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the bad news, harsh economic reforms adopted after
the December 1994 peso crisis are paying off, Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment and inflation are down, while economic growth is
up. More workers than ever before now are covered by social
security health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 15 largest economies of the world, ours had the second
highest growth rate of gross domestic product,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   But while Mexico's economic underpinnings are sound, the country
still is subject to a shaky global economy that is unlikely to
stabilize in the foreseeable future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo predicted Mexico's economic growth would slow to a rate
of about 4 percent for 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must build so that the next president has the conditions to
continue improving Mexico's future,'' said Zedillo, whose term ends
in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
