<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, Sept. 3, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-DISCRIMINATION (Seattle) Jesse Jones is black; his
superiors at The Boeing Co. are white. Those are two undisputable
facts. Much of the rest is uncertain in a federal court battle
between a black manager and The Boeing Co. that is set to go to
trial in Seattle on Sept. 15. Jones earns $84,000 a year _ a fact
that might make many Americans, most of whom make less than that,
think that he has little to beef about. But he says he has been
shunned by his colleagues, sidetracked into a job he does not want
(director of disaster preparedness), and told by high executives
that his belief he is a victim of discrimination is not real. He's
angry. He wants vindication. Profile of Jesse Jones discrimination
case against Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS-WATTERS (Kirkland, Wash ) This is the week Ricky
Watters goes back to Philadelphia, where he was a Pro Bowl running
back with a reputation for being selfish. It started with his first
game for the Eagles.
</P>
