<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5078 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-COLD-WAR-     09-02 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-COLD-WAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW NASTY FACTS ABOUT OUR MILITARY TOXIC WASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The ecological consequences of the Cold War are extremely
severe. And in terms of deserving the blame, the United States and
Russia share the winning ticket.
 &HT;    Moreover, both our countries, believing that such matters
involved national security, kept this information very secret until
recently.
 &HT;    I have looked at the geography of the post-Cold War toxic waste
sites. I have looked at the fact that military industries are still
operating. I have concluded that the challenge to curb the new
dumping and clean up the old waste is enormous _ economically,
politically, geographically and otherwise.
 &HT;    In the United States, the Rocky Flats Arsenal near Denver,
Colo., has stored for 30 years 125 types of toxic waste. Nerve gas
and pesticides were also processed there. The site has been called
``the most polluted square mile on earth.''
 &HT;    In Dover, N.J., the ground water in one toxic site has more than
5,000 times the permitted levels of trichlorethylene.
 &HT;    Russia has even worse locations. Since 1952, near Lake Karichai
in the Urals, liquid wastes were stored and eventually spilled, and
traces of the waste are now found in the Arctic Ocean thousands of
miles away.
 &HT;    In the Urals, by 1988, thermal energy produced by toxic waste
had resulted in the evaporation of an entire lake. A total of 120
million curies of radioactive waste, two times that released in the
Chernobyl accident, were released. Now that lake has been covered
with a thick layer of concrete.
 &HT;    According to ``Russia's National Interests and Security
Problems,'' a study conducted in 1995-'97 by the Gorbachev
Foundation's Center for Global Programs, of about 100,000 hazardous
production facilities, at least 1,500 nuclear and 3,000 chemical
facilities are particularly dangerous.
 &HT;    In Russia, according to the study, ``the total land area subject
to possible chemical contamination is about 300,000 square
kilometers, with a resident population of about 54 million people.
The most hazardous area is Russia's central region, where 16
million people live in zones subject to potential danger.''
 &HT;    It reports that among the sources of potential environmental
danger, Russia's nuclear complex facilities are of particular
concern. And of equal danger to the accumulated radioactive waste
are the enriched uranium and plutonium from nuclear weapons and
nuclear fuel.
 &HT;    Furthermore, it states, an additional factor to take into
account ``is the radioactivity absorbed by the biosphere from
nuclear tests, accidents and the operation of the nuclear complex.
Most of the highly active waste is concentrated in the regions of
Chelyabinsk and Tomsk Oblasts and Krasnoyarsk Krai.
 &HT;    ``Our scenic harbors host a serious threat posed by spent
nuclear fuel in the reactors of decommissioned nuclear submarines.
At least 75 such submarines are afloat in harbors, with the fuel
still inside. The expenditure needed for modernization,
retrofitting and decommissioning of such equipment could be as high
as 15 percent to 20 percent of Russia's gross national product,
which the country's economy would not be able to afford.
 &HT;    ``An additional threat could be posed by industrial terrorism as
a result of heightened sociopolitical tensions and criminalization
of society, as well as unauthorized tampering with hazardous
facilities during ethnic conflicts.''
 &HT;    These are the extreme examples, but we can also look at the
troubling situation in the former locations of U.S. military bases
in West Germany and old Soviet bases in East Germany.
 &HT;    Clearly the toxic legacy of militarism and the arms race has the
potential to affect _ and already does affect _ the health and the
lives of millions and millions of people.
 &HT;    And as to the environmental challenge beyond the military toxic
legacy?
 &HT;    We know that 1 billion people lived on earth at the beginning of
this century. Today we are perhaps 6 billion people. Imagine the
pressure that is exerted on the resources of our planet, on the
environment, on the biosphere. The pressure is already affecting
the earth's capacity to recuperate.
 &HT;    Moving into the 21st century we have to change our ways of doing
business. Our laissez-faire economic systems are based solely on
the profit motive _ and this does not take into sufficient account
the needs of a healthy society and the environment.
 &HT;    Moving toward the 21st century we must find a way to live in
harmony with nature. We need more modesty in consumption and an
aggressive attitude toward cleaning up the outcome of our past _
and ongoing _ environmental avarice.
 &HT;     c.1998 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
