   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Sept. 3:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA SUMMIT MEETING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUMMIT (Moscow) _ Ledeall: Clinton and Yeltsin conclude
summit meeting; other developments. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OPPOSITION (Moscow) _ Clinton meets with Russian
opposition leaders and others. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Moscow) _ Clinton comments on his Monica
Lewinsky speech. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-GENOCIDE (Arusha, Tanzania) _ A U.N. tribunal
investigating mass killings in Rwanda hands down its first guilty
judgment, convicting a small-town mayor on nine counts of genocide
and crimes against humanity. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-SECURITY (Washington) _ U.S. embassies gird for a
possible new round of terrorist attacks. The embassy in Kuwait
warns that it may be the target of a bombing. Embassies close in
Ghana and Togo. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-SINN-FEIN (Belfast) _ A day after declaring its
commitment to ending violence in Northern Ireland, Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army, announces it will
cooperate with efforts to plan ways to disarm paramilitary groups.
By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-POLITICS (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ Malaysia's Deputy
prime minister, who is also finance chief, is dismissed after
months of disagreeing with the prime minister on economic policy.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-UNREST (Jakarta) _ After two days of fierce riots and
looting in the troubled province of Aceh, Indonesia's military
halts its withdrawal of troops from the region. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., the Dow industrial average was
up 106 points, the Nasdaq index up 48 points. Overseas, prices rose
4.2 percent in Hong Kong and closed almost unchanged in Tokyo. They
increased 1.9 percent in Frankfurt and nine-tenths of 1 percent in
London. On the American debt market, at midday he long bond was off
2/32 point, with the yield at 5.35 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   BANK-LOSES (New York) _ Chase Manhattan says it expects to take
a $200 million charge for losses in Russia and Asia. Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette says it earned about $40 million before taxes
during the first two months of the third quarter, after taking into
account losses in Russia. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-BROKERS (New York) _ Looking at the brokerage stocks. By
Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-HEDGE-FUNDS (New York) _ The hedge funds' August
performance. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-SMALL-TOWN (Marshalltown, Iowa) _ Revisiting the town
where investors were gleeful as they played in the stock market
earlier in the year. They are a bit less gleeful now, but most say
that declines have happened before and the market will come back.
In fact they are not on the edge of their seats. There is more talk
about McGwire's home runs and Clinton's troubles than about the
markets. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-COMPETE (Undated) _ The competition increases among
pharmaceutical companies that make drugs for the treatment of
breast cancer. Zeneca and Genentech today hope to receive FDA
approval for their products, Tamoxifen and Herceptin, which could
be big sellers and deal a blow to Eli Lilly's Evista, an
osteoporosis drug that the company wants to have approved as a
breast cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   See also SCI-BREAST-TAMOXIFEN and SCI-BREAST-HERCEPTIN listed
below.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-TAMOXIFEN (Undated) _ Advisers to the Food and Drug
Administration are expected to weigh in today on whether to
recommend that healthy women take the drug tamoxifen to prevent
breast cancer later in life. The drug, tamoxifen, made headlines
last spring when the National Cancer Institute declared it could
help prevent breast cancer in women at high risk of getting the
disease. But in July, British researchers reported that they found
no protective effect in several thousand women who took tamoxifen.
By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-HERCEPTIN (San Francisco) _ An FDA advisory panel is
expected to approve Herceptin, a monoclonal antibody, for treatment
of breast cancer. The drug, made by Genentech, would be beneficial,
officials say, for the estimated 30 percent of breast cancer
patients who have a defective gene called HER2/neu that makes their
cancer aggressively spread through the body. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   See also DRUGS-COMPETE, listed under Financial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-STRIKE (Minneapolis) _ Both sides in the Northwest
dispute have put on national advertising campaigns in an effort to
win sympathy. Many people in Minneapolis side with the pilots
because they are mad at Northwest for a variety of past sins. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FIRES (Los Angeles) _ The California fire season _ made
worse by unusually high temperatures, dry conditions and an
abundance of tall grass that came with El Nino _ has begun with
dozens of wildfires that have charred 34,000 acres of brush and
destroyed 39 homes.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-STORM (Panama City, Fla.) _ Gulf Coast residents cleared
out Wednesday as an unpredictable tropical storm shifted course and
careered eastward, growing from a distant threat to a sudden
danger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER (New York) _ President Clinton will be
back in New York for a major fund-raiser _ a Sept. 14 gala at ``The
Lion King'' for an anticipated $3 million _ and many Democratic
candidates here are not happy. Not only does the event compete with
the Democratic candidates for dollars, but it falls on the eve of
the primary and is sure to distract attention from the candidates.
By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARKET-IMPACT (New York) _ The stock market decline is
worrying some people in the commercial and residential real estate
industries.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GOV-DEBATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Democratic candidates for
Governor debate.
</P>
