<HEADER>
A5121 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-WATTERS-     09-02 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-WATTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHERS WONDER WHICH RICKY WATTERS WILL SHOW ON SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's first down and the Seahawks hand the ball to Ricky Watters.
There he goes: signing autographs, doing charitable work, joking
with the media, heading toward the end zone, gathering momentum and
adulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro Bowl running back appears to be a likeable man with a
sense of humor and urgency who also has the tools of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   But everywhere he has been, it always reaches fourth down in the
figurative football game. Occasionally, he picks up the necessary
yardage. Too frequently, he gets stuffed at the line and fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday in a wonderfully ironic development, Watters' new
team takes on his old one when the Seahawks visit the Philadelphia
Eagles at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The story line will evolve that afternoon, but the intrigue is
already here. After rushing for more than 1,100 yards in each of
his three seasons in Philadelphia, you would think Watters will be
embraced upon his return, hailed for his contributions, mourned
like a passing hero.
</P>
<P>
   But he will be welcomed back like Shawn Kemp was in Seattle, the
boos and cheers in a pick-em battle over which are more audible.
</P>
<P>
   ``People either hated him or loved him,'' said Joe Altomonte of
WIP, the sports radio station in Philadelphia. ``One guy would say:
`How could you want to get rid of the best player on the team?'
Another guy would say: `This guy sucks. He runs his mouth. Let's
get rid of him.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception?'' said Seahawks linebacker Darrin Smith, who
played with Watters last year in Philadelphia. ``I'm not sure what
it was. I don't think it was positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Try to get a handle on Watters. He is a football at Husky
Stadium in November, slippery and bouncing all over the place. The
truth is more elusive than Watters in the open field.
</P>
<P>
   Perception and reality are oftentimes opposites. With Watters,
they collide.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be a person who means well, talks a good game and
usually backs it up. But then Watters blazes off on an unusual
tangent, prompted by his extreme competitiveness, fiery nature and
healthy ego. He is a big beautiful backyard that requires a lot of
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   For this combustible mix, the Seahawks paid Watters $13 million
for four years, hoping he will produce chunks of yardage instead of
copy for the tabloids. They prefer explosiveness between the
sidelines and nowhere else. It would seem a naive belief that could
be altered as early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In his very first game for the Eagles in 1995, Watters showed up
as the ballyhooed player who helped the 49ers win the Super Bowl
the year before by scoring three touchdowns against San Diego. He
left Veterans Stadium as a loser in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay beat the Eagles 21-6 and Watters was widely ridiculed
for his flippant response afterward. On a pass play across the
middle, Watters did not stretch out to try for the reception,
fearing head-hunting repercussions from a defensive back. He could
have said he made a mistake and really should have laid himself out
and taken one for the team.
</P>
<P>
   But Watters ran a politically incorrect route, essentially
saying he didn't want to kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``For who? For what?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an endearing moment. The next day the Philadelphia
Inquirer ran a headline: ``Watters' debut a big disgrace,'' and
columnist Bill Lyon wrote: ``It was the most graceless, clueless,
classless debut by a professional athlete in Philadelphia in
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Watters apologized two days later, but no one remembers. The
most surprising thing was that the play contradicts Watters'
essence. He normally works hard, even in practice, driven by his
ambition to win.
</P>
<P>
   Watters figures the best chance his team has to win is if the
ball is in his hands. In some circles, that colors him selfish. In
others, it makes him a team player. With Watters, there is
continually a point-counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a highly productive guy and a great player, but I have a
problem with a guy who gets 1,300, 1,400 yards and acts like he
does it by himself,'' said Arizona linebacker Eric Hill two years
ago. ``He's so self-centered, when things go wrong, he's the first
to blame everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is being a winner,'' Smith said. ``Micheal Jordan
never turned down a game-winning shot. It's the same feeling Ricky
has when he wants to get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently it is an overwhelming feeling. During those years
with the Eagles, Watters touched the ball more than anyone in the
league and yet it was not enough. The situations and plays weren't
right. That led to friction between Watters and offensive
coordinator Jon Gruden, now the Raiders' head coach.
</P>
<P>
   On his weekly TV show, Watters criticized Gruden. During one
game, he made an obscene gesture from the sideline to Gruden in the
pressbox. There was tension between a player and a coach,
divisiveness on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of last season, Watters' role was further
reduced. He became one of three backs in a rotation also featuring
Charlie Garner and Duce Staley. In the last eight games, he nearly
rushed for 100 yards against Cincinnati and Atlanta but was more
apt to trudge for 48 yards on 20 carries like he did against
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the banged-up and otherwise marginally talented offensive
line. But it was legitimate to question Watters too. The Eagles did
not want him anymore. The scuttlebutt is that Watters, never
possessing tremendous outside speed anyway, might be through at 29,
an occasionally over-ripening age for tennis players and running
backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People questioned his ability at the end but never his
heart,'' Altomonte said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Eagles and 49ers initially, the Seahawks are infatuated
in the early stages of the relationship. They see him running out
plays in practice, offering leadership, counseling younger backs
Ahman Green and Michael Black.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very emotional person. That's part of why he's a good
player. He has a passion for winning,'' said offensive coordinator
Bob Bratkowski. ``I can't say anything negative about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratkowski said the Seahawks ran thorough background checks and
made an interesting discovery in the Eagles locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all to a man said: `I want him on my team,''' Bratkowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet in 1996 when he led the NFL in yards from scrimmage with
1,855, the Eagles selected him third in the vote for team offensive
MVP behind Irving Fryar and Ty Detmer.
</P>
<P>
   Watters' new teammates notice nothing but a warm handshake in
the preliminary bouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't brought any of the baggage everybody said he would
bring,'' guard Pete Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. Or maybe, as has been known in the past, Watters
appears and then his bags arrive on the next flight, spilling all
over the concourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have matured,'' Watters said. ``(But) I'm still the same
person. I still want to win. I still want the ball in my hands in
clutch situations. ... I'm not going to come in here and be some
prima donna. Like `I'll only do the job if I have the ball.' I'm
going to do the job all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Watters discussed his years in Philadelphia at training camp but
is now tiring of the topic, declining an interview. He will rehash
the Eagles' years one more time for everyone's consumption this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In Cheney, Watters said that Sunday's game is just one on the
schedule, not more significant than another. He doesn't know why
the Eagles did not want him anymore nor does he care. Regrets? For
who? For what?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5128 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-DISCRIMINATION     09-02 2678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DISCRIMINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL BRINGS BOEING RACIAL ISSUES TO HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jesse Jones is black; his superiors at The Boeing Co.
are white. Those are two undisputable facts. Much of the rest is
uncertain in a federal court battle between a black manager and The
Boeing Co. that is set for trial in Seattle on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' case, the first to go to trial in what now number dozens
of discrimination complaints against the aerospace giant, will test
not only whether he was discriminated against, but also whether the
company did enough by destroying the power clique behind his ill
treatment that Boeing owes Jones nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Jones earns $84,000 a year _ a fact that might make many
Americans, most of whom make less than that, think that he has
little to beef about. But he says he has been shunned by his
colleagues, sidetracked into a job he does not want (director of
disaster preparedness) and told by high executives that his belief
he is a victim of discrimination is not real. He's angry. He wants
vindication.
</P>
<P>
   His supervisors at Boeing ``did not call me a black jelly bean,
but they certainly treated me like one,'' wrote Jones in a 1996
memo to John Warner, senior vice president. He refers to an
incident that year at Texaco Inc. in which a tape of a high-level
meeting contained remarks that some found to be racist, though
others interpreted as innocuous. The Texaco tape led to the
intervention of affirmative-action campaigner Jesse Jackson, and a
$176 million payout by Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has now taken up the cause of Jones and other African
Americans in two additional lawsuits against Boeing. Jackson has
secured a meeting with Boeing Chief Executive Officer Phil Condit
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones spent half an hour with Condit in September 1996. He
remains unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing says in a prepared statement, ``We believe Jesse Jones
has been treated fairly and equitably.'' The company concedes that
in Jones' department, security investigations, ``distinct cliques''
pitted former FBI agents against non-agents. The department had
``organizational problems.'' There was ``endemic poor
communication.'' Boeing tackled these problems by moving the key
people out, including Jones' opponents (the FBI ``clique'') and
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   To the company, it was a problem that needed to be fixed. ``We
believe it has been fixed, and without regard to race,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Jones sees the chain of events as injustice against him _ and
that Boeing managers, by fixing an organization without taking
sides in the conflict that damaged it, defaulted on the
responsibility of moral judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they admit that there is a racial problem at Boeing?'' he
asks. ``In 1998? Not in this lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's attorney, Lawrence Hannah of Perkins Coie, argues in
court papers that Jones is trying ``to litigate his life story at
Boeing.'' Jones is offering ``a universe of allegations and
laments,'' Hannah says, that ``transform unexceptional workplace
occurrences, speculation and conjecture into an epic far exceeding
the sum of its parts.''
</P>
<P>
   An epic it is. To Jones, the moral of it is that, in Boeing
management, ``you've got to be white.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is from Fort Worth, Texas. When Jones was 7, just after
World War II, his father left, and Jones was raised by his mother.
He was the first person in his family to graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   According to his statement to the court, Jones' first career was
as a military policemen in the Army. He served two years in
Vietnam, for which he was awarded a Bronze Star and a Purple Heart.
In the 1970s he earned a bachelor's degree in law enforcement and a
master's degree in human relations. In 1979, when he'd finished his
20 years and qualified for a pension, he left the Army and accepted
a $22,000 job as a security investigator for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was the only African American security investigator in the
Puget Sound shop, and would remain so. Jones says that in the 18
years he was in the department _ fewer than a dozen investigators _
all other investigators or managers were white except for a
Polynesian he hired.
</P>
<P>
   Jones advanced in his career during that time, but not at the
pace he felt entitled to. His bosses repeatedly reached outside his
unit and promoted people over him _ always white men, and usually
former FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Jerry Femling, a former FBI agent, was hired as an
investigator. In 1990 both Femling and Jones were promoted, but
Femling was placed over Jones. Jones testified later that Femling
``harassed and threatened'' him. In 1993 Femling proposed in a memo
``that Jesse Jones be removed from his present position as manager
of Puget Sound Investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was not ousted, but he was awarded no more increases in
his base salary, $69,150, for several years. In 1994, Femling
retired.
</P>
<P>
   Femling's replacement was John Fulks. Fulks had been Jones'
subordinate; he became Jones' boss. Jones resented that. Fulks and
the boss who promoted him, Richard Blay, are both ex-FBI men, and
white.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1995, Fulks evaluated his new subordinate, Jones,
as ``excellent'' in most categories. ``Jones is very enthusiastic
and gives 100 percent to every task he is assigned,'' Fulks wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Jones thought he deserved Fulks' job. He also wanted the glamour
assignment of protecting Boeing executives on foreign trips. In
1995 he applied for a passport. But Jones was kept home. Boeing, he
concluded, did not want its executives guarded by black men. His
superiors explained it a different way. Foreign assignments weren't
glamorous, and Jones, who is married with five children, had given
them the impression he didn't want to leave town. Blay would later
testify, ``Because of my responsibilities as director, I felt
obliged to go on such trips. I also had occasion to use John Fulks
because of his FBI experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, Jones filed a formal complaint of
discrimination. He did not file it with the federal or state
governments, but with Boeing's internal equal employment
opportunity office. Where he filed it would turn out to be crucial
because of legal time limits on going back to prosecute
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing began an investigation. Jones says he thought its aim was
to uncover the wrong, and right it. Viola Keith, then Boeing's head
of affirmative action, says in a deposition that a Boeing lawyer
told her he expected Jones to sue, and that the purpose of the
investigation was ``to provide legal advice to Boeing management.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was managed by in-house attorneys and
conducted by Boeing's internal equal employment opportunity staff.
In May or June 1996, Wally Alder, Boeing vice president for support
services, told Jones that ``the investigation found no
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1996, Boeing's human resources department conducted
a second investigation. It also found no discrimination, Boeing
said.
</P>
<P>
   That month, Jones met with Condit, Boeing's chief executive, for
half an hour. ``It felt good being in there with the man,'' Jones
would later say. Condit asked Michael Stewart, vice president for
employee relations, to look into Jones' complaint and resolve it.
Boeing's attorneys would later argue that Condit had little to do
with the issue and was ``akin to an innocent bystander.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1996, Fulks completed his annual evaluation of
Jones. The subordinate who in 1995 had been ``excellent'' and
``very good'' in all categories was in 1996 ``adequate,'' ``poor,''
and ``very poor'' in all categories.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was beginning to boil over with indignation.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 24, 1996, memo to Keith, he had asked only that the
company adjust his base salary for missed raises, and watch that he
suffer no more discrimination. But on Sept. 18, after the meeting
with Condit, Jones asked Stewart for a promotion, a pay increase to
$90,000 and ``$500,000 for the way I was treated.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 10, 1996, he wrote Stewart, ``it took me involving Phil
Condit in order to receive some respect, and still nothing has
happened.'' He wrote, ``My new demand is $1 million and counting as
long as these incidents of retaliation continue.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 29, 1996, he wrote to the senior vice president, Warner,
and upped his demand to $5 million. In a second memo to Warner,
Nov. 14, he compared his case to the ``black jelly bean'' incident
at Texaco Inc. ``The difference being that I have not gone to the
media nor have I informed Jesse Jackson,'' he wrote. ``I do not
plan to sue Boeing, unless all negotiations break down, and then
all bets are off. I will continue to fight for all people of color
in this company.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 8, 1996, Jones wrote to Warner, ``If our negotiations
fail, I will sue this company and I will win. I think you know
it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 13, 1996, he wrote, ``The new settlement price is $6.5
million. It will continue to go up!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stewart, the vice president delegated to handle the
case, sent his lieutenant, Clark Nebeker, to reconnoiter Jones'
department, security inestigations. On Dec. 20, 1996, Nebeker
reported that morale was ``extremely low'' and that employees were
polarized into ``camps'' _ the Jones camp and the Blay-Fulks camp.
``In the short time that I've had to look at this, I cannot
determine which side carries more credibility,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart presented Boeing's decision to Jones in a meeting in
January 1997 and followed it with a letter dated Jan. 22. Blay
would retire from Boeing. Fulks would be transferred to Florida.
And to Jones he wrote, ``It is also essential to reassign you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones had a choice of a job at disaster preparedness with a
$6,350 raise to $77,500, plus a tax-free payment of $25,000, or he
could retire with a package worth $238,000.
</P>
<P>
   The $238,000 was not a settlement offer. Jones could still sue
the company _ but he could not keep his job in security
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Jones protested in writing. The security investigations
department was his career, and he wanted to stay there. But he took
the job in disaster preparedness _ and passed up the $238,000.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also stated in his letter to Jones that Boeing had found
the security investigations department ``a dysfunctional
environment.'' But he added, ``As we discussed, Boeing's
investigation did not confirm your allegations of racial
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Was that correct? In October 1996, Boeing had retained attorney
Gloria Flentje of Foulston &AMP; Siefkin, Wichita, Kan., to report on
Jones' allegations and whether he had a legal case against the
company. Flentje's report, like the two before it, was to be for
Boeing eyes only. But somebody photocopied it and mailed it to
Jones. It arrived at his home with a little sticker that said, ``A
gift from Blay.''
</P>
<P>
   It sure wasn't from Blay. Who it was from, Jones says, is still
a mystery. ``Somebody cared about me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jones gave the report to his attorney, John Sheridan of Sherrard
&AMP; McGonagle. Boeing attorney Hannah went to Judge William Dwyer and
tried to have Sheridan booted from the case for using a ``purloined
document'' as a ``road map'' to sue Boeing. Dwyer let Sheridan
stay, but ordered all copies of Flentje's report be given back to
Boeing. Sheridan had to tell the court everyone who had read it,
and each of them had to sign an agreement not to tell anyone what
was in it.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones knows exactly what Flentje concluded. He had her report
in his hand, he says, when he asked Stewart ``point-blank what was
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said Boeing's investigations had uncovered no
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Keith, Boeing's affirmative action officer, heard Stewart's
answer. When Sheridan asked her in depositions whether Stewart had
lied, Hannah instructed her not to answer the question. Since then
Keith has said publicly that Boeing lied and that there was
discrimination found by the company, though she would not comment
for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Keith is no longer working at Boeing. While still on Boeing's
payroll, she has been assigned to work at the Urban League in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless her,'' Jones says. ``It was brave what she did.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannah didn't have any hesitation, however, about letting
Stewart answer whether he had lied. ``I did not lie to Jones, at
that meeting or otherwise,'' Stewart said in his deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a lie for Stewart to say that Boeing had found no
discrimination? No, argued Hannah. It was a statement about what
Boeing found, and what Boeing found ``was determined by Boeing, not
by Flentje.''
</P>
<P>
   What Boeing found is what management concluded, not necessarily
what its attorney's report said.
</P>
<P>
   In its written statement to the press, Boeing stated: ``In the
course of three EEO reviews, the company never found any instances
of racial discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   But what did Flentje find? In his latest filings with the court,
Sheridan now argues that Boeing can no longer keep the report as a
privileged document, because the company is using its claim of
privilege to cover up lies made under oath.
</P>
<P>
   On April 18, 1997, Jesse Jones sued The Boeing Co. and Blay,
alleging racial discrimination, retaliation, negligent infliction
of emotional distress, outrage and defamation. When asked to
provide a list of actionable incidents, Sheridan listed 58 of them.
</P>
<P>
   But by waiting until he did to file a federal complaint, Jones
may have ruled out his most promising claims. Under the federal
statute of limitations, Jones cannot collect damages for actions
before May 2, 1996; under the state statute, not before April 18,
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial promotion of Fulks over Jones happened 3{ weeks
before that, on March 24, 1994. Judge Dwyer ruled that the jury can
decide whether the Fulks promotion can be considered, but he also
ruled that most of the earlier claims cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Why had Jones waited? ``I'm not a lawyer,'' he says. ``I didn't
know about the statute of limitations. The company just kept
saying, `Have patience; we're working it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer narrowed the case, throwing out a number of claims,
including that Boeing has a racially hostile work environment.
Jones had planned to call consultant Maria Root to testify on
institutional racism. Root, who earns $250 per hour for her court
appearances, has given testimony in cases involving Boeing, Seattle
City Light, Crescent Foods and the J.C. Penney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing attorney Hannah has asked the court to exclude her.
``Based solely on Jones' untested anecdotal allegations,'' Hannah
argued, ``Root stands prepared to label Boeing a racist
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer's ruling focuses Jones' case on more specific incidents _
things that qualify as ``adverse employment actions.'' Jones has to
show that in these actions he was treated differently than people
of other races. Boeing has to explain why it treated him
differently. Jones then has to prove that Boeing's explanation is
factually incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   There is no law against promoting an underling over someone's
head. It happens all the time. There is no law against an FBI
clique. There is a law against a white man's clique.
</P>
<P>
   Which was it?
</P>
<P>
   Boeing says it was an FBI clique and a non-FBI clique. Boeing
fixed the problem, it says, by bringing in a new director from
outside the company. ``Tough action'' was taken with Jones'
superiors, the company says. ``The head of security was encouraged
to take early retirement, which he did, and another senior manager
was transferred across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Jones got a raise, and now makes $84,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jones doesn't accept that. ``The company says it's not race;
it's cronyism. Call it discrimination and retaliation. Call it
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, Jones says, he was a white guy, and all the guys
promoted over his head, who got the plum assignments and benefits
for which he was better qualified, were black. ``I would have an
excellent reverse discrimination charge,'' he says. ``The white
community would support me all the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
