<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5133 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINT-HNS &LR;      09-02 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINT: PROLIFIC AND PERFECTLY SATISFYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This summer I gave in to the mint dominating our
herb garden. Instead of cursing the aggressive plants as they
enacted hostile takeovers of small pockets of soil set aside for
basil, oregano and thyme, I decided to embrace the mint, one sprig
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The results have exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed primarily until now as a traditional accompaniment to
Easter lamb, mint now rates as one of my favorite herbs.
</P>
<P>
   What I have learned, through modest experimentation, is that
mint is a wonderfully versatile herb, one that bestows a unique
personality to fruits, grilled vegetables and seafood as well as
traditional meat dishes.
</P>
<P>
   When I have told friends about some of the different ways I'm
using mint, they tend to look perplexed. No small wonder. Mint is
an herb that grows like a weed, dominating any garden space into
which it is introduced. Besides being both prolific and predatory,
though, mint is also underappreciated and underused.
</P>
<P>
   Few restaurants (except for those featuring Greek, Indian or
Thai cuisine) or home cooks take advantage of the many ways in
which mint can be utilized to make a piquant marinade for fresh
vegetables or as a savory counterpoint to the tartness of lemons
and limes.
</P>
<P>
   Mint is also among the hardiest herbs in colder climates. It is
one of the first plants to awaken each spring, climbing toward the
sun far sooner than most of its brethren. And it is one of the last
of the summer bounty to depart, providing a full four to five
months to experiment with its many uses.
</P>
<P>
   So let us praise Mentha viridis, an herb that should be valued
as dearly as basil or thyme.
</P>
<P>
   It is an herb with a rich and enticing history. In Ancient
Greece, Athenians believed mint to have the aroma of strength, and
they would rub leaves over their arms to bolster their endurance.
Peppermint oil was mentioned by Aristotle as an aphrodisiac, and
the use of wild mint by soldiers of Alexander the Great was
forbidden because he felt it so aroused them erotically that it
took away all desire to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Arabs have also used mint for centuries, partaking of mint teas
as a social drink as well as a virility stimulant. The familiar
after-dinner mints evolved from the ancient custom of concluding
feasts with a sprig of mint to soothe the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Most fresh mint found in supermarkets, like the mint running
amok in my garden, is spearmint. It is a lightly hairy type of mint
with long leaves, less strong and overbearing than peppermint.
</P>
<P>
   Walk along almost any country road, though, and you're sure to
encounter one of its nearly identical cousins, field mint.
</P>
<P>
   For medicinal purposes, particularly soothing teas, the variety
utilized is peppermint.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recipes that showcase how mint can enhance
different dishes:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED EGGPLANT WITH MINT MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves four)
</P>
<P>
   Two medium eggplants, cut across into one-half-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   One and a half cups mint marinade (see below)
</P>
<P>
   Two tablespoons chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Place the eggplant slices on paper towels and sprinkle with the
salt. Let drain for 30 minutes. Rinse and pat dry. Place the
eggplant in a bowl. Reserve one-third cup of the marinade and pour
the rest over the eggplant, turning to coat it well. Set aside no
longer than 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat a grill or broiler. Grill or broil the eggplant until
browned and tender, about 5 minutes per side. Divide among four
plates, drizzle with the reserved marinade and sprinkle with mint.
Serve.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MINT MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   (Maked three-quarters cup)
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   Two teaspoons chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   One-and-a-half teaspoons dried basil
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarter teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine the olive oil, red-wine vinegar, white wine, mint,
basil, oregano and salt and pepper in a bowl and whisk.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROILED RED SNAPPER WITH MINT
</P>
<P>
   (Serves four)
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarter cup mint marinade
</P>
<P>
   Four red snapper fillets, about eight ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen whole fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Pour the marinade into a large, shallow
baking dish. Put the snapper in the pan and lay four mint leaves
over each fillet.
</P>
<P>
   Broil until the snapper is just cooked through, about eight
minutes. Transfer the fillets to four plates and spoon the marinade
over the top. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PASTA WITH FRESH TUNA AND MINT
</P>
<P>
   (Serves four to six)
</P>
<P>
   Six tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   One large onion, peeled and cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half pounds tomatoes, peeled, seeded and coarsely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   One pound fresh tuna, cut into one-half-inch thick steaks
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Three garlic cloves, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   One pound penne rigate
</P>
<P>
   Place four tablespoons of the olive oil and the onion in a large
saute pan. Cook over low heat until the onion is tender, about 10
to 12 minutes. Add the tomatoes and salt and pepper to taste. Cook
over medium heat, partly covered, until juices thicken and a sauce
forms, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the tuna into one-half-inch dice. Season with salt and
pepper to taste. Place the remaining two tablespoons of olive oil
in a separate medium-sized skillet. Turn up heat to medium, add
tuna, and toss until tuna is cooked on the surface but still pink
at the center.
</P>
<P>
   When the sauce has thickened, add the tuna, mint and garlic, and
cook for an additional two to three minutes, or until tuna is just
cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the penne in abundant salted boiling water until al dente.
Drain the pasta well. Place in a serving bowl. Add the sauce and
toss gently. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRESH LEMON MINT MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup finely chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Two teaspoons grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   In small saucepan, combine sugar and lemon juice. Bring to a
boil, stirring constantly. Cook and stir until sugar dissolves.
Remove saucepan from heat; cool about 10 minutes or until
completely cooled. Stir in mint and lemon peel.
</P>
<P>
   Pour mixture over fresh fruit, such as cantaloupe, honeydew,
kiwi fruit, peaches, nectarines, plums and/or strawberries;
refrigerate until serving time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
