<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-GROOVE-0903-COX     09-02 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-GROOVE-0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OUTRAGE ERUPTS OVER 'STEREOTYPICAL' REMARK IN POPULAR SUMMER
MOVIE
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Haitian groups are outraged over what they call a
derogatory remark that links Haitians to the AIDS virus in the
popular summer movie, ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more disturbing, they say, is that the movie was written
and directed by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed and I feel betrayed by the
African-Americans who are involved with the movie,'' said Marie
Declama, who heads the Association for Haitian-American Development
in Atlanta. ``The remark was totally unnecessary and it only brings
back painful memories for the Haitian people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, 40-year-old divorcee Stella, played by actress
Angela Bassett, has an affair with a young Jamaican man. When her
two sisters press for details, one asks if he used a condom
``because those people have a history of AIDS.'' The other sister
interjects ``No, that's Haiti, Miss Manners.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is based on the best-selling novel by Terry McMillan,
who co-wrote the screenplay. The Haiti-AIDS reference was not in
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Haitians say the remark rekindles the stigma attached to
Haitians years ago when the U.S. government branded them as
potential AIDS carriers and barred them from donating blood.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration removed Haiti from its official
list of high-risk AIDS carriers in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Jocelyn McCalla, executive director of the New York-based
National Coalition for Haitian Rights, was one Haitian who
protested the federal ban on blood donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assumed Haitians were prone to the virus,'' he said.
``This movie brings back a lot of the pain for me.''
</P>
<P>
   McCalla said that he's(CQ) afraid young African-Americans
celebrating McMillan's success will accept the notion that Haiti
and AIDS are synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, whether it be on black-oriented radio, in coffee
shops, or even on the Internet, Haitians this week are trying to
figure out how to respond to ``Stella.''
</P>
<P>
   Some groups have called for a public apology from 20th-Century
Fox, which released the film. Others have asked the studio to
remove the reference from further releases of the film on video and
in foreign markets. Still other groups have pushed for a boycott of
the movie altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Haitians recently gathered at a music store and agreed
to launch a petition drive. In midtown Manhattan, a picket line was
planned outside the Sony Theater on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to mobilize Haitians in Atlanta to write 20th-Century
Fox, and to do anything else they can to protest,'' Declama said.
</P>
<P>
   She said between 7,000 and 10,000 Haitians live in the Atlanta
area.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for 20th-Century Fox declined to comment on the
issue Wednesday. A publicist for McMillan said the author also
would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ken Boodhoo, an expert on Haiti at Florida
International University in Boca Raton, Fla., agreed that the
movie's remark was a callous one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attitudes are stereotypical whether they're white or black,
but it does hurt to know that blacks were involved with this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1443EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
