<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5180 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-HNS &LR;      09-02 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS KREMLIN NEWS CONFERENCE HE `REGRETS' AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton, standing next to Russian President
Boris Yeltsin at a Kremlin news conference, on Wednesday defended
his expression of ``regret'' last month for his sexual relationship
with Monica Lewinsky and said it was intended to extend ``to all
who were hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake; said that I
regretted it; asked to be forgiven; spent a lot of very valuable
time with my family in the last couple of weeks and said I was
going back to work,'' Clinton said, his voice resigned and his mood
somber.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he was ``quite encouraged'' by what he said
was the favorable reaction of the American people and world leaders
to his remarks on Aug. 17, just hours after he testified before a
federal grand jury investigating the alleged sexual relationship
with Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and the cover-up of the
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's acknowledgement of a relationship with Lewinsky that
was ``not appropriate _ in fact it was wrong'' came after seven
months of public denials by the president, his wife and White House
aides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I misled people, including even my wife. I
deeply regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Kremlin, Clinton was asked about the tone of his speech
on Aug. 17 when he didn't apologize and instead lashed out at
independent counsel Kenneth Starr, who is investigating the
Clinton-Lewinsky relationship for evidence of perjury, subornation
of perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it (the speech) the other day again, and I thought it
was clear that I was expressing my profound regret to all who were
hurt and to all who were involved and my desire not to see any more
people hurt by this process and caught up in it,'' Clinton replied.
</P>
<P>
   As he has previously, Clinton sought to portray the Lewinsky
affair as a private matter to be worked out within his marriage to
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do my best to continue to go through this
personal process in an appropriate way, but to do my job, to do the
job I was hired to do,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming Starr, Clinton said he believed the ongoing
four-year, $40-million inquiry ``had consumed a disproportionate
amount of America's time, money and resources, and attention and
now continued to involve more and more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``All I wanted to say was I believe it's time for
us to now go back to the work of the country and give the people
their government back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin news conference with Yeltsin was the first
opportunity for reporters to meet with Clinton since his Aug. 17
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., who accompanied Clinton aboard
Air Force One as a member of the official U.S. delegation,
upbraided Reuters White House correspondent Laurence McQuillan for
asking one of the two questions about the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an American I'm outraged,'' Hoyer, a member of the House
Democratic leadership, told the veteran White House correspondent
who had asked Clinton whether he felt he needed to ``offer an
apology'' and whether he wished the tone of his Aug. 17 address had
been different.
</P>
<P>
   His Kremlin comments represented his third attempt in 17 days to
put the White House sex scandal to rest and quell a political
controversy that imperils his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   During his vacation last month on Martha's Vineyard, Mass.,
Clinton interrupted his family retreat to visit a church and tell a
predominantly black audience that he was ``having to become quite
an expert in this business of asking for forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said then that he had learned during the controversy
that he had to ``forgive those we believe have wronged us'' before
he could ``ask for forgiveness from people we have wronged.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a former Bush administration Justice Department official
and federal appeals court judge, is expected to report his findings
to the House of Representatives by the end of the month. House
Republicans are gearing up to weigh Starr's findings to determine
whether an impeachment inquiry is warranted by the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In his Aug. 17 address, Clinton lambasted Starr, accusing him of
steadily broadening a court-approved investigation into the
Clintons' failed 1978 Whitewater land scheme in Arkansas into a
wide ranging probe of White House operations and his private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to stop the pursuit of personal destruction and the
prying into private lives,'' Clinton declared. ``This has gone on
too long, cost too much and hurt too many innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had declared in a Jan. 17 deposition in Paula Jones'
$700,000 civil sexual harassment lawsuit that: ``I have never had
sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright in Little Rock, Ark.,
issued an order Tuesday that she would release the misleading
deposition on Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Wright wrote in a one-sentence footnote to her decision that she
had ``concerns about the nature'' of Clinton's deposition in light
of his subsequent admission that he did ``not volunteer
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said her court ``makes no findings at this time regarding
whether the president may be in contempt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
