<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     09-02 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Oh, just shut up
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, the Indiana Republican who behaves as a kind of
personal moral scourge of Bill Clinton, has alerted constituents to
expect an egregiously ugly story about his personal life in Vanity
Fair magazine. Vanity Fair has interviewed several hundred friends,
relatives and associates, and Burton has apologized in advance for
whatever the magazine will have to say about him. Burton suggests
Clintonite poltroons at the root of his problem. Not much of a
surprise there.
</P>
<P>
   Affronted Clintonites and Vanity Fair scoff at the allegation.
What do you expect them to do? There is no reason to rejoice or go
all crestfallen about Burton's plight. Burton once called the
president a ``scumbag.'' That is his right, but it is at a level of
discourse akin to heaving your breakfast into a howling gale.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people around Congress are probably feeling pretty
vulnerable these days. Their sins are presumably no greater than
most American families learn to tolerate and shut up about. But
that is the problem with setting a high moral tone for others.
There is nothing more delicious than gossip about gossipy
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports indicate that the Burton stuff is mostly the tale
of a lengthily troubled marriage. This may bring off the almost
impossible trick of turning Dan Burton into a sympathetic figure.
Didn't work for Bill Clinton, but, what the hey, it's worth a try.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
