<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEENS KNOW ABOUT POP CULTURE BUT NOT CONSTITUTION
 &HT;    560&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More American teenagers can name all Three Stooges
than know the three branches of government, a witness told a Senate
subcommittee on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At a appropriations subcommittee hearing, Philadelphia Mayor
Edward G. Rendell released a national survey showing a predictable
gap between teenagers' grasp of pop culture and their knowledge of
the U.S. Constitution. Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 25 percent knew the Constitution was written in
Philadelphia but about 75 percent knew that 90210 was the zip code
of Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nearly three of every four of the surveyed teenagers knew that
the Vice President is Al Gore, while nearly nine out of every 10
knew that the male star of the movie ``Titanic'' was Leonardo
DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Three of every four teens knew that Bart Simpson lives in a
cartoon Springfield, but only about one in 10 knew that Springfield
(Ill.) was the hometown of Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Only about 2 percent knew that William Rehnquist is Chief
Justice of the Supreme Court while nearly 95 percent knew that Will
Smith played the Fresh Prince of Bel-Air on TV.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About one in five knew there are 100 U.S. senators, while more
than four in five knew there are three brothers in the Hansons
musical group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't view these poll results as an indictment of our
teens,'' cautioned Rendell, recalling that a similar survey a year
ago found that only about 5 percent of American adults could
correctly answer 10 basic questions about the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the surveys and for Rendell's testimony is to
raise money for a $210 million National Constitution Center to be
built in Philadelphia. The mayor is seeking $65 million, spread
over three installments, in federal funds. The museum would tell
the continuing story of the so-called living document in which the
founding fathers set up a government at the Constitutional
Convention of 1787 and through which the nation has operated ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has included a total of $20 million for the project
in its FY 1999 Interior and Education budgets but the House has not
funded the Center. ``It's a continuing battle,'' conceded Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., chairman of the subcommittee and author of
the original1988 legislation authorizing the National Constitution
Center (NCC).
</P>
<P>
   Specter expressed outrage that some of his colleagues had called
the project ``pork.''
</P>
<P>
   With the bulk of the funding coming from private donors and
state and local governments, Rendell said supporters are aiming for
a groundbreaking ``on the first Constitution Day of our third
millenium, Sept. 17, in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Expected to draw 1 million visitors a year and to connect online
with classrooms and virtual visitors around the world, the center
would change the results of future surveys on constitutional
knowledge, the backers testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no surprise to us that teens know more about pop culture
than the Constitution, but it is shocking that the gap is so
wide,'' said Joseph Torsella, the NCC president. ``Ironically, it
is the very essence of the Constitution that enables such a vibrant
pop culture in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide telephone survey of 600 Americans between the
ages of 13 and 17 was conducted in August by Luntz Research Company
and has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the other findings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nearly 60 percent could name Three Stooges (Larry, Moe, Curly
Joe and Shep) while 41 percent could name the three branches of
government (executive, legislative and judicial).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  While 35.5 percent could recite the first three words of the
Constitution (''We the People), 72.2 percent knew the three letters
(www) that follow ``http'' in Internet website addresses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Just over half picked the century (20th) in which women
obtained the right to vote but more than 9 in 10 knew the band that
celebrates ``girl power'' _ the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Only 1.8 percent knew that James Madison is considered the
Father of the Constitution, while 58.3 percent knew that Bill Gates
is considered the father of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  However, more teenagers (90.8 percent) knew that 18 is the
minimum voting age for president than knew that you have to be at
least 17 to see an R-rated movie without a parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  While about one in three knew that Newt Gingrich is Speaker of
the House, nearly 9 in 10 knew that Tim Allen is the father in TV's
``Home Improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
