<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
CAN AMERICA PRACTICE WHAT IT PREACHES ON MORALITY? (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asha was trying to force me to take a bite of her candy.
</P>
<P>
   I was busy reading and thinking what I might say about this
thing causing my heartache. So I turned away from the red, wet
lollipop and, in that voice I use in response to annoying behavior,
said to my little girl: ``Please, Asha.''
</P>
<P>
   When she finally gave up, she turned to bounce out of the room
and said, ``I love you, Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   With my head still buried in James Baldwin's ``The Devil Finds
Work,'' I managed to mumble, ``I love you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, she turned back, looked at me and said, ``Oh,
yeah? Prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, I knew this thing that had taken hold of me. For
weeks, I'd been trying to decide what to make of the constant and
diverse chorus of voices talking about morals and morality.
</P>
<P>
   At no other time in history have I seen so many people willing
to dissect and debate the morality of others. Part of me believes
this is a good thing. But I worry about what seems to be a
recurring problem in our judgment: a tendency toward simplicity and
contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, an anonymous reader called the other day to take
exception to a column I wrote about two teen-age mothers who were
denied admission into the National Honor Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, there should be no rewards for pregnant unmarried
teen-agers,'' she said. ``It's the parents' fault for not putting
those children on birth control. Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The call ended there, and I wondered later if she were sorry for
disagreeing, or sorry for what seemed to me a contradiction. Was
she suggesting that it's OK for teens to be sexually active as long
as they avoid pregnancy?
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this again last Sunday, as I sat in church
listening to a guest minister tell the story of the prophet Elijah.
Afraid for his life, Elijah had sought refuge in the mouth of a
cave, when the Lord came to him and asked, ``What are you doing
here, Elijah?'' It was the same question God asked Adam in the
Garden of Eden after Adam and Eve ate the forbidden fruit: ``Adam,
where art thou?''
</P>
<P>
   As the preacher pointed out Sunday, this was not a question of
either of their physical locations, but rather where they were in
their relationship to God. Where are you morally, Elijah? Adam?
America? Prove it.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of all the scandal, the rape and murder and lies that
saturate our lives and our newspaper headlines, and wondered how it
is that, with all the talk about morals, we find ourselves in such
a wretched place.
</P>
<P>
   Now my daughter had transported me with a simple question into
the darkness again, and I realized I'd missed an opportunity to
show my love for her. In effect, to prove the God in me.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Asha returned. This time, I closed my book, set
it down on the table in front of me and gave her my undivided
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Still bouncing, she asked if I'd sell the items from the
brochure she'd brought home from school ``at your work.'' I told
her I'd try.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a really good mother,'' she told me with a wet kiss,
``because you're going to help out.''
</P>
<P>
   As she left the room a final time, I was warmed by her
compliment. Am I really who she says I am?
</P>
<P>
   Only I can answer that. But where are you, America? Prove it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com. Send e-mail to gbs\Nstar-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-1STL     09-02 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CREDIBILITY QUESTIONS FOLLOW IN WAKE OF CLINTON'S WORDS
 &HT;    Subs final grafs with 2 grafs to include full Clinton quote.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is drawing on his fabled gift of
gab in his counteroffensive to rescue his administration. But his
efforts to take refuge in popular issues is creating deeper cracks
in his support.
</P>
<P>
   Adhering to the credo of Richard Nixon to ``nail down your
base'' first, Clinton has carved out time in the midst of crises at
home and abroad to meet with his most loyal voter groups after his
admission of a sexual liaison with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On the Massachusetts resort island of Martha's Vineyard last
week, Clinton clasped hands with veterans of the civil rights
movement and linked himself to one of the cherished heroes of
racial equality, Nelson Mandela. Under fire for his improper
relations with a 21-year-old White House intern, the president
likened his situation to that of Mandela, who spent 27 years in
prison doing hard labor for leading the opposition to South
Africa's white apartheid regime.
</P>
<P>
   The president suggested that he had learned from Mandela how to
forgive ``people you believe have wronged you,'' apparently putting
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr in a category with Mandela's
racist tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   If that was a stretch inviting ridicule or outrage, Clinton
emerged temporarily unscathed, with images of a warm embrace by a
group of his most ardent defenders. But he may now be paying a
price, as in a chiding from Clifford Alexander, who was a prominent
black member of three Democratic administrations and former
secretary of the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's in trouble, and even when he's not, Bill Clinton is
known to play fast and furious with issues of race,'' writes
Alexander in Wednesday's editions of The Wall Street Journal, in
which he lambastes Clinton for portraying himself as being at the
center of the struggle for racial equality and then failing to give
the subject ``concentrated leadership, thought and attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's role in his race initiative had been more as a
``TV talk-show host'' than leader, Alexander says.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's attempts to rejuvenate his languishing education
agenda falls into a similar danger zone. Just since his confession
Aug. 17 of the liaison with Lewinsky, the president has made three
visits to schools, including an appearance with First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton at a Moscow elementary school. All the events
stressed his interest in a subject dear to the hearts of his
``soccer mom'' vote.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping off in Herndon, Va., on Monday before his departure for
Russia, Clinton met a friendly crowd eager to rally behind ideas
for better schools. However, the visit Monday was marred by one
prominent local ex-supporter who didn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply could not bring myself to come and be with Mr.
Clinton,'' said Jane K. Strauss, a Fairfax County school board
member, in an interview after she boycotted the appearance. ``I
can't support somebody who on the one hand says he supports the
rights of women and the protection of women when in fact he is
taking advantage of a young woman who is not much older than my own
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hiding behind schools and children to somehow convince us
that we can believe him and that we can trust in his judgment,''
added Strauss, a Democrat who said she twice voted for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Now even Clinton's education proposals are ``hollow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Clinton's unfinished agenda for schools could add to
his credibility problems. Although he vowed a year and a half ago
to make education his top priority for his second term, he has
failed to deliver on most of his promises.
</P>
<P>
   Still undelivered and mired in difficulties are national testing
to raise standards, linking up every classroom to the Internet, and
money to help rebuild crumbing schools. Not only has his plan to
pay for 100,000 new teachers flopped, but a teacher shortage has
grown so acute in some areas that the Bronx school department in
New York has begun importing teachers from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has worked only in fits and starts on these and other
issues, raising yet more questions as Clinton travels overseas and
beams back messages tailored for American ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake, said that I
regretted it, asked to be forgiven, spent a lot of very valuable
time with my family in the last couple of weeks and said I was
going back to work and said I was going back to work,'' Clinton
said at his news conference Wednesday in Moscow, in his latest
attempt to close out the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   But he has yet to ask the public formally for forgiveness, and
his statement added one more obstacle to restoring his lost
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
