<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5268 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BUY-OR-LEASE-ART-     09-02 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BUY-OR-LEASE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDING UP THE PLUSES AND MINUSES OF BUYING OR LEASING A PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rapid pace of evolution in the personal computer industry
guarantees that today's cutting-edge personal computer will be dull
in about two years. And at the rate computer prices are falling,
better and faster computers will be available in two years _ or two
months, for that matter _ at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a PC buyer to do? Some are turning to personal leases
as a hedge against obsolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Leasing is not for everyone. Leasing a PC _ in effect, borrowing
it from the manufacturer or a leasing company in return for fixed
monthly payments for a specified period _ almost always winds up
costing more than buying the computer outright.
</P>
<P>
   For entry-level to mid-range PCs, leasing usually costs hundreds
of dollars more. For top-of-the-line computers, the kind many
people will consider leasing, the difference can easily top $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive way to buy a PC is to pay cash. But for
people who need a computer right away and do not have the cash to
buy it outright, or for those who are sure that they will want to
trade the computer in for a newer and better model in two or three
years, leasing is an increasingly popular option.
</P>
<P>
   Most leases give the customer an option of buying the computer
at the end of the lease, either for some independently established
price (typically the ``Orion Blue Book'' wholesale price for used
computers) or for a fixed percentage of the original contract
price.
</P>
<P>
   But buying the PC at the end of the lease defeats the purpose of
leasing. The customer ends up with an outdated PC that inevitably
costs far more than if the computer had been purchased at the
start.
</P>
<P>
   Financial calculations on leasing are complex, especially if the
computer is to be used for a business. Lease payments can be
tax-deductible in some cases, while the purchase price of the same
equipment can be deductible or depreciated, depending on
circumstances. It makes sense to check with a tax adviser before
deciding.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, however, if you know with certainty that you
are going to want a new computer in two or three years and you are
willing to pay hundreds of dollars to avoid the hassle of selling
the old one, a lease may make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Or if you need a computer today but lack the cash to buy it
outright and do not want to take on a bank loan or credit card
debt, a lease may be the right solution.
</P>
<P>
   But if you entertain even vague thoughts about keeping the
computer at the end of the lease, it probably makes more sense to
buy the computer outright, even if that means extending payments on
a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an example:
</P>
<P>
   Joe is a graphic designer and game fanatic who covets a Dell
Dimension XPS R Mini Tower desktop computer with a 450-megahertz
Pentium II system, 128 megabytes of high-speed RAM, a 16.8-gigabyte
hard drive, a DVD-ROM drive, a Zip drive, a 17-inch monitor, 3-D
video and 3-D sound with a subwoofer, a 56 kilobits per second
modem and other frills. Dell's price is $2,699. He has $500 in the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Joe knows that in two years he will want something better and
faster.
</P>
<P>
   Dell offers a 24-month lease for his chosen computer at $131 a
month; under the plan, Joe makes no payment for 30 days. His total
monthly payments will be $3,144 (plus tax and shipping).
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the lease, Joe does not own the computer. He can
either return it to Dell (he pays the freight back), or he can buy
it for 22 percent of the original price, which comes to $593.78. If
he buys the computer, his total purchase price will be more than
$3,700.
</P>
<P>
   Joe can lower his monthly cost by taking a longer-term lease
($101 a month for 36 months), but his overall payments, including
the purchase price at the end of the lease _ 15 percent of the
original cost instead of 22 percent, which shows how rapidly PCs
lose value _ will be higher: $4,040.85. Or he can pay to ship the
computer back to Dell and lease a newer system.
</P>
<P>
   If Joe decides to buy the same Dell computer outright by
charging it to his Visa card and paying the cost in the same 24
months, he would almost certainly come out better. According to
figures supplied by Visa International, assuming an annual interest
rate of 16.5 percent and a purchase price of $2,699, Joe would make
24 monthly payments of $132.80 each and would own the computer
outright. Interest charges would be $488.13, making his total
payments $3,187.13 (plus tax and shipping).
</P>
<P>
   He could then sell the computer and put the proceeds toward his
next machine.
</P>
<P>
   Now let us assume that Joe can pay cash for the computer. His
$2,699 (plus the familiar tax and shipping fees) could have been
relaxing in the bank, earning a few percentage points of interest
for 24 months. Given the current paltry level of bank interest
rates, his additional cost of lost interest income, minus the taxes
on his interest income, would be trivial. So paying cash is the
least expensive way to buy a computer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, of course, Joe would have been much better off if
he had skipped buying the computer altogether and had instead
bought $2,699 worth of Dell stock 24 months ago. It would be worth
more than $40,000 now, based on the midday stock price Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight can be cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Another approach is Your Ware, offered by Gateway. In Your Ware,
the customer buys a PC and related services under a 48-month
purchase plan for a monthly fee as low as $50 and has the option of
trading the computer for a new one in two to four years. It is not
a lease; Gateway is financing the purchase, and the customer owns
the PC.
</P>
<P>
   The twist is that Gateway promises to buy the used computers
from its Your Ware customers, at any point after the 23rd month and
before the 49th month, for the prevailing wholesale price at the
time, as determined by the ``Orion Blue Book'' only if the customer
applies the money toward another Gateway PC.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say Joe decided at the last minute to choose a Gateway
G6-450 computer instead of the Dell machine, which has roughly
comparable specifications but trades a few gigabytes of hard disk
space for a component enticingly called 12MB 3Dfx Voodoo-2 3D
Accelerator with Extreme Gaming. It costs $2,699, the same as the
Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Your Ware program, Joe decides to finance his purchase
for 24 months at Gateway's 14.9 percent interest rate. His monthly
payment is $131, the same as Dells for a machine costing the same
$2,699. But at the end of the two years, Joe owns the Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   He can keep it, sell it or send it back to Gateway, which will
pay him the ``Orion Blue Book'' value and apply the money toward a
new Gateway computer.
</P>
<P>
   The Gateway customer also has to pay shipping fees to return the
computer, and the computer has to be in good shape, with all of the
original manuals and disks.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway reserves the right to reduce the trade-in value below
the ``Orion Blue Book'' listing at its sole discretion, as the
lawyers say, and if the customer does not like the price, Gateway
will return the computer at the customer's expense.
</P>
<P>
   For those concerned about both price and obsolescence, the
Gateway Your Ware plan can cost as little as $35 a month for a
peppy Celeron 333 computer system on a four-year plan. The customer
can choose to trade for a newer Gateway computer between the second
and fourth years, applying the residual value of the older computer
toward the new financing plan.
</P>
<P>
   Your Ware is a clever way for Gateway to lock in customers who
might otherwise switch to different brands in the future. If the
customer is not firmly committed to buying Gateway computers in the
future, however, the end-of-contract buyout probably does not make
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Leases raise many other issues, including the following:
</P>
<P>
   Some leases require the customer to get permission before making
any upgrades, like adding more memory. Any upgrades made to the
system must be removed and the original equipment installed at the
end of the lease. Some leasing programs allow the customer to
upgrade a system for additional fees.
</P>
<P>
   Monitors and printers typically have longer useful lives than
computers, so it makes more sense to buy them rather than lease
them.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to return the computer, you must make arrangements
to transfer your data to a new computer. Some companies will
transfer the data to a new leased machine for a fee, but otherwise
the customer has to figure out how to send back the old computer,
get the new computer and make sure the data and applications move
from one to the next.
</P>
<P>
   There are substantial penalties for early termination of a
lease. Watch for hidden fees.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to ask what technical support is included in the lease.
Make sure you know who is responsible for maintaining the PC and
fixing it if it breaks. If the machine has technical problems, will
the leasing company replace it or pay for repairs? If the machine
is to be replaced, how quickly will you get a new one? These issues
should be spelled out in the lease.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure your home insurance policy covers the leased computer
because you are responsible if the computer is stolen or damaged.
Some leasing companies will provide insurance on the leased
equipment for an additional monthly fee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
