<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
CAN AMERICA PRACTICE WHAT IT PREACHES ON MORALITY? (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asha was trying to force me to take a bite of her candy.
</P>
<P>
   I was busy reading and thinking what I might say about this
thing causing my heartache. So I turned away from the red, wet
lollipop and, in that voice I use in response to annoying behavior,
said to my little girl: ``Please, Asha.''
</P>
<P>
   When she finally gave up, she turned to bounce out of the room
and said, ``I love you, Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   With my head still buried in James Baldwin's ``The Devil Finds
Work,'' I managed to mumble, ``I love you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, she turned back, looked at me and said, ``Oh,
yeah? Prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, I knew this thing that had taken hold of me. For
weeks, I'd been trying to decide what to make of the constant and
diverse chorus of voices talking about morals and morality.
</P>
<P>
   At no other time in history have I seen so many people willing
to dissect and debate the morality of others. Part of me believes
this is a good thing. But I worry about what seems to be a
recurring problem in our judgment: a tendency toward simplicity and
contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, an anonymous reader called the other day to take
exception to a column I wrote about two teen-age mothers who were
denied admission into the National Honor Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, there should be no rewards for pregnant unmarried
teen-agers,'' she said. ``It's the parents' fault for not putting
those children on birth control. Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The call ended there, and I wondered later if she were sorry for
disagreeing, or sorry for what seemed to me a contradiction. Was
she suggesting that it's OK for teens to be sexually active as long
as they avoid pregnancy?
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this again last Sunday, as I sat in church
listening to a guest minister tell the story of the prophet Elijah.
Afraid for his life, Elijah had sought refuge in the mouth of a
cave, when the Lord came to him and asked, ``What are you doing
here, Elijah?'' It was the same question God asked Adam in the
Garden of Eden after Adam and Eve ate the forbidden fruit: ``Adam,
where art thou?''
</P>
<P>
   As the preacher pointed out Sunday, this was not a question of
either of their physical locations, but rather where they were in
their relationship to God. Where are you morally, Elijah? Adam?
America? Prove it.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of all the scandal, the rape and murder and lies that
saturate our lives and our newspaper headlines, and wondered how it
is that, with all the talk about morals, we find ourselves in such
a wretched place.
</P>
<P>
   Now my daughter had transported me with a simple question into
the darkness again, and I realized I'd missed an opportunity to
show my love for her. In effect, to prove the God in me.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Asha returned. This time, I closed my book, set
it down on the table in front of me and gave her my undivided
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Still bouncing, she asked if I'd sell the items from the
brochure she'd brought home from school ``at your work.'' I told
her I'd try.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a really good mother,'' she told me with a wet kiss,
``because you're going to help out.''
</P>
<P>
   As she left the room a final time, I was warmed by her
compliment. Am I really who she says I am?
</P>
<P>
   Only I can answer that. But where are you, America? Prove it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com. Send e-mail to gbs\Nstar-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
