<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5276 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DENTISTRY-ART-2TA     09-02 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DENTISTRY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERBITE, UNDERBITE, MEGABYTE: DENTISTRY GETS AND UPGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass., Utah, Ill., N.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology has always been the dentist's stock in trade. From
high-speed drills to X-rays, the men and women who pull and
preserve teeth have often turned to technology to take their
practice one more step beyond the image of the torture chamber.
It's no surprise then, that dentists are going digital.
</P>
<P>
   Patients will still have to open wide, of course, to have
cavities filled and teeth removed. Some things never change. But
X-ray film may one day be replaced by a wafer-sized sensor that
electronically generates an X-ray image on a chair-side monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The dental mirror may be replaced, or at least augmented, by a
slender fiber-optic tool that uses a miniature video camera to show
incipient trouble spots. And along with the fiber-optic wand may
come a range of computerized devices that inject Novocain, check
the health of the gums and even analyze the bite _ no more chomping
and grinding the teeth on squares of black paper.
</P>
<P>
   The new technologies appear to offer faster treatments, less
exposure to radiation than with conventional X-rays and, in some
cases, less pain and suffering. But patients may pay a premium for
the convenience of some of the new high-ticket equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Some dentists simply refuse to go digital. Dr. Stephen S.
Markow, for instance, who regularly upgrades the equipment in his
Brooklyn Heights office in New York City (the drill, X-ray
equipment and autoclave have all been updated within the past four
years), laughs at some of the new digital technology, particularly
at a $75,000 crown-making machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem with the price,'' Markow said. ``It would
mean cutting down on lunches for the next thousand years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Price, who teaches dentistry at Boston University
and often speaks on behalf of the American Dental Association,
urges both dentists and patients to leaven their enthusiasm for
whiz-bang equipment with a healthy dose of skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dentists as a group love bells and whistles,'' he said, joking
about his own ``$600 paperweights'': expensive equipment that has
ended up collecting dust on his desk in Newton, Mass., where he
practices dentistry. ``Now I wait and see instead of being the
first on the block to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gordon J. Christensen, a dentist in Provo, Utah, who is the
co-founder of a nonprofit group that tests dental products and
publishes its findings in a newsletter that some practitioners
regard as the dental equivalent of Consumer Reports, urges people
not to accept new equipment solely because it is digital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the new computerized devices are to the patient's
advantage,'' he said, ``but dentists and their patients must choose
between what is new and better, and what is just new. Intraoral
cameras and digital radiography, for instance, actually make the
practice faster and, in the end, lower fees as they serve patients
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The costs to dentists for digital technology vary from a few
hundred dollars, for programs that keep track of patient
medications, to about $75,000 for the computer-operated machine
that produces crowns and other ceramic restorations on the spot,
letting the patient get all the work done in one two- to three-hour
visit to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eugene L. Antenucci, a dentist in Greenlawn, N.Y., is one of
a handful of dentists in the New York area who have the new
instrument for making crowns and inlays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a decision early in my practice to provide the most
advanced technology that has been proven to work,'' Antenucci said.
``A crown is still a crown, but this machine allows me to do crowns
and other restorations in a one-visit procedure, chair-side with
the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dentist with the crown machine is Dr. Steven David, who
practices in Manhattan and is also a clinical professor at New York
University. ``It does take an act of faith to invest so much money
in one piece of equipment,'' he said, ``but patient volume and
satisfaction soon pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many venturesome dentists are using computers for small jobs,
like scanning X-rays from referring dentists into their databases
to create digital files for patients, sending digital X-rays by
e-mail to show their work to insurance companies and communicating
with one another on the Internet, often using digitized images to
discuss diagnoses and treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer technology is going to affect every part of dental
practice,'' said Dr. David A. Whiston, president of the American
Dental Association, based in Chicago, whose membership includes
143,000 dentists. The association will have a program on
integrating digital technology into dentistry, called Taking the
Byte out of Technology, at its October meeting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first areas of digital dentistry to achieve wide
acceptance will probably be digitized X-rays. Dr. Randolph Todd,
whose Manhattan office specializes in endodontics, like root
canals, has used digital X-rays since 1995. ``The main reason is
low radiation _ about 90 percent less,'' Todd said. ``This is a
substantial patient benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   For digital X-rays, the patient opens wide not for X-ray film,
but for a sensor with a computer chip, similar to the sensors found
in digital cameras. Because the sensor is far more sensitive than
regular film, less radiation is required.
</P>
<P>
   The sensor transmits the data directly to a computer, and a
digital X-ray appears on the screen within seconds. The image can
be manipulated to change the contrast, resolution, orientation and
size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of three or four minutes, depending on the type of
processing to do conventional X-rays, it's three or four seconds,''
said Todd, who uses a machine manufactured by Schick Technologies.
``I can see where I'm working, and so can the patient.'' Todd uses
a networked system that allows him to call up X-rays for patients
in any of his five treatment rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Christensen, whose center has evaluated digital radiography,
said the quality of its images was about the same as for
conventional X-rays. But he added: ``It's superior for speed, lower
radiation and communication, as the method offers long-term, easily
stored records. It is far more commonly used in Western Europe. I
think there's going to be an explosion of use in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiber-optic dental cameras are also expected to become more
popular in the United States as they become less expensive and more
familiar. To use the technology, a dentist holds a small
fiber-optic device that looks like a wand and aims it at an area of
the mouth; the image is transmitted to a miniature video recorder.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Patients and doctors look at the image on a computer monitor,
where views may be magnified to many times the original size. The
devices are similar to the fiber-optic tools used by doctors to
view areas of the body that are otherwise hard to see.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan Goldstein has used fiber-optic dental cameras for many
years in his busy Manhattan office and says they can pinpoint
problems before they get bigger. ``Often patients feel a sensation
long before a tooth breaks,'' he said. ``This technology allows me
to see things before they get worse. Over a period of time, teeth
with big filings get weak. Cracks start. My ability to see these
cracks early means I can sometimes put a cap on them before they
need a root canal, or fracture and are lost. It's a huge patient
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Christensen, too, says the new cameras are important to
dentistry. ``We've been evaluating them for 12 years,'' he said.
``Two or three of them are superb, and they are down in price from
$30,000 to $10,000 for good, $5,000 for acceptable. They are
mandatory for a practice for the dentist and the patient to see
what the problem is. Without them, you are practicing 1947
dentistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Other digitized devices are also making their way into dental
offices, including a possible replacement for that fearsomely sharp
piece of steel, the periodontal probe, that dentists use to measure
the depth of any treacherous spaces, or periodontal pockets,
developing between teeth and gum.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth S. Magid, who has a general practice in Harrison,
N.Y., uses an electronic probe that has a flexible tip instead of a
steel one. At the other end is the inevitable cable to communicate
with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   With a standard probe, he said, ``the depth of the pocket
depends on how hard you push _ that means inherent inaccuracy.''
The digital probe is more accurate, he explained. ``The computer
probe always uses the same amount of force,'' he said, ``and it
measures to a tenth of a millimeter, so you wind up with very
repeatable, extremely accurate measurements. And you don't have to
worry about being heavy-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even dentists with high-technology practices may not be pure
technophiles. Goldstein, whose equipment ranges from fiber-optic
dental cameras to digital radiography and lasers, is not
enthusiastic about a new computerized injection system he bought,
although some other dentists think it useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it is is a needle to give an injection under controlled
pressure,'' Goldstein said. ``I sent mine back. It's not as
intimidating as a regular needle _ it looks more like a little pen
_ but my patients didn't like the amount of time it took.''
</P>
<P>
   Many patients worry about that dentists may pass on the cost of
expensive equipment to them, no matter how often dentists reassure
them that they will not need to charge more because the equipment
allows them to do more procedures in the same amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   Christensen said larger offices and team practices were less
likely to raise prices after getting expensive digital equipment.
``In a well-run office, auxiliary staff can use much of the
equipment _ for instance, the digital camera _ freeing the dentist
for other jobs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ross W. Nash, who practices in Charlotte, N.C., said a few
of his charges were related to the cost of equipment but that most
were not. ``We don't charge a premium for digital radiography,'' he
said. ``It's more convenient to use; the X-rays are easier to read;
the time and money they save means they don't cost any more to do
than conventional X-rays. But when we do laser surgery, we charge
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions of cost and value are at least theoretically
answerable in trying to assess the value of new technology. But
there are some benefits that are hard to quantify.
</P>
<P>
   One of Todd's patients, for example, was so taken with the
images of his teeth that he made them into art. ``I loaded the
X-rays onto a floppy disk for him,'' Todd said, ``and he blew them
up into a poster-sized picture. Up close, the image is all dots,
but as you move back, you can see the tooth. He has it hanging on
his wall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
