<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUPELO-UPHOLSTERY-ART     09-02 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUPELO-UPHOLSTERY-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA: THE UPHOLSTERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUPELO, Miss. _ The Burlington Northern Railroad cuts through
downtown Tupelo, Miss., twice, at both ends, east and west, which
is a matter of about 10 blocks. The trailing wail and the
crossings' clanging are as ubiquitous as the bug songs of the
cicadas and crickets that pulse like a fever from the shade trees
and the flowering crepe myrtle.
</P>
<P>
   Standing alone at noon in a silver shiver of 95 degree August
heat on Main Street, you might not feel like you're at the center
of anything, except a train whistle. But you would be at the center
of the known upholstered universe.
</P>
<P>
   Tupelo _ if you're counting quantity, not quality of sofas, love
seats and recliners _ is the upholstered-furniture capitol of the
world. There are more than 230 furniture manufacturers within a 50
mile radius, with more than 26,000 employees, producing 50,000
upholstered pieces a day.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not from Tupelo, you are there for one of two
reasons: the upholstery industry or Elvis Presley. Tupelo is his
birthplace, but today furniture is king.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th annual fall Tupelo Furniture Market was held two weeks
ago _ 1.25 million square feet of product lines on display in nine
hangarlike sheds. The wholesale market and its Mississippi
manufacturing base are the resource and last refuge for the mom and
pop retail furniture stores in America.
</P>
<P>
   V.M. Cleveland, a real estate developer from Alabama, conceived
of and built the market in 1987. ``The only way you used to find
out about Tupelo is somebody would say, `Hey, it's the home of
Elvis Presley,''' Cleveland said, sitting at his massive office
desk. ``Now, when you go places, they'll tell you Tupelo is the
furniture market. That's a pretty good feat, because he is a
well-known guy, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Elvis' birthplace, a prim, painted two-room white wooden shack
with a big black porch swing, still stands, at the center of a
small park and visitors' center at the end of a short road of
shacks. At 7:30 on a recent evening, a young family circled the
lawn and read the plaque.
</P>
<P>
   There is, in fact, an Elvis-furniture cross-over. The
19-year-old Presley was employed for nine months by the Bozof
Company, based in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worked the night shift, making metal dinettes,'' said Albert
Bozof, the owner of the company, which is no longer in business.
``Ninety cents an hour. His mother said she didn't want him working
in a place like that.''
</P>
<P>
   From the swing on the Presleys' porch, the failing light and
gentling heat might have been the summer of 1935, the year Elvis
was born, for all that appears to have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Tupelo today is a city of 35,000. By Wednesday, Aug. 19, 22,000
people had registered to attend the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got some strangers on board! Tell them what to do, Rosie!''
yelled J.R. Pegues, a retired life insurance salesman, to the woman
standing at the back of the Lunch Bunch restaurant, behind the
steam table trays of fried catfish, creamed chicken casserole,
macaroni and cheese, and hush puppies. What to do was to pay four
and a half dollars and load your plate, empty it while you talk
Tupelo, Elvis and furniture, then make another trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``You the fellow from New York? I heard about you,'' said Duane
Jones, a junior high school teacher and a shuttle-van driver
working between the highway hotels and the exhibition halls.
Southerners call this kind of surveillance hospitality. Tupelo is
named for a gum tree. Being there is like stepping in gum;
everywhere you go, you stick.
</P>
<P>
   The industry calls Tupelo a ``promotional furniture'' market.
Promotional is a point of price, not style.
</P>
<P>
   ``In upholstery, it would be $150 sofas, which would be a
wholesale price, which would be $299 retail, and up,'' said Harvey
Bailey, the sales manager of Style-Line Furniture, a Tupelo-based
manufacturer that produces roughly 65,000 units annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a guy come here yesterday who wanted a group for $100,''
said Matt Nicholson, a partner in Magnolia Furniture Industries, a
three-year-old company that employs 20 in Fulton, Miss. ``He didn't
care what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson, a young man in a brown necktie and white shirt
sleeves, gestured to a trio of jumbo-size, Dumbo-shaped rolled-arm
furniture pieces grouped like a herd of baby elephants around a
watering hole: Magnolia's Market Special. ``Three-piece traditional
_ sofa, love seat, settee _ $299,'' he said. ``It's got a skirt on
it. A lot of people like that look right now.''
</P>
<P>
   This is cheap. And that's why people come to Tupelo.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi is home ground for the regional ``independents''
from largely rural southern states who can't afford the costs of a
trip to North Carolina's lavish seven-million-square-foot October
market at High Point, the more expensive furniture on display or
the minimum orders required by the big companies exhibiting.
Chances are they have no customers at home for the high-end items
either.
</P>
<P>
   The ``majors'' or the aggressive, regional discount chains like
American Furniture, based in Denver, Colo., also shop Tupelo for
bargains at the bottoms of barrels that North Carolina doesn't
build anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This for me is like the garment center in New York used to
be,'' said Morton Seaman, upholstery shopping for Rooms to Go, a
Florida-based chain of 60 furniture stores that his family runs.
(They are the Seamans of the Seaman Furniture Co. in New York,
which the family sold in 1987.) ``High Point is just the fancy
show; this is where it's really done,'' Seaman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about the design leaders,'' said Lester
Craft, the editor in chief of Furniture Today, an industry
publication. ``This is the meat and potatoes, bread and butter,
middle market and mass market furniture we see here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Epperson, a furniture industry financial analyst at
Interstate Johnson Lane in Charlotte, N.C., said of the
professional wrestle for the industry title: ``North Carolina ships
more dollars. No question, Mississippi ships more units.''
</P>
<P>
   Magnolia Industries' Nicholson said: ``We're trying to upgrade,
every market, but you don't want to forget about the horse that
what done bring you _ is that what the old folks say?''
</P>
<P>
   Based on three days' observation, the horse is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Couples crowded the market. Older couples had grown children
with them _ the next generation of ownership for a store or small
chain of stores that has served its community as a furniture outlet
for generations. While wives chose the important sales features _
styles and fabrics _ husbands debated the number of units to order.
</P>
<P>
   Like many things in Mississippi, the upholstered furniture
industry is family _ buyers and sellers both. Bill Joiner, a former
Panola County deputy sheriff, started the Batesville Warehouse, a
furniture and gift store in Batesville, Miss., 14 years ago with
his wife, Linda, a former insurance company secretary, to put their
children through college. The Mississippi industry was started 50
years ago this month by one man, Morrie Futorian, a Chicago
upholsterer who was lured to Lee County, of which Tupelo is the
seat, with financial incentives by the Community Development
Foundation, an organization of local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Futorian arrived with an innovation: to build sofas and chairs
on an assembly line model like the automobile operations he had
seen in Detroit. He is known in Mississippi as the ``Henry Ford of
furniture.'' His company, the Stratford Company, continues in New
Albany. Futorian died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the companies today, including big players like Action
Industries, are ``cousins'' _ once or twice removed _ of Futorian's
factory, started by skilled line foremen or sales managers. At
Style-Line's 147,000-square-foot plant, where an assembly line can
push an upholstered piece through, from wood-frame assembly to
plastic shipping bag, in 15 minutes, the lesson is easy to see:
making a sofa is not rocket science. Style-Line was founded 32
years ago by Margie and Billy Anderson, who worked at Futorian's
plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people at that point were operating out of their
garages at home, their chicken houses, whatever,'' Mrs. Anderson
recalled. ``We backed a truck up to our door and ran the furniture
right off the line into the truck.''
</P>
<P>
   The circus was in town; it was just a question of putting up a
tent. V.M. Cleveland's original market in 1987 was a
14,000-square-foot building.
</P>
<P>
   Today, behind him, on a wall of office bookshelves, is a set of
Elvis Presley figural canisters, a replica of the shack where Elvis
was born and a coffee mug with a reproduction of The Northeast
Mississippi Daily Journal's front page and the headline, ``The King
Is Dead,'' from the day he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's phenomenal what he did, as a little old country boy,''
Cleveland said.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur appeared at home in the shadow of Tupelo's
favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my daddy,'' he said, pointing to a photograph of a man
in overalls and six children, hanging below a set of Elvis
Presley's first four Sun label singles. ``He was a fix-it guy, sort
of a shade-tree mechanic. As you can see, we were very poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six years ago, Cleveland moved to the big city _ Tupelo,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Bish, who was at Cleveland's market this year, said, ``We
like the night life here.'' Bish and his wife, Wendy, were shopping
for Lake Road Furniture, their store in Meadville, Pa. ``The only
thing I don't like is the $4.50 rum and Cokes,'' he said. ``Back
home, at our Days Inn, they're $2.70.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're from a small town,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
