<HEADER>
A5284 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TRAFFIC-MONITOR-A     09-02 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRAFFIC-MONITOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUTERS TAKE UP DIGITAL ARMS TO BATTLE TRAFFIC SNARLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash., Texas, Ariz., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MIKE ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 8 a.m. in Seattle, and a commuter looks down at his watch.
The digital pager display tells him that there's been an accident
on his preferred route to work, so he considers an alternative.
What about taking a bus?
</P>
<P>
   To see if that's a good idea, he flips open his palmtop with
wireless modem and sees that the scheduled bus on his route is
running late. Maybe he'll drive after all.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the kinds of decisions being made in the Seattle area
by commuters in an $18 million federal Department of Transportation
pilot project that pits the latest Internet gadgetry against
traffic congestion. The service to alert wearers of Seiko pager
watches about traffic problems has been commercially available
since July 1, and the palmtop service has been available since May.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic problem, as any car commuter can testify, is a tough
one. Traffic has swelled 30 percent in the United States since
1989, according to the federal Department of Transportation, with
50 percent more cars expected on the road by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The department is betting that it can get people to their
destinations more quickly without building new roads if commuters
can use digital equipment to outsmart traffic snarls.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has appropriated $95 million per year through 2004 for
various projects involving what is called intelligent
transportation, like the pilot project in Seattle. Similar pilot
programs are under way in Phoenix and San Antonio, and one is
planned for New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Like most software demos, the pilot projects and their Web sites
are Pollyannish and slick. Since the federal government is not
known for being on the cutting edge of technology, there may seem
to be something incongruous about a federal bureaucracy's
sponsoring a Web site that is so complex that it uses the most
advanced versions of Netscape Navigator, 4.06 or the beta version
of 4.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real cultural shift for us,'' said Toni Wilbur, who
administers the four pilot programs for the federal Highway
Administration in Washington. ``We're bridge engineers and pavement
engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Ms. Wilbur said her mission was to
find practical solutions and prove that traffic software wasn't
``all Buck Rogers pie-in-the-sky stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many of the prototypes of Web pages offering traffic
information to Seattle commuters take advantage of simple devices
built into the highways 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle pilot project features Web sites that display
highway maps with real-time traffic speeds by tapping a data stream
from electronic strips, called loop detectors, under area roadways;
many of them were installed under Interstate 5, which runs through
the Seattle area, in the 1960s to monitor traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The kinds of intelligent traffic systems being studied would fit
in well with the kinds of on-board car computers envisioned by
Microsoft, a partner in the Seattle project, and some car
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Richards, one of the people testing the technology in
the Seattle project, said the Seiko wristwatch received traffic
information collected by the Washington State Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   And bus-tracking software by Fastline for palmtop computers gets
data from King County Metro Transit, which keeps track of Seattle
buses through a network of radio signals sent by each bus to small
receivers on traffic signs along every route. Now the Internet is
making it possible to distribute such information to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle project, dubbed Smart Trek
(www.smarttrek.org/html/projects.html), includes 29 separate
traffic, safety and transit initiatives. In addition to the
pager-wristwatch service and the bus-tracking software for palmtop
computers, a feature called Traffic View is offered by Microsoft at
seattle.sidewalk.com.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smart Trek projects also include Web sites with frequently
updated still shots from more than 200 strategically placed
closed-circuit highway cameras, a local cable television program
called ``Traffic Check'' and Metro bus station kiosks that post bus
arrival times on monitors like those in airports.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Trek has marquee partnerships with Microsoft, Boeing and
Metro Networks, a leading provider of television and radio traffic
reports.
</P>
<P>
   One of its powerful tools is a server designed by electrical
engineers at the University of Washington. Daniel Daily, a
professor of electrical engineering at the university, said he had
become interested in the traffic problem because he was intrigued
by the similarities between highway congestion and the turbulence
in the flow of boiling water in nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Daily knew that the traffic information would have value beyond
his academic pursuits. In partnership with Smart Trek, Daily built
the Intelligent Transportation System Backbone server in Seattle to
collect travel and transit data from the disparate and otherwise
incompatible systems at the state Department of Transportation,
King County Metro Transit and the Washington State Patrol and
organize it into a publicly available standard format.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: the roughly 3,000 loop detectors in the
Seattle area furnish a continuous stream of traffic speed and
congestion information to the State Department of Transportation,
which passes the data on to the Intelligent Transportation System
Backbone server at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the State Patrol may be tracking an accident that
corresponds to a slowdown reported in the traffic data.
</P>
<P>
   The Backbone makes the data from the different sources available
in a single format. A company like Metro Networks can get access to
the data and, in partnership with a digital map maker, Etak, can
offer complete and instantaneous online traffic information to
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Such companies _ like another Smart Trek partner, the Cue Corp.,
a data broadcasting company _ can license that traffic information
and dispatch it to pagers, wristwatches or cars outfitted with an
Auto PC.
</P>
<P>
   By getting in on the ground floor of the Department of
Transportation's technology plans, companies can use the Seattle
project and the other pilot projects as laboratory settings for
developing products.
</P>
<P>
   Daily said he hoped that Smart Trek's distribution strategy
would become a model for intelligent transportation programs in
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilbur, the federal Department of Transportation project
leader, said the program included safety projects as well. On July
21, city and state transportation officials began in San Antonio
the Trans Guide pilot program, which features fiber optic video
conferencing between hospital emergency rooms and ambulances in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   The project in New York City, called iTravel, has yet to be
officially unveiled, but it will be a $10 million pilot project
covering traffic in the tristate metropolitan area. The project
will focus on trip planning and transit information services rather
than the wireless gadgets that are part of the projects in the
smaller cities.
</P>
<P>
   Straphangers, accustomed to being monitored by surveillance
cameras on subway platforms, will no doubt welcome the day that
iTravel turns the tables to let passengers keep an eye on the
subway system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5287 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-AIRLINE-SHOPPING-     09-02 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-AIRLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO-IT-YOURSELF TRAVEL WITH A LOAD OF GUILT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have avoided taking infants on airplanes ever since the mashed
peas incident of 1990. On a nonstop flight from Phoenix to New
York, my 11-month-old daughter smeared a handful into the hair of a
sleeping woman in the row ahead. The next three hours were as
suspenseful as any Hitchcock movie; what if the passenger woke?
</P>
<P>
   She slept. But next time I might not be so lucky. Plus, now
we're a family of five, counting the current infant. Air fare to
Arizona to visit my parents in December would cost roughly as much
as a cruise missile. For that kind of money, shouldn't we head to a
tropical resort instead?
</P>
<P>
   ``But you said you wanted to visit your relatives,'' said Diane
Bacigalupo, the assistant manager of Village Travel in Huntington,
N.Y., where I live. She looked up from a screen full of air fares
to see me biting my nails nervously.
</P>
<P>
   I admit that I have some idiosyncrasies when it comes to travel.
Could any travel agent know enough about my quirks to create the
perfect itinerary?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I needed to be my own travel agent, a role the Internet
has made possible in recent months with a proliferation of online
sites where travelers can confirm room rates and air fares, book
reservations and read reviews of hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour later, I was at my home computer, ready to pit the
machine against the real-life travel agent. I would start small, by
comparing the cheapest round-trip air fare that Ms. Bacigalupo had
found _ $486 a person, including an $8 travel agent's commission _
to the rates on three Web sites. I logged onto Travelocity
 &UR; (www.travelocity.com) &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Microsoft's Expedia  &UR; (www.expedia. &LR; 
 &UR; com) &LR;   &UR;  &LR; and the Internet Travel Network  &UR; (www.itn.com) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   It took less than five minutes for even a novice like me to
figure out how to compare dozens of possible itineraries by
entering the time and date of the trip, the number of people
traveling together and destinations. But other online features were
worrisome. For instance, Expedia was the only site where I could
specify that I would be traveling with an infant on my husband's
lap. At the other sites, my group was identified as four
passengers. I feared that this could lead to problems later; in the
past, reservations clerks have always wanted to know ahead of time
if an infant was accompanying me.
</P>
<P>
   The three sites rely on different computerized reservations
databases, but each quoted an identical low fare: $478. Such
details as airlines, connections and flight times differed
slightly, but not enough to matter. And I could shave off the $8
commission. But Ms. Bacigalupo had spent an hour listening to me
whine _ er, talk _ about my concerns. Guilt overtook me.
</P>
<P>
   Next, where to stay near my parents' house? None of the sites'
resort or hotel databases had information on the dude ranches that
Ms. Bacigalupo had pinpointed. With her leads, I conducted fruitful
keyword searches at  &UR; www.hotbot.com &LR;  and quickly found encyclopedic
listings at  &UR; www.duderanches.com  &LR; and  &UR; www.ranchweb.com &LR; . I sent
e-mail to the owner of the Kay El Bar Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   But before I received a reply, Ms. Bacigalupo phoned: the Kay El
Bar was fully booked. Besides, she pointed out, these dude ranches
were pricey. Would my family get its money's worth? Now that she
mentioned it, I remembered Arizona as being too chilly and windy in
December for long rides in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   After wrestling with these questions for three days, I went on
line again _ and was shocked to learn that I could now fly the same
route on the same days for less money. This time, the three sites'
fares differed, ranging from $442 to $464. I phoned representatives
of the three Web sites to ask why prices were fluctuating. ``The
airlines make one million changes in their inventories every day,''
said Lois Shore, vice president of marketing at the Internet Travel
Network. ``There could be a drop in price, an increase, a change in
time, in routing.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the different air fares? Although the sites' databases are
similar, my method of searching was slightly different at each. At
one, for instance, I rquested nonstop flights.
</P>
<P>
   That volatility in price might be a comfort to an unencumbered
solo traveler who could take advantage of last-minute deals. For
those free spirits, the Internet Travel Network has a low-fare
ticker that flashes tempting fares like ``San Francisco to Boston,
round trip $273.'' Just click on the ticker to book the flight.
</P>
<P>
   But I was getting so frustrated that I was ready to mash peas
into my own hair when the phone rang _ Ms. Bacigalupo again. ``Why
don't you fly to Phoenix, stay a night with your family, then fly
from there to the Baja Peninsula?'' she said. ``It's warm and costs
less than a dude ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, I came clean. ``I've been checking out some
online travel sites,'' I admitted. ``So I can also check out air
fares.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next 10 minutes, we tested itineraries simultaneously.
The best fare she found was $1,141. But Expedia quoted $811. Even
odder, when I changed the parameters of my multiple-destination
search slightly to eliminate any mention of Phoenix on the return
trip, Expedia quoted $685 for an identical itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not getting that rate,'' Ms. Bacigalupo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What should I do?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reserve it,'' she said. ``Quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ms. Bacigalupo nor a spokeswoman for Expedia could
explain the disparity. ``It reminds me of a TV show a while back
where they went onto a plane and asked all the passengers how much
their tickets cost,'' said Suzi LeVine, a product manager for
Expedia. ``They were all different.''
</P>
<P>
   But by bypassing Ms. Bacigalupo, who had helped me so much, I
felt as if I had cheated her out of the $32 commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a moral dilemma,'' Ms. LeVine observed.
</P>
<P>
   If so, we are all going to lose in this particular battle of
computers vs. humans. No, I will pay Ms. Bacigalupo the commission
anyway. Technically, the machine won this contest; no wonder Ms.
Bacigalupo said she worried that the Internet's ability to blithely
reshape industries overnight would transform real-life agents into
``dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not. Without help from both quarters, I would have
stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
