<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5290 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DENTISTRY-MORPH-A     09-02 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DENTISTRY-MORPH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAIGHTER TEETH IN MERE MOMENTS, AT LEAST ON SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Calif., Texas, N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DEBRA NUSSBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Monica Tantlinger can see the future. She even
has a computer printout of it.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monica got her braces 18 months ago, her orthodontist,
Dr. Michael Theurer, gave her a glimpse of a straighter tomorrow.
He used a new computer-imaging device to show her what her teeth
and jaw would look like after the treatment was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really cool,'' Monica said. ``I was afraid of getting
braces at first, but once I saw what my teeth would look like, I
said, `Let's do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her top braces are off, and she is happy with the results. The
bottom braces will come off soon.
</P>
<P>
   Computer imaging came on the scene for orthodontists and oral
surgeons more than a decade ago, but as the technology has improved
and prices have dropped, more dentists have adopted equipment that
lets patients envision the future.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the 8,700 orthodontists practicing in the United States
and Canada, 15 percent to 20 percent have some type of computer
imaging equipment, said Pam Paladin, a spokeswoman for the American
Association of Orthodontists in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the patient has to be aware that nothing is certain.
``This is a potential after look,'' Mrs. Paladin said. ``This is a
representation of how one might look, not a guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest technology in dental imaging equipment, made by
companies like Dolphin Imaging and Quick Ceph Systems, both in
California, actually ``morphs'' the picture of the patient's face
to show how braces or surgery will change the jaw, cheekbones and
teeth. A patient is photographed with a digital camera, views the
probable change in appearance on a computer screen and takes home a
printout.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment is becoming so popular that Dolphin Imaging, which
has about 600 clients, has seen a 30 percent to 40 percent increase
in sales of software, computers and service each year for the past
three years, said Chester Wang, director of the company. And Quick
Ceph Systems has sold imaging equipment to about 2,200 practices
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Appel Orthodontix, based in Houston, which manages 130 practices
in 20 states and Canada, has imaging and morphing systems in 10
offices now, but it will have the equipment in 50 offices by the
end of the year and in 90 percent within 12 months, said Dr. John
Vondrak, Appel's chief executive and a former orthodontist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average person is highly influenced by high technology,''
said Vondrak, whose company markets to middle-level consumers by
offering payment plans for treatment. ``A picture is worth 1,000
words. And when you show someone what they will look like, you
don't have to sell it. It is the selling of what is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the morphing feature was available, orthodontists used
slower computer systems. They spent up to an hour circling teeth on
a computer screen, then moving them by cutting and pasting. They
would have to call the patient back for another appointment to see
the results.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph M. Pelle, who practices in Denton, Texas, said he
would often spend 45 minutes drawing a patient by hand to show the
expected changes. Now he can make the changes by clicking and
dragging on the image of the patient's face with the Dolphin
Imaging system. Going from a digital photograph to a morphed face
takes about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer changes everything,'' said Theurer, who practices
in Lancaster, Calif., and also has a Dolphin Imaging system. ``I
just put a square around the front teeth and click, and it
straightens the front teeth. You can show the patient how they will
look in silver, gold, clear or colors on their braces. Most of them
sit with their mouth open, just amazed, and say, `That's me, that's
me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert H. Kazmierski, in Moorestown, N.J., takes eight
digital photographs of every patient and puts them on the screen.
Patients can see their faces with and without smiles. They can see
the morphed versions of their new looks and leave with color
printouts.
</P>
<P>
   While the prices for imaging systems have decreased, they are by
no means cheap. A total package of equipment would have cost about
$40,000 in the early 1990s; that would cost less than $15,000 now,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   Vondrak said the systems paid off for orthodontists. In his
offices, he said, 40 out of 100 new patients will sign on for
treatment without the computer imaging, while 75 percent to 80
percent sign up after seeing the imaging.
</P>
<P>
   Patients, of course, have to exercise normal caution about
signing up for expensive orthodontic treatments and need to
remember that the computer images are just that: images.
</P>
<P>
   And some orthodontists urge caution for their colleagues as
well. Pelle, who has used the Dolphin Imaging equipment for the
past month, said: ``You have to be careful how you use it. You have
to be careful about what you can do and what you can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   People who want free computer-generated pictures of what they
might look like after orthodontic treatment can send color
photographs to Smiles, American Association of Orthodontists, 401
North Lindbergh Boulevard, St. Louis, Mo. 63141-7816.
</P>
<P>
   Each photograph must be a clear, close-up shot showing the front
of the face with a wide smile. Include your name, address and
telephone number. When the image shows up, it will carry a
disclaimer on the back that says, ``This photograph is an
approximation and is not intended to guarantee identical results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
