A5299 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HANDCUFFS-NYT &LR;      09-02 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HANDCUFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLING ON TECHNOLOGY TO BUILD A BETTER HANDCUFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: W.Va., Calif.)   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As many police officers will admit, there's no such thing as a
pick-proof handcuff. The engineers and law enforcement officials
who work at developing one are simply outnumbered by the convicts
who spend many hours a day figuring out how to outwit their
restraints.
</P>
<P>
   But now the computer is being put to use to figure out a way to
build a better handcuff and improve upon the ones in use now, which
were basically patented in 1915 and not modified significantly ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Worthey, an engineer at the National Institute of Standards
and Technology, has programmed a device to measure force and torque
levels on individual parts of handcuffs under stress.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has contracted with Touchstone Research
Laboratory of Triadelphia, W.Va. to use the device and software to
find the weakest parts of various handcuffs and recommend possible
improvements to the national standards governing handcuff
production.
</P>
<P>
   The need for such improvements in the current models appears to
be great, especially for police transporting prisoners. In Los
Angeles for example, the trip from jail to court hearings can be up
to 80 miles each way and take several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2,000 prisoners moved every day, at least one will likely
get free himself while on the bus, said Dennis Kennedy, a deputy
with the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Office. With only two
officers _ one of them a driver _ per busload of 30 to 50, the
results can be frightening: fights with other inmates, attacks on
officers, and escapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give someone one to three hours to figure how to
violate something, they'll do it,'' Kennedy said. ``They stay up at
night trying to do this. They spend more time at it than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners have figured out ways to use the large staples from
food boxes and other bits of metal to pick the common handcuff, he
said, and they are often able to pry apart the ratchet apparatus of
their cuffs, using the cuffs of nearby prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Worthey wrote software to enable a device called a force torque
transducer to measure the forces necessary both to unlock and to
break handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rare for people to have equipment to record torque, and
it was certainly rare to measure the combination of force and
torque,'' he said. ``We want to find out how strong can it be made,
and are there weak ones out there. We wanted to raise the level of
the engineering discussion, and see what can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Touchstone's report is expected in about six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make little improvements in the formal standard, but
hopefully not make it longer,'' Worthey said, noting that it costs
manufacturers about $50,000 to comply with each new sentence added
to the official National Institute of Justice standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The handcuff does a lot with a small number of moving parts.
It doesn't weigh a lot, and police are not ready to give up the
common handcuff and go to something vastly more expensive,''
Worthey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
