<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     09-02 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO JOBS, ONE LOVE: THE SAXOPHONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny Guadarrama would love to stay _ really, he would.
</P>
<P>
   But he can't.
</P>
<P>
   This is the common thread that connects every time I've seen
Guadarrama playing saxophone, whether he was with the Fort Worth
Guitar Army at Billy Bob's last November or Latin Express at the
J&AMP;J Blues Bar a couple of weeks ago: He shows up, plays some great
sax, and then is gone into the night, back to his 9-to-5 gig, which
in his case is a midnight-to-noon gig, fixing laser printers for
Xerox, as he has for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere in his travels, you've seen him, whether you
realize it or not.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy up there on the bandstand in bars and ballrooms
with Latin Express or Eddie Miller &AMP; the Heavy Hitters, or doing
the lucrative circuit of country clubs, private parties and wedding
receptions with the RayBans (who know stuff by everyone from Wilson
Pickett to Elton John to Merle Haggard). Or maybe sitting in with
blues band Count Blue or jazzer Johnny Case.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy you used to see in the Cajun band Acadiana, and in
the avant-garde jazz group Picasso's Nightmare in the late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy with the trim mustache, carrying himself with quiet
confidence and class and digging into a superb solo that can make
even an oldie like ``Respect'' or ``Oye Como Va'' sound brand-new
and interesting.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy who, at 40, keeps going on an endless round of
shows and long nights at work, because he loves the music first and
the money second.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pager will go off on the bandstand,'' he says over lunch.
He's just finished a shift, and been up since at least yesterday
evening, but he still looks and sounds fresh and alert. (I'd be
passed out, face-first in the appetizer.) ``But it's manageable if
you plan ahead. I've motivated myself to do this; I had a vision of
being versatile enough to play with different bands and do
different styles of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it and I love music; I like to keep my foot in the
environment of music, and that's why it's worth it to me. Right now
my priority band is the RayBans, and Latin Express keeps me in
touch with traditional music and the culture and everything else _
my roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Guadarrama's roots are in a family of musicians led by father
Frank, who played piano and saxophone. All the boys in the family
(Johnny is the youngest of five) were horn players; he was
seriously into the music by age 10, playing ``rancheras'' with his
dad's band and then listening hard to records by John Coltrane,
Dexter Gordon and Cannonball Adderly.
</P>
<P>
   He learned to appreciate music, and the freedom of expression it
gave him. He learned to read charts and to improvise, which is
something he says more players should train themselves to do. He
learned to appreciate the humor of Latin Express leader Leo Saenz,
with whom he has been playing for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   And he learned that making music is its own reward, that it can
be a lifetime love affair as real as the kind two people share _ if
you nurture it and respect it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's not hard, he says _ and exhausting at times.
Because it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have one of those back-to-back weekends, it can seem
endless,'' he says. ``I'll look at my wife and say, `Don't you wish
our life was normal?' And Christine will say, `Your life has never
been normal.' And it's true; it's always been hectic. We get
through it. My music is part of me; and my wife understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, he says, the payoff is so much larger than the
hardships. The money is good _ ``I make sure when I play it's worth
my while,'' he says. But Johnny Guadarrama knows he may well never
get rich, and he may never get beyond the bars and the wedding
receptions, because few do, no matter how talented.
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't seem to care _ or, at the very least, to let it
bother him. He loves his work _ and anyone who spends much time at
all listening to music in Fort Worth is the better for it. I know I
am.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love music more now,'' he says. ``Musicians are always
learning, but when the fundamentals are mastered, then you can
concentrate on the spiritual and the emotion it takes to make the
music even more beautiful and really express yourself. You can
really focus on the heart. I don't know what I'd do without my
music _ I really don't.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com. Dave Ferman is at
dfer\Nstar-telegram.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
