<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- ADS. Two congressional Democrats representing
Orange County are getting a boost from the largest advertising
blitz ever launched by an environmental group. (Working.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- LIEBERMAN. Despite speculation that he would call
for censure of the president over the Monica Lewinsky scandal, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman said today that any calls for legislative action
are premature. He said he will give a statement later in the week
about his thoughts on the Lewinsky matter. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   -- SIERRA. The Sierra Club has begun broadcasting issue ads in
support of Republican Rep. Nancy Johnson. (Working.) Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- MILLER. U.S. Rep. Dan Miller Wednesday called on
President Clinton to consider resigning in the wake of his public
admission that he lied to the nation about his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky. Williams
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. (Working.) Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- ROADS. A $2.1 million federal grant for an
experimental road warning system could soon make its debut in
Indiana cars, making driving safer for thousands of Hoosiers.
(Working.) Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- WASTE. The Senate gives final approval to the plan to
ship Maine's nuclear waste from private reactors such as the
defunct Maine Yankee to a site in west Texas, sending the bill on
to President Clinton, who is expected to sign it. Kane
</P>
<P>
   NEW MEXICO -- DONORS. Roughly 70 New Mexico residents doled out
their own money to help President Clinton and the first lady defend
themselves against charges related to alleged White House scandals.
Gorman
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- DEBT. More and more Americans, and Ohioans, are going
bankrupt. On Friday, the Senate is expected to take a step toward
making it harder to erase debt. But the details of the bill and how
it was influenced remain unclear. Story includes positions of
Ohio's congressional delegation. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   -- DEWINE-YOUTH-CRIME. (Re-sent.) How can communities best stem
the rising wave of juvenile crime? The Senate Subcommittee on Youth
Violence -- which includes Ohio Republican Mike DeWine -- held a
hearing Tuesday titled ``Fixing a Broken System: Preventing Crime
Through Intervention.'' Hamilton County Judge David Grossmann
testified. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- FEDERAL-FUNDS. (Possible.) Ohio received 93 cents for every
tax dollar sent to Washington in 1997, which is one of the lowest
levels in the last 10 years, according to a report released Tuesday
by the Northeast-Midwest Institute. The state ranks 41st among the
states in per-capita federal spending. Will include county-specific
numbers. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- TURNOUT-DEMS. (Thursday morning, for the WEEKEND.) Political
analysts say that what was originally going to be a challenging
year for Ohio Democrats may turn into a downright electoral
disaster. The key will be turnout, and analysts say the combination
of President Clinton's problems, the inability of Dem Sen. John
Glenn to campaign, and a strong Republican ticket could keep Ohio
Democrats home on Nov. 3. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- CONST. More high school students can correctly
identify the names of the Three Stooges than can properly name the
three branches of the federal government. Armed with similarly
damning statistics about Americans' knowledge of the U.S.
Constitution, Philadelphia Mayor Ed Rendell told a Senate panel
that $20 million of federal money would be well spent on the
public-private effort to build a National Constitution Center on
Independence Mall. Kane
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- NUCLEAR WASTE. Texas senators joined the majority of
their colleagues Wednesday to give their final stamp of approval to
legislation establishing a low-level nuclear waste site in Sierra
Blanca. Brown
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- GOV. Two years ago, with tuxedoed waiters
catering and a steel band entertaining, about 100 people welcomed
the opening of a new Virgin Islands governor's Washington office
with great fanfare. Today, the front door to the office is
sometimes locked during business hours, while telephone calls
frequently go unreturned. Williams
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- SENSENBRENNER. He's the most senior member of the
Wisconsin delegation and has not faced major opposition in an
election since 1978. Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., chairs the
Science Committee and will play a pivotal role in the upcoming
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton, as a member of the
Judiciary Committee. (working) Marlin
</P>
