   &UR; HOME &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HOME-BUYERS (Shanghai) _ There seems to be no end to the
number of people eager to buy homes in China's cities, where a
massive conversion of housing from public to private hands means a
revolution in Chinese living standards. This year, millions of
urban families in China are buying homes for the first time. After
years of talking about it, Chinese authorities are finally getting
serious about supporting home ownership, by making mortgages
available in some cases, and by ordering local governments to do
away with state-allocated housing that has been a mainstay of the
Socialist system here. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   TUPELO-UPHOLSTERY (Tupelo, Miss.) _ The Burlington Northern
railroad cuts through downtown Tupelo, Miss., twice, at both ends,
which is a matter of about ten blocks. Standing alone at noon in a
silver shiver of 95 degree August heat on Main Street, you might
not feel like you're at the center of anything, except a train
whistle. But, if you're counting quantity, not quality of sofas,
loveseats and recliners _ is the upholstered furniture capital of
the world. There are over 230 furniture manufacturers within a
fifty mile radius, with over 26,000 employees, producing 50,000
upholstered pieces a day.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SWIMMING-POOL-DESIGN (Undated) _ The reverence most people feel
for the sight and sound of water in the garden doesn't necessarily
extend to the swimming pool. What seems the essence of serenity in
the contemplative setting of the Alhambra, or in Hockney's
aquamarine acrylics, turns garish when suburbia's acrylic pool
liners are viewed from the air. Still, swimming pools endure,
worlds unto themselves and, recently, landscape designers. By Julie
Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photo
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CT-POOL-HOUSE (Undated) _ ``We wanted clean, simple, serene,''
the owner said. ``We wanted to feel the air, the wind.'' And so his
pool-house-without-walls, in woodsy northwestern Connecticut, is no
more substantial than a breezeway with a pavilion at each end. Yet
with its playful evocation of Mies van der Rohe's pavilion in
Barcelona, Spain, and Philip Johnson's glass house in New Canaan,
Conn., it has more impact than the pool, itself. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE-CAN-DESIGN (Undated) _ It's the garbage can that got
glamour. Since its introduction two years ago, the Umbra company's
Garbo can, in black, white and translucent colors, has moved from a
best seller at such humble retailers as Linens and Things and Bed,
Bath and Beyond to become a celebrity of the design world. It's
been celebrated in the Italian design press from Domus to Interni,
the Milan-based magazine on whose current cover it appears, and
this fall will get its own ads in Vogue. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FRESH-WATER-POND (New York) _ The six teen-agers working on
the new Eib's Pond Community Park on Staten Island did not spend
their childhoods catching tadpoles in rural ponds. Before they
started work on Eib's Pond, few of them had ventured very far into
its 17 acres. Most New York City wetlands are brackish salt
marshes; Eib's Pond (pronounced ``eyebz'') is a rarity: a
freshwater pond. Covering three acres, it is the largest in the
five boroughs of the kettle ponds that were scooped out by the
retreat of the Wisconsin glacier 12,000 years ago. By Mac Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOUSE-BUYING (New York) _ So what if you're about to plunk
down a good portion of your savings _ and have pledged another
chunk of your income for the next 30 years _ on a house or
apartment you now think may have been overpriced? Or maybe it's not
overpriced _ but you think you can't afford it anymore? Or maybe
you just think that with the stock market's woes, you can get it
cheaper? That's where learning to play poker comes in. You've got
to learn when to bluff, when to stay in the game, and, of course,
when to fold. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   (With howto graphic)
</P>
