603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1993 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most do-it-yourselfers are willing to tackle furniture
restoration projects because refinishing products are readily
available and the skills needed are easy to learn. They are are
less likely to work on metal objects, like vases, plates or lamps,
because they assume that only experienced artisans can restore
metalware.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there can be difficulties in working with cast iron or
hard steel. But fortunately for the do-it-yourselfer, many
beautiful objects are made of soft metals like brass, copper,
aluminum, pewter, tin.
</P>
<P>
   Removing dents from soft metal is not difficult. The only tools
required are a hammer or mallet and an anvil. Metal smiths use a
hammer with a smooth polished face called a planishing hammer to
tamp metal, but you can use a lightweight (eight ounce) ballpeen
hammer or a wooden mallet. Use these to tap dents in flat pieces
like plates or trays.
</P>
<P>
   For working curved surfaces in vases, kettles or buckets, you
will need a special tool called a bossing mallet. The bossing
mallet has an egg-shaped head made of hard wood. Use it to reshape
curved metal surfaces. Bossing mallets are available through
mail-order suppliers that stock metal-working tools.
</P>
<P>
   The anvil is simply a hardwood surface that supports the piece
as you hammer it. If you are straightening a flat piece, the anvil
can be a plank of hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   For curved surfaces, you will have to shape a hardwood block to
match the contours of the metal piece. To reshape a metal bowl, for
example, you would need to hollow out a wooden block to the shape
of the bowl. Sometimes it takes more time to fashion the anvil than
it does to work the actual metal piece, but if the anvil is not
precise, the piece will be distorted.
</P>
<P>
   Fashioning anvils can be a lot of work, but fortunately there is
another alternative. Many metalsmiths support their work on
sandbag. These bags are made of leather and stuffed with sand. You
can make one by sewing a pouch of heavy cloth, like denim or
canvas, and filling it with sand. Press the work into the sandbag
and gently hammer out the dent. Work carefully because with the
sandbag it is possible to hammer too hard and ''out dent'' the
work.
</P>
<P>
   When the dents are removed, you can proceed to polish the piece.
Start by cleaning off all grease and dirt with a stiff-bristled
brush dipped in kerosene (kerosene is flammable so work outdoors if
possible). If there are any traces of corrosion, remove them with
crocus paper (a paper coated with jewelers rouge).
</P>
<P>
   Most metal surfaces look dull because they are covered with a
network of very fine scratches. Polishing consists of rubbing the
metal surface with fine abrasives until all the scratches are
removed. First, remove any deep scratches with fine emery cloth or
by rubbing them with a paste made of pumice powder and water.
</P>
<P>
   You can polish most metals with commercial liquids, but you get
better results _ a high polish without streaks _ by using a
polishing motor and a buffing wheel. The most useful are cloth
wheels, which are made by sewing pieces of circular cloth (muslin,
cotton or soft wool) together. Mount the wheel onto the motor with
a small screw-on clamp called an arbor.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have a polishing motor, you can chuck the
polishing wheel into a portable electric drill. Set the drill to
its highest speed (for variable speed drills) and mount it on a
stand; this will keep the drill stationary so you can hold the
work.
</P>
<P>
   Charge the wheel with polishing rouge. Rouge is mixture of red,
iron-oxide powder and hard grease that is molded into a stick.
Press the stick lightly against the revolving wheel until cloth
picks up the abrasive. Hold the work against the wheel, a little
below center, keeping it in constant motion, until the surface
acquires a bright luster.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the metal is likely to oxidize and you will have to
polish it again. To prevent this, you can apply a coat of lacquer.
The lacquer will dull the brilliance slightly and it may affect the
color of the metal, but it will coat the metal surface so it does
not tarnish. An easy way to apply an even coat of lacquer is by
spraying the piece with artist's spray fixative (one brand is
Krylon Crystal Clear).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
