<P>
   RUSSIA-SUMMIT (Moscow) _ President Clinton signaled Wednesday
that the West would be willing to expand its program of financial
assistance if Russia carried out tough economic reforms. Clinton's
message was intended to encourage the Yeltsin government to stick
with its pro-capitalist course despite the nation's deepening
economic crisis. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Moscow) _ For President Clinton, there is no
escaping Monica Lewinsky. Even within the walls of the Kremlin, at
a time when Russia is seething with political intrigue and economic
privation, Clinton was confronted with questions about his
acknowledged relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, a 25-year-old former
White House intern. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-GENOCIDE (Arusha, Tanzania) _ A U.N. tribunal
investigating mass killings in Rwanda handed down the first guilty
judgment by an international court for the crime of genocide
Wednesday. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
