<HEADLINE>
ROAD TO RECOVERY IS PAVED WITH LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cinco. Five. It took five tries, and every ounce of courage I
had, to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Five times, I grabbed my husband's arm and sank my nails deep
into his flesh. Five times, I bit my lip to muffle my agonized
screams, because my children were watching. I could feel the
stitches in my shoulder straining to hold my severed flesh
together. What held the rest of me together, I do not know.
</P>
<P>
   The pain made the Demerol evaporate like sweat on a sidewalk in
hell. On the final attempt, I did it. I managed to sit up in the
hospital bed so that I could dress and go home. It was ``day
surgery'' after all, and there was no room at the inn for the likes
of me. A mere five hours after surgery to repair the rotator cuff
in my right shoulder, I was dismissed with a warning not to drive.
I would have laughed, but it hurt to move.
</P>
<P>
   Every four hours, my husband gave me two pain pills. For three
days, I lay flat on my back and tried to avoid going to the
bathroom. To go to the bathroom, I had to sit up. That action
required using the back and shoulder muscles _ bring on the pain!
</P>
<P>
   It's been almost two weeks, and I can barely raise my right arm
enough to put on deodorant. From the shoulder to the elbow, I have
minimal strength. I'm worryied about my family and my job. I wonder
if I'll ever be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   It's a humbling experience being totally dependent on other
people, isn't it? My mother has fed me soup and wiped my mouth. My
sister combs my hair every day. My father runs errands for me. And
my husband, well, he does everything else. I do as much as I can
for myself, but I'm right-handed, and it was my right shoulder that
was sliced up.
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that, along with my family, my friends have
demonstrated their love for me in such a magnificent way that even
on my worst days, I can only manage a baby-blue mood. I didn't
expect all of the flowers and cards. And I certainly never imagined
that kind neighbors would bring my family dinner almost every day.
We're eating better now than we did before the surgery. I'm
thinking about getting this bunion removed now.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I start fretting about the future, the phone rings,
and it's someone calling to wish me a speedy recovery and remind me
to take advantage of this time to relax. I've learned a lot about
how to be a true friend during this ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're like I was before this happened, and you take
yourself for granted. You have no idea what a difference you can
make to someone who is injured, or ill, or just lonely. Will you do
me a favor? Give that someone a call and share your love. Come on.
Do it now, you've got the time. If I can type this column with one
hand, you can share a word of encouragement. Really, it means so
much. That simple gesture can turn a darkest hour into a shining
moment. Believe me, I know.
</P>
<P>
   Share some love today. It doesn't cost you anything. And that's
good news.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
