<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Generations of Hollyhocks &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. By continually purchasing lots of seeds _ 10 to 15 packs a
year _ and asking for seed of any unusual color I see in other
gardens, I have finally established a group of hollyhocks in a wide
selection of colors: peach, light and dark pinks and reds, and a
maroon that's almost black. Most are singles, but a few doubles
have accidentally been introduced. Will the colors stay true or
eventually blend because of cross-pollination? And are the doubles
likely to dominate the singles?
</P>
<P>
   A. The tall, single forms of Alcea (or Althaea) rosea, commonly
called old-fashioned hollyhocks, are classed as biennials, plants
that bloom and then die the year after they are sown. They
sometimes hang on for three or four years and may occasionally be
propagated by division. But most gardeners assure themselves of an
ongoing supply by letting the plants self-sow, and it sounds as
though you would like to do that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds from mixed plantings will not necessarily mimic their
parents. For instance, a pink flower might end up giving you seeds
for red-flowered plants. And the red plant's seeds might give you
pinks or maroons (or both). Similarly, doubles will cross with the
singles, giving you doubles, singles and semi-doubles as well.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the crossings will produce a range of colors and
numbers of petals, so as long as you have a good-size patch, you
should be able to keep a wide mixture by letting nature take its
course. Mixed hollyhocks have been grown in home gardens this way
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Not all strains are equally stable, however, so it pays to be
vigilant. If you notice a particular color or petal style starting
to take over, chances are its genes are dominant. Remove the
dominant types as soon as you see the flowers, or the recessive
colors and forms will eventually be overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to improve your chances of a stable mix by
getting seeds from one of the members of the Flower and Herb
Exchange, a project of the nonprofit Seed Savers Exchange, in
Decorah, Iowa. The exchange's 1998 yearbook, which functions as a
catalog, lists mixed-color hollyhocks from 20 different home
gardens in almost as many states, and many of them are described as
having persisted for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the Flower and Herb Exchange is $10; the address:
3076 North Winn Rd., Decorah 52101; (319) 382-5990.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving Plants &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When we left our Connecticut garden, we took a fair number of
divisions of perennials. Our new house in Delaware is supposed to
be completed in early September, but I am not optimistic. What is
the latest date you would recommend planting the divisions in the
new garden? Is there a point after which it would be better for
them to overwinter in their pots in the garage?
</P>
<P>
   And if the plants are pot-bound, would it be advisable for us to
divide before transplanting? My wife is concerned that the
divisions might be too small to be viable, whereas I would like to
get as large a planting as possible. The plants we have include
hostas, cranesbill, cornflowers, rudbeckia, campanula and
coreopsis.  &QL; 
A. The garden stalwarts on your list should survive nicely as long
as they have six weeks or so for the roots to settle in before the
ground freezes for the winter. Weather prediction is always tricky,
but let's say this means you have until mid-October to plant.
</P>
<P>
   If you notice Halloween sneaking up _ and we are, after all,
talking about house construction _ the keys to wintering over in
pots are allowing the plants to go dormant before stashing them
away, and stashing them in a place where they will stay dormant but
not frozen (32 to 45 degrees, and the less light the better).
</P>
<P>
   Don't divide the plants until spring unless it's absolutely
essential. Even if by some miracle your house is actually ready on
time, the plants should be heading toward dormancy, not being
forced to grow lots of new roots. Division is healthy in the long
run, but it does temporarily weaken plants and is best done when
they will have plenty of time to recover.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sunflowers' Toxins &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Please explain how to manage sunflowers in a garden or bed
with other plants, both while they are growing and in subsequent
years after they have grown. What can be done to prevent and
counteract any toxins they may produce?
</P>
<P>
   A. Studies conducted by the United States Department of
Agriculture have proven that sunflowers do secrete substances that
can suppress the germination and growth of other plants, but
fortunately these substances are weakest in the annual sunflowers
most commonly grown. Plants as close as a foot away show no signs
of failing to thrive, and the allelopathic (growth-inhibiting)
effect will not persist in the soil if you remove the sunflower
plants _ roots, seed hulls and all _ after they are finished for
the year. Just to be on the safe side, don't put them in the
compost.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Away, You Cats &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I dissuade roaming cats from using my flower garden
as their personal litter box and sunning area?
</P>
<P>
   A. Keeping cats from sunning themselves is about as likely as
keeping the sun itself from rising, so you might as well
concentrate on learning to admire how lovely they are when they are
lolling about.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the litter box problem, work on making sure your
garden does not resemble one. The most important thing is to remove
the main sources of litter-box odor, since cats go where their
noses tell them cats have gone before. Follow up with a commercial
cat repellent, to cover any smells that may have been left behind.
(Don't expect the repellent to perform like Hercules; you really do
have to start by cleaning up).
</P>
<P>
   Once the odor problem is solved, make it hard for them to dig
again by covering any open soil with dark-colored paper or plastic
mulch. This leaves newly planted soil as the only vulnerable area.
Cover it with chicken wire until the new plants have achieved fair
size and can be mulched, and you should have the little dears
thoroughly thwarted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pruning and Burning &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been reading a book on pruning. Several times the
author mentions removing dead, diseased or damaged branches and
burning them. He gives no explanation why burning is necessary. In
these days of recycling and compost making, is there a particular
reason he says this?  &QL; 
A. Even a well-made compost pile may not heat up enough to kill the
disease spores on sick plants, so anything of this sort you remove
should leave the garden permanently. And wood takes much longer
than other compost ingredients to decompose, even when it has been
shredded.
</P>
<P>
   Where the law still permits, the easiest way to get rid of this
stuff is to burn it. Fire is a great purifier _ no disease can
survive the heat _ and it reduces huge piles of prunings to small
piles of ash quickly.
</P>
<P>
   If open burning is out, bury any sick material at least a foot
deep, burn it in the fireplace, or send it to the landfill.
Anything that isn't sick can go through a chipper (rentable, if you
don't have one) and can then be used for mulch. Or your town may
have a ``wood dump'' to which it can be taken.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jug Irrigation &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This summer's drought and underwatering may be causing very
poor cucumber and tomato production from my raised beds. For a
simple irrigation system, a friend suggests cutting holes in the
bottoms of gallon water jugs, inverting the jugs, poking the tops
three or four inches deep into the soil six to eight inches from
the stems of the plants, and filling the jugs with water. What do
you think of this method?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not much, I'm afraid. It sounds good on paper, but in
practice you end up with a garden full of plastic jugs. This does
make a sort of sculptural statement but not one that's especially
handsome or space-efficient. As adjacent plantings grow, foliage
covers the jugs, which makes them hard to fill. Dirt falls into
them when you weed. They tend to get deposits of dead bugs, fallen
leaves and other debris, and will eventually support a nice growth
of algae.
</P>
<P>
   And they have the same drawback as all single-point
drip-irrigation systems; plants send roots to where the easy water
is instead of spreading them down and out. This makes for weak,
poorly anchored plants that are overdependent on the irrigation
source. Go away for a week or just plain forget to fill those jugs,
and your plants are toast. Soaker-hose systems take longer to set
up, but they work better in the long run, are less obtrusive and
better for the plants.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
