<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FRESHWATER-POND-AR     09-02 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FRESHWATER-POND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAXING A STATEN ISLAND WALDEN BACK TO IDYLLIC SPLENDOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., N.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MAC GRISOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The six teen-agers who worked on the new Eib's Pond
Community Park on Staten Island this summer did not spend their
childhoods catching tadpoles. Even though they live nearby, few had
ventured very far into the 17 wetland acres, which were fenced with
metal guard rails and filled with the rusted hulks of more than 20
abandoned cars. The park borders some of Staten Island's
highest-density and lowest-income housing, and is within walking
distance for thousands in the Clifton area.
</P>
<P>
   Most New York City wetlands are salt marshes; Eib's Pond
(pronounced eyebz) is a rarity: a freshwater pond. Covering three
acres, it is the largest in the five boroughs of the kettle ponds
that were scooped out by the retreat of the Wisconsin glacier
12,000 years ago. The water level in Eib's Pond, actually a series
of three clay-bottomed ponds linked by wetlands, is replenished
only by runoff and rain, and so varies strikingly from season to
season, making it a home for a wide variety of plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Eib's Pond is named after the 19th-century family that used it
as a watering hole for their livestock. In 1843, Henry David
Thoreau spent the summer nearby. ``The cedar seems to be one of the
most common trees here, and the fields are fragrant with it,'' he
wrote on May 22. He describes gum and tulip trees, native
honeysuckle, meadows red with Indian paintbrush and fence rows
crowded with seedling peach trees. ``The whole island is like a
garden,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Being the kind of ecumenical observer he was (admiring even the
dead fish washed up on Staten Island's shore), Thoreau would
probably still think Eib's Pond was special. Studies have shown
both soil and water to be startlingly clean. Bulrushes, cattails,
cinnamon fern, sassafras and other native plants thrive despite
rampaging exotics like porcelain berry, phragmites and mugwort.
Frogs, fish, painted turtles and muskrats attest to the water
quality. Waterlilies bloom. Blue herons, ducks and snowy egrets
nest.
</P>
<P>
   Because urban wetlands are usually polluted, they are often
handed over to professionals _ engineers, ecologists and landscape
architects. What distinguishes the Eib's Pond project, now in its
second year, is how it offers ecologically sound landscape design
that lay people can use. For the minority youth of this particular
neighborhood, seeing their own designs take shape was empowering.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Hood, a professor of landscape architecture at the
College of Environmental Design of the University of California at
Berkeley, explained why there are so few black landscape
architects. ``It's a luxury profession,'' he said. ``If you are
from the projects in Orange, N.J., and the first in your family to
go to college, your career decision is going to be closely tied to
economics. Law or medical school, or business administration _
those are the ways to make big money, not landscape architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, there is low visibility within the field of education.
How many colleges teach landscape or environmental studies as a
profession? Last, there are no role models in popular culture. The
closest we get to a professional profile is the architect in Spike
Lee's `Jungle Fever.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hood went to an all-black college in North Carolina, the
Agricultural and Technical State University in Greensboro, which
had one of the first undergraduate landscape programs in the
country. There he met Charles Fountain, a professor of landscape
design who had received his degree from the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The young Staten Islanders were employed by the Urban
Conservation Corps, the summer jobs program run by the Parks
Council, a nonprofit advocates' group. Eib's Pond falls under the
Parks Council's Green Neighborhoods program, which program director
Sean Andrews said requires strong local partners. In this case, the
partners are the Rev. Hattie Smith Davis, head of the Fox Hills
Tenant Association, and the local community board chairman, George
Caputo, a longtime Eib's Pond fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   A powerhouse of a woman, Ms. Davis is also an honorary member of
the local police force. She runs year-round after-school and summer
programs for more than 100 children, and also teaches baking.
</P>
<P>
   Eib's Pond has always had a system of trails, and secret
entrances on each side. Visitors in the past were evenly divided
between fishermen and drug dealers. Quixotically, however, Eib's
has also been a precious refuge. ``It's a place to listen to
quietness,'' Ms. Davis said. ``When troubled kids ran away from
home, they would head in there. But they'd tell me where they were
going.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Parks Council first appeared, Ms. Davis and the
neighborhood were wary of any attempt to better the pond. Ms. Davis
has a Thoreau-like attitude toward the place: ``At first I wanted
to keep the old cars where they were. The fish had got used to
them, and the birds sat on their tops, just like people get used to
living in certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have much that's ours,'' she continued, ``and we
wanted to make sure Eib's would go on being ours.'' Concerns abated
when she met Sari Weissman, a student from the Harvard Graduate
School of Design, who came to Eib's Pond last summer, and Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I met Sean and Sari,'' she said, ``I could see they were
here not to take but to give.'' Besides, she said, her 10-year-old
grandson convinced her Eib's needed some changes. ``Grandma,'' he
told her, ``the fish can't drive the cars, and why can't the birds
be in the trees?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weissman developed the guidelines for the park and hacked
out the first new paths last summer with help from Ms. Davis, local
teen-agers and environmental experts marshaled by the Parks
Council. For seven weeks this summer, a new crew pulled weeds, did
cleanups, and kept journals of their work.
</P>
<P>
   They also attended design workshops and visited and critiqued
other parks. They learned that paths had to be accessible to the
handicapped but that in a protected wetland, paths must follow
existing topographic lines, because the land cannot be graded.
</P>
<P>
   They helped to build and install a redwood bridge and
observation deck with cantilevered seats. To do so, they had to
pour concrete pilings in a swampy bottom. None of them had poured
concrete before, not even Ms. Weissman, but they managed. (Before
the bridge was built, getting across this stretch of marsh had been
an athletic event requiring climbing into and out of an old car
lying in the mud.)
</P>
<P>
   As the team discovered the landscape, they discovered themselves
and their skills. Kadedra Butler became so well known for her
ability with the hoe that the Parks Council gave her the tool to
keep. ``I'm going to carve my name and the date in the handle,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   William Arce captured every flower with his pencil. His caption
for a glowing drawing of a waterlily reads, ``I like this flower
because it brings out the beauty in the wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   Moshia Dupree admitted that the job was different from what he
had expected. ``I didn't think I'd be planting trees,'' he said.
``I thought I'd be pulling weeds. And birds _ I never knew there
were so many different kinds of exotic birds out there, like that
blue heron. I've started to get people to come to see how it looks,
so they won't be destroying it any more.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the summer, the workers were given their own cedar
trees to plant anywhere in the park. ``I planted mine next to the
first pond,'' Moshia said. ``Now I come down there to water it
because new trees need water. Last weekend there was a whole bunch
of people in the park, children on the bench and all. They said,
`You did this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Moshia, who lives two minutes by bus from the pond, wants to
work in the park again next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you find something that you really like, that you
can keep your mind on,'' he said. ``Who knows? Maybe I'll be a
botanist someday. I already took biology and earth science, and I'm
good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Eib's Pond Community Park will again exhale the fragrance
of Thoreau's cedar trees. ``I see the Bible,'' Ms. Davis said,
describing what Eib's Pond's regeneration means to her. ``Genesis
1:29: He has given us every herb of the earth. These things were
there all the time, but to find them was the revelation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
