A5421 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-02 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOV. GARRY MAURO' NOT MOST TEXANS' VISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garry Mauro is on a roll. The latest Texas Poll shows that he's
gained six points in his race to unseat Gov. George W. Bush, which
means that Bush's lead is down to a razor-thin 47 points.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the campaign, the Texas Poll gave Bush a 53-point
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro boasted that he would close the gap as the Nov. 3 election
drew closer; and, by golly, his prediction came true. At this rate,
Mauro might be able to cut the deficit down to a measly 30 or 40
points by Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks. The 1998 election for governor of Texas
was over long ago. It was probably over before Mauro decided to
run. It was certainly over once Mauro hit the campaign trail and
started trying to peddle his pie-in-the-sky agenda to the Texas
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   As the Texas Poll poll testifies, voters in the Lone Star State
are much too smart to be taken in by the promise-now, pay-later
malarkey of an old-fashioned tax-and-spend Democrat such as Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate who has no chance of winning enjoys a certain
freedom, of course: the freedom to make wild-eyed promises that he
will never be expected to keep. Among Mauro's more outrageous
promises: unaffordable pay raises and signing bonuses for
schoolteachers, and unachievable changes in health care.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro says that his people have knocked on more than 1 million
doors in his quest to prevent Bush from becoming the first Texas
governor to win election to consecutive four-year terms.
Unfortunately for Mauro, he could knock on every door in Texas and
never alter the undeniable reality of the election: Bush has done
an outstanding job as governor, and Texas voters know it.
</P>
<P>
   So do voters in other states, which is why we keep hearing all
this talk about Bush being a front-runner for the Republican
presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's backers have complained that Bush spends too much time
out of the state _ supposedly promoting his presidential ambitions
_ but they should be grateful to all those out-of-state candidates
who have been asking the Texas governor to help them raise money.
If Bush has racked up a 47-point lead while taking time to visit
other states, how breathtaking an advantage would he have if he'd
been campaigning as hard as Mauro has in recent months?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Mauro camp's wish for Bush to spend more time
in Texas will come true after the governor's trips this week to
Illinois, Georgia, Arizona and Colorado. It surely won't be long
before Mauro will be longing for the good old days, when he had the
field more or less to himself.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush spending more time on the campaign trail and Mauro
looking to his pal Bill Clinton for help on the hustings _ well,
there's no telling how devastating the Bush landslide might be.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Bush undertook his campaign against incumbent
Ann Richards as the underdog, trailing in most polls by double
digits. The so-called experts were certain that Richards'
popularity was so overwhelming that she would breeze to
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But Richards' popularity was based on her status as a celebrity,
not her performance as governor. She was the state's official
stand-up comic, regaling Texans with folksy witticisms and scathing
wit; she attempted to defeat Bush by insulting him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead in the polls is a different story. This governor is
popular because he has done what he promised to do when he asked
voters to support him back in 1994. He is popular because he has a
vision for the state and he has demonstrated the ability to achieve
it.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro constantly accuses Bush of being out of touch with
ordinary Texans, but it is Mauro who is out of touch. Bush promises
limited government intrusion into the lives of Texans; Mauro
promises more state interference in education and health care. Bush
promises an era of personal responsibility; Mauro promises
ever-increasing dependence on the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Mauro camp says the Texas Poll is flawed. Could be.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead might be bigger than the poll says it is.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
