<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BIORHYTHMS-NYT &LR;      09-02 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BIORHYTHMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGE THINGS HAPPENING? BLAME YOUR BIORHYTHMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You oversleep and walk in late and unironed for your Big
Meeting, plus you're limping from tripping over the curb on the way
in. Mama said there'd be days like this, and now she can call up a
Web-based biorhythm calculator on her laptop and warn you ahead of
time _ all in good fun, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The pseudoscience of biorhythms, sometimes thought of as on a
par with astrology _ except that the fault, dear Web surfer, lies
within you instead of with the stars _ has been around for a
century, and the Internet offers many sites that will let you plot
your own. All you need is a birthdate and a browser.
</P>
<P>
   Two popular sites with biorhythm calculators are Web-O-Rhythm
(www.qns.com/html/weborhythm) and Life Sines (www.lifesines.com),
but there are plenty more out there. Just do a search for
``biorhythms,'' and you'll probably score a few hits for sites
offering similar programs for downloading.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that biological rhythms affect emotions, alertness
and readiness to mate, among other things, was developed from about
1897 to 1932 by medical doctors in Paris, Berlin and Vienna,
Austria, as well as Philadelphia and other cities. The basic
biorhythm chart has three undulating lines crossing a horizontal
line. The wavy lines represent the physical, the emotional and the
mental, or intellectual, cycles of a person over a period of time.
</P>
<P>
   On a basic biorhythm chart, which is based on one's birthdate,
the physical cycle lasts 23 days, the emotional cycle 28 days and
the mental cycle 33 days. The first half of each cycle, falling
above the chart's horizontal line, is considered to be positive,
while the second half, below the line, is thought to influence
those particular aspects negatively.
</P>
<P>
   The days on the chart when each cycle crosses the line are said
to be ``critical.'' When two or more cycles hit the same critical
day, bad things will happen, believers say, but these days are easy
enough to predict, supposedly, with the aid of mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual curves are generally plotted as sine waves of the
appropriate length,'' said Jeff Jetton, a programmer with a
biorhythm program for the Pilot (www.mindspring.com/ jetton/pilot).
``Who said you'd never use trigonometry again?''
</P>
<P>
   While certain circadian rhythms (like digestive timetables, the
sleep-wake cycle and hormone activity) have been shown to exist in
all sorts of organisms, the human biorhythms described above are
thought by most scientists to be mere whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons cited is that natural rhythms in living
organisms approximate regular cycles but vary in exact cycle
lengths because of environmental and other factors and could never
maintain the rigidly precise period lengths described in the
biorhythm hypothesis.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific papers addressing biorhythms, but not supporting the
biorhythm concept, have been published in The New England Journal
of Medicine and The Journal of Safety Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I haven't come across any experimental evidence,
which is not to say that there isn't any out there, so I remain a
skeptic,'' Jetton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it's a fun theory,'' he added, ``and very useful for
giving an excuse for locking your keys in the car or blowing off
your workout.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
