   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DOW-MYTHS _ A look at the myths and realities of the stock
market. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-LAYOFFS _ Northwest Airlines laid off 27,500 employees
_ more than half its staff. Checking to see how many if any of
those laid off are mechanics at Hartsfield. The White House urged
both sides to resume negotiations. Federal mediators sought a
meeting with both sides. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS _ A good part of the new wealth created in Austin in the
1990s has been tied to the stock market, much of it to the
incredible rise in Dell Computer's stock over the past four years.
But not every technology company has created a huge base of wealth
workers. At VTEL, for instance, the stock price has dropped well
below the option excercise price for many workers. For the time
being, at least, those options are worth zero. (Ladendorf, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DAY-TRADERS _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ If any investor can stand up to
the gut-wrenching swings of this week's volatile stock market, it's
a day trader like Andy Friis. He is one of a new breed of investor
who earns his daily bread by squeezing fractional profits from each
share he buys and selling as a stock rolls in one direction or
another. (Pounds, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SILVER-LINING _ Domestic stock markets' free fall Monday and
partial recovery Tuesday proved that at least one cliche has some
cachet: The dark cloud over the markets does indeed have a silver
lining. On Monday, when the market fell a staggering 512 points,
veteran money managers figured, hey, it's a buying opportunity. The
lurking bear produced some pretty good bargains in solid companies.
(Utley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
