<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIMMING-POOL-DESIGN-     09-02 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIMMING-POOL-DESIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POOL: NATURAL, OR UNNATURAL, PHENOMENON? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reverence most people feel for the sight and sound of water
in the garden doesn't necessarily extend to the swimming pool. What
seems the essence of serenity in the contemplative setting of the
Alhambra, or in Hockney's aquamarine acrylics, turns garish when
suburbia's acrylic pool liners are viewed from the air.
</P>
<P>
   Still, swimming pools endure, some strong, worlds unto
themselves and, recently, landscape designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing about pools is how completely they are
about artifice,'' said Michael Van Valkenburgh, a landscape
architect and a professor of landscape architecture at Harvard
University. ``There's nothing that could be less of nature than a
swimming pool.''
</P>
<P>
   The term ``natural'' in pool design today might mean anything
from a bathhouse with a Darth Vader flying-insect force field to
concrete lava rocks and simulated waterfalls (favored by new luxury
hotels) to an invented pool-as-pond with imported,
wild-at-the-edges prairie grasses. Even shade has become a modifier
of pool design, says James van Sweden, a landscape architect in
Washington, as people forgo deep tans for a cancer-free pallor.
</P>
<P>
   In Bel Air, Calif., at the home of the interior designer Rose
Tarlow, a pond-like pool in a wooded clearing is the visual
equivalent of the meditative mantra ``om.'' On one of those steep
and prickly California slopes made famous during mud slides, it
seems as untouched as if Tarzan and Jane had just stumbled upon it.
``Rose told me she wanted it to look like it has always been there,
like you just happened upon it in a forest,'' said Los Angeles
landscape designer Edina Weinstein. ``My first reaction was, `Oh,
sure.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Designed as a large circle, the pool is 20 feet in diameter and
comes within eight feet of the climbing slope. Standing hard by is
a pagoda-shaped pavilion providing shade, where Ms. Tarlow can read
and paint. At 10-by-10-feet square, it is made of plaster with
small holes in it to encourage climbing vines. An extravagantly
peaked roof made of 17th-century slate tiles that Ms. Tarlow
brought home from England insures the pavilion's status as a folly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like those turquoise pools,'' Ms. Tarlow said. ``I
like large pools that don't fight the landscape.'' Achieving the
just-excavated look took a herculean effort: far from fighting the
landscape, the pool and pavilion are trying hard not to succumb to
it. Their small pad of land required retaining walls worthy of a
fortress to protect it from the slippery slope. Disguising those
walls with local plant materials ``that looked like they came from
where we are, not Connecticut,'' became Ms. Weinstein's main
challenge. ``A natural California hillside in August is not a
beautiful sight,'' she said. ``There aren't enough nutrients in the
soil to go for the overplanted look.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weinstein's solution was to encourage and embellish on such
natives as pine, oleander, the bushy silver berry and the vinous
clematis. She was also careful to select plants unappealing to the
many deer that roam the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The pool itself lies almost even with the ground. Ms. Tarlow
envisioned greenery overrunning the coping and obliterating the
edge between water and earth. The landscape designer suggested
creeping thyme as ground cover but that would necessitate stepping
stones _ or shoes _ to negotiate the walk from bathhouse to pool.
Going barefoot is elemental to the illusion Ms. Tarlow had in mind,
and so grass covers the ground around the pool, which is approached
along a rustic processional of railroad ties as steps, with sod
risers.
</P>
<P>
   Pools don't always get so much attention. Landscape
Architecture, the industry magazine, hasn't written about them in
years, says its editor, Anne Powell. van Sweden, author of
``Gardening With Water'' (Random House, 1995), estimates that fewer
than 40 percent of the more than 400 gardens he has designed
include pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pools used to look like bathtubs sitting out there,'' he said.
``And they're unsightly in winter with those covers.'' When he does
design swimming pools he draws inspiration from ``the utter
naturalness'' of a tropical garden pool in Rio de Janeiro designed
by Roberto Burle Marx, which was made by damming a river. He finds
that the swimming pool as pond or lily pool has become more popular
than pools with the so-called infinity edge, where water
overflowing the coping seems to melt into the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now everyone wants a circular pool with a negative edge and
the lawn right up to the coping,'' said van Sweden, who warns
homeowners finnicky about keeping their pools clean to think twice
about this leaf-prone variety.
</P>
<P>
   For a pool that he designed in Bedford, N.Y., van Sweden nestled
a 75-foot-long irregular oval pool into a natural outcropping of
rocks along a wooded site. His coping is covered with fountain
grass that doesn't shed but helps to soften the pool's edge. A pool
house designed by the architectural firm Shope Reno Wharton takes
up the cause of nature with a twist: for supports the designers
used rough-hewn stone columns with a gray slate roof inspired by
the 19th-century park structures of Frederick Law Olmsted. ``Ever
since I had skin cancers removed I've been interested in making
sure that the pools I design get plenty of shade,'' van Sweden
said.
</P>
<P>
   What his clients really want, van Sweden confessed, is a
pond-like pool at least 50 feet across the middle _ large enough to
do laps, its bottom painted a mottled midnight blue. Of his latest
pool commissions, van Sweden said, ``I find a single lane marker
across the bottom like a zipper looks great _ and very stylized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
