<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5441 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GUITAR-CDROMS-2TA     09-02 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GUITAR-CDROMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING AND STRUMMING LESSONS VIA DISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matt Resnicoff, a former senior editor at Musician magazine, is a
writer, producer and guitarist based in New York.  
 By MATT RESNICOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To play the guitar _ and to play it well _ do you have to learn
music theory? According to Sabina Skalar, a developer of the eMedia
guitar-education course reviewed below, the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't want all this difficult stuff thrown at
them,'' Ms. Skalar said in a breathless rush that I might have
dismissed as hucksterism if she weren't also a first violinist with
the New York City Ballet orchestra. ``If you're just into the
enjoyment of music, you can live your whole life without learning
the theory.''
</P>
<P>
   As a lowly scribe, I was tempted to hold my tongue rather than
debate with a professional. And yet, as a guitar student whose
initial fear of music theory resulted in years of frustration, I
was rankled by her pessimism about fledgling guitarists.
</P>
<P>
   The argument, after all, was coming from a woman whose career
(and presumably her greatest joy) hangs on her ability to glance at
a piece of written music and give it life through her instrument.
Are we guitarists not entitled to the same pleasure?
</P>
<P>
   Despite its occasionally brutish role in rock, the guitar is a
complex and unforgiving beast that many introductory methods have
attempted to tame through oversimplification. But saying that music
theory encumbers students is like suggesting that learning a
foreign language does not really require knowing what the new words
mean, as long as you can form them with your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   There is a huge gulf between truly learning the guitar and
merely acquiring the muscle memory necessary to reproduce sounds
heard in most of the popular songs we know.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, some of the following guitar programs feed the
hope that you can play immediately, and they even make good on the
promise by demonstrating how to operate the instrument on its most
basic level. Some avoid the fast path, covering admittedly tedious
studies like sight reading and ear training.
</P>
<P>
   Others fall prey to the use of chord dictionaries, which offer
diagrams or photos of the guitar neck being gripped this way or
that to form a given chord, often without indicating that there are
countless other colorful ways to voice such chords.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of this software succumbs to the lure of a system
known as tablature, a bane of guitar education, used by magazines
like Guitar, that hawks hit songs on fingering-by-the-numbers
grids. While tablature can be an aid, it is more often a crutch for
the able-minded and can hobble the process of decoding passages by
ear, transcribing them and eventually grasping why they were played
that way in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that the guitar should be taught any less
methodically than other instruments is precisely what has corrupted
its evolution and promotes its misuse in popular music.
</P>
<P>
   This is no stylistic bias. I started as a rock player and love
rock dearly, but I cannot in good conscience recommend any CD-ROM
without an accompanying text like Mick Goodrick's ``The Advancing
Guitarist,'' a book to shatter the imprisonment of chord ``grips''
if ever there was one.
</P>
<P>
   Using the best of these programs with unfailing patience, you
can begin a fruitful relationship with this perplexing instrument.
Despite its occasional clumsiness, the computer gives ample
leverage in taming the beast, although processor speed alone can't
accelerate the process.
</P>
<P>
   One sage teacher, Joe Diorio, once offered the best bromide to
anyone hungering for proficiency on the guitar. ``It doesn't come
when you're ready,'' he said. ``It comes when it's ready.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Lighthearted Approach, But a Solid Information Base &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUITAR 101/THE FENDER METHOD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (G-Vox Interactive Music; $39.99; Macintosh and Windows 95.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most introductory guitar software, Guitar 101 does not
throw a folio of familiar songs at you until after you've completed
an extensive, well-paced tutorial on the basics of music theory and
the physical aspects of playing. That includes everything from the
definitions of sharps and flats to the proper methods for holding
and fingering the guitar without unnecessary physical tension.
</P>
<P>
   The program has several virtual classrooms, with periodic visits
from the teacher who designed the course, a sort of
Stratocaster-toting Wilfred-Brimley-meets-Max-Headroom character
seen only on a television monitor. Exercises and quizzes conclude
each section.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an introductory sequence that comes off like an
infomercial for Fender guitars, Guitar 101 is quite approachable,
even in showing how hard-won music knowledge will support any style
of playing.
</P>
<P>
   Though more extravagant graphically than the average tutorial,
the visuals seem incidental (each ``new'' classroom simply
rearranges the furniture of the previous chamber, and for some
reason a clock perpetually reads 3:20).
</P>
<P>
   The program has a few weaknesses: Spoken and written text often
reiterates points made by a woefully underused tour guide, the
brilliant Los Angeles guitarist Carl Verheyen.
</P>
<P>
   The guitar neck is explored through well-designed ascending and
descending drills. Preprogrammed accompaniments actually harmonize
and ``musicalize'' the most rudimentary open-string exercises,
allowing the simplist exercises to feel like actual music-making.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying ``band'' _ admittedly a stiff lot of simulated
hacks _ manages to get progressively hipper in its support as the
work intensifies. Because it's less dependent on tunes and relies
on intriguing musical subtleties like these, this fine CD is for
players seeking more complete control of the guitar from their
first lesson on. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lots of On-Screen Options And a Band to Back You Up &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLAY GUITAR WITH ROSS BOLTON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Play Music Inc.; $49.95; Windows 95, 98 and NT.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The merits of the CD-ROM as a surrogate music instructor are
best seen in this program's interface, which adds unlikely
conveniences to such computer inevitabilities as small-screen video
clips bordered with written music and tiny on-screen buttons.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the windows themselves can be moved, so the screen can
be organized to taste. The videos, which include demonstrations of
chord forms, melodic passages and technical advice, can be shuttled
in real time like a VCR, allowing for an examination of the
teacher's fingerings.
</P>
<P>
   The options for viewing the program's animated guitar neck are
panoramic: Dots dancing on the fretboard can be seen from overhead,
from directly across, from a birds'-eye view and even from the
vantage of a lefty.
</P>
<P>
   Subtle frills aside, Play Guitar excels at putting forth pivotal
music fundamentals, but here again, the features are nearly
unprecedented. In the performance videos, the instructor's guitar
can be muted so you can practice the material backed by a band of
real musicians rather than synthesized digital accompaniment. A
loop feature lets you select with precision those passages within
the section that you wish to hone.
</P>
<P>
   A formal practice mode ends each section, and a virtual mixing
console allows complete control over the blend of the background
music. In on-screen text, underlined words, when clicked, fly you
into a glossary of terms defined through voice-overs, staves and
sound samples.
</P>
<P>
   This is also one of the few CD-ROMs available that does an
adequate job instilling the concept of triads and the idea that a
common chord ``grip'' is but one voicing, or arrangement of notes,
that characterize a given chord.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with this understanding, you maintain a good chance of
escaping the prison of rote finger motion that locks so many
players into always playing chords in the same way. A personal
history menu shows you the topics you have already covered, which
really helps in a program with so many lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Two gripes here: Traditional staff notation is used in only
parts of the program and is inexplicably absent on far too many
screens. And the discussion of changing keys is based on a device
known as the capo, which is basically a clip that depresses all the
strings at a chosen fret, freeing the player from that pesky
musical skill known as transposing. Until a capo is invented for
the cerebrum, the device cannot be mentioned responsibly in a
beginning guitar course. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Well-Paced Music Tutorial &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUITROPOLIS: AN ADVENTURE IN LEARNING TO PLAY THE GUITAR  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alfred Publishing; $49.95; Macintosh and Windows 3.1 and 95.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As if navigating Superlocrian scales and fingering complex
chords were not enough strain on an aspiring guitarist, Alfred
Publishing offers an instructional game in which students must
simultaneously learn the basics of playing and conquer a virtual
city. In some ways, to navigate the surreal Guitropolis is to see
the actual vagaries of the musician's life: tune an instrument
incorrectly and a geeky music-store clerk jeers and goads; seek
admission to a record mogul's office and be rebuffed because you
haven't mastered your sight reading.
</P>
<P>
   In its attempt to superimpose slick game graphics onto
interactive educational features, Alfred has created a lighthearted
but respectable course providing a solid base of musical
information. The game aspects overwhelms their own purpose at
times, as with the virtual tuning, which replicates the process
about as accurately as a skiing program simulates chapped lips.
</P>
<P>
   Some games make their point effectively: after two hours of
shooting savage airborne alien quarter notes, you'll never forget
how many beats there are in a measure. But such exercises are more
likely to induce carpal tunnel syndrome than excessive practicing
on a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the user will naturally yearn for liberation
from the tyrannical test-and-reward methodology that governs
Guitropolis, the package also thoughtfully includes a no-frills,
nongame version of the instructional method. There is also an
online guitar tuner and a rudimentary chord reference.
</P>
<P>
   Each lesson is distilled into informative screens and exercises,
which eventually allow for practice of rock, metal, country and
jazz chord progressions, Although traditional staff notation is
fully integrated, I can't envision Juilliard adopting Guitropolis
just yet. Classicists are partial to Asteroids. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good Program for Beginners, Though Short on Notation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EMEDIA GUITAR METHOD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Volumes 1 and 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (eMedia Corp.; $59.95; Macintosh and Windows 3.1 and 95.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A beginners' program emphasizing folk and rock, because these
styles are based in simple, fixed chords strummed in varying
rhythms, the eMedia 1 course focuses its strongest portions on
right-hand techniques. It explains how the pick is held and
dissects the system of rests and pick strokes that propel this
music.
</P>
<P>
   Each concept uses relatively well-known songs as a reference,
and a recorded version can often be run at fast or slow speeds.
On-line videos demonstrate individual topics with a warm, if static
demeanor; ``talk'' buttons offer gentle encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, eMedia 1 completely avoids the use of traditional
staff notation in lessons on melody, and it fails to define the
function of notes within common chords. It also neglects to mention
the fundamental harmonic and structural role of chords in pop and
blues. While these may indeed lie beyond the course's intended
scope, a hint here and there would undoubtedly lay some groundwork
to help students in further study.
</P>
<P>
   When the course does offer alternatives to grips, it scarcely
names the new chords or the notes that create them.
</P>
<P>
   Both eMedia volumes are song-based. An on-screen recording
feature allows you to lay down chords or melodies and play along
with them. Chord inversions are introduced but not explained
adequately, and no distinction is made between the qualities that
make a chord major or minor.
</P>
<P>
   The eMedia 2 CD-ROM offers a choice of tablature
(fingering-by-number grids) or standard musical notation, therefore
correcting some of the missteps of the first volume. The level of
playing is high, particularly in the classical tunes and a
late-period blues-rock offering from Jeff Beck.
</P>
<P>
   To tackle the material offered in eMedia 2 is a significant
accomplishment, and the program ably sets the student on the right
path.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
