<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN03-COX     09-02 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stock market still beats Social Security
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEW! Good thing Americans haven't yet convinced Congress to
invest their Social Security taxes in the stock market. Look at the
hit they'd have taken!
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly the line we expect to hear in coming days from
the detractors of Social Security privatization. They'll point to
the market's gyrations _ Monday's 512-point loss and Tuesday's
288-point gain _ and say market volatility and sudden, unexplained
drops are exactly why Americans shouldn't tie their retirement
hopes to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   We couldn't disagree more. Wall Street's troubles give us no
reason to back away from our support for allowing Americans to
invest a portion of their Social Security taxes in stock and bond
markets. They'll still do far better than they would under Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious risks associated with investing in the stock
market, as Monday's drop proved. The U.S. economy is not
recession-proof, nor can it be insulated from foreign financial
crises such as those in Asia and Russia. The history of business
cycles shows recessions follow economic expansions, like the
eight-year run we've just experienced.
</P>
<P>
   But neither is Social Security risk-free. Every time Congress
cuts benefits, raises the retirement age or increases payroll
taxes, your Social Security ``investment'' takes a dive. Since
1950, payroll taxes have climbed 1,200 percent. Benefits have
increased by only a third as much. Guess who eats the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, over the long haul, even accounting for drops like
those we've seen recently, private markets provide far better
returns than Social Security. From 1926 to 1996, stocks averaged an
annual return of 10.89 percent _ despite the Great Depression,
World War II, Vietnam, Watergate, the oil crisis and the market
crash of October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security, meanwhile, provides a negative return for
millions of Americans, and a paltry return of 2 or 3 percent for
single-income families with children. Private markets, even with
declines like Monday's, will beat Social Security every time. The
market's worst long-term performance, a 3.36 percent return from
1929 to 1948, beats expected returns from Social Security. Over the
course of a working career, about 46 years, the market's worst
performance (from 1929-1974) generated a 7.32 percent return.
Social Security doesn't come close.
</P>
<P>
   If Monday's decline scares you away from privatizing Social
Security, consider the accompanying chart. It shows how far the
market would have to fall to match the low level of return from
Social Security for a low-wage worker.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, privatizing Social Security doesn't mean every
American must ride Wall Street's roller coaster. Americans could
choose a level of risk that fits their situation: Workers nearing
retirement could choose risk-free T-bills, while 25-year-olds could
bet on risky stocks. The current system provides no such
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fool's game to point to a blip in time, like Monday, and
make long-term financial decisions affecting millions of Americans'
retirement. Despite the drop, and subsequent free falls that are
sure to come, investing in equities over the long haul remains a
wise choice _ as millions of working people have shown by retaining
their 401(k) investments. Monday's drop shouldn't slow the drive
toward privatizing Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman is the associate editorial page editor for the
Atlanta Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
