<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5447 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YELTISN-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      09-02 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTISN-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS COMBATIVE COMMENTS IN SEX SCANDAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A weary President Clinton on Wednesday dismissed
critics' suggestions that he no longer is an effective leader and
defended his combative Aug. 17 address to the nation as an
expression of ``profound regret'' to all who have been hurt by the
sex scandal overshadowing his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton turned aside an opportunity to issue a formal apology
for misleading Americans about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky and offered a somewhat revisionist view of his nationally
televised address last month.
</P>
<P>
   At a summit-ending news conference with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, Clinton faced reporters for the first time since
acknowledging to the nation that he had an inappropriate
relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have stepped up their calls for Clinton's
resignation as Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr wraps up an
investigation into allegations that Clinton lied in sworn testimony
and obstructed justice in trying to conceal the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was no longer as effective as he should be, Clinton
said: ``No, I've actually been quite heartened by the reaction of
the American people and leaders throughout the world about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show a majority of the American people dislike Clinton's
personal conduct but don't want him ousted as president because of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake, said that I
regretted it, asked to be forgiven, spent a lot of very valuable
time with my family in the last couple of weeks and said I was
going back to work,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent 13 days on vacation at Martha's Vineyard with
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and daughter Chelsea for what
aides described as a healing session for the family. The first
lady, portrayed as hurt but committed to her marriage, accompanied
the president to Russia and left Wednesday for Northern Ireland
ahead of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he felt the need to issue a formal apology and if
he regretted the tone of his national address, Clinton sidestepped
the question. He said he had recently reread the four-minute
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was clear that I was expressing my profound
regret to all who were hurt and to all who were involved and my
desire not to see anymore people hurt by this process and caught up
in it,'' Clinton said. He appeared to be extending his regrets to
others, such as Lewinsky, who reportedly was hurt that she received
no apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to say was that I believe it's time for us to now
go back to the work of the country and give the people their
government back and talk about and think about and work on things
that will affect the American people today and in the future,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also disclosed, for the first time, that Clinton
has discussed the scandal, in general terms, with world leaders,
whose names were not revealed. The leaders reportedly offered words
of support and encouragement that Clinton and the United States
will maintain an international leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Clinton told the nation that his answers, in a
deposition in the Paula Jones harassment case, denying a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky were legally accurate but misleading. He
expressed regret for misleading Americans, but did not ask
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, I did have a relationship with Miss Lewinsky that was
not appropriate. In fact, it was wrong. It constituted a critical
lapse in judgment and a personal failure on my part for which I am
solely and completely responsible,'' Clinton said in his nationally
televised address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that my public comments and my silence about this
matter gave a false impression. I misled people, including even my
wife. I deeply regret that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Aug. 17 address came hours after he testified before
Starr's grand jury via closed-circuit television from the White
House. During the address, Clinton appeared angry and combative as
he attacked Starr for continuing the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Aides had hoped the national confession would allow Clinton to
put the issue behind him. However, many critics believed it fell
short of a sincere apology and Democrats on Capitol Hill have
distanced themselves from the president.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complain the scandal is overshadowing the issues they
want to highlight in their quest to reclaim the House from
Republican control. Led by Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas, many
Republicans have called for Clinton's resignation even before
receiving Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton indirectly addressed the issue last week when, on a
break from his vacation, he spoke at Union Chapel on Martha's
Vineyard to mark the 35th anniversary of the civil rights March on
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you know, I'm having to become quite an expert in this
business of asking for forgiveness,'' he told a racially diverse
audience that had warmly embraced him. ``It gets a little easier
the more you do it. And if you have a family, an administration, a
Congress and a whole country to ask you, you're going to get a lot
of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Clinton had addressed the issue of
forgiveness, saying he learned anew that in order to get it, one
must give it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had anticipated questions about Lewinsky because it was
his first meeting with reporters since the television speech.
However, Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., one of five members of Congress
traveling with Clinton, cornered the Reuters reporter who asked a
Lewinsky question and, waving his finger, said ``Speaking as an
American, I'm outraged.'' He said the media should ``drop its
obsession'' with Lewinsky because Americans don't care.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee will consider calling impeachment
hearings once it receives Starr's report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
