u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-REDJACK-GAME-NYT &LR;      09-02 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-REDJACK-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TITLE ON THE CUTLASS EDGE OF SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn.)   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When your dramatic palette is limited, pirates are a fairly good
bet. As long as you stick to the accepted ``Treasure Island'' ideas
about how they're supposed to dress (earrings, tattoos, beards,
rough-hewn prosthetic limbs) act (crude, jolly, brutal) and speak
(``Yarrrr!!!!''), you can swashbuckle your way through a story
without too much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   By its very nature, swashbuckling is a theater of broad
gestures, and sword-fighting spectacles on the high seas can
succeed on the basis of sheer kinetic energy. It worked when silent
films made the transition to sound _ directors didn't really know
what they were doing with dialogue, but Errol Flynn and Basil
Rathbone sure looked great dueling on the mast. And audiences loved
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So it is with interactive drama. Three-dimensional modeling and
animation software is just barely good enough to make
character-driven games. But no one knows how to direct them. So
it's time for pirates again, this time from Cyberflix of Knoxville,
Tenn., the developer of last year's best-selling mystery adventure
set aboard a doomed ocean liner that shall remain nameless.
</P>
<P>
   This year's nautical title is Red Jack: Revenge of the Brethren,
a computer-animated tale of villainous betrayal, supernatural
curses and buried treasure. It's a coming-of-age story, of course.
With a love interest. And sword fighting. And cannonballs. And
sharks. And rum.
</P>
<P>
   The object is to uncover the traitor, revenge the great fallen
pirate, dig up the gold, get the girl and sail off into the
Caribbean sunset. It's a classic pirate yarn, driven forward by the
player's interaction with its motley cast of characters.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many of these characters would as soon slice you up
for bait as talk to you. But dialogue is an option, although a
multiple-choice format constrains the discussion. A conversational
menu consisting of (a) ``What curse?'' (b) ``Where's the map?'' or
(c) ``Can I join your crew?'' does not yield a great deal of
psychological insight. But then, these are pirates, and pirates
aren't expected to be complex, articulate or bright. All they
really need are a few colorful phrases and flamboyant gestures.
</P>
<P>
   And virtual actors are getting very good with body language. You
can see them breathe. They can do all sorts of complex things with
their eyebrows and the corners of their mouths. You can see subtle
shifts in stance and facial expression as these characters make up
their minds. You can see them in a state of distrust, or doubt, or
barely contained anger. These puppets are really starting to learn
how to act.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, the puppeteers are learning how to manipulate a more
complicated set of strings. For digital characters, the
interpretation usually done by actors becomes the director's
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I become a choreographer,'' said Steven McBride, a character
animator who studied movement at the American Repertory Theater and
now works as Cyberflix's in-house dramaturg. ``I'll set every
single dance step so you can see how they're thinking _ there might
be a blink, a grimace or the raising of a brow just prior to their
utterance. That's the difference between theater and dealing with
animated characters. You have to go from the outside in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' McBride said. ``I kind of dug back to a really
old set of theories _ Francois Delsarte. He basically developed a
system which lent itself well to gestural work. If you see a
character whose elbows are away from the body _ like, you see this
with a lot of football players, where their elbows are way out from
the body _ it shows a confidence. I guess the reason Delsarte's
been ridiculed so much is because obviously a theater or acting
based on gestures will lend itself to melodrama _ it's all
external. But it's very handy when you're flipping from the voice
actors to these digital puppets.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems counterintuitive that this highly technological medium
should lean so heavily on 19th-century dramatic techniques. But
when actors aren't sentient, the Method doesn't cut any ice. It's
no accident that the most compelling characters in the virtual
world are silent or minimally vocal.
</P>
<P>
   Mario and Lara Croft are the digital world's Charlie Chaplin and
Mary Pickford _ they are operating in a medium that has yet to find
its technological feet. And until computer games can muster truly
powerful artificial intelligence, natural language capability and
digital voice synthesis, their characters will be marionettes
attached to strings of gestural instruction code.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, some Stanislavskian programmer will be drilling
digital actors to tap into their demons. But for the moment, we
have swashbuckling digital pirates. Delsarte's ghost is rattling
the machine. And somewhere, Errol Flynn and Basil Rathbone are
smiling.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (THQ Inc., CD-ROM for PC and Mac, $39.95. Rated Teen. Animated
blood and gore, mild language, portrayals of tobacco and alcohol
use.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
