<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOUSE-BUYING-NYT &LR;      09-02 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOUSE-BUYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET JITTERS AND THE HOME DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About to buy a place to live, and the stock market's
roller coaster ride is giving you indigestion? (And a smaller nest
egg?) Or perhaps you're the victim of mid-deal panic? To close or
not to close, that is the question.
</P>
<P>
   Buying property these days is like playing a hot game of poker.
Two months ago, you were loaded. But in the last six weeks, some of
you have lost almost all of your gains for the year, and others are
under water.
</P>
<P>
   So what if you're about to hand over a good portion of your
assets for a down payment and to pledge another chunk of your
income for the next 30 years on a house or apartment? Maybe now you
think you're paying too much for it. Or maybe you think that with
the stock market's woes, you can get it cheaper through strategy:
using the seller's possible panic to drive the price down.
</P>
<P>
   No one has reported falling real estate prices _ only stable
ones _ but potential buyers are already asking their lawyers when
and how to bargain more. The phrase ``going for the jugular'' has
been used by aggressive bargainers more than once in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the experts are advocating reneging on deals in the
face of stock-market volatility. It all depends on your sense of
the market _ and how much you love the property. But they say there
is almost always a way out, if you want or need one, up to the very
day of the closing.
</P>
<P>
   To the experts _ real estate lawyers _ buying a place is a
series of choices, a series of times to walk away from the table.
As the process evolves from first sight to closing, getting out
gets more difficult. But be careful, said Thomas Higgins, a partner
in a midtown firm. ``There's a downside to coming in and acting
like a rug merchant.''
</P>
<P>
   One man buying a $2 million apartment on Central Park West
recently got cold feet, agents familiar with the deal said. He got
out the expensive way: he left his $200,000 deposit behind. That's
always an option.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Siegler, head of co-op practice at Stroock &AMP; Stroock &AMP;
Lavan, said that most real estate contracts these days have a
clause that protects the buyer against liability beyond his
deposit. Although some sellers want to force a buyer into going
through with the deal _ or paying damages _ that's usually not in
the cards.
</P>
<P>
   But obviously, giving up the deposit is a costly option _
especially for a would-be buyer whose portfolio isn't what it used
to be. But it might not be necessary. The loss of a major chunk of
your assets from the stock market may excuse you from a deal if you
show proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, a lot of people don't have to worry about getting
out of a deal,'' said Mark Zimmerman, a midtown real estate lawyer.
``When the bank approving the mortgage, or the co-op board, takes a
look at a vastly changed financial statement, they may take the
decision out of your hands. They'll turn you down.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest, who are feeling queasy and want to know what
their options are, the lawyers give the following advice, depending
on what stage of the transaction you have reached.
</P>
<P>
   STAGE 1: BEFORE THE CONTRACT IS SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   If your offer has been accepted, but the contract has not been
signed by both buyer and seller, you can get out of the deal by
telling your lawyer to stop the process. ``The best way to get out
of a deal in the midst of a turbulent market is by not getting into
one,'' said Eric Davis, a real estate lawyer in New York and New
Jersey. Davis advises patience. It's unlikely that prices will rise
now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if you still love the apartment, or the brownstone, or the
country cottage, Stage 1 is probably the WORST time to renegotiate
the price, Higgins said. ``At this stage, if you already have
agreed on a price, if you start backtracking, the seller, who can
still get out of the deal, may say, `Why would I want to deal with
this person?' _ and pull out of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Better to wait until . . .
</P>
<P>
   STAGE 2: AFTER THE CONTRACT IS SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   When drawing up a contract in these volatile times, try to
convince the seller to accept as many contingencies as possible:
ways to get out of the deal with your deposit returned intact.
``Make sure your lawyer puts in enough exit clauses _ a mortgage
contingency, an inspection contingency,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   One man was buying a $300,000 three-story Colonial-revival house
in Montclair, N.J., Higgins said. He had a structural, or
inspection, contingency. If an inspector found any problem he
deemed to be structural, the buyer could get out of the deal. But
the man didn't want to get out of the deal. He wanted to
renegotiate. So when the inspector found a crack in a main beam _ a
crack that had been there for decades _ he got about $15,000 worth
of concessions, including a price reduction.
</P>
<P>
   But there is risk. The seller may challenge the report, although
lawyers agree that when a hitch comes so late in the process, the
seller will usually give in or _ if the object is really to get out
of the deal _ let the buyer out and look for a new one.
</P>
<P>
   If would-be buyers are confronted with substantial losses in the
stock market, the loss of a job or some other major event, they
will probably not get a mortgage commitment and, if there is such a
contingency, will get the deposit back.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City co-ops, there is another contingency: the buyer
must pass the board. Every lawyer and real estate broker has
stories of buyers with cold feet deliberately blowing the board
interview. Siegler told of one couple who ``dressed
inappropriately, like in jeans'' for the formal meeting. They were
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman said that ``legitimately, if someone has suffered big
losses, when they tell the board, the board will probably be
uncomfortable enough to reject them.''
</P>
<P>
   STAGE 3: GETTING OUT AFTER THE DIE IS CAST
</P>
<P>
   What if you want to get out after the contract is signed, the
mortgage has been granted and (in New York) you've passed the board
interview? Now you're in trouble. Most lawyers agree that almost
the only way to get out at this stage is by forfeiting the deposit.
Zimmerman, the lawyer, said that at the closing you must sign an
affidavit certifying that your financial position is the same as it
was when you filled out your loan application.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've just lost a million in the stock market and mention
this at the closing, you may get out of buying the apartment,'' he
said. ``The bank will probably take away their mortgage. But unless
you have enough left to take out your checkbook and write a check
for the whole amount, you'll probably kiss your deposit goodbye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
