<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRILLEDPIZZA-AZR &LR;      09-02 2331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLEDPIZZA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROW ANOTHER PIZZA ON THE BARBY!  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You're the master of the grilling universe. You
conquered the Weber long ago. You own three different barbecue
aprons given to you by grateful family members, and in the back
yard you are armed at all times with an array of long-handle
specialty tools. You are fluent in hickory chips, starter chimneys,
grilling baskets and the instant-read thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, grilling veterans, to a new frontier: grilled pizza.
America's favorite meal-on-a-crust has landed on the mainstream
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Trust us. This is going to be a major hit at your Labor Day
get-together or at tailgate parties. It just takes a little
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the beauty part: You can make grilled pizza in many ways
from scratch, with frozen dough or with dough made in your bread
machine. You can even use a premade baked pizza shell. Or _ stretch
that boundary even further _ bake a premade fresh pizza on the
barby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
From the ground up &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with scratch, because in many ways it's the most
delicious, creative and satisfying. The recipes for Pizza Dough and
Grilled Pizza Margarita are adapted from ``Cucina Simpatica,'' a
1991 cookbook by the pioneering couple who invented grilled pizza,
a couple of Rhode Island restaurateurs named Johanne Killeen and
George Germon. Their Al Forno restaurant in Providence is the
original home of grilled pizza.
</P>
<P>
   The dough is not complicated. You can make it up to 24 hours
ahead of time and let it rise the first time in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Pizza (Bread Machine Version) is from Laura Brody, who
adapted a Killeen-Germon recipe for her ``Pizza, Focaccia, Flat and
Filled Breads from Your Bread Machine: Perfect Every Time.'' Brody
says grilling pizza takes a little practice and patience, and don't
worry about making perfect circles of crust. It's free-form time.
</P>
<P>
   Her bread-machine dough can be made up to three days ahead of
time, stored in a large plastic bag in the refrigerator, or frozen
for up to three months, then defrosted still wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   You can grill almost any pizza dough as long as it is rolled out
very thin, she notes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Buy dough, top it yourself &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can also buy frozen dough to grill. Count on letting it thaw
in the refrigerator for at least one day. Italian delis often sell
frozen pizza dough.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Furano, who co-owns Guido's Deli in Mesa, Ariz., with his
cousin Mark Guido, says grilling pizza is not too hard. He points
out that you can do grilled meats, then the dough, then combine the
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could literally do whatever you want to grill,'' Furano
said. ``A grilled chicken pizza with a pesto sauce is fabulous. Or
use fresh mozzarella. There are a lot of choices.''
</P>
<P>
   His personal favorite combination is grilled chicken pizza with
roasted red peppers and pesto. Are you hungry yet?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Prefab crusts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rummaging around in the supermarket will yield a number of
prefab pizza crust choices. The latest ones we've seen are
individual-size discs packaged several to a box, perfect for
teenagers to top and shove into the toaster oven. Donna Rodnitzky's
``The Lowfat Grill'' suggests using tandoori-style naan, a type of
Indian bread (look for it at Asian stores), for crisp
individual-size pizza bases to grill. They crisp up well, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Bobolis have become so popular that some stores have their own
house brands. A couple of grill marks on any of these pizza bases
adds a lot of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't set them on fire. The key to pizza-grilling success
is to keep an ever-watchful eye on it. Pizzas heat very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for Grilled Mexican Pizza is from LHJ Online, the Web
site (www.lhj.com) of ``Ladies Home Journal'' magazine. (Check out
the ``Inside the LHJ Kitchen'' area for the RecipE-mail service
that sends a new recipe every day.)
</P>
<P>
   This pizza uses a packaged 12-inch thin crust, topped with an
avocado-lime juice mixture and tomatoes, pepper-Jack cheese, bacon
and sliced green onions. Of course, you could put these toppings on
your own homemade crust, if you wish. Or switch those toppings onto
a Boboli.
</P>
<P>
   Your mouth is watering now, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
On the grill &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Owner Patrick McAvoy of Take Me Bake Me, which specializes in
ready-to-cook-at-home meals In Phoenix, has started barbecuing
ready-made pizzas as well as ready-made lasagnas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several ways to do it,'' McAvoy said. ``Our way is
different. We take the fresh dough, which is on a thermal platter,
and put that right on the grill. That's one way. You can also
parbake them, then grill them straight up; or use a pizza stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The two keys to grilling ready-made pizzas are a lid for the
grill and indirect heat. Because ready-made pizzas are already
loaded with toppings, it's trickier to move them around. You also
can't put them directly over the fire.
</P>
<P>
   With a dual-burner gas grill, McAvoy recommends turning both
burners on high and then putting the lid down for about 10 minutes
to preheat. Turn one of the burners off, and turn the other down to
medium (about 425 degrees). Put the pizza on the thermal platter
over the turned-off burner. Cover and let sit for 10 minutes.
That's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barbecue works like a convection oven,'' McAvoy said.
``The key is no peekies. You peekie, you let the heat out.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaming is also a bad thing. If you set the thermal pan, which
includes cardboard in its composition, right over direct heat, it
will catch fire. McAvoy's granddaughter learned this the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   To grill pizza with charcoal, build the fire on one side and put
an aluminum pan on the other side. The area over the aluminum pan
becomes the cool side.
</P>
<P>
   Parbaked pizzas are much easier to transfer, although you still
don't want to roughhouse them, McAvoy says. To parbake a loaded
ready-to-go pizza, put it on a pizza screen, which has holes in the
bottom to let air crisp up the crust. Put your pizza in a
425-degree oven for three to five minutes, then pull it out. The
outside should be set, and the crust won't rise much more, if at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it cool off,'' McAvoy advised. ``Then you can take it and
grill-mark it and barbecue it the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pizza stones also can be used on the barbecue grill to ensure
that crisp crust. However, you must be careful not to put it on a
hot grill, McAvoy cautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put it on a cold grill and fire it up,'' he said.
``You put it on a hot grill, it's going to crack. It has to be
heated up.''
</P>
<P>
   We believe other ready-made pizzas in deli cases, such as the
ones in Trader Joe's stores, could be barbecued per McAvoy's
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled pizza allows endless options for personal expression.
</P>
<P>
   You grill masters will be dreaming up signature pizzas in no
time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grilled Mexican Pizza &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From LHJ Online: www.lhj.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 packaged 12-inch pizza thin crust (such as Boboli)
</P>
<P>
   1 avocado, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cracked black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 large tomatoes, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups shredded pepper-jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   6 slices bacon, cooked and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sliced green onions &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heat grill. Combine avocado, oil, lime juice, cumin, salt and
pepper in small bowl. Assemble all topping ingredients on a platter
and place near the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Grill pizza crust, top side down, over low coals, about 4
minutes. Remove crust from grill. Top with tomatoes, leaving 1-inch
border, and sprinkle with cheese. Grill covered about 4 minutes or
until cheese is melted and crust is crisp. Top with avocado
mixture, bacon and green onions.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 slices.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 275 calories, 17 g fat, 30 mg
cholesterol, 20 g carbohydrates, 473 mg sodium, 56 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grilled Pizza Margarita &QL; 
(Adapted from ``Cucina Simpatica,'' by Johanne Killeen and George
Germon) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Dough
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup olive oil for brushing and drizzling
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded Fontina cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Pecorino
</P>
<P>
   Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups canned or fresh tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch basil
</P>
<P>
   To prepare Pizza Dough. Place the olive oil and a brush in a cup
with a pour spout, and assemble all the topping ingredients on a
platter to take to the grill.
</P>
<P>
   When dough is ready; divide it into 4 equal pieces. On large,
oiled cookie sheet, spread and flatten 1 piece of dough with your
hands or a rolling pin into a 10- to 12-inch free-form round, 1/8-
inch thick. You may end up with a rectangle rather than a circle;
the shape is unimportant, but do take care to maintain an even
thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Place dough on grill rack 3 to 4 inches above heat. Within a
minute the dough will puff slightly, underside will stiffen, and
grill marks will appear. Using tongs, flip the crust over.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly brush the grilled surface with olive oil. Scatter
one-quarter of garlic and cheeses over the dough, and spoon
one-fourth of tomatoes over the cheese. Do not cover the entire
surface of the pizza with tomatoes. Finally, drizzle the pizza with
1 to 2 tablespoons olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Using tongs, rotate pizza frequently for even browning, checking
underside often. The pizza is done when the top is bubbly and the
cheese is melted, about 6 to 8 minutes. Serve at once, topped with
about 8 basil leaves and additional olive oil, if desired. Repeat
with remaining dough and topping ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Work Time: 10 minutes plus about 2{ hours rising time for dough.
Total time about 20 minutes per pizza plus about 2{ hours rising
time for dough.
</P>
<P>
   Makes four 12-inch pizzas, enough for 16 appetizer or 4
main-dish servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per appetizer serving: 255 calories, 13 g
fat, 20 mg cholesterol, 2 g carbohydrates, 390 mg sodium, 46
percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pizza Dough &QL; 
(From ``Cucina Simpatica'' by Johanne Killeen and George Germon)
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1 cup warm water (105 to 115 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   Pinch sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fine-ground white cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 to 3 1/2 cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve yeast in the warm water with sugar. After 5 minutes,
stir in salt, cornmeal, whole-wheat flour and oil. Gradually add
all-purpose flour, stirring with a wooden spoon until a stiff dough
has formed. Place the dough on a floured board, and knead for
several minutes, adding only enough additional flour to keep dough
from sticking.
</P>
<P>
   When dough is smooth, transfer to a greased bowl. To prevent a
skin from forming, brush top of dough with additional olive oil,
cover bowl with plastic wrap, and let rise in warm place, away from
drafts, until doubled, 1 1/2 to 2 hours. Punch down dough. Knead
dough several times on lightly floured board. Return dough to bowl;
cover and let rise 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Punch down dough. If sticky, knead in a bit more flour. Use to
make pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can mix this and let it rise the first time in the
refrigerator for up to 24 hours. Bring to room temperature before
final rising and shaping.
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough dough for 4 12-inch pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 488 calories, 5 g fat, 0 mg
cholesterol, 96 g carbohydrates, 1,064 mg sodium, 9 percent
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grilled Pizza with Bread-Machine Crust &QL; 
(From ``Pizza, Focaccia, Flat and Filled Breads from Your Bread
Machine'')
</P>
<P>
   For the dough:
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons yeast
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely ground cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water, plus 3 or more additional teaspoons if necessary
</P>
<P>
   To finish the pizza:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mixed fresh herbs, such as basil, thyme, oregano and
chervil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded soft cheese, such as fontina
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   6 oil-packed sun-dried tomatoes, cut into quarters
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place all the dough ingredients (yeast, flour, cornmeal, salt,
olive oil, water) in the machine, program for Dough, Basic Dough,
or Manual, and press Start, adding the extra water if necessary to
make a soft dough that forms a relaxed yet discrete ball.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat a gas grill or start a charcoal fire. Place the rack 3
to 4 inches above the coals. At the end of the final cycle,
transfer the dough to a lightly oiled work surface and use your
hands (or a rolling pin) to push and flatten the dough into a rough
10- to 12-inch circle without a lip. Or divide the dough in half
and make 2 smaller circles. This is a free-form pizza(s); don't
make yourself crazy trying to get the circle(s) perfectly round. An
even thickness is more important than an even edge.
</P>
<P>
   Lay the dough on the grill and let it cook for 1 minute, or
until it puffs slightly and the underside stiffens and grill marks
appear. Use a wide spatula or tongs to turn it over and place it on
the side of the grill (off the direct heat). Quickly brush the top
with half of the 3 tablespoons of oil and distribute the garlic,
herbs and cheeses over the top. Add the sun-dried tomatoes and
finally drizzle on the remaining oil. Slide the pizza back to the
middle of the grill and continue cooking; rotate the pizza to
assure even cooking. The pizza is done when the cheese has melted,
about 5 to 6 minutes. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 to 3 large servings or several more appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per one-half recipe serving: 1,283 calories,
63 g fat, 25 mg cholesterol, 158 g carbohydrates, 2,255 mg sodium,
43 percent calories from fat. (Note: These servings are huge, the
equivalent of half a loaf of bread plus toppings. To lower fat and
calories eat smaller pieces and be sparing when brushing on olive
oil.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
