<SLUG> BC-PIZZATIPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDLE PIZZA DOUGH WITH TLC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Start driving down the road to grilled pizza:
</P>
<P>
   - To prevent the dough from sticking, be sure the grill is clean
and then brush oil on the grill and the dough, says Chris Bianco of
Pizzeria Bianco in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   - When using fresh dough, roll or pat it out by hand. Make it
thin and even with no rim. The thinner it is, the crispier it will
be. You can move rolled discs of dough to the grill on cookie
sheets.
</P>
<P>
   - The dough will rise if it is outside in the heat for any
amount of time. So, you might want to start with your pizza dough
on the cold side, suggests co-owner Pete Furano of Guido's Deli in
Mesa. Note: Refrigerating dough, covered, will retard rising.
</P>
<P>
   - Whole-wheat pizza dough works well on the grill because it has
less protein and is a bit less stretchy, Bianco says.
</P>
<P>
   - Smaller individual pizzas about as big as your palm are easier
to handle at first, Bianco suggests. They are easier to turn, less
likely to tear or develop holes and convenient to eat. After a few
of them, you should be able to handle a bigger 10-inch pizza
easily.
</P>
<P>
   - Have all your ingredients ready. Bianco suggests shredding
cheese on the finest holes of the grater so it will melt more
readily and chopping ingredients finely, except such things as
Gorgonzola crumbles or fresh greens.
</P>
<P>
   - Meats such as sausages and heartier vegetables such as
mushrooms should be cooked ahead, because the cooking time for the
pizza is so brief, Furano notes.
</P>
<P>
   - If your grill can be moved up or down, crank it up four or
five inches over the hot fire before you start. Turn one side of
your gas burners off so you have a hot side and a cool side to work
with. If you have a charcoal fire, put a disposable aluminum pan on
one side of the coals to block the fire and serve as the cool side.
</P>
<P>
   - Transferring the dough to the grill can be tricky, because
once it has landed on the hot grids it's going to stay in that
position until the bottom stiffens and you can turn it. Use both
hands to pick up each disc from the platter and put it on the
grill. Go slowly and you'll get the hang of it.
</P>
<P>
   - Bubbles may appear on the top of the dough as the bottom
heats. If you want, you can mash them down with a spatula.
</P>
<P>
   - Use tongs to lift the disc of dough and peek at the bottom.
When the grill marks are dark enough for you, flip it over, brush
the top side with olive oil, and keep peeking underneath at the
grill marks to ensure the dough doesn't burn.
</P>
<P>
   - Avoid charring by paying attention. Keep checking the dough
for grill marks. Slide the dough onto the cool side when necessary.
Pizza dough or Boboli crusts can go quickly from dark brown to
burned.
</P>
<P>
   - When both sides are marked, pull the disc onto the cool side
and sprinkle on some or all of the toppings, such as cheese or
things that are important to heat.
</P>
<P>
   - If you add cheese, put the lid down briefly to melt it and
attain the smoky flavor, Furano says. This should take about four
minutes. Otherwise, you don't have to put the lid down.
</P>
<P>
   - Use tongs to slide finished pizzas off the grill onto a
serving platter or individual plates.
</P>
<P>
   - If you're making several pizzas, it's useful to have a helper
who can sprinkle on additional ingredients after you've done the
crusts and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   - Have your guests assembled and ready to eat, because grilled
pizza is at its best right off the grill. However,grilled pizza is
still delicious when served at room temperature or reheated hours
later. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
