A5465 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-945(2T     09-02 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-945(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif., Miss.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Microsoft Muse
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to dominate world markets. High-level intrigue.
Manipulation of the justice system. Executives talking about
``killing'' competitors.
</P>
<P>
   These are the general themes of two new books inspired by the
business dealings of Microsoft Corp. And only one of them is
classified as fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ulterior Motives,'' by Daniel Oran, a former Microsoft
programmer, is the story of murder and political intrigue at a
Seattle-based software giant named Megasoft. The book (Kensington,
$22.95), which hit stores last month, focuses on the political
ambitions of Megasoft's power-hungry chief executive, who will stop
at nothing in his effort to dominate the world.
</P>
<P>
   Oran, 33 years old, is the one-time inventor of the Start button
on Windows 95, but several years ago traded his programming prowess
for a pen. He said he based his character loosely on a mix of Bill
Gates and Ross Perot. So, does Megasoft wind up taking over the
world?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give away the end,'' said Oran, who lives in
Cambridge, Mass. ``Let's just say he's thwarted.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest there be any confusion, that's the work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The nonfiction book, ``The Microsoft File: The Secret Case
Against Bill Gates,'' (Times Books, $25.95) came out just this
week. It purports to take readers into the ``inner sanctum'' of
Microsoft, to show that its top executives manipulated markets and
crushed competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Wendy Goldman Rohm, a writer who has covered the
high-tech world for over a decade, relies on discussions with
Microsoft employees and competitors, internal documents from
Microsoft, and private e-mail messages between Microsoft
executives, including one in which a vice president writes to Gates
that they have to be prepared to ``kill'' the competition,
(speaking figuratively, of course).
</P>
<P>
   Her conclusion: Microsoft set out to crush competing operating
systems with the aim of establishing an absolute monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rohm's publisher concedes that in some cases the author
quotes sources who requested anonymity, which critics of the book,
including, not surprisingly. Microsoft, may seize on as a reason to
dispute its conclusions. ``It makes things dicey,'' said Will
Weisser, publicity manager for Times Books, a division of Random
House, referring to the anonymous quotes. ``But she stands behind
them and we stand behind her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dicey'' isn't the half of it, according to Microsoft.
``Bookstores will want to position this book in the fiction
section,'' said a company spokesman, Greg Shaw. He said Ms. Rohm
gave Microsoft little opportunity to present its side of the story.
``It's one-sided,'' he said. ``It's a rehash of tired
allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Someone Says Nice Things About Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   Under the word ``Monopoly'' in the dictionary, Richard McKenzie
and William Shughart don't believe there should be the Microsoft
logo.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's activities have not hindered competition in the
software market, the two economists write in the fall issue of
``Independent Review: A Journal of Political Economy,'' which is
published by the Independent Institute, a nonprofit research
organization in Oakland, Calif. McKenzie and Shughart conclude, in
fact, that it is the Justice Department, not Microsoft, that is
``squelching competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair write that Microsoft cannot afford to restrict output
and raise prices, as a monopoly would be expected to do, because
competition would immediately jump in to take away the business.
Further, they say it is illogical for Microsoft to raise prices for
its operating system, because then it could not attract customers
to its Internet browser, which is bundled with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its market pricing and product development do not square with
those of a monopolist,'' write McKenzie, a professor at the
University of California at Irvine, and Shughart, a professor at
the University of Mississippi. Their article can be found on the
Independent Institute's site at www.independent.org.
</P>
<P>
   No Paper Chase
</P>
<P>
   Applicants hoping for admission to the Sloan School of
Management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology had better
know their way around the World Wide Web. If not, the admissions
staff will not be admitting them; in fact, they won't even look
over their applications.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Sloan is apparently the first graduate business
school to accept only applications submitted over the Internet.
Sloan officials said their motive in mandating online applications
was not so much to ensure that applicants would be tech-savvy as to
save space and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our traditional application process, we printed and mailed
30,000 applications,'' Rod Garcia, Sloan's director of admissions,
said in a statement available on the Sloan Web site
(web.mit.edu/sloan/www). He called the new system a ``significant
step'' in eliminating ``all the paper waste and postage and mailing
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The online application program, effective for the fall class of
1999, works through a process called Grad Advantage
(www.gradadvantage.org). Developed by John Pyrovolakis, an MIT
graduate, the process allows an applicant to set up a
password-protected folder and fill out the forms a little at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   He or she can submit the final application when ready and use
the basic information to apply to some of the other 40
participating graduate schools, without having to retype the data.
</P>
<P>
   At least one part of the process still is old-fashioned.
Decisions on applications will be sent through regular mail,
meaning applicants still will have to sweat it out by the mailbox
for the good (or not so good) news.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Small Book Publisher
</P>
<P>
   What do you get when you cross the printing press with the Palm
Pilot? The answer is Peanut Press, a fledgling publisher with a
novel idea for presenting the printed word.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Press, based in Sudbury, Mass., is signing up
partnerships with mainstream publishers to make their books
available for the Palm Pilot. Among others, Peanut Press has
reached an agreement with Tor Books, publisher of such successful
science-fiction authors as Vernor Vinge and Orson Scott Card.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of presenting books on a PDA _ Puny Digital Assistant _
may itself sound like a bit of science fiction, but there already
are several Web sites that provide public-domain books for
downloading into the Palm Pilot. Peanut Press is trying to build on
that by going after books not yet in the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Reichelt, who co-founded Peanut Press along with fellow
computer scientist Jeff Strobel at the beginning of 1998, said the
books would be for sale for downloading ``this fall.'' He insists
there is plenty of room on the Palm Pilot screen to display text in
a readable fashion. ``It's the width of a magazine column,''
Reichelt said. ``Your eye can take it in quickly; it's an awful lot
of fun to read books.''
</P>
<P>
   The screen may get more reader-friendly still. The new Palm
Pilot, code-named ``Razor'' thanks to the fact that it will be only
1/3 inch thick, is slated to be able to support a new color LCD
screen. The new models, which are due out in November, reportedly
will have 4 megabytes of memory and a rechargeable lithium-ion
battery.
</P>
<P>
   So what's up next for the ever functional Palm Pilot: software
that will enable it to go out for groceries, wash the family dog,
and baby-sit the kids?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
