<HEADLINE>
FIRM FINDS NEW WAY TO USE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID HOYE   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - As the Internet has gone mainstream, tales of how
people are putting it to use are getting more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Take what happened at New Vision International, a $200 million
Tempe, Ariz., company that distributes nutritional supplements
around the world via a network of 700,000 salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   It was the week of Aug. 9, and all was looking good. The company
was humming along. Plans were being finalized for a
company-sponsored convention in Las Vegas. About 3,000 distributors
and others were expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mother Nature took over. A monsoon storm dumped so much
rain on Tempe one night that the roof of the company's
50,000-square-foot warehouse and headquarters building collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Stock was damaged, and the company's computer system _ the heart
of its communications with its distributors _ went down with the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   Employees worked all night to bring order back to the sudden
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Jason and BK Boreyko, who co-own New Vision,
immediately expanded their World Wide Web site, describing the
damage and cleanup efforts and reassuring distributors that orders
would be filled _ albeit a bit late.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site at www.new-vision-intl.com and at www.nviworld.com
also provided important last-minute details to the thousands of
people headed to the Las Vegas convention, which was held in late
August.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, New Vision went far beyond that important
content, adding interesting first-person accounts of what happened
as the storm hit. For example:
</P>
<P>
   New Vision employee Mike Tucker: ``I was sitting in my office,
just across from the computer room, and the ceiling began to shake.
I remember we had just installed a new air-conditioner above the
computer room and thought it might be off balance. Thinking nothing
of it, I walked around and sat back down again. My eyes widened
when the walls began to shake.''
</P>
<P>
   Company spokeswoman Myra Richman said, ``They would definitely
be out of business if it wasn't for their ability to update
everybody via the computer and the Internet.'' &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
Doggone it, that's funny
</P>
<P>
   Our recent contest that invited readers to write in with their
examples of how things would have gone if God had used a PC for
creation has prompted several people to send in related humor.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one reader sent in a list of 20 reasons why dogs
don't use computers.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the funnier (and cleaner) examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ They can't stick their heads out of Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's hard to read the monitor with their heads cocked to one
side.
</P>
<P>
   _It's too difficult to ``mark'' every Web site they visit.
</P>
<P>
   _Involuntary tail wagging a dead giveaway when they visit porn
sites.
</P>
<P>
   _Three words: Carpal Paw Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   _Can't help attacking the screen when they hear ``You've got
mail!'' &QL; 
David Hoye is an online editor and covers computer- and
Internet-related issues for Arizona Central, the Web site of The
Arizona Republic. He can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-31-98 1718EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
