<SLUG> BC-CPT-SCHOOL-COMPUTER01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Computers head list of back-to-school supplies for today's college
students  
 By Mark Clothier   
 c. 1998 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next to deciding whether to go to class on a regular basis,
picking a computer to use at college is one of the biggest
decisions a student makes.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of college students, responding to a poll
commissioned by Sprint, named the computer the most important
back-to-school item. It ranked ahead of calculators, stereos and
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking help buying a computer often encounter a barrage
of confusing and conflicting advice. But most experts agree that
you should buy as much computer as you can afford. But, with prices
falling by the day, that may be more computer than you'd imagine.
</P>
<P>
   As a starting point, most students can spend $1,400 and get a PC
that should be more than adequate. A 15-inch color monitor will run
about $300 more.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want an IBM-compatible PC, Brian Carr, assistant
director of the Georgia Tech bookstore, recommends buying at least
a 266 megahertz Pentium processor, 32 megabytes of RAM and a 2
gigabyte hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   For Macintosh users, Carr recommends the iMac, with a 233
megahertz processor, 32 megabytes of RAM and a 4 gigabyte hard
drive. In both cases, he recommends a 56k bps modem.
</P>
<P>
   Carr says to buy the most machine you can, but hold off on
software purchases until you see what discount packages your school
offers.
</P>
<P>
   Tech junior Divya Gupta followed that advice and bought a
top-of-the-line IBM-clone when she started school two years ago. If
she had to do it over again, she would spend a little less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look for the best deal and don't get suckered into what's
the best thing out there,'' said Gupta, a third-year mechanical
engineering student from Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's best isn't what's necessary for school. You don't need
anything too extravagant and you don't need a top-of-the-line
model,'' she said. ``You just need something that processes fast
enough and that has a decent modem, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Dell Computers recommend checking with your
university or college before buying a computer. Most schools post
minimum technology recommendations on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   They also advise reading computer reviews in newspapers and
industry magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the company backs up the machine with a warranty and
enhances your tech knowledge with toll-free, 24-hour-a-day support.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech is one of the few local colleges with minimum
technology requirements. Emory University, like most schools,
limits itself to making recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Cabot is in charge of computer support for Georgia Tech.
She said the school lets students know the minimum computer
requirements by mail and with postings on Tech's Web site by May.
</P>
<P>
   Tech also requires a standard suite of software programs. This
year's list includes Microsoft Office 98, Adobe Pagemill and
Symantec Cafe and costs about $325.
</P>
<P>
   Each year the selection changes slightly. A committee reviews
and posts any changes by March 1, Cabot said.
</P>
<P>
   Gupta, 20, said she uses her computer to read course syllabuses
online, to get homework assignments and then check her answers. Her
PC also serves as a telephone answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big help,'' she said. ``I was like, `Wow. This is
really going to be handy.'''
</P>
<P>
   A self-described pre-college tech-novice, Gupta became
well-versed enough to install a second hard drive when the software
she downloaded from the Web clogged up the first. It took her about
a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a computer and you have to use it, you tend to
play around with it, talk to people and you learn to make things
work. You get less intimidated by technology by having the
computer,'' she said. ``But still, I would never have dreamed I
could have done it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEW AND HOT
</P>
<P>
   What's new _ and expensive _ this year in the computer world.
</P>
<P>
   400 megahertz Pentium processors The extra speed lets you handle
3-D graphics, digital photographs and video editing more quickly
and, thus, more practically. And Intel recently introduced a 450
megahertz chip.
</P>
<P>
   Pentium II technology for notebook computers Some of the hottest
notebooks are now just as powerful as desktop machines.
</P>
<P>
   56k modems You can download bit-laden text, graphics and image
files via the Internet much faster.
</P>
<P>
   Digital versatile discs or DVD This technology makes it possible
to run full-motion movies and high-end games on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Places to buy a computer online
</P>
<P>
   Computer Discount Warehouse
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cdw.com
</P>
<P>
   iMall
</P>
<P>
   http://www.imall.com
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart
</P>
<P>
   http://www.wal-mart.com
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA computer store
</P>
<P>
   http://www.compusa.com
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computers
</P>
<P>
   http://www.dell.com
</P>
