<SLUG> BC-BASSHALL-SO </SLUG>
 FAR-TEX 
Bass Hall so far: an opening dud, a stunning silence 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazing and memorable moments have occurred since the Nancy Lee
and Perry R. Bass Performance Hall opened in May. I have attended
orchestra concerts, a solo recital, a chamber music concert, an
opera, a ballet and ``Phantom of the Opera.'' The most thrilling
moment was hearing the Fort Worth Symphony in its first rehearsal
in the new hall in April.
</P>
<P>
   As the orchestra rehearsed that great monument of 20th-century
music, Shostakovich's Fifth Symphony, a whole new world opened up
for the ensemble. Perfection is still in the distance, but the
clarity and resonance in the string sections, the ease with which
the winds and brass found their balance, proved that wonderful
possibilities await.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, the opening gala _ the variety show with
Carol Burnett and Frederica von Stade _ was an ill-conceived event,
the main benefit of which was to show what shouldn't happen in the
Bass Hall. New York-based producers, apparently totally ignorant of
orchestral acoustics and confident in the lack of sophistication of
Fort Worth audiences, proved that the hall can be used
inappropriately.
</P>
<P>
   On the amazing, unforgettable side, there was that moment during
Van Cliburn's concert with the Fort Worth Symphony, when 2,000
people saw the world's most famous pianist faint and fall flat on
his back on the floor next to the piano. Dead silence followed _
proving that this hall can be totally quiet, with no outside noise.
No one dropped a pin, but you could have heard it if someone had.
</P>
<P>
   Building a multipurpose hall was a risk _ maybe not so big a
risk as spending twice as much money to build a separate opera
house and orchestra hall, but a risk nonetheless. The verdict is
nearly but not totally complete, pending the results of the next
few seasons, particularly in ballet. But so far, we can be fairly
confident that Bass Performance Hall works.
</P>
<P>
   We'll know better as the years pass just how much the minor
inconveniences _ the bottleneck at the entrance on the ground
floor, the maze of stairs and halls _ really disturb the audience's
experience, and if the carefully engineered acoustics advance Fort
Worth as a cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of its multi-use design, Bass Performance Hall appears
to be a better symphonic facility than some dedicated orchestra
halls _ including the Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center in Dallas.
Acoustician Christopher Jaffe's innovative adjustable ceiling is
more than just an expensive gimmick; the room picks up just the
right range of frequencies from the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Even the noisier sounds of a wind ensemble came off with clarity
and resonance in a performance by the Texas Wind Symphony. When a
gargantuan chorus joined the Fort Worth Symphony for Orff's
``Carmina Burana,'' the sound was appropriately velvety and lush.
The only problem I noticed with orchestral sound was when I sat in
the upper balcony, where the volume was noticeably lower. That part
of the hall is not for the hard of hearing.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times columnist Frank Rich, referring to the long run
of ``Phantom of the Opera'' at the hall, had a legitimate point
when he questioned the appropriateness of presenting ``one of the
aged road tours'' in a new cultural center. But the Broadway
musical (or in this case, the West End musical) is an important
20th-century art form, and Bass Performance Hall proved to be a
worthy venue that can preserve a reasonable degree of intimacy
while presenting a lavish production. It's a huge improvement over
the larger venues _ such as Fort Worth Convention Center and Fair
Park Music Hall _ where Broadway touring companies traditionally
appear, and where the sense of connection between the audience and
the actors is often lost.
</P>
<P>
   For solo recitals, an artist with lots of charisma and physical
power _ such as Van Cliburn, who presented the first solo recital
in the hall _ will come off grandly, as will a high-quality chamber
ensemble such as the Ying Quartet, which broke in the hall for
chamber music. Less powerful performers, however, may not
communicate so effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Because a room this large and grand demands a large personality
and musical excellence, it should be an appealing venue for the Van
Cliburn International Piano Competition in 2001, allowing the
artist with the big heart and big sound to show to good effect.
</P>
<P>
   The hall's elegance should also enhance the Cliburn's position
on the competition circuit. The comment once made to me by the head
of another major competition, that the Cliburn holds its opening
rounds in a room not much better than a high school auditorium,
will no longer be true.
</P>
<P>
   For opera, the situation is similar. The grandeur of the room
itself enhanced without detracting from the lively, attractive sets
for the Fort Worth Opera's production of Puccini's ``La Boheme.''
Very good voices will thrive in Bass Performance Hall, but the
less-than-great should be prepared to have every weakness exposed.
Careful casting will be essential for the opera in years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet is the big question mark so far. The all-important visual
balance suffers toward the side seats; friends who sat in the
balconies tell me they heard too much stage noise during the Fort
Worth Dallas Ballet's presentation of Balanchine's ``Jewels.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the quality of the acoustics will be pretty well
settled in the next two or three seasons, it will take longer to
tell about the architecture. Will David Schwarz's nostalgic
evocation of the past be a sore thumb and an anachronism in a
lively urban center? Or will it be a perfect symbol of respect for
the past and vision for the future? Time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
