<HEADER>
A5543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-0903-C     09-02 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHILE CLINTON AND YELTSIN TALK, RUSSIAN CRISIS GROWS DEEPER
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-LEWINSKY-0903.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The summit of few expectations produced few results.
</P>
<P>
   Two politically wounded presidents, Boris Yeltsin and Bill
Clinton, concluded two days of talks Wednesday with Russia sliding
deeper into trouble and America powerless to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   Dogged by questions about the Monica Lewinsky affair, Clinton
departs Moscow for Northern Ireland on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves behind his ailing friend Yeltsin headed for another
confrontation Friday with the Communist-dominated parliament over
the appointment of a new prime minister and the future course of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In a concluding news conference at the majestic and gilded
Catherine's Room in the Kremlin, a grim-faced Yeltsin predicted
``much blood, sweat and tears'' for his anxious country. As he
spoke, the ruble was falling to new lows and the one of the world's
largest nuclear powers approached the end of a second week without
a full-time government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always emerged victorious from the most dramatic
trials. I am sure we will from this one as well,'' Yeltsin told
reporters following his meetings with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist opposition urged Yeltsin to find a new, compromise
candidate to lead the government, vowing to again reject acting
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin in a vote scheduled for Friday
in the Duma, the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, a former prime minister dismissed by Yeltsin
earlier this year and widely blamed for helping to create the
current economic crisis, was decisively defeated in a first vote in
the Duma on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who appointed Chernomyrdin after firing the previous
five-month-old government on Aug. 23, has vowed to stick by him.
Yeltsin also reappointed several Cabinet ministers by decree,
including the defense and foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin can present his candidate for prime minister three
times, according to Russia's constitution. If rejected on a third
vote, the president must dissolve the Duma and call new
parliamentary elections within three months. Yeltsin would then
rule by decree, and with an interim government, until the new
parliament is seated.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a risky game of brinkmanship for both Yeltsin and
the parliament. Resentful Russians have watched their spending
power slashed in half in recent weeks as the ruble went into
free-fall. The Central Bank cut the official rate to 12.8 rubles
per dollar on Wednesday -- half what it was worth three weeks ago
-- while on the street it was trading as low as 15 to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kremlin is half-dead, the government is paralyzed, and we
are on the verge of a paralysis of legislative power as well,''
said Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov. ``A lack of government
would inevitably lead to bandits and criminals taking over power.''
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov and more than 20 other opposition leaders met privately
with Clinton on Wednesday at the U.S. ambassador's residence in
Moscow, Spaso House. The president encouraged them to find common
ground with Yeltsin to form a government and fix the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't predict that future with any certainty, but we can
say we've done everything we can do ... to make that more hopeful
outcome a reality,'' said White House spokesman Michael McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also repeated the theme that marked his appearances in
Moscow: urging Russia to remain on the road to democracy seven
years after the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the opposition figures, including the
Communists and other factions from across the political spectrum,
stated that Russia would not revert to Soviet-era policies. No one
is against reforms, they said, but no one in the current crisis can
do much to advance them.
</P>
<P>
   But some parliament members warned Clinton of social unrest if
the situation in Russia deteriorates further.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Lebed, a regional governor and former army general,
said the revolt was possible in the disgruntled, ill-paid army.
Lebed, a presidential candidate in 1996 who still aspires to the
job, said he told Clinton that Russia was more insecure than the
period leading up to the 1917 Bolshevik revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance with Yeltsin at the Kremlin, Clinton pledged
that America would stand behind Russia and he promised to pursue
new international financial aid to help pull the country out of
crisis -- but only if Moscow pushed ahead with market reforms and
its commitment to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A country that rebuffed Napoleon and Hitler can surely adjust
to the realities of the global marketplace,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is scheduled to receive a $4.3 billion loan from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Sept. 15, part of a $22.6
billion bail-out package announced in July. But IMF officials in
Washington said Tuesday that the loan may be delayed until October
or beyond as it monitors Russia's reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials conceded that Russia, with no
government, has devised no comprehensive plan to deal with its
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is very much in their court. We do not have any new
or additional aid or plan in our pocket,'' said a senior
administration official.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, the two presidents agreed to disagree on the
expansion of NATO into Eastern Europe, a move Russia views with
alarm and which Yeltsin called on Wednesday ``a historic mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The only tangible results of the summit were two quickly
arranged accords on arms control, including an agreement to
eliminate some of their stockpiles of weapons-grade plutonium. But
the Russian domestic turmoil pre-empted Clinton's main aim:
attempting to convince the Duma to ratify the 1993 START II treaty
to reduce U.S. and Russian nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summit was a total political show. Clinton needed to show
he is abreast of the situation in Russia, that he is not distracted
by the Monica Lewinsky affair. And Yeltsin needed to show that even
if he is not popular in Russia, that abroad he is loved and treated
well,'' said Viktor Kremenhyuk, a political analyst with the
U.S.A.-Canada Institute, a Moscow think tank.
</P>
<P>
   While Russia's economic and political problems occupied much of
the summit, senior Clinton administration officials said the
Lewinsky affair was never discussed between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his first formal news conference at the Kremlin
since his televised Aug. 17 address, was confronted with questions
from reporters about his ``inappropriate'' relationship with the
former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
