<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Cheap PCs intriguing, but you probably won't purchase one  
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been expecting grocery stores to start selling computers in
the checkout line any day now. They'd be stacked up somewhere
between copies of the National Enquirer and boxes of Good 'N Plenty
and would cost about the same.
</P>
<P>
   After all, everyone says computers are dirt cheap these days.
And you don't have to go any further than this newspaper for proof.
Just look at the ads. You'll find computers _ brand new ones _ for
as little as $400 or so. I can remember when a person paid that
much for a modem.
</P>
<P>
   The low prices are real. But they can be misleading, too. I'm
not saying the stores are trying to deceive you. What I am saying
is that _ once you get in the store _ you may find that the bargain
basement PCs aren't for you.
</P>
<P>
   Let me explain. Last weekend I went shopping for a new computer.
I finally got tired of using a PC that sounded like a washing
machine filled with rocks and soft drink bottles. It was scaring my
cat. Besides, the old machine was way too slow.
</P>
<P>
   While it is powerful enough for word processing, browsing the
Web and checking e-mail, it is showing its age. The once-gigantic
1-gigabyte hard disk now seems tiny. The 256-color video card is
something of an antique. The 125-megahertz processor speed (that's
not a typo, the 125 megahertz is the result of an Overdrive chip)
seems way too slow now.
</P>
<P>
   It was on a shopping trip to replace that PC that I discovered a
truth that can only be learned at the cash register: For someone
who needs a relatively powerful PC, prices haven't really changed
much.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who know me _ either through this column or
face-to-face _ understand I'm not exactly a free spender. With cars
and computers, I tend to wait as long as I can before replacing
what I own. I think there are still some good miles left in my Nash
Rambler, but my computer is on its last legs.
</P>
<P>
   I went shopping with the notion of picking up a new PC for $500
or so. After all, I've been earnestly assuring you that most of us
don't need a state-of-the-art machine.
</P>
<P>
   But being a TechnoBuddy doesn't make a person immune to the sort
of raw hunger for power that hits folks in a computer store. Before
long, I was rationalizing with the best of them. I told myself
those inexpensive computers weren't much more powerful than the PC
I wanted to replace.
</P>
<P>
   I told myself I was looking for a machine that would have some
chance of being useful for three or four years. And yet I didn't
want to pay top dollar for the fastest chip around. The machine
needed more RAM memory and a much bigger hard drive, and it needed
one of the new 100-megahertz motherboards.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. There was one other thing. The new machine needed to
be powerful enough to play computer games. The old machine just
wasn't powerful enough for modern games. Lately I've been getting
this powerful hankering to kill space aliens. It's a plain and
simple fact that the most demanding computer programs these days
are games.
</P>
<P>
   I ended up buying a 350-megahertz Pentium II machine with an
8-gigabyte hard disk and 64 megabytes of RAM. That's not the
fastest machine on the market, but it should be powerful enough to
play most of the games that have been collecting dust on my
bookshelf. And since it uses the new 100-megahertz bus _ the bus is
the circuitry that moves data on the motherboard _ I should be able
to upgrade the machine as new chips come along.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of machines like that to choose from. And the
price spread for PCs with these specifications was real familiar:
It ranged from about $2,000 for brand-name machines down to $1,300
for no-name PCs. That's identical to the prices I saw the last time
I bought a PC. What I'm trying to say is that while there may have
been some really big changes in computer prices lately, human
nature is still pretty much the same.
</P>
<P>
   I'm betting that the $500 machines will get you into the store
but that you won't go home with one.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted appreciates hearing from you but can not respond to
all e-mail. Personal home page: http://www.mindspring.com
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
