<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-CAPITAL-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP WANTED: TOP EXECUTIVES FOR NEW-MEDIA START-UPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By JANET STITES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lon Otremba has a rare advantage among top executives
in New York City's Silicon Alley high-technology industry: a track
record as an executive who took an Internet company from ground
zero to a respectable public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the original management team of the online publisher
Cnet, Otremba is now the chief operating officer of Iname, a
start-up that offers permanent and personalized e-mail accounts. In
an industry that has very little history and thus a dearth of
experienced, successful executives, he is already on Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of experienced managers in technology industries is
especially acute in New York. Unlike Silicon Valley, Northern
California's hotbed of high-technology start-ups, or Dallas, the
hub of the telecommunications industry, Silicon Alley has only a
handful of executives who have actually built a company from the
ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an ongoing problem to attract senior
management and build a board,'' said Michael Flannery, president of
the New York-based executive search firm Redwood Partners. Although
successful initial public offerings by a handful of Silicon Alley
companies have made the industry more attractive to experienced
executives and have thus eased the problem a bit, more recent
start-ups are still struggling to find and lure top managers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the tiny pool of second-generation entrepreneurs,
recruiters must turn to the corporate world, he said, and gamble
that an executive hailing from an established corporation can drive
a start-up to success.
</P>
<P>
   Flannery, who also manages a small venture capital fund and is
in need of managers for his own portfolio of companies, says there
is no sure formula for determining who can make the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough call,'' he said of finding the right executive.
``I really put them through the drill. I take them down the road,
painting a picture of what it's like to run a start-up; making
payroll; constantly raising capital; building a model. I watch
their facial expressions. Sometimes, after I'm finished they say,
`You're right, Mike. I don't want to do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The executive candidate is gambling, too. When Otremba joined
Cnet in 1993, for example, he was leaving a comfortable position as
publisher of PC Magazine, a Ziff-Davis publication.
</P>
<P>
   In his job at Ziff-Davis, he could see the Internet coming, so
when Cnet's founders, Halsey Minor and Shelby Bonnie, approached
him with their idea for a company that would produce television and
Internet programming about computers, he understood the potential.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, with his proven track record in traditional publishing,
his high marketability and a wife and two children to consider,
Otremba, who was then 36, had a lot of options. In addition, the
job would require him to commute weekly to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no doubt the idea was a good one,'' he said in a recent
interview. ``Still, I had to do a lot of soul-searching to decide
if it was the right time to join a start-up. Finally, I realized I
wouldn't be starving if the whole thing imploded.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside was an equity stake in Cnet and the opportunity to
create a corporate culture and be part of a technology revolution.
On the other hand, he had to create the company from scratch and
sacrifice many amenities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big deal for me when I could arrange for car service
to the airport, when I got my corporate credit card and could hire
an assistant,'' he said of the growth of Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   Otremba stayed with Cnet three years, until he was fully vested,
helping take the company from 10 employees to 600. Then he was
ready to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``People read the registration statement, so they knew exactly
when my vesting was up,'' he said. ``I started getting calls
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Otremba was commuting weekly from New York to San
Francisco, so when he ran into the founders of the New York-based
Iname, he was ready to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was available for a second run while it was still early'' in
the development of the Internet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting firms have recognized the challenge and are setting
up special efforts to find executives for new-media start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Among those specializing in Silicon Alley companies is Cara
Erickson, a partner at the search firm of Accord Group/Johnson,
Smith &AMP; Knisley who has placed executives for companies like
Chicago-based Classified Ventures and Microsoft Corp. She is now
seeking a chief executive for the online financial news service
TheStreet.com, whose founder, James Cramer, already runs a hedge
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation is often not the issue, Ms. Erickson said, because
the industry has matured enough that many start-ups, particularly
those with solid venture backing, can compete with the high-end
salaries of the established corporate world and are not deterred by
the price tag for seasoned executives.
</P>
<P>
   But finding the right executive can take time. Ms. Erickson says
she looks for problem solvers who fit into the management team
puzzle _ that is, a chief executive, chief financial officer and
chief operating officer who complement each other in skills and
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to find one person with all the elements
necessary to help build a company,'' she said. ``You have to look
at the management team as a whole. If you have a CEO who has never
taken a company public, then you need to have a CFO who has.''
</P>
<P>
   Start-ups often find themselves in a chicken-and-egg quandary.
Without good management they cannot find financing, but without
financing, they cannot afford good executives.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-30-98 1743EDT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Lisa Church, who turned down the opportunity to
run a start-up to take a lower-level job at a more established
company.
</P>
<P>
   Like Otremba, Ms. Church found herself in New York City with a
unique resume that included helping to build a technology company
from the ground up. As vice president of marketing and new-business
development for Advent Software of San Francisco, she was
responsible for building the company's East Coast presence.
</P>
<P>
   She joined Advent, which specializes in portfolio management
software, in 1985 when the company had six employees and sales in
tens of thousands of dollars. When she left last year, the company
employed more than 300, and revenues were approaching $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that it was time to move on, Ms. Church took stock of
her opportunities while observing and, eventually, participating in
the evolution of Silicon Alley. She spoke seriously with several
Alley companies and came close to joining a New York software firm
as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But she turned down that opportunity to join Decalog, a
Boston-based, Israeli-backed software company, as vice president of
North American sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lure of the new-media business is that it's a new
technology and a new industry,'' Ms. Church said. ``It's fun and
exciting, but there are the financial realities of life. I've got a
family and a mortgage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she said, she took the Decalog job because it
promised to be equally exciting, but more stable. ``The company's
just more established,'' she said, adding that she still hopes to
work with a start-up in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists face similar decisions in finding the right
company, said Ed Sim, senior vice president of the venture-capital
firm Dawntreader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight of the 10 companies we speak to need management,'' Sim
said. ``Part of the deal has to be we can either bring in a new CEO
or COO to complement the founder. We get resumes in every day, so
the tricky part is to identify the right person.''
</P>
<P>
   What his group can offer potential executives is ``the wealth
factor'' and a long-term relationship with the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them that if the company doesn't work out for market
reasons, we'll drop them in another one of our companies,'' Sim
said. ``So then it's a portfolio risk versus a single company.''
</P>
<P>
   Among an executive's biggest fears when contemplating joining a
start-up, he said, is failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, a company might fail through no fault of the CEO,''
he said. ``We mitigate their fear by pointing out that every
company is developing an Internet strategy, so their experience
will be invaluable, that it's still early, and people like wounds
and scars.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some executives who emerged from start-ups are intrigued
but ultimately put off by culture shock when stepping into the
world of Silicon Alley start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Peter Kestenbaum recently resigned as director of
North American field marketing for Sun Microsystems after 13 years
with the company. Having joined Sun a year before the company went
public, he was already familiar with the grueling hours and
guerrilla tactics of start-up life. And having witnessed the birth
of Silicon Alley, he decided that the time was perfect to try some
start-up companies on for size.
</P>
<P>
   His first experience was less than perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was in shorts and sandals,'' he said. ``There was no
receptionist, so I just wandered to the back looking for the person
I was there to meet. But the clincher came when I went to use the
bathroom. There I was, standing in my $1,000 suit, and the urinals
were filthy. It was like a gas station. I thought, `I can't do
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kestenbaum has decided to look for a position with a more
established company.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the hardest part of finding the right executive is
finding someone with a passion for the product, not just the money.
</P>
<P>
   Otremba agrees: ``When you join a start-up it's like joining a
family. All the stock options in the world don't amount to anything
if the business doesn't interest you. There has to be a passion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-30-98 1743EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
