</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PER-KILO-DINING-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING: WEIGHTY COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By JACK EPSTEIN 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ It's early in the lunch hour but dozens
of customers are already waiting for a table outside the Couve Flor
restaurant. The Couve Flor is one of Rio de Janeiro's most
successful restaurants, serving more than 600 people daily and
twice that on weekends. Diners are attracted by its wide selection
and tasty dishes.
 &HT;    But the popular Rio eatery has another important ingredient
that's packing in customers: it is one of a growing number of
``comida por kilo'' restaurants that charge not by what a customer
orders but how much he or she eats. It's a concept that has spread
throughout the Brazilian restaurant industry since the early 1990s,
mostly near office buildings and urban commercial zones. ``It's a
virtual fever,'' said Couve Flor owner Jair Pinto, who converted
his Italian restaurant to per kilo style in 1993.
 &HT;    In fact, some are doing so well that they have become the major
competitor of fast-food franchises such as McDonald's, Pizza Hut
and Kentucky Fried Chicken. In recent months, several fast foods
franchises have slashed their prices including McDonald's by 18
percent and Bob's, a Brazilian hamburger chain, by 5 percent. ``Per
kilo is definitely taking some of our business,'' says Marcelo
Barbosa, who manages a Bob's outlet at the Rio Sul shopping mall.
 &HT;    Typically, per kilo restaurants offer a buffet of hot and cold
dishes and a scale near the cash register where plates are weighed.
Many are small operations that are open Monday-Friday only during
lunch time, the most important meal of the day. At the low end,
these restaurants provide several hot dishes, including the
standard Brazilian fare of rice, black beans, spaghetti and beef
for between US$5 and $7 a kilo. At the high end, restaurants like
Couve Flor, located in the trendy Jardim Botanico neighborhood,
offer 20 hot dishes, 23 salads and 37 desserts at a cost of $13.50
a kilo. Diners are typically executive secretaries and businessmen
who don't worry much about the higher cost. Customers are attracted
not only to the idea of paying for the amount they eat but the
variety of foods, including non-greasy items such as salads and
vegetables. ``I like to eat light, but with a la carte restaurants,
you never know what you are going to get or how much food to
expect,'' says Rio secretary Fernanda Marsena. ``With per kilo, you
see what you are going to eat and control what you put on your
plate.'' Weighing food in restaurants began in 1990 after
then-President Fernando Collor de Mello froze all savings accounts
over $1,000 for 18 months as part of a radical attack on inflation.
That and other austere economic measures caused massive layoffs in
which some of the newly unemployed were given buyouts by their
firms. Many then opened per kilo restaurants to attract customers
who could no longer afford to spend much on a meal.
 &HT;    Around half of Sao Paulo's 32,000 restaurants, and a fifth of
Rio's 14,000 restaurants now charge by the kilo, according to
restaurant unions of both cities. Marsena says most of her
colleagues prefer per kilo restaurants and constantly exchange
information about the best places. In fact, except for an
occasional handbill or billboard, owners typically spend nothing on
publicity campaigns, and, instead, rely on recommendations.
``Word-of-mouth is the most effective type of marketing,'' added
Sergio Teixeira, marketing manager for Antarctica beer and ardent
per kilo devotee. ``It reflects one's personal opinion and not paid
propaganda, which can be deceiving. That's why good per kilo
restaurants do well.''
 &HT;    In Sao Paulo, Vienna Express is currently the nation's largest
per kilo franchise with 60 outlets. In Rio, Couve Flor has branched
out with three restaurants and plans to open another in a new $200
million amusement park.
 &HT;    Specialty foods franchisers are jumping on the band wagon: The
58 store chain Amor aos Pedacos now offers desserts by the kilo,
while Guillerme Ferreira, the president of Arby's of Brazil,
predicts that the next wave of franchises will be per kilo chains,
which are already appearing in the nation's shopping malls. In
doing so, says Katia Francischi, spokeswoman for the Association of
Brazilian Franchising, they have become a force in the market:
``Per kilo is changing the corporate behavior of Brazilian
franchises.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
