<HEADLINE>
CONSIDER SHIFTING FROM AUTOMATIC TO MANUAL IN UPDATING PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1998 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell me about the various software packages
designed to ``automatically'' update the software and drivers on a
PC? Two that I am familiar with are Cybermedia's Oil Change and
IMSI's UpdateNow. How automatic is automatic? Do you have to
manually download and run a lot of executable files, or does the
software do it all for you? Are driver updates so common that you
would be updating almost daily?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both of the programs you mention work by first scanning your
computer to see what's on it. They check both for the applications
you have _ everything from word processors to Web browsers to games
_ and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   After that's done, the programs contact a server on the
Internet. The server has a list of applications, drivers and
current updates. The programs then check this against what was
found on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   If there are any updates available to you, you'll be alerted and
given the chance to download the ones you need. Once they are moved
to your computer, one of two things happen: You can let the
retrieval program install the update for you or you may have to do
it yourself. Whether it's automatic depends on whether the
publisher of the update has made it that way.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a lot of different programs on your computer, you
probably could find a new update to snag almost every day. Software
constantly is being improved, updated and patched, and grabbing
updates over the Internet makes distribution of these fixes easy
for both users and developers. But only some of them could be
considered crucial updates.
</P>
<P>
   More and more programs have this update capability built into
them. For example, all of Quarterdeck's titles come with UpdateIt,
which automates the downloading and patching of that company's
programs. Symantec's similar technology is called LiveUpdate.
Windows 98 also has an update feature.
</P>
<P>
   The services you mention charge an annual fee for access to the
update database. Frankly, unless you don't want to mess with
downloading and installing software at all, it's cheaper and even
more effective to do it yourself. That's because these servers
don't have all programs on them. And you may be offered software as
an ``update'' that's actually a demo for a program a publisher
wants you to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Think self-service. Just bookmark the Web sites of the makers of
the software and hardware on your computer and visit their support
areas regularly _ say, once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you clear the commands from Run in the Start Menu of
Windows 95? When I click the arrow at the Run command on the Start
Menu I have a list of 24 commands. Most of them are ones I have
previously typed in. Many were typed wrong and did not work, so
there is no use having them in there. I have looked in a number of
those 2-inch-thick books on Win95 that ``tell all'' but have found
nothing about this problem. Also, I have not found any tech help
people or experts in Houston that know how to do this.
</P>
<P>
   A: The best way to do this is to use the TweakUI, one of the
PowerToys for Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Get TweakUI at www.microsoft.com/windows/downloads/. Install it,
and then go to the Control Panel, where you'll find the icon for
TweakUI. Doubleclick it, then look for the tab marked Paranoid.
From there you'll be able to clear the Run command, as well as
several other places where past commands are stored, including the
Documents list and the Internet Explorer history list.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; XXXX END OF STORY
