<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``C.S. Lewis: Writer, Dreamer, and Mentor''
</P>
<P>
   By Lionel Adey
</P>
<P>
   Eerdmans, $22
</P>
<P>
   ``The C.S. Lewis Readers' Encyclopedia''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Jeffrey D. Schultz and John G. West Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Zondervan, $22.99
</P>
<P>
   For many writers, heaven would be not only having your books in
print 35 years after your death but having books written about you
as well. But then again, the reason that C.S. Lewis can claim those
honors is that he took the idea of heaven more seriously than many
writers do.
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Adey, however, approaches Lewis not as a man of faith but
as a man of letters. ``We have ... to my knowledge no book on Lewis
as what from childhood he set out to be, a maker and reader of
books,'' the Canadian scholar says in ``C.S. Lewis: Writer,
Dreamer, and Mentor.''
</P>
<P>
   Carefully considering his subject as a literary
historian/theorist, critic, novelist, essayist, correspondent,
pleader and poet, Adey says that the Chronicles of Narnia
``constitute a body of fiction worthy of their immense and
sustained readership.'' The novels ``most deserving of survival''
are ``Till We Have Faces'' (a retelling of the myth of Cupid and
Psyche) and ``Perelandra'' (the second book in Lewis' ``space
trilogy'').
</P>
<P>
   Adey covers a great deal of ground that will be alien to those
familiar only with Lewis' religious books. (Adey's own theology is
basically indiscernible.)
</P>
<P>
   For those who really want to expand their Lewisian horizons to
the Utter East and back again, there is ``The C.S. Lewis Readers'
Encyclopedia.'' Beginning with a biographical sketch, this volume
of 400-plus pages _ edited by Jeffrey D. Schultz and John G. West
Jr. _ contains entries on everything from Lewis' intimate
associates to his major (and minor) works, to his letters to
various publications.
</P>
<P>
   Although obviously a work of respect and love, the ``Readers'
Encyclopedia'' generally avoids overt adulation (indeed,
contributor Marvin D. Hinten forthrightly notes the difficulty of
some of Lewis' academic writing). The photographs depict Lewis'
family and early editions of his books; curiously, there is no
picture of Joy Davidman Lewis (the author's wife before her death
in 1960) and no entry devoted to her 1955 book, ``Smoke on the
Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   The breadth of ``The C.S. Lewis Readers' Encyclopedia'' will
commend it to fans, trivia buffs and students of the author's life
and work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   ``The Inclusive Language Debate''
</P>
<P>
   By D.A. Carson, $13.99
</P>
<P>
   Baker/Inter-Varsity Press UK
</P>
<P>
   D.A. Carson's latest book? ``Gender Fender-Benders: When the
Worlds of Language, Feminism and Translation Collide.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, not really, although that sums it up pretty well. ``The
Inclusive Language Debate'' (the real title) reacts to a 1997
controversy involving a proposed edition of the popular New
International Version of the Bible. The dispute focuses on whether
words such as ``person'' or ``humankind'' (or the use of plurals or
``you)'' are sometimes preferable to ``man'' and other
male-oriented words when translating passages that apparently apply
to men and women.
</P>
<P>
   The battle is hotter than you might think, and Carson's basic
message is: It's not that simple. The Illinois writer is more
critical of the inclusivists' foes than of the inclusivists (at
least in this case), arguing that the practice often makes for more
accurate translation.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing as it does with linguistic technicalities, ``The
Inclusive Language Debate'' requires close attention, but Carson
works his territory well and produces a sensible and readable work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   ``Scratching the Surface''
</P>
<P>
   Erin O'Donnell
</P>
<P>
   Cadence Communications
</P>
<P>
   Erin O'Donnell elbowed her way into the crowded field of solo
female contemporary Christian music acts with her debut effort,
1996's engaging ``A Scrapbook of Sorts.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the elbows have given way to feet. With
``Scratching the Surface,'' O'Donnell climbs above the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's not elbows or feet that make O'Donnell stand out.
It's her beautifully clear voice, the songwriting talents of
husband Brad O'Donnell, and the pair's willingness to take chances.
Combine that with a liberal dose of musical maturity since the
initial release, and you get one of the most pleasant releases of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to this album is like opening Christmas presents. Each
song is like a brightly wrapped package, and there's a neat,
unexpected surprise in each one.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of This,'' the first cut _ and first radio hit _ contains
a classic pop hook, but it's driven by strings. Other songs
emphasize piano, acoustic guitars, electric guitars, a bass track
and horns. The title track begins with a muted vocal over
synthesizers, which gives way to guitars and drums.
</P>
<P>
   Brad O'Donnell's lyrics also are fresh and original. They are
not overtly about Christ, but definitely written from a Christian
perspective toward life's twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
