<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-     09-02 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRETTIER GRAPHICS WITHOUT TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY   
 c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: The graphics on some Web pages are distorted.
Is there something I can do to make them clearer? I can't even read
them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blurred
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BLURRED: Well, I always try to sober up a bit before I
begin surfing.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, your display settings are probably wrong.
Web graphics are usually designed from a palette of at least 256
colors. If your computer is only displaying 16 colors, the graphics
are going to look like bad photocopies of somebody's hindquarters,
which, incidentally, I wish you people would stop mailing me.
</P>
<P>
   If you have enough video memory to display more colors, changing
your settings will make everything look better. In Windows 95/98,
right-click on an empty spot on the desktop and pick Properties
from the menu that appears. On the Settings tab is a box showing
available color settings. Make the change, then do a restart.
</P>
<P>
   If that box only shows 16 colors, you either don't have enough
video memory or you don't have the right display driver, the little
program that tells your display what it's capable of. If you have a
name-brand PC, go to the manufacturer's Web site and download the
correct driver for your model. If you have a clone or a junker,
you'll have to figure out who built the motherboard or video card,
then hope the manufacturer has a download site.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: What is pipe cache?
</P>
<P>
   _ In the Dark
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DARK: Isn't that something crackheads need to get high? I,
of course, know nothing about such things.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``pipeline'' cache is a different matter altogether.
Pipelining is the continuous flow of instructions to the processor
chip. While the chip is working on one instruction, another is
already in the pipeline, sort of like in the assembly line at GM,
unless those parts plants go on strike again.
</P>
<P>
   A cache is a chunk of memory dedicated to holding that sort of
data temporarily, making it rapidly accessible to the
microprocessor. Think of it as a waiting room for your data. Stuff
may be coming in or going out too fast for some component to handle
it, so it waits temporarily in the cache until it can be processed.
Generally speaking, microprocessors can handle data much faster
than regular memory can deliver it. Cache memory serves it up
faster.
</P>
<P>
   Level-1 (or L1) cache memory is built into the microprocessor
and delivers its load more quickly. PowerPC chips use L1. L2 is
usually on a separate chip, but still faster than regular RAM. And,
as with everything else in computing except the price tag, the
bigger the number, the better. Most current PCs have 512K caches.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't you sorry you asked? Most people just ignore all those
numbers and get the computer than runs fastest in the showroom.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Are you in favor of forcing computer
administrators to speak English?
</P>
<P>
   Englishmajor\Nnamelesscorp.mad
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MAJOR: Yes. I also fervently believe that pigs can fly, and
the only reason they don't is a lack of motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Computer geeks are no different. They too often live in their
own little world of bits and bytes, falling into an arcane patois
of their own making that only their ilk understand, seeing no
compelling reason to leap out of their trees. But if you take one
out to the ballgame, buy him some nachos and pump a few beers in
him, you'll find he's pretty much the same as any other human, and
can even speak your language if pressed. But if he starts yapping
about pipeline cache while McGwire's up to bat, just pop him one in
the schnoz.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-28-98 1556EDT &QL;
</P>
