<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5628 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     09-02 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTS' FROLICS WITH WOMEN WHO WERE NOT THEIR WIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Long before Bill Clinton strayed off the marriage
reservation, presidents and presidents-to-be frolicked through
affairs with women who were not their wives or who were other men's
wives.
</P>
<P>
   Not all such liaisons were consummated. But some were torrid
anyway, and all were memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Take this example:
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire was warm. The sofa was soft. We held each other
close, closer. ... Wouldn't it be wonderful if this were the day we
conceived a baby _ our very first time. Ike was very tender,
careful, loving. But it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   So wrote Kay Summersby, an English woman who served four years
during World War II as Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower's driver and,
according to her memoirs, the woman he loved.
</P>
<P>
   Although they talked about having a child, Summersby explained,
she and Eisenhower never consummated their love because his
inability to do so. He may have been too stricken with guilt to
perform the sex act because his wife of nearly 30 years, Mamie, was
waiting in Washington for his return from war.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Harry Truman told a biographer that Ike had written
to Gen. George C. Marshall, the Army chief of staff, saying he
wanted to get a divorce and marry Summersby. In reply, Truman said,
an irate Marshall threatened to bust Ike out of the army if he ever
did such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   When Ike returned from Europe in 1945 to succeed Marshall as
chief of staff, the affair ended. He later became president of
Columbia University, supreme commander of NATO forces and in 1952 a
successful candidate for president on the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In that campaign, Ike's relationship with Summersby never became
a public issue although there was some gossip about it because the
two had been photographed together many times.
</P>
<P>
   Summersby had written a book when the war ended about her
service with Ike without even hinting at romance. Then, in the
1970s, when she was dying of cancer and he was already dead, she
wrote her second book, ``Past Forgetting: My Love Affair with
Dwight D. Eisenhower.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the father of our country had his amorous longings for
another man's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Young George Washington cared deeply for Sally Fairfax, who was
married to his friend and neighbor, George William Fairfax.
Washington confessed his love in a letter to her written in 1758,
when he was 26 years old and engaged to marry Martha Custis, who
became his wife.
</P>
<P>
   As the drive for American independence gathered momentum, the
Fairfaxes remained loyal to George III and eventually returned to
England.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Thomas Jefferson was dispatched to Paris to
succeed Benjamin Franklin as American minister to France. There,
the 43-year-old widower from Virginia met and fell in love with an
English woman named Maria Cosway, 27, whose husband painted
miniature canvases.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson and Mrs. Cosway spent many engrossing hours together,
and when she and her husband left Paris for London, Jefferson was
devastated. For some time thereafter, he and she kept up a
correspondence in which they spoke of their love for each other.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, historian Fawn M. Brodie, author of ``Thomas Jefferson:
An Intimate History,'' claimed that the letters exchanged between
the squire of Monticello and Mrs. Cosway were missives of such
ineffable tenderness that they constitute the most remarkable
collection of love letters in the history of the American
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Brodie was one of the historians who claimed that Jefferson
shared his bed for many years with Sally Hemmings, one of his
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Jackson, who was elected president in 1828, and his wife
Rachel were excoriated as adulterers because they had married in
1791 thinking her divorce from her first husband, Lewis Robards,
was final. It was not.
</P>
<P>
   When Robards learned that they were living together as man and
wife, he sued her for divorce, charging them with adultery since
legally she still was Mrs. Robards.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson and Rachel Robards were married legally in
1794, the adultery charge hounded them the rest of their lives.
Jackson contended that it contributed to her death in December
1828, shortly before his first presidential inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   At her burial Jackson said: ``I can and do forgive all my
political enemies. But those vile wretches who have slandered her
must look to God for mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a half century after Jackson left the White House,
Republican opponents of Democratic presidential nominee Grover
Cleveland, a bachelor, converted his sexual escapade with one Maria
Halpin into a chant:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma, Ma, Where's my pa?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone to the White House, ha, ha, ha.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland and Halpin had produced a son, and he later affirmed
her claim that he was the father of the boy and agreed to pay child
support. Reports of his relationship with Halpin made for lurid
headlines in the 1884 presidential election _ which he won.
</P>
<P>
   Warren G. Harding is another president famous for his sexual
encounters. For many years before his nomination in 1920 Harding
had an affair with Carrie Phillips, the wife of one of his Ohio
friends. To avert scandal in the election, the Republican National
Committee sent the Phillipses on a voyage to Japan, paid them
$20,000 and then allocated modest monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   Harding's best-known affair was with Nan Britton, a worker in
his campaign who was 30 years his junior. After his death in 1923,
she claimed he was the father of her daughter and unsuccessfully
sought money from his estate. She then wrote a best-seller entitled
``The President's Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, we have learned that Franklin D. Roosevelt had
a long-standing romance with Lucy Mercer Rutherfurd and that John
F. Kennedy enjoyed the sexual favors of Marilyn Monroe and numerous
other young women.
</P>
<P>
   So in the future, as we consider the qualifications of
presidential candidates, maybe we should also invoke the French
saying _ ``cherchez la femme'' (look for the woman).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
