<SLUG> BC-CPT-AMD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 AMD's New Chip Can't Catch Intel  
 By Dan Fost   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its race to keep up with Intel, Advanced Micro Devices will
unveil a faster version of its K6-2 chip Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But AMD's 350 megahertz chip already is lagging Intel's 450 MHz
Pentium II processor, which was announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, they're making good progress with the K6 and
ramping up the clock speed,'' said Linley Gwennap, editor of
Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter. ``That's good news
for AMD, but Intel keeps running faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Dana Krelle, vice president of marketing for AMD's computer
products group, conceded, ``We are not quite able to match them all
the way up the line, but we're closing the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   AMD, which is based in Sunnyvale, has been Intel's biggest
thorn, pioneering the chips for personal computers that sell for
under $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Intel of Santa Clara, the world's largest chipmaker, now
concedes that it was late in recognizing the importance of the
low-cost PC and this week unveiled a new version of its inexpensive
Celeron chip.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a lower-priced chip, Intel won't match AMD's prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same performance level, AMD is 25 to 30 percent less
expensive,'' Gwennap said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's 450-MHz Pentium II, for instance, will sell in volume to
PC-makers for $669, while AMD's 350-MHz chip is selling in bulk for
$317 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Krelle said AMD will have a 400-MHz chip out later this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-26-98 2218EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POOR-SUBURBS-$ADV06-C     09-02 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOR-SUBURBS-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 6.
 &HT;    With COX-POOR-DATA.
 &HT;    Trying for photo of Roop.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ It started out as a straight trade, tools for
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Roop, a man worn thin by manual labor, offered up his
electric saw to the pawn shop clerk at a suburban strip mall along
Route 1 in Fairfax County. Outside in a battered pickup truck his
longtime companion, Cassandra Stewart, waited patiently. She needed
the money he would get for his saw to pay for medicine to ease the
pain of a chronic pancreas condition.
</P>
<P>
   But as Roop counted out the money he got for pawning his saw,
another problem loomed. A few months earlier Stewart had run out of
medicine and Roop had pawned his prized shotgun. If he didn't use
$8 from the money he got for the saw to meet his monthly payment on
the shotgun, he would lose the gun forever.
</P>
<P>
   Roop is puzzled. It's not supposed to be like this. It's
supposed to be like it was for his father, a blue-collar worker who
worked his way up to foreman, bought a house, raised a family and
prospered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a greedy person,'' Roop said. ``I'm just trying to
make a living. And I'm willing to work from daylight to dark. But I
just can't seem to get a toe hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Roop works full-time as a heavy equipment operator. At 33 he has
worked all of his adult life. He is up every morning at 5 o'clock
bursting to start work. In the afternoons, he is calling the office
every few minutes lining up a job for the next day. Until recently
Stewart worked too at a supermarket. But despite today's Tiffany
economy, men like Paul Roop are finding it harder to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Roop and Stewart, with whom he has lived since 1994, are part of
what the U.S. Department of Labor classifies as ``the working
poor.'' They are two of the nearly 7.4 million Americans who live
near the official poverty level _ $10,850 a year for couples,
$16,450 for a family of four _ but make too much to qualify for
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   What is worse, economists say the ranks of men like Roop are
growing. When economists look at the U.S. economy they see a giant
poker game where a few have won most of the chips while everyone
else at the table is scrambling to win a hand just to stay in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   In the past quarter century, the incomes of those making more
than $100,000 have increased 30 percent while those making less
than $25,000 have seen their incomes shrink by 21 percent,
according to a study by the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities,
a nonprofit group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Despite unprecedented economic growth, including the lowest
unemployment and inflation rates in decades, the poverty level of
the United States has remained almost immune to improvement in the
past decade. Today, 36.5 million Americans, 13.7 percent of the
population, live in poverty, even with modest wage gains in the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent gain in wages is a welcome reversal of long-term
wage decline, but most working families are still playing
catch-up,'' said Jared Bernstein, an economist at the nonprofit
Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the gap between the haves and have-nots can be
seen all too clearly along this ragged stretch of Route 1 where
Roop is literally going into hock.
</P>
<P>
   Route 1 cuts through the eastern edge of Fairfax County, one of
the richest counties in the United States. Between 1990 and 1996,
Fairfax County residents with annual incomes exceeding $100,000
increased an astounding 11.21percent, from 16.39 percent to 27.60
percent, according to Claritas, an economic research firm. But its
middle and working classes have not reaped the economic benefits
that its wealthier residents have.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Seay, owner of the pawnshop where Roop brings his
possessions, knows this only too well. Seay boasts that business is
so good in Fairfax County he only has to work two days a week.
</P>
<P>
   While statistics are difficult to come by, Professor Robert
Johnson of the Credit Research Bureau at Georgetown University
estimates that the number of pawnshops like the one Seay operates
have doubled in the last 10 years. And most of that growth, he
says, is in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in pawnshops that cater to people like Roop has been so
phenomenal that five chains are now listed on either the New York
Stock Exchange or the NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   And along with pawnshops have come check cashing outlets. Roop,
for example, cannot scrape together enough money to open a checking
account. He cashes his payroll checks at a check-cashing outlet for
a 2 percent fee. He pays his bills with money orders, 25 cents each
at a local convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four months, he has been operating heavy equipment
for Driggs at $13.50 an hour, with no benefits. He gets between 30
and 37 hours of work each week, sometimes not enough to cover his
meager living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Before the job at Driggs, he worked for 13 years at Dyna
Electric, getting $15.50 an hour making traffic lights, a job he
had held since dropping out of high school. But he was laid off
last December, two weeks before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra has applied for a $7-an-hour job at a nearby Food Lion
grocery store, but her health and job history _ a series of
part-time and entry-level jobs _ have hindered her prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and politicians argue over why such a vibrant economy
would at the same time increase the ranks of the working poor. They
cite the decline of unions, the erosion of the minimum wage, the
shift from manufacturing to service jobs, the globalization of the
economy through trade and immigration, technology's demand for
skilled workers, tax policies that favor the rich over the poor and
changes in family structures.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the economic and policy chatter in Washington
matters much to Roop. Every cent he and Stewart spend has
consequences. Even a 60-cent candy bar poses a budget dilemma.
That's why pawning his shotgun was such a sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   The .410 shotgun from Montgomery Ward was not expensive. And it
reaped only a $40 loan from the pawn shop. But to Roop, it was
special, a gift from his parents on his 15th birthday , and he had
used it to bag his first deer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But medicine is more important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now with five $10 bills from pawning the saw, should he pay $8
to the pawn broker to hang on to the shotgun another month?
</P>
<P>
   He hands back one of the $10 bills to the pawn clerk. ``I don't
want to lose it,'' he would explain later. ``To me, it's worth a
million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
