<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-ORACLE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-02 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ORACLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Oracle Has Big Plans Online  
 By Jamie Beckett   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oracle chief executive Larry Ellison has seen the company's
future _ and it is on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The database giant's chairman yesterday unveiled Oracle Online,
a plan to allow customers to lease Oracle programs and space on its
computers over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For Oracle, the plan is key to its battle to challenge
Microsoft's dominance of the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's future is based on the idea of Windows
everywhere,'' Ellison said at a press conference. ``We think that
will never happen. We think it will be the Web everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, the world's second-largest software company, is trying
to shift more computing from the desktop to the Web, which Ellison
says is cheaper, easier to manage and more efficient for customers.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, Oracle is readying new versions of its
database software and its application server that are able to
handle the traffic and demands of Web computing.
</P>
<P>
   With Web-based computing such as the Oracle Online scheme,
applications would be debugged, upgraded and maintained on a
central server instead of on each personal computer, and users
would access them using a Web browser, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about a massive paradigm shift,'' Ellison said.
``We're betting very heavily that's how the world will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft responded yesterday by chiding Ellison for
``apparently being consumed with Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile we remain entirely focused on our customers, and
we'll see who builds the best technology,'' said Greg Shaw, a
spokesman for the Redmond, Wash., software giant.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison said Oracle expects to introduce Oracle Online soon, but
he did not specify an exact date. Oracle Online is aimed at
small-and medium-size businesses that would otherwise have to buy
expensive hardware and set up complex computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not have to install software. All you would have to
do is log onto Oracle Online, and we'd do it all for you,'' Ellison
said.
</P>
<P>
   In his typically ebullient style, the 54-year-old executive
detailed ways other companies could customize Oracle Online. One
example would be a ``Yahoolike service'' for doctors, in which
physicians log onto a secure Web site containing such data as
patient records, billing information and pharmaceutical
information. Doctors could go to the same site to use a software
program that would do their accounting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors want to figure out how Windows NT works. They want to
figure out how your body works,'' Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Oracle Online service would be an industry
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``My jaw was on the ground. I haven't seen anything like it,''
said Juliana Nelson, an analyst at International Data Corp. in
Mountain View. She said the success of Oracle Online will depend on
its pricing, which wasn't divulged yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson called Ellison's focus on Web computing ``dead on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry was saying they're making a bet (on Web computing). I
don't think it's a bet. It's happening,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Web computing ``is the best possible positioning for them to
assume in their battle with Microsoft,'' said Merv Adrian, an
analyst at Giga Information Group in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's event at Oracle headquarters was designed to show
off the newest version of its application server, a crucial piece
of the company's Internet strategy. The program acts as a
go-between that makes it easy for users to pull database
information and programs off of a central server. Oracle said its
Application Server 4.0 can handle 10 times more data and 10 times
more users than previous versions.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle 8i, the newest version of Oracle's database, is due out
by Christmas, said Mark Jarvis, senior vice president of worldwide
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The database, Oracle's first to adopt the popular Java
programming language, is designed to ``do everything to set up
electronic commerce,'' Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-26-98 1858EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
