<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5641 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TELNET-ART-2TAKES     09-02 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TELNET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELNET TEXT OFFERS EASY ASSET TO INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By GLENN FLEISHMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You log onto the Internet one day, and it's blazingly fast; no
more World Wide Wait. Pulling up Web pages is instantaneous. Your
e-mail soars by more quickly than you can read it. Information is
at your fingertips with hardly a pause.
</P>
<P>
   A dream of the future? No, it's the Internet of yesterday: no
graphics, no fancy software, simply unformatted text in an
80-character-by-24-line window.
</P>
<P>
   With a few bits of knowledge in hand, you can gain access to the
World Wide Web, your e-mail, terabytes of file archives and other
Internet resources using telnet, a piece of Internet technology
that has been aged to perfection over the last 30 years. It's fast,
efficient and less subject to the vagaries of regularly changing
bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Telnet is a method of typing text on your own computer which
gets sent over the Internet to another computer, either at the next
desk or on the next continent. Through text commands, just like
those found in MS-DOS, you can operate this other computer.
</P>
<P>
   This can amount to something as simple as listing the files in a
directory or as complex as reading e-mail or Web browsing _ all
without pictures, buttons or clicking.
</P>
<P>
   Working over the Internet, telnet connects a computer using a
program that runs on, for example, a PC with Windows 98, to another
machine that can handle several users at once, like a mainframe or
a server computer. (The server is typically running the Unix
operating system, but Microsoft Windows NT and other computer
systems can handle telnet as well.)
</P>
<P>
   After connecting, you can execute programs on that separate
machine, just as if you were typing on a keyboard directly
connected to that machine.
</P>
<P>
   To run a program, type the command and hit enter; this is why it
is called a command-line interface _ as opposed to the graphical
user interface, with icons and mouse movements, that describes both
the Macintosh and Windows operating systems. The server runs the
software you specify and displays the results. There are no images.
</P>
<P>
   In real terms, let's say you are on vacation overseas, with your
laptop far behind, and you want to read your e-mail. Find any
computer with an Internet connection, no matter how slow, and you
can connect to your Internet service provider or your company's
computer with little fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people still use telnet every day around the world
to handle their e-mail, write software, search library collections
and create documents _ all without a graphic in sight.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, telnet is often favored by programmers and the
visually impaired. Speed is also a benefit: because it is
text-based, even the slowest possible connection still seems perky.
</P>
<P>
   Telnet was developed in the early 1970s, when the collection of
networks that would later come to be called the Internet first
allowed university researchers to connect to machines all over the
country by directly dialing into a modem connected to those
machines. Telnet evolved as a way to operate those distant machines
while taking advantage of the nascent network.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists and military personnel were the original audience;
many computer scientists still rely on it as their primary tool. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Telnet's original purpose was to mimic older machines that had a
single function: sending and receiving text through a wire
connected directly to a mainframe computer. The first of these
devices, the teletypewriter, or tty, was just a typewriter and a
roll of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Later advances brought a monitor-and-keyboard combination called
a video-display terminal, or VDT, but users still exchanged only
text. Graphics required too much computer horsepower, and the
connection speeds were far too slow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not every server or mainframe will allow someone to telnet in.
Some corporations and other institutions have firewalls, or
software that acts as a protective barrier between machines inside
the institution and those outside. These firewalls often prevent
outside users from using telnet via the Internet if they are
outside of the corporate network. Secure versions of telnet that
exchange encrypted information may be used in these cases.
</P>
<P>
   So why use such an ancient mechanism, aside from the geek appeal
and the desire to impress friends and colleagues with your
technical elan? For one thing, it works almost everywhere; for
another, a text-only connection can be extremely fast. There are
also some services you can't gain access to any other way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many libraries spent a lot of money in the 80s and early 90s
providing dial-up connection and telnet access to their catalogs
and related information. Most of those services remain active and
updated _ and not on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Public Library, for instance, maintains a full
searchable catalog via telnet at spl.lib.wa.us. Seattle library
patrons can also request books on line and have them transferred to
branches near them throughout the city, or get put on a waiting
list for the next available copy.
</P>
<P>
   The Library of Congress has long maintained a telnet service
(locis.loc.gov) for searching its vast information base and now
offers the same searching on the Web (www.loc.gov).
</P>
<P>
   With some ISPs, you can use a Web browser called Lynx after
establishing a telnet connection. Lynx is a program that runs on
the computer you connect to, and it retrieves the Web pages you
request and displays only the text from those pages.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   You navigate by using the arrows keys and the Tab, Enter and
space keys to move around and select links on the pages. Many Web
sites offer text-only versions of their sites, which are somewhat
easier to navigate with Lynx.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Telnet may be quaint. But even though text-only telnet surfing,
e-mailing and word processing can be an odd experience on this
ever-more-graphical Internet, it can make a pokey connection into
Niagara Falls. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How to Do It &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting the telnet software
</P>
<P>
   Windows: Windows 95, 98 and NT have a stripped-down version of
telnet software that is installed along with the built-in Internet
software. From the Start menu, select Run. At the prompt, enter
``telnet'' and hit Enter.
</P>
<P>
   More elaborate telnet programs are available as freeware or
shareware, or commercially. Dave Central, an index to resources on
the Web, lists 47 telnet programs
(www.davecentral.com/telnetclnt.html). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Macintosh: NCSA Telnet, formerly the most widely used telnet
program, has not been updated since 1995. Better Telnet, a more
recent adaptation of that original software, is available free from
Sassy Software (www.cstone.net/rbraun/mac/telnet). For other
choices for Macs, see www.macatawa.org/mthomas/telnet.html. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Connecting &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Connecting via telnet is simple: enter the full name of the
remote machine or its Internet Protocol (IP) number. For example,
subscribers to Panix, a large Internet service in New York, connect
to either panix.com or 166.84.1.66; the name and address are
interchangeable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before using telnet to connect to a machine, you need a user
account on that server computer. Getting a user account is like
getting a room in a hotel; you can wander the halls at will, but
without the key to your suite, you can't get in to use the phone or
watch a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Many ISPs used to include these accounts as part of the service.
Few nationwide providers now offer it, but many regional ones still
do. You can also get an account at a nonprofit community network or
local ``freenet.'' These free or inexpensive accounts often include
limited telnet access to run software like Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   With an account, you connect and enter your user name and
password as prompted. Some systems provide a menu of programs or
services. Others connect you directly to the equivalent of an
MS-DOS prompt, at which you type the name of the software, like
``lynx.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bit of warning: many servers, for security reasons, set off
internal alarms when someone connects via telnet, even when the
server computers automatically rebuff the attempt. To avoid a
problem, or even prosecution, connect only to services you signed
up for, or publicly advertised ones like library catalogs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A nice test drive for your newfound knowledge that does not
require a user account is the Library of Congress catalog. (Note
that many parts of the catalog are unavailable late at night and in
the wee hours.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Always press Enter after typing in text at each step below.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Connect to the Internet in whatever way you normally do (or
none at all if you're always on line). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Start your telnet program (this varies depending on your
software). If you're given a chance to select a ``terminal type'' _
the kind of old hardware that telnet will behave like _ select
vt100, which acts as a standard least common denominator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Enter the name of the Library of Congress Information System
server, locis.loc.gov. (Different telnet programs prompt you for
the name in different ways: in the built-in Windows telnet program,
select Connect from the File menu; in NCSA Telnet for Macintosh,
select Open Connection from the File menu. In either program, enter
locis.loc.gov in the field labeled Host Name.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Text will appear on the screen, giving you access to
different collections. Enter 1 to browse the library's catalog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. At the next screen, enter 3 to search books catalogd since
1975. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. The library's catalog has many somewhat cryptic commands, but
here is a sample search to get you started. Below the ``ready for
new command'' text, enter ``b gates, bill'' to browse (``b'') for
books by or about Bill Gates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. Enter ``f b06'' to retrieve listings representing that set of
found books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. Enter ``display item 18'' to read one of the bibliographic
entries. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
