<HEADER>
A5647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-POOL-HOUSE-NYT &LR;      09-02 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-POOL-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOLSIDE POETRY, HIGH-TECH HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with SWIMMING-POOL-DESIGN)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We wanted clean, simple, serene,'' the owner said. ``We wanted
to feel the air, the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   And so his pool-house-without-walls, in woodsy northwestern
Connecticut, is no more substantial than a breezeway with a
pavilion at each end. Yet with its playful evocation of Mies van
der Rohe's pavilion in Barcelona, Spain, and Philip Johnson's glass
house in New Canaan, Conn., it has more impact than the pool,
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Framed like a picture _ or a mirror _ the pool is edged in wide,
rosy flagstone and set in a crisp lawn. It faces a prairie meadow
of wild grasses, black-eyed Susans and ruffs of Queen Anne's lace
and reflects the pool house, the design of Elizabeth Demetriades, a
Manhattan architect, and her associate, Patrick Walker, a designer.
The pool and two surrounding acres are the work of Ken Smith, a
Manhattan landscape architect.
</P>
<P>
   The client and his wife, who prefer anonymity, have a 1968
Normandy-style brick weekend house but are modernists at heart.
Four years ago, the client called the architects separately and
told them what he wanted. The house and pool were to be on a
hayfield next to but hidden from the tennis court. The house was to
be self-sufficient, a spare yet friendly machine for leisure, where
the family could listen to Frank Sinatra (the adults) or the Blues
Brothers (the pre-teen-age daughters), grill steaks and watch
television.
</P>
<P>
   Who needed a main house? This was to be a pool house of earthly
and technological delights, airy yet sheltering. The enemies were
the gnats and mosquitoes and occasional summer squalls.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Demetriades designed a paradox: an open structure that also
defies insects. The trick? Screens that, with a press of a button,
roll down from the ceiling on three sides. (The fourth side, the
kitchen, has sliding aluminum doors.)
</P>
<P>
   The pool house is an homage to high-tech, but imbued with a
little poetry. From the main house, the approach is down a path to
a slanting retaining wall of stuccoed concrete, and then down 12
steps to the pool house, itself. The structure is silver gray, with
roof and siding of aluminum and zinc-coated steel. Ms. Demetriades
painted the poles and beams orange, like ``urban primed steel,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The pavilion on the west, shaped like a wedge, is the changing
room and bath, where translucent glass provides privacy while
letting light filter in. The changing room opens onto an outdoor
shower.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite pavilion, which houses a kitchen, is predictably
state-of-the-art. On a wall is a tiny screen, activated by touch.
It's a control center for this minimal house, regulating a network
of lights and four zones for music: there are amps by the pool,
under the roof, at the tennis court and by the barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   The client asked Smith to point the pool to the unobstructed
south, so that it would reach toward the open sky. Smith calls the
pool and garden American Zen. ``It has the basic emptiness about
it, connecting the sky and the water,'' he explained. ``When you
look out, it seems very simple, very open, very infinite.''
</P>
<P>
   The simplicity is ``deceptive artifice,'' said Smith, who made
sure that the water was the same natural shade of the sky on any
given day by making the pool out of speckled gray concrete. ``If
you have a white-bottomed pool, like in California, the water looks
turquoise, and if you have a black-bottom pool, you get a mirror
effect. But if you choose medium-gray, the water looks like the
sky. It looks blue.''
</P>
<P>
   If simplicity was his mandate, what could be more artless than a
prairie meadow of wildflowers? But these flowers haven't been
randomly chosen. They are white shading into cream and canary, part
of a golden palette that contrasts with the water and sky. ``Reds
and purples would muddy the place,'' Smith said. So, he planted
thousands of black-eyed Susans, day lilies, tiny white asters and
feathery native grasses the color of wheat. Goldenrods were already
in the field, and the stalks of Queen Anne's lace were a
serendipitous gift of nature. ``They blew in,'' he said. They are
late bloomers, flowering from June to September, and so extending
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   To divide the pool from the rest of the property, Ms. Smith
created a viburnum hedge and a discreet handmade fence. Woven from
two-inch copper flashing and set into a redwood frame, it is
weathered gray, with only a few patches of copper glinting with the
original sheen.
</P>
<P>
   The client is so delighted that he wants Smith to design another
project for his 20-acre property. What does the man who already has
a tennis court and a pool want?
</P>
<P>
   A one-hole golf course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
