<HEADER>
A5648 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEACH-BOOKS-TEX     09-02 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS FOR VACATION READING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Blast From the Past''
</P>
<P>
   By Kinky Friedman
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster
</P>
<P>
   254 pages; $23
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THE KINKSTER: A cigar-chomping Texan, Friedman was a
contemporary of the ``outlaw'' country movement of the early '70s,
which included Willie Nelson and Waylon Jennings. Kinky also hung
out with Bob Dylan and penned tunes such as ``They Don't Make Jews
Like Jesus Any More.'' He turned to writing pop-culture-laden
mysteries years ago; all feature him in the starring role as a
gumshoe/singer/songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THE BOOK: This latest take on the ol' Kinkster-on-the-case
formula is sort of a prequel to the others: Our hero is knocked out
and transported back to the decadent '70s, when he did lots of
cocaine, drank lots of Irish whiskey, slept on friends' couches,
scraped together a meager living playing New York clubs, and
generally was a down-but-not-out country singer.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLOT? Well, it has to do with what appears to be a vengeful
ghost. Noted radical Abbie Hoffman makes several appearances.
Gunshots are fired, an apartment is blown up, and there is much
drinking and a bit of breaking and entering before the whole thing
is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   CAN I READ IT QUICKLY? Like, on a beach? Yes. Friedman's style _
peppered with wry humor and phrases like ``take a Nixon'' (used
whenever one has to go to the bathroom) _ is breezy.
</P>
<P>
   YEAH, BUT DO i WANT TO? Well ... yeah. But ``Blast'' is not
Kinky's best book: The plot is not exactly robust. Kinky is locked
into one style, and he doesn't veer from it, although one feels
that perhaps he should.
</P>
<P>
   Those who love the guy _ mainly folks over 30 who remember him
from 'way back when _ will devour this book. Those who have never
read him before may be better off starting with ``Greenwich Killing
Time'' to see what all the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   ``Suits Me: The Double Life of Billy Tipton''
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Wood Middlebrook
</P>
<P>
   281 pages, Houghton Mifflin, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   THE AUTHOR: An English professor at Stanford, Diane Wood
Middlebrook last wrote a biography of poet Anne Sexton. The genre
seems to be her forte; her research here is impeccable, especially
for a subject who left behind no written account of why she chose
to live her life the way she did.
</P>
<P>
   BILLY TIPTON, THE WOMAN: Born Dorothy Lucille Tipton in Oklahoma
City in 1914, Tipton lived her life as a man when she became aware
that a woman couldn't make a career as a jazz musician in the
Midwest. The secret wasn't revealed until a doctor's exam upon her
death in 1989. Even her five ex-wives and adopted children were
surprised to learn that their Billy was a woman.
</P>
<P>
   HOW'D SHE DO IT? The restroom door was always locked, the
bedroom lights always off and her torso bound, which she blamed on
rib damage from a car accident when she was young. She wouldn't let
her lovers touch her. Still, one wife claimed Billy was the best
lover she ever had.
</P>
<P>
   THE UNFOLDING: Middlebrook starts with Tipton's home life,
telling of her eccentric parents (her father was an inventor and
airplane enthusiast who would take the 6-year-old Dorothy on
daredevil wing walks).
</P>
<P>
   The most fascinating section chronicles the transformation from
Dorothy to Billy, and relates life in the misogynist jazz age. The
book is illustrated with photographs, some of which tell more than
anything the author could explain.
</P>
<P>
   PRONOUNS, PRONOUNS: Pay attention to the use of ``he'' and
``she.'' The author frequently interchanges them, using each as it
pertains to the aspect of Tipton's life being discussed at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Mark Lowry
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
