<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-CONFESSIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SITES TO CONFESS ONE'S SINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Nev., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By PAMELA LI CALZI O'CONNELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet may be the world's largest confessional. Its
paradoxical combination of anonymity and intimacy provides fertile
ground for admissions that might never be aired in ``real'' life.
</P>
<P>
   Even when real names are known, the medium _ a step removed from
physical contact and thus, perhaps, from perceived consequences _
somehow evokes a closed-curtain, hush-toned closeness that draws
people out in occasionally astonishing ways.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who frequents a newsgroup, e-mail discussion group, or
chat room will eventually be privy to a confession _ of a lie, a
vice, or even a crime. In a recent dramatic example, a regular
participant in a Net support group for alcoholics admitted that he
had killed his daughter in North Dakota, and was arrested after
several members notified the police.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the man, Larry Froistad Jr., was given a 40-year
sentence with 10 years suspended as a result of a plea agreement in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   There are also Web sites that display or collect confessions. In
these sanctuaries, the act of confession is emphasized. The
audience is secondary. Take Confess.net (www.confess.net). At this
simple, spare site with its somehow soothingly straightforward
address, only the confession of the last visitor is displayed until
a new one is added. No identifying data are required, and the site
has no other content. This is the confessional as streamlined
application.
</P>
<P>
   Tane Langton, a New Zealander and web designer now living in
Prague, says he posted the site a few months ago for no other
reason than ``it's the kind of thing I'd like to use myself because
it's anonymous and public at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   A site that alternately allows all archived confessions to be
viewed is being collected as part of ``Surpu Masu,'' an event that
will take place Friday at the Burningman art festival in the Black
Rock Desert of Nevada. Surpu Masu will involve the burning of a
13-foot wooden ``sacrificial scapegoat'' stuffed with printouts of
the sins confessed to the Web site
(www.serv.net/jmurphy/anunaki/sm.html).
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle resident, Wally Glenn, one of the site's creators,
describes it as ``a mix of ancient mythology and a bit of
showmanship'' that borrows liberally from Sumerian, Chaldean, and
Semitic cultural symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite extreme of the public nature of Glenn's site is
The Ten Nines (www.fred.net/turtle/journal/tellme.html), a personal
confessional, for lack of another term, on the homepage of a
Baltimore computer consultant who goes by the online handle ``The
Turtle.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's name is taken from John Brunner's cult sci-fi novel
``The Shockwave Rider,'' which describes an untappable, untraceable
phone confession line reached by dialing the number 9 ten times.
</P>
<P>
   The Turtle's version of The Ten Nines provides an open text box
where visitors can type a confession to him and him alone, but the
results are not posted on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The Turtle does keep his own open Web diary called ``My Head
Talking'' that is linked to The Ten Nines. As a result, visitors
may feel they can use him as a ``disinterested sounding board,'' as
he puts it, because he's so open about his own life.
</P>
<P>
   While he won't quote directly from any of the dozens of postings
he says he's received, he says ``it's pretty amazing the range of
things that people will say when they're pretty sure that no one
can throw it back in their face. People have confessed to crimes.
People have told me stories of infidelities, revenge, fetishes and
perversions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some may be reluctant to take the Turtle at his word, since
there's no way to review the messages he's received. In fact, that
goes for the confessions that are openly posted at various other
sites; there is no way to tell a true confession from a false one.
</P>
<P>
   But surely cabdrivers and bartenders, favored confessors of the
pre-online era, would confirm that people will tell strangers the
most amazingly personal things. With the ease _ and sense of
removal _ provided by technology, is it any surprise, as Glenn
says, that ``people want to confess and will use whatever means
possible''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
