A5685 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOE-MANIA-TEX     09-02 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOE-MANIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THE SHOE FITS _ OR NOT _ I'LL BUY IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shoes are covered in purple-and-white checked cloth, flecked
with little purple and green flowers; they have impossibly pointed
toes and lavender stiletto heels, one of which the cat has chewed.
Circa 1955. I call them my ``I Love Lucy'' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   I paid $2 for them 14 years ago at a garage sale, and since then
have had them on my feet for perhaps three hours total, possibly
because the pain involved is akin to that of childbirth. (Possibly
because they are purple.) Still, I hang on to them just in case
they someday miraculously fit.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I have a thing for shoes. So did Cinderella. So did
Dorothy. (Ruby slippers, anyone?) So do a lot of other women. So
many that a Fort Worth publisher this week introduces ``Shuz: Your
Complete Guide to What's Underfoot'' _ the first magazine dedicated
to shoe freaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prefer to call them shoe enthusiasts,'' editor Stacy Girard
said diplomatically. ``Shuz,'' published by Magnolia Media Group,
hit newsstands this week with the first of its twice-yearly issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has either been, `I don't get it' or `Oh my God!
I've got to have a copy!' '' Girard said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the average American woman owns 30 pairs of
shoes and that women's shoes are a $15 billion-a-year business,
it's a wonder that no one has thought of this before.
</P>
<P>
   But Girard notes that not even the fashion mags such as
``Vogue'' devote much space to shoes; models are often photographed
barefoot. This may owe much to the fact that a 6-foot-tall model
can rarely wedge her foot into one of those tiny size-5 samples.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the area of clothing, shoes may be the great
equalizer: Most of us will never look like Cindy Crawford, but we
can have her shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like trying on a bathing suit, where you have to look
at yourself, and maybe you don't like what you see,'' said Lori
Vargo, a staff psychologist at Temple University in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your feet don't change as dramatically as the rest of your
body,'' she said. ``Shoes are just like the perfect fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers figured that out a long time ago. There are many, many
stores devoted solely to shoes, but hardly any that sell, say, just
sweaters or tube tops. Part of that is due to the practicality of
shoes:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has to wear them.
</P>
<P>
   They're inexpensive; you can find great shoes for less than $50,
and even the best designer shoes cost far less than the best
designer dresses.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to unzip or unbutton anything to try them on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's something to the fact that people can be
serviced hand and foot, if you will,'' said Steve Lunder, vice
president of marketing for Dexter Shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has to wait on you. It's a quick and easy purchase.
You can go in and find a shoe and be out very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to a true shoe lover, that misses the entire point.
The thrill is in the hunt _ in the feel of the leather or the
suede, in the shape of the heel or the cut of the upper.
</P>
<P>
   I have friends who can't pass a shoe window without pausing to
look; others who keep their many dozens of shoes neatly labeled in
their original shoe boxes; others who buy basically the same shoe
over and over, only with this heel a little higher, that buckle a
little smaller, or in patent leather instead of suede.
</P>
<P>
   That this obsession applies mostly to women is largely due to
the vagaries of fashion. Men have fewer options. They need black
dress shoes, maybe brown ones. A pair of casual shoes. Athletic
shoes. Maybe hiking boots or work boots. Sandals, if they're daring
or young.
</P>
<P>
   Women _ well, women need shoes to go with short skirts and long
skirts; for work, for formal occasions. For jeans, for casual
pants, for dress pants, for shorts. Pumps, sandals, loafers, boots;
high heels, low, in-between. There's a
</P>
<P>
   good reason most of us own at least 30 pairs.
</P>
<P>
   But if 30 is average, how many is too many? After I took
inventory last week, I began feeling like a shoe junkie.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the 10 pairs in my take-to-Goodwill stack, or the
sandals I wear only to water the lawn, or the aerobics shoes I
store in my trunk in case of, well, an aerobics emergency, I own
... 43 pairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not that many,'' Lunder said encouragingly. (Sure, but
this comes from a man who owns perhaps 20 pairs _ the average man
owns well under 10.)
</P>
<P>
   Um, but 19 pairs are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure, when you're looking at the shoes, you see the subtle
differences,'' he reassures me.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a theory that is similar to the theory behind golf _
that the reason people like golf so much is that they always have
the potential to hit that perfect shot,'' Lunder says. ``It's the
same with shoes. There's always that potential that you'll find the
perfect pair of shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   That hardly explains why I once felt compelled to buy a pair of
purple-and-white stilettos, but still, just looking at those shoes
makes me happy. To a shoe enthusiast, that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
