<HEADER>
A5687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITS-BOWL-LADN     09-02 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITS-BOWL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITS SHOW TRUE LOVE FOR BROADWAY AT THE BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Hearing a Broadway musical in Britain can be sort
of like serving up bangers and mash at an East Texas barbecue. No
matter how artfully the thing is done, you may well lose something
in the translation.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for British actors Lynn Redgrave and Patrick Stewart,
that was never the case. Redgrave became hooked on American
musicals as a child, when her famous father, Michael Redgrave,
would bring back sheet music and recordings from his frequent
Broadway trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a great fan of American musical theater,'' she
recalls. ``He worshiped it.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up under quite different circumstances, in England's
gritty industrial north, Stewart says he and his brother used to
sing snatches of musicals together while sitting up in the bed they
shared as boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got all of my experience of American musicals probably for
the first 35 years from the movies,'' says the actor probably
best-known as Capt. Jean-Luc Picard of TV's ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation.'' &UR;  &LR; ``So I was brought up with `Carousel,' `Oklahoma!'
`Seven Brides for Seven Brothers,' not to mention all those Doris
Day movies, Tab Hunter and so on, `An American in Paris,' `Singin'
in the Rain'.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend at the Hollywood Bowl, as part of a musical bill
that Redgrave jokingly dubs ``Brits on Broadway,'' she and Stewart
will perform selections from Broadway classics ``Camelot,''
``Sweeney Todd'' and ``The King and I.''
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the ``Broadway With Fireworks'' programs that the
Bowl typically uses to close out its summer seasons with a bang.
Earlier in the evening, conductor John Mauceri will lead the
Hollywood Bowl Orchestra through suites from ``Ragtime,'' The Lion
King,'' ``Cabaret'' and ``Chicago,'' plus the Entr'acte from ``The
Sound of Music.'' The orchestra will wrap up with Jule Styne's
overture from ``Gypsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave can cite several breakthrough youthful encounters with
Broadway. She remembers getting the sheet music for Irving Berlin's
``Annie Get Your Gun,'' and later seeing Chita Rivera in ``West
Side Story'' when that musical swept London's West End.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s through the early 1960s, Broadway musicals
expressed postwar America's buoyancy and drive, while setting new
standards for dancing, subject matter and plain old-fashioned
spectacle. At the same time the Broadway musical was basking in its
golden age, British musicals of the time ``were all tennis
rackets'' and romantic high jinks, Redgrave says.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that when Redgrave was in New York City in 1966 to
publicize ``Georgy Girl,'' the comedy-of-manners film that launched
her movie career, she asked Columbia Pictures to get her tickets to
see Angela Lansbury in ``Mame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I just adored it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Britons of his generation, Stewart developed his first
mental pictures of America from movies _ which, as often as not,
meant Astaire and Rogers hoofing their way up a spiral staircase,
or Technicolor MGM fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my impressions of America came from movies, or maybe a
copy of the Saturday Evening Post that I'd managed to get my hands
on,'' he says. ``So until I was a little older and saw movies by
(Elia) Kazan and (John) Cassavetes, my image of the United States
was that it consisted of white picket fences and tree-lined
streets, or else the Wild West, plains and mountains and oceans of
grain. I had a kind of National Geographic idea of what America
looked like.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Stewart says, he's especially looking forward to
doing the selections from ``Sweeney Todd _ The Demon Barber of
Fleet Street,'' the blackly comic Stephen Sondheim/Hugh Wheeler
show about a deranged London haircutter who slits his customers'
throats and bakes their bodies in pies. Stewart calls Sondheim's
score ``one of the most emotionally powerful of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a role that I have fantasized playing ever since I heard
the recording of it,'' he says. ``First of all, the score is
brilliant, brilliant in its musicality, brilliant in the way it
communicates the madness and passion of Sweeney, in the way it
communicates the time, in the way it drives the story forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, in recent years several prominent British
directors have been revisiting American musicals and gleaning
darker themes and visual subtexts from them. Nicholas Hytner's
recent production of ``Carousel'' for Britain's Royal National
Theatre (which played at Los Angeles' Ahmanson Theatre) placed a
strong emphasis on the musical's class divisions and its plotline
involving domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Nunn's current London revival of ``Oklahoma!'' reportedly
looks past the reassuring Corn Belt homilies of the Rodgers and
Hammerstein musical to the isolation and loneliness that also
framed the American frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be in the English nature a tendency to look for
perhaps some darker and even grimmer undertones in all kinds of
work,'' Stewart observes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Redgrave, who lives with her husband in Topanga, took
another big step toward Americanization: She officially became a
U.S. citizen, primarily, she says, so she'd be entitled to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't ready for it for a long time,'' she says of
becoming a citizen, ``not that it makes any difference to anyone
else. It's more a sentimental gesture to oneself.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she intends to stay in the United States, which she calls
a ``bigger pasture'' than Britain, she still occasionally gets
pangs for her homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear a bit of music that takes you back to the green
fields and the lushness that only England seems to have in the
summer, or the smell of, I don't know, an English sausage!
Something quintessentially English.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone for adding English sausages to the Bowl takeout menu?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
