<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-NUKES03-COX     09-02 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-NUKES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The fate of a proposed radioactive-waste dump in
West Texas is now fully in the hands of Texans after the U.S.
Senate voted Wednesday, 78-15, to allow waste from Maine and
Vermont to be shipped to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   With a veto from President Clinton unlikely, the next move is up
to the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission, which is
weighing whether to license the dump's location near Sierra Blanca,
about 90 miles southeast of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate action _ backed by both of Texas' senators,
Republicans Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison _ did not specify a
site for the waste but ratified an agreement among Texas, Maine and
Vermont that will allow the smaller states to ship their
radioactive waste south as soon as a storage site is built. Nine
similar agreements, known as compacts, among a total of 41 states
have previously been approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush was pleased by the Senate vote, according to
spokeswoman Shirley Green, but he is withholding full endorsement
of the location until the commission rules on the safety of the
Sierra Blanca site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has said that he's troubled that two
administrative law judges do not feel that the applicants have
proven the safety of the Sierra Blanca site,'' Green said,
referring to a July report from two examiners for the commission.
``He has said all along that if the site is not proven safe, he
will not support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's challenger for the governor's office, Democratic Land
Commissioner Garry Mauro, criticized Bush for opposing amendments
to the Senate action that would have foreclosed any other state
from eventually using the Texas dump site. None of the other
agreements approved by Congress contained that limitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is talking out of both sides of his mouth,''
Mauro said in a statement Tuesday. ``Governor Bush says he supports
the Sierra Blanca site if it's proven safe; he says he won't let
Texas become a national dumping ground. But Governor Bush hasn't
instructed his appointees to the TNRCC to reject the Sierra Blanca
site, and he opposed an amendment to the compact bill that would
have prevented Texas from becoming a national nuclear dumping
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas opponents of the dump site _ some of whom watched the
debate and vote Wednesday from the gallery above the Senate floor _
said they will continue their fight before the TNRCC and the Texas
Legislature, which must appropriate money for the waste authority
that will operate the dump site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we're done with the Congress, we're going to be
focused on the Legislature,'' said Erin Rogers of Austin, executive
director of the Sierra Blanca Legal Defense Fund. Rogers said she
wasn't surprised by the lopsided Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was happy we got through to 15'' senators, she said.
``For a while, we just had one,'' Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who
was the only senator who spoke against the compact.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison took to the Senate floor Wednesday to urge her
colleagues to approve the compact: ``I would never support a
hazardous waste site in my state that is not in full compliance
with state and federal regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said after the vote that he did not speak out on the
Senate floor because ``my views on this are well known.'' He said
he was following the lead of Gov. Bush, Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock and
other state officials who support the compact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Wellstone tried to make his case, and, obviously,
nobody bought it,'' Gramm said. ``Am I to assume that Senator
Wellstone is more concerned about Texans than the governor?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Austin, who fought an open-ended compact
in the House, said he was disappointed that more state officials in
Texas didn't speak against the waste agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sounds of silence on this issue from most of our statewide
elected officials have sent a loud but unfortunate message to the
country,'' Doggett said: `` `Send Texas your nuclear garbage.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
