<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HOME-BUYERS-2TA     09-02 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HOME-BUYERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SALE AT LAST IN CHINA: DREAM HOMES, BUT NO SINK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Buying a home is a relatively new phenomenon
in China, and so is serious home furnishing. Even in Shanghai, the
nation's most affluent and modern-minded city, the decor in most
apartments still ranges from Spartan to dowdy to just plain
tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   But change is on the way. And not just because Ikea opened a
store here early this year. A new consciousness about home
furnishing is germinating in many Chinese cities, and it is growing
out of the surging popularity of buying a home itself.
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few kinks to be worked out. For one thing,
many home buyers have to pay cash, and that means toting bundles of
100-yuan bills _ the largest available, worth about $12 each _ that
have to be painstakingly counted at the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Once a sale is final, a new home is rarely ready for occupation,
even in a brand-new building. Getting an apartment in this city
usually means getting the space itself, without anything as basic
as paint on the walls or wiring within them, much less plumbing in
the bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. There seems to be no end to the number of people
eager to buy homes in China's cities, where a vast conversion of
housing from public to private hands means a revolution in Chinese
living standards.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of urban families in China are buying homes for the
first time. After years of talking about it, Chinese authorities
are finally getting serious about supporting home ownership, by
making mortgages available in some cases and by ordering local
governments to do away with the state-allocated housing that has
been a mainstay of the socialist system here.
</P>
<P>
   In the first seven months of 1998, housing sales in China shot
up 71 percent compared with sales a year earlier, authorities
reported. Although the number of new homes was not available,
official reports said a total of roughly 3 trillion square feet of
housing was sold
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Chinese tenants generally resisted buying as long
as their rent was almost free. But buyers are now emerging in big
numbers, not only because rents are certain to skyrocket with the
end of subsidized housing, but also because relaxed rules on
reselling homes mean that apartments are finally a viable
investment. Demand for housing looks so insatiable that average
prices are expected to climb for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   For Sindy Lee, a 30-year-old graphic designer in Shanghai,
owning a home means first of all having a little more space to live
in. Ms. Lee said that she gets along fine with her mother-in-law,
but that it was not ideal to be living with so many people _ her
husband, infant son and parents-in-law _ in a cramped apartment, as
most Chinese families do. Especially not when another choice came
along.
</P>
<P>
   The new one-bedroom apartment she and her husband bought for
$50,000 earlier in 1998 is in a building of about 30 stories in the
Xuhui district, a pleasant residential neighborhood downtown.
</P>
<P>
   While it is only 500 square feet, the apartment seems spacious,
since it is roughly double the average space for a family of three
in this city. Although modest in size, it has been carefully and
tastefully decorated, partly inspired by the the new
home-furnishing style magazines cropping up in this city of 14
million.
</P>
<P>
   The living room is painted a soft lime green _ ``a light, fresh
color that is kind to visitors,'' Ms. Lee explained. The bedroom is
peach, a warmer color, for herself. Instead of holding to any
specific set of feng shui-like rules, Ms. Lee seems have her own
sense of what works.
</P>
<P>
   And it does. The kitchen, gleaming with stainless-steel counter
tops and wooden cabinets, is unusually clean and modern for a
Chinese home. There is no oven _ Chinese cooking involves little
baking _ but there are four burners on the stove and two sinks, a
luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make our home a good place for my son,'' said Ms.
Lee, a pert woman with a page-boy haircut. ``Everything had to be
the way we wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lee and her husband chose pine flooring that is softer than
the concrete they were used to, and easier on the head of their
1-year-old son, Chi, when he falls. The corners of their yellow
cotton upholstered sofa and wooden coffee table are carefully
rounded, as are the edges of a desk where the family computer sits.
</P>
<P>
   Although most state-run furniture stores in China still play to
a widespread taste for chrome and black leather, Ms. Lee said she
did much of her furniture shopping at Ikea, which opened here in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The international chain has advertised widely, distributing a
million 16-page catalogs, and has found that birch, beech and
leather sell particularly well in Shanghai. (``Leather seems
popular because it's easy to clean and looks expensive,'' said
Chung Liu, an Ikea representative in Shanghai.)
</P>
<P>
   Taking such care in the renovation of a home is becoming as much
of a fad as buying one in China. Though credit cards are still in
their infancy, most homeowners expect to lay out at least half the
price of a new home for renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is probably what's keeping the economy alive this year,''
said Ms. Lee's husband, Richard Chen, referring to the renovation
and decoration business. A lot of his friends are either buying a
home or trying to buy one, Chen said, and all plan to carry out
extensive renovations.
</P>
<P>
   For Chen, who is 28, it was not so much the psychological sense
of security that made him want to buy an apartment. Nor was it just
plain economics, even in a society known for a careful evaluation
of the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the impetus for plunking down a lot of cash _ $50,000 is
a huge sum in a country where the average urban wage is still $50 a
month _ was his desire to improve his family's living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could never have things so nice if we rented,'' Chen said.
``The most important thing is having a higher standard of living.''
</P>
<P>
   In Shanghai, as in many other Chinese cities, most housing is
still in low-rise buildings where tenants have to share a kitchen
and a toilet with their neighbors. In the past, rent was not a real
concern, since it was typically less than $10 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The catch was that the standard of upkeep was appallingly poor.
And that is clearly part of why families like Ms. Lee's and Chen's
do not blink at spending half the cost of their home, or nearly
$25,000, on a thorough renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People buy a home because it means they can fix it up the way
they want,'' Chen said. ``You can renovate it to your own
specifications.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chen's case, this meant starting almost from scratch. In
China, perhaps because private housing is a relatively new thing,
developers get away with selling apartments in new buildings that
lack even the most basic amenities, like electrical outlets or
faucets in a sink _ in some cases, even the sink itself.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Chen knew that. He is a graphic designer for American
Standard, the maker of bathroom and kitchen fixtures, and he was
eager to have the apartment done over.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton visited Shanghai in June, he spent an
afternoon meeting with homeowners as a way of recognizing the new
freedom Chinese people have to live where they wish, rather than
where they are assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders are pushing home ownership, less for the freedom
it affords people than for the opportunity it gives the state to
get rid of an onerous and finance-draining responsibility. Housing
subsidies for all of China's 200 million to 300 million urban
residents are scheduled to be phased out by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders are also eager to find ways to get access to the
enormous cash holdings that ordinary Chinese have in the bank,
since the nation's savings rate of roughly 40 per cent of income is
among the highest in the world. In Shanghai, as in many other
cities, state-owned developers are putting up thousands of
apartment buildings, creating a huge glut of new housing.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of housing is already benefiting China's
carpenters, decorators, plumbers, brokers and financiers.
Economists point to housing reform as a key to China's economic
health. So restrictions on buying and selling homes are dropping
away. On June 1, Shanghai formally made it legal for people to
resell their homes on the open market; previously, special
permission was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measure aims to stimulate the city's property market,''
said Cai Yutian, director of the Shanghai Housing and Land
Administration Bureau. That enables Ms. Lee and Chen to look ahead
to selling their apartment and finding a bigger one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a bit small,'' Ms. Lee observed. ``Our son is still
a small child, so it's OK having one bedroom. But when he gets
bigger, we're going to want more room.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many buyers, Ms. Lee and Chen combined a bank mortgage with
loans from relatives. Typical mortgages are now available for 10 or
15 years, at 7 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly payments of about $400 require about a third of Ms.
Lee's and Chen's combined income. A little adjustment may be
necessary, since they are not used to paying for housing, but the
couple said they would manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I don't get laid off, we're OK,'' Chen said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities say that few home buyers have defaulted on
mortgages in cities that pioneered housing reform. That message is
meant to encourage state-run banks _ which are still unused to
making loans to individuals _ to venture into the mortgage
business.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's work at American Standard made him particular about how
his bathroom was done. First he had it expanded to a length of
about 8 feet, roughly twice the original length, even though that
meant cutting into the living room. Then he had a full-length
bathtub installed, a rarity in a Chinese home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to play in the tub,'' Chen said, gesturing at his
son.
</P>
<P>
   Chen also had a shower with a sliding Plexiglas door installed,
as well as a wide sink. He had gray tiling laid, with a design he
selected himself.
</P>
<P>
   Since most Chinese customers are first-time home buyers, few
have experience working with contractors, and stories of shoddy and
substandard work are legion. Chen said he had to watch the workers
night and day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually moved in next door for two months so I could
supervise them,'' he said. ``I don't think they liked that very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is justifiably proud of the results. Chen's home is a
pleasant contrast to many new Chinese homes, filled as they are
with all that chrome furniture with black leather upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very particular idea of what we wanted,'' Chen said.
``Buying a home is still new in China. It's a lot of work, but it's
worth it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
