<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: JUST THE TICKET; ONE PERFORMANCE ONLY; GERMANY
HONORS SPIELBERG; 500 YEARS AND STILL SINGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa., Mass., Maine, Canada)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One-stop shopping for full-price tickets to most
Broadway and Off Broadway shows came to Times Square Wednesday when
the League of American Theaters and Producers opened the Broadway
Ticket Center in the Times Square Visitors Center on the east side
of Broadway between 46th and 47th Streets. The center, open from 8
a.m. to 8 p.m. seven days a week, sells tickets to same-day and
advance performances. On opening day, the league, the national
trade organization for the Broadway industry, offered tickets to 16
Broadway shows, excluding the Disney attractions, and five Off
Broadway shows, and said it hoped to expand the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Coming Attraction
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has songs by Cole Porter, a book by Moss Hart and
a cast that includes Bea Arthur, Tyne Daly, Michael Jeter and
Damian Woetzel of the New York City Ballet, all directed by Herbert
Ross. It's the 1930 romp ``Jubilee,'' featuring classics like
``Begin the Beguine'' and ``Just One of Those Things.'' It will
have only one performance, a benefit concert for Gay Men's Health
Crisis on Oct. 10 at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Honors
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of his impact on the world's understanding of the
Holocaust, Steven Spielberg is to be awarded the Officer's Cross of
the Order of Merit by President Roman Herzog of Germany in
ceremonies Sept. 10 in Berlin. Herzog's office said Wednesday that
Spielberg's 1993 film ``Schindler's List,'' about a man who saved a
thousand Polish Jews from the Nazis, provided ``a very noticeable
contribution to the issue of the Holocaust.'' Spielberg's latest
film, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' opens the Venice International Film
Festival Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Old Boys
</P>
<P>
   In 1498, by decree of the Hapsburg Emperor Maximilian I to
provide soprano and alto parts in sacred music performed for the
monarchy in the Imperial Chapel, the Vienna Choir Boys were
established. In celebration of its 500th anniversary, this beloved
musical ensemble will tour 10 North American cities from Oct. 12 to
25. Joined by the Chorus Viennensis, an ensemble of former Vienna
Choir Boys, and by the Vienna Chamber Orchestra, the choir will
present works by, among others, Mozart, Haydn, Schubert (himself a
Vienna Choir Boy) and Antonio Salieri, the choir's artistic
director for nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Concerts are scheduled in Montreal (Oct. 12), Kitchener, Ontario
(Oct. 14), the New Jersey Performing Arts Center in Newark (Oct.
16), Lewisburg, Pa. (Oct. 17), the Tilles Center in Greenvale, N.Y.
(Oct. 18), Carnegie Hall in New York City (Oct. 19), Amherst, Mass.
(Oct. 20), Portland, Maine (Oct. 22), Symphony Hall in Boston (Oct.
23) and the Kennedy Center in Washington (Oct. 25).
</P>
</TEXT>
