<SLUG> BC-TV-CAYUTAVILLE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CAYUTAVILLE': RURAL LIFE HAS ROOM FOR ANGST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beneath the picture-postcard scenes of pastoral America,
writers, at least since Sherwood Anderson and Edgar Lee Masters,
have discerned a depressing reality: Things are not as they seem
amid the foliage.
</P>
<P>
   Now a television documentary maker confirms that civilization's
discontents do not spare an upstate New York community despite the
beauties of a snowy winter and the childhood frolickings of summer.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cayutaville,'' Diana Crone Frank trains her camera mainly
on two families, the Chapmans and the Soules, and finds plenty of
angst. Theirs is a Christian community, centered around faith and
church, but these prove frail defenses against early death, heroin
addiction, economic buffetings and family breakups. Shunning
narration, she lets parents and children tell their own, mostly
melancholy stories.
</P>
<P>
   Particular attention is given to the most dire cases: Robert
Chapman, father of three, who is unable to shake off his grief over
a daughter's death years ago at the age of 10, and one of the Soule
sons, Robert, who passed much of his life cut off from his parents
and in a heroin haze. (Robert has since died.)
</P>
<P>
   Cayutaville is not prospering, and neither family is awash in
money. Chapman has resigned his teaching job for reasons not made
clear; the beautiful old Chapman home has been mortgaged. Robert
Chapman's attention to tending his daughter's grave seems obsessive
and plays into the breakup of his marriage. A daughter says her
mother has finally ``gotten out from under his thumb,'' but it is
he who seems liberated.
</P>
<P>
   Soule, retired from his job as a guard at a youth camp,
apparently carried his authoritarian style into his home and may
have contributed to his addict son's sense of failure. But his
other children seem content to raise their own families not far
from home in jobs that are guaranteed not to make them rich.
</P>
<P>
   Despite intimations of guilt, blame, responsibility, Ms. Frank
sensibly stays clear of judgments of what went wrong. Instead she
returns to church meetings where some of the family members find
consolation for their disappointments in the warmth of community
and the security, despite everything, of small-town living.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CAYUTAVILLE'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Friday night
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 10)
</P>
<P>
   Diana Crone Frank, creator and director; Ms. Frank and Christine
Solinski Romero, editors; Ms. Frank and WSKG Binghamton, producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
