<HEADER>
A5725 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHAT-WE-BELIEVE-TEX     09-02 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-WE-BELIEVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD RELIGIONS: THIS WEEK, BUDDHISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORIGIN: Buddhism, one of the world's major religions, began in
what was northern India, now southern Nepal, and traces its origin
to Gautama Siddhartha, who lived from 566 to 486 B.C. Revered as
the Buddha, ``the awakened one,'' Siddhartha was a prince who
married, had a child, and then left his royal family and became a
wandering monk in search of truth. He was destined to achieve
enlightenment because of the merits he had accumulated in his
former existences. He saw ``the four sights:'' a sick person, an
old person, a corpse and an ascetic who was trying to avoid
suffering and death by abandoning the pleasures and
responsibilities of ordinary life. Siddhartha also tried asceticism
but later adopted ``the Middle Path,'' in which he led a balanced
life of self-denial and self-indulgence. He is seen as a source of
enlightenment but is not worshipped.
</P>
<P>
   MEMBERSHIP: U.S. Buddhists are a growing presence, but they are
a small portion of the 300 million adherents worldwide. Estimates
vary, but the Yearbook of American &AMP; Canadian Churches estimates
that 565,000 Buddhists live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The world's most famous Buddhist leader is the Dalai Lama,
spiritual leader of Tibetan Buddhists. He is revered as a
reincarnation of the Buddha. Most Buddhists live in Asia and
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEFS AND RITUALS: Buddhist practices vary from culture to
culture. Basic beliefs include reincarnation and meditation to
achieve spiritual ascendance. The ultimate religious experience is
to end the cycle of rebirth by achieving ``nirvana,'' a state
marked by a cessation of worldly cares and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhists follow the eightfold path divided into three areas:
moral conduct (right speech, right action, right livelihood);
mental discipline (right effort, right mindfulness, right
concentration); and intuitive wisdom (right views, right
intentions). Five moral precepts are: not to kill, not to steal,
not to lie, not to abuse sex and not to use intoxicants. Images of
Buddha are central in worship.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Abingdon Dictionary of Living Religions; The
HarperCollins Dictionary of Religion; Yearbook of American &AMP;
Canadian Churches; Encyclopedia Americana.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
