<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday, Hurricane warnings were issued for the central Gulf
Coast as Hurricane Earl crawled sluggishly northeastward through
the Gulf of Mexico. Though Earl will likely remain a minimal
hurricane in terms of its wind speeds, the tropical cyclone will
bring prodigious rain to southern Alabama, southern Georgia and
sections of the Florida panhandle on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rainfall tallies could exceed 10 inches in a few spots by
evening, causing local flooding, particularly in areas already
affected by the storm's torrential rain bands. Meanwhile, partial
sunshine will fuel additional showers and thunderstorms in the
sultry air covering the Carolinas and Florida peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Subsiding currents of air behind the tropical system will
squelch clouds across the southern Plains and Texas. The resulting
sunshine will help boost afternoon readings past 100 degrees near
the Red River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation around a swirling mass of cool air aloft will bring
unsettled conditions to the northern Great Lakes and interior
Northeast on Thursday. A solid layer of low, gray stratus clouds
will enhance the chill, holding daytime readings in the 60s from
northern Michigan to upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably hot air will continue across much of the West on
Thursday as a strong ridge of high pressure near 20,000 feet
remains over the region. Beneath ample sunshine, late afternoon
temperatures will soar past 100 degrees in the Central Valley of
California. The heating of the uneven terrain will spark isolated
thunderstorms over some of the mountain peaks of the interior
West. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: HURRICANE WARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, hurricane warnings were issued for parts of the
Gulf Coast despite the fact that an offshore storm was designated
Tropical Storm Earl. The apparent discrepancy is an outgrowth of
unique considerations in warning the public about tropical
cyclones. The prospect of a landfalling hurricane often impels
emergency management officials to order evacuations of coastal
areas, which can require many hours to complete. On Tuesday,
despite uncertainty about the intensification of Earl, forecasters
hoisted hurricane warnings so precautions could be completed before
the storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
