<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES SLIP SLIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of most Treasury securities slipped slightly
Wednesday, as stock markets around the world stabilized and the
dollar weakened in currency trading, lessening the flight into the
government securities market that has been an almost daily
occurrence lately.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, however, the 30-year Treasury bond rose 3/32,
to a price of 102 17/32. The yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, slipped to 5.33 percent from 5.34 percent the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   With yields at a 30-year low, the lure for some investors is not
as strong as it was a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Davis, senior technical analyst at Thomson Global
Markets in Boston, said, ``Essentially, the markets are all due for
some corrective activity,'' which, she added, could come on Friday,
when the Labor Department reports the nonfarm payroll number for
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``An aggressive 350,000 gain or more will probably knock bonds
for a loop, sending prices lower and yields higher,'' she said,
particularly if the dollar continues to weaken. ``The next bond
trade is apt to be down,'' she said, adding that the ``price has
come too far too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The range of economists' forecasts goes from 205,000 new jobs to
430,000. Thomson Global Markets is looking for a rise of 325,000,
which is slightly lower than the consensus, but still on the high
side.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Whelan, vice president and portfolio manager at Aeltus
Investment Management, is also cautious on bond prices. He urged
investors not to try to rationalize current low yields on economic
grounds. While Treasuries may have become a commodity symbolizing
safety for speculators and day traders, he said, ``long-term
investors must be able to square bond prices with economic
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite investors' many worries about the effects of weaker
foreign economies on the United States, factory orders in July rose
by a strong 1.2 percent, the Commerce Department reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whelan cautioned that Treasury securities, having priced in a
50-basis-point drop in rates, already reflected a lot of the good
news. ``In fact, with the admission that economic data lag, there
is no proof yet of a dramatic slowing in the U.S. economy,'' he
said. ``Current data suggest that third-quarter GDP growth is
likely to be 2.5 percent to 3 percent, not 1 percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
