   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUMMIT (Moscow) _ President Clinton signaled Wednesday
that the West would be willing to expand its program of financial
assistance if Russia carried out tough economic reforms. Clinton's
message was intended to encourage the Yeltsin government to stick
with its pro-capitalist course despite the nation's deepening
economic crisis. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Moscow) _ For President Clinton, there is no
escaping Monica Lewinsky. Even within the walls of the Kremlin, at
a time when Russia is seething with political intrigue and economic
privation, Clinton was confronted with questions about his
acknowledged relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, a 25-year-old former
White House intern. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-GENOCIDE (Arusha, Tanzania) _ A U.N. tribunal
investigating mass killings in Rwanda handed down the first guilty
judgment by an international court for the crime of genocide
Wednesday. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ President Clinton told the grand
jury investigating his relationship with Monica Lewinsky that he
was troubled by the onetime intern's transfer out of the White
House and considered bringing her back last summer, according to
lawyers familiar with his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-TAMOXIFEN _ An advisory committee to the Food and
Drug Administration voted unanimously Wednesday to approve the
marketing of a drug, tamoxifen, to reduce women's' risk of
developing breast cancer. According to the National Cancer
Institute, tamoxifen is the first drug that can diminish the
chances that healthy people would get a major cancer. But the drug
is not a panacea, experts warn. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-FATHERS (Washington) _ With tough new rules now in place
for welfare mothers, the spotlight is turning to welfare fathers,
and dozens of programs have sprung up in the last few years,
seeking to raise the incomes of these missing men and strengthen
their ties to their children. By Jason DeParle. With photo. 2,200
words.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-STRIKE _ Northwest Airlines laid off 27,500 workers
Wednesday and canceled all its flights through the Labor Day
weekend, turning the five-day old strike by the airline's pilots
into a more protracted battle. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
</TEXT>
