<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5766 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACKING-BLACKFILMS-TE     09-02 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKING-BLACKFILMS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a Dallas professional, Inez Brand has a full plate during the
week. On the weekend, however, she always finds time for a movie _
especially if it's targeted at African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually somehow falls into the weekend plans,'' said Brand,
a diversity specialist for Northrop Grumman in Dallas. ``Friday,
Saturday or Sunday _ it'll fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand is after more than entertainment. She is president of the
Dallas chapter of the First Weekend Club, a group that supports
films starring and/or made by African-Americans. Although the seeds
were sown with the premiere of 1995's ``Waiting to Exhale,'' the
club was founded in March 1997 in Los Angeles, with the Dallas
chapter forming late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas chapter's phone message describes the club's mission:
``Our goal is to grab Hollywood's attention by supporting selected
African-American films at the box office in their first weekend of
release.'' The current message encourages callers to catch ``Why Do
Fools Fall in Love,'' a story about '50s teen idol Frankie Lymon.
It opens today and stars Larenz Tate, Halle Berry, Lela Rochon and
Vivica A. Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The club, with chapters in nearly a half-dozen cities
nationwide, uses phone calls, faxes, letters and e-mails to alert
members to the openings of African-American movies. In the
competitive movie market, a good opening weekend can mean the
difference between a movie staying in the theaters for weeks _ and
becoming a hit _ or getting quickly shuttled off to video stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we have waited for the video to come out or for
the crowds to die down,'' Brand said, ``without being aware of how
important the first weekend of box office was.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it puts the emphasis on quality, the group doesn't try
to boycott such films as Ice Cube's prostitution-themed drama ``The
Players Club.'' It mobilized 4,700 people nationwide to catch ``How
Stella Got Her Groove Back'' in its first weekend. ``Stella,''
starring Angela Bassett and based on Terry McMillan's bestselling
novel, debuted at No. 2 at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive was the performance of ``Blade,'' starring
Wesley Snipes, which was last weekend's No. 1 box-office movie.
Another movie featuring African-Americans, ``Dance With Me,''
debuted at No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the African-American audience is underserved at the
movies. Approximately 250 movies will play Fort Worth-Dallas in
1998; only about a dozen are aimed at African-American audiences.
They range from the major-studio ``Stella'' to the cruder hip-hop
comedy of ``I Got the Hook-Up'' to the romantic comedy-drama ``Hav
Plenty,'' a Woody Allen-influenced indie that had a brief run on
one Dallas screen.
</P>
<P>
   After the ``blaxploitation'' craze of the early '70s, few
black-oriented movies were made until the mid-'80s, when films by
Spike Lee and Robert Townsend started gaining attention. Even so,
Lee's latest, ``He Got Game,'' received a very limited release,
despite being one of 1998's more masterfully directed movies.
</P>
<P>
   But even ``Game'' depicted some characters (especially women) in
a bad light, and one of the club's motives is to see more positive
images in African-American movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got a long way to go,'' Sandra Evers-Manly, the
club's co-founder, said from Los Angeles. ``You don't see a lot of
movies with black romance, or with a black child praying.''
</P>
<P>
   And although many films star black actors, they're usually in
tandem with a white star, who is usually higher-billed. That
doesn't mean the club would rule out a movie like ``The
Negotiator,'' in which Samuel L. Jackson shared top billing with
Kevin Spacey. But the club particularly hopes to drum up support
for movies built around stars such as Jackson and Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   The club is based at the Black Hollywood Education and Resource
Center in Los Angeles, where Evers-Manly is president. The club
also has chapters in Washington, D.C.; Oakland, Calif.; and
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas chapter has more than 100 members, Brand said; anyone
interested in supporting black cinema is welcome. ``Our group in
Dallas is more diverse than other places, in fact,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other unrelated organizations have been helping get the word
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, we've sponsored screenings of movies such as
`Ghosts of Mississippi, The Preacher's Wife' and `Waiting to
Exhale,' '' said Gwen Barbee, executive director of the Women's
Division of the Fort Worth Metropolitan Black Chamber of Commerce.
``We're going with quality _ not just because it's a black movie
that's out there. We want movies we can recommend.'' The
African-American newspaper Dallas Weekly and urban-contemporary
radio station KKDA also sponsor preview screenings.
</P>
<P>
   The gay-oriented newspaper Dallas Voice does similar sponsorship
of gay-themed movies. But neither the Fort Worth or Dallas Hispanic
chamber of commerces were aware of any similar group supporting
Latino-themed movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take into consideration the size of the Hispanic
population, you can make an argument that the population is
underrepresented as far as characters go,'' said Rene Rodriguez,
film critic for the Miami Herald. ``But many Hispanics have grown
up so assimilated into American culture, I don't think they're as
hungry for Hispanic movies as African-Americans are for movies like
`Stella.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics and other people of color can also benefit from the
First Weekend Club, however. Chayanne, the leading man in ``Dance
With Me,'' is Puerto Rican, and ``Selena'' director Gregory Nava is
behind the camera again for ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love,'' the
club's target movie this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The recent box-office numbers feed Brand's optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a huge difference, and you're going to see
it fast,'' she said. ``I think the percentage is going to increase
as black people take a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
