<HEADLINE>
DRUG PRICES VARY, SURVEY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Drug prices can vary dramatically among local
pharmacies, sometimes by as much as 91 percent for prescription
drugs and 175 percent for over-the-counter drugs, according to a
survey released Wednesday by the Massachusetts Public Interest
Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's astonishing,'' said Dierdre Cummings, the group's
consumer program director who has supervised surveys on everything
from insurance to groceries. ``I have never seen a spread that wide
in any retail product.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the survey found that prices for Augmentin, a
prescription drug used to treat infections, cost $111.32 for 42
pills at a Stop &AMP; Shop Pharmacy in Allston, but $173.17 at an Osco
Drug store in Boston. A tube of Neosporin costs $2 at Stop &AMP; Shop,
but $5.49 at Osco.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted in June, compared prices for 28
prescription and 15 over-the-counter drugs at six Boston area
pharmacies. Prices reported in the survey may have changed since
then, Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lesson is the same: Consumers can save hundreds of
dollars by doing some comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, however, aren't used to shopping around for their
pharmaceuticals, Cummings said. Many assume prices are similar at
all drug stores. Some patients, particularly those who are sick or
elderly, prefer the nearest pharmacy. Others don't care because
their insurance covers much of the cost for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing, Cummings said. As health insurers face soaring
drug costs, many are scaling back drug benefits, leaving an
increasing number of people to pay their own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more consumers are having to pick up the tab,''
Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Abramowitz, a health care analyst at Sanford Bernstein
in New York, estimates that up to 40 percent of Americans, roughly
110 million people, do not have prescription drug coverage, while
Deborah Socolar at Boston University School of Public Health put
the estimate at more than 30 percent of the population, or about 80
million people.
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Dion at Deloitte &AMP; Touche Consulting noted that drug
coverage among the elderly in particular is shrinking. ``Older
people are more likely to have chronic conditions and complex
illnesses that require lots of medication. That makes these price
spreads more important for them,'' Dion said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey estimates the number of prescriptions written per
person is expected to jump 15 percent this year from 1997, when
each adult and child in America was given an average of 11
prescriptions. An aging population, more rapid introduction of new
life-enhancing drugs, and aggressive pharmaceutical advertising
directed at consumers are among the forces leading doctors to issue
an increasing number of prescriptions, Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey has its limits, she cautioned. It did not include
mail-order drug companies, pharmacies at health maintenance
organizations and independently-owned pharmacies. In addition, the
survey captured prices during a one-week period in June, and
included sale prices and ``regular'' prices. Those prices have most
likely changed, and consumers will have to do their own homework to
get fresh figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1832EDT &QL; 
