<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SCHUMER IN THE STRETCH  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internal polls are starting to show Rep. Charles Schumer neck
and neck with _ or even slightly ahead of _ Geraldine Ferraro in
the three-way Democratic primary race for the U.S. Senate, with
Public Advocate Mark Green trailing.
</P>
<P>
   The polls, commissioned by candidates, have not been released
publicly. They focused on likely primary voters as opposed to all
eligible voters, and they reflect what has been a widespread
feeling among reporters and other political observers _ that there
has been considerable erosion in Ferraro's once-commanding lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would still be nervous if I were Chuck,'' said a person
familiar with the poll numbers, ``but his campaign seems to be
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, the best known of the candidates, has run a campaign
that at times has been so low-keyed as to seem nonexistent. She
announced her candidacy in January when she was well ahead in the
polls, and apparently decided that the best strategy was to do as
little as possible.
</P>
<P>
   She has tried to immunize herself against criticism by
repeatedly warning her opponents not to attack her, has tried her
best to avoid debating, and has fought angrily with reporters who
have attempted to pin her down on this issue or that.
</P>
<P>
   She has acted as though the Senate nomination should be handed
to her in the same way that Walter Mondale presented her with her
claim to fame _ the vice-presidential slot on his ticket in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll data suggest that Ferraro's strategy could be
leading to the kind of debacle that befell the hare that raced the
tortoise. She does well in surveys that target all eligible voters.
But Schumer seems to do better and better as the pollsters weed out
respondents who are not likely to vote in the primary. He does very
well among voters who are familiar with all three candidates, and
among those who are well versed on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro still benefits greatly from her celebrity status,
but her shrinking lead is proof that it is dangerous to run a
campaign entirely on what Mark Green has derisively described as
``the fumes of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary election is on Sept. 15 and the winner will go head
to head with Sen. Alfonse D'Amato. But while the momentum would
seem to favor Schumer, that may not last. The heavily financed
Schumer campaign has been running television ads introducing the
candidate to the voters all summer. Schumer has been on the tube
virtually alone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with less than two weeks to go, Ferraro and Green are also
going on the air. Ferraro, who has had trouble raising money,
nevertheless has about $1 million to pay for commercials between
now and Election Day. Her first ads, attractive and engaging, have
been well received.
</P>
<P>
   And while Green has had very little money to work with, the poll
data show that in a three-way race with a low turnout expected, his
candidacy is still viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see what happens now,'' said Lee
Miringoff, director of the Marist Institute for Public Opinion,
which conducts the respected Marist Poll. ``Now there will be lots
of ads by lots of people on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has an impressive legislative history. He is, among
other things, the leading gun control advocate in Congress and the
principal sponsor of the 1994 crime bill. But he was less well
known than either of his opponents and has struggled to boost his
name recognition around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Green has an impressive history as a consumer advocate but has
been chronically short of campaign cash. That has contributed to
concern that he might not be able to mount a winning campaign
against D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have tried to convince voters that their
accomplishments in public office make them better qualified for
admission to the Senate than Ferraro's most valued political asset
_ her celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Miringoff said he was doing a poll now and the results should be
released on the weekend. He noted that the primary has been
overshadowed by events on Wall Street, in Washington and around the
world. But he added that the campaign itself has been less than
exciting. ``It's been like a modern dance,'' he said. ``There
hasn't been any contact with anybody. No one touches anybody.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1843EDT &QL; 
