<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5791 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-WEDDING-TEX     09-02 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-WEDDING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTER UP TO THE MARTITAL PLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Reds and the Blues would probably prefer
that this story run on the sports page.
</P>
<P>
   Especially the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this was a baseball game. Last month, 19 guys
withstood the heat in order to replay history, a time a few years
back when many of them hit, pitched, caught, stole and ran for the
Southwest High School Raiders. Most of them, still in great shape,
meant business, even if there were other motives for calling the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The reunion was in celebration of 24-year-old Monte Pearson, who
on August 22 wed his high-school sweetheart, Jodi Sturgiss, at
First United Methodist Church in downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   What? A bachelor party without a cake girl or stag films?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, sir. Play ball!
</P>
<P>
   The best man with the plan was Michael Brandon, 24. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Monte and I both grew up loving baseball,'' he said. ``We
figured this would be our last chance to play a real, organized
baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Plan executed.
</P>
<P>
   There were red and blue T-shirts with the league's logo:
``Pearson's Bachelor Party, August 15, 1998'' (in that
baseball-style lettering, of course).
</P>
<P>
   There were buckets of bubble gum and packets of sunflower seeds
(hey, what's a ballgame without spit?). During the third and fourth
innings, Reds captain J.R. McLaughlin grilled 'dogs. There were
pickles, water jugs and ice chests full of Gatorade made from a
mix, which meant about an inch of sugary sludge at the bottom of
the bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon prepicked the teams, placing himself on the Reds and
Pearson on the Blues. ``I know everyone and could even it up,''
Brandon said.
</P>
<P>
   They rented a field at Fort Worth's Rockwood Park and hired an
ump from Texas Amateur Baseball Umpires. They got Bubba Selmon, who
obviously preferred his strikes low.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon even bought a ``Baseball's Greatest Hits'' CD, which
included such ballpark classics as ``Who's on First,'' ``Take Me
Out to the Ballgame'' and ``Casey at the Bat.'' The teams lined up,
hands over hearts for the national anthem, to begin the game.
</P>
<P>
   They had a few spectators. Occasionally, a parent would appear,
including the father of the bride, Dave Sturgiss.
</P>
<P>
   And, as is typical of sporting men, there was plenty of
locker-room camaraderie and references to the male anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   Missing were the organist grinding out ``Charge,'' recorded
music by Guns `N Roses and the ``Macarena,'' and that annoying HOT
DOG guy. And, oh, yeah, thankfully there wasn't a large-screen
wedding proposal.
</P>
<P>
   That had already happened, albeit not on the large screen.
</P>
<P>
   They played with Little League rules. ``You can steal after the
ball is past the plate,'' McLaughlin pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, had it not been for stolen bases, there wouldn't have
been many runs to home, even though the game was not devoid of
stars _ the Blues' Graham Robbins was the heavy hitter and Reds
pitcher Alan Hutson had some crafty pitches up his sleeve. The
groom, who claims that he ``wasn't all that good in high school,''
even had some luck on the pitchers mound.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the best man and his team got the best of
the groom's team. The score: 10-8 Reds. But no one cared who won or
lost; it was that they were ``able and willing'' to play with a
friend in what would be his last game as a single man.
</P>
<P>
   And at least there were no major injuries, an especially big
relief for Pearson's future father-in-law. ``What I was really
worried about is some of them getting hurt. We've got the best man,
the groomsmen, ushers ... I'd hate for them to come in on
crutches,'' Sturgiss said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
