<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-ARTIST-COX     09-02 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ARTIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Country stars of past bank on nostalgia craze
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug Johnson, the president of Giant Records in Nashville, is
pumped about his newest artist. ``I can't tell you how excited we
are about the album,'' he says, with the enthusiasm of a schoolboy.
``The music is alive and vibrant and real. Listening to it was an
absolutely spiritual event.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Johnson has an agenda for the hyperbole, but he's not
hyping some new, 25-year-old bellybutton artist who's going to give
Shania Twain a run for her money. Giant's newest act has gray hair,
sad eyes and is 59 years old. Longtime country fans will
immediately recognize his name: Don Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1974 and 1986, Williams had 17 singles that went to No.
1 on the country music charts, including hits such as ``Amanda,''
``Till All the Rivers Run Dry'' and ``You're My Best Friend.'' But
in the Garth Brooks-influenced '90s, Williams _ along with dozens
of other established country acts _ faded into obscurity. Now the
tide may be shifting.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Nashville labels have started taking a second
look at older artists, signing many to new recording contracts.
Ronnie Milsap, 52, who had 35 No. 1 singles between 1974 and 1989,
is working on an album for Warner Bros., set for release in 1999.
At age 57, Grand Ole Opry diva Connie Smith (``If It Ain't Love,
Let's Leave It Alone'') is reviving her late-'60s heyday with an
album produced by her husband, country star Marty Stuart. More than
two decades after he told his boss to ``Take This Job and Shove
It,'' wild and woolly Johnny Paycheck, 57, is working on an album
for Lucky Dog Records, while Georgian Bill Anderson, 61, is writing
and recording under a new contract with Reprise Records.
</P>
<P>
   Will country audiences respond? Lon Helton, the country chart
editor for the trade publication Radio &AMP; Records, says these
artists may find a home in the growing niche of classic country
radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Country radio has a wider audience age spread than any other
format in America,'' he says. ``Finding a song that appeals to an
18-year-old girl and a 55-year-old man is a pretty daunting task.
There have been a lot of interesting country formats that have
grown up in the last few years. Maybe if a classic country station
is already playing Ronnie Milsap, they'll play his new stuff as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1854EDT &QL; 
