<HEADER>
A5806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESERT-RECIPES-COX     09-02 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESERT-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Recipes for simple deserts with quick cleanup
</P>
<P>
   By Reagan Walker
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   A mixing bowl or saucepan. A spoon to mix and some to measure,
along with a cup. And a baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   That's all the equipment you'll need to make these divine
desserts. That means that's all there'll be to clean up, too.
</P>
<P>
   For those pressed for time, distressed by a perceived lack of
culinary prowess or depressed by the thought of a dirty kitchen,
these desserts are for you. The ingredient lists are simple,
containing many common pantry items. The skill required is minimal,
the cleanup quick.
</P>
<P>
   But the result? Trust us. When you tell your guests or family
that ``it's just a little something I threw together,'' they'll
chide you for being so modest.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   S'Mores Bars
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Utensils needed: One measuring cup, one measuring spoon, one
medium bowl, one double boiler or small bowl, one 9-by-13-inch
baking dish, one mixing spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Just the thought of s'mores fires up an image of a bonfire and
fun. But there's not much time to gather wood these days. Try
these. They deliver the incomparable combination of chocolate,
graham crackers and marshmallows without the fuss of a fire.
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2cups graham cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1pound milk chocolate
</P>
<P>
   4cups mini-marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a medium bowl, place butter;
microwave at 100 percent for 1 minute or until melted. Stir in
crumbs, sugar and salt. Reserve 1 cup of the mixture; press the
rest into the bottom of a flame-proof 9-by-13-by-2-inch baking
dish. Bake the crust for 12 minutes, or until golden. Cool in the
dish on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   In a metal bowl set over a saucepan of barely simmering water,
melt the chocolate, stirring until smooth. (Or place in a small
glass bowl and microwave at 100 percent power for 2-3 minutes or
until soft). Pour chocolate over the crust, spreading evenly.
Sprinkle the marshmallows over the chocolate, pressing them
lightly. Top with the reserved crumb mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Broil under a preheated broiler, about 2 inches from the heat,
for 30 seconds, or until the marshmallows are golden. Cool
completely and cut into squares. _ Adapted from ``The Best of
Gourmet'' Vol. 6 (Conde Nast Books, $27.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 194 calories, 1 gram protein, 11 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 52), 25 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 71 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Raspberry
</P>
<P>
   Cobbler Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Utensils needed: Measuring cup, measuring spoon, 9-by-13-inch
baking dish, one large mixing bowl, one mixing spoon.
</P>
<P>
   This decadent cross between a cobbler and a cake is sensational
warm with a scoop of vanilla ice cream, or cold with a glass of
milk.
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup (1 1/2 sticks) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4cups raspberries, fresh or frozen (no need to thaw)
</P>
<P>
   1cup semisweet chocolate chunks or chips
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Melt the butter in a
9-by-13-inch baking dish. In a large bowl, mix together the flour,
baking powder, salt, milk, vanilla and brown sugar. Pour half the
batter directly into the hot, buttered pan. Add 3 cups of the
raspberries and the chocolate chunks. Pour the remaining batter
over the berries, then top with the last cup of berries. Place the
pan in the oven and bake 35 to 40 minutes or until the center is
set. Let cool at least 10 minutes before serving. _ From ``Nathalie
Dupree Cooks Quick Meals'' (Clarkson Potter, $22.50)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 387 calories, 4 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 56 grams carbohydrates, 35
milligrams cholesterol, 118 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   The Dampest, Darkest, Deadliest Brownies
</P>
<P>
   of All Time
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 large brownies
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Utensils needed: One small knife, measuring cup, measuring
spoon, 9-inch-square baking pan, one large saucepan, one mixing
spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've tried these, you'll never want to use a mix again.
Andrew Schloss, author of ``One-Pot Cookies'' (Broadway Books,
$12.95) swears his title is not an overstatement. We tend to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   4ounces unsweetened chocolate, broken in pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4cups dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3eggs
</P>
<P>
   1cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Coat a 9-inch-square baking pan
with nonstick cooking spray. In a large, heavy-bottopecans and stir
well. Spread the coconut on a plate. Place a large storage
container next to the plate. Pinch off enough dough to make a ball
the diameter of a quarter. Squeeze the dough in your fist, then
roll into a ball, using both hands. Place the ball on the coconut
and repeat until about a dozen cookies are formed. Rinse and dry
your hands, then roll the balls in the coconut to coat. Remove them
to the storage container and repeat until all the cookies are
formed and coated. _ From ``Desperation Dinners'' by Beverly Mills
and Alicia Ross (Workman, $13.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 79 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 11 grams carbohydrates, 3
milligrams cholesterol, 54 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Impossible Coconut Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 pies, 6 servings each
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Utensils needed: One measuring cup, one measuring spoon, one
medium bowl, 1 mixing spoon, two 8-inch pie pans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impossible'' pies were quite popular in the '60s and '70s,
according to Pat Willard, author of ``Pie Every Day'' (Algonquin,
$19.95). That's because such recipes combine the crust and the
filling in one bowl, only to have them magically separate again in
the oven. This one, for custard lovers, is Willard's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup self-rising flour or biscuit mix
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1cup (2 sticks) margarine, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2cups canned flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a medium bowl, combine flour or
biscuit mix and sugar. Stir in eggs, milk, margarine, vanilla and
coconut. Pour mixture into two 8-inch pie pans. Bake in the center
of the oven for about 30 minutes or until a knife inserted in the
center comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 382 calories, 6 grams protein, 24 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 38 grams carbohydrates, 112
milligrams cholesterol, 327 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
