<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5807 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE03-COX     09-02 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Between-meal treats pack nutritional punch
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise. A recent study that looked at the eating
habits of teenagers found that America's kids are veritable eating
machines.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Teen Eating Study, commissioned by Channel 1 Network,
laid waste to the three-meals-a-day norm and found that close to
half of the nation's 23 million teens eat at least five times a
day, with 19 percent eating a whopping six times daily. Translated,
that means there's a whole lot of snackin' goin' on. In fact, the
study dubbed the afternoon snack ``the fourth meal.''
</P>
<P>
   A snack is broadly defined as food informally eaten between
regular meals, which means a snack could be just about anything. As
it is, the study found that teens favored fast food hamburgers,
pizza and Tex-Mex, in that order.
</P>
<P>
   But snacks can contribute more than empty calories. If you want
to start taking kids' snacks seriously, a good place to get started
is the Internet. For a feast of snacks start with
http://godzilla.eecs
</P>
<P>
   .berkeley.edu/recipes/snacks/index4.html. Just under the granola
category alone we found at least 50 variations of that classic.
Besides that there are hundreds of other possibilities, from
easy-to-make fruit bars to energy balls.
</P>
<P>
   For trail mixes that can be made up in large quantities and
easily stored, check out http://www.gorp.com/gorp/food/foogorp
</P>
<P>
   .htm. And finally, if you want to ratchet up your snack menu,
check http://www.pillsbury.com/seasons/recipes/appet.html for a
listing of some delectable snacks that could easily double as
appetizers or hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   SNACK
</P>
<P>
   Easy Bruschetta Snack
</P>
<P>
   Makes 15 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 15
to 17 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2teaspoons sesame seeds, divided
</P>
<P>
   1(8-ounce) can Pillsbury Refrigerated Crescent Dinner Rolls
</P>
<P>
   1(6-ounce) can pitted ripe olives, drained
</P>
<P>
   1cup finely chopped tomato
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup grated Parmesan and Romano cheese blend
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Brush large cookie sheet with 1
teaspoon of the oil; sprinkle evenly with 2 teaspoons of the sesame
seeds. Unroll dough; place over sesame seeds, firmly pressing
perforations to seal. Press to form 9-by-14-inch or larger
rectangle. Brush dough with 2 teaspoons of the oil; sprinkle evenly
with remaining sesame seeds. Bake 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in food processor bowl with metal blade or in blender
container, combine olives and remaining 3 teaspoons olive oil.
Process until olives are finely chopped.
</P>
<P>
   Spread olive mixture over partially baked crust. Top with tomato
and cheese. Bake an additional 5 to 7 minutes, or until edges are
golden brown. Cut into rectangles and serve warm. _ From Pillsbury
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 120 calories, 4 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 60), 7 grams carbohydrates, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 300 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SNACK
</P>
<P>
   Tortilla Roll-Ups (above)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 Preparation time: 20 minutes Chilling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1(4 1/4-ounce) can deviled ham spread
</P>
<P>
   1(3-ounce) package cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   4ounces (1 cup) shredded hot pepper Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   4(10-inch) flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, combine ham spread, cream cheese, Jack cheese and
parsley. Mix well. Divide mixture evenly among tortillas and
spread, covering entire surface. Gently roll up each tortilla,
jelly-roll fashion. Wrap each roll tightly with plastic wrap;
refrigerate 1 hour or until thoroughly chilled. To serve, cut each
roll into 6 slices._ From Pillsbury
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 416 calories, 16 grams protein, 24 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 33 grams carbohydrates, 60
milligrams cholesterol, 741 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Crunch
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   5small to medium apples
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Peel and dice apples and place in
medium baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle with cinnamon and 1/3 cup sugar. Cream butter and 2/3
cup sugar. Beat egg and add to butter mixture. Sift flour, baking
powder and salt. Add to butter mixture. Drop and spread thick
batter over apples. Bake 10 minutes at 425 degrees; reduce heat to
350 and continue cooking for 20 minutes. _ Adapted from Meal-Master
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 242 calories, 2 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 12), 53 grams carbohydrates, 41 milligrams
cholesterol, 126 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
