 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take the labor out of Labor Day meals with hassle-free desserts
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Labor Day weekend, the last three-day interlude of the
summer. Maybe the relatives are headed your way, and you'd like to
have a sweet snack on hand to greet them.
</P>
<P>
   Or your neighbors have invited you over for a backyard blowout
and your duty is dessert.
</P>
<P>
   But working in the kitchen is not your idea of taking a break.
As much as you'd like to show your family and friends they're
special, this just isn't the weekend to pull out the
cake-decorating kit and heat up the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Don't fret. We know how to take the labor out of Labor Day
desserts without resorting to the nearest bakery or supermarket
freezer case. There are a number of crowd pleasers that don't
require a 12-step cooking process, then a cleaning crew.
</P>
<P>
   With just a few basic cooking tools, you can throw together a
Chocolate Raspberry Cobbler Cake that's sure to be a sensation. Or
if you have a crowd coming, we've got a recipe for Orange Butter
Balls that takes just 20 minutes from start to finish and yields
several dozen irresistible morsels.
</P>
<P>
   Some of our recipes come from the series of ``One Pot''
cookbooks written by Andrew Schloss and Ken Bookman. By using only
one pan, these recipes eliminate not only hassle in the preparation
but also a sinkful of dirty dishes afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the idea when I used to visit a friend of mine who is
culinary-impaired,'' Schloss said. ``She always had the same
chocolate cake, which she said she could make because it only
required one pan. So I took the idea and started experimenting.''
</P>
<P>
   Cakes are by far the trickiest to streamline, Schloss says,
because they are more sensitive to chemical balances. Any recipe
that calls for beating egg whites is out, said Schloss, because
that requires a mixer and bowl. But many sweet treats can be
adapted to a ``one-pot technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some general guidelines from ``One Pot Chocolate
Desserts'' (Broadway Books, $12.95) for streamlining baking and
dessert recipes:
</P>
<P>
   -- Eliminate sifting of dry ingredients in many recipes. Sifting
is done to aerate the ingredients, but aerating flour is essential
for only the most delicate sponge or angel food cakes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Simplify the creaming of butter and sugar by partially
melting the butter in a large saucepan. The heat generated
completes the melting off the stovetop. When chocolate is part of
the recipe, it, too, will finish melting off the heat, so there's
no danger of scorching.
</P>
<P>
   -- Using the same saucepan as for the butter, add less
heat-sensitive ingredients next, such as sugar, vanilla, spices,
sour cream and yogurt. Then add the eggs after the mixture has
cooled a bit to prevent curdling.
</P>
<P>
   -- Baking powder and baking soda are added in pinches to allow
them to soften and disperse through the batter before the remaining
dry ingredients are added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of this technique is you can bake a lot more often.
I can throw a cake in the oven an hour before the kids get home or
when I start making dinner,'' Schloss says.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, we offer low-labor desserts perfect for the busy,
back-to-school pace of the coming weeks. None requires hauling out
mixers or food processors, or more than 20 minutes' preparation. We
show you how to become the star of the school bake sale with ``The
Dampest, Darkest, Deadliest Brownies of All Time.'' And the trick
to making s'mores without building a bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
