</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Down-home cooking with taste of Japan
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ If Michiko's restaurant were a bar, you could
call it Cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Hood tends to patrons with the casual care of a genial host
at home, while his wife, Michiko, turns out the dishes from the
kitchen, leading many regulars to call it ``the only Japanese
restaurant you'll find with home cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it's the only one I've found in the
Georgia-Tennessee-North Carolina mountains. Hoping to appeal to
visitors drawn to the area by the kayak and whitewater events at
the nearby Olympic venue on the Ocoee River, the Hoods opened
Michiko's before the 1996 Games. ``We figured people would come
here for a short visit, and later on, they'd come back to eat with
us,'' says Herb Hood.
</P>
<P>
   The Games are over, and the visitors keep coming, kayaks and
canoes lashed atop the sport utility vehicles that line downtown
streets on weekends. Weekdays, however, area regulars hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   Michiko's very existence in this tiny community on the
Georgia-Tennessee border says much about the general blending of
culinary cultures in inland America _ and in particular, about the
increasing popularity of Japanese cuisine, echoing the longtime
establishment of Chinese restaurants in myriad small towns across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Herb, a native of McCaysville, and Michiko, who was born in
Tokyo, married almost 45 years ago in her hometown. After he spent
22 years in the Air Force and 22 years with the Postal Service, the
Hoods, parents of five, moved here in 1991_ opening the restaurant
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, it is like many such establishments, serving
teriyaki chicken, shrimp tempura, nori maki (seaweed and rice
rolled around crab meat and carrot) and many other dishes,
including two of my favorites, red miso soup (heartier and thicker
than white miso soup) and scrambled tofu with fresh vegetables over
rice.
</P>
<P>
   On another level, Michiko's is a gathering place for townsfolk _
individuals and groups. ``The Kiwanis Club met here just last
night,'' Herb said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   One night during green tea after dinner, he pulled out a huge
stack of photographs, many of them very old, showing buildings and
people in downtown McCaysville-Copperhill, as well as scenes from
the once flourishing copper industry. The fading photographs
amounted to a historical tour of the Copper Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thomas, a retired newspaperman and still active
raconteur, and I have enjoyed our ink-stained chats at the
restaurant. And at lunchtime, I've seen the big round table near
the door filled with dining women who swap stories and share the
fun fostered by the gentleman I call ``the scarf man.'' He's
officially Clark Barker, a retired Air Force officer, who on any
given day is likely to stroll into Michiko's carrying a colorful
array of scarves, giving them away with a flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know who's going to show up,'' says Herb.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's for sure: You don't show up more than once without
everybody knowing your name.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
