</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A marmalade cake that is easier to make
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As promised last week, here is an orange marmalade cake that is
considerably easier to make than the one we published last week.
That one, created by Atlanta chef Scott Peacock for Victoria
magazine, was based on a prize-winning cake in Jan Karon's Mitford
novels.
</P>
<P>
   After Margarett Kinton of Roswell requested such a recipe,
dozens of readers sent in Peacock's version. Still others sent
recipes for orange marmalade cakes they found in their own files.
Our tester liked this one from Anna Hall of Marietta, topping lemon
cake mix with a mixture of marmalade, coconut and butter.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Citrus Crown Cak--
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50-55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   112-ounce jar orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup flake coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2stick butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1box Duncan Hines Moist Deluxe Lemon Supreme Cake mix
</P>
<P>
   (prepared as directed using 3 eggs, 1 1/3 cups water and 1/3 cup
oil)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Spray a 10-inch bundt pan with
nonstick spray, or grease and flour well. In a small bowl, combine
marmalade, coconut and melted butter. Pour into prepared pan.
Prepare cake mix according to directions on box. Pour batter over
marmalade mixture. Bake for 50 to 55 minutes. Remove from oven and
cool in pan 10 minutes. Invert cake onto serving plate. If some
marmalade sticks to the pan, scrape it out with a rubber spatula
and put back on the cake. Cool completely before slicing. Use a
serrated knife and wipe it clean with a damp cloth between slices.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 373 calories, 4 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 53 grams carbohydrates, 64
milligrams cholesterol, 343 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   -- Barbara Benson of Jefferson is trying to find a recipe for
tomato gravy like one her husband says he enjoyed while serving in
the Navy in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe Swap, Food
Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
