<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson's 8th CD good fix for fans
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years, Alan Jackson has become country music's name
brand label. Like a pair of quality workboots that show up each
year in an outdoor catalog, his handcrafted songs are always a
perfect, functional fit for the hard-core country fan. This new CD
(Jackson's eighth), is another dose of pristine, pickup truck music
that deviates little from his satisfying, established pedal
steel-and-fiddle formula. He dabbles in cowboy swing (``Right on
the Money''), odes to the pre-Wal-Mart, good ol' days (``Little
Man''), and badly broken hearts (``What a Day Yesterday Was''). In
the tune ``I'll Go on Loving You,'' the normally reserved Jackson
gets downright sexy as he recites a kind of muscle shirt rap about
``slippin' off your dress'' and ``the pleasures of the flesh.''
Whew. The weepie ``Gone Crazy,'' about the end of a relationship,
is so effectively melancholy it's enough to make you spill tears
without blinking. Jackson may not be bold in his experimentation,
but so what?
</P>
<P>
   ``High Mileage''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Arista. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
