<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unusual touches give Willie creative edge
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a very few of the most ornery entertainers who have
survived decades, generations, of career upheavals and passing
fashions, Willie Nelson has learned how to hone everything down to
the essence. He's so purely gestural in his approach to
performance, so ruthlessly pared-away, that his glance is as good
as a gander. So it makes a certain kind of sense to hear Nelson in
the hands of New Orleans studio wizard Daniel Lanois, the former
Brian Eno protege, who has built a magnetic reputation as the
high-end Don Was: lending some aesthetic pizazz to longtime artists
whose icon status has slipped a few notches.
</P>
<P>
   Those unfamiliar should know that Lanois is Mr. Atmospheric,
beloved of ambient washes of sound that have an almost mystically
hypnotic effect. It's tweaky, but effective, doing the trick for
Bob Dylan (``Time Out of Mind''), Emmylou Harris (``Wrecking
Ball''), and even the studio-unfriendly Neville Brothers (``Yellow
Moon''). It works for Willie, too, who has made one of the best
albums of his life, often singing in tandem with Harris, and
sensitively set up with a set list that emphasizes, as one title
puts it, ``My Own Peculiar Way.''
</P>
<P>
   His plain speech and scruffy elegance are powerfully contrasted
by African-influenced drumming and floaty guitar licks that could
make you wonder if you walked in on a Paul Simon album by mistake.
But the genius here is clearly the singer and the song, as a
30-year-old gem called ``I've Just Destroyed the World'' will
testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teatro''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Nelson. Island. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Old dog, new producer, great music.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
