A5814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS03-COX     09-02 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS03-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Audio Reviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
</P>
<P>
   By Sonia Murray, Doug Hamilton, Shane Harrison, and Richard L.
Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   -- R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul of a Woman''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Price. Island Black Music.
</P>
<P>
   13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is an album of pretty decent songs sung
extraordinarily well. Sure, the first release from this debut has
remained atop the R&AMP;B charts for the past five weeks, but ``Friend
of Mine'' would be just another somebody's-done-some-woman-wrong
song if it wasn't Kelly Price telling the story. Price isn't simply
a narrator. For her, microphones become lecterns from behind which
her soaring range and emotive ability compel you to ache along with
the betrayed in ``Friend,'' appreciate the women in your life in
``Soul of a Woman'' and testify as she does in the song most
complementary to her talents, the truly soul-powered ``Lord of
All.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``International Velvet''
</P>
<P>
   Catatonia. Vapor/Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   This sophomore effort by Welsh quintet Catatonia recently hit
No. 1 on the British charts, suggesting that there are slim
pickings across the pond these days. Whereas fellow Welsh acts
Super Furry Animals and Gorky's Zygotic Mynci attempt to expand the
boundaries of pop, Catatonia hews to the standard alterna-rock
formula. Singer Cerys Matthews, whose voice is pitched somewhere
between those of Bjork and the Divinyls' Christina Amphlett,
displays a modicum of charisma. And the leadoff track, ``Mulder and
Scully,'' cleverly evokes TV's favorite alien investigators in a
lyric about the mysteries of desire. But, mostly, ``International
Velvet'' offers the sound of a band beating a dead horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Dog and Pony Show''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mould. Rykodisc. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Former Husker Du and Sugar frontman Bob Mould has announced that
this fall's tour will be his last with a full electric band; hence
the title of his fourth solo recording. Though not surprising, it's
still a shame, because he sounds hungry for the first time in
years. The guitars clatter and ring with renewed vigor behind the
best batch of songs Mould has offered since Sugar's 1992 debut,
``Copper Blue.'' Despite his instrumental exuberance, he's never
the most upbeat of lyricists, so this set is frequently concerned
with things lost or taken away, as titles such as ``Moving Trucks''
and ``Taking Everything'' attest. In ``First Drag of the Day,''
Mould intones that ``it's starting to sound like it's time to sign
off.'' I beg to differ.
</P>
<P>
   -- BLUES-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Anutha Zone''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John. Virgin/Pointblank. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Having dabbled in jazz and pop standards of late, New Orleans
R&AMP;B great Dr. John attempts to resurrect the spooky, funky vibe of
his late-1960s work on his 36th (!) album. An unlikely corps of
supporting players help him set the mood _ ``Anutha Zone'' boasts
cameos by members of such cutting-edge British acts as Supergrass
and Spiritualized. But the ultra-slick production by hot British
knob-twiddler John Leckie (The Verve, Radiohead) undercuts the
hoodoo groove of such numbers as ``Ki Ya Gris Gris'' and ``John
Gris,'' and the guest artists sound curiously anonymous.
Thankfully, Dr. John's born-on-the-bayou rasp and effortlessly
soulful piano playing add spice to this somewhat bland gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   -- DISCO
</P>
<P>
   ``54 _ Music From the Miramax Motion Picture Vols. 1 &AMP; 2''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Tommy Boy.
</P>
<P>
   32 tracks (2 CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Here's a vertible trove of 1970s sonic nonsense. Almost
everything is here: Diana Ross' ``The Boss,'' Sylvester's ``You
Make Me Feel (Mighty Real),'' Thelma Houston's ``Don't Leave Me
This Way,'' Odyssey's ``Native New Yorker'' and Silver Convention's
``Fly Robin Fly.'' Although ``54'' isn't the first retro '70s flick
to cobble together two soundtracks worth of vintage disco (1997's
``Boogie Nights'' also did an admirable job), this set is far more
delectably cheesy and comprehensive. Whether you were old enough to
don puka beads and actually get into disco clubs 20 years ago or
just fantasized about it while suffering through the watered-down,
PG version of ``Saturday Night Fever,'' this collection is a
must-have. One further advantage is that most of this material was
originally issued on vinyl and only now is making its CD debut.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
