<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    iMacs: the Apple of the consumers' eye
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple Computer is shipping ``tens of thousands'' of iMacs a week
but still can't meet the demand for the company's glitzy new
consumer model.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, some computer retailers say iMacs are selling out
almost daily but that they they are able to restock them in a day
or so. Still, Apple Computer estimates that it has a backlog of
150,000 orders for the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not been able to keep with the demand,'' Steve Jobs, the
company's interim chief executive told the opening session of the
Seybold publishing conference in San Francisco Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Inability to meet demand is not a new problem for Apple
Computer. In the past, the company has left retailers waiting up to
months for their machines.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the problem is not supply, it's demand,
according to Apple. Jobs said the company is shipping tens of
thousands of iMacs a week.
</P>
<P>
   Some merchants nationwide report receiving up to 60 new iMacs
daily but then sell them out in a day or so.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, iMacs are sold at CompUsa and Micro Center in
Marietta. CompUsa couldn't be reached for comment but a spokesman
for Micro Center said that the store continues to receive iMacs.
</P>
<P>
   The machines sells out quickly, said Micro Center. Demand,
though, has tapered off from the feverish pace of the first two
weeks following Apple Computer's release of the iMac on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Jobs said he was thrilled with the continued
interest in the iMac. ``We have had a phenomenal response to this
product,'' he said in his keynote address to Seybold.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the struggle to meet demand in the US, Apple Computer
has begun selling the iMac in Japan. Already, that market is sold
out through September, said Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Now Apple Computer plans to launch the iMac in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
