A5817 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-LEWINSKY-0903-     09-02 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-LEWINSKY-0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ON LEWINSKY AFFAIR: 'IT'S TIME TO ... GO BACK TO WORK'
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CLINTON-0903.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES and BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Defiant in the face of his critics, President Clinton
said Wednesday he had said enough about his Oval Office affair with
Monica Lewinsky and appeared to rule out any further public
discussion of the matter or a formal apology to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Donning his mantle as leader of the free world, Clinton said he
was too busy trying to tame nuclear arms and avert a global
financial meltdown to devote additional attention to a scandal that
has dogged his presidency for nearly eight months and raised the
prospect of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And, with an eye toward polls suggesting the American public is
weary of the tawdry matter and wary of the methods of independent
counsel Kenneth Starr, Clinton took another swipe at the federal
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Starr's investigation has ''consumed a
disproportionate amount of America's time, money and resources and
attention,'' and, once again, urged the country to set the matter
aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake, said that I
regretted it, asked to be forgiven, spent a lot of valuable time
with my family in the last couple of weeks and said I was going
back to work,'' Clinton said in response to a question at the
closing press conference of a two-day summit with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see from what we're discussing here, there are very
large issues that will affect the future of the American people in
the short run and over the long run,'' Clinton said, standing
beside Yeltsin in an ornate Kremlin ceremonial room. ''There are
large issues that have to be dealt with now in the world, and at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides have suggested in recent days that Clinton
revisit the Lewinsky matter publicly to help counter criticism that
he was more combative than contrite when he addressed the nation on
the issue August 17.
</P>
<P>
   In the nationally televised address, Clinton acknowledged that
he had misled his wife and the American people about a relationship
that was ''not appropriate.'' He did not explicitly apologize for
the affair or for the months of deception, however. Nor did he ask
for national forgiveness, saying instead that the matter was
''nobody's business but ours,'' a reference to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of varying ideological stripes assailed the speech,
saying it fell short of a full apology and was laden with
gratuitous criticism of Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday marked the first time Clinton has taken questions on
the matter since his speech to the nation, and he appeared to have
a ready response. He said the speech he gave was a good one and the
American people liked it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have actually been quite heartened by the reaction of the
American people and leaders throughout the world,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I read it again the other day and I thought it was clear that
I was expressing my profound regret to all who were hurt and to all
who were involved, and my desire not to see any more people hurt by
this process who are caught up in it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And I was commenting that it seemed to be something that most
reasonable people would think had consumed a disproportionate
amount of America's time, money and resources and attention and was
now continuing to involve more and more people,'' Clinton
continued. ''It's time for us to now go back to the work of the
country, give the people their government back.''
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Stephen Hess said there was little Clinton
might do now to correct the deficiencies his critics perceived in
his earlier address.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did it. He didn't do it well, he didn't do it right, but to
try to fine-tune it, I think, would not really go over very well,''
said Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, a
Washington think tank. ''Maybe now that's going to be the party
line -- 'We've said it, that's it and we're just going to move
on.'''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately clear whether Clinton's critics would be
satisfied with Wednesday's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction was muted on Capitol Hill, where lawmakers from both
parties are awaiting Starr's investigation report, likely to be
sent to Congress soon after the House returns from its summer
recess next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With midterm elections in November, Democrats are being cautious
not to be too critical of their party's standard bearer, while
Republicans are wary of overstepping public opinion by sounding off
too sharply against a president who continues to enjoy job approval
ratings topping 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for House Minority leader Richard Gephardt said the
Missouri Democrat would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   In general though, the aide said, Gephardt doesn't feel it's
necessary for Clinton to say anything further about the matter in
public.
</P>
<P>
   ''He thinks the president's apologized, he felt that he's done
enough and that it took a great deal of courage to do what he
did,'' the aide said, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   An aide for Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., said that publicly the
senator's had little to say about the Lewinsky matter and is
awaiting the Starr report before commenting further.
</P>
<P>
   ''On background,'' the aide said, ''I'm not sure he wants to
hear anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, have been scathing in their criticism of
Clinton since his August admission.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Monday that
Clinton had squandered the moral authority necessary to govern.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a moral dimension to the American presidency, and
today that dimension, that power, has been lost in scandal and in
deception,'' Lott said. ''I am very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans, including Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas,
have called for Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report will be critical in a decision by the House over
whether to begin impeachment proceedings against Clinton, censure
him, or do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   When allegations first surfaced in January that Clinton had an
affair with Lewinsky, a former White House intern, he categorically
denied it. For the past seven months, he's dispatched cabinet
members and senior aides to deny it as well, a strategy he
abandoned last month, only after Starr's investigation had
reportedly turned up extensive evidence rebutting Clinton's earlier
denials.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had hoped the Russia summit would give Clinton
an estimable setting in which to put the Lewinsky scandal behind
him and concentrate on foreign policy. But two of the three
questions from American reporters Wednesday were about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   That drew the ire of ninth-term Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., who
jumped an American correspondent after the press conference, wagged
a scolding finger in his face and upbraided him for raising the
Lewinsky matter in the Kremlin press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''Speaking as an American, I'm outraged,'' Hoyer told Reuter's
White House Correspondent Lawrence McQuillan, former president of
the White House Correspondents Association. Hoyer said the scribe
had tried to embarrass the president abroad and he admonished the
American media to ''drop its obsession'' with the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   McQuillan later told reporters traveling with Clinton that his
questions were justified.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bill Clinton gave the most important speech of his presidency
two weeks ago and then went into hiding,'' McQuillan said. ''l
didn't choose the venue,'' for Wednesday's questions, ''he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica-gate was also on the minds of some Russians.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton met with parliamentary and regional leaders in
Moscow, one emerged to give his own bizarre assessment of meeting
the American president for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envy Monica Lewinsky,'' a smiling Dmitri Ayatskov, governor
of the region of Saratov, told reporters as he left the meeting
with Clinton. ``He's a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was accompanied to Moscow by his wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, and some White House correspondents looked for body
language and nuance to assess their relationship in the wake of
Clinton's confession.
</P>
<P>
   Some media reports noted that Hillary Clinton introduced her
husband at a Russian elementary school on Tuesday, but failed to
say just that: ``my husband,'' her customary public reference to
the president.
</P>
<P>
   And on the eve of a Russia-US summit Monday, the Russian
ultra-nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky, known as ``Mad Vlad'' for
his outrageousness, told parliament that Clinton should stay at
home and marry Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as individuals with high moral character, would prefer not
to meet a person who still can't sort out his relationship with his
secretary,'' said Zhirinovsky, himself no stranger to questions
about moral character. He bottles his own vodka with his face on
the label and starred in his own soft-porn film last year.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
