<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DISC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Sphere's' technical spots shine
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weird thing about ``Sphere'' is that it could well go down
in history _ cinema and national _ as the film that made ``Wag the
Dog'' possible. Director Barry Levinson and star Dustin Hoffman
were committed to this big-budget, special-effects picture when
scheduling fallout gave them some free time. So they made ``Wag the
Dog,'' which, along with The Dress, The Tie and The Bombing Raids,
has become part of the whole Bill 'n' Monica lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   But back to ``Sphere,'' which has recently come out on DVD. As
movies with heavyweights like Levinson, Hoffman, Sharon Stone and
Samuel L. Jackson go, it's something of a disappointment
(translation: not worth renting on video). But the DVD format
brings out the picture's technical excellence, beginning with the
opening shot of Hoffman's helicopter sweeping over the Pacific to a
secret destination. What awaits him and his fellow experts? A giant
alien sphere that crash-landed in the ocean ... 300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bonuses here are twofold: a mini-history of sci-fi in the
movies (it takes up screen after screen of print, but it's
well-researched for a surface treatment) and voice-over comments by
stars Hoffman and Jackson. Hoffman reveals that some of the scenes
were improvised, while Jackson explains his shaved-head look: It
wasn't an homage to Michael Jordan but a carry-over from a film
he'd just shot, ``The Red Violin.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
