u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND03-COX     09-02 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This Weekend on TV
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Vis-a-Vis'' (PBS-check local listings)_ Hooked up by a
digital video link, a police sergeant in the South African township
of Soweto talks about his job with a cop in Philadelphia during
this program that attempts to bridge the gap between divergent
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mystery: Hetty Wainthropp'' (PBS-check local listings)_ The
sleuthing senior citizen is hot on the trail of a teen who
disappears around the same time as a rash of suspicious fires
breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Endless Harmony: The Beach Boys Story'' 3 p.m. EDT, VH1 _
Another airing of the watchable documentary about tanned but
troubled family members who went on to become one of the most
popular rock bands in American history, and whose music turned the
United States of America into Surfin' USA.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Playing With Fire: The Tenth Annual Van Cliburn
International Piano Competition'' (PBS-check local listings) _ Some
of the world's best young pianists tickle the ivories in this Grand
Prix of grand pianos.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   -- ``An American Werewolf in London'' (1981) 8 p.m. EDT, Comedy
Central_ Great, ghoulish special effects and sly comic sensibility
about the horror movie genre (later developed in movies like
``Scream'') flesh out this story about a young man (David Naughton)
touring Europe who begins having really bad hair days after being
attacked by a wild beast.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``When Harry Met Sally'' (1989) 8p.m. EDT, Lifetime_ A Woody
Allen-ish romantic comedy without the neurotic self-loathing asks
the question: Can a man and a woman just be friends? Billy Crystal
in one of his best outings and Meg Ryan at her perky best prove why
it's not as easy as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Rain Man'' (1988) 9 p.m. EDT, TBS _ Quadruple Oscar winner
has Tom Cruise as a slick, selfish car dealer who discovers he has
an older brother (Dustin Huffman) who is an idiot savant with a
gift for numbers and an obsession for Judge Wapner on ``The
People's Court.'' A manipulative piece of moviemaking by Barry
Levinson (who also has a cameo) if ever there was one, but the
great performances all around more than make up for the shameless
string-pulling.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Frontline: From Jesus to Christ'' (PBS-check local
listings) _ Scholars revisit the story of Jesus, trying to separate
gospel fact from fiction. First of two parts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
