<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL03-COX     09-02 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Some celluloid salutes to working men and women
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The origins of Labor Day _ that oxymoronic holiday _ have almost
been lost. For most of us, it's become a last long weekend before
the grind of work, school, etc., sets in. But lest we forget, Labor
Day, which was declared a national holiday by Congress in 1894, was
instigated by a Philadelphia-based secret organization of working
men called the Knights of Labor. So God bless the working man (and
woman), and here are some ideas of how to honor them at the video
store.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Blue Collar'' (1978): Having written ``Taxi Driver'' for
Martin Scorsese and ``Obsession'' for Brian De Palma, Paul Schrader
made his directorial debut with this astute story of three friends
(Yaphet Kotto, Harvey Keitel and Richard Pryor) who work on the
assembly line at an auto factory in Detroit. Figuring that their
union does them no more favors than it does their bosses, they
decide to rob the union office. The filming was pretty much a
battle on all sides. Kotto and Keitel were having problems with
Schrader, and all three were having problems with a deep-into-drugs
Pryor. Plus, even before production began, the Detroit city fathers
decided that the movie might not be a paean to their No. 1
industry. So, 10 days before shooting, Schrader still didn't have
an automobile assembly line lined up. At the last minute, the owner
of a Checker Cab plant in Kalamazoo offered his place.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Molly Maguires'' (1970): Sean Connery and Richard
Harris both got their Irish up for Martin Ritt's film about rugged
Irish immigrant coal miners in Pennsylvania in the 1870s. Tired of
being exploited by the mine owners, they form a secret union called
the Molly Maguires. Connery plays the group's leader, while Harris
is a company detective sent to infiltrate it. While it's somewhat
preachy _ director Ritt wanted to stress parallels with the 1960s
civil rights movement _ the movie benefits from its two charismatic
leads and a compelling, fact-based story. The studio, incidentally,
wanted Ritt to shoot in color, while he leaned toward a grittier
black and white. He solved the problem by agreeing to color, then
saturating everything on location (Eckley, Pa.) in coal dust.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Norma Rae'' (1979): Martin Ritt went back to the factory
with this movie about management-labor struggles in a Southern
textile mill. Also reality-based, it stars Sally Field as a
blue-collar wife, mother and millworker transformed into a union
maid by labor organizer Ron Liebman. Though it lost to ``Kramer vs.
Kramer'' in the race for best picture, the film won Field the first
of her two Oscars as best actress. Accepting the award from
presenter Richard Dreyfuss, she graciously told the audience,
``Marty Ritt is Norma Rae; he's fought all his life to put on films
that have something to say.'' Shot just across the state line in
Alabama, ``Norma Rae'' used a lot of Atlanta talent in featured
roles. Among the more noticeable faces on the factory floor are
Stuart Culpepper and a then Atlanta-based Grace Zabriskie
(best-known these days as the woman who almost became George's
mother-in-law on ``Seinfeld'').
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Devil and Miss Jones'' (1941): Not to be confused with
``The Devil in Miss Jones,'' a well-known porno film of the
mid-1970s. In this Capra-esque social comedy (actually directed by
Sam Wood), longtime character actor Charles Coburn plays a gruff,
standoffish millionaire who poses as a shoe clerk in his own
department store to ferret out potential malcontents among the
workers. Robert Cummings is the union man most likely to lose his
job, and Jean Arthur is Coburn's unsuspecting co-worker, who takes
him under her wing and humanizes him. The movie was co-produced by
Arthur's husband, who was trying to find his wife better roles. It
worked; she got her best reviews since ``Mr. Smith Goes to
Washington.'' But the movie belongs to Coburn, who also nabbed a
best supporting actor nomination.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Roger and Me'' (1989): The ``Roger'' in the title is Roger
Smith, then chairman of General Motors. The ``me'' is Michael
Moore, who made his film debut with this hilarious, heart-wrenching
documentary and went on to a successful career as a professional
thorn in the side of corporate America. His movie shows what
happened in his hometown of Flint, Mich., after GM closed its plant
there. Quite simply, the town died _ a slow, agonizing death made
worse by GM's indifference and the buffoonish efforts of the city
fathers (at one point, they try making it a tourist mecca). The
spine of the film concerns Moore's one-man crusade to bring Smith
to Flint to see the human cost of the closing. Essentially, it's
moviemaking as grudge match, as unabashedly one-sided as a protest
march. Moore was up to his old tricks more recently with ``The Big
One,'' a look at corporate downsizing across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
