<HEADER>
A5824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-TITANIC-COX     09-02 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-TITANIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Passage of time sinks the big ship
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Icome not to praise ``Titanic,'' but to sink it.
</P>
<P>
   I gave the blockbuster teen tear-jerker an A- when I reviewed it
last winter. But the ``minus'' part of that grade, like a stealth
iceberg, has grown bigger in the intervening months till it's
punched a hole in the side of my first reaction.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the loathsome behavior of writer-director James
Cameron, with his crowing rooster routine and fake piety at the
Oscars. No, you can't judge a movie by the spoiled behavior of
directors, or their bad habits. If we did, who could love
Hitchcock?
</P>
<P>
   Cameron's technologically groundbreaking film made us believe
the unsinkable liner was sinking again, right before our eyes. His
visionary approach in past movies has sparked new technology,
particularly in CGI (computer-generated imagery). Remember the
watery probe in ``The Abyss,'' or the liquid-metal dude in
``Terminator 2?'' Thank Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   So how come my estimation of ``Titanic'' has sunk so low? Well,
it's a mix of his cardboard script and the avalanche of awards the
movie won.
</P>
<P>
   When it first came out, the air-brained Harlequin romance
between lower-class Jack (Leonardo DiCaprio) and upper-class Rose
(Kate Winslet) was a guilty pleasure. And the wrap-around story
with Gloria Stuart as the ancient Rose was good nose-blowing hokum
for the Kleenex-susceptible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' is still grand entertainment. But it isn't original.
It's a paste-up job, a pastiche that exploits our nostalgia for a
more innocent kind of movie (and period of history). It's like
``Star Wars'' and ``Raiders of the Lost Ark,'' both astonishing
bits of affectionate wizardry. But like these films, ``Titanic''
is, for all its heart-will-go-on melodrama, a heartless, shrewd
piece of machinery. And it functioned exactly as Cameron wanted it
to, at the box office, at the Price-Waterhouse ballot box and now
at your local video store.
</P>
<P>
   Did the movie deserve its technical Oscars? Absolutely. But an
Oscar for best picture of the year? No. Unless the year is 1937,
not '97.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
