<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAIN-SIDE-COX     09-02 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Automobile accidents account for 50% of brain injuries
 &HT;    By Ellen Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_As seat belts, air bags and medical technology have
improved chances of surviving a head injury in recent years, health
care specialists have stepped up efforts to treatand research brain
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 375,000 Americans are hospitalized each year because of a
traumatic brain injury. Of them, more than 90,000 sustain lifelong
disabling conditions. The annual cost of traumatic brain injuries
in the United States is $48.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia alone, more than 60,000 people incur a brain injury
each year; about 1,700 of them die and 2,000 face permanent
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   But because brain injuries are individual, it is often difficult
to predict what those disabling conditions may be. Depending on
which portion of the brain is damaged, communication or
coordination skills may be affected in varying degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more severe the injury, the longer the recovery period and
the greater the deficits the injury creates,'' said Dr. Alan
Harben, a physiatrist at Emory University (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Automobile accidents account for 50 percent of brain injury
incidents while others are the result of sports accidents, falls or
gun violence. Most incidents cause one of two types of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In one, the brain directly hits the skull. Most often, the
impact leads to injuries in the frontal and temporal lobes, the
parts of the brain that plan day-to-day activities and regulate
memory. In addition, car accidents can also force the head to slow
down too quickly, jolting the brain within the skull and damaging
nerve cells and blood vessels by shearing or stretching them.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mechanical trauma happens in about 50 milliseconds, but
over the next few hours and days, there are biochemical events
occurring that lead to toxic injury to the brain,'' Harben said.
</P>
<P>
   In the secondary phase, the injury can worsen, as toxic
chemicals can cause the brain to swell. Damage to other organs in
the body can cause drops in blood pressure or in oxygen
concentration in the bloodstream, both affecting the brain, Harben
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, doctors diagnose patients with mild, moderate or
severe brain injuries. Effects of mild brain injuries - dizziness,
confusion, fatigue - usually disappear within a few hours or days.
</P>
<P>
   Those with moderate brain injuries suffer a loss of
consciousness for less than six hours. They have some degree of
impairment in thinking, attention, problem solving and
concentration, but will eventually resolve most problems within
three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   Severe brain injuries cause a loss of consciousness for more
than six hours. Patients may have amnesia for more than a day,
suffer cognitive deficits and experience paralysis, a loss of
balance, visual and hearing difficulties and sometimes behavior
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Support groups and the Brain Injury Association of Georgia help
patients and families struggling to cope.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's brain injury support groups are behind Amendment 3, a
state constitutional amendment on November's ballot establishing a
Brain and Spinal Cord Injury Trust Fund, with money from a 10
percent increase in fines for drunken drivers.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the Brain Injury Association of
Georgia at 1-888-334-2424 or the national family help line at
1-800-444-6443.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
