<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAIN-life-COX     09-02 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-life-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'A second life': Couple still together despite severe brain
injuries
 &HT;    By Ellen Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_On one of their first outings, Mandy Fugate and Morris
Steinheimer took a walk outside her mother's home. It was an
inauspicious beginning. En route home, she accidentally tripped
Steinheimer, giving him a bloody nose when he fell to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Now, seven months later, they move in sync. In the living room
of their apartment, Fugate rises from her chair, her right arm
reaching out to steady herself. Steinheimer immediately grabs her
cane and places it within her reach.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, when the couple recite their wedding vows, their
promise to stay together and love each other ``in sickness and in
health'' will have greater meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a disability where they can't live alone,'' says
Fugate's mother, Sandy. ``But together they're one whole person.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Fugate, 22, and Steinheimer, 36, are recovering from severe
traumatic brain injuries. Their plan to live independently
confounds their doctors early predictions and delights their
families. But their challenges likely will last the rest of their
lives.quote from someone at the brain injury association here about
the difficulties of recovery from this type of injury?)
</P>
<P>
   Brain injuries can affect the entire body, slurring speech,
blocking communication skills, or hindering movement and
coordination. At the most extreme, brain injuries can leave people
in a vegetative state, unaware of the environment around them and
in need constant care, usually at a nursing home. On the other end
of the spectrum, a mild brain injury causes temporary confusion and
short-term memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fugate and Steinheimer suffered severe brain injuries after
vehicle accidents, the most common cause.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before her 11th birthday, Fugate fell off an
all-terrain vehicle, slamming her head against the ground after
being thrown some 10 feet in the air. She was in a a coma for six
weeks, and doctors told her mother that she would never wake up,
and if she did, she would probably be in a vegetative state and
would require around-the-clock care.
</P>
<P>
   Steinheimer's car accident, which left him partially paralyzed,
was 15 years ago. He keeps a reminder in the pocket of his pants:
Pins that were drilled into his toes to help them heal, then
removed when they began to cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take them out, in case someone asks me why I walk so
funny,'' he says. ``Everything has been changed since the time of
the accident. It's like living a second life.''
</P>
<P>
   Fingering the pins with his hands, Steinheimer says they also
are a symbol of bad choices. He had been drinking and driving.
</P>
<P>
   Though Steinheimer walks hunched, he no longer walks with a cane
and has few other outward signs of disability. Fugate's family
hopes her progress will follow his.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, he lived with his parents on a ranch in Good
Hope, Ga., where the former mechanic helped with the farm. Now he
is looking for volunteer opportunities or a job to make use of his
Mr. Fix-it abilities, and to keep him busy while Fugate undergoes
daily rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Fugate's brain injury was at least as severe. After waking up
from her coma, she didn't speak for three months. She was paralyzed
from the neck down _ not from spinal injury but because her brain
couldn't tell her body what to do. She had to relearn the most
basic functions _ controlling her bowel movements, brushing her
teeth and swallowing, for example. It took 17 months of therapy to
walk again.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, therapists had to retrain undamaged brain cells to
pick up where the damaged brain cells left off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thousand times harder to teach them over again than to
teach a baby,'' says her mother, Sandy Fugate. ``I brought home
this child that wasn't the same as the one I took in.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 years after the accident, Fugate this year moved
out of her mother's house and into an apartment. An assistant stays
with her 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Steinheimer joined her, so the couple could
prepare to become independent and test what it would be like to
live together. They soon will have the assistant's help four days a
week, instead of seven.
</P>
<P>
   Like other young couples making a life together, it's give and
take. Early mornings, they exercise together, walking along the
patio, riding an exercise bike and doing sit ups. Though it's part
of Fugate's rehabilitation program, it's more important to exercise
now than ever, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wedding dress barely fits,'' Fugate jokes, carefully
enunciating each syllable.
</P>
<P>
   Steinheimer helps Fugate apply make-up, brushing her eye lashes
with mascara and painting her lips a glossy pink. Sometimes, he
helps her with nail polish. ``I don't mind helping her because of
the shakiness of her hand,'' he says. ``It's hard to paint the
nails on your right hand if you're right-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fugate's right hand is dominant, not only because she is
right-handed, but also because the left side of her body is
generally weaker.
</P>
<P>
   Often, she wears a single white glove on her left hand because
her hand gets cold from lack of circulation. When it does,
Steinheimer helps her, finger by finger, slip the glove onto her
hand.
</P>
<P>
   It seems only appropriate that Steinheimer does the deed _ he
now has use of both his hands. His left hand was the dominant one
after his accident, and for some time, he walked with his right arm
perpetually held against his chest.
</P>
<P>
   After they prepare breakfast together, Fugate's full day of
therapy gets started, often at her computer.
</P>
<P>
   Side by side, two clocks rest on the wall above the computer
station. Both tell the time, but one has colored slips of paper at
each hour, noting breakfast at 7 a.m., dinner at 6 p.m. and other
activities like physical therapy and tutoring throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   The labels are reminders, like those in the kitchen where
cabinets have tags for ``large bowls,'' ``small bowls'' and ``good
China,'' and the refrigerator door has a list of foods that are
stored inside and the week's menu of foods to be eaten. Even light
switches have notes, to turn the light off after leaving the room.
</P>
<P>
   The tags affirm the ongoing problems that brain injury patients
face, life-long scars that can appear in cognitive problems like
memory or fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Leila Hartly, a speech and cognitive therapist,
visits Fugate at 10 a.m. First they practice repeated sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pa-pa-pa-pa-pa,'' Fugate says, enunciating as fast as she can.
She uses a computer program developed for vision and speech therapy
that times the speed of her speech. As she speaks into the
microphone, a frog on the computer screen jumps from lily pad to
lily pad, to the rhythm of her words. At the end, it gives her a
score by averaging the speed of her speech. Though it continues to
improve, her speech remains much slower than average.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the computer, a board lists the different speech
exercises Fugate must practice on her own: Work on saying two pages
of long words, getting the accent on the right syllable and getting
good speed; practice sheets of words, phrases and sentences; look
in the mirror; keep jaw closed.
</P>
<P>
   Fugate's rehabilitation program is designed to help her regain
her fullest potential, but it is an expensive one that has taken an
inordinate amount of time and money to develop. Besides Hartly, two
academic teachers, a physical therapist and a neuropsychologist
visit Fugate on a set schedule that she, her mother and health care
specialists developed a few years ago. Each therapist can charge up
to $150 an hour and monthly expenses usually totals $10,000,
including rent and salaries.
</P>
<P>
   All of it is out of the family's pocket. Fugate doesn't qualify
for Medicaid, and private insurance won't cover her pre-existing
illness. Instead, some money flows in from a lawsuit that the
family won after the accident; her mother also mortgaged her home
to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I get the money back. It's worth it just to
see the independence she's gained,'' Sandy Fugate says.
</P>
<P>
   The fairy tale wedding is worth it, too, her mother says. Fugate
will wear a traditional white gown and $800 corrective wedding
shoes, designed so that she can walk down the aisle without her
cane. A horse and buggy will transport the couple to the wedding
site at a country club in Stone Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The couple will join hands outdoors before a hundred guests.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether they have any fears about the relationship,
Fugate's reply is succint: ``No.'' Then she adds, ``I'm very
thrilled about everything. I'm looking forward to getting
married.''
</P>
<P>
   working on this ending Steinheimer is looking forward to a life
he never thought he'd have. ``It's such a good feeling to be with
someone who's been through something I've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
