A5830 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILL-COX     09-02 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Birth control pill used after sex to be marketed in U.S.
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``morning-after pill,'' a type of emergency birth control
that can be used within 72 hours after sex, soon will be widely
marketed to American consumers for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration approved the
PREVEN Emergency Contraceptive Kit, which contains oral
birth-control pills and a urine pregnancy test.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Gynetics Inc. of Belle Mead, N.J., the $20 kit will
be available only by doctor's prescription. It should arrive in
pharmacies in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The ``morning-after pill'' is actually several birth-control
pills that must be taken in two doses, starting within 72 hours of
unprotected sex. The pills do not cause an embryo to abort, as does
the controversial abortion pill RU-486, which has been used up to
two months after conception.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency contraceptive pills prevent pregnancy by blocking
the release of an egg, by blocking an encounter between an egg and
sperm or by blocking an already fertilized egg from implanting in
the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Though many women are unaware of this emergency contraceptive
method, it has been in use since 1974 and acknowledged by the FDA
since February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Preven kit contains four oral contraceptive pills. Two pills
must be taken within 72 hours of sex, followed 12 hours later by
the other two pills.
</P>
<P>
   The dosage is considered safe and about 75 percent effective.
Another emergency contraceptive method, which involves inserting a
copper intrauterine device) within seven days after sex, is 99
percent effective, but is more costly and must be performed by a
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Kaiser Family Foundation found that of
1,000 women age 18 to 45, one in four knew pregnancy could be
prevented after unprotected sex Told such an option is available,
almost half the women said they would consider using it.
</P>
<P>
   While doctors generally don't consider emergency contraception
an abortion, the introduction of a kit designed to prevent
pregnancy after sex is controversial among some religious groups
and anti-abortion organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
