<HEADER>
A5832 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REM-ALBUM-COX     09-02 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REM-ALBUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three Remainingh R.E.M. members ready to move on
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ After a tumultuous year in which they found themselves
at professional and personal crossroads, the three remaining
members of rock band R.E.M. have begun the carefully choreographed
media dance of unveiling their new album.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear why they named the new work ``Up'': singer Michael
Stipe, guitarist Peter Buck and keyboardist Mike Mills seem
genuinely happy and enthusiastic about the new collection of songs,
their first without long-time drummer and founding member Bill
Berry, who retired last October.
</P>
<P>
   What everyone soon will be hearing is quite different from past
R.E.M. albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of relish that,'' said Buck, of the new somewhat
ethereal sound. ``Bill's leaving allowed us to redefine what we do
and how we do it. We really had to reinvent ourselves. Except for
Michael's vocals, it really doesn't sound like R.E.M. And I like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers' executives and the band are toiling to get the
project ready for the scheduled Oct. 27 release. As the musicians
relaxed in their individual hotel suites Tuesday, sipping tea and
talking on cellphones, label executives zealously protected the
lone available ``Up'' CD, while unrolling the newly delivered
mock-up of the album's cover art across a queen-size bed. The
artwork consisted of a collage of photos of the band in dark, muted
tones with calligraphy of the lyrics scrawled across the sleeve.
The musicians worked late Tuesday night, heading back into the
studio for final mixes and to determine the lineup of songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This album forced the three of us to become essentially a new
band,'' said Stipe, 38, sitting in his suite, dressed in an eletric
blue shirt and black jeans. ``All the things we used to be doing,
and the way we worked in the studio, were thrown out the window. We
didn't want to bring in a drumnmer to be the new Bill Berry. That
wasn't going to work...This is about the saddest and most romantic
record I've every made. It's like, here's an alternative universe.
Please come in. Expect anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people know we're not a juke box,'' Mills said. ``We're a
band that's always going to take left turns. I think people like a
challenge. I think they get tired of the same thing.'' Alluding to
Berry's retirement, Mills, 41, added, ``Any record is a reflection
of what is going on in your life at the time. We've been through a
lot in the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Although R.E.M recently scrapped plans for a tour to support the
new album later this year, Stipe, Mills and Buck are spending the
rest of the week in a Queens production studio to shoot a video for
the first single, ``Day Sleeper.'' Buck, 41, explained that in lieu
of touring, the band will concentrate on television appearances on
MTV, VH-1 and ``Late Show with David Letterman.'' R.E.M. also plans
to play the benefit ``Bridge Concert'' with Neil Young in San
Francisco on Oct. 17. ``At this time in our lives, and at our ages,
it doesn't make sense to go out and play songs because that's what
we're supposed to do,'' Buck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evident in the music and everything that goes into it
that we enjoy what we're doing,'' Stipe said. ``We're not doing it
for the wrong reasons. We've never been a three-piece before, but I
have to say it feels really great. I'm on top of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
