<SLUG> BC-MA-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOBSTER DENIES TAPING FBI DEALINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In FBI documents made public during months of hearings
in federal court, Stephen Flemmi and his criminal sidekick James
``Whitey'' Bulger are portrayed as electronically-savvy gangsters
obsessed with security -- sweeping their cars for bugs, installing
elaborate alarm systems in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the question: Did they secretly tape record the FBI
handlers who they claim offered them nearly-blanket protection from
prosecution in exchange for information they gave the bureau on the
Mafia?
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, questioned for a final time Wednesday in federal court,
said no, he'd never taped a conversation with the FBI. As for
Bulger, who has been on the run for more than three years, Flemmi
wasn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Mr. Bulger it's very possible,'' Flemmi said in a
response to a question by US District Judge Mark L. Wolf. ``I can
say he's very capable of it. For him, everything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi said he and Bulger had discussed taping their talks with
the FBI, to provide them ``protection.'' He'd seen Bulger's tiny
tape recorder but said he was never part of any secret taping
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't received any tapes in the mail (from Bulger), have
you?'' Assistant US Attorney Fred M. Wyshak Jr. asked Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I haven't,' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi was called back to the witness stand Wednesday to answer
some questions that Wolf had determined he had no legal right to
refuse to answer. In testimony last week, Flemmi had invoked his
Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination more than 200
times.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf must decide whether Flemmi had a valid agreement with the
FBI that promised him immunity for prosecution in exchange for
information he provided the bureau as an informant.
</P>
<P>
   When Flemmi Wednesday again refused to answer certain questions
-- such as whether his longtime FBI handler John Connolly had ever
quizzed him about his alleged involvement in drugs, including
extorting drug dealers -- the government once again asked Wolf to
strike all of Flemmi's testimony, which is the most severe penalty
for improperly taking the Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi's attorney, Kenneth J. Fishman, argued that such action
would be extreme, since Flemmi had refused to answer ``a very
limited number'' of questions. Wolf refused to strike all of
Flemmi's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf also set conditions for the testimony of a New Jersey FBI
supervisor, casting doubt on whether the government will not call
him as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   James B. Darcy Jr., who has investigated organized crime for the
Atlantic City FBI office, is expected to testify that field agents
did not routinely report the alleged criminal activity of
informants to headquarters in Washington, as required by informant
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Flemmi and his co-defendants, including New England
Mafia boss Francis P. Salemme, argue that the failure to notify
headquarters is evidence of an immunity agreement.
</P>
<P>
   If Darcy testifies, Wolf said defense lawyers must be provided
with the informant documents he used to compare Bulger and Flemmi's
treatment with that of informants in New Jersey, a condition which
Assistant US Attorney James D. Herbert said would probably make it
``impractical'' to call Darcy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER03-COX     09-02 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBS showing British series until American version makes new
episodes
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PBS' ``Antiques Roadshow'' is a fine, enjoyable, sometimes even
wonderful series. But it's in repeats now _ and, boy, do we mean
repeats. How many more times can you watch that guy's jaw drop when
he finds out the rusty old sword he once cut watermelon with is
actually a Civil War relic worth $35,000?
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, PBS is juicing its ``Roadshow'' mix with the original
British version of ``Antiques Roadshow'' (check local listings).
</P>
<P>
   It's the start of 33 ``Roadshow'' episodes you've never seen
before. And several of its right-you-are British finds are nearly
as jaw-dropping fun as the antiques discoveries in the American
series.
</P>
<P>
   One woman with a pocketful of jade fingering pieces she bought
in Hong Kong learns one object is likely worth $2,400. The entire
collection might be worth $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   It's practically the same type of show you've been watching the
past couple of years as the American ``Roadshow'' has toured U.S.
cities.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a couple of differences. British participants
don't seem to act with as much astonishment as Americans when they
learn their collections are worth more than they might have
thought.
</P>
<P>
   What does that jade woman, for instance, utter when told her
pieces are worth thousands? ``That's rather shattering,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, is it?
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man who presents his pre-World War I collection of
tiny metal Salvation Army ``fig-uhs'' learns they're likely worth
$1,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you very much,'' the man says almost plainly. ``You've
made my day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, none of the Brit experts are as oddly compelling as those
Keno twins, who appraise furniture with such aplomb on our shores.
And Britain's host, Hugh Scully, apparently has a personality and
spits his lines, which makes him no match for the watchable
blandness exuded by our own Ed Sullivan clone _ the remarkably
stiff-necked Chris Jussel.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this fresh ``Roadshow'' might be too British for
you. If so, take heart.
</P>
<P>
   The American ``Roadshow'' will continue in reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Did he really say that Civil War sword was worth $35,000?
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
