A5844 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-HEALTHCARE-TEX     09-02 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-HEALTHCARE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM ADDRESSES CULTURE GAP IN CARING FOR ASIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Normally, Dr. Andrew Phan avoids making distinctions based on
race.
</P>
<P>
   But in a health-care setting in which Asian-Americans are
increasingly becoming sicker because of language and other cultural
barriers, race can carry great significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Asians in Tarrant County who either aren't
getting treated at all, or they are waiting until they are so sick
they need emergency care,'' said Phan, an assistant professor of
family medicine at the University of North Texas Health Science
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Phan's sentiments underscore plans by the health science center
to launch a community-outreach initiative between its
family-practice residency program and the Asian-American community.
Several Asian-American organizations, including the Hmong American
Planning and Development Center and the Asian-American Chamber of
Commerce, will help institute the program.
</P>
<P>
   A grant from the Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board is
helping to make the program possible.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 20,000 Asian immigrants live in the Metroplex, but
because of language and cultural barriers, many have trouble
accessing health care that others take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   By making its resident clinic more ``ethnosensitive'' and hiring
a bilingual and culturally diverse staff, the center hopes to
increase the number of patients it serves and improve the skills,
knowledge and attitudes of family-practice residents in managing
ethnic and cultural issues.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities make up about 60 percent of the patients at the
resident clinic, known as Seminary Drive Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of statistics, but I do know that within
the community, fear keeps a lot of people from going to the
doctor,'' said Phan, who is Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes, stroke, cardiovascular disease, and breast and other
gynecological cancers are the most common ailments affecting
Asian-Americans, he said. In addition, doctors are also seeing a
lot of parasitic infections in people from Laos and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of the problems are concentrated in the older
population,'' he said. ``Because of superstitions, they tend to
resist Western medicine, especially any kind of surgical
procedures. We still use a lot of traditional, Chinese-type
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Phan said, many Asians opt to use herbal treatments
rather than undergo surgery. Depending on the year of the Chinese
calendar, many Asians consider surgery too risky. ``That's the kind
of cultural thing Western doctors aren't aware of. This program
will address issues like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jon Sivoravong, a family-practice physician and assistant
professor at the health science center, said it is hard to judge
just how sick the community is. Data on Anglos and
African-Americans have been collected for years, but little has
been done on the health status of other ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Of the patients he sees at the center's clinic, Sivoravong said,
about 10 to 15 a day are of Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of people who have been bounced around from one
doctor to the other because of language barriers,'' said
Sivoravong, who is Laotian. ``A lot of them, when they come, are
already very, very sick.''
</P>
<P>
   They also often lack health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Sivoravong recalled a thirtysomething Laotian patient who sought
help after experiencing paralysis in his legs. ``He had a very
severe thyroid problem, but when he came he didn't have any records
of his treatment. He basically walked in and said the doctor hadn't
told him anything. So I had to start from the beginning and get his
records and talk to the doctor who'd cared for him.''
</P>
<P>
   As the population gets older and assimilates, Sivoravong said,
the community will probably become even sicker and suffer from the
kinds of diseases _ congestive heart failure, diabetes _ that
characterize Americans.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, diabetes is nearly nonexistent in China, but the
rate of diabetes in immigrants is near the rate for
African-Americans and Hispanics. ``There haven't been any studies
to look at the specific causes,'' Sivoravong said, ``but my guess
is it has to do with diet, lifestyle and lack of exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Phan and Sivoravong said that details for the new initiative
have yet to be worked out, but that plans call for treating 2,000
additional patients a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking to do something like this for a while,''
said Sivoravong. ``We tried to do this at the community clinic in
Haltom City, but it was very difficult to get the (financial)
support. That's why this is so exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
