<HEADER>
A5848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERBS-COX     09-02 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawsuit has local Bosnians astir
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they fled their war-torn homeland for the safety of a new
life in America, Bosnian Muslims tried to leave behind horrible
memories of torture, rape and being forced to leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
   They concentrated on starting over in a new country they didn't
understand. They struggled to learn English, get a job and put
their children in school. They assumed everyone else they met here
from Bosnia, even those who are Serbian, had suffered the same
indignities, but they didn't often talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   A federal lawsuit filed last week in Atlanta may change all
that. A Serbian refugee who lives in Clarkston was accused of
having tortured Muslims and Croats during the war in the former
Yugoslavia in 1992. The suit was filed by Kemal Mehinovic, a
Bosnian Muslim refugee who lives in Salt Lake City. He claims he
was repeatedly brutalized by Nikola Vuckovic, a former Serb
soldier. Mehinovic filed suit after learning from friends that
Vuckovic was living in metro Atlanta, said one of his lawyers, Paul
Hoffman, chairman of Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Vuckovic declined to comment, but told his employer at a Tucker
compressor plant that the allegations were ``all lies.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the lawsuit is slowly spreading through metro Atlanta's
Bosnian community, because many do not speak English and had not
heard about the case. But some Bosnians ``are reacting pretty
emotionally'' when they learn about it, said Mirza Hadzibegovic, a
Bosnian Muslim who works at Lutheran Ministries of Georgia and
helps refugees find jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't like to hear about this. They are pretty
disappointed,'' said Hadzibegovic, 40, who has lived in Atlanta
four years. ``If someone came here to the United States from the
hell of Bosnia and someone from another nationality came here, too,
most Bosnians suppose that person is OK. They don't expect they
will find a killer or someone who did something terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,200 Bosnian refugees have resettled in metro
Atlanta, most in DeKalb County. The majority are Muslim, but there
are Croat and Serb refugees here as well. Many live as neighbors in
the same apartment complexes, because the refugee agencies that
find them apartments do not routinely separate people by their
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Some Serbs qualified as refugees because they are married to
Muslims and being in a mixed marriage makes them targets for
persecution. Other Serbs were forced out of the Krajina region of
Croatia by Croatian soldiers in 1995. The Serbs in Belgrade
wouldn't take them and instead sent them to Kosovo, where they are
now fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Bosnian refugee program started in 1993, the United
States has accepted 61,000 Bosnians, according to the State
Department. Seventy-six percent are Muslim, 10 percent are Serbs
and 7 percent are Croats. The rest are classified as ``other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All ethnicities are eligible for the resettlement program,''
said Peter Herbert, director of the International Rescue
Committee's Atlanta office, which has resettled hundreds of
Bosnians here. ``If you are in a mixed marriage, you may not be
welcome or able to return to your home in any part of Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuckovic has told his employer, Our Way Inc. in Tucker, that his
wife is Muslim. Vuckovic's supervisor, Don Hood, has said he is a
``model employee'' who is ``very easygoing, friendly and very
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Each refugee is screened by the State Department and the
Immigration and Naturalization Service before being allowed to
enter the United States. Each one has to pass medical and security
background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Vuckovic's name did not show up when it was run through a
Justice Department database of people suspected of committing
wartime atrocities, a State Department official said. His status as
a refugee is unchanged because the allegations haven't been proven,
the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert said all ethnic groups seem to get along once they get
here, and they don't dwell on their past. ``There is a lot more
anxiety over other issues, like who got a better job, who came with
more money or who got a spot in the best ESL (English as a Second
Language) class,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers from other agencies that resettle Bosnians
concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``My refugee families out here help each other,'' said Linda
Dowd, who works at World Relief's office in Lawrenceville. ``They
don't seem to care who is from where. They are all starting over
from nothing and they are interested in having a new life and
having jobs and good schools for their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert said he is not aware of any tension in the Bosnian
community since the lawsuit was filed. ``I don't know if anybody
really knows the truth yet,'' he said. ``I would not be surprised
if people who have been through the worst in the war are upset over
the thought that something like this is taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hadzibegovic said most Bosnians do get along, regardless of
their ethnicity. But this lawsuit may make some more suspicious of
their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They expected they would be safe here. That's why some of them
are pretty disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
