<HEADER>
A5855 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SUDAN-AZR &LR;      09-02 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SUDAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRORIST, SUDAN PLANT LINKS NOT VERY REASSURING  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN WEDNESDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - As news emerged from Egypt of the capture of
Palestinian guerrilla chief Abu Nidal _ accused of killing hundreds
of people all over the world _ the whereabouts of that other
terrorist, Osama bin Laden, remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the suspect in the Aug. 7 embassy bombings in Kenya and
Tanzania is in the mountains of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he is in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing seems certain. The U.S. cruise missile attacks on
his training bases did not kill him, and he remains a threat to
American targets all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Clinton administration miss an opportunity to
destroy this monster in its military strikes on his terrorist
facilities in southeastern Afghanistan, the U.S. attack on an
alleged chemical weapons plant in Khartoum, Sudan, has forced
American foreign policy onto the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Was the Shifa Pharmaceuticals plant an innocuous producer of
simple medication?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps learning a lesson from the Gulf War when Iraq claimed
the Unitd States had struck a baby formula factory, Sudanese
officials claimed before the United Nations that their plant
manufactured painkillers and malaria medicine and not chemical
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been forced to concede that links between
bin Laden and the pharmaceutical plant are rather ``fuzzy,''
although officials emphasize a clandestine soil sample from the
Sudan plant property showed traces of a material with no commercial
uses that is a key ingredient in certain chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen explained that bin Laden had
``financial interest'' in the plant, and the facilities that the
United States struck were important parts of the bin Laden network
of terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the administration has been hard pressed to explain why
that particular plant was not mentioned in previous reports on the
manufacture of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves the strength of U.S. electronic intercepts of
telephone calls, tenuous financial links and soil samples to
justify its strike against the Sudanese plant.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Clinton administration's dubious record of honesty and
candor, the American people _ and, indeed, the world _ might need
more evidence to feel confident an appropriate and effective blow
was delivered against international terrorism. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1907EDT &QL; 
