u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-FINANCE-HNS &LR;      09-02 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON STILL CRITICAL OF RENO DESPITE CAMPAIGN FINANCE MEETING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of Attorney General Janet Reno's harshest
congressional critics said Wednesday he was not satisfied after
meeting with her over the issue of campaign finance investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general appears to be trying to protect the
president and vice president of the United States,'' said Rep. Dan
Burton, R-Ind., after a 2 1/2-hour meeting between Reno and
lawmakers. Burton has been critical of Reno for not calling for an
independent counsel to investigate alleged campaign fund-raising
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and members of Congress who met with Reno and her
advisers on the campaign finance issue focused on Justice
Department memos urging the attorney general to call for an
independent counsel. Burton has threatened to ask the House to hold
Reno in contempt of Congress for failing to surrender those memos
to the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee, which
Burton chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who has rejected the calls for an independent counsel, let
Burton and other lawmakers at the meeting review edited versions of
the memos. However, Burton said the attorney general's revisions
left him questioning what evidence of campaign finance abuses might
have been excised.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Burton said, Reno declined to answer many
questions regarding the Justice Department's examination of alleged
fund-raising abuses by Vice President Al Gore, citing agency policy
prohibiting comment on pending investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that everything we wanted was given to us,''
Burton said. Nevertheless, he called the meeting ``helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Burton said he would withdraw his threat to press
the House to hold Reno in contempt of Congress until his legal
advisers have had a chance to review the edited sections.
</P>
<P>
   But Burton added he might renew his call for a contempt citation
if the review does not answer his questions regarding Reno's
refusal to call for an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Reno declined to comment when she left the meeting. However, her
chief spokesman, Bert Brandenburg, said Burton's allegations
regarding a cover-up are without merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She bases her decisions on the facts and law and nothing
else,'' Brandenburg said. He added that Reno believed the meeting
was ``constructive'' because it allowed her to address the
lawmakers' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Reno last month told a panel of three federal judges that she
had called for a preliminary 90-day investigation of Gore and this
week launched a similar examination of Harold Ickes, a former aide
to President Clinton. At the end of the 90 days, Reno can seek an
additional 60 days to wind up the probe, ask the panel to appoint
an independent counsel or report that the Justice Department found
no credible allegation warranting further inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's refusal to name an independent counsel in the Gore case
prompted Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
to call the attorney general to his Capitol Hill office for
Wednesday's meeting. Also attending was Charles LaBella, the former
chief of the Justice Department's campaign finance task force,
whose memo calling for an independent counsel sparked the criticism
of Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who has criticized Reno for not seeking an independent
counsel, said the attorney general was ``forthcoming'' at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh has also written a memo urging Reno to
ask the three-judge panel to name an independent counsel to
investigate alleged campaign finance abuses by Gore. Freeh did not
attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Waxman of California, the ranking Democrat on the
committee Burton chairs, praised Reno for her willingness to meet
with her congressional critics and answer all the questions she
could without compromising the ongoing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memos were helpful, and the discussion was helpful,''
Waxman said. ``The attorney general is making a good-faith effort
to comply with Congress's right to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day probe of Gore will focus on dozens of telephone calls
Gore made from his government office in late 1995 and early 1996
soliciting money for the Democratic Party. In December, Reno ended
a similar probe, saying there was not sufficient evidence to
require naming an independent counsel to conduct a full
investigation
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department last month obtained a 1995 White
House memorandum bearing handwritten notes that appear to
contradict Gore's repeated claims that the 45 calls in question
were made to solicit only contributions to the Democratic Party and
not to the Clinton-Gore re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day probe of Ickes was prompted by a report from the
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, which accused Clinton's
former deputy chief of staff of ``misleading and inaccurate''
testimony during a congressional hearing into alleged fund-raising
abuses by the White House and the Democratic Party. The Ickes probe
was not on the agenda of the closed-door session.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending the Reno meeting were Sen. Patrick Leahy of
Vermont, top Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee; Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary Committee; and Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder Jr. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
