<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAUSE SPEAKS VOLUMES   FOR YELTSIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ For a full 10 seconds, the president of Russia was
silent, visibly uncomfortable, strugging to answer the question his
embattled nation needed to ask:
</P>
<P>
   Was he, Boris Yeltsin, ready to dissolve the Communist-led
legislature if it kept rejecting his candidate to lead his nation
out of its worst crisis in five years?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that,'' Yeltsin started sluggishly before his
long, embarrassing pause, ``that rather many events will take place
before we reach that result.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's halting answer did little to clear up doubts that the
Russian leader is fully in control as the ruble took another
nosedive Wednesday in his politically and financially paralyzed
country.
</P>
<P>
   Beside him, President Clinton waited for Yeltsin to say more, as
did reporters in the Kremlin hall. Hands shaking, mouth turned down
in a permanent scowl, Yeltsin finally responded, ``That's all,''
prompting nervous titters from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty obvious, isn't it?'' said one Russian government
official who saw the press conference and asked not to be
identified. ``We are at the end of the Yeltsin era. Don't the
Americans see that?''
</P>
<P>
   In Yeltsin's first press conference since he abruptly fired his
government and split down 11 days ago, Clinton shrugged off the
Russian president's hesitation and literally bailed him out,
ad-libbing a joke about Yeltsin's good reply.
</P>
<P>
   But among Russians, all but Yeltsin's most loyal allies have
long ago written off the president as a spent political force.
</P>
<P>
   At 67, after surviving open-heart surgery, Yeltsin can no longer
work full days, or even more than a few hours at a time, according
to the powerful business magnate Boris Berezovsky, who has close
financial and personal ties to the Yeltsin family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preservation of power is all Yeltsin thinks about,''
</P>
<P>
   said Dmirty Pinsker, a political analyst for the news magazine
Itogi. ``It's his only concern.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Yeltsin has preferred to ride out his country's worst
crises in the shadows, re-emerging to cow his opponents in
parliament and show the world that he is still in charge. But this
time, after the Russian economy collapsed under a burden of debt,
revenue shortfalls and capital flight, the State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, has energetically challenged Yeltsin by
spurning his choice for prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis will grow because no one is stopping it,'' said
retired general Alexander Lebed, now a regional governor and a
possible future presidential candidate, who was one of several
opposition leaders who met with Clinton Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Duma rejected Chernomyrdin, who served for five
years as prime minister and whom many Russians blame, along with
Yeltsin, for their problems. Yeltsin quickly asked the Duma to vote
a second time, and senior lawmakers, who set a new vote for Friday,
say Chernomyrdin has little chance of passing. If they vote ``no''
a third time, Yeltsin is mandated by the Constitution to dismiss
the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers, aware of Yeltsin's weakness, suggest the
legislature may refuse to disband and instead may try to impeach
him.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, ignoring a Duma request to back down and name another
candidate, Wednesday approved Chernomyrdin's request to form an
interim government, even as legislators questioned the legality of
the move.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has vowed to protect Russians' savings as the ruble
crumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday the Central Bank ordered all accounts in faltering
commercial banks, which have been virtually closed for the past
three weeks, switched to the state savings bank. The Central Bank
also set a new rate of 12.89 to the dollar for the ruble, half the
currency's value as late as August 17.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russia waits for more details from Chernomydrin's
boss, Yeltsin, whose silences have only deepened the nation's
uncertainty, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the whole systsem of the country is falling apart
because it depends on one man being active,'' said Nikolai Petrov,
a political analysts at the Carnegie Moscow Center. ``And he is not
all that active.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
