A5872 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SUMMIT-HNS &LR;      09-02 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES OPPOSITION LEADERS, YELTSIN TO WORK TOGETHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton urged opposition leaders to work with
President Boris Yeltsin for reform as the summit between the two
leaders ended without an indication of how Russia intends to
resolve its massive political and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day session seemed only to offer a brief respite for
Yeltsin from the political infighting in the Communist-led
legislature, which has blocked his efforts to form a new government
to deal with the financial mess.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference at the ornate Catherine Hall deep
inside the Kremlin, President Clinton warned Yeltsin's political
opponents: ``I think if other political forces in Russia try to
force the president to abandon reform in midstream or even reverse
it, what I think will happen is even less money will come into
Russia and even more economic hardship will result.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin acknowledged that Russia must resolve its economic woes,
which in recent days have seen the ruble plummet in value, banks
freeze assets and an almost insolvent stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not saying that we count solely on support from the
outside,'' Yeltsin said. ``What we need from the United States is
political support to the effect that the United States is in favor
of reforms in Russia. Then all the investors who would like to come
to the Russian reformed markets will do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men sat side by side after signing agreements to reduce
plutonium stockpiles and to establish a mutual early warning system
for missile launches.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared tired and Yeltsin fielded questions with a
lopsided smile. Both men are under fire at home and have faced
repeated calls for resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to say _ and I hope Bill will agree with me _ the
summit was a success,'' Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian president offered a confusing response when asked if
he intended to press for Viktor Chernomyrdin's appointment as prime
minister even if it meant dissolving the Duma and calling new
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I must say, we will witness quite a few events for us to
be able to achieve all those results,'' Yeltsin said. After a long
pause in which people waited for him to continue, he smiled, turned
to his press secretary and said, ``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   The political confrontation between the Communist-led Duma and
Yeltsin will replay itself Thursday or Monday when Chernomyrdin's
name is placed before the chamber for a second vote. If the Duma
rejects Chernomyrdin three times, the legislative body is dissolved
and new elections are called.
</P>
<P>
   The political drama has delayed a coordinated response to the
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, after two days of hearing of Russia's
commitment to reform, now intends to watch Russia for its action as
the deadline nears for a mid-month decision by the International
Monetary Fund to continue its installments of Moscow's $22.6
billion bail-out fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the ball I think is very much in their court. We do not
have any new or additional aid or plan in our pocket. I think the
first order of business for Russia is clearly going to be putting
forward a plan that would lead to the resumption of the current IMF
package,'' said a senior administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at the news conference and later at a meeting with Duma
leaders, continued to press for changes that would make Russia more
attractive to international investors.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official later said, ``While it is
reassuring, and there have been a lot of reassuring comments made,
I think that the focus of the IMF, as well as ourselves, will be on
the action that is taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with more than a dozen parliamentary leaders and
regional politicians at Spaso House, the U.S. ambassador's
residence. The group included Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the
Communist Party faction, who has accused Yeltsin of setting the
stage for a civil war, and Aleksandr Lebed, the former military
official turned politician. Clinton spoke to the leaders as a group
and later met with them individually.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, he reiterated his outline for reforms that Russia must
undertake, including the creation of a fair tax system to meet its
spending requirements, effective regulations for banks and allowing
the rule of law apply to all.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a friend I say I do not believe that you can defy the rules
of the road in today's global economy anymore than I could defy the
laws of gravity by stepping off the top floor of Spaso House,''
Clinton said. ``It has nothing to do with politics, and everything
to do with the way the world is working today.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on the political factions to work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can find a way to work together and work through this
crisis, the United States will stand with you and will not presume
to judge the specific social systems you decide to put in place
within a democratic system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Clinton and Yeltsin met
one-on-one to discuss the situation in Kosovo, Iraq and with the
Western defense alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin spoke of Russia's opposition to an expanded North
Atlantic Treaty Organization and to the use of military force
whether in Kosovo, Iraq or Afghanistan, a reference to Clinton's
use of missile strikes aimed at terrorist camps.
</P>
<P>
   The two also talked about the energy-rich Caucasus and Clinton
pressed for U.S. firms to have access to the energy sector there.
</P>
<P>
   The aide said the issue of the international space station was
discussed only briefly and was ``remanded to the experts'' for
further talks. Russia has had numerous problems delivering its part
of the construction of the international project.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day Clinton telephoned Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat for brief
chats about the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials offered no details of the conversation
other than to say hopes for a resumption of the peace process were
closer than ever.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli spokesman quoted Clinton as saying he ``intends to
take steps to speed up the talks with the Palestinians, as soon as
he gets back from Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton leaves Russia on Thursday for a visit to Northern
Ireland and Ireland to champion the peace process there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
