<TEXT>
<P>
   (th) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Sept. 3. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUMMIT (Moscow) _ President Clinton signaled Wednesday
that the West would be willing to expand its program of financial
assistance if Russia carried out tough economic reforms. Clinton's
message was intended to encourage the Yeltsin government to stick
with its pro-capitalist course despite the nation's deepening
economic crisis. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Moscow) _ Directly questioned for the first
time in public about the Monica Lewinsky matter since his televised
admission two weeks ago, President Clinton said at a Kremlin news
conference Wednesday that he believed he had expressed ``profound
regret'' to those who had been hurt by his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ President Clinton told the grand
jury investigating his relationship with Monica Lewinsky that he
was troubled by the onetime intern's transfer out of the White
House and considered bringing her back last summer, according to
lawyers familiar with his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-FATHERS (Washington) _ With tough new rules now in place
for welfare mothers, the spotlight is turning to welfare fathers,
and dozens of programs have sprung up in the last few years,
seeking to raise the incomes of these missing men and strengthen
their ties to their children. By Jason DeParle. With 2-column
photo. 2,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
