<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ENDS SUMMIT, SKIRTS APOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton ended his summit with Boris N.
Yeltsin Wednesday by again skirting a public apology for his
adulterous affair with Monica S. Lewinsky and his lies that
followed it. Both leaders faced questions about their conduct in
office and the fate of the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin lauded the friendship between the two nations, but
bluntly spoke of his differences with Clinton. He criticized the US
for using military force in the August 20 missile launches on
suspected terrorist sites in Sudan and Afghanistan and said that
Russia abhors the expansion of the NATO military alliance into
former Iron Curtain countries in central Europe, which he described
as ``a blunder, a big mistake'' and ``a historic error.''
</P>
<P>
   In a contrast of surreal proportions, Clinton and Yeltsin
gathered in the Kremlin's majestic Catherine Hall to sign a pair of
pivotal military agreements, then stammered their way through
subjects raised by reporters from Clinton's sexual conduct to
Yeltsin's political competence.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Yeltsin, asked about his strategy to win
confirmation for his nominee as prime minister, uttered a virtually
incomprehensible answer that had no bearing on the question, then
abruptly ended his response with a wave of his hand and the words,
``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Clinton blushed bright red when reporters questioned him
on his affair with Lewinsky, the former White House intern less
than half his age, as well as his defiant public admission on
August 17. Pointedly given the opportunity to apologize for his
actions, Clinton refused. He said the American people understood
his position and were ready to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it the other day again,'' Clinton said of his earlier
speech, ``and I thought it was clear that I was expressing my
profound regret to all who were hurt and to all who were involved,
and my desire not to see anymore people hurt by this process and
caught up in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I was commenting that it seemed to be something that most
reasonable people would think had consumed a disproportionate
amount of America's time, money and resources and attention, and
now continued to involve more and more people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was anathema to many White House strategists,
Democratic allies and Republican opponents who have pleaded
publicly and privately with Clinton to apologize explicitly for his
affair and lies, and temper the defiant front he has mounted to
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   For two and a half weeks, the White House has wrestled with the
issue of a proper, public apology by Clinton. Some aides had
privately hoped that he would offer it in Moscow, during his first
press conference since he admitted his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Asked earlier in the press conference if the Lewinsky affair has
diminished his effectiveness as president, Clinton said no, adding,
``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake, said that I regretted
it, asked to be forgiven, spent a lot of very valuable time with my
family in the last couple of weeks and said I was going back to
work. I believe that's what the American people want me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's responses to the Lewinsky questions and Yeltsin's
troubling performance overshadowed the end of a summit at which the
United States sought to lure Russia further down the road of market
reform by raising the prospect of economic aid. As the summit
ended, the Russian economy continued to deteriorate. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``America and the international community are, I am convinced,
ready to offer further assistance if Russia stays with the path of
reform,'' Clinton said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Under the gold-fringed dome in Catherine Hall amid towering
white columns, Clinton and Yeltsin sat side by side at a long desk
and penned their signatures to a pair of military agreements that
their aides have described as crucial.
</P>
<P>
   One of the agreements calls for each nation to remove 50 tons of
weapons-grade plutonium from its nuclear stockpile. The other
establishes a global early warning system for all missiles launches
to prevent an accidental or mistaken retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Before their news conference, Clinton and Yeltsin met again
Wednesday morning in the presidential study of the Kremlin, turning
what was supposed to have been a widely attended gathering into
another face to face encounter between the two leaders alone. The
meeting lasted over an hour, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Clinton met with Russian opposition leaders
and prodded them toward economic reform. Before Clinton spoke at
the US ambassador's residence, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright chatted amiably with Aleksandr Lebed, the hard-line former
general who is now the governor of the Krasnoyarsk province in
Siberia. As soon as Clinton concluded his speech, he walked
directly to Lebed and talked to him for at least five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the ceremony and signs of friendship, it was an
bizarre summit by any measure. The two leaders made an unusual
couple. Yeltsin is politically crippled by his nation's imploding
economy and ailing health. Clinton is dogged by issues of
credibility and the prospect of damaging evidence presented in an
upcoming independent counsel's report.
</P>
<P>
   Their respective weaknesses were highlighted in one particular
exchange initiated by Reuter's reporter Laurence McQuillan, who
asked Yeltsin whether he would be willing to nominate someone other
than Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime minister or if he would be
prepared to dissolve the Duma, the lower Huuse of the Russian
parliament, to get his way.
</P>
<P>
   As the question was posed, Clinton, sitting next to Yeltsin,
seemed to smile, looking first toward press secretary Mike McCurry,
then over to Madeleine Albright sitting nearby. But before Yeltsin
could respond, McQuillan turned to Clinton and said, ``Mr.
President, another Lewinsky question.'' With that, Clinton flushed
red.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders then looked at each other. Yeltsin, after
hesitating, haltingly said, ``Well, I must say, we will witness
quite a few events for us to be able to achieve all those
results.'' He paused, looked to his press secretary, then added,
``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Before responding to the Lewinsky inquiry, Clinton laughed and
said, ``That's my answer, too. That was pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a hallway of the US embassy here, Democratic Rep.
Steny Hoyer of Maryland cornered McQuillan, jabbed his finger in
his chest and said, ``Speaking as an American, I'm outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the question an attempt to embarrass the president
while he was in Moscow conducting important business. He said the
media should ``drop its obsession'' with Lewinsky because Americans
don't care. But ironically, Hoyer would periodically interrupt
himself to add that he didn't condone Clinton's activities with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, US officials continued to defend their stated
position that Yeltsin was engaged in all of his meetings with
Clinton and seemed to retain an intellectual grip on the issues
that confront him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
