A5895 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROCERY-ADDICT-TEX     09-02 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROCERY-ADDICT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DO I LOVE GROCERIES? LET ME COUNT THE WAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only in the past few days have I discussed my addiction.
</P>
<P>
   It was with the sort of giddiness that a clotheshorse feels at
visiting Nordstrom that I confessed to a close friend _ upon
learning that the newest Tom Thumb ``new generation'' store was
open in my neighborhood _ that I go to the grocery store every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``EVERY day?'' she asked with doubt.
</P>
<P>
   OK, six out of seven. That might seem weird, since I don't have
a large family to feed and I only cook once or twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, grocery shopping fills me with unbridled pleasure.
To me, food is spiritual and sensual.
</P>
<P>
   On some trips, I don't buy anything _ just being there provides
the euphoria I crave. In Houston, for instance, I make a point of
visiting Rice Epicurean simply to look at the displays of pates and
breads. In Austin, I always make a trip through Central Market,
just to gawk at the vast vats of imported olives, the
unpronounceable brands of vinegars and oils, the fruits that look
as if they're on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Fort Worth, I visit the Asian markets on Belknap
Street to look over the strange vegetables and fruits, or to find
the rare ingredients to make red curry paste. Then there's the
cornucopia of chiles and Mexican cheeses at Fiesta Food Mart.
</P>
<P>
   When I actually do some serious grocery shopping, I'll easily
drop $8 on a hunk of cheese or $10 on a bottle of olive oil. If my
whole tab comes to $150 or $200, what the heck. Yet I'm racked with
guilt if I spend lavishly at Target or Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this addiction is genetic. As a child, I remember sitting
in the cart as my mom _ another grocery addict _ hummed happy tunes
while choosing produce, chatting with the butcher or pointing out
to me all the spices and explaining their uses.
</P>
<P>
   When the holidays are upon us, I'm intoxicated with the thought
of numerous grocery trips to prepare party foods and family meals.
Sometimes that calls for more than one trip per day. Ecstasy!
</P>
<P>
   Here, for instance, are 10 reasons you'll find me in the aisles
of the new Tom Thumb _ one of the few places in Fort Worth where
you can find all of these under the same roof:
</P>
<P>
   1. Huge floral section. Right at the entrance, just like in
European and Mexican markets. The cut-flower selection includes
tropical blooms such as anthuriums at $4.99 per stem, giant
heliconias at $9.99 each and tiny purple-and-white orchids for
$3.99 each.
</P>
<P>
   2. HMRs _ Home Meal Replacements. Ready-to-heat entrees include
meat loaf marinara with mashed potatoes and green beans, chicken
enchiladas with rice, and chicken Parmesan with pasta, $6-$8. Or
opt for the herbed rotisserie chickens, $5, and cool Caesar salad,
$2.50.
</P>
<P>
   3. By-the-pound Greek vegetable salad, $5.99; chicken breast
salad with green grapes, $8.99; dolmas, $4.99; and grilled salmon
fillets, $10.99.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bakery. Yummy. Mini-cheesecake topped with fresh fruit and
surrounded by sliced almonds is the perfect dessert for four,
$6.89. Thick, dense focaccia topped with basil, rosemary, red bell
peppers, mushrooms and Parmesan is $3.59.
</P>
<P>
   5. Fresh sushi, made daily and packaged with wasabi and pickled
ginger.
</P>
<P>
   6. Selection, selection, selection. Five kinds of polenta, five
kinds of tofu. Blue, Roquefort, Stilton and gorgonzola cheeses.
Fresh red jalapenos, pale green habaneros, long thin Fresno chiles.
At least 20 kinds of olive oil, as well as peanut, sesame, walnut
and avocado oils.
</P>
<P>
   7. There are _ counted 'em _ 90 kinds of salsa. In addition to
the expected Pace and El Paso, there are brands you've never heard
of, using everything from peaches and pineapple to black-eyed peas
and black beans.
</P>
<P>
   8. Exotics. Finally, we can throw together a Southeast Asian or
Indian dinner without trotting all over the county to various
ethnic markets (although purists will still do so). Choices include
Thai lemon grass oil, Panang red curry, Keow Wan green curry, pure
coconut milk and tandoori paste.
</P>
<P>
   9. Curbside video and game drop-off. No kidding; you don't have
to leave your car.
</P>
<P>
   10. Friendly staff. We've grown weary of surly grocery store
people. These folks seem to actually enjoy their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
