u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-VOTES-BOS &LR;      09-02 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-VOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY SEES GOP DELAYS ON HEALTH, WAGE BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after Senator Edward M. Kennedy helped
push into law a health insurance portability bill and a 90-cent
increase in the minimum wage, his attempt to repeat that
performance with two similar bills is being stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is trying to pass new regulations for health maintenance
organizations and a $1 increase in the current $5.15-an-hour
minimum wage, but Wednesday he acknowledged that Senate Republican
leaders, emboldened by President Clinton's troubles, think they can
stonewall attempts to pass the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, he is totally overshadowed by a completely weakened
president and an economy that all of a sudden is shaky,'' said Chip
Kahn, the chief operating officer and president-designate of the
Health Insurance Association of America, a leading trade
association for the insurance industry. ``You just cannot play
these non-central issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he is confident that his bill to guarantee certain
patient rights and impose rules on managed care plans as well as
the minimum wage increase would pass if either came to a vote on
the Senate floor because both issues have strong public support. He
said if Republican leaders continue to block the bills, Democrats
will end the session with campaign issues for November.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues are enough to win in just about any district in
America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This week Senate Democratic leader Thomas Daschle changed
tactics and offered to use the House managed-care bill as a base
bill for Senate consideration, provided Republican leaders allow
Democrats to offer amendments.
</P>
<P>
   After Majority leader Trent Lott said he would allow only three
amendments, Kennedy said at a news conference Wednesday, ``A gag
rule is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after Clinton had effectively blamed the GOP for the
1995 government shutdown, moderate Republicans backed
Kennedy-authored bills on health insurance and the minimum wage,
guaranteeing passage prior to the election.
</P>
<P>
   This year the ongoing investigation into Clinton's relationship
with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky has drowned out debate over
such issues, congressional observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, delays in passing spending bills, which must be
approved before the start of the new fiscal year Oct. 1, have
crowded out most other legislation from the congressional calendar.
Government operations cannot continue without approval of 13
separate spending bills, the first of which went to the White House
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy plans to attach his minimum wage proposal to a
bankruptcy reform bill that could reach the Senate floor as soon as
Friday, a move that could force Majority Leader Trent Lott to pull
the legislation from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Support for another minimum wage increase is not as great as it
was two years ago, said Lee Culpepper, vice president of federal
relations for the National Restaurant Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996 Senator Kennedy discovered an issue that became a
political tsunami, that was the minimum wage increase. This time
around he is finding out that the tide is out,'' said Culpepper.
``This issue is not anything that is really a top-of-the-mind
concern of voters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1931EDT &QL; 
