A5903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-OPPOSITION-NYT     09-02 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OPPOSITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CLINTON MEETS WITH RUSSIAN OPPOSITION, DIRE FORECASTS
CIRCULATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia struggled through another day without a
government; the ruble's value fell again; people had less money
than ever, and spirits and fortunes were sagging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is worse than in 1917,'' the year that the
Bolsheviks seized power in a country depleted by war and government
indecision, Alexander Lebed, the ex-general and regional governor
with presidential ambitions, said he told President Clinton on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that the situation in Russia is catastrophic,''
said Lebed, who joined other Russian political leaders Wednesday
afternoon for a meeting with Clinton at the U.S. ambassador's
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Bleak predictions flourished in Moscow on Wednesday, as
newspapers and commentators sifted through various scenarios _ from
dictatorship to armed insurrection _ that could result from the
standoff between President Boris Yeltsin and his opposition in the
lower house of the Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house is now set to meet Friday afternoon for a second
round of voting on the nomination of Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime
minister, five days after his candidacy was rejected the first
time. If no political breakthrough occurs before then, and the
parliament rejects Chernomyrdin a third time, then Yeltsin is
constitutionally bound to disband it and call for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into the breach Wednesday with a presidential decree,
Yeltsin named six acting cabinet members, including Boris Fyodorov,
Russia's tough-talking top tax collector, and for the moment, the
lone clear and authoritative voice advocating Western-style
remedies for Russia's worsening economic and financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Fyodorov drew the line at any
mass printing of new rubles, an option Yeltsin's opposition pushed
in its own economic program. Such a course, he said, would only
lead to hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody intends to go down the road to inflation,'' he said
flatly.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk would be reassuring to Clinton and Russia's other
western allies, who all week have been pressing Moscow to stay the
course on economic reform, and not slide back into Soviet-era
practices like price controls and excessive state spending.
</P>
<P>
   Blasting the Central Bank for policies that set the stage for
the ruble's collapse, Fyodorov also floated the idea of a currency
board, a solution that imposes strict controls on money supply and
which has been used successfully in Argentina, Bulgaria and other
countries to steady inflation and restore investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov said he would continue to pursue the idea at a meeting
Thursday with Domingo Cavallo, Argentina's former economy minister
who presided over a currency board that halted inflation by
requiring the central bank to hold one U.S. dollar for every
Argentinian peso in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   But without a government to carry it out, Fyodorov's pledges and
proposals had a ring of prematurity. ``Who can tell me who is going
to be Russia's prime minister in a week?'' asked a western
official. ``That is the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has insisted he will not back off Chernomyrdin's
nomination, although he prevaricated Wednesday when the question
was put to him at a news conference. Most analysts thought it
unlikely that Yeltsin would be the first to blink in the current
standoff since any concessions would only further embolden his
opposition to press for more.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio interview Wednesday, Boris Berezovsky, the financier
who helped engineer Chernomyrdin's nomination, suggested that
Yeltsin may ultimately have to resign to allow a strong political
figure to emerge in his place. An alternative, he said, would be to
create room for a strong political figure who would rule alongside
Yeltsin, ``quietly putting up with the fact that the president
cannot, to the necessary degree, take part in the swiftly
developing events.''
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, in a later television interview, said he thought
parliament may still be outmaneuvered by the Kremlin, and that
Chernomyrdin's chances of becoming prime minister are not lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chernomyrdin had a chance,'' said Berezovsky. ``It's another
question how he will use it now. He had a real chance. I still
think far from everything has been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin picked up support from a group of regional
governors, who urged the lower house to act swiftly so that a
government can start putting a program in place. He is due to meet
Thursday with the parliament's upper house, made up of regional
leaders, which has influence, but no power over the formation of
new governments.
</P>
<P>
   The political paralysis continued to take an economic toll
Wednesday, as the value of the ruble fell again during electronic
interbank trading. Continuing uncertainty about the value of the
currency caused major stores to halt credit card transactions, even
as their shelves were being emptied of essential goods.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Central Bank said it was preparing measures to
transfer savings accounts from six major banks to the
government-controlled Sberbank, although in an interview on
television Wednesday night, a top bank official said depositors
would have the option to leave their accounts untouched ``if they
have faith in their bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Central Bank official said in a radio interview that
Russia had spent $9 billion in the last two months defending the
ruble, and had had no choice now but to let its value float.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping that if events took a normal course, the rate
could be held without any intervention,'' said deputy bank chairman
Denis Kiselyov. ``What is happening now in economics and politics
can in no way be called a normal course of events.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
