<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME FOR TAKING STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: For many market players, the past few weeks have been a
bearish torment they'd only heard about but never experienced.
</P>
<P>
   They're the ones who discovered stocks in the '90s, and their
timing was exquisite. These bull market beneficiaries have known
nothing but good times. Even the occasional stomach-wrenching
sell-offs have been embraced as buying opportunities that
subsequently drove prices ever higher. Playing Wall Street's game
had to seem to this lucky bunch of novices like the next best thing
to winning a lottery jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has all unraveled. Since the major indexes peaked July
17, a huge collapse has vaporized an estimated $2 trillion in
market value. That is about one-fourth of the value of all the
goods and services that will be generated by the U.S. economy this
year _ otherwise known as the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   It's a funny thing about stock market values. Stocks at any
given moment are worth only what buyers and sellers say they're
worth. So why was the market worth $2 trillion more in mid-July
than it was on the last day of August?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in a word, is confidence. There was no magic moment
when confidence was lost, however. Moreover, the day investors lost
confidence didn't occur during the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   No, the signs of an impending major decline had been building
for months. The only question among those who understand the
market's most-telling auguries was whether the market was in for a
substantial correction or whether a full-fledged bear market was in
the cards.
</P>
<P>
   While the most widely watched indicators showed strength, the
stock market's lesser lights had been deteriorating for months.
While the aftermath of Monday's tornadic destruction left the Dow
Jones industrial average with a loss of only 4.7 percent for the
first eight months of the year, the Russell 2000 was showing a 23
percent decline for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The deterioration of the Russell 2000 before August's dramatic
market break was important because this index comprises middle- and
lower-tier capitalization companies. When the shares of the smaller
companies experience the kind of extended decline that was
occurring to Russell 2000 stocks, it's usually only a matter of
time until the big-capitalization companies are pulled into the
vortex.
</P>
<P>
   Another portent of the market's shaky condition before the July
17 peak was the weakness of the breadth numbers. Declining stocks
were beginning to outnumber gainers with disturbing frequency, as
were the stocks making new lows compared with those making new
highs. Thus, from a technical standpoint the market was slipping
into a sorry state long before major gauges hit their highs.
</P>
<P>
   What will it take for investors to regain enough confidence to
bid aggregate stock prices back up enough to recoup the lost $2
trillion? It's said that the market moves between fear and greed.
Greed has been in ascendancy throughout the '90s, but an
increasingly uncertain world has put fear back in the driver's
seat.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy is slowing along with corporate profit growth,
Russia is imploding, Latin America remains iffy, Japan seems frozen
in the headlights of its banking crisis, Southeast Asia's recovery
depends largely on Japan, and North Korea just launched a missile
across Japan's bow.
</P>
<P>
   With so much to fear, the market may show occasional bounce, but
recapturing sustained upward momentum will be difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1938EDT &QL; 
