<SLUG> BC-MA-YANDLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING DELAYED ON KILLER'S PAROLE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With Acting Governor Paul Cellucci ordering the parole
board to tighten its verification process, the Governor's Council
Wednesday decided to wait another week before scheduling a hearing
on whether to revoke the commutation of murderer Joseph Yandle.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Sheila Hubbard, chairwoman of the parole board,
Paul Johnson, Cellucci's legal counsel, Wednesday ordered the board
to tighten its verification procedures by requiring that:
</P>
<P>
   _Any petitioner for clemency submitting documents to the parole
board comply with the state laws of evidence regarding the
authenticity of those documents.
</P>
<P>
   _All petitions be sworn under oath and subject to perjury
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   _The board verify all claims of military service.
</P>
<P>
   _The board clearly identify the evidence supporting any facts or
information contained in its recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The administration issued those instructions after finding that
the parole board only began verifying military records in 1993 _
and then only when questions arose _ and that it began routinely
verifying records with the military as recently as last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, a mistake was made here,'' Cellucci said. ``That
military record should have been verified. It was not.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the acting governor tried to deflect some criticism on
the issue, saying he and Weld had not gained control of the board,
whose members are filled by gubernatorial appointments, until 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Yandle's hearing before the board came in 1992. The board, which
accepted his forged military records claiming a bogus record of
heroism in Vietnam, recommended a commutation in June of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Weld subsequently endorsed that recommendation, which the
Governor's Council granted in 1995, commuting the life sentence
Yandle had received for his felony-murder conviction as the getaway
driver in a 1972 Medford liquor store holdup. A man was murdered in
the holdup.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Governor's Council Wednesday were mixed on how to
proceed in the matter of revoking the commutation for Yandle, who
has admitted he forged the military records.
</P>
<P>
   Councilor Dorothy Kelly Gay, a Democrat from Somerville, said
she wanted to ask former governor William F. Weld and his former
legal counsel, Brackett Denniston, what factors had led them to
recommend commutation for Yandle.
</P>
<P>
   Councilor Christopher Iannella Jr., a Jamaica Plain Democrat,
thought the council should query the former parole board members
who recommended commutation for Yandle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Council ultimately voted unanimously for the motion of
Councilor Edward M. O'Brien to wait another week to see how the
parole board handles the issue of revoking Yandle's parole.
</P>
<P>
   The parole board this week provisionally revoked Yandle's
parole. Wednesday, administration officials said a final hearing on
the matter has been set for Sept. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
