<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTATASTE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A TASTE: TIME TO BONE UP ON BASICS OF NUTRITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Whether your child is a picky eater, budding gourmet or
a well-adjusted vegan, back to school signals it's time to bone up
on the basics of good nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few tips from the experts:
</P>
<P>
   - The ABCs
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Nutrition Research Center at the Baylor College
of Medicine in Houston suggests using the vitamins A, B and C as a
guideline when packing a lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin A: Just 1/2 cup of a deep yellow or deep orange fruit or
vegetable is packed with vitamin A. Possible choices: baby carrots,
cubed cantaloupe or dried apricots.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin B: You'll find this vitamin in whole grains, meat, nuts
and seeds. Pack two serving of grains or bread and some protein
every day. Possible choices: meat, cheese or peanut butter
sandwiches on whole-grain bread, pasta salad with cheese and kidney
beans, graham crackers, oatmeal-raisin cookies and sunflower seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin C: This vitamin and calcium are abundant in
calcium-fortified orange juice. Or try 1/2 cup serving of fresh
strawberries, cubed pineapple or citrus fruits. For calcium you can
try the dark, leafy green vegetables such as collard greens, kale,
mustard greens or turnip greens. If that's a tough sell, try 1 cup
low-fat milk or yogurt to get the necessary calcium. If you're
child eats a vegan diet, try calcium-fortified soy milk and tofu.
</P>
<P>
   - Sack lunch safety
</P>
<P>
   To keep your kid from trading lunches _ or worse, throwing it
away _ the Asceptic Packaging Council recommends the following
packaging tips:
</P>
<P>
   Keep foods fresh by keeping cold foods cold and hot foods hot.
Freeze drink boxes the night before and use as a cold pack.
</P>
<P>
   Peel fruit. Kids often don't eat fruit because it takes too long
to peel, like a first-grader confronted with an orange. Dip fruit
in lemon juice to retard browning.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap pickles in aluminum foil, and mold the foil into
interesting shapes. Do the same with tomatoes and lettuce to keep
sandwiches from getting soggy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're harried in the morning, make lunch the night before.
Or even freeze a week's worth of sandwiches ahead of time. Mayo
doesn't freeze well but butter and mustard work fine.
</P>
<P>
   - Homework for picky eaters
</P>
<P>
   The American Dietetic Association offers the following
suggestions to keep mealtimes from becoming a parent//child tug of
war:
</P>
<P>
   Offer choices of foods so kids can make their own decisions.
This also increases the likelihood they will be open to trying new
foods.
</P>
<P>
   Make foods fun. Cut sandwiches into fun shapes, offer vegetable
dips, ``hide'' bits of fruit in yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   Involve the child in food preparation. Even toddlers like to
help tear lettuce for salad or measure ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Stay calm when your child rejects what you've served.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, set a good example by allowing your children to see
you eat healthy foods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5918 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT &LR;      09-02 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBDUED CLINTON REITERATES HIS REGRET FOR HURT CAUSED BY LEWINSKY
MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Directly questioned for the first time in public about
the Monica Lewinsky matter since his televised admission two weeks
ago, President Clinton said at a Kremlin news conference Wednesday
that he believed he had expressed ``profound regret'' to those who
had been hurt by his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   While his remarks Wednesday amplified his previous statements,
the president again stopped short of issuing an outright apology
for the relationship or for lying about it to his family, his staff
and the nation. And Clinton reiterated that the investigation by
the independent counsel Kenneth Starr that brought him to this pass
was ``disproportionate'' to his alleged offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake, said that I
regretted it, asked to be forgiven, spent a lot of very valuable
time with my family in the last couple of weeks and said I was
going back to work,'' Clinton said, speaking at a joint press
conference here with President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that's what the American people want me to do, and
based on my conversations with leaders around the world, I think
that's what they want me to do and that is what I intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he was ``heartened'' by the reaction of the
American people and world leaders to his public admission on Aug.
17, the same day that he testified to the grand jury about
accusations that he had lied about the relationship and tried to
cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   But within the walls of the Kremlin, as Russia is seething with
political intrigue and economic privation, Clinton looked anything
but heartened by having to deal with the Lewinsky matter when he
would prefer to be conducting high-level diplomacy. Clinton's
demeanor during the news conference, which lasted 43 minutes _
indeed, throughout the two-day summit meeting in Moscow _ was
subdued, almost mournful.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, Clinton has come under heavy criticism,
much of it from members of his own party and political allies, who
said he was insufficiently contrite and overly defensive in his
public statements two weeks ago. Aides said he had been prepared
for questions about the Lewinsky matter at the news conference and
decided on his own to address them rather than rebuffing them as
inappropriate in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton's response Wednesday to the first question left many
in the White House press corps dissatisfied. At the next
opportunity, he was asked whether he regretted the bitter tone of
his statement and felt that he owed an apology to his family, his
supporters and the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried to avoid the question by jokingly echoing a curt
response by Yeltsin to a separate question about his prospects for
forming a government out of the current political chaos in Moscow.
But Clinton then gave a fuller answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the question of the tone of the speech, and people's
reaction to it, is really a function of _ I can't comment on
that,'' Clinton said as Yeltsin looked on alternately bemused and
bewildered by the spectacle in the beautifully restored Catherine's
Hall in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued, ``I read it the other day again, and I
thought it was clear that I was expressing my profound regret to
all who were hurt and to all who were involved, and my desire not
to see any more people hurt by this process and caught up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, elaborating on his combative words toward Starr, Clinton
added: ``And I was commenting that it seemed to be something that
most reasonable people would think had consumed a disproportionate
amount of America's time, money and resources and attention, and
now continued to involve more and more people. And that's what I
tried to say.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides offered no elaboration on the president's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this matter,'' said Michael McCurry, the White House press
secretary, ``the president obviously wants to speak from the heart,
and he did. He said what he wanted to say, and I don't think it's
the role of staff to try to amplify or comment further on his
remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor would McCurry or other aides provide the names of the
``leaders around the world'' who Clinton said had offered him
support and encouragement after his admission of an inappropriate
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and his misleading public statements
on it. Officials would not say whether Clinton's comments Wednesday
would be his last on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent some of the rare unscheduled time on this trip
making calls to the United States to gauge the impact of his
admission, a senior White House aide said. Other officials on the
trip have also been in contact with Congressional Democrats to try
to judge their mood as they return to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official who has worked closely with
Clinton at the summit meeting said he had seen no evidence that the
president was dejected over the Lewinsky revelations and the
critical reaction to his televised speech last month.
</P>
<P>
   The official said Clinton's somber mood over the last two days
reflected the turmoil in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious situation which does not lend itself to
laughter,'' the official said, speaking on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The official said Clinton's mental state had not affected his
ability to do his job. ``Not on this trip,'' the official added.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin did not comment on the questions about Ms. Lewinsky,
either in the news conference or in private meetings with Clinton,
American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of a liberal political party here,
said that many Russians sympathized with Clinton for the legal
problems he faced arising from the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at it in a more personal way,'' Yavlinsky said. ``We
don't take this juridical view.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
