<HEADER>
A5922 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-02 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECEPTION FOR CLINTON MAY BE COOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ In 1995, when Bill Clinton became the first sitting
American president to visit Northern Ireland, he was greeted on
both sides of the border as a hero and an independent broker who
would help propel the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received tumultuous welcomes in Belfast and Dublin then.
The day in Belfast was, according to Clinton and his senior aides,
the best day of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is a political settlement between Catholics and
Protestants in place for which Clinton has received substantial
credit. When he returns to Belfast Thursday, and when he goes south
to Dublin Friday, the welcome undoubtedly will be warm. But few
here believe it will be nearly as enthusiastic as it was three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dogged by the Monica Lewinsky scandal, and even more by his
decision to attack Afghanistan and Sudan, Clinton is tarnished,
even in Irish eyes. He will see in throngs of admirers a sprinkling
of vocal critics. Activists here are planning a series of protests
over the strikes which Clinton authorized in retaliation for the US
embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern Ireland, Clinton is scheduled to visit Omagh, the
town where 28 people were killed and 220 injured by a terrorist car
bomb on Aug. 15. While Clinton's display of sympathy to the victims
of the worst atrocity in Northern Ireland this century will likely
prove poignant, it will also provide uncomfortable parallels to the
American missile raids that, while directed at terrorists, killed
and injured civilians, too.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, only the fringe or the anonymous questioned Clinton's
involvement in the search for a political settlement, which was
reached last April and endorsed by an overwhelming majority of
people on both sides of the border in a May referendum. But now the
dissenting voices are more mainstream and more willing to be heard
publically. Among those leading the protests are Patricia McKenna,
an Irish member of the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two weeks, several letters have been published in
The Irish Times, widely considered Ireland's best and most serious
newspaper, drawing comparisons between what the dissident Catholic
group known as the Real IRA did in Omagh and what Clinton did in an
attempt to destroy the terrorist operations of the Saudi exile,
Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Molly O'Duffy, the chairperson of Comhlamh, a Dublin
organization of international development workers, said it is
hypocritical to ``quite rightly condemn punishment beatings by the
IRA while raising no voice against punishment bombings by the US.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omagh bombers killed 28. The US bombers killed 26. The
Omagh bombers, including the godfathers, receive our repudiation
and opprobium. The US godfather does not even have his invitation
to visit Ireland withdrawn,'' O'Duffy complained.
</P>
<P>
   Juliette Cunliffe, a Briton who is one of Comhlamh's leaders,
added that the Irish make up a disproportionately high percentage
of the aid workers in the Third World and are especially skeptical
of American claims that such bombing raids are surgical strikes at
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is civilians get killed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She compared the anti-Clinton sentiment today to that which
greeted Ronald Reagan when he visited Ireland in 1984. Reagan was
politely welcomed by most of the Irish, but he also provoked
protests over American policy in Central America at the time. The
Catholic bishops made public their contempt for US support of
right-wing dictatorships in the region. And even the Irish premier
at the time, Garret FitzGerald, gently rebuked US foreign policy in
a speech.
</P>
<P>
   But, like Clinton himself, the Irish bishops have been dogged by
a series of sex scandals and are no longer the political force they
once were in Ireland. The Irish government, meanwhile, is unlikely
to criticize Clinton, which Dublin credits with adding the
``international dimension'' necessary to push the peace process
along.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Irish diplomats make no secret of their dislike of
retaliatory air strikes that inevitably kill civilians. The Irish
have been among those who criticize Israel for similar actions. But
the Clinton administration is extremely popular with the government
led by Bertie Ahern, the Irish taoiseach, or premier.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments are indebted to Clinton. They
believe that without him and his appointee as Irish envoy, former
Maine senator George Mitchell, who chaired the peace talks, last
spring's political settlement would not have been reached.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky affair is seen here as embarrassing rather than
impeachable. Still, Irish officials worry that it will be used by
some to embarrass the president, and there have been some efforts
to minimize potential embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   In Ballybunion, the seaside town in rural County Kerry where
Clinton is scheduled to play golf on Saturday with Dick Spring,
Ireland's former deputy prime minister and foreign minister, a sign
was discreetly removed last week. Hung over a defunct hairdresser's
shop, it carried the name of the former hairdresser there: Monica.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern Ireland, most people will welcome Clinton to show
their appreciation of the White House's even-handed approach to the
peace process. Clinton has promised that US support will continue,
and he will urge more US investment in an economy that has been
sustained largely by $5 billion in annual subsidies from the
British government.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some dissident voices. Oliver Gibson, whose niece
was killed in the Omagh bombing, accuses Clinton of using the Omagh
tragedy to score political points. Gibson is a member of the new
Northern Ireland Assembly. But as a member of the Democratic
Unionist Party of the Rev. Ian Paisley, he was unlikely to welcome
Clinton under any circumstances. Paisley's hardline party considers
Washington biased toward Irish nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are others who are going out of their way to
welcome Clinton. The White House is especially appreciative that
the Sinn Fein leader, Gerry Adams, chose this week to acknowledge
that violence in Northern Ireland was no longer justified under any
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments, and especially Protestant
unionists, had been urging Adams and other political allies of the
Irish Republican Army to make such a statement. Adams' choice of
timing is seen as a gesture of thanks to Bill Clinton, who these
days is taking kind gestures wherever he can find them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
