u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-SINN-FEIN-53     09-02 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-SINN-FEIN-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINN FEIN AIMS TO TRY TO HALT ILLICIT ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ A day after declaring its commitment
to ending violence in Northern Ireland, Sinn Fein, the political
wing of the Irish Republican Army, announced Wednesday that it
would cooperate with efforts to plan ways to disarm paramilitary
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the eve of President Clinton's visit here, Gerry
Adams, president of the party, appointed the party's chief
negotiator, Martin McGuinness, to the independent international
commission on disarmament that was set up by last April's peace
settlement. He coupled that with an assertion that ``the issue of
arms must be finally and satisfactorily settled.''
</P>
<P>
   A product of the peace settlement, the commission is headed by
Canadian Gen. John de Chastelain and is charged with arranging
gradual disarmament of guerrillas over a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   While the IRA has maintained a cease-fire for 14 months, it has
resisted repeated calls from political leaders to indicate any
willingness to destroy or surrender its tons of Armalite assault
rifles, machine guns, AK-47s, Semtex explosives, rocket launchers,
homemade mortars and flame throwers hidden in underground bunkers
throughout the Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant opponents have seized on this refusal to challenge
the right of Sinn Fein members elected to the new Northern Ireland
Assembly to take up positions they are entitled to in the 10-person
cabinet that will run the province.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement did not reverse the IRA's stance, but
it signaled an interest by the clandestine force in the creation of
procedures for disarming, known as ``decommissioning.'' It also
added substantial momentum to the quickened political pace stirred
by Adams' statement of Tuesday that ``Sinn Fein believe the
violence we have seen must be for all of us now a thing of the past
_ over, done with and gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that a fight over Sinn Fein's role in the new Assembly
could imperil the peace process, the British and Irish governments
and the White House have been pressuring Adams to declare an end to
``the war'' and to agree to scrapping weapons. More than 3,200
people have lost their lives as a result of violence by warring
Catholic and Protestant paramilitary groups in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Ulster Unionists, the largest party in the
Assembly, welcomed both of Adams' statements, saying, ``This will
obviously be welcomed and seen as another step in the right
direction. They are obviously now reacting to the lobbying and
pressure from the U.S. government and others.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said both moves were a Sinn Fein initiative to use the
visit by Clinton ``as an opportunity to build dynamic into the
process, that the visit becomes a catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Maginnis, the Ulster Unionist Party's security spokesman who
generally condemns the statements and actions of Sinn Fein, said of
Wednesday's action, ``Every tentative step towards the
psychological hurdle of disarmament will be welcomed by the UUP.''
</P>
<P>
   David Ervine, spokesman for the Progressive Unionist Party,
which is linked to Protestant paramilitaries, said, ``As far as I
am concerned, if the IRA war is over, then the loyalist war is
over.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the political parlance of Northern Ireland, Protestants are
known as loyalists or unionists, reflecting their desire to remain
part of the United Kingdom and loyal to Britain, while Catholics
are known as nationalists or republicans because of their desire to
associate themselves more closely with the Republic of Ireland to
the south.
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, the party's leader and first minister of the
Northern Ireland Assembly, on Wednesday called on the leaders of
eight parties, including Sinn Fein, to attend a meeting Monday to
plan the opening of the new body Sept. 14. Though Trimble and Adams
were both negotiators and signatories of the peace settlement, the
two men have never spoken, at Trimble's insistence.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the accommodating statements of the past two days and
the presence in Belfast on Thursday of Clinton, an active party to
the Northern Ireland peace negotiations, there is still only a slim
expectation that Trimble will use the occasion to end his snub of
Adams.
</P>
<P>
   What would be a simple gesture in most societies constitutes one
of great risk for Trimble, whose leadership of the Protestant
community is subject to challenges from hardliners who accuse him
of being weak.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Democratic Unionists, the Rev. Ian Paisley, said
he would not attend the meeting on Monday. ``I am going to give Mr.
Trimble no cover to the dirty deed of getting IRA-Sinn Fein into
the government of Northern Ireland,'' Paisley said.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant leaders reacted positively Wednesday to the early
release from prison of two Scots guardsmen who had been serving
life sentences for shooting dead an unarmed 18-year-old Catholic
here in September 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted,'' Maginnis said. ``I have been campaigning
with others that they should be released. It is far, far too
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Protestant leaders angry over the releases of Catholic prisoners
in recent months had cited the case of the two soldiers as an
example of discrimination. Some 400 Catholic and Protestant
prisoners are to begin leaving prison next week under early-release
provisions included in the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The two soldiers, James Fisher, now 30, and Mark Wright, 25,
killed Peter McBride as he fled down an alleyway in the Catholic
New Lodge area of North Belfast. The soldiers argued that they
feared that he carried a weapon. But testimony showed that McBride
had minutes before been searched and found to be unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the British and Irish Parliaments returned to London
and Dublin Wednesday for emergency sessions to draw up
anti-terrorism legislation. The bills, expected to be rushed to
overwhelming passage, are aimed at members of dissident
paramilitary groups opposed to the peace settlement and bent on
disrupting it with violence. Among the targets is the Real IRA, the
renegade republican group that bombed Omagh two weeks ago, killing
28 people.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions of the bills under debate include one that would
make the opinion of a single police officer admissible in court as
evidence of membership in a terrorist group and another that would
allow courts to ``draw inference'' from a suspect's refusal to
answer questions about paramilitary groups. A third provision would
let the government seize assets used to support groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
