u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-BRAZIL-COX     09-02 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-BRAZIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market exceeds expectations of BellSouth in Brazil
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Brazilian partnership led by BellSouth has now grown to
535,000 customers for its four-month-old wireless service, company
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of the business _ with subscribers mostly
coming in the huge metropolitan area of Sao Paulo _ is a promising
sign for BellSouth's multi-billion-dollar bet on Brazil and Latin
America. For BellSouth, the region still promises a lucrative
payday down the road, despite the current global economic malaise,
said Charles C. Miller, president of BellSouth International.
</P>
<P>
   ``The explosive demand we are witnessing confirms and exceeds
our expectations for the Brazilian market,'' he said. ``And, as our
waiting list demonstrates, that demand shows no signs of slowing.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and its partners have more than 2.4 million customers
in nine Latin American countries. In Brazil, the 18 million-person
area of Sao Paulo has so far produced about 485,000 customers and
the company has a waiting list of 550,000.
</P>
<P>
   Two licenses _ one to serve Sao Paulo and another for the
northeast region around Recife _ cost BellSouth and its partners
more than $2 billion last year. The service has only been available
since the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The company made its commitment to wireless before last fall's
Asian currency crisis, which has deepened even as other economic
dominoes fall _ most recently in Russia. Latin America has thus far
avoided a serious downturn, although Brazil in the past year has
slashed public spending and cut loose thousands of government
workers. BellSouth did bid on only one license _ and lost _ during
the most recent round of auctions for wire-line phone companies in
Brazil. However, another round is coming up this fall.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street this week, BellSouth stock has bobbed like a
contrarian cork on the surf of the changing daily mood. Investors
rallied to BellSouth Monday when the market was plunging, shied
away Tuesday when the market rallied. Wednesday the market dipped
and BellSouth edged up 46.25 cents to close at $66.37 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   It is the strength of BellSouth's business in the Southeast _
coupled with the lack of investments in Asia and Russia _ that make
the stock attractive as a ``safe haven'' when the market is
tumbling, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
