<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-MYTHS-COX     09-02 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MYTHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Timing, and other myths of the market
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lesson for small investors in the stock market's
recent trading pattern: Don't try to time the market. You won't
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The wisdom behind this frequently offered piece of investment
advice has now been documented in a new study by analysts at
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the stock market has bounced back from a major decline,
gains have frequently been concentrated in a few days, weeks or
months. This makes it extremely difficult to `time' the market,''
said Jonathan Thomas, an analyst with the Smith Barney Consulting
Group and author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an investor tried to get out of the market on every drop,
he would miss the upside potential,'' Thomas said in an interview.
``The investor is trying to time the market twice: when to get out
and when to get back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas looked at 11 monthly losses by the S&AMP;P 500 index since
October 1987 _ the month of the market's biggest crash. Only twice
did the market fail to recover its losses within two months, and in
every case _ including the crash _ the market was back within six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, analysts have developed many schemes to ``time''
the market so an investor could be in stocks when they are rising
and out of the market when it is falling.
</P>
<P>
   That this can be done is, by almost universal agreement, one of
the myths of Wall Street. But there are others, as well as
messages, that investors can take from the recent selling. Here are
some of them:
</P>
<P>
   The myths and realities
</P>
<P>
   Myth: The stock market is a leading economic indicator, and the
economy will follow its trend.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: Maybe, maybe not. Economist Paul Samuelson once
observed that the stock market had predicted ``10 of the last five
recessions.'' The economy boomed in the year following the 1987
crash. Recessions are typically caused by high inflation and rising
interest rates, neither of which is a problem now.
</P>
<P>
   Myth: It's a new paradigm, the old rules no longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: Except that they do. By all accounts, the stock market
got overbought in the period of manic stock buying since 1990. If
the value of a stock is the future earnings of the company that
issued it,then people were eventually paying more for some stocks
than they were worth.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, savvy investors were certain to unload those
overpriced shares, which is what they have been doing since July
17, when the Dow set its all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   Myth: The big threat is that small investors will panic and sell
when the market tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: It may be too early to call this one, but the early
evidence suggests that small investors stood their ground. It was
the professionals who panicked.
</P>
<P>
   The Investment Company Institute says total assets in stock
mutual funds declined by $30.4 billion in July. That's a drop of
only 1.1 percent _ hardly a bolt for the door on the part of small
investors. To be sure, the August numbers will be more indicative.
</P>
<P>
   The market's messages
</P>
<P>
   Keep things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 10 biggest one-day point losses by the Dow Jones
industrial average occurred in 1997 and 1998, the other being the
Oct. 19, 1987, crash. But of the 10 biggest one-day percentage
losses, two were in October 1987 and the rest were in the 1920s and
'30s, with one in 1907 and another in 1899.
</P>
<P>
   Even a stopped watch is correct twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   Those bearish stock market forecasters who have warned for years
of impending disaster were bound to be right, eventually. Here's
what one market letter said in August 1995: ``We ... wouldn't be
surprised in the months ahead to see market corrections approaching
10 percent, with lightninglike plunges of 300, 400 or even 500
points taking place in just a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who got out of the market then, and stayed out, would
have missed the Dow's subsequent rise of 4,727 points, or 102.5
percent, to its recent high.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to keep the market's decline in perspective, but don't
get too casual about it.
</P>
<P>
   The recent loss was, in fact, staggering by any measure.
Monday's selling loss has been estimated at $2.3 trillion. Look at
it this way: Since the stock market added $12.5 trillion to
household wealth since 1994 (the Federal Reserve says), Monday's
sell-off took back 18 percent of that gain _ no small sum.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions really are important.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock market tanks in an economy that is still growing
_ with modest but rising profits, minimal inflation and falling
interest rates _ the selling has to come from a sense of fear on
the part of investors.
</P>
<P>
   The fear may be that stocks are headed for a crash, that the
Asian flu really will hurt the economy, that Russia's economic
problems will lead to political instability, that ... well, you get
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   What may be needed to turn investor psychology around is another
big event. A good candidate would be a cut in interest rates by the
Fed, but don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
