u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYCEUM-COX     09-02 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCEUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lyceum first in Atlanta to offer ADSL
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tiny Internet company on Wedesday beat BellSouth to the punch,
becoming the first in metro Atlanta to offer a speedy new
technology for faster transmission of data.
</P>
<P>
   Lyceum Internet, a six-year-old, 10-person firm, announced the
availability of ADSL _ which stands for asymmetric digital
subscriber lines. The service being trotted out by Lyceum, which
will pump data over regular phone lines, and compete right away
against other means of high-speed transmission like high speed T-1
data lines and Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) lines.
</P>
<P>
   ADSL is capable of transmitting data at better than 1.5 million
bits per second, as fast as a T-1 line. That's at least 30 times
faster than the fastest modems and 10 times as fast as ISDN.
</P>
<P>
   ADSL is also seen as the key rival to cable modems _ especially
among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Lyceum will first target businesses in Buckhead, expanding in
coming months to other areas, said Lindsey Crawley, company founder
and president.
</P>
<P>
   The foray into ADSL puts Lyceum ahead of the region's dominant
telecommunications company _ but probably not for long. BellSouth
is unveiling the service in New Orleans today and plans to unveil
the service in metro Atlanta Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Lyceum's version of ADSL will cost businesses between $400 and
$1,000 a month, depending on how fast a connection the customer
wants. Lyceum believes companies of 20 workers or more that need
fast links to the Net will see ADSL as a more sensible expense than
the other high-speed options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are going to complement what BellSouth is doing,''
Crawley said. ``They are a much bigger company and they will deploy
it on a bigger scale.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth will sell the ADSL service to Internet Service
Providers who will, in turn, market it to customers. BellSouth's
Internet unit is planning to charge residential customes $60 a
month for ADSL, plus a $100 installation cost and $200 for the
equipment, according to BellSouth spokesman John Goldman. Customers
that have the company's ``complete choice'' phone package would get
a $10 a month discount.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth had planned to offer ADSL to consumers by September,
but delayed the launch in order to study a proposal by federal
regulators that could reshape the way they do their high-speed data
business, Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Competition to BellSouth's ADSL will come from tiny players like
Lyceum and cable companies like MediaOne, Comcast and Charter
Communications. ADSL will also be offered by other Net companies
like MindSpring and America Online, and MGC Communications, which
this year started competing with BellSouth for local phone
business.
</P>
<P>
   An ADSL offering will proabably come by early next year, said
MGC Chairman Maurice J. Gallagher. ``The big mystery is how to
price these things.''
</P>
<P>
   ADSL also has some flaws, since not every phone line in every
home can handle the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
