<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-LAYOFFS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Northwest layoffs hit Hartsfield
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Northwest Airlines pilots strike hit Atlanta in a big way
Wednesday, but in the form of layoffs rather than travel
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   The grounded airline laid off 27,500 employees, including most
of the nearly 2,000 workers at its maintenance hangar at Hartsfield
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   An official of the International Association of Machinists,
which represents Atlanta mechanics, said all but 300 or 400 workers
were sent home until further notice. The bulk of the Atlanta
workers are mechanics, but they also include clerical, technical
and management employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a waiting game,'' said Dennis Isaacs, a
mechanic and spokesman for the IAM local. ``Some of the guys will
be looking for temporary work.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers can file for unemployment benefits next week.
Northwest said health benefits will continue through September.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot strike began Saturday. The impact on air travel has
been greatest in the Midwest, where Northwest has hubs in
Minneapolis, Detroit and Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which inherited the Atlanta hangar in a 1986
merger, had a small flight schedule at Hartsfield. Another airline
labor dispute may affect more Atlanta travelers this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Airlines and its flight attendant union are in
last-ditch contract talks through Friday. If they fail, the
Association of Flight Attendants is threatening spot walkouts that
would not shut down AirTran but would disrupt its schedule and
cause uncertainty for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran vows to maintain its schedule, in part by training gate
agents as substitute attendants and using fewer attendants than
normal if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots at Air Canada also went on strike after failed contract
talks, and that carrier canceled all flights including
Atlanta-Toronto service.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest layoffs could be followed by more today. In
Washington, the National Mediation Board called an ``exploration
meeting'' Saturday to bring airline and pilot union representatives
back to the table to identify areas of flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has canceled all flights through Monday and says it
will take eight to 10 days after a settlement to rebuild its
system.
</P>
<P>
   Other major airlines are accepting Northwest passengers if space
is available.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are deadlocked on pay rates, back pay and job
security provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes a strike, but it's not the pilots' fault,'' said
Isaacs, adding he believes mechanics firmly support the pilot
union.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the IAM is in the midst of its own contentious contract
negotiations with Northwest. It recently asked the mediation board
to declare an impasse, which would start the countdown to another
potential strike. The board hasn't yet ruled on that request.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
