A5932 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRIS-ROCK-TEX     09-02 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-ROCK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS ROCK THE FAMOUS IS THE SAME MAN AS CHRIS ROCK THE UNKNOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Rock might be ``the funniest man in America,'' but some of
us recall a rail-thin brother with a flattop fade, bug eyes and a
hearty appetite for racially inflammatory material. That was Rock
during his ``Saturday Night Live'' days, when he was just as sharp,
just as deep, just as promising, but when few would have noticed
had he left comedy and gone off to sell Slurpees at a 7-Eleven.
</P>
<P>
   That was before his HBO show, of course, and before he stole the
show in this summer's ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' and before those
ubiquitous (but funny) 1-(800)-COLLECT commercials. Still, it's
astonishing to Rock that he has suddenly been anointed as the
standard-bearer of comedy; that now we're all laughing and bowing
our heads to a comic who seems to have jolted us out of our
otherwise humdrum lives.
</P>
<P>
   Read deeply into his slew of magazine articles, watch carefully
during his TV appearances, listen closely to what he says and
particularly what he DOESN'T say, and you'll come away with the
image of a young blood who deserves to swagger but is still a
little shaken that the world finally woke up and said, ``Oh, I get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock believes he's the same cat who created Nat X, the
politically strident talk-show host on SNL; the same brother who
responded to death threats against Tiger Woods with, ``Oh, he knows
he's black now;'' the same sharp observationist who opened his HBO
special by dumping on Washington's beloved Mayor Marion Barry and
its Million-Man March by quipping, ``Even in our finest hour, we've
got a crackhead on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there are TV viewers unhip to an existing Chris
Rock talk show on HBO illustrates how under-the-radar Rock was just
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last season's ``The Chris Rock Show'' (the talker returns at
10:30 tonight with Johnnie Cochran) was a highlight reel of
enlightenment and laughs. (That Whoopi Goldberg tete-a-tete ranks
not only as my favorite interview, but tops among everything I
witnessed last season.)
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, this does include Jay Leno and David Letterman, who are in
such a fierce battle that their shows have become safe, bland,
boring and insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   With the leg room supplied by cable, Rock delves into territory
that Leno and Letterman are forbidden to touch, and I don't mean
playing fast-and-loose with obscenities. Cable plays to Rock's
strength as a conceptualist able to stay so firmly within the gray
areas that he's considered an equal-opportunity jokester.
Republicans think he's a Democrat, Democrats figure a Republican,
and black folks want to revoke his brother-down-for-the-cause
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing irked some blacks more than Rock's ``Vanity Fair''
article last month, with cover and inside photos showing him in
ashy white face. During an interview, Rock defends this by saying,
``I'm a comedian; it's a joke. Get over it,'' and later spewing a
few of those F-words to slam home the point.
</P>
<P>
   Rock and African-Americans have had a dicey relationship during
his anointment phase. It was fine when Rock's core audience was a
roomful of buppies, with whites merely invited to listen along.
Rules change when you're on mainstream magazines' covers and giant
cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   Black intellectuals, Rock is certain, don't like him, and have a
difficult time with comedy in general. They ``tend to overanalyze
show business,'' Rock says, ``and don't let the audience be an
audience. I mean, you have to be Dr. Martin Luther King in
everything you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedian D.L. Hughley, with whom Rock is collaborating on an ABC
sitcom due next month, says pretty much the same thing. He's
already in defense mode about perceived stereotypes in his series
about a black family's migration to the white suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that Rock's anointing began when he skewered
the Republicans at their 1996 convention as special correspondent
for Bill Maher's ``Politically Incorrect'' program, then on Comedy
Central. His most memorable dispatches came not in talking with
candidates but in his search for hair-care products, underlining
New Hampshire's less-than-diverse demographic.
</P>
<P>
   The metamorphosis was complete when Rock went off on the
difference between blacks and ``niggas'' in his now-infamous 1996
HBO special ``Bring the Pain.'' The black intelligentsia is sure
that's when white America decided to push him front and center,
seeing in him a black man saying what white folk want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Rock often appears irritated by the assertion that his
``acceptance'' means being brought along by a dominant culture able
to pick and choose its superstars. ``I'm no puppet for anybody,''
Rock says. ``Pleez, that would insult any comedian.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised with both parents in a low-income but established
Brooklyn neighborhood, Rock, 32, voices views that merely reflect a
childhood that was more conservative than many might think. Rock
often talks about the misconceptions about black Americans, meaning
not just media myths about welfare and crime, but also the
assertion that the average black person is a die-hard liberal when
it comes to, say, family values.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly out of the Rock context to ask on stage, ``Are there
any single parents in the house?'' and, if so, well, tell them to
go back home to their kids. Or to harp on some folks' acceptance of
antisocial behavior as legitimate black cultural differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me old school,'' Rock says, ``but I still believe that
individual merit counts for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, the Rock anointing coincides with a smarter, wiser
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no control over who I'm reaching,'' Rock says. ``I just
have control over the kind of work I do. I'm a comic. I make people
laugh. To say that black people are hands-off is ludicrous. To say
black people are untouchable, that they shouldn't be criticized, is
unproductive. Are you telling me there are no crazy black people? I
meet them all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks back, Rock was in Washington, D.C., to meet
with members of the National Association of Black Journalists, in
town for their 23rd annual convention. He came to boost a fledgling
undergraduate humor magazine he is helping finance at Howard
University.
</P>
<P>
   Rock talked proudly of wanting young black men and women to
think of comedy-writing, since that's where the money is. This
wasn't Rock the comedian, but Rock the brother down for the cause,
trying to stir some noise among the brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, he was talking to a group of black journalists far
more interested in their drinks and conversations. Rock talked
above the chatter for about 10 minutes before simply walking off,
frowning and groaning.
</P>
<P>
   Outside afterward, waiting for a car to whisk him way, the
anointed one shook his head, as if saying, I-told-you-so. ``Your
people,'' he says, looking off in disgust. ``Your people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
