<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIAN PREMIER DISMISSES DEPUTY WHO DIFFERED ON ECONOMIC
POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CAMBODIA-UNREST) 
(nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ In a swift and politically brutal move,
Malaysia's prime minister, Mahathir Mohamad, on Wednesday dismissed
his deputy and heir apparent, Anwar Ibrahim, who had opposed his
insular and free-spending economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, 51, who was seen as the standard-bearer for a new and
more liberal generation of Asian leaders, became the latest
political casualty of the region's economic turmoil _ this time the
victim of a backlash by the old guard.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to the government, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said he expected Anwar to be charged with sedition for
supposedly leaking government documents. Anwar was dismissed from
his posts as deputy prime minister and finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was told to resign,'' the informer said. ``He told the
prime minister, no way I'm going to resign. If you want to, you can
fire me and I'll defend myself in court.''
</P>
<P>
   The deputy was dismissed one day after the prime minister acted
to close off Malaysia's economy from the pressures of international
finance by making the currency, the ringgit, nonconvertible and
fixing its exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   These steps, in turn, followed the introduction in July of a
stimulus package that overturned Anwar's tight fiscal policies by
lowering interest rates and boosting government spending on big,
expensive projects.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Anwar was already on the political defensive, his
position severely undermined by what was, by Malaysian standards, a
lurid back-room brawl.
</P>
<P>
   For the last six years, Anwar had been the heir apparent to the
72-year-old prime minister and had developed a broad political base
of his own. While Mahathir was a leading advocate of authoritarian
``Asian values,'' Anwar appeared more in tune with the Western
liberal tenets of open markets and the free flow of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The odd but successful coupling of their differing styles and
philosophies became strained over the last year as the economy
soured and as Mahathir rattled foreign investors with his attacks
on currency speculators, neocolonialists and Jews, all of whom he
said were trying to ruin Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar was left to placate critics and at times to correct
Mahathir's statements, and his profile and popularity rose _
dangerously, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, at the annual general assembly of the ruling
party, Umno, Anwar's supporters tested their strength, bringing a
tentative challenge to Mahathir's leadership. One speech raised
accusations of corruption and nepotism _ code words drawn from the
opposition in Indonesia that successfully toppled former President
Suharto in May.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash was swift. The editors of Malaysia's two largest
newspapers, both allies of Anwar, were forced from their jobs. The
governor of the Central Bank and his deputy, also seen as close to
Anwar, stepped down in protest against the changes in economic
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's influence was severely undermined by the appointment of
his predecessor as finance minister, Daim Zainuddin, as a special
economic adviser to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   He was also politically wounded by a book filled with
unsubstantiated and sometimes fantastic allegations of sexual
impropriety titled, ``Fifty Reasons Why Anwar Cannot Become Prime
Minister.''
</P>
<P>
   He got the message and retreated from the limelight,
ostentatiously supporting Mahathir with statements like: ``Compared
to the prime minister I am just a student. I cannot fight my
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   But as in Indonesia and other nations suffering through Asia's
economic crisis, political maneuvering, even by a master like
Mahathir, is no longer enough. Economic hardships, often subject to
forces beyond national borders, can force political change, as they
have already done in Thailand, South Korea, Japan and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Malaysia announced that it had fallen into its
first recession in 13 years, with its economy shrinking by close to
7 percent after a decade of growth of more than 8 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The construction sector _ a key barometer of economic health _
was down by 22 percent in the second quarter of the year, compared
with 12 percent growth in the corresponding period last year, the
Central Bank announced.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide unemployment rose to 6.7 percent in a country that
until recently had to import workers to fill its needs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the currency has lost 40 percent of its
value against the dollar and the stock market has lost 75 percent
of its total worth. More than 2,600 people are losing their jobs
every week, according to the Human Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's announcement of new foreign-exchange controls,
the government Wednesday fixed the exchange rate for the ringgit at
3.8 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts said the moves might offer a short-term fix
but leave Malaysia with longer-term problems as investors steer
clear of an unpredictable economy. With reduced foreign investment,
they said, Malaysia is likely to have more difficulty reviving its
ailing banking system and pulling itself out of recession.
</P>
<P>
   With its economic and political hardships intensifying, Malaysia
began to move away from its months of pugnacious denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing reality now and saying the good old days will
not return,'' Daim said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
