<SLUG> BC-RASPUTINA-POP-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RASPUTINA': HARD ROCK, WITH CELLOS AND CORSETS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By JON PARELES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a world of rock bands, Rasputina is unique for its
combination of lineup _ three female cellists and a male drummer _
and costumes. At Shine on Tuesday night, the three women wore
corsets; two had elaborate lacy dresses, while the third proudly
displayed tattoos and a pierced lip.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed visual signals, part Marie-Antoinette and part metal,
carry over into Melora Creager's songs, which use the cellos for
punctilious chamber-music counterpoint and then switch to grunting
hard-rock chords, scraping the strings for distortion effects.
Above the cellos, she sings in a high voice with a metronomic
vibrato; between songs, she pouts, rolls her eyes and makes
pronouncements like, ``It was four score and seven years ago that
we last ventured out of doors to perform a recital.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, in other words, artifice aplenty; Rasputina and its
songs are mannerisms incarnate. But the songs are inseparable from
the mannerisms, existing in a zone of private obsessions and
associations. Ms. Creager writes about wayward characters and,
especially, women who have become grotesques, as in ``Transylvanian
Concubine,'' ``Leech Wife'' or ``Diamond Mind,'' in which she
trades her usual lifted-pinky tone for a heavy Long Island accent
to demand a diamond from her hapless mate while the cellos play
genial opera buffa lines. The songs are elaborate constructions,
like Gothic reliquaries, holding shards of emotion. Within the
Satie-like suspended chords of ``Signs of the Zodiac,'' she sings
to someone who's dying, ``Oh honey, I know it hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasputina is admirable for its sheer waywardness. Its peculiar
instrumentation and showmanship fit songs that putter around the
odd corners of 20th century life, quizzical and heartfelt and
comic. At Shine, they played Lesley Gore's hit ``You Don't Own Me''
as an encore, and they lived up to it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
