<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      09-02 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKIANS WIN BID TO SAVE CALUMET TROPHIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A grass-roots campaign in Kentucky to
save the Calumet Farm's racing trophies from being dispersed to
help pay the farm's debt was declared a success Wednesday when no
other bidders surfaced to meet the home-state bid of $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The treasures include 536 trophies, plates and julep cups and 40
paintings amassed between 1934 and 1982, when Calumet horses were
winning 148 stakes races and $26.4 million in purses. The spoils
were destined to be included in the estate's assets when the farm
went bankrupt, but a group led by James Bassett organized the fight
to keep them in their old Kentucky home. They have been enshrined
since 1982 at the Kentucky Horse Park in Lexington, where Calumet
Farm once spread over 900 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, banded as the Save the Calumet Trophies Committee,
raised $1.2 million in private donations from 44 states and three
foreign countries, plus $1.5 million from the state of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The New York auction house Guernsey established a deadline of
Aug. 31 for bids to be entered for the collection and, when it
passed Monday, nine inquiries had been made but no serious bids
were in sight. So, the committee's offer of $2.7 million was
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be done, it's part of our racing legacy,'' said
Bassett, chairman of the Keeneland Race Course and former chairman
of the Breeders' Cup. ``It would have been a travesty, a tragedy
and an embarrassment to the community, the state and the racing
industry to permit the dissolution of this magnificent
collection.''
</P>
<P>
   4 Months Out for Smith
</P>
<P>
   Mike Smith was still listed in fair condition but was resting
comfortably at Albany (N.Y.) Medical Center, and was expected to be
released Friday. But he will not resume riding for perhaps four
months.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old jockey suffered two fractured vertebrae in his
upper back when his horse was trapped in traffic during an
allowance race and flipped him into the hedges lining the grass
course at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``A body cast will be placed on him later today or tomorrow,''
reported Jim Smith, a spokesman for the hospital. ``He is still
lying on his back, but he's in good spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Edwin Cotto, the jockey whose horse started the chain
reaction of bumping that led to the spill, was suspended for 30
days by the stewards at Saratoga for ``grossly careless riding.''
He appealed the suspension, and was riding Wednesday, pending a
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away Off to Belmont
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Hine and Skip Away were back at their Saratoga barn after
their close call in the Iselin Handicap at Monmouth Park in New
Jersey last Saturday. But the trainer said his superstar horse was
``feeling good'' and would leave Thursday for Belmont Park to
continue his campaign for fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away, carrying 131 pounds, was forced to dig in and rally
in the homestretch to beat back Stormin Fever, who was carrying
118. The 5-year-old gray champion rallied just enough to win by a
nose for his eighth straight stakes victory and to raise his career
earnings to $9.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race didn't take too much out of him,'' Hine said. ``He's
actually fresh and ready to race. I think he will move forward from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hine said that Skip Away would resume training next Thursday for
the $500,000 Woodward at a mile and an eighth on Sept. 19. Older
horses carry 126 pounds and 3-year-olds, 121.
</P>
<P>
   Storms Cancels Saranac
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga has been blessed with a season of generally dry and
beautiful weather, but the good times came to an end late Wednesday
when thunderstorms with heavy lightning struck the area and flooded
the track.
</P>
<P>
   So, after keeping the horses for the ninth race, the Saranac
Handicap, waiting in the paddock until the lightning subsided,
track officials decided to cancel the ninth and 10th races in the
interests of safety.
</P>
<P>
   No replacement date for the Saranac was announced. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
