<HEADLINE>
AT THIRD WORLD MEETING, HOPES FOR CONGO PEACE RISE AND FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Hopes for a cease-fire in Congo were
quickly raised and as quickly dashed here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   First, all parties to the war appeared at the meeting of
Non-Aligned Nations here, including President Laurent Kabila of the
Congo, who flew in unexpectedly at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication of potential movement toward peace, the
U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, here for the meeting, scheduled
meetings with several of the leaders involved in the war.
</P>
<P>
   And Deputy President Thabo Mbeki of South Africa said twice
Wednesday that he was ``certain'' there would be a cease-fire in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But as the day wore on the few public remarks made by the
warring parties became increasingly belligerent and diplomats
seemed discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   President Sam Nujoma of Namibia, who has sent troops to Congo to
fight on the government's side, alongside those from Zimbabwe and
Angola, was one of the opening speakers at the meeting, and said
his men ``would leave when the job is done to the satisfaction of
the government of the Congo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust the summit will endorse this position,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila spoke late in the day, in the part of the program in
which 86 national leaders are each allotted seven minutes to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing Nujoma's slot, he spoke volubly, rapidly and in florid
prose, baiting the Tutsi and accusing the Rwandan and Ugandan
armies, his former partners in the overthrow of the Zairian
dictator, Mobutu Sese Seko, of assassination, rape and using
children as cannon fodder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I request from your august assembly an unequivocal
condemnation and a demand for the withdrawal of these aggressors
from our territory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their words were in stark contrast to the pacific tones taken by
the two senior statesmen at the summit, President Nelson Mandela of
South Africa and Annan. Annan referred to the Congo war in his
address, saying: ``My brother African leaders, I appeal to you once
again. We Africans must summon the will to resolve our problems by
political, not military, means. For every day that we fail to do
so, the innocent people of this continent pay a terrible price.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabila did not meet face-to-face with anyone from Rwanda or
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has dared suggest it,'' said Bin Karubi Kikaya, one of
his spokesmen. Instead, he met with a diverse list of summit
dignitaries, including Yasser Arafat of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In Congo itself, the capital, Kinshasa, was returning to normal.
Last week, a rebel attempt to move in on the capital failed, and
many of the attackers were captured and killed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, electricity was sporadic, as it has been in recent
weeks, and a curfew remained in force, but the roadblocks that had
filled the city for several days last week were almost all gone.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels still control the eastern parts of the country and
the central city of Kisangani, and are pushing toward the south.
</P>
<P>
   They claimed to hold Kalemie, near Lake Tanganyika, and to be
moving toward Kabila's birthplace, Moba, in Katanga province.
</P>
<P>
   The government said Wednesday that its troops had encircled the
rebels near the lake, but little is known about what is really
happening in the southern region because there are no sources of
information independent of the rebels and the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
