<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS MIXED IN SLUGGISH TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After two days of a frenzied selloff and a partial
recovery, stock prices were broadly mixed Wednesday in
comparatively sluggish trading Wednesday. But few analysts were
prepared to predict that the reverberations from the market's
recent steep slide have ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up more than 100 points
early in the day, building on Tuesday's 288-point gain. But the
run-up, coupled with a big drop in transportation stocks, persuaded
some investors to once again move to the sidelines as the closing
bell neared. The late selling helped push the Dow down 45.06 points
at the close, or 0.6 percent, at 7,782.37.
</P>
<P>
   ``From its lows on Tuesday to its highs Wednesday the market was
up 550 Dow points,'' said Al Goldman, chief market strategist at
A.G. Edwards in St. Louis. ``There was some buying fatigue, and
there were bound to be a few second thoughts after the blood
letting on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Broader market indexes also fell. The Standard &AMP; Poors 500-stock
index dipped 3.78 points, down 0.4 percent, to 990.48. The Big
Board's composite index slipped 1.30, or 0.3 percent, to 494.63,
</P>
<P>
   But the Nasdaq composite index posted a healthy gain, bolstered
by rising prices for favorites like Dell Computer and Cisco
Systems, as well as recently battered Internet stocks like Yahoo
and Amazon.Com. The Nasdaq rose 17.76, or 1.13 percent, to 1592.85.
The Russell 2000 index of small stocks rose 4.55, or 1.3 percent,
to 352.65,
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Tuesday's session, the busiest in its history,
trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange was relatively light,
with just over 896 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case on Tuesday, buying seemed to be concentrated in
sectors that have been severely battered since mid-July, when the
Dow peaked at 9,337. And while some said the steep decline had
brought equity prices down to more reasonable levels, analysts said
the market's problems are not over.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize that August of 1998 was the worst month
in the market since October of 1987, and one of the ten worst
months since the 1927 crash,'' said Richard Bernstein, chief
quantitative strategist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure we will have a firm grip on what is going on
here for another week or two, because things are still too
emotional for institutional and individual investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Cliggott, United States equity strategist at J.P. Morgan
Securities Inc., said that ``back in mid-July, the equity market
was priced for a perfect outcome. But we are not living in a
perfect world now. Still, the dramatic declines we have seen since
the peak has readjusted prices to the point where the market is a
more robust and resilient animal than it was in July.''
</P>
<P>
   After severely punishing financial service stock prices over
fears about third quarter earnings repercussions of trading losses
in international markets, including Russia and Asia, investors
began to move back into those stocks Wednesday. Cliggott said those
fears have been largely assuaged because firms have been timely in
informing investors where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of trading Wednesday, stocks of big brokerages like
Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Donaldson Lufkin
Jenrette all posted gains.
</P>
<P>
   Among major money center banks, Citicorp rose $2.13, to 108.75;
Bankers Trust was up $0.38, to $73.50; and BancAmerica was up
$1.25, to $65.75.
</P>
<P>
   Still, worries about the health of international economies
continued to plague any number of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which derives roughly 70 percent of its revenue and
75 percent of its profits from overseas operations, fell $4, to
$64.25. And Proctor &AMP; Gamble dropped $1.09, to $78.41.
</P>
<P>
   James Higgins, an analyst at Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette, said
concern about airline stocks with significant international
exposure was a big reason for the day's big 52-point drop in the
Dow transportation index.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of major carriers, which have sustained heavy price
declines since July, were hammered again Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Airlines fell $6, to $97.41. AMR Corp. lost $3.09, to
$52.09. And UAL Corp. dropped $1.13, to $61.88.
</P>
<P>
   Among important Nasdaq stocks, Dell Computer rose $1.88, to
$110.25. Cisco Systems closed at $91.63, up $1.63. But Intel fell
by $1.13 a share, to $74.88. And Microsoft dipped $0.34, to
$100.28. Yahoo surged 5{, to 77}, and Amazon.com rose 7 59/64, to
87~.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
