<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIAN POWER STRUGGLE ESCALATES OMINOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Cambodia's parliamentary election more
than a month ago was only the opening round in a struggle for power
that is pushing the nation toward a chaotic and possibly violent
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The newly elected National Assembly is scheduled to open in
three weeks, but that date now seems to amount to a deadline for a
face-off among three bitter rivals who split the electoral vote.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 10 days, thousands of protesters have filled a park
in Phnom Penh, putting up blue plastic tents, digging latrines,
eating banana-flower salad and prawn cakes and holding constant
rallies to denounce the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent strongman and official winner of the election, Hun
Sen, first threatened to evict them, then promised nonviolence, but
the protests carry an air of menace. Reporters listening to the
speeches stay at a safe distance on a nearby rooftop.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen's two challengers, Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Sam
Rainsy, who are usually bitter rivals, have joined forces to lead
the protests. They insist that they will block the formation of a
new government unless election irregularities are investigated.
</P>
<P>
   King Norodom Sihanouk _ the prince's father but not necessarily
his supporter _ has opened an attempt to broker an agreement, but
there is no sign now of compromise among the feuding politicians.
</P>
<P>
   When the final election results were announced Tuesday,
confirming the preliminary count released a month ago, they were
almost irrelevant. The battle lines had already been drawn.
</P>
<P>
   The official tally gave Hun Sen's formerly Communist Cambodian
People's Party the victory with 41 percent of the vote. Prince
Ranariddh's royalist party won 32 percent, Sam Rainsy's party won
14 percent, and the rest was scattered among 36 tiny parties.
</P>
<P>
   This outcome was a blueprint for unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the election was fundamentally acceptable, as some
experts have concluded, or whether it was fatally flawed by its
many irregularities, as others insist, its official outcome gives
nobody a convincing win.
</P>
<P>
   Under a complicated formula that is one of the chief issues of
protest, Hun Sen's 41 percent of the vote gives him a majority of
seats in the assembly: 64 out of 122.
</P>
<P>
   This falls short of the two-thirds needed to form a government
and means that Hun Sen must persuade at least one of his rivals to
join him in a coalition. But it is enough to prevent these rivals
from joining to form their own governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   If the formula was replaced by an earlier version, as the two
opposition parties demand, they would together have the majority
and could seek to form a government that excludes Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   They are also demanding a review of the vote tabulation, which
was controlled by Hun Sen's backers, and a new vote in the most
questionable districts.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen has invited both opposition parties to join him in a
coalition government but insisted on controlling all the key posts.
The man most likely to accept the offer is the Prince, who may be
using the protests to enhance his bargaining position.
</P>
<P>
   But a Western diplomat said the protests might already have gone
too far to allow the prince to back away from them and join Hun
Sen.
</P>
<P>
   The protests gained additional credence, even among some who do
not support them, when the National Election Committee and the
Constitutional Council that is the court of last resort _ both of
which are packed by Hun Sen supporters _ refused on Monday to
investigate the complaints of the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This leads some people, including some foreign diplomats, to
wonder if some funny things are going on,'' a European diplomat
said. ``Why is it so complicated to check back a few things and
defuse the protest?''
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts say Sam Rainsy, who is leading the challenges,
has failed to present a coherent and compelling case that the
accumulation of irregularities and intimidation are enough to
nullify the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The ``idealists'' here argue that even before it was held, the
election was invalidated by Hun Sen's ouster of his co-premier,
Prince Ranariddh, in a coup in 1997 and by scores of political
killings and a campaign of intimidation that followed.
</P>
<P>
   The ``realists'' say that the election, with all its flaws, was
as clean and fair as could be expected in a country torn apart by
violence for nearly three decades and that its official outcome
broadly reflects the will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Kassie Neou, a respected human rights advocate who resigned from
the election committee in protest last month, nevertheless
supported the outcome in a statement published this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skeptics were wrong about the Cambodian elections,'' he
wrote. ``Although marred to some extent by pre-election violence,
intimidation and lack of full media access to the opposition, the
elections themselves were conducted according to international
standards for free and fair polls.''
</P>
<P>
   He said charges of election irregularities should be
investigated, but added: ``It is vital that the Cambodian people
and the international community accept the election results as
legitimate. If not, there will be trouble ahead for the new
government.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cambodia does not have a tradition of good losers. Instead,
it has a tradition of bitter personal rivalries whose roots go back
decades. For many of the contestants, a democratic election here is
just one element to be exploited in these rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people who are caught up in such long-drawn-out
historical struggles and who don't have the means or the interest
to try to compromise,'' a Western expert with long experience in
Cambodia said, insisting that his name not be used. ``They are
impelled in good part by ego, and they keep struggling no matter
what the cost to the Cambodian people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 1952EDT &QL; 
