<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BREAST-TAMOXIFEN-     09-02 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-TAMOXIFEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PANEL BACKS APPROVAL OF BREAST CANCER DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cautiously opening the door to a new approach to lessening the
toll of breast cancer, an advisory panel Wednesday recommended that
the government approve the use of the drug tamoxifen for healthy
women at at high risk for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement was a tentative one, however, because of its
side effects and the lack of proof that the drug, sold as Nolvadex,
actually prevents the cancer, rather than just delaying it for a
short time. Specialists are still questioning whether the delay
offsets the danger from the side effects, which include a higher
risk of endometrial cancer and blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   Given these concerns, Boston specialists said they would not
rush to recommend tamoxifen for healthy women until more data is
available on its long-term benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even know who should get it,'' said Dr. Steven Come,
director of the hematology-oncology units at Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center. To address that problem, the National Cancer
Institute said it will soon make available at no cost a computer
CD-ROM _ known as a ``risk disk'' _ that that will help patients
and their doctors assess each woman's individual cancer risk and
guide the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory panel to the US Food and Drug Administration was
also expected Wednesday night to recommend approval of Herceptin, a
new-generation genetically engineered drug that offers hope to some
women who face a poor prognosis because their breast cancer has
spread.
</P>
<P>
   Herceptin, made by Genentech, Inc., of South San Francisco, is a
monoclonal antibody that shuts down abnormal growth signals found
in about 30 percent of breast cancer cells. In studies, the drug
has shown impressive results against advanced breast cancer when
combined with standard chemotherapy drugs like Taxol.
</P>
<P>
   Both Herceptin and tamoxifen had been given ``fast-track''
status at the FDA because of their promise in as new weapons
against breast cancer, which strikes more than 180,000 women each
year and kills about 44,000. The FDA usually follows the
recommendations of its advisory panels: final approval could some
before year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen, sold as Nolvadex by Zeneca Pharmaceuticals, has been
used for 25 years to treat breast cancer and has been shown to
sharply reduce the chances that a woman with breast cancer will
develop it in the other breast.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence that it can prevent a first cancer in healthy women
came in April, when data from the National Surgical Adjuvant Breast
and Bowel Project, a government-funded research study, showed that
tamoxifen reduced the risk of breast cancer by 45 percent, compared
to a placebo, in high-risk women.
</P>
<P>
   That trial was stopped early when the significant benefit became
clear, and critics said that made it impossible to tell how long
the preventive effect would last. Moreover, the study revealed a
slighly higher risk of endometrial cancer, and of thromboses, or
blood clots, in deep veins or the lungs in women taking the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Zeneca filed an application to market tamoxifen as a preventive.
</P>
<P>
   The drug acts by protecting breast cells from the
growth-stimulating effects of the hormone estrogen. In the national
study, women who took tamoxifen for five years had fewer breast
cancers, but none had been followed for more than three or four
years when the trial was stopped. Panel members argued that the
drug might only be delaying the development of cancers _ a benefit
that might not be worth the added risks.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leslie Ford, a cancer prevention official at the NCI, hailed
the panel's decision, saying, ``I think it's incredibly significant
that it's the first recommendation of a drug for reducing the risk
of breast cancer in a group of women known to be at high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether it matters whether you call it reduction
of risk or prevention,'' Ford added in a telephone interview. ``It
just depends on what time period you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCI has estimated that as many as 29 million US women have
the same level of breast cancer risk as the women who benefited
from tamoxifen in the study. Age _ being over 60 _ is the biggest
risk factor for the great majority of those women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is going to be a lasting benefit'' from
tamoxifen ``at least in a subgroup of women,'' said Dr. Irene
Kuter, chair of the breast clinical committee at Massachusetts
General Hospital. But she said that many women may opt to wait
until safer risk-reducing drugs become available. One of them,
called raloxifene, will be compared to tamoxifen in a trial
beginning later this year or early in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's decision on Herceptin appeared to be much more
straightforward, because the drug has proven remarkably free of
side effects and has brought a new kind of weapon to the treatment
of advanced breast cancer. Herceptin is the first of an expected
flood of drugs designed to attack specific molecules on cancer
cells while sparing normal cells from damage.
</P>
<P>
   In research trials reported last April, Herceptin combined with
standard chemotherapy halted or shrank cancer in 49 percent of
women with metastatic tumors, compared with 32 percent who had only
the chemotherapy. The responses lasted for an average of 9.3 months
in the Herceptin group, compared to 5.9 months in the chemotherapy
alone group. A small number of desperately ill women have had
long-term responses.
</P>
<P>
   Kuter at MGH said that in about a dozen patients treated
experimentally there, ``I've seen some pretty impressive
responses'' including one woman whose large tumors ``melted away.''
She is ``still doing fine'' after almost two years, Kuter added.
</P>
<P>
   Herceptin is in short supply, but Genentech has expanded a
lottery program to make it available to women whose cancer has not
responded to other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   If the FDA gives final approval to Herceptin this year, as
expected, Genentech will be able to expand production to meet the
anticipated market, said Marie Kennedy, a company spokeswoman, in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   She said the increased supply will make possible new clinical
trials to test whether Herceptin can be even more effective when
given at earlier stages of breast cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
