<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: DOWN WITH `DISABILITY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If in marketing parlance a used car is pre-owned, toilet paper
is bathroom tissue and the elderly are mature, why not bolster the
image of a provider of individual disability insurance by
describing its primary product as income protection plans?
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea behind television commercials and print
advertisements, scheduled to begin appearing on Monday, for
Provident Cos. Spending will total more than $10 million between
now and the end of the year with a planned annual budget of $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which carries the theme ``Protecting everything
you work for,'' is the first from Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in New York
since the agency was awarded the Provident account in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take the lead in educating consumers about this
form of insurance, for which there has been limited public
awareness,'' said J. Harold Chandler, chairman, president and chief
executive at Provident in Chattanooga, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mistake as an industry in not pursuing a broad
market,'' he added, ``by pursuing only a very narrow market segment
of the upscale and not professionals, managers and middle-income
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Provident's push to pitch makes sense because it is the largest
American insurance company specializing in coverage of doctors,
dentists and others who can't work as a result of injury or
illness. Stimulate interest in the product, the thinking goes, and
that will benefit Provident's sales.
</P>
<P>
   As for the use of income protection, Chandler said: ``We're poor
marketers as reflected by the name given the product. After all,
life insurance is death insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler provided a preview of the campaign at a meeting last
week in midtown Manhattan where he was joined by executives of
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   The term disability insurance ``in itself has been a
roadblock,'' said Jennifer Laing, chairwoman and chief executive
for the North American operations of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, a unit of
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   According to consumer research conducted by the agency with
psychologists, Ms. Laing said, the word disability ``conjures up
images of bodily injury and loss, which create feelings of fear,
concern and anxiety _ and talking about insurance in that context
gets you nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But re-express it as `income protection,''' she added, ``and
that's the best advertising route in. It means a paycheck, power,
protecting that which is important to you, giving you control,
independence, self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that the campaign is starting on Monday,
Labor Day, Chandler said, because Provident wants ``to celebrate
those we seek to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we are self-selecting those we think make good customers:
Those who honor work,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial shows rosy vignettes of office and factory workers
that would not have been out of place in a spot from the original
``Miller time'' campaign for Miller High Life beer or the campaign
for rival Budweiser that carried the theme ``For all you do, this
Bud's for you.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Provident commercial unfolds, an announcer intones: ``We
Americans have a funny thing about work. We actually like it. We do
a good job, even when no one is watching. We linger long after the
clock says to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we get much more out of work than a paycheck,'' the
announcer asserts. ``But the paycheck feels pretty good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is of course where Provident is meant to come in,
according to the spot, because with disability insurance _ sorry,
income protection _ ``if you're ever sick or hurt and can't work,''
the announcer says, ``the money keeps coming in along with any help
you need so you can get back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   People ``would rather be working than not working,'' said Tod
Seisser, chief creative officer at Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, adding:
``They define who they are by what they do. Certainly the people
we're talking to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   That is also addressed in the print ads. One, for instance,
carries this inquisitive headline: ``If you couldn't work, what
would you miss most? The camaraderie? The challenge? The
adrenaline? The paycheck?'' The text declares that `Most people
would say `All of the above.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another print ad asks ``What did you make at work today? A tough
decision? A hard sale? A better mousetrap? A paycheck?'' The text
reads: ``Whatever it was, keep up the good work. You're just the
kind of person that Provident income protection plans are designed
for.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are to run during ``60 Minutes'' and coverage of
football and baseball games and the U.S. Open tennis tournament.
The print ads are to appear in such consumer magazines as Fast
Company, Forbes, Inc., Money, Newsweek and Time as well as in trade
publications for insurance agents and benefit managers like
Employee Benefit News and National Underwriter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
