<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECESSION-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK PRICES RISE AND FALL, AND THAT'S THAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET, MARKET-BROKERS, MARKET-SMALL-TOWN) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are plunging stock prices a harbinger of economic crisis? Paul
Samuelson, the Nobel laureate in economics, once quipped that stock
market declines had anticipated nine of the previous five
recessions.
</P>
<P>
   That impish caution from decades ago has been updated by Peter
Temin, a colleague of Samuelson at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. After examining every recession this century, he
concludes that only a minor downturn, in 1903, was caused by
falling stock prices. Some recessions were caused by
anti-inflationary policies of the Federal Reserve Board. Others
were caused by external events, like the oil price shocks in the
1970s. Even the Great Depression of the 1930s did not stem from
plummeting stock prices. Chalk that horror up to persistent policy
blunders here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   History does not necessarily repeat itself. But the nearly
unblemished record is a sobering counterpoint to breezy speculation
this week about recession, rising unemployment and other economic
woes that could follow the recent plunge on Wall Street. On Monday,
the broad market gauge lost more than 7 percent of its value,
leaving it down nearly 20 percent from its peak in July.
</P>
<P>
   Though no forerunner of recession, stock market plunges can
nevertheless slow an economy. Consumers react to their shrunken
wealth by cutting purchases. Companies, fearful of uncertainty and
forced to issue a larger number of (lower-priced) shares to raise
any given amount of money, react by cutting investment outlays. It
is possible, then, that a stock market crash could tip an economy
into recession.
</P>
<P>
   But that leap would occur only after a sharp decline and then
only under certain conditions. A back-of-the-envelope calculation
shows why a stock drop the size of the one in the last couple of
weeks is unlikely to do serious harm.
</P>
<P>
   American stocks are worth about $10 trillion; in recent weeks,
their value has fallen about $1 trillion. Economists estimate that
consumers cut back spending by about 4 cents for every dollar of
wealth they lose. So a trillion-dollar stock market plunge would
cause about a $40 billion drop in annual consumer spending, about
one-half percent of total spending. Professor Benjamin Friedman of
Harvard University points out that it ordinarily takes a spending
cut four times that size to bring on a recession.
</P>
<P>
   A $40 billion cut in consumer spending could produce a downturn
in an already-stagnant economy. But this economy is strong, with
consumer spending and business investment growing briskly in the
first half of the year. Besides, consumers may not cut back
spending even as much as these estimates suggest because many might
not react to a drop in paper wealth from recent sky-high levels
they never regarded as secure. Consumers did not rush out the
minute the Dow hit 9,300 to order a new yacht, nor will they cancel
the family vacation because of a possibly temporary fall below
8,000.
</P>
<P>
   If the argument sounds Pollyanna-ish, consider what was wrought
by October 1987, when the market plunged by more than 20 percent in
one day. Main Street _ national output and jobs _ barely noticed,
though some regions, like New York City, were hit hard. The economy
is more resilient today than it was 11 years ago. Inflation,
interest rates and unemployment are low. Bank reserves are high.
The Federal Reserve could readily fight off recession by pumping up
the money supply without fear of igniting inflation or making other
smoldering problems worse.
</P>
<P>
   That is what the Fed, under its chairman, Alan Greenspan, did in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is one problem today that Greenspan did not face in
1987. Asia is mired in recession, and financial crises plague
Russia and threaten Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some economists and market watchers called this week for
the Fed to set domestic monetary policy with an eye toward the
plight of the country's trading partners, perhaps nudging rates
down even if the American economy needs no such help.
</P>
<P>
   Lower interest rates would ease the debt burden of foreigners
who have borrowed in dollars. Lower rates would also permit the
dollar to fall on foreign exchange markets, pulling down currencies
tied to the dollar. That would help those countries bolster export
sales. And, the argument goes, if a Fed easing helps Asia and other
beleaguered regions recover, then the United States will eventually
reap the benefit of trading with prosperous partners.
</P>
<P>
   But while it's easy to call on the Fed to take global factors
into account, federal law and good sense dictate that Fed policy
follow home-grown events. Friedman cautions against having the Fed
tailor its policies to foreign borrowing practices or exchange rate
policies. Professor Alan Blinder of Princeton, a former vice
chairman of the Fed, says the impact of Fed policy on foreign
economies is neither huge nor certain.
</P>
<P>
   Counting on Fed easing to help the domestic economy by
bolstering foreign economies is to rely on a speculative chain of
events that provides no sure guide to policy. Economists agree that
the Fed needs to factor foreign demand for exports into its
projections about the domestic economy. Blinder can imagine times
when the Fed would decide to ease because of weakness abroad even
though it was otherwise wavering between cutting rates and staying
pat. But almost always, the Fed's focus must be domestic needs
alone.
</P>
<P>
   The important point, on which monetary experts agree, is that
the Fed's monetary weapons are powerful enough to keep the American
economy in line, short of financial catastrophe abroad. The Fed can
pump up domestic spending by making it easier to borrow. Any
shortfall in foreign demand for American products can be offset by
additional American purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Doomsayers point out that plummeting stock prices could spook
the international currency and capital markets, leading to a
self-fulfilling pessimism among consumers and investors. From there
the story turns to worldwide downturn and even deflation
reminiscent of the 1930s. But few economists find that story
compelling. They point out that a lot of stock investments are tied
up in retirement and pension accounts and will not be dumped the
minute the markets turn sour. Besides, investors who lived through
the carnage in 1987 are secure they can ride out the next nosedive.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to exaggerate the impact of dramatic events like
this week's stock market volatility. But consider that even at this
week's low, stock prices were about where they were in January _
and well above the levels at the end of 1996 that Greenspan warned
were irrationally high.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, rather than soaring beyond 9,000 in July and swooning
to 7,500 in August, the Dow had merely moseyed its way on an even
track for eight months at what were widely perceived to be high
levels. Would any of us be wringing our hands over a recessionary
blow to the American economy that could reverberate across
international borders? Stock prices rise and fall and, as Samuelson
taught us 30 years ago, that's that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
