u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORPUS-THEATER-600&AMP;AD     09-02 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPUS-THEATER-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY THAT STIRRED OUTCRY PREPARES FOR ITS OPENING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About three months have passed since the Manhattan
Theater Club decided not to produce ``Corpus Christi'' by Terrence
McNally and then reversed itself after an outcry from artists and
civil liberties organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, printed postcards registering opposition to the play
have poured into the theater by the thousands, as have many letters
of support from the theater community, the public and Theater Club
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The theater recently announced the cast and began rehearsals for
the drama, which early reports said featured a gay, Jesus-like
figure who had sex with his apostles. In May, the theater received
anonymous threats of violence when details of the play's content
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The production, directed by Joe Mantello, is scheduled to open
on Oct. 13 at City Center in Manhattan. Previews begin on Sept. 22.
The cast is made up of mostly unknown actors, including Anson
Mount, who will play the lead character, Joshua, a gay man whose
life is traced from contemporary Corpus Christi, Texas, to ancient
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights, which
describes itself as the nation's largest Catholic civil rights
group and led the initial outcry against the production, plans a
protest at the theater on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of artists and representatives of civil liberties
organizations met recently to discuss how to respond to such a
demonstration and to consider approaching opponents of the
production about the long-term free-speech issues raised by the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Manhattan Theater Club is trying to say as little
as possible. ``To protect the privacy of the rehearsal process, and
given the nature of controversy surrounding this production, MTC
has agreed with McNally and Mantello to let the play speak for
itself and not to discuss the production process,'' the theater
said in a statement issued on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, the theater said it had hired Kroll
Associates, the private investigation and security company, as a
consultant and that the theater's representatives had met
``repeatedly with top officials of the NYPD, and have spoken with
the police commissioner, Howard Safir.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater declined to discuss its safety precautions in
detail, citing security concerns. In a note sent to subscribers
with their tickets, the theater said: ``Because of increased
security, you may experience some temporary inconvenience at the
theater during the run of the play. If you decide you do not wish
to see the play, we will promptly refund your money. If you choose
not to attend the play, please return your ticket to the
subscription office and do not sell it to a stranger.'' The theater
has also established a telephone number for people with questions
or comments: (212) 642-5929.
</P>
<P>
   For nonsubscribers, limited seats are available, the theater
said in the statement, and tickets go on sale Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the theater, Chris Boneau, said the principals
in the production declined to be interviewed. Some cast members did
not return calls and several have unlisted numbers.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the circumstances surrounding the
opening of ``Corpus Christi'' were sensitive, Boneau said that
theaters typically do not offer a look behind the scenes before a
play opens.
</P>
<P>
   For the opening night demonstration, the Catholic League said it
expected busloads of people from as far away as Baltimore and
Philadelphia, as well as nuns, priests and lay people from Long
Island. ``Hopefully we'll send a message that this is basically
unacceptable,'' said William Donohue, the league's president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A league spokesman said the organization planned to get a permit
for the protest and that police were aware of its plans.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue said that 45 national religious organizations _
associated with Catholics, Protestants, Jews and Muslims _ had
signed a statement condemning ``Corpus Christi'' and that he
planned to release the statement on Sept. 22. Although the league
objects to the play's content, Donohue said it is not seeking to
close it down. ``History has shown that an attack on one religion
may open the door to attacks on other religions,'' the statement
says, ``and that is why we call upon the good will of all Americans
to join with us in condemning this blasphemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, who said he had not been able to obtain a copy of the
play but had secured a ticket, emphasized that the league does not
promote or condone violent tactics. ``I think it is a very nice
tactic to point fingers at people going into a theater and yell,
`Shame, shame shame!' That's certainly something I'm going to
encourage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters of the play said the league helped stir up some
of the extreme reactions to the play in May, particularly with its
strong presence on talk radio. Donohue said, ``I'm not going to
take any responsibility for the excesses of some lunatic out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the larger issues of artistic freedom that some believe
are at stake, a small group of people involved in the arts and
issues of artistic freedom gathered recently to plan their
strategy. The group included the playwrights Tony Kushner and Craig
Lucas; Joan Bertin, executive director of the National Coalition
Against Censorship; Michael Roberts, executive director of the PEN
American Center; Amy Schwartzman of Volunteer Lawyers for the Arts,
and Ben Cameron of Theater Communications Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any sort of trouble, I think we have to be
prepared to respond,'' said Kushner, who called the meeting with
Lucas. ``It would be terrible to see this kind of pressure work in
New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to discussing a counter-demonstration, the group
drafted a statement it has yet to release about the principles
raised by the ``Corpus Christi'' matter and discussed the
possibility of organizing a dialogue between the opposing camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're eager to point out what's really at stake here is not a
religious issue but homophobia,'' Kushner said. ``Many Catholics
are not homophobic. The Catholic League does not represent those
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kushner encountered similar protests in response to his
play ``Angels in America,'' and the National Endowment for the Arts
has long been a target of attack, civil liberties experts suggest
that the theater world is largely unfamiliar with such combat. ``I
think people in the theater community are not used to this,'' Ms.
Schwartzman said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kramer, the playwright and author, said he believed that
the theater's initial decision not to produce the play might make
playwrights think twice before bringing their work there in the
future. ``Did it hurt Manhattan Theater Club in my eyes?'' Kramer
asked. ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lucas said that what mattered was that the theater
ultimately did the right thing. ``I would take my work to Manhattan
Theater Club,'' he said. ``The right wing often succeeds in getting
the left to fight with ourselves. I think we should stick together
and support each other. We have to know who the enemy is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
