r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIMBELL-DIRECTOR-TEX     09-02 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIMBELL-DIRECTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KIMBELL DIRECTOR IS BATTLE-TESTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Kimbell Art Museum trustees didn't hire
Timothy Potts as their new director because he shut down an
exhibition last year. They knew of the incident _ it involved
Andres Serrano's controversial photographs _ but they were looking
at his other credentials, which range from exhibition curating to
investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if anyone outside Australia or the art world has heard of
Potts, hired this month, it is probably because of the Serrano
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Potts' predecessor at the National Gallery of Victoria in
Melbourne planned the exhibit, and Potts knew it would be trouble.
Leaders of Melbourne's Catholic community had attempted to prevent
its opening, and Potts had been criticized for scheduling it
concurrently with a major Rembrandt exhibition. But how could he
know that Serrano's infamous ``Piss Christ'' photograph would be
attacked twice and ultimately destroyed by extremists who entered
as visitors?
</P>
<P>
   When that happened, Potts and his trustees considered their
options and chose the most radical. They closed the exhibition, not
as an act of censorship, but out of concern for the safety of staff
members and visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Potts was called a coward, and his decision was
described as a blow to freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing an exhibition is something no director or curator
wants to do,'' Potts said. ``Indeed, most people just try to avoid
the issue altogether and, in some ways, understandably. I didn't
have that option.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the circumstances it seemed the right thing, and I
still believe what we did was right. I wasn't about to put anyone's
personal safety at risk for any exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Potts was even more eloquent when he addressed freedom of
expression in an essay that can be found on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ``Was this not,'' Potts wrote, ``a backing down on an equally
unnegotiable point of principle _ the right of an artist and
gallery in a free society to show important art? No, it was a
decision to shift the battlefield to an arena where people's lives
would not be at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``Does anyone really believe that those who find
Serrano's work blasphemous will be persuaded otherwise by the NGV
turning itself into a fortress and toughing out the exhibition for
two months? If so, they confuse persuasion with defiance.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that last sentence that hits me, as a critic working in a
culture in which so much art is laden with provocative content,
content that seems intended to defy certain sensibilities rather
than work persuasively for change.
</P>
<P>
   Potts' handling of the Serrano exhibition confirms to me his
promise. It demonstrates his ability to make and stand by a tough
decision and to articulate the complexities of that decision, as
well as the larger issues surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   True, Potts is unlikely to add that to his resume, sandwiched
between ``Ph.D. in ancient Near Eastern art and archaeology'' and
``contributing art and book reviewer, he Financial Times, New York
and London.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was an accomplishment of sorts, one that the Australian
press duly noted along with Potts' fund-raising acumen and
expansion projects, in its Page One reports of his resignation.
True to their barbed, tabloid-style approach to journalism, the
Australian media pointedly criticized Potts as much as they faintly
praised him for making Australia's oldest and largest museum its
most popular, as well.
</P>
<P>
   And in doing so, they managed to make Potts' departure sound
quite disastrous _ a possibility that he discounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that things will grind to a halt with my
departure,'' he said. ``We have very good senior management here,
and trustees. Life will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   And in October, Potts will go on: He'll leave Melbourne and come
to Fort Worth with his family. And, once in Fort Worth, he seems
certain to make a beeline for the Kimbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very keen about getting my feet under the desk there,'' he
said. ``So at that point, I don't think wild horses could keep me
away.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
