<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXECUTIVE-PAY-ART-2TA     09-02 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTIVE-PAY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN AND ASIAN EXECUTIVES START TO GET U.S.-STYLE PAY PACKAGES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on executive pay in U.S. and Britain is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rose Gerrit Huy was a fast-rising executive at Daimler-Benz AG,
the German industrial giant that makes Mercedes-Benz automobiles. A
Harvard-educated economist, she was in charge of developing cars
like the SLK roadster before she was promoted to head the company's
finance and telecommunications subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Ms. Huy, 43, quit Daimler after 11 years to
become Compaq Computer Corp.'s managing director in Germany. Not
that her Daimler salary was skimpy, but the Texas-based computer
maker offered something that could catapult her into vastly greater
riches: stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Huy would not disclose the size of the options package that
lured her away, but these numbers provide a clue: While the
chairman of Daimler holds a form of options worth less than $1
million, the options of the Compaq chairman are worth more than
$188 million at last count.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two decades, even as the global economy has
demolished national barriers to trade and investment, the executive
pay gap between America and the rest of the world has widened
dramatically. While American executives were loading up with stock
options, restricted stock and other compensation intended to align
their interests with those of shareholders, their counterparts
overseas continued to collect only salary and modest bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   That is largely because the political cultures of many European
and Asian countries recoiled at the idea of lavishing vast riches
on capitalist chieftains for a single year's work. Many Europeans
were left aghast by pay packages like the $49.9 million that
Travelers Group chairman Sanford Weill collected in 1997, or the
more than $556 million that Walt Disney Co. chairman Michael Eisner
made in 1997 by exercising fewer than half of his stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, that attitude is changing, albeit slowly. To stem a
drain of executive talent to their American rivals, big European
and Asian corporations have begun pressing their governments to
modify securities laws and accounting practices that discourage
jumbo pay packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the world is moving to our pay model,'' said Kevin
Murphy, a University of Southern California finance professor and a
leading expert on worldwide executive pay. ``Maybe that movement is
out of efficiency, maybe it is out of greed _ we don't know which
yet _ but the trend is clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Japan revised its commercial code to
allow stock options. Already, 160 companies, including Sony, the
entertainment and electronics concern, have adopted option plans,
according to Bob Buford, a compensation specialist with the
consulting firm Towers-Perrin in New York, who has worked with many
Japanese companies.
</P>
<P>
   The invasion of American-style pay plans, including stock
options, is uneven in Europe, specialists say: faster in high
technology, like telecommunications and software, and slower in
manufacturing and heavy industry. But it is having a big impact
wherever it is found, and the recent turmoil in global stock
markets, although it may have cut the value of some compensation
packages, is unlikely to have any long-term effect on equity-based
pay.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the Netherlands and Australia, a few companies have
started adding options and other forms of equity to executive
compensation packages, a practice that the British began widely
adopting in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany last month, a court earlier upheld a form of stock
options that Daimler offered two years ago to 170 executives, a
pool it has since expanded tenfold, while also increasing the size
of its still-modest option packages.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Doell, a partner in Frankfurt with the executive-search
firm Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, said that two years ago Ford Motor Co.
extended its American pay levels to its operations in Europe, and
immediately lured two top executives from Volkswagen. Ford is now
fishing for lower-level managers using the same bait _ stock
options _ and this has increased the pressure on the German auto
industry, one of the slowest areas of German business to adjust, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is now moving to the U.S. model because it works
very well for shareholders,'' said Steven Kaplan, a finance
professor at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options give the holder the right to buy shares at a given
price over a specified period, usually 10 years. If the stock
surges, the holder can exercise the option, sell the stock at a
much higher price and pocket the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Even in America, where it is the most widespread, the practice
is controversial, especially when poor-performing executives walk
away with multimillion-dollar payoffs either because their stock
has been held aloft by the bull market or because the exercise
price has been reset downward.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the criticism, other countries are embracing the
practice. In London, Paul Hodgson, an editor at Income Data
Services, which tracks executive compensation at British companies,
said that the ``only difference is in the size of pay, not the
components, which are going toward the U.S. style.''
</P>
<P>
   While options in Britain have tended to be modest, Unilever PLC,
the British-Dutch household-products maker, and Marks &AMP; Spencer
PLC, Britain's largest retailer, are moving toward American-style
mega-grants.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, including SmithKline Beecham PLC, the drug
concern with major operations in London and Philadelphia, and Four
Seasons Hotels and Hilton International, a unit of Ladbroke Group
PLC, the multinational lodging companies, have made all or parts of
their compensation packages identical regardless of where an
executive is stationed.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation experts call such plans ``global pay.''
Translation: pay on an American scale.
</P>
<P>
   These experts say global pay eliminates internal tensions that
arise when, say, the home office executives in Brussels or Osaka
make less than their subordinates in Chicago or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity in pay between American companies and the rest of
the world came into sharp focus in May, when Daimler agreed to
acquire Chrysler Corp., whose No. 2 executive made more last year
from salary, bonus and cashing-in options than the top 10 Daimler
executives combined.
</P>
<P>
   Both Daimler and Chrysler have told shareholders that the new
DaimlerChrysler will have separate pay plans for executives in
Stuttgart and in Detroit, an indication that it does not plan to
quickly equalize pay. But Daimler is also planning to ask
shareholders to approve a new equity pay plan, said Daimler
spokesman Roland Klein.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robert Eaton, the No. 2 Chrysler executive, predicted that the
highest German and American executives at DaimlerChrysler would
someday be paid similarly. ``We have to be competitive,'' Eaton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Kay, a partner in New York with Watson Wyatt Worldwide, said
that in recent years, foreign owners have begun to adopt long-term
incentive pay, including small grants of options, which he saw as
signs of how foreign-owned companies were moving closer to
American-style pay. By paying executives with equity, American
companies have performed better than those overseas, Kay argues in
his book ``CEO Pay and Shareholder Value: Helping the U.S. Win the
Global Economic War'' (St. Lucie Press, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Gareth Williams, an international pay expert in the Chicago
office of the consulting firm William M. Mercer, said that in five
years or so there would be many ``global executives who will not be
hamstrung by their location'' and who would earn global pay that is
heavily dependent on stock options and other forms of equity-based
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   The trend to raising the compensation of executives at
multinational companies to the levels in the United States has
encountered all sorts of opposition _ even from the very executives
who stand to benefit from it. Alan Johnson, a compensation
consultant in New York, said many European and Asian executives he
has worked with showed an obvious distaste for huge options
payouts. ``I have been surprised that it is not just a legal,
wake-up-and-smell-the-money issue,'' Johnson said, ``but it is
deeply rooted in their culture and views that you just don't seek
unlimited money.''
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to the United States, Commerzbank chief executive
Martin Kohlhaussen stunned an American banker recently when he said
he owned no Commerzbank stocks. ``What makes you tick?'' was the
American banker's response. Commerzbank chief economist Ulrich Ramm
said Europe was moving toward American-style pay, but added: ``It's
done here with more sensitivity than in the United States, with all
the exaggerations there. Here you try to spread it a little more
broadly.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson predicted that like Daimler ``most companies will change
in baby steps.'' He added, ``It will take a decade or so to get
like the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the slow pace, in the view of John England, a
Towers Perrin executive-compensation specialist in Brussels, is the
greater responsiveness of European companies to stockholder
concerns. When Daimler's original options plan for its executives
came under attack from an investor, for example, England said that
Daimler modified its option grants. ``You never see a U.S. company
do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's high income-tax rates can make perks like cars,
chauffeurs, gardeners and lifelong health benefits as big a draw as
options. And European tax laws discourage companies from making
bountiful options awards by treating them as a cost on the
corporate balance sheet rather than as a deduction on their taxes.
As a result, European stock-incentive plans are often watered-down
versions of their American counterparts. For example, what Daimler
calls ``options'' are more like what Americans call convertible
debentures.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Daimler plan, executives use after-tax money to buy
securities that pay about 4.4 percent interest for 10 years and
give the right to convert to stock at a fixed price once the shares
have risen 15 percent. The plan limits the 170 top executives to a
$120,000 investment a year, pocket change for American chief
executives, while senior managers can invest only $30,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Foley, an executive compensation lawyer in White Plains,
N.Y., said that requiring executives to buy into their equity, what
he called ``putting some skin in the game,'' might lower resistance
to American-style pay plans in Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Buy one, get two' sounds a lot better than giving
something'' away free, as most American stock-option plans do, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Graef Crystal, the editor of an executive-compensation
newsletter who once designed executive pay plans, took a more
jaundiced view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virus,'' he said, ``is now spreading around the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
