<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-ART-     09-02 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA KEEPS TROOPS IN RIOTING PROVINCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ After two days of riots and looting by mobs
in a northern province, the Indonesian military halted its
withdrawal of troops from the region Wednesday in an effort to
restore order.
</P>
<P>
   The army sent several thousand fresh troops to Lhokseumauwe, a
medium-sized industrial city in the province of Aceh, where mobs
set on Chinese-owned shops on Monday and Tuesday. Two people were
killed and at least 10 were wounded when security forces fired into
a rampaging crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face is an embarrassing setback for the military,
which had portrayed its withdrawal as a conciliatory gesture toward
Aceh, a predominantly Muslim province in North Sumatra with a
fervent separatist movement. Rather than applaud the retreating
soldiers, the Acehnese pelted them with rocks.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday witnesses said a tense calm hung over Lhokseumauwe,
with no reports of mob violence. But the rest of Indonesia has been
rattled by the most serious eruption of unrest since the riots in
May in Jakarta that left 1,200 people dead and precipitated
President Suharto's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the powerful military is at the eye of the storm. In
a report Wednesday, the National Commission on Human Rights accused
the military of conducting a campaign of terror against the people
of Aceh since 1989, when Suharto sent in combat troops to quell the
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military operations do not have to lead to human rights
violations,'' the vice president of the commission, Marsuki
Darusman, said. ``This was a situation where people were terrorized
and intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Human Rights Commission dug up mass graves in
Aceh that it said contained dozens of victims of army killings. The
commission estimated that more than 750 people had died at the
hands of soldiers in the occupation of Aceh for the last nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Darusman presented the full report on Aceh, which
accuses the military of a catalog of crimes, including summary
executions, torture, rape and sexual assault. ``We're recommending
that the officers and soldiers who served there be brought to
justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report has no binding authority on the government. Indeed
senior military and government officials have been openly skeptical
about the claims of widespread violations of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the report is the latest installment in what has become a
grim excavation of the military's role in Suharto-era Indonesia. In
July the commission said that the army had stood by as gangs raped
hundreds of ethnic Chinese women in the riots in Jakarta. And in
April the panel said security forces might have played in a role in
the kidnappings of several political activists.
</P>
<P>
   The barrage of accusations has put the military in an extremely
awkward position. On the one hand it is trying to fashion a more
benign image for itself in the post-Suharto era. Last month the
army discharged Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto, the fiery son-in-law of
Suharto who spearheaded many of the military's less savory
adventures, including its occupation of East Timor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the other hand the army seems unwilling to be held
responsible for every atrocity in Suharto's 32 years in power. Last
week the chief of the armed forces, Gen. Wiranto, said that claims
that the military had shot hundreds of people in Aceh were
unconfirmed. And this week he said that the military had found no
evidence of mass rapes in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Darusman said the denials were fomenting unrest in places like
Aceh, where people already view the army with deep suspicion.
``There is a sense that the riots are more a reaction to comments
made in Jakarta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some people here said the army might have instigated
the disorder in Aceh as a pretext to remain there. Witnesses said
the worst violence broke out in Lhokseumauwe on Tuesday, the day
after the last convoy of 659 troops had left the military
headquarters. Although people threw stones at the soldiers, they
saved their real fury for Chinese-owned stores, restaurants and
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto announced that he had ordered troops to return to Aceh
after a Cabinet meeting here Wednesday. ``It is the responsibility
of the armed forces to carry out its duty in safeguarding the whole
nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the new president, B.J. Habibie, the mayhem in Aceh could
jeopardize his campaign to resolve regional conflicts that began
under Suharto. Habibie has made progress in talks with Portugal
over East Timor. The withdrawal of troops from Aceh was to have
been another old wound healed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
