<HEADER>
A5981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-BROKERS-ART-71     09-02 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BROKERS-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BROKERAGE STOCKS FALL VICTIM TO FICKLE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER TRUELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shares of Wall Street brokerage firms have been battered in
recent weeks, in some cases falling more than 40 percent, suddenly
becoming pariahs after months, even years, when they were among the
market's darlings.
</P>
<P>
   So is this an opportunity for the smart, hardy investor to
profit, or would buying mean throwing good money after bad?
Analysts' answers to that depend on their views of the overall
market. If the market stabilizes and builds on its fledgling
recovery, brokerage-firm stocks might offer handsome opportunities,
but if the market's slide continues, they might best be left alone,
according to Wall Street wisdom on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been beaten down far more than the damage to date
would justify,'' said Raphael Soifer, bank analyst at Brown
Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co., the New York brokerage firm. ``For those
people interested in a recovery play, the brokerages are safer than
the banks,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank earnings are economically sensitive, while brokerage
earnings are market sensitive,'' said Soifer, who, like many
analysts, is recommending the stocks of bigger and more diversified
brokerage firms such as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co. Those, like the group as a whole, rose Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch edged up 56.25 cents, to $67.8125, still down 37.9
percent from a high of $109.125 on July 13. Morgan Stanley advanced
$1.375, to $59, down 39.5 percent from its high of $97.50 on July
21.
</P>
<P>
   But, Soifer added, some investors may prefer to wait and see
whether the current market turmoil represents a correction or a
full-fledged bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, they were the best-performing group in the S&AMP;P
index,'' said Sallie Krawcheck, who follows brokerage firms at
Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co. Now, she added, ``lack of earnings clarity,
as well as absolute fear'' has made these stocks one of the
worst-performing groups in the recent downdraft. For some, she
added, citing Morgan Stanley, ``it seems to be overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Krawcheck said she had cut her expectations for Morgan's
third-quarter earnings by 10 percent to 15 percent, yet the stock
has plummeted almost 40 percent. ``That's overdone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities depend on your market view,'' Ms. Krawcheck
said. ``If one expects Latin America to roll over next, then, no,
they are not a buy. But if you expect a stabilization, then they
are a buy.'' The recent widening of credit spreads has particularly
hit Wall Street's bond and high-yield debt businesses _ where firms
like Lehman Brothers and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette have had to
mark down the value of their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman gained $2.50 Wednesday, to $42.125, just less than half
its high of $85 on July 13, and its price-to-earnings ratio is an
extraordinarily low 6.68, compared with 13.83 for Merrill and 12.45
for Morgan. Donaldson, up $1.75, to $34.125, is down from a high of
$63.75 on July 13 and has a price-to-earnings ratio of 9.89.
</P>
<P>
   At Donaldson, with its big high-yield business, Ms. Krawcheck
expects earnings of 31 cents a share for the three months ending
Sept. 30, compared with $1 or more in each of the first two
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, forecasting brokerage-firm revenue in a rapidly
changing market is tricky when it is not clear what the effects
will be on volatile businesses such as junk bonds and
emerging-markets securities. ``We have opened up a box that history
says causes quite a lot of difficulty in forecasting revenue
flows,'' said Sam Liss, a managing director at Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some are still confident that now is the time to
buy. ``Goldman did a call to clients this morning,'' said Richard
Strauss, a brokerage-firm analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``We came
out very bullish. We have lowered our numbers,'' for estimated
profits, ``but only very mildly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the best vehicles for playing the rebound are Morgan
and Merrill,'' he added. ``For the most part, our estimate
revisions were less than 5 percent relative to a 40 percent
correction in these stocks.'' Goldman, of course, is planning its
own multibillion-dollar initial public offering, and its market
strategist, Abby Joseph Cohen, has produced some of the most
bullish stock-market forecasts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   However, there is little hope that the rapid consolidation among
financial-services firms might soon resume and help buoy stock
prices of brokerage firms. ``Most buyers are scared,'' said one
Wall Street financial adviser who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. He added that more mergers of brokerage firms were
unlikely until there was a lot more pain on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mergers have to be willingly done in this business,'' said
Soifer, who cautioned that otherwise a brokerage firm's most prized
assets _ its people _ would leave. And, he added, brokerage firms
``have to have gone through quite a thin time, enough of a thin
time for their credit and counterparty risks to come under
attack,'' before they would willingly contemplate a merger. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
