A5983 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-EDITORS'NOTE-T     09-02 0197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-EDITORS' </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS' NOTE FOR STAR-TELEGRAM HEROIN PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 NOTE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note:
</P>
<P>
   As heroin streams into Texas from Mexico by every means
imaginable, the mechanisms of law enforcement appear to be
outmatched. Everyone, from federal agents, military officials and
police to judges and probation officers, struggles against the
momentum of multibillion-dollar trafficking organizations.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as part of the Star-Telegram's intensified coverage
of heroin abuse, we examine the battle that federal, state and
local authorities are waging on heroin trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of us is touched by the war on drugs, which consumes
billions of tax dollars each year. Lawmakers are facing crucial
decisions on whether to escalate the battle with more resources,
more staffing and tougher laws. But with each new effort to stop
heroin and punish those who sell and use it, traffickers counter
with their nearly unlimited resources, their constantly shifting
strategies and increasing violence.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
