<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5988 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-02 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAKED TRUTH ABOUT THE CITY COUNCIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Were it not for the time-consuming and costly efforts
of Phoenix City Council, the good citizens of our community would
have no concept of the important work performed for us by people
like ``Jesse.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't realize it myself until shortly after noon Wednesday,
when the young thin woman took her first slow steps onto the stage
of The Jungle Cabaret in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   She strolled lazily past the kind of artificial waterfall you
might have constructed for the seventh grade science fair _ and
gotten a C _ then continued past the statue of a lioness.
</P>
<P>
   She stopped and turned, looking over her shoulder toward an
audience she probably couldn't see.
</P>
<P>
   It was dimmer than midnight inside the place, with only
occasional flashes of light, as if the room were being illuminated
by a distant thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of so patrons sat around small tables below the stage.
</P>
<P>
   None of them took note of Jesse's entrance, although it had been
announced by the amplified voice of a disc jockey shouting over the
opening strains of Prince's ``Little Red Corvette.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse wore high-heeled shoes and enough of a bathing suit to
make a slingshot, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The men seated before her had an uninterested air about them.
Perhaps it was ignorance. My guess is they hadn't attended the City
Council meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If they'd been there, they'd have been more appreciative. They'd
have understood the enormous civic obligation someone like Jesse
must carry on her wispy shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The disc jockey seemed to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on boys!'' he shouted. ``Don't be shy. Put your hands
together.''
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   One man in a white shirt and tie did approach the stage. Jesse
leaned over him, placed her hands on his shoulders and let her hair
brush against his face. Then she pulled the string of her bikini
away from her hip, just a little, while he slipped a dollar bill
under it.
</P>
<P>
   If the council has it's way, such exchanges will be carefully
monitored, particularly the touching part, which will be legal only
during the moment the money is exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but Council wants to subject the members of
Jesse's profession to the kind of rigorous licensing requirements
and background checks usually reserved for police officers or
public school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a sideshow,'' said Councilman John Nelson. ``This
is a very serious issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It must be.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, why would our politicians spend so much of their time
and so much of your money studying the work habits of women like
Jesse?
</P>
<P>
   Why would they then devise new forms of license and regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Why would they commit the resources of law enforcement and
government bureaucracy to enforcing them?
</P>
<P>
   If Council gets its way, dancers in places like The Jungle
Cabaret will be made to obtain a special identification card.
They'll be fingerprinted and run through crime computers. They'll
go through a more rigorous screening process than it takes to get a
driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   To work in retail selling weapons.
</P>
<P>
   To advise the ignorant on ``nutritional supplements.''
</P>
<P>
   To baby-sit.
</P>
<P>
   When the top of Jesse's bathing suit dropped to the floor, it
wasn't gravity that did it, but the weight of her responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Why else would government be so interested in a person whose
background _ and foreground _ become a matter of public record
every fifth of sixth song during the average lunch hour?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Jesse's occupation has tremendous community value.
If not, if it wasn't worth a damn, it would be like all the
professions that require no fingerprint taking, no background
check, no nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapering, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   And politics. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
