<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton has offered Russia moral support but no financial
help. Sounds like what we used to get from our parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people,'' Mr. Clinton says, ``very much want
Russia to succeed.'' As long as we don't have to listen to
political speeches about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the future of Russia,'' says Mr. Clinton. No
doubt he wishes he were as certain about the future of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Russians need to know, says the president, there are no
``painless solutions.'' Unfaithful husbands, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says Russia should ``reject the failed policies of
the past.'' As he himself did when he decided to tell the truth
about Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The president says one reason for his trip to Russia is to
``tell them that the easy thing to do is not the right thing to
do.'' That's a sermon he might have done well to preach to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems that develop beyond our borders,'' Mr. Clinton says,
``sooner or later find their way to our doorstep.'' Where they must
compete for attention with home-grown problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe our fundamental economic policy is sound,'' the
president says. But some days it sounds like a scream of someone
jumping off a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nation will ever have a monopoly on ideas,'' says Mr.
Clinton. True. Bad ideas come from everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   September is nature's way of reminding everyone that there are
parts of the world where it's already too late to send Christmas
presents by ship.
</P>
