<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5998 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-SUMMIT-ART-NYT     09-02 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUMMIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LINKS TOUGH REFORMS TO MORE AID FOR RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on Clinton's itinerary is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton signaled Wednesday that the West
would step up its aid to Russia if the Kremlin pressed ahead with
tough economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   His message, intended to encourage Russian President Boris
Yeltsin's government to stick with its capitalist-oriented course
despite the nation's deepening economic crisis, capped a two-day
summit conference dominated by a collapsing ruble and a government
that has been paralyzed by its battles with an emboldened Communist
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the reform process can be completed, then I for one would
be strongly supportive of greater assistance to Russia from the
United States and the other big economic powers,'' Clinton said
during a joint news conference with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Russia recently negotiated a $17 billion bailout with the
International Monetary Fund, of which $4.8 billion has been
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   But the financial turmoil that has rocked the Yeltsin government
has led the United States to think about further steps to speed and
expand Western assistance.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials do not have a detailed plan of just how much
additional aid might be provided and where the funds would come
from.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has told his aides that the United States should be
prepared to lead a new international aid effort, which could draw
on the Group of Seven industrialized nations and on international
organizations such as the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a clear movement toward reform, I'll do everything
I can to accelerate outside support of all kinds,'' Clinton said,
echoing assurances that were also provided in private meetings with
Yeltsin, according to Clinton's aides.
</P>
<P>
   Providing further assistance to Russia is far from a popular
idea within the U.S. Congress and among some U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides said that giving Russia billions in new aid would
be a small price to pay if it would help keep Russia's young
democracy on a reform course and prevent the rise of an
anti-Western regime.
</P>
<P>
   However, they stressed that fresh assistance would only be
provided if the Kremlin demonstrates it has the political will not
just to talk about reforms but to carry them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely critical for the well-being of the United
States for decades to come that Russia not lurch backwards,'' a
senior U.S. official said. ``But we have also made it clear that
Russia needs to take steps to insure that the money that is here
stays here and does not leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Russia can summon the determination to put its economic
house in order, however, is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Yeltsin vowed to proceed with economic reforms and
reappointed Boris Fyodorov, an aide who backs a strong free-market
policy, as deputy prime minister. No sooner was Fyodorov officially
restored than he began talking about tough measures to stabilize
Russia's battered currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need from the United States is political support,
support for Russian reforms,'' Yeltsin said. ``Then all investors
who want to come to the reformed Russia will come.''
</P>
<P>
   However, few believe that gestures alone will accomplish this.
For example, Yeltsin still lacks a prime minister, leaving in doubt
the Kremlin's overall commitment to economic reform and its ability
to garner support for its policies.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's current choice for prime minister, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, was decisively rejected by the Communist-led
parliament Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another vote on Chernomyrdin's nomination is scheduled for
Friday, but his opponents say he sure to lose again.
</P>
<P>
   A third defeat would result in the dissolution of the
legislature and in new parliamentary elections, according to
Russia's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent a major escalation in the Kremlin's tug of
war with the Communists. But it is far from clear whether the
politically and physically weakened Yeltsin has the will for the
fight. Wednesday, he dodged a question on his commitment to
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say Yeltsin appears to be pondering whether he
should abandon Chernomyrdin for a new candidate like Konstantin
Titov, the reform-minded governor of the Samara region; Yegor
Stroyev, the head of the upper house of parliament and a Yeltsin
ally; or Yuri Luzkhov, the powerful Moscow mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The delays in forming a new government have also put off the
economic decisions that are needed to extract the nation from its
crisis and regain credibility with the West.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF, for example, was scheduled to decide whether to
distribute the next $4.3 billion installment of its loan by
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Fischer, the fund's number two official, said that the
IMF would be unlikely to take up the matter before October, if not
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what we know now about the changes in the exchange rate,
of course difficulties in the banking system, possible difficulties
in the budget, it's clear that the Russians will have to do quite a
lot before that money could be released,'' Fischer told Cable News
Network program ``Moneyline.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer's timetable clashed with the Clinton administration's
promise to try to accelerate aid, pointing to the confusion in the
Western ranks about how to help Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But without a new government in place even Yeltsin's biggest
boosters found it difficult to make the case for speedy help.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the addled Russian political scene, Wednesday's summit
meeting was more substantive than many observers had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration scheduled the summit conference,
hoping to promote Russian ratification of START-2 strategic arms
treaty. It soon found the START-2 issue issue overtaken by the rush
of economic events.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two leaders signed arms an accord to sharing missile
warning data, a measure to lessen the chance of an accidental
nuclear war. They also agreed to begin disposing of bomb-grade
plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his sessions with Yeltsin to encourage him to stay
the economic course.
</P>
<P>
   During his meeting with opposition politicians Wednesday,
Clinton tried to persuade Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov of the
need to play by the rules of the free market. There was no sign
that Clinton made any headway on that score _ or in persuading the
Communists to cooperate with Yeltsin. However, some opposition
leaders said that Clinton did the right thing by coming.
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Yavlinsky, the leader of the liberal Yabloko party, said
many Russians appreciated that President Clinton had gone through
with the summit conference, despite the nation's latest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right idea to come,'' he said. ``Clinton was a
brave man to come to Russia in the conditions we are in now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
