<SLUG> BC-CRATE&AMP;BARREL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRATE &AMP; BARREL ROLLS INTO PHOENIX AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN CRENO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - After 35 years of running the show at Crate &AMP; Barrel,
Gordon Segal could call it a career.
</P>
<P>
   He could shop for some nice beach furniture, find a quiet
stretch of sand and spend some time watching the waves. He could
live the life people dream about when they buy Powerball tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not his idea of a good time. Segal, 59, still has the
same verve for retailing that got him into the business of selling
housewares in a bare-bones store that used packing crates and
barrels as merchandise fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking to build a chain of stores. I wasn't looking
to go public and make a killing. I had none of those motivations 35
years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some neat product for cooking and dining that wasn't
available in the United States, and we thought it would be fun to
bring it here and see if we could sell it and make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel turned out to be a very neat way to make a
living. From its start in an old elevator factory in Chicago, the
company has expanded to 77 stores in 15 U.S. markets plus a catalog
business that is both a moneymaker and a marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   Its next stop is Scottsdale Fashion Square in Scottsdale, Ariz.
The store there will anchor a mall extension that connects to a new
Nordstrom store across the street. The mall is getting Crate &AMP;
Barrel's top-of-the-line format, the combination housewares and
furniture store that the company puts in showcase spots like
Madison Avenue in New York and Michigan Avenue in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel was a big catch for Fashion Square. It took 10
years of talking by the mall's owner, Westcor Partners, to make the
deal for a store that Biltmore Fashion Park in Phoenix also
aggressively pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel's entry in the Valley was delayed by a couple of
things. The company had other markets it wanted to get into first,
and Segal said it wanted a spot where it could put one of the
combination stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very much looking at the Biltmore at one time and
thinking should we put it there,'' Segal said. ``But when you had
to think of where would you put one store, we felt this was more
near the core between Scottsdale and Phoenix. It was a hard
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35,000-square-foot store opens Sept. 18, along with
Nordstrom and about 50 other shops and restaurants. The store's
first floor will be furniture, and the second will be housewares.
The furniture floor has street access for shoppers who don't want
to walk through the mall.
</P>
<P>
   The layout is designed to look light and airy; it has a large
staircase, as well as crating wood on the walls, a reminder of the
company's first store in Old Town Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The store itself, even without the product, is going to be
beautiful. It's just going to show off the product beautifully,''
said Terri Kail, the Scottsdale store's housewares manager.
</P>
<P>
   The store will be loaded with what Segal said is the sort of
out-of-the-ordinary merchandise that Crate &AMP; Barrel strives to
find: cookware, glassware, dinnerware, gadgets and the casual
furniture that Crate &AMP; Barrel sees as a big part of its identity as
a destination for shoppers who no longer want to live in
off-the-rack homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has gotten more sophisticated,'' Segal said.
``People want nicer things for their homes. After you get to a
certain level of having enough of everything else, you start
focusing on your home and how you furnish it and how you build it
and decorate it.''
</P>
<P>
   The retailing landscape is packed with companies trying to cash
in on the home craze. Besides traditional furniture stores, there
are superstores like Linens 'N Things and such specialty retailers
as Restoration Hardware, Williams-Sonoma and Pottery Barn.
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel thrives by pushing to find merchandise that no
one else has and selling it for what Segal said are ``fair-value''
prices. Attitude also is important. Crate &AMP; Barrel first looks for
nice people when it's hiring, then drills them on merchandise and
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay humble; stay nervous'' is the company's motto.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retail, you're only as good as your last transaction,''
Segal said. ``You really don't have a chance to make good if you
screw up too many times with customers. People are more demanding,
and they're more critical, and there's more competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel is a private company and doesn't release detailed
financial information. Segal did say the company expects to ring up
sales of $480 million in its current fiscal year, which ends Jan.
31.
</P>
<P>
   Catalog shopping accounts for 8 percent to 10 percent of Crate &AMP;
Barrel's business. The company uses the catalog primarily as an
advertising and marketing tool and plans to jump into Internet
retailing this year.
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel recently expanded its store at Park Meadows, a
Denver-area mall, to add furniture to its housewares offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Beaudry, the mall's marketing director, said the expansion
made the store even more popular since the area, like the Valley,
is in a home-building boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're building the new home,'' she said. ``It's 2,000 square
feet. You need to fill it. Or you're working from home. And people
are doing more entertaining. It has to do with people spending more
and more time focused on their home.''
</P>
<P>
   Kail thinks that shoppers will warm up to the Scottsdale store
quickly and that the company will want another Valley location in a
couple of years. She's worked for Crate &AMP; Barrel for 10 years and
has been involved in the management of four stores, unusual loyalty
in a business where turnover is common, sometimes rapid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the company,'' she said. ``I love what it sells. It's
an extremely fun place to work. I enjoy coming to work every day.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Segal says.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three decades, he still is a cheerleader for the
business, still loves to get into the stores and still gives his
trademark pep talk to the staff of every new store before it opens
on its first day of business.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't sound like a guy headed for the beach any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much enjoy this business,'' he said. ``I work at it
very hard. I very much enjoy my people. I enjoy the projects we
undertake. I enjoy the product we sell. Yes, I'm very involved. I
don't play golf. I work at my business five, six days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started it with enthusiasm. We've still got it. The day we
lose it we should get out of it. It's too hard if you're not
enthusiastic, if you're not having fun. It's a hard business.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glen Creno can be reached at glen.creno(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
