r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-DEALER-TEX     09-02 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-DEALER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALER SAYS HE SOLD TO FEED HIS ADDICTION
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALTOM CITY, Texas _ Like an evangelist, Jason M. spread his
gospel about heroin to stoke its sale to his friends and their
buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good, man. You gotta try this,'' he would tell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would glamorize it, and I didn't let them know what it would
do to them,'' the 21-year-old Haltom City man said. ``I was a
dealer; I didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason estimates that his sales pitch hooked at least 30 people
during the four years that he pushed heroin in Northeast Tarrant
County before he entered a court-ordered treatment program.
</P>
<P>
   On two occasions, Jason filled a syringe with black tar heroin
and injected it into the veins of friends who were first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never put the needle in their arms,'' said Jason, who
asked that his last name not be used. ``Guess what I did? And I've
got to live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason was never arrested on heroin charges. But the threat that
he could get caught didn't deter him because, like most
street-level heroin dealers, he was just as hooked as his
customers.
</P>
<P>
   His only criminal conviction was for marijuana possession. Even
as he was standing in a Fort Worth courtroom being sentenced last
year, the pager in his pocket was vibrating to alert him that a
customer was waiting.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the courtroom, he paid a fine, took the first of
12 urine tests that he subsequently failed and climbed into his
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   He drove to a nearby drugstore, where he bought syringes. From
there, he headed for a club in Dallas, where he had arranged some
sales. Before he got there, Jason made sure that he found his own
steady stream of black happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason first, that was my philosophy,'' said the green-eyed,
soft-spoken father of two young children.
</P>
<P>
   Jason began doing methamphetamines and smoking marijuana when he
was 12. He dropped out of school in sixth grade. By 17, he was
doing heroin.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, he said, he had someone injecting cocaine in one of
his arms while someone else sent heroin coursing through the veins
of his other arm.
</P>
<P>
   Jason began dealing heroin to feed his $300-a-day habit.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling in the money, he said, had as much allure as getting
enough junk to pump into his veins. He cleared $3,000 or more a
week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of money fosters a mentality that precludes any 9-to-5
employment efforts, said Dennis Longmire, a criminal justice
professor at Sam Houston State University in Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not unlike white-collar criminals. It's hard to tell
somebody that can make a million on a bank job that they need to
continue their $52,000-a-year job,'' Longmire said. ``The same kind
of thinking takes place with these street dealers. Most are young,
rational, most weigh the consequences with the alternatives, and to
them it makes a lot more economic sense for them to deal heroin.''
</P>
<P>
   From the time Jason awakened until he called his day done, he
was busy filling the needs of his customers.
</P>
<P>
   He replenished his supply every three days or so, getting as
much as 4 ounces of black tar heroin at a time from a supplier in
south Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted the help of others to distribute it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fronted out my dope so I wouldn't have to sit on it,'' Jason
said.
</P>
<P>
   When users dialed his pager, they punched in their telephone
numbers before adding a numerical code to identify themselves to
Jason. Then they added numbers for the quantity of heroin they
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, I could decide whether I wanted to mess with it,''
he said. ``I had plenty of clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Clients who wanted to buy a large quantity _ 15 capsules or more
of chiva, a powdered form of black tar heroin _ went to his home.
For smaller sales, Jason hopped in his Chevrolet S-10 pickup and
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Jason packed a pistol when he went on delivery rounds for fear
of being robbed, although he never was. He used only ground
telephones, avoiding cellular and cordless ones that can be
monitored on police scanners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had dope on me, I'd be real paranoid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the back of his mind, he said, he always knew that his
grandfather could get him an attorney on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   But after he left the area and failed to report to his probation
officer, he was ordered into a 120-day substance abuse program in
Mansfield. During his four months in the residential program, he
got counseling and passed a high school equivalency examination.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hasn't felt the opiate course through his veins in
almost six months.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Jason says he has a plan for his future. Foremost, he
yearns to be with his children on their birthdays. He would like to
become a welder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a want to learn now,'' Jason said. ``I never had
anything but the desire to do my dope.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to help others who are battling drug abuse,
perhaps through counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hurting people for so long, I feel I owe people,''
he said. ``I never cared back then what I was doing to people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
