<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6002 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOBOYZ-MOVIES-2TAK     09-02 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOBOYZ-MOVIES-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MILLER LITE TO THE MAKING OF MOVIES LITE? 
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (af) 
 By MICHELLE WILLENS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Taking up a whole page in Daily Variety recently
was a story about a young six-man Swedish advertising team known as
Traktor that had been signed to direct a feature film in the United
States. (Albeit a small one by Hollywood standards, a mere $10
million.)
</P>
<P>
   The article explained that Traktor's ``idiosyncratic
sensibilities'' had been applied to some 200 commercials. The
group, it seems, directs in pairs, giving it ``the good benefits of
being four eyes,'' the piece went on to say.
</P>
<P>
   While Traktor readies its first feature film, ``Shiny New
Enemies,'' Hype Williams, 29, will be putting the finishing touches
on his, the urban thriller ``Belly.'' The film will be released in
November by Artisan Entertainment, a production company that beat
out heated competition to nab Williams, a music video director who
is considered as good as it gets in that arena.
</P>
<P>
   And so you might ask, is this what getting to direct a movie has
come to? Win an award for a Miller Lite spot or a Sean (Puffy)
Combs video, and you're this close to a six-picture package?
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that anyone could produce a movie: all you
needed was money, the ability to hire good people and very good, or
very bad, taste (as long as you were consistent). But to direct one
you surely needed concrete experience, every John Ford and Preston
Sturges move at the ready and a proven ability to handle actors.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that was then but maybe not now, when a new generation of
aspiring movie makers are getting incredible opportunities based
largely on razzle-dazzle. And when overnight successes like the
brothers Peter and Bobby Farrelly (``Dumb and Dumber'' and
``There's Something About Mary,'' which together have so far earned
$150 million) are flaunting their lack of knowledge and style
rather than kissing the studio grounds on which Billy Wilder once
walked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all supplicants in today's film world, and there's a
deplorable tendency to assume the audience's attention span of a
gnat and to look for those who can play to that,'' said the veteran
producer David Brown (``Deep Impact''), whose career spans three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Dare we call them the gnat pack? Long on visual, short on
content and complexity. Are they responsible for the potholed plots
and one-dimensional characters prevalent in mainstream movies?
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bay, the young director behind ``The Rock'' and
``Armageddon,'' is surely the scapegoat of the year, a fact that
many of his own contemporaries think is unfair and studio
executives seem perfectly willing to ignore. The latter are already
seeking out the next Bays, hoping these directors have the pulse of
American moviegoers who have grown up with the remote control and
the sound bite _ and that their high-voltage style can attract a
worldwide audience that seeks nonstop action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoping'' is the operative word here: ``It's probably true some
of these young directors will be great at transferring from
commercials and videos to movies,'' said Gareth Wigan, a co-vice
chairman of Columbia Tri-Star Motion Pictures. ``But a music video
has two and a half minutes to tell a story, and the question is,
How do you hold a story for two hours?''
</P>
<P>
   Amir Milan, the president of Artisan Entertainment, acknowledged
the risks, but believes that ``the possible rewards are greater.''
``These guys think with their eyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a long list of those with the thinking eyes, including
Mark Romanek, Spike Jonze, David Fincher, Mark Pellington, Scott
Kalvert, Williams, F. Gary Gray, Brett Ratner, Paul Hunter, Kevin
Kerslake, Gary Fleder, Adam Bernstein and Michele Gondry.
</P>
<P>
   A few have arrived, most notably Fincher (``Seven,'' ``The
Game''), whom many point to as the ideal model, the anti-Bay if you
will. A modern young man but one steeped in film lore, with style
and ambition to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the real deal,'' said the longtime producer Art Linson,
who is working with Fincher on his newest film, ``Fight Club,''
which stars Brad Pitt. ``He may come out of music videos and
commercials but those were always stepping stones for him; he knows
everything about the movie-making process. I'd call him the
wonderful exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell if he is the exception or if the others can also
do more than just bring in da noise. The director William Friedkin
(``The Exorcist,'' ``The French Connection'') asserts that the gnat
pack _ many of whom cite him, along with his 70s contemporaries
like Francis Coppola, Peter Bogdanovich, Martin Scorsese and Hal
Ashby as role models _ far surpasses its elders technically,
largely because of the instruments at its disposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the X factor, which is inspiration, even genius, can't be
acquired with a Steadicam or the latest gadget,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Genius may or may not come, but in the meantime their technical
prowess is often being sought not only to please restless youth but
also to compensate for mediocre material. Begging the question:
could the sinners of today's cinema instead be the saviors?
</P>
<P>
   When Gary Fleder, 35, who had made commercials and the 1995
independent film ``Things to Do in Denver When You're Dead,'' was
approached by the producer David Brown about directing this year's
``Kiss the Girls,'' he was looking at pretty standard stuff. Still.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my chance to do a genre film like `Klute' and `Cape
Fear,' and I wanted to see if I could succeed,'' said Fleder, who
got to work with the stars Morgan Freeman and Ashley Judd. ``I
tried to turn a pretty conventional story unconventional, making
the point of view less the killers' and more the good guys'. More
of a psychological, 70s-style thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin said, ``He made a very familiar story about serial
killers that we all thought we'd never want to watch somehow
watchable.'' Similarly, F. Gary Gray, 28, had earned a reputation
making music videos and some smaller films (``Friday'' and ``Set It
Off'') when he was offered ``The Negotiator,'' a $50 million
feature that opened in July.
</P>
<P>
   Most reviews pointed out the routine nature of the story, but
almost all said that the director's control of tension and the
performances of his two stars, Kevin Spacey and Samuel L. Jackson,
made the film work.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Rush Hour,'' starring Jackie Chan and Chris Tucker, is
released on Sept. 18, audiences can decide if Brett Ratner, 28, is
another video master who can turn chopped live into pate. (Or at
least is worthy of his three-picture deal with New Line.) Ratner
did what was asked of him last year, giving the middling ``Money
Talks,'' an action comedy staring Charlie Sheen, some much-needed
adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ratner makes no apologies for his style and claims it has
remained consistent through his shift of mediums. ``Even my videos
were more like mini-movies, telling a story,'' he said. ``But I do
have a short attention span, and I feel if I'm looking at my watch
it's time to cut to the next scene. The story isn't driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Others of the Millennium Generation are just saying no to
mediocre material, and holding out for something more personal, or
something that allows them to veer drastically from the fast-paced
glitz they've become associated with.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pellington, 36, had come off a very successful career doing
promos and videos at MTV (along with some commercials and
mini-documentaries) when he decided he was ready to make the move
to the big screen. He spent more than a year working with a
screenwriter to adapt Dan Wakefield's book ``Going All the Way,''
about two young Korean War veterans in the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   The film (starring a then-unknown Ben Affleck) did little
business last fall. But no one could accuse it of moving too fast
and not concentrating on the characters.
</P>
<P>
   Now he tries again with the forthcoming ``Arlington Road,''
starring Jeff Bridges and Tim Robbins. ``There's more pressure on
the second one,'' conceded Pellington, ``this one being $25
million, the last about $3 million. I'm still learning that on the
big screen the cuts control you, while with videos I control the
cuts. I'm shedding old skins and growing new ones. But no one will
call this a quick-cut MTV movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Romanek, in his mid-30s, wants his feature debut to be
something that matches the stately, photographlike quality he
brought to videos for artists like Nine Inch Nails, Beck, REM and
others. After turning down some big screen offers, he hopes to go
long form finally with an autobiography of the photographer Diane
Arbus.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Jonze, 28, another of the most respected MTV directors of
the moment, also turned down many big-screen offers before recently
starting the offbeat comedy ``Being John Malkovich,'' for Gramercy
Pictures, starring Cameron Diaz and John Cusack
</P>
<P>
   Their admirable reluctance to leap too soon from being videoboyz
to men is partly due to a sensitivity toward the MTV-bashing as
well as watching some of their contemporaries founder. Adam
Bernstein, 38, who made some 70 videos over 10 years, got his first
movie opportunity with ``It's Pat,'' a ``Saturday Night
Live''-inspired enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Though it did lead to offers like ``Camp Wanna Barf,'' Bernstein
said he despised the lack of participation working with a big
studio and is ``determined to have more control over what I do
next.'' True to his word, Bernstein directed an independent
feature, ``Six Ways to Sunday,'' to be released early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Some will surely fall out, but for now, ``they are very often
being picked over more experienced directors simply because they
haven't failed yet,'' said David Brown, who 20 years ago took a
chance on a new kid named Spielberg by giving him ``Jaws.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spielberg generation was considered the last truly serious
students of film, growing up at the feet of heroes like Ford and
Welles, riding every New Wave, both American and European, and
doing for film schools what Woodward and Bernstein did for
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me is that these kids don't have any interest in
much before the 70s,'' said the director Peter Bogdanovich, who
speaks often at film schools.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Daley, dean of the University of Southern California's
School of Cinema and Television, puts it slightly differently. ``We
don't graduate anyone who doesn't know his Ford, his Hitchcock, his
Bertolucci,'' she said, ``but we also want them to understand the
scope of what a career is today. We believe in expressing yourself
with sound and image, and today that may mean music videos and
television as well as movies.''
</P>
<P>
   So the time has come to consider that there are many ways to
come up to directing, through writing (Nora Ephron, Robert Benton,
Don Roos), through live television (the Sidney Lumet and John
Frankenheimer generation), through episodic television (Spielberg,
Mimi Leder). Yes, even through advertising school in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the Millennium Generation claim that their Mariah
Carey or Pepsi-Cola days should not be held against them, and that
it's not their fault that studio executives are consumed with
audience attention spans or, in the words of David Brown, ``more
concerned with how many left a theater during a movie than how many
stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   They also point out that respected filmmakers like Spike Lee,
Gus Van Sant and Jonathan Demme occasionally dabble in music
videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only started doing music videos to learn to master the
camera,'' said Hype Williams, who has directed videos for Will
Smith, LL Cool J and Baby Face. ``But I was born to make movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brett Ratner: ``Hey, the day they started putting
directors' names on MTV videos was the day Hollywood starting
watching us and we really began taking the work seriously. It was a
great place to experiment, another form of school. And now it's
starting to pay off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
