<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS AND OWNERS, AMID GROWING PESSIMISM, TO MEET AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In their economic game of chicken, neither the
National Basketball Association team owners nor the players will
blink. One month before training camps are scheduled to open and
two months before the start of the regular season, the bargaining
table is empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting increasingly pessimistic,'' the league's deputy
commissioner, Russ Granik, said. ``It's not like we've committed
ourselves to losing games. We want a new agreement. But whether
that happens or not remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties reconvene in a Manhattan law office Thursday
morning for the arbitration hearing which will decide whether
players with guaranteed contracts should be paid during the
lockout. The arbitrator, John Feerick, has scheduled Thursday,
Friday, next Tuesday and possibly Wednesday for the remainder of
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Klempner, an attorney with the Players Association, is
scheduled to continue his testimony. The union's executive
director, Billy Hunter, is also scheduled to testify.
</P>
<P>
   After the arbitration ends and post-hearing briefs are filed,
Feerick has 30 days to render a decision. Officials on both sides
have privately said they expect to meet again before the
arbitrator's decision. But with no progress in sight, the chance of
losing games to labor strife for the first time in NBA history
increases exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for the season to commence on time, I would think we
would have to have a deal in place by Oct. 1, or at least the
outlines of the deal,'' Hunter said. ``With training camps
scheduled to open then, I would hope we could get serious before
the last week of September.''
</P>
<P>
   The first casualty may be the league's rookie orientation, which
is scheduled for the last week of September. The season is
scheduled to open Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have any hope?'' Hunter said. ``Not at this point.
They're convinced that once the players miss a paycheck, they're
going to cave. And that's unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The main stumbling block in negotiations has been the players'
refusal to budge on any proposal that would put a ceiling on
salaries. The owners walked out of a meeting on Aug. 7 after they
heard a new round of proposals from the players. While several
provisions were addressed, the central issue of playing under a
hard salary cap _ which the owners deem paramount _ was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those proposals were all ancillary issues,'' Granik said.
``The key is that the owners cannot afford to play the season under
a totally open-ended system. When it comes to that, we haven't made
any progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hunter, ``We're determined not to play under the hard cap.
We don't want a closed-in system.''
</P>
<P>
   During the arbitration over the next few days, Granik,
Commissioner David Stern and the NBA's legal team will most likely
exchange amicable pleasantries with Hunter and his staff of
attorneys. From one of those conversations may emerge a forthcoming
bargaining session.
</P>
<P>
   But with two sides adamant on sticking to their own idea of good
league economics _ the players determined to keep playing for
whatever the market holds and the owners steadfast in curbing
exorbitant salaries _ the possibility for a September
reconciliation seems remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go back to the bargaining table tomorrow if we felt we
could get anywhere,'' Granik said. ``The real problem right now is,
there does not seem to be any reason to bargain.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
