<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-KINGPINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIN PLAYERS SELDOM FALL INTO DRUG AGENTS' NET
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARISA TAYLOR 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The police officer became leery when he smelled the strong scent
of deodorizer in the car he had pulled over in a routine traffic
stop along Interstate 40 in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Mike Garbo became more suspicious when he asked to
search the car, and the passenger fainted.
</P>
<P>
   After pulling back the armrest covers in the back seat, Garbo
and other officers in a drug task force found 44 pounds of
Colombian white heroin, the largest amount of heroin ever seized by
such an agency in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The heroin, confiscated in August 1997, was 96 percent pure and
worth an estimated $40 million on the streets, officials said. It
gave the Nashville Police Department reason to tout the drug task
force, formed five months earlier as part of a growing cadre of
highway patrols across the nation targeting drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   But a year later, a Dallas jeweler suspected of being the main
heroin supplier remains at large after Tennessee and federal
authorities suffered a series of setbacks. The case exemplifies the
difficulties faced in tracking down the main suppliers and
distributors in a drug organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're the windshield, sometimes you're the bug,''
said John Zimmermann, a Nashville assistant district attorney who
is working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The first mistake in the case came when authorities, because of
botched test results, initially charged both men with possession of
cocaine instead of heroin, slowing the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we thought it was cocaine,'' Garbo said. ``We had
never seen heroin of that quantity, and it was wrapped in plastic
and duct tape like a kilo of cocaine. It was a very big surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor commmunications among local law enforcement agencies also
hurt the case.
</P>
<P>
   When they were arrested, both men _ Herman Zapata, a 22-year-old
from Colombia who lived in Flower Mound, Texas; and Omar Amaya, a
24-year-old from Colombia who lived in Dallas _ said they wanted to
cooperate with police. They gave the following account, which
became part of court documents obtained by the Star-Telegram:
</P>
<P>
   Amaya, who was unemployed, said he agreed to drive to New York
at the request of a friend in Dallas, knowing that he was being
paid to transport something that might be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the friend, 44-year-old Nestor Marulanda, who owned
a Dallas restaurant and jewelry store, gave him $4,200 cash to buy
a used car for the trip. Marulanda also promised an additional $800
when Amaya returned.
</P>
<P>
   Marulanda told Amaya to call him when he arrived in New Jersey,
and he would then give Amaya the telephone number of a man named
Lucio. Lucio would meet Amaya in New York and load the car with
``party hats and party decorations'' to bring back.
</P>
<P>
   Amaya said that as he was leaving Marulanda's house on Forest
Lane in Dallas, Marulanda cautioned him that there was ``something
in the car and to drive slow and be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Amaya said he then picked up Zapata in Flower Mound and the pair
began their trip north.
</P>
<P>
   After Amaya made his statement, he and Zapata told authorities
that they would deliver the heroin so police could nab the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Police, with the assistance of the Drug Enforcement
Administration, told Amaya to call Marulanda at his Dallas jewelry
store, Innovations. But when Amaya reached Marulanda on his
cellular phone, the jeweler was suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you guys got busted in Nashville,'' he told Amaya.
</P>
<P>
   Police then learned that county jail officials that morning had
allowed Zapata to call his wife, who quickly called Marulanda.
</P>
<P>
   By the time DEA agents in Dallas went to Marulanda's house the
next day, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been approximately over 100 man-hours concentrated on
finding him,'' said Paul Villaescusa, a DEA spokesman in Dallas.
``But he wasn't located.''
</P>
<P>
   Marulanda, who in the 1970s was running from the law on cocaine
charges in New York, is a federal fugitive again and is believed to
have fled to Cali, Colombia. His businesses, which are now closed,
are believed to have been covers for drug trafficking, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state authorities were successful in tracking down
Lucio, the New York contact.
</P>
<P>
   They told Amaya to call him and set up a meeting. Luis ``Lucio''
Jimenez-Zuleta, a 59-year-old New York resident originally from
Colombia, arrived with $32,000 cash, and agents arrested him.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez-Zuleta was recently sentenced to 30 months in federal
prison for conspiracy to distribute heroin, instead of the maximum
10-year sentence. His attorney, Jose Castaneda, had argued that
Marulanda lured him into drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about an unsophisticated individual, someone who
sold T-shirts on the street, doesn't speak English and is a
diabetic,'' Castaneda said. ``The big guys are too smart to get
caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office sought federal charges against Zapata
and Amaya. But the federal magistrate dismissed the case against
Zapata because of insufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A district attorney's office in Tennessee has charged both men.
The state case is set to go to trial Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents said that with large heroin operations, multiple
smugglers and distributors are often involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously with that amount of heroin, you have several runners
_ one guy would have 10 people running distribution,'' said Coleman
Ramsey, the DEA resident-agent-in-charge of the Nashville, Tenn.,
office. ``It's very difficult to catch them on both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
