<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6025 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANGLEWOOD-TEACHERS-$     09-02 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGLEWOOD-TEACHERS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TEACHERS, THE BEST ARE OFTEN THE LEAST  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 6)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (af) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND 
   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teachers come in different shapes and sizes, and finding the
right fit might sort out some of the educational controversies
going on at the Tanglewood Festival up in Lenox, Mass. The troubles
have been well rehearsed in these pages, and are not likely to go
away when the season ends this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Have Tanglewood's long-respected summer programs been
emasculated by dismissals and resignations, or have they been
reinvigorated by a new involvement on the part of the Boston
Symphony and its music director, Seiji Ozawa?
</P>
<P>
   Keeping score is not easy, for good things can happen at the
same time damage is being done. The first question for all parties
is simply, ``What is it that music teachers do?'' ``Teach music''
is no answer. There are too many kinds of teaching going on.
</P>
<P>
   Let's begin with the celebrities. They divide into two
categories: performers with public profiles, and teachers whose
powers of connection attract exceptional students. Great performers
are occasionally great teachers, but not often. Yet their presence
in academia (when they are not off giving concerts) is a strong
attractant.
</P>
<P>
   Just as law firms hire former cabinet members to drum up
clients, so music schools use the famous name as a kind of logo.
The student prospers, too, for no matter how little he or she
learns, the advertisement can read, ``Student of the Great
So-and-So.''
</P>
<P>
   My piano teacher at the Paris Conservatory _ a woman of
astonishing technique, minimal teaching skill and sublime ignorance
of any style but her own _ had once, over a period of three or four
lessons, played the keyboard pieces of Ravel for the composer.
</P>
<P>
   Ravel, she told me, corrected the many typographical errors in
the Durand edition, suggested tempos and interpretive ideas,
collected his substantial fee, then saw the lady no more. An
abbreviated course of study, not cheap, but there was a reward.
``Student of Ravel'': think of the authority that title conveyed on
her interpretations, no matter what nonsense she superimposed on
the master's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity performer and celebrity teacher are doorkeepers,
with access to important managers and intendants. Students find
their way under such wings, grateful for the connections and happy
for any learning at all. (It often comes in the form of tips: how
to finger that hard passage in the Chopin G minor Ballade, what to
leave out in the Brahms Second Piano Concerto.)
</P>
<P>
   Performers typically charge fees in the hundreds of dollars per
hour simply to discourage applicants. They would rather be
practicing. Celebrity teachers charge big fees because they can get
them. Amend ``There are no great teachers, only great students'' to
read, ``Teachers succeed professionally by their ability to attract
great students.''
</P>
<P>
   Another category of teacher is the kind Tanglewood seems to have
lost in considerable numbers during the recent unpleasantness: the
teacher of music, a performer who might operate on the fringes of
the public music world or might not play concerts at all.
</P>
<P>
   Like coaches in major league baseball, they are eloquent
purveyors of information, for struggling with their own hard-earned
skills has forced them into a self-examination largely foreign to
the easy virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers of music are less interested in the careers of their
students than in the passing-on of styles and traditions. Achieving
the right balances in a Haydn string quartet supersedes winning an
audition before a 57th Street manager.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher of music is less a reservoir of useful tricks than a
purveyor of information: which tempo might work, how harmony
affects accentuation, what a phrase mark means, how ``allegro'' in
1780 and ``allegro'' in 1880 mean different things. I learned
something about piano playing from my Paris teacher simply by
standing behind her and watching. I learned more about music from
an unpleasant and disheveled old man in Pittsburgh than from any
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   I am delighted to hear of the euphoria with which the ``new''
Tanglewood seems to have been greeted this summer. Ozawa and his
Boston players are evidently doing good things. Robert Spano will
still be teaching conductors, asking questions of his students, so
that they will find their own answers.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere at Tanglewood there is a broader question to be
asked: What is the purpose of a music school altogether? Is it
preparation for jobs, or is its first aim to deepen understanding?
</P>
<P>
   I am troubled by the idea of classes teaching violinists how to
be concertmasters. These are practical skills better won by sitting
in the second-violin section of an orchestra and observing. Would
not such class time at Tanglewood be better spent pondering
Beethoven's ambiguous accent marks and Mozart's overlapping slurs.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of offending my journalistic colleagues, if I were a
newspaper executive faced with hiring either a journalism-school
graduate trained in news-gathering or a good writer steeped in
economics, history and political science but with no news
experience, I would choose the latter every time. The difference
between knowledge and expertise is misunderstood these days.
</P>
<P>
   I know I shall also offend the Guarneri String Quartet by
questioning its recent addition to Tanglewood's faculty. The
Guarneri has a distinguished past and a high public profile, and
maybe its players are splendid teachers despite their persistently
crude performances in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the troubling possibility remains that their presence has as
much to do with public relations as with musical substance. At any
rate, the gain of these four players and the loss of Gilbert
Kalish, Leon Fleisher, Joel Krosnick and Julius Levine seems not an
equal trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
