<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-BUYOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTARY BUYOUT OFFER EXTENDED BY BELL ATLANTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only weeks after agreeing to a new contract with its unionized
workers, Bell Atlantic Corp. has extended a voluntary buyout offer
to some of its management employees.
</P>
<P>
   In an internal message dated Tuesday, one senior Bell Atlantic
executive said that involuntary layoffs might become necessary
later this year if the voluntary program did not attract enough
employees.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Bell Atlantic, the nation's largest local
telephone company, said there was no plan to cut jobs across the
company. Instead, she said, some departments were offering the
buyouts to cut their work force in an effort to meet existing
financial targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a massive effort to lay off 20,000 people,'' said
Susan Kraus, the spokeswoman. ``There was a top-down effort to get
everyone to meet their budget targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all within the normal course of business. We
continually look at ways to streamline and adjust our force.''
</P>
<P>
   About 47,000 of Bell Atlantic's 142,000 employees are not
unionized. It was unclear Wednesday how many of those management
employees would be eligible for buyout programs and how many jobs
the company planned to cut. Wednesday night, Ms. Kraus said it was
unclear how many of the company's departments had recently started
buyout programs.
</P>
<P>
   But in a printed message dated Tuesday to ``all management
employees'' in the finance group for the unit that runs the
company's communications network and the unit that sells
communications services, Doreen Toben, the units' chief financial
officer, said the buyout applied to ``all director level and below
management employees in my organization with limited exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No cap will be placed on the number of employees who will be
allowed to accept the offer,'' her memo said, adding that the
buyout plan was necessary to help her department meet a goal of
reducing costs by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the voluntary buyout plan, called the ``force
management program,'' the message said, ``If a sufficient number of
employees do not take advantage of the FMP offer, an involuntary
reduction in force (RIF) may be required later in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the memo, employees will have until Oct. 14 to
accept the offer, and those who join the program will be released
from the company's payroll as of Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice-mail message early this week to ``all business
marketing personnel,'' Ron Rothenbach, a vice president for
marketing to business customers, suggested that major parts of Bell
Atlantic might feel pressure to cut jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his boss, Bruce Gordon, the group president for
retail marketing, Rothenbach said, ``I do have additional
head-count challenges, challenges that have been leveled against
the entire Gordon organization, and therefore, of course, mine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've grown from 1.5 percent to 3 percent in revenues,''
Rothenbach said, referring to his department's annual growth
targets. ``We're still not making the revenue targets of 4.4
percent and as a result need to downsize so that the corporation
can stay financially viable and be able to compete in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kraus said that Rothenbach was speaking for himself and not
for the corporation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major benefits contemplated in the merger of Bell
Atlantic and Nynex was the ability to eliminate certain duplication
in employees, and some force reduction is not therefore a
surprise,'' said Eric Strumingher, a telecommunications analyst at
Paine Webber. ``However, if it is true that revenue targets are
coming below expectations this would by definition not have been
anticipated and potentially suggests some other issues at work,
potentially the effects of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kraus did not estimate the size of Rothenbach's department.
She said that Ms. Toben's finance organization had between 500 and
600 management employees.
</P>
<P>
   In his message, Rothenbach said he planned to come up with a
more detailed buyout plan for his department by the end of
September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
