A6041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-CHILD-PORN-N     09-02 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CHILD-PORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET PORNOGRAPHY CLUB IS SEIZED HERE AND ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Calif., Maine, Texas, Utah)  (jt) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police in 22 states and a dozen countries late
Tuesday and early Wednesday swept down on scores of homes belonging
to young and old, professional people and factory workers, all
suspected of belonging to a huge Internet club trafficking in child
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen people were arrested, but officials said they
expected more than 100 to be charged as law enforcement officers
with expertise in computers downloaded the contents of hard drives
and floppy discs that were seized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume is enormous,'' Ray Kelly, the commissioner of the
United States Customs Service, said Wednesday, noting that the
investigation had turned up a data base of more than 100,000 sexual
photographs of naked boys and girls, some younger than 2, some
engaged in sexual acts with adults.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said the material went far beyond anything that could
remotely be called art, and a British police official agreed.
``It's stomach-churning,'' said Detective Superintendent John
Stewardson, who led the British phase of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials in the United States and Britain called the
operation one of the largest against the spreading netherworld of
child pornography in cyberspace. The suspects were believed to
belong to the Wonderland Club. A membership requirement, police
officials said, was possession of pornographic photographs of
children and a willingness to share them.
</P>
<P>
   The raids in the United States took place in places as diverse
as Brooklyn, N.Y., Salt Lake City, Dallas, Kennebunk, Maine, West
Orange, N.J., and Norcross, Ga. They yielded a half-dozen arrests
and a treasure trove of computer equipment that will be used as
evidence, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those arrested was a University of Connecticut teacher
seized at his home in New Britain, said an official familiar with
the operation. Another raid, in Missouri, turned up a cache of
weapons as well as child pornography in a heavily fortified
trailer, this official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Customs Service, which coordinated the U.S. raids in
connection with local authorities, did not release the names of the
arrested. The accused face federal child-pornography charges that
could bring up to 10 years in prison, said a Customs agent, Bill
Anthony. They could also face local charges, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, Wonderland Club members are believed to have
posed their own children for pictures, Anthony said. In other
cases, parents may have taken money to let their children be used,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the children, where they are now, whether they
can be saved _ these are among the questions investigators are
agonizing over and will be for weeks as the inquiry unfolds,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said law enforcement's knowledge of the Wonderland Club
grew out of a 1996 investigation in San Jose, Calif. In that case,
16 people in the United States and abroad were charged with taking
part in an online pedophilia club.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Anthony said some of those implicated in the 1996 case
began cooperating with investigators. The information thus gleaned
proved invaluable, especially when it was shared with British
detectives, who earlier this year discovered pedophiles downloading
child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Over many months of looking into the Wonderland Club,
investigators learned how its members communicated by code and on
some occasions were able to follow cybertrails back to their points
of origin, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony said the raids were timed to minimize the risk of
Wonderland members' warning one another. They began around 5:30
a.m. Wednesday in Britain, when it was late Tuesday on the East
Coast of the United States. Homes in Australia, Austria, Belgium,
Finland, France, Germany, Italy, Norway, Portugal and Sweden were
also raided.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Packham, the deputy director general of Britain's National
Crime Squad, was pleased afterward. ``I am unaware of another
police operation that has ever pulled together so many law
enforcement agencies worldwide to effect simultaneous raids and
arrests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a Customs special agent, Dick Weart, offered a perspective
on how hard a fight lies ahead. Where, he was asked, is the
headquarters of the Wonderland Club?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based in cyberspace,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
