<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-DIRECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVENT HIRES ARTISTIC DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In their first major move since disclosing serious
accounting problems and suspending two company executives,
officials of the theater production company Livent Inc. announced
Wednesday that they had hired Todd Haimes, artistic director of the
Roundabout Theater Company, as their artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   In appointing Haimes, they effectively supplanted Garth
Drabinsky, the company's co-founder and the producer of ``Ragtime''
and several other lavish musicals that Livent brought to Broadway
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and a company vice president, Myron Gottlieb, were
suspended on Aug. 10 after the company's new management team,
headed by the former Hollywood power broker Michael Ovitz and the
New York investment banker Roy Furman, said they had found
accounting irregularities dating back several years that concealed
the company's extravagant expenses. The irregularities are said to
involve several millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, securities regulators in Canada have begun a formal
investigation of Livent, which is based in Toronto, and trading of
its stock has been halted.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky, who remains suspended pending an investigation
ordered by the company, has denied the reports of irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes, 42, has been credited with building the once-bankrupt
Roundabout into the nation's second-largest nonprofit theater
company and successfully moving a string of shows and revivals,
including ``Cabaret'' and ``A View From the Bridge,'' from
Roundabout's smaller theaters to larger Broadway houses.
</P>
<P>
   Though the appointment is ostensibly an artistic one, Furman
said that Haimes' fiscal successes were a key element of his appeal
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he provides an excellent artistic vision, a fine
creative mind and understanding of what it is to handle several
shows running at once,'' Furman said. ``That combined with
financial discipline is a total package that is very positive for
Livent.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual arrangement, however, Haimes will remain the
director of the Roundabout until next year to oversee the company's
move into its new home at the Selwyn Theater on West 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said he saw no conflict of interest in running two
competing companies at once because ``the Roundabout does small
productions and Livent does larger commercial productions.''
Supervision of musicals already scheduled by Livent, including
``Parade'' and ``Fosse: A Celebration in Song and Dance,'' will
fall to Marty Bell, who was promoted Wednesday to the position of
senior producer at Livent.
</P>
<P>
   Although Haimes added it was too soon to say what his artistic
vision would be at Livent, he also said, ``I actually get a great
deal of enjoyment out of doing things as well as possible for as
little money as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
