<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6048 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCRIMSHAW-ANTIQUES-$A     09-02 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCRIMSHAW-ANTIQUES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASING THE GREAT WHITE WHALEBONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass.)  (For release Sunday, Sept. 6) 
(bl) 
 By FLETCHER ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The hardy seamen who took up scrimshawing to pass the
time during long voyages in search of whales more than a century
ago would probably be dismayed to learn that their handiwork had
been enlisted in the cause of feminism. But consider the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The finely engraved teeth, the whalebone pie crimpers, bodkins
and busks that they made as gifts for their wives and sweethearts
back home were tokens of affection that in the sexual politics of
today might be construed as the actions of tough guys wanting to
show their soft side. Then there was the act of scrimshawing
itself. How different was it from the embroidery, needlepoint and
sewing, the so-called domestic pursuits, that women of the day
engaged in?
</P>
<P>
   Such intriguing possibilities are raised by an exhibition of 52
pieces of scrimshaw at Snug Harbor Cultural Center's Newhouse
Center for Contemporary Art on Staten Island. The collection is
part of a larger, multimedia exhibition _ and here context is key _
with the provocative title ``Ahab's Wife,'' a reference to an
unnamed character mentioned only once by Herman Melville in
``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivia Georgia, director of visual arts at the Newhouse Center
and an organizer of the exhibition, which closes Oct. 4, said the
conceptual underpinning for ``Ahab's Wife'' was the creation a
``heroic role'' for the wife, a kind of reimagining of Melville's
epic tale from a woman's perspective. That theme is suggested in
the work of the half-dozen contemporary artists and several
historical exhibits, like the one devoted to scrimshaw, that are
presented in the show.
</P>
<P>
   If the whaling industry had its golden age from roughly 1825 to
1865, much the same can be said of scrimshaw. It was during this
period that whalemen, often at sea for three to five years at a
time, turned to scrimshaw for relief from the boredom and the
feelings of separation from loved ones. The whaling industry waned
in the latter part of the century after petroleum and electricity
replaced whale oil as fuel for lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Using pocket knives, handmade jigsaws and other crude tools,
scrimshanders, as they were known, cut the bone and ivory to size
and, on surfaces, engraved images; fashionably dressed women,
famous people and sailing scenes were common. Lampblack, India inks
and tobacco juice were used to color the carvings. The seamen
produced a range of objects, both utilitarian and decorative: from
whalebone spoons to ivory picture frames.
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados see scrimshaw as an expression of the heart, devoid
of today's commercialism. As with other folk arts, this link to an
idealized past in part accounts for their long love affair with
scrimshaw. But it was President John F. Kennedy who helped
popularize scrimshaw by displaying several of his favorite pieces
on his desk in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Druckman, director of American folk art at Sotheby's in
New York, said that a ``fairly significant'' market existed for
scrimshaw, particularly among collectors of marine art, for whom it
represents ``the jewel in the crown.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, she noted, a whale tooth engraved with a naked
odalisque figure sold for $45,000, a record for scrimshaw. Less
expensive pieces are available, however. A pie crimper with a
serpent-shaped handle and fluted wheel might run to $1,000, while a
clothespin would go for under $100. She said the most coveted _ and
the earliest _ scrimshaw was a series of engraved teeth known as
``Susan's Teeth,'' which depict scenes from a whaler named Susan's
stay off the coast of Japan in the late 1820s. One such tooth
fetched $44,000 in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Druckman said that increased market activity carried with it
a new risk. ``There are a lot of fakes,'' she said, noting in
particular plastic reproductions from the Azores.
</P>
<P>
   While the authenticity of the pieces on view at the Newhouse
seems beyond question (they are on loan from the Berkshire
Athenaeum in Pittsfield, Mass., the South Street Seaport Museum in
Manhattan and Mystic Seaport in Connecticut), their original
provenance isn't. Ms. Georgia said she had no information about
when, where or by whom the objects were made, not surprising in a
field in which few works were signed or dated.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most arresting objects on view is a tiered sewing box
that resembles a wedding cake. Made of wood and tortoiseshell with
hand-turned ivory posts to hold spools of thread, it has a
pincushion at the top and two drawers for storing sewing
accessories at its base.
</P>
<P>
   Also of interest is a crownlike sewing basket with whalebone
tines and a five-pointed star engraved on its wooden base, and an
inlaid box of wood, ivory and baleen with two large carved ivory
fists crushing snakes mounted on its lid adding an air of mystery.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to what Ms. Georgia calls ``role reversal'' in men
making scrimshaw, she finds another irony. Scrimshaw was created
from the bones of killed whales. ``Scrimshaw is a testament to how
art transforms the more violent parts of our lives into something
beautiful,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
