<HEADER>
A6052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REGRET-790&AMP;AD     09-02 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REGRET-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGER AMONG DEMOCRATS GROWING OVER SUPPORT FOR CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE and LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said Wednesday that
he had been contemplating calling for the censure of President
Clinton. But, he said, Erskine Bowles, the White House chief of
staff, called him on Monday and implored him to hold off making any
comment at least until the president had returned from his trip to
Russia and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said other Democrats, including Sen. Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., the minority leader, were so worried that
Lieberman would go to the Senate floor and call for censure that
they also intervened on Monday to stop their colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about censure but was not ready to go to the
floor, and I'm still not,'' Lieberman said in an interview, adding
that Daschle urged him to consider the consequences of what he was
going to say.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, of Delaware, another leading Democrat, said
Clinton's further public comments Wednesday and last Friday about
Monica Lewinsky were starting to clear the air, ``slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators Christopher Dodd of Connecticut and Bob Graham of
Florida, both Democrats and both seeking re-election, disagreed.
They said the brief, repeated statements, were not working _ and
that the president must do something more.
</P>
<P>
   In the inner caucuses of the Democrats, the angst is deepening
and the added remarks from Clinton last week from Massachusetts and
Wednesday from Moscow do not seem to be calming the waters. If the
president cannot turn to his own party for support, he could find
it particularly difficult to exert influence on legislation, build
support for his own initiatives, or mute critics calling for his
resignation or impeachment. Democratic lawmakers also face their
own perils, with elections approaching in November.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many party leaders and candidates said they did not see
any great political value at this point in Clinton delivering a
nationwide address or sitting down for a major interview to make up
for his initial performance two weeks ago. Those comments were
denounced even by some in the White House as too combative and not
sufficiently contrite.
</P>
<P>
   For now, officials at the White House and in the Democratic
Party are most nervous about Lieberman, as evidenced by the fact
that Bowles took the unusual step of pleading with the senator to
hold off commenting on Clinton. Lieberman said Bowles told him he
first learned of the senator's possible intentions on the radio on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman had called for censure on Monday, party officials
said, such a move would have drawn huge press attention and been
quite damaging to the president and his party. Some of Lieberman's
colleagues have privately expressed disapproval about Lieberman's
deliberations, saying that if Lieberman speaks out that would press
other Democrats who are facing re-election to scold the president
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he has decided that it is premature to consider
censure or any other kind of legislative action before independent
prosecutor Kenneth Starr releases his report to Congress. But
Democrats should not rest easy: The senator said he planned to
release a statement or deliver a floor speech by the end of this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all very difficult and very personal,'' Lieberman
said. ``In a lot of ways, he's trying to repair his relationship
with his own family and the larger American family. I'm trying to
put together my thoughts on the whole experience and the
implications of what the president acknowledged.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he was not influenced by Daschle's pleas at a
luncheon of Senate Democrats on Tuesday that lawmakers should
stress the issues and not lambaste Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is to urge people to be restrained and not leap
ahead,'' Lieberman said. ``But people are talking about it and we
have an obligation to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman is still weighing what he should say publicly,
Dodd was not timid. He said the president's amplified comments were
not sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, the president is going to have to address this
again,'' he said. ``It doesn't help for every day to have a little
piece of this. He needs to pick a time and a place where it will
have maximum effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham agreed. ``He needs to have a conversation with the
American people that is more than a single speech to overcome the
unfortunate speech of Aug. 17,'' he said. ``I think it was a
failure. It's not hard to apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graham expressed reservations about calling for Clinton's
censure. ``My threshold concern is that we already have a president
whose leadership has been eroded,'' he said. ``Will this further
undermine his capability to deal with a staggering number of
serious issues?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While many Democrats insist that they were still disappointed,
even furious, at Clinton, they said he has past the point where a
deep apology to the nation would do any good.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's done is inexcusable,'' said Ken Lucas, a Democrat
running for the House in Kentucky. ``But to keep talking about it,
I don't know what that accomplishes. How much can you beat on this?
It doesn't change what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, the national chairman of the Democratic
Party, had also complained that Clinton's initial remarks did not
go far enough. But Wednesday, he pronounced himself satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is enough _ it is sufficient,'' Romer said. ``He's been
very sincere in the times he's spoken about it. People ought to see
that even in a trip to Russia he repeats, `I've asked for
forgiveness.' What more can you say?''
</P>
<P>
   But as Romer and other party leaders work to keep their own
ranks unified, they are at odds over what the president should do
next.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who attended the luncheon on Tuesday said the most
emotional comments were from Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California,
who repeated her public statement of two weeks ago that Clinton had
shattered his own credibility.
</P>
<P>
   But some leaders in the party applauded the president for his
comments in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he references to it, it becomes clear to the public
that he really is ashamed,'' Biden said. ``To seek forgiveness and
have it granted requires real contrition. What comes across is this
sense of contrition _ slowly. What I see is shame. That's not a bad
thing for the American people to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden added, ``You can't say, `Yep, that's it.' You will end up
having to necessarily mention it 50 more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., also said the president's comments
Wednesday will only help. ``He's getting closer to saying, `I'm
sorry,''' he said. ``What he said the first time was not well said.
Any time he clarifies or elaborates, it helps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
