<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-DOGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNIFFER DOGS DO WHAT MACHINES CAN'T
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON DICKSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most efficient drug detectors is one of the cheapest.
It is sophisticated enough to differentiate the aroma of the
tiniest amount of contraband from hundreds of other smells.
</P>
<P>
   Police dogs are doing what machines can't.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs are so effective that drug trafficking organizations
buy them to ``dog proof'' shipments before sending them to the
United States, said Raphael Lopez, special agent for the U.S.
Customs Service in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Traffickers take other measures to counter dogs' effectiveness.
In Laredo, Texas, one pooch was so renowned for its narco-busting
nose that drug traffickers offered a reward for its death,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In North Texas, dogs have played a major role in some of the
biggest heroin busts.
</P>
<P>
   In June, two men were arrested at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport
after Smokey, a drug-sniffing dog, alerted officials to their
luggage. Police found more than $5 million worth of white powder
heroin sewn into clothes. The suspects, one from Mexico and one
from the Dominican Republic, were en route from McAllen to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   While some detection methods bring up questions of privacy
invasion, police dogs have the courts on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most courts won't even consider the sniff to be a search,''
said Phillip Lyons, a criminal justice professor at Sam Houston
State University in Hunstville, Texas. ``The dog is just sniffing
the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the dog has the credentials to identify drugs, the
sniff can be probable cause for the police to conduct a search.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
