<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MILLION YOUTH MARCH' COULD DRAW FAR FEWER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Pa.)  (mk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ and MONTE WILLIAMS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With just two days to go before Khallid Abdul
Muhammad's planned youth rally in Harlem, the event's organizers
have done little to draw a strong turnout despite their contention
that people will be flooding into Harlem from around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, organizers of the rally have drastically scaled
back their initial estimates that more than 1 million young people
will show up for what they are calling the Million Youth March.
Now, they are saying that they expect no more than 50,000 to attend
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but black elected officials and community leaders
in New York City and beyond say that the rally's organizers have
provided them with so little information about the event that they
do not know what to expect of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as though I am in the dark'' about the rally, said
Democratic state Sen. David Paterson of Harlem. ``I just haven't
seen the kind of preparations that as a public official I usually
see when a large event like this is being planned.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent lack of preparation is in striking contrast to the
days preceding the Million Man March in Washington, in which scores
of chartered buses and caravans of cars helped transport hundreds
of thousands of people to the nation's capital for the 1995 rally
organized by the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Sadiki Kambon, head of the Black Community Information Center in
Boston and former organizer of Boston's Million Man March
Organization Committee, said he had not been contacted by the
organizers of the New York event despite being no more than a
four-hour car ride away. ``I'm not aware of youth going'' from
Boston, Kambon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, one of the event's most prominent
supporters, insisted that the organizers were making arrangements
for people to attend, and a lawyer for the organizers said that
dozens of buses would be transporting people to Harlem for the
event, but he refused to offer specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relative lack of organization, the furor over the
rally could prove to be the wild card that draws attention, and
turnout, to the event. Over the last month, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
has vehemently attacked the rally's leader, Muhammad, and branded
the event ``a hate march.'' Since then, several more moderate black
leaders have said they support the idea of the march, and have
encouraged people to turn out to assure that the rally is peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Wright, a Democratic assemblyman from Harlem, said the
rally had received fairly little attention until the mayor began
speaking out. ``The fight with the mayor has put this march on the
map,'' he said. ``The people who live here in Harlem are not
involved in the planning of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally's organizers continue to insist that their event will
be well attended and that their confederates in other states have
chartered between 50 and 100 buses to ferry people to Harlem. But
the organizers did not respond to a request to provide names of
organizers in other cities, and black leaders in other urban areas
said local residents were not showing enthusiasm for the event.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, for instance, the head of a major youth group that
works with gangs, the National Ten Point Leadership Foundation,
criticized the rally, and said he saw little evidence that young
people from there would attend. In Washington, the president of the
NAACP's local chapter said that organization did not plan to send
anyone to the march. The same was true in Philadelphia, where the
youth adviser for the local NAACP branch said the organization
would have nothing to do with the event.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that there is extensive grass-roots organizing
going on, it is among community leaders and elected officials in
Harlem. Bracing for the worst, they have recruited volunteers to
act as a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not doing this in support of or in conjunction with
Khallid Muhammad,'' Bill Perkins, a City Councilman from Harlem,
said. ``They have offended the neighborhood leadership. They don't
have much of a base in Harlem. Civic, religious, business and
community organizations were not consulted, so as a result there is
no base in the community. We realize we are going to have something
in our neighborhood so we want to be helpful in avoiding
altercations.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Green, who heads the Crown Heights Youth Collective,
said his organization was publicly opposed to the rally but, for
safety reasons, was counseling parents to accompany their children
to the event if they were planning to let them attend.
</P>
<P>
   Another black leader who spoke on condition of anonymity put the
matter more bluntly. ``In my opinion, this is a hate march, and we
don't participate in anything that smacks of hatred,'' the official
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
