<HEADER>
A6063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-USOPEN-CHANG-NYT &LR;      09-02 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-CHANG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANG IS UNSEEDED, BUT OPTIMISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1996, Michael Chang played in the final of the
U.S. Open in Louis Armstrong Stadium. That stadium, now sliced
nearly in half and overshadowed by one named for Arthur Ashe, is no
longer the center of attention at this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Chang, but there he was on Wednesday, back on the
hardcourt surface of his old yet new stomping ground in the first
round. Chang's thigh muscles still bulge; his straight black hair
still bounces on his head as he hustles from corner to corner. What
is missing this year is a number next to his name.
</P>
<P>
   He was seeded second a year ago: the year he blinked against the
eventual champion, Patrick Rafter, in the semifinals with his first
U.S. Open title and second major championship title clearly,
tantalizingly in view. Twelve often frustrating months later, Chang
is not seeded at all. There have been mysterious losses; there have
been multiple injuries, and now there are multiplying doubts about
Chang's ability to contend at a tournament where he has reached the
quarterfinals or better in five of the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the 20th-ranked Chang has lost faith, and as he
answered questions on Wednesday after his very routine 6-1, 6-3,
6-1 victory over Eyal Erlich of Israel, he sported a T-shirt that
read, ``Jesus Loves You,'' and a relaxed, buoyant attitude that
said, ``Don't Forget Me Just Yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have as good a shot as anybody out there,'' he
said, ``and I have gotten close in the past, so why not have the
attitude that I can come out and play great tennis and maybe even
win this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Chang's optimism comes from winning at Brookline, Mass.,
on Sunday. It was Chang's first tournament victory in more than a
year, and although he hardly swept through the draw _ requiring
three sets to defeat three of his five opponents _ he and his
brother and coach, Carl, are much more obsessed with tennis points
than style points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I think Michael turned the corner last week,''
Carl said.
</P>
<P>
   Chang might not have Goran Ivanisevic's serve, Pete Sampras'
forehand or Rafter's volleys, but in an era when weapons are a
prerequisite for membership in the top 10, he has long been able to
rely on his legs. Chang is among the quickest players, and with the
exception of a hip fracture in 1989, he has been relatively free of
injuries during his career.
</P>
<P>
   This year, his luck has run out. In January, he strained a
stomach muscle shortly before the Australian Open. In March, he
bruised his foot and then partly tore the medial collateral
ligament in his left knee when he slipped while training with
Andrei Medvedev in Indian Wells, Calif., after a sprinkler system
began operating on an adjacent clay court.
</P>
<P>
   Chang said he tore ``25 percent'' of the ligament, which allowed
him to forgo surgery but not a three-week layoff. ``My knee feels
good right now,'' he said. ``I am definitely able to move about
whichever way. I have lost a little bit of flexibility, but the
doctors say with any kind of torn ligament it is not uncommon for
the injury to take 16 months to be 100 percent healed.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the knee injury, Chang has also experienced tendinitis in
his left wrist, which hampers him on his two-handed backhand, and
he is nursing a slight groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   But if the injuries help explain Chang's forgettable 1998
season, they do not explain his disastrous autumn last year, when
he struggled mightily except for some fine play in the Davis Cup
semifinals against Australia. It was as if his disappointment at
failing to win the U.S. Open had seeped into his tennis. But Chang
and his brother reject this theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, maybe after Pete had lost, I definitely
felt the pressure to be able to win this event,'' Michael said. ``I
knew I had a great opportunity. I had some tough matches in the
round of 16 and quarters and Pat was just too good there on the
semifinal day. I think I could look back through the past few years
at missed opportunities and stuff, but one thing I have learned is
not to dwell on missed chances or times where you have failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang said he never trained harder in an off season than he did
last winter. The question is whether he pushed his body too hard
and whether his body and psyche are ready for the French Open
champion, Carlos Moya, in the second round here. Moya is seeded
10th, but being an underdog in a major championship is not
necessarily a problem for Chang. It agreed with him quite nicely
back in 1989 when he won his first and only major title at the
French Open at age 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know Michael, you know that he loves these kind of
challenges,'' Carl said. ``And you also know that if you look at
the guys ahead of him in the rankings right now, he has beaten them
all before.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
