r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-DEA-TEX     09-02 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-DEA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING HEROIN IS AN EVER-CHANGING JOB
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    EDITORS' NOTE: The Drug Enforcement Administration leads U.S.
efforts in combating drug trafficking organizations around the
world.
 &HT;    With support from local and state law enforcement agencies,
4,238 DEA agents enforce federal drug laws, and collect and analyze
information on illegal drug activity. The agency, formed in 1973,
also develops federal drug enforcement strategies and programs.
 &HT;    With its annual budget of $1.2 billion, the DEA also tries to
deter the drug trade through nonenforcement methods such as crop
eradication, crop substitution and drug prevention training of
foreign officials.
By DOMINGO RAMIREZ JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For 20 years, Julio Mercado has tracked the heroin
trade from Mexico to the Middle East, from the inner-city streets
of New York to the suburbs of North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen the purity level go from 1 percent to 90 percent,
and the face of users change from hardened street addicts to
baby-faced teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   As an agent for the Drug Enforcement Administration, Mercado,
49, has watched the federal agency constantly add resources to try
to keep up with the changing heroin trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I've made some difference,'' said Mercado, special
agent in charge of the Dallas DEA office. He has made 700
drug-related arrests, most involving heroin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we didn't get the dealer on every investigation I was
on, but I feel confident that in time that dealer was going to be
arrested by some agency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mercado can trace the evolution of the heroin trade through
volumes of court papers on the agency's investigations during the
past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The source has changed: One investigation involved a
Massachusetts heroin ring in the early 1980s that distributed the
drug nationwide, according to federal court records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation led us to Lebanon, and that was the first
time we had seen heroin coming from there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon and Middle East countries remain sources of heroin for
this country, particularly in New York. But Mexico has become the
No. 1 heroin supplier in Texas, and Colombia is pushing out Asian
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The dealers have changed: ``Back then, the big fish stayed in
the United States,'' Mercado said. ``Now, they're in foreign
countries shipping it here.''
</P>
<P>
   The addicts: ``Users in the 1970s knew that they had to call 911
immediately to give their overdose friends a chance to survive,''
Mercado said. ``Users these days don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The methods: ``Beepers weren't around back in the 1970s,''
Mercado said. ``If a dealer wanted to reach someone back then, he
may call or he would just walk into a neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The price: Five years ago, dealers were selling a kilogram of
heroin for $180,000 to $240,000. These days, a kilo of heroin sells
for $700,000 to $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What all that has meant is that we've had to pour in more
resources and work more with local and state agencies,'' Mercado
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some criminal justice experts, noting that 80 percent of federal
money used in the war on drugs has gone to enforcement, say the
spending is ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DEA and other agencies deal with the suppliers, but you
block one artery and another will soon be created to supply the
user,'' said Sheila R. Maxwell, an assistant professor of criminal
justice at Michigan State University in East Lansing, Mich.
``Research has shown that curtailing the demand is much more
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement agencies say they rely on the federal help
to bust major traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our local drug agents can go after the street dealers, but we
need the DEA to go after the higher-ranking drug dealers,'' said
Police Chief Gary McKamie of Euless, whose department is a member
of two DEA task forces, one in Fort Worth and another at
Dallas/Fort Worth Airport. ``The federal resources are just greater
than what we have locally.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, a heroin investigation has meant nonstop work for six
to eight months for DEA agents.
</P>
<P>
   For Mercado, who was born in Puerto Rico and is the only member
of his family in law enforcement, it's a beloved yet tedious
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``You woke up early in the morning to follow the heroin
dealer,'' Mercado said. ``And you put him to bed at night. In
between, you find out about his friends, the telephone calls, the
restaurants and all the other stops.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Mercado acknowledged, friendly relationships developed
with relatives of dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You visit with a dealer at his home 10 to 15 times in an
investigation,'' Mercado said. ``You play with his kids. You would
feel for the kids and wife.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mercado said his job came first.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time, you would remember what you were there to do,''
Mercado said. ``You would remember that this dealer is spreading
all this poison. I had to make that arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980902.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
