<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-LOSSES-NYT &LR;      09-02 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-LOSSES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 RUSSIA'S IMPACT ON U.S. BANKS DWARFED BY '80s LATIN CRISIS  
(bl) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Chase Manhattan Corp. and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
on Wednesday joined the chorus of financial services companies
announcing losses on their business in Russia, investors may soon
be able to breathe more easily about the Russian impact.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of American banks' exposure to Russia, analysts say,
pales in comparison to the hits taken as a result of the Latin
American debt crisis in the 1980s. And quick action by several
American financial institutions in recent days to mark down their
possible losses by as much as 85 percent, should limit the damage
to their bottom line, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad quarter,'' said Carla D'Arista, a managing director
and banking analyst at Friedman, Billings, Ramsey &AMP; Co. in
Arlington, Va. But, she added, ``It's in no way meaningfully
derailed the fundamentals of the largest U.S. banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Chase Manhattan said it expected to take a $200
million charge in the third quarter, primarily for losses in Russia
and Asia. Its direct Russian exposure was about $250 million, with
the bulk of that, about $140 million, related to commercial banking
activities, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to institutional investors and investment funds
collateralized by ruble-denominated Russian treasury securities was
about $210 million, Chase said, with the majority of this exposure
backed by ``significant'' non-Russian assets.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also reported trading revenues for July and August of
approximately $160 million. Analysts said that was a significant
drop from average monthly trading revenues of about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have captured most of what can be the impact of
Russia,'' said Chase executive vice president and treasurer Dina
Dublon.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, which has an inventory of about $50 million of Russian
securities remaining, still expects to post ``substantial''
earnings in the third quarter, Ms. Dublon said.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette said Wednesday that it earned about
$40 million before taxes during the first two months of the third
quarter, after taking into account losses in Russia. A spokeswoman
declined to be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner Bank AG, Germany's third-largest bank, said Wednesday
that its unsecured credit exposure to Russia totaled 1 billion
marks, ($571 million), bringing the total for the big four German
banks to less than 4 billion marks of unsecured lending. Dresdner
bank has already made provisions to cover about 60 percent of its
Russian loan exposure. Recently, Commerzbank AG has reported 1
billion marks in exposure; Deutsche Bank AG said it had 1.35
billion marks, and Bayerische Hypo-und Vereinsbank AG 500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Citicorp, Bankers Trust, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, Barclays and Nomura Securities also reported heavy losses
on Russian business. Among the largest were those of Salomon Smith
Barney and Bankers Trust. Salomon, a unit of the Travelers Group,
said it lost an estimated $360 million after taxes in its arbitrage
and Russian-related credits businesses, while Bankers Trust put its
pretax trading loss at $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   But State Street Bank Corp. in Boston said Wednesday that recent
events in Russia, Asia and Latin America had had no significant
impact on its revenue and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week BankBoston Corp. said that it lost $30 million this
quarter in United States and international trading, including $10
million in Russia. BankAmerica, and J.P. Morgan also reported
trading losses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their Russian exposure, most banks, with the exception
of Bankers Trust, should report positive earnings for the third
quarter and see minimal impact in 1999, said Thomas Hanley, a
managing director at Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks have thrown in the kitchen sink in the third
quarter,'' he said. ``They faced up to the problem this time
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of 1998, foreign bank lending to Russia
totaled about $61.4 billion, according to the Bank for
International Settlements.
</P>
<P>
   German bank exposure equals about one half of that, Hanley said.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, major American money center banks have about $1.6
billion of pretax losses from Russia, Hanley estimated. Prior to
the Russian crisis, the banks' total exposure was about $6.4
billion. Pretax losses and withdrawn lines of credit have reduced
their net exposure to about $3.3 billion, he said, a modest
percentage of the banks' total capital of about $92 billion and
their total reserves of $15.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, at the height of the Latin American debt crisis
in 1984, loans from money center banks totaled about $58.5 billion,
outpacing the banks' total capital of $26.7 billion and reserves of
$4.1 billion, according to a Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
report.
</P>
<P>
   Banks needed several years to recover from the losses, Hanley
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
