<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OVERCOMING, NOT JUST SURVIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alone, with a magazine and her private thoughts.
That's how Monica Seles spent the time before she was summoned onto
the Arthur Ashe Stadium court Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In the bustling players' lounge, she stretched herself out by
the window in two facing chairs, draped a towel across her ankles,
and remained in that detached position longer than most
24-year-olds could.
</P>
<P>
   You wondered how many times she might have drifted off to a sad
remembrance of her father, or even the terrible stabbing event that
five years ago nearly shattered and certainly reconfigured her
life. But then a new man in her corner said this would be missing
the essential point about one of the most fascinating and estimable
figures in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica deals with things,'' said Gavin Hopper, her new coach,
after Seles arranged Joannette Kruger's routine departure from the
United States Open, with a 6-2, 6-3 victory in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   It took Hopper one tournament, one fortnight, to realize the
depth of her ability to cope. Karolj Seles succumbed to stomach
cancer, at 64, one week before the French Open last May. A grieving
Monica wore the wedding ring of Karolj _ her father and best friend
and coach _ around her neck, and strung together a chain of
victories that took her all the way to a three-set defeat in the
final to Arantxa Sanchez Vicario. If anything, this was a rousing
triumph of the will.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hadn't been on the court for months,'' he said. ``But the
thing about Monica is that she was prepared by her father to take
control of situations by herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that what every parenting deal is, or ought to be? As it
applies to tennis, the temptations are often too great, the
emotions too wild. The fine line between earnest coach and abusive
parent is recklessly crossed. This is an offense that just keeps
repeating itself, especially when young tennis girls are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Pierce resurfaced here Tuesday after a five-year ban as the
mentor of someone else's child, but he was still lobbing verbal
grenades at his estranged daughter, Mary; still telling her that
she remains a nobody as long as she isn't No. 1. And then there is
the latest tennis teen-ager to flee daddy dearest, Mirjana Lucic,
with her mother and siblings, amid charges of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is between her and her dad and her family,'' Seles said
curtly when asked about Lucic. But could it just be coincidence
that Seles, herself prematurely forced to adulthood, is partners
with Lucic in women's doubles here this week?
</P>
<P>
   For all her cuts and slings and arrows, Seles, by all accounts,
had a demanding coach but no insufferable dad. Karolj Seles, she
has said, never forced her to the court when she didn't want to
play, never burdened her with the responsibility of winning for
anyone but herself. He even presented her the option of getting out
for good as she nursed the scars of being attacked in Germany by a
deranged fan of her rival, Steffi Graf.
</P>
<P>
   External wounds heal much faster than those to the heart. Cheap
psychology, yes, but, in Seles' case, probably on the money. She is
not No. 1, may never be again, but Hopper wanted to say she is much
more than a survivor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at a tape of her playing Sabatini in 1991 and then
switched to one of her playing Venus Williams three weeks ago,'' he
said. ``It's true, she's not in great shape right now, but she is a
better player than she was. It's just that the other players got
bigger, stronger. They caught up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopper, an Australian, formerly coached Amanda Coetzer but
signed on to chaperon Seles along the road to a fitter place, from
where she might add to her nine Grand Slams. He has two young
daughters himself, and one, 7-year-old Jade, is something of a
prodigy at the Bollettieri Academy in Florida, where Seles once
happened upon them. Hopper's firm but gentle style reminded her of
Karolj.
</P>
<P>
   ``She saw that I wasn't the mean tennis dad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At her father's urging, Seles made a call, and Hopper was soon
at the Seles homestead, trying to bridge a language gap with a
dying man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those last few weeks of his life, Karolj kept saying that
Monica's life after tennis was what he was most concerned with,''
Hopper said. ``He wanted her last years in tennis to be happy. Of
course he wanted her to try to get the most of her ability, to put
in the work, but only if she could again love doing the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopper was asked if he recalled any last request Karolj Seles
had made.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I want my daughter to enjoy the here and now.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
