<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS-REDSKINS RIVALRY VIBRANT AFTER 66 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Giants safety Percy Ellsworth on
Wednesday offered this summary of the appeal and importance of
Sunday's season-opening game with the Washington Redskins:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a home game, it's a game against the team most people
think will win our division and it's a game against a team we hate.
The Redskins are going to come up here mad and they're going to
come up here trying to kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man,'' he said, ``it's the best opening game we could possibly
ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   The season hasn't even started, but the Giants-Redskins rivalry,
which dates to 1932, is already in midseason form.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, via a conference call with reporters, Redskins Coach
Norv Turner said that he expected a physical and emotional game.
His counterpart, Jim Fassel of the Giants, called Sunday's matchup
``a huge game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Giants linebacker Jessie Armstead:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Redskins have a bad taste in their mouths because we beat
them for the division and then they had to watch us celebrate. We
know they want revenge. But if they think it's going to be a
cakewalk, they're in for a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   There has rarely been anything ordinary about games between the
Giants and Redskins, who have met 130 times. They have had
important, weighty struggles, and games that bordered on the inane.
Thirty-two years ago, Washington defeated the Giants, 72-41, the
most points scored by a National Football League team in a
regular-season game and the most points scored by two teams in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the Giants won the National Football Conference
East title with a stirring 30-10 victory over Washington at Giants
Stadium. It was a game that left the Redskins out of the playoffs
for a fifth successive season and it moved Washington to rework its
roster with the Giants in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants rushed for 287 yards in their two games against
Washington last year. Like other teams Washington faced, the Giants
found the Redskins' defense soft up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Washington spent $57.4 million to lure the
free-agent tackles Dan Wilkinson and Dana Stubblefield to bolster
the defensive front four. It is the biggest reason Washington has
emerged as at least co-favorites in the NFC East with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a normal football response,'' Fassel said of the
Redskins' off-season acquisitions. ``Who won the division? What do
they do? We've got to stop what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants no doubt will still test the middle of the Redskins'
line with fullback Charles Way, who had two of his best games last
season against Washington, rushing for a combined 133 yards on 28
carries.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants will surely test the edges of the Redskins'
defense as well. A short passing game could be crucial, too, since
the Giants' running backs may offer a speed mismatch against the
Redskins' linebacking corps.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, expect a spirited game, with the bad blood between
the teams resurfacing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Washington quarterback Gus Frerotte left the first
meeting, a 7-7 tie, between the teams last year with an injured
neck when he head-butted a retaining wall after scoring a
touchdown. Ellsworth said he would be sure to remind Frerotte of
that blunder Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I'll bring that up to him,'' Ellsworth said. ``That
was a crazy thing to do and I'm going to mess with him about it. We
have a lot of guys who talk out there, and so do they. You watch
closely, you'll see who dislikes who pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth was asked to be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say it's a healthy dislike all the way around,'' he
said. ``Throw everybody in there. You've got two good teams
fighting for the same thing. That's what makes a real rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
