<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VISIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Gov. Bush backs Millner at posh fund-raiser
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush touted Guy Millner before
about 550 Republican activists Wednesday, bolstering the GOP
gubernatorial candidate's campaign bank account and racking up IOUs
the Texan can call in if he decides to run for the presidency in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, who paid $1,000 per person, dined on steak and
salmon in a private dinner before hearing from the son of former
President George Bush, an event Millner's campaign predicted would
add about $500,000 to its already bulging coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a winnable race. Guy Millner is a good candidate, and
one I think the people of Georgia will support,'' Bush said,
speaking to reporters in a news conference at Peachtree-DeKalb
Airport before heading to the pricey event at the Grand Hyatt hotel
in Buckhead. ``There's one thing I can help do, and that is raise
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, considered a leading contender for the GOP presidential
nomination in two years, spent much of the morning on a similar
mission for Republican U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell, holding press
conferences and fund-raisers in Columbus and Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the first of at least five potential presidental
aspirants scheduled to campaign for Millner before the November
election. Publishing magnate Steve Forbes, former Vice President
Dan Quayle, 1996 presidential hopeful Lamar Alexander and Tennessee
Sen. Fred Thompson also will stomp for Millner in his contest with
Democrat Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it helps to show leadership around the country
recognizes the importance of this race,'' Millner said, noting that
Republicans are trying to break the Democrats' 129-year lock on the
governor's mansion in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   But the visits could be almost as important to would-be
presidential contenders who want to make contacts with the party
faithful in a state that can deliver considerable electoral votes
in an early primary, political scientists said. Bush, who this year
is trying to make history as the first Texas governor to be
re-elected to a four-year term, said he is still undecided about a
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats panned the visit as an overt attempt by a presidential
hopeful to gain ground for the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Though President Clinton has appeared in an event for
Coverdell's opponent, Democrat Michael Coles, Barnes said he never
planned to solicit support from Vice President Al Gore or Clinton,
whom he's roundly criticized for the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Barnes said, Gov. Zell Miller and former Sen. Sam Nunn,
both highly respected Georgia Democrats, will headline his
fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
