<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane Earl's Entry Expected
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricane Earl was expected to saturate Georgia today and Friday
after slamming ashore along Florida's panhandle, prompting
emergency officials to start bracing for floods.
</P>
<P>
   Though still offshore, Earl's effects were already being felt
along the Florida's Gulf Coast by early Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   On Santa Rosa Island, outside Pensacola, cars plied flooded
streets while trash cans, roofing shingles, small plants and realty
signs flew through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusted up to 50 mph as Panama City Beach residents boarded
up homes and businesses. Many tourists packed up and left.
</P>
<P>
   Apalachicola to the east was practically deserted as stores and
even the bank closed up.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, hurricane-force winds extended out 90 miles to
the east of the center of the storm and tropical storm-force winds
of 39 mph extended out 175 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Earl, which was expected to hit the northwest
Florida with winds of 90 to 100 mph early today and then cut a wide
path northeast through Georgia to South Carolina, is that it's been
an erratic hurricane. The Georgia Emergency Management Agency was
preparing for the possibility that the Flint River may overflow
around Albany, but weather officials said that right now the state
is likely only to get a healthy rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river levels are down, so southwest Georgia may escape
severe flooding,'' said GEMA spokesman Buzz Weiss. ``We're
preparing for the worst because we've had this experience before...
Alberto, our old friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Alberto brought a flood that was the worst
natural disaster in the state's history after it dumped 24 inches
of rain in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Earl also is expected to cool off Atlanta. The forecast for
today was a high of 80 degrees, with a 60 percent of chance of
showers during the day, and lows in the upper 60s, with an 80
percent chance of rain tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earl is a bit sluggish,'' he said. ``That's concerning because
Tropical Storm Alberto was sluggish and it stalled over southwest
Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued a flash flood warning for
southwest Georgia and said Earl was expected to bring 5 to 6 inches
of rain along its arch from Panama City, Fla., to Macon to Raleigh,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   John Feldt, the hydrologist in charge of the Southeast River
Forecast Center in Peachtree City, said several inches of rain
could mean ``problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I think we're going to get a very welcome rain,''
he told The Associated Press Wednesday afternoon. ``As far as
flooding, I would say unless it stalls or slows down, we should be
in acceptable shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
