<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-RELAPSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS STRUGGLE TO HANDLE TEEN'S UPS AND DOWNS
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE LEE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kristen Taylor is back in rehab, almost nine months after her
parents had her arrested and jailed in a last-ditch attempt to
break her three-year heroin addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor served 28 days in Tarrant County Jail in December and
January before being released to a treatment center and then to her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   She was doing well, working and attending counseling sessions,
but had a relapse in May, her parents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her why she did. She said, `Just no reason,' '' said
her father, Tommy Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Because she is part of Tarrant County's drug court program,
Kristen Taylor, 19, was not arrested for violating the terms of her
probation. Instead, she was sent to a six-month rehabilitation
program in Little Rock, Ark., Tommy Taylor said. Her parents are
paying for the program.
</P>
<P>
   The judge chose Little Rock to isolate the teen-ager from her
friends, many of whom are former or current drug users.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the thing; she kept running into people,'' her father
said. ``One of the times when she relapsed, she ran into someone
(with heroin) at a filling station. I'm sure it is just as readily
available up there, but those daily temptations are not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Taylor and his wife, Barbara, were not allowed to write or
visit their daughter for her first few weeks at the rehab center.
They got together on the July Fourth weekend, but Kristen Taylor
was not allowed to leave the center.
</P>
<P>
   The teen has since moved to a halfway house and is scheduled to
be released this month. Her rehabilitation term was reduced because
of the progress she is making, her father said. She and her parents
keep in touch through letters and telephone calls. Tommy Taylor
said his daughter is considering getting a job in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Taylor could not be reached to comment because of
confidentiality rules at the treatment center.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy and Barbara Taylor are still getting used to the
adjustments they made to cope with their daughter's addiction. They
moved into a smaller home this summer in Bedford, Texas, partly to
defray the costs of the treatment and a defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Taylor, an insurance salesman who is on the
Hurst-Euless-Bedford school board, started teaching this semester
in a vocational program at O.D. Wyatt High School in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed it. He was really starting to withdraw, dealing with
Kristen all the time,'' Barbara Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Taylor said he has no regrets about his decision to have
his daughter jailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went up there to visit ... a man came up and said,
`You're Tommy Taylor. I want you to know that what you did helped
me,' '' Taylor said. ``He had had his son arrested, and he said,
`It saved my son's life.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
