<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shortstop DeRosa gains opportunity
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years removed from the University of Pennsylvania campus,
Mark DeRosa had made good progress through the Braves system, but
nothing that suggested to him that a Tuesday night phone call would
be summoning him to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, such is Atlanta's state at shortstop. With Walt Weiss
sitting out a week after a cortisone treatment for a chronic left
quadriceps, with Ozzie Guillen nursing a sore thumb, the Braves
purchased DeRosa's contract from Class AA Greenville to protect
themselves at short in a September surprise.
</P>
<P>
   It might also mean an end to outfielder Damon Hollins' days with
the organization. To make room on the 40-man roster for DeRosa, the
Braves designated Hollins for assignment, meaning he can be claimed
by any team over the next five business days. A seven-year veteran
of the organization, Hollins hit .264 at Class AAA Richmond and at
age 24, had not made substantial progress toward making the Atlanta
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still young. He has a future,'' said general manager John
Schuerholz. ``But he had not played as well as he might have this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   DeRosa hit .267 with Greenville with 26 doubles, eight homers
and 49 RBI. But he made 20 errors in 125 games, which interests the
Braves most. Invited to the major league camp last spring, he made
a strong first impression but never envisioned finishing the season
in Atlanta. Until Weiss recovers, he may see playing time through
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't played a lot (2 1/2 minor league seasons) but he's
an athlete,'' said manager Bobby Cox. ``He's been playing very good
defense. He had a solid year with the bat. He's going to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Odalis intro
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are not planning any further September call-ups,
after third baseman Wes Helms is recalled today. But left-hander
Odalis Perez already scored the first strong impression, after
throwing a scoreless seventh inning Tuesday night. He said he was
nervous but for just one pitch. His fastball topped out at 97 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone rings and they tell me I'm up,'' Perez said. ``So,
this is my opportunity. I've got to do my job. I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez threw a 156 1/3 innings this season (23 starts in
Greenville and 13 relief appearances in Richmond). Though he
experienced some shoulder trouble in April _ he worked on strict
pitch-counts in 1997 to avoid arm problems _ Perez wound up
striking out 165 with just 60 walks.
</P>
<P>
   Javy, meet Doggie
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez caught Greg Maddux for the first time all season
Wednesday night, taking over Eddie Perez's usual duty. The purpose
was two-pronged. Lopez will be teamed with Maddux during the
postseason, which gives them at least one game to re-acquaint
themselves on the field. The other is related to offense, since
Andres Galarraga began serving his suspension Wednesday night and
Lopez entered the game with seven homers in his last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galy's out of the lineup,'' said Cox. ``You can't sit 80 home
runs, I don't think.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez hit in Galarraga's clean-up spot.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart's limp
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Keith Lockhart is hopeful sitting out Wednesday,
combined with today's off-day, will be enough to cool off a
strained right hamstring he sustained Tuesday night while trying to
field a Derek Bell grounder. Already slated for left (non-throwing)
shoulder surgery after the season to repair a torn rotator cuff,
Lockhart has never encountered hamstring trouble before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 13th season and I played 11 without really
anything,'' he said. ``It's just tough to be consumed by an injury
all the time, whether it's a shoulder or whatever. You try to mask
it as much as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
