<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No reduction for Galarraga
 &HT;    ByThomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fax was in his clubhouse letter box waiting for him, but
Bobby Cox gave Andres Galarraga the news Wednesday before he got to
the envelope: Take some time off. Now.
</P>
<P>
   National League president Len Coleman denied the Braves first
baseman's appeal of his suspension, letting stand without comment
Galarraga's three-game penalty for ``instigating a bench-clearing
incident,'' as Coleman's letter called it, on Aug. 22 against Los
Angeles. Also upheld was the $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping at least one day (in reduction),'' Galarraga
said. ``I was expecting two days, max. I think it's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga was instructed by Coleman to begin serving the
suspension immediately, which means he missed Wednesday night's
final game with Houston and will miss the first two of four games
against the Mets in New York this weekend. Darren Dreifort, the
Dodgers pitcher who hit Galarraga on both Aug. 15 and 22, when the
fight ensued, was not penalized.
</P>
<P>
   Despite interim Dodgers general manager Tommy Lasorda's demand
that manager Bobby Cox also be punished for threatened retaliation,
Cox never was included in Coleman's judgement. But it did not mean
that Cox accepted Wednesday's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let it drop at this,'' he said. ``It was intentional both
times. I don't give a damn what anybody says. And that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves made a 45-minute appeal to Coleman on Tuesday,
including video tapes of both Dreifort plunkings. Although the
incident seemed to stem the barrage Galarraga had been withstanding
_ he has been hit just once in the 10 games since the fight _ it
could not have helped his case that Galarraga served a three-game
suspension for the same offense just last year. He has charged the
mound three times in his 13-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I though (the hearing) would do a little bit of good,
presenting our story, which is the truth,'' Cox said. ``But it
didn't get us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to tell everybody,'' Galarraga said, ``(that)
we can't charge the mound, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
