A6096 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS03-COX     09-02 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carolina tries West Coast style
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Atlanta Falcons line up against Carolina on Sunday in
the season opener, the Panthers will offer something different. The
West Coast passing offense will be nothing like the more
traditional look Carolina offered in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, the Panthers replaced offensive coordinator
Joe Pendry with former Green Bay receivers coach Gil Haskell, and
he brought with him parts of the offense devised by, among others,
former 49er and Stanford coach Bill Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the passing offense relies more on short, timing
routes, and quarterback Kerry Collins is called upon to take a
shorter drop, generally three to five steps, and get rid of the
ball in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina coach Dom Capers said the decision to change wasn't
difficult. After watching the 49ers run circles around the NFC West
for years, and seeing other teams have success with versions of the
same game plan, he called Haskell and offered a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always go back to the things you have the hardest time
defending,'' Capers said. ``I have great respect for what (Packers
coach) Mike Holmgren (a former 49er offensive coordinator) has done
... and playing against them the last two years, we had as tough a
time defending them as any team we played.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense will take advantage of Carolina tight end and
Falcon-killer Wesley Walls' ability to find seams in coverages and
get yards after the catch.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, who had the 26th-ranked passing attack in the NFL
last year when they averaged 177.8 yards per game, ran it well in
the preseason, completing 91 of 149 passes (61.1 percent) for 1,146
yards, six touchdowns and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   But the running game has struggled, averaging just 78 yards per
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not running the 49er offense; let's make that clear,''
said Rich Brooks, Falcons assistant head coach and defensive
coordinator. ``The passing game is the biggest change. The running
game is a mixture, probably leaning toward what they did a year ago
(with a lot of fullback-lead plays).
</P>
<P>
   ``(The passing game is) a problem because the ball is out so
quick,'' Brooks said, ``unless you can reroute some receivers,
disrupt the timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta right defensive end Chuck Smith, who has five sacks in
six games against Carolina, is not happy about the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to have a good secondary; they got to hold (receivers)
up,'' Smith said. ``You're going to have to blitz some. They just
drop, 1-2-3, boom! and the ball's out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
