<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLOTS COUNTED AND FOLEY IS CAPTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ His teammates are convinced that Glenn Foley
is not only their quarterback but their leader, too. Wednesday they
elected him the offensive captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor, obviously. I didn't expect it,'' said Foley,
who has had only five previous career starts before Sunday's
regular-season opener against the 49ers in San Francisco. ``It's
been a rocky road to become the starter.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Foley suffered two season-ending injuries. In
1995, he suffered a dislocated shoulder and last season he tore
knee ligaments.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the title of captain is merely an honorific. Last
season, it was quarterback Neil O'Donnell. But it took Joe Namath
four years to be voted the captain by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mariucci, the 49ers' head coach, was asked Wednesday,
``What do you think of Foley?'' Mariucci knows the Jets' personnel.
He was able to point out the first and last names of each member of
the Jets' defensive backfield, including the rookie free safety,
Kevin Williams. But Mariucci, a former quarterback coach, froze on
Foley's first name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane Foley? I think Shane Foley's a good player,'' said
Mariucci. ``A smart guy and a good decision-maker. I worked him out
in college. I think he's doing well for himself. I think he's in a
perfect situation for what he's playing. They're going to run the
football which I think is an ideal situation for a quarterback to
be in.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand if the name Glenn Foley doesn't come as
easily as, say, Steve Young or even Neil O'Donnell. But to his
teammate Keyshawn Johnson, Foley was the obvious pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for him,'' said Johnson. ``Everyone likes him. You
look at him. He's the quarterback. It makes a lot of sense. You
want him to be the leader. I think he likes being the leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been one to play hard and have confidence,'' he
said. ``You have to perform consistently every day, and leadership
qualities go with that. This is a big honor for me. It's the guys I
work with. It's not height or weight or experience.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not have an abundance of those _ he is 6 feet 2 inches
tall. He put on 15 pounds to tip the scales at 220. He has never
produced a complete-game victory. Over all, he has seen action in
parts of 13 games since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Parcells told Foley that he had been elected captain,
the coach added, ``now you're going to have to talk to me.'' That
was a response to Foley, who has complained to Parcells that, ``I
play better when I don't have to talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the vote says something about Foley, Parcells
replied, ``absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a secret ballot,'' he said. ``There's no raising
hands. We bring in the papers and make them vote. There's no time
for lobbying in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets you motivated,'' said Wayne Chrebet. ``He's not afraid
to say how he feels. He'll stick his nose in there, and if guys are
banging heads, he's banging heads, too. He's a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the inexperienced Foley, a pair of senior
linebackers each got the same number of votes and were elected
defensive co-captains: Mo Lewis, a Jet since 1991, and 34-year-old
Pepper Johnson. Johnson had the honor last year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
