<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 USWeb, CKS Group in $300 million deal   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
In a merger of Bay Area Internet-consulting pioneers, design firm
USWeb Corp. yesterday agreed to buy advertising agency CKS Group
Inc. in a stock swap worth about $300 million.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The combined company will resurface under the new name Reinvent
Communications Inc., which company officials hope will take
advantage of the two firm's strengths _ USWeb's technological
acumen and CKS's creative marketing prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies have lost client opportunities because we've
lacked each other's depth'' of services, said Joe Firmage, chief
executive of Santa Clara-based USWeb.
</P>
<P>
   Firmage will take the same role with Reinvent when the deal is
completed around year end.
</P>
<P>
   Cupertino-based CKS Group Chairman Mark Kvamme will be chairman
of the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on a cell phone while they were driving from one
headquarters to another, Kvamme and Firmage scoffed at reports that
they would bump heads on strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We immediately saw the opportunities and came together very
quickly,'' Kvamme said. ``We have a complete vision lock, kind of
like a mind meld.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts said the deal makes strategic sense in a
rapidly changing Internet advertising market.
</P>
<P>
   However, they also said USWeb faces the challenge of reinventing
its own brand image and potential pitfalls in assimilating the
creative culture of CKS Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one fell swoop, USWeb has considerably bolstered their
creative capabilities,'' said analyst Ullas Naik of First Albany
Corp. ``The problem is they have spent a lot of money investing in
the USWeb brand name.''
</P>
<P>
   Each company has about 800 employees, and Firmage said there are
no plans to cut back staff. The companies have not decided where
its new headquarters will be located.
</P>
<P>
   This is the biggest purchase yet for USWeb, which has grown
largely through acquisition. USWeb provides Internet consulting and
design services for companies like Chevron, Charles Schwab and
Harley-Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   But Firmage said his firm recently lost a major account, which
he declined to name, because USWeb could not provide a creative
marketing plan.
</P>
<P>
   Kvamme, meanwhile, said CKS found it could not even submit a bid
recently because the potential client required a powerful computer
CKS did not have.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've seen in the marketplace is the need for a company
that can truly integrate creative capabilities with technology,''
Firmage said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Reinvent will have the expertise to deal with a
client's company technical and marketing executives _ an important
strength as businesses move toward Web commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given where the market was going, I felt they needed to beef
up their technological side,'' said Steven Horen, an analyst with
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities.
</P>
<P>
   USWeb will exchange 1.5 shares for each of CKS Group's 15.9
million shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   CKS stock, which last year hit a high of $46.25 per share,
closed up $1.13 at $15.25 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   USWeb shares dropped about 14 percent, closing down $2.13 at
$12.32.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
