<SLUG> BC-YU-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Intel Insider Tells How Chipmaker Stays on Top   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Intel's rise to the ranks of a superpower in the semiconductor
industry has been due in part to a willingness to take risks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a senior vice president and the man in charge of Intel's
microprocessors, Albert Yu details some of those risks in his new
book, ``Creating the Digital Future.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yu's book leaves out the one story that illustrates his own
risk-taking credentials.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year career veteran at Intel left the chipmaker briefly
in 1977 to start a company called Video Brain that turned out to be
an unsuccessful attempt to build home computers six years before
anyone was ready for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unbelievable task,'' Yu said in an interview. He
said when the home PC finally became a hit in 1983, ``it was
basically no different than what we had put together, except we
used audio tape, not a floppy disk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a risk,'' Yu said. ``Financially, I didn't do well.''
</P>
<P>
   But that experience provided him with some valuable lessons,
including the need to keep an entrepreneurial edge. ``Intel is a
30-year-old startup,'' Yu said. ``A lot of our success is due to
the way we manage.''
</P>
<P>
   His book provides some management tips to maintain that edge,
including the company's legendary cubicle culture. Everyone,
including chief executive Craig Barrett, works in a standard gray
cubicle. ``We have no doors,'' Yu said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the modern startup, which tends to have a loose informal
culture, discipline plays an important role in Intel's corporate
culture. ``Meetings start on time,'' Yu said. ``If someone's not
there on time, we look at that guy funny. ... The point is, the
customer expects us to do certain things.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees are also encouraged to practice ``constructive
confrontation.'' For example, when Intel was struggling to put out
the latest version of its 386 computer chip _ a precursor to
today's popular Pentiums _ Yu fought efforts to remove cache memory
functions from the chip.
</P>
<P>
   People ``presented me with data showing they could get the chip
out much faster, and manufacturing would be much easier'' without
the cache, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yu said they were right and the company went on to create a
successful chip without cache memory. ``Just because I have a
position of power doesn't mean I'm right,'' Yu said.
</P>
<P>
   Yu's book is not a tell-all, and he doesn't use it to criticize
anyone other than himself. That's understandable since he still
works at Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``His book really outlines some of the challenges Intel has
faced, and how they've overcome them,'' said Linley Gwennap, editor
of Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
