<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-ROUTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEROIN SUPPLY SHIFTS SOUTH, PUTS PRESSURE ON TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARISA TAYLOR and SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a dramatic shift, Mexico and Colombia have edged out Asia as
leading U.S. suppliers of heroin, prompting more drug traffickers
to use Texas as a major heroin smuggling route, Drug Enforcement
Administration reports show.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of European lab technicians, Colombian traffickers
hit on a formula in 1993 for producing high-grade heroin, according
to authorities. Forced to compete, Mexican drug organizations began
producing larger quantities of better-refined black tar heroin two
years ago for U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heroin has also come across from Mexico for a long time; it's
one of the older drugs,'' said Roberto Medina, U.S. customs
associate special agent in charge in El Paso. ``What's made it more
popular and common is its better refinement.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in what authorities describe as a marriage of convenience,
Mexican and Colombian drug kingpins have joined forces to push pure
heroin into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies suspect that Colombian drug cartel lab
technicians have been teaching Mexican drug organizations how to
better refine opium poppies to produce white powder heroin, which
is even more potent than black tar or brown powder dope. Mexican
drug organizations usually skip the chemical treatment and
filtering steps that turn heroin into a white powder.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, heroin addicts have traditionally preferred
inexpensive Mexican black tar, even when it was only 30 percent
pure.
</P>
<P>
   Black tar heroin, still considered cheap, is now hitting the
streets at 70 percent pure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The border is wide open, everything is coming from Mexico. The
dope is just pure,'' said John Hyder, a heroin addict and a
prisoner in Lew Sterrett Justice Center in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian traffickers first turned to Mexican syndicates after a
crackdown against the cocaine empire in south Florida in the late
1980s forced them to find new routes. At first, Mexican syndicates
were content to be paid per haul of cocaine to allow Colombian drug
lords to use their established routes.
</P>
<P>
   Later, impatient with the deal and bolstered by their increased
wealth, Mexican cartels demanded half the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant the Colombians had to give up territory and cities
in the U.S.,'' said Don Ferrarone, a retired Drug Enforcement
Administration official who led the Houston office. ``They had to
say to the Mexicans, `OK, if you sell on the street, we're not
going to come after you, we're not going to kill you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Colombian drug lords eventually want to monopolize the U.S.
heroin market, just as they do in the cocaine trade. They even
require cocaine dealers to sell heroin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a buyer and you want to buy 250 kilos of cocaine,
the Colombians say, `We're going to give you 2 kilos of heroin and
you're going to sell it for this price,' '' Ferrarone said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
