<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-CUSTOMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTINCT A KEY TOOL FOR CUSTOMS INSPECTORS
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   D/FW AIRPORT _ The woman with a Panamanian passport in her hand
and a baby on her hip made a blip on Jeff Trahan's internal
drug-seeking radar as he scanned the crowd in the international
terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Trahan, a U.S. Customs Service inspector, stopped the woman as
she got off a flight from Panama City _ a place on the ``hot list''
for smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Her answers to his questions raised more red flags.
</P>
<P>
   The woman had traveled from Panama City to San Jose, Costa Rica,
to Guatemala to Dallas/Fort Worth Airport. When she said she had
only been to the United States twice, Trahan wondered why she spoke
English so well. Then, there was the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trend,'' he said. ``Smugglers travel with kids to throw
you off the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Politely but persistently, Trahan questioned the woman and
searched her luggage, but found no evidence of drugs and told her
that she was free to go. He switched his radar back on.
</P>
<P>
   With their appointed roles as front-line troops in the war
against drugs, customs inspectors have much broader search and
seizure powers than other law enforcement agencies. They can search
any traveler in the airport _ any time _ without a warrant, and
they can send suspects to the hospital for X-rays to see whether
they have swallowed drug-filled balloons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet their challenge is daunting: pinpointing the ``mules''
bringing in heroin and other drugs among the millions of passengers
that travel through D/FW's international terminals each year.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, as many as 40 customs inspectors scrutinize 4,000
baggage-toting travelers looking for clues to the potential drug
smugglers. Could it be the businessman with callouses? The
grandfather who appears jittery and avoids eye contact?
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1997, D/FW customs inspectors seized 382 pounds of
narcotics, including 22 pounds of heroin, said Anne Marie Spiess,
director of passenger operations for customs at D/FW. A year
earlier, they seized 5 pounds of illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Although computers generate profiles of potential smugglers,
experienced inspectors say that instincts, tips and detective work
are better indicators. Because even tiny quantities of heroin can
be profitable, the drug can be hidden almost anywhere, and
smugglers change their methods as quickly as inspectors detect a
technique.
</P>
<P>
   D/FW agents have found heroin and cocaine in false bottoms of
suitcases, in surfboard bags, in shampoo and deodorant bottles, in
a skullcap woven to a woman's hair, in a 50-pound bag of rice.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, inspectors once detained a man who had had his thigh
surgically opened and filled with cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy couldn't walk by the time he got off the plane,''
Spiess said.
</P>
<P>
   But inspectors also must be on the lookout for counterfeit
trademarks, pornography, undeclared cash and harmful plants. And
they have a commitment to ensure that the majority of passengers
are cleared within five minutes of picking up their baggage, Spiess
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationwide, every customs office will tell you we never have
enough sets of eyes and brains out there,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a mad 2 p.m. rush on a recent weekday at D/FW, hundreds of
passengers clogged the baggage claim area after arriving from
Caracas, Venezuela; Frankfurt, Germany; London and Manchester,
England; Monterrey, Mexico; Panama City; and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Trahan and two other inspectors quickly scanned the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough _ especially on the weekends when you have 1,000
people at four carousels and an eight-man team of inspectors,''
Trahan said.
</P>
<P>
   He kept his eye on luggage tags to see where the travelers were
going. He reviewed passports, looking for travelers from Colombia.
He interrogated a young man in a wheelchair who was en route to New
Orleans from London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people use wheelchairs to throw you off, like the
babies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of smugglers tend to be foreign nationals, Spiess
said. The ``hot'' flights to watch come from Brazil, Chile,
Guatemala and Panama, and from Caracas, Venezuela, Mexico City and
Lima, Peru.
</P>
<P>
   But as politics change, so do the smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think eventually you will see Russia being used as a transit
area or Cuba, if things get settled there,'' Spiess said.
</P>
<P>
   Because smugglers often travel at short notice, many have new
passports and clothing. In some cases, inspectors have seen a
passenger with a price tag hanging from his suit.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors pepper any suspect with questions about
passports, tickets, travel plans and other issues for clues. In
many cases, smugglers don't buy their tickets, so they may be hard
pressed to answer inspectors' queries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you catch them in an outright lie, they fall apart,'' said
Trahan, 32, who worked six years on the Texas-Mexico border as a
customs inspector and canine enforcement officer before joining
D/FW agents last year.
</P>
<P>
   With their sweeping search authority, customs inspectors can
look through a traveler's wallet, ask a man to lift up his pants
leg or open gift boxes in luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Wallets can be a gold mine of information, Trahan said,
especially when it leads to the discovery of the ``$2,000 money
trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Colombia drug dealers pay their smugglers $2,000, he said.
The smuggler must pay $40 in airport taxes to leave Cali, Colombia,
and then has $1,960 left over _ most of it in $100 bills.
</P>
<P>
   Spiess once nabbed a heroin smuggler through her keen ear for
accents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a man who said that he was Puerto Rican,'' Spiess
said. ``I grew up in New York and realized his accent was not
Puerto Rican.''
</P>
<P>
   She checked into his ticket and found discrepancies in his
frequent flier number and passport. After some digging, she
pinpointed his identity: a cocaine trafficker who had escaped from
an Ecuadorean jail. This time, he had heroin hidden in the false
bottom of a suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials say they lack the latest technology to help
nab drug traffickers. If North Texas is designated as a
high-density drug trafficking area, an estimated $5 million in the
first year would help pay for additional law enforcement resources,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an agency, we are very enforcement-minded and want to take
drugs off the street,'' said Judy Turner, a spokeswoman for the
Customs Service in Houston. ``No matter how much we seize, we want
to be finding more.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
