u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STANFORD-LEUKEMIA-590     09-02 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-LEUKEMIA-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-GENERAL FIGHTS FOR SCHOOLS, AND FOR HIS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ga.)  (lb) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle made an unusual choice three years ago when it
tapped John Henry Stanford as superintendent of public schools. He
had no background in school administration, but the former Army
general and director of logistics in the Persian Gulf war did bring
a Patton-style intensity to his crusade to improve public education
here.
</P>
<P>
   He inspected schools as though they were platoons, rallied
corporate Seattle to create a charitable arm for public education,
and cajoled voters into approving a $150 million school levy that
they had rejected just months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   If Stanford's can-do spirit seemed a tad too self-assured at
times _ ``Perfect and improving'' was his standard response to a
``How are you?'' greeting _ people in Seattle by and large seemed
thrilled to have the retired two-star general in charge.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanford, who liked to boast that he had not missed a single
day of work in 38 years, is now fighting a more personal crusade,
one that has drawn an extraordinary amount of local attention and
that he is using to try to teach the schoolchildren of Seattle yet
another lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Stanford can do this, you know, you can do anything too,''
said the 59-year-old general, speaking by telephone in a raspy
voice, weakened by treatments he is undergoing for myelogenous
leukemia, a type of blood cancer, that was diagnosed this past
spring like a bolt from the blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a man who is not giving up,'' he continued, referring
to himself, as he is inclined to do, in the third person. ``So why
would you ever give up, just because you have a problem you don't
understand? Stanford's undergone three chemotherapies and a bone
transplant, and he's not giving up. He says he's coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   After the chemotherapy was deemed unsuccessful, Stanford
underwent an operation a few weeks ago, in which doctors injected
cells from his older sister's blood in the hope of regenerating
healthy cells in Stanford. But the doctors have put the odds of a
successful recovery at somewhere between 1 and 4 and 1 in 5.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's fight with leukemia has been the subject of extensive
newspaper and television coverage, and has set off a wave of public
support. The Stanford Book Fund, established by a foundation that
supports the public schools and widely publicized with a $78,000
contribution from Pearl Jam, the alternative rock group based here,
has quickly collected more than $500,000 _ more than enough to meet
the district's goal of buying at least one new book for each of its
47,500 students.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, Seattle plans to hold a citywide ``100 percent
back-to-school rally,'' largely to honor Stanford, who, as a black
general and the ambitious son of parents with a grade school
education, has frequently been compared by the Seattle media with
his famous friend Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Even from his hospital bed, Stanford said, he is carrying on as
much of the work of superintendent as he can. Visitors are limited,
but he speaks by phone with principals and other administrators and
says he is looking forward to two-way videophone conferences when
he returns home from the hospital in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   But the broader question for Seattle's roughly 100 public
schools is whether Stanford can successfully use his personal
struggle to galvanize further action on the promises he made when
he came here from the county manager's job in Atlanta, or whether
his illness will impede his efforts to change a system that has
been struggling to prevent middle-class flight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He is frequently on the telephone, still full of ideas. ``He
just called one day,'' after checking into the hospital this
spring, said BiHoa Caldwell, principal of the 625-student South
Shore Middle School in southeast Seattle. He wanted ``to know how
the kids were doing, what progress we were making. But it was
clearly tough on him, not to be out and about. He's a very
action-oriented person.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the attention given to his current plight gives him an
educational platform, Stanford is unable to cut the figure with
children that he did when he was healthy. He sometimes engaged in
wall-climbing exercises, and even flew a helicopter onto school
grounds for the children to reward them for their reading. When a
student asked him how much money he made, Stanford said: ``I make
$175,000 a year, and so can you if you read, read, read.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford has generally drawn praise for injecting a new sense of
vitality and optimism into the schools. When he first arrived, he
was a constant presence, giving speeches or appearing at community
events, always with the same message: ``You will doom this city
that you love if you fail to support the public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have tried to get that point across,'' he said.
``Everyone should feel a stake. You cannot do this business of
public education without the taxpayers who don't have children in
schools, parents who do have children in the schools, without
business, churches, temples and mosques, nonprofits, the government
at every level.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite some benchmark improvements _ SAT scores rose
recently for the third year, climbing above the national average,
and dropout rates have declined _ Stanford's mission is far from
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents, especially whites, still send their children to
private schools. The student population in the district is about 40
percent white, and the minority population, except for small
percentages of Hispanic and American Indian students, is roughly
split between blacks and Asian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of all parents with school-age children in
Seattle send them to private schools, compared with a national
average of around 14 percent. Overall, Seattle once had about
100,000 students in its public schools, but despite its population
boom in recent years, the number of children in the public schools
is less than half that. While some of the drop is attributable to
decreased family sizes, it also stems from declining confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were Stanford's ideas universally acclaimed here. His
suggestions that all public school students wear uniforms and that
parents be assessed with ``report cards'' on how well they prepare
and encourage their children, did not go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   One disgruntled teacher even established a Web site critical of
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Still the evidence of good will now, during his illness, is
overwhelming. He has been deluged with letters and hats, and his
request that well-wishers buy books for the schools instead of
flowers for him has obviously caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Pasquarella, president of the Alliance for Education, a
nonprofit organization that supports public education here, said
she believed his message was being heard. ``This city rallied
behind him even before he got sick,'' she said. ``That's the
important part of this story.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
