<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-BOMBINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DEFENDS ATTACK ON SUDANESE DRUG PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIM WEINER and STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the United States launched cruise missiles
against a factory in the Sudan on Aug. 20, it was unaware that the
plant made medicines, Secretary of Defense William Cohen said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that the incomplete intelligence was irrelevant
to President Clinton's decision to destroy it. He said the attack
was justified by information showing that the plant made Empta, a
key ingredient for VX, a nerve agent, and might be linked to Osama
bin Laden, a Saudi millionaire suspected of ordering the bombing of
the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The financial connection between the plant and bin Laden was at
most ``indirect,'' Cohen said Wednesday, modifying his assertion on
the night of the attack that ``he had contributed to this
particular facility.'' In the decision to destroy the factory, ``we
decided that if he had a connection, as we believe he did, it would
be wise to take it down,'' Cohen said Wednesday during a visit to
Fort Drum in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing the attack, Sudan's ambassador to the United States
said Wednesday that it showed Washington's ``Wild West,
shoot-first-boys-and-ask-questions-later philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the United States did not learn until at least three
days after the attack on the plant that it made medicine. Other
officials said intelligence officers had searched the factory's
Internet site and commercial databases and did not find lists of
medicines for sale.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with senators Wednesday, the CIA again asserted
that its reported discovery of Empta near the factory was proof
that the plant could be used by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as January, senior U.S. officials had no hard
evidence linking the Sudan to chemical weapons, according to
testimony before the Senate intelligence committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the CIA sent an agent to the plant, and that agent stole a
soil sample from inside the plant's gates, a few yards from the
building, officials said. The soil contained more than twice the
level of Empta that would be considered a trace, the director of
Central Intelligence, George Tenet, told senators Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Empta is a rare chemical used in the production of VX. The
United States insists there is no reason for it to be found in a
pharmaceutical plant. Others, however, say it could be confused
with pesticides that have similar characteristics. And the
international body that seeks to eliminate chemical weapons says
that theoretically there are other uses for Empta, though it does
not know of any commercial products using it.
</P>
<P>
   But Sudan's ambassador, Madhi Ibrahim Mohammed, insisted
Wednesday that the plant was not part of an Iraqi-backed effort to
make weapons for bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plant was not manufacturing chemical weapons for
terrorists,'' he said in a speech at the National Press Club. ``It
was engaged in manufacturing human and veterinary medicine, and was
an approved supplier of export medicine under the U.N.'s
food-for-oil program. The U.N. licensed the Sudan to send medicine
under that program, under the supervision of the U.N., to Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said Wednesday that the contract, awarded in
December, has never been fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed said his nation would have been glad to help root out
suspected terrorist operations if Americans had asked. ``They
instead organized a strike team and sent Tomahawk missiles soaring
into our capital, killing and maiming innocent civilians and
destroying private property,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador, who said his superiors had approached the White
House, the State Department and the FBI offering to help fight
terrorism over the past two years, said his government was
recalling him to Khartoum in protest of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed met on Tuesday with Susan Rice, assistant secretary of
state for African affairs. She told him the attack was ``not
against the Sudanese people, and not against the Sudanese
government, but against a facility where we had very credible
evidence that this chemical was being produced,'' said an American
official at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting and Mohammed's speech Wednesday disclosed how deeply
the two countries disagree over whether the Sudan has been an eager
backer of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, at the request of the United States and Saudi Arabia,
the Sudan expelled bin Laden, who moved to Afghanistan. It handed
over the fugitive terrorist known as Carlos to France in a CIA
operation.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not enough to remove the Sudan from Washington's
short list of states it considers sponsors of terrorism, where it
landed in 1993. Sudanese leaders and diplomats stand accused by the
United States of taking part in conspiracies to blow up landmarks
in New York and to assassinate President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt.
The American Embassy in Khartoum, closed in 1996 after a terrorist
threat, is shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudan remains on the list because it never carried out
promises to fight terrorism, said an American official who met with
Mohammed on Tuesday. ``The Sudan did not follow up against other
groups and the remnants of bin Laden's organization,'' the official
said. ``The Sudan and its supporters are now engaged in a public
relations campaign to convince the world that the Shifa plant was
not a legitimate target.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement by Sudanese officials that the plant produced
roughly half of the medicines used in the Sudan, one of the world's
poorest nations, has elicited some sympathy among European,
African, Arab and Asian diplomats. But the soil sample said to
contain Empta has convinced the United States government that the
plant was a legitimate target.
</P>
<P>
   BOMBERS SENT TO TRAIN ON GUAM
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ The Pentagon announced Wednesday that it was
sending three B-52s and three B-2 stealth bombers on a training
mission in Guam that officials characterized as a show of force
aimed at terrorist groups associated with Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   The six bombers _ along with tanker aircraft and 250 aviators
from Barksdale Air Force Base in Louisiana and Whiteman Air Force
Base in Missouri _ are to arrive on Sunday and stay for about a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Since launching cruise missiles against a paramilitary base in
Afghanistan and a factory in the Sudan, Defense Secretary William
Cohen and other administration officials have refused to rule out
the possibility of strikes against other sites associated with bin
Laden.
</P>
<P>
   The B-52s and B-2s are powerful bombers, capable of dropping
thousands of pounds of nuclear or conventional bombs. But the B-2s,
which cost $2.3 billion each, have never taken part in a combat
mission. The deployment to Guam will be only their second training
mission overseas; its first came earlier this year when two of the
black, bat-shaped bombers spent five weeks on training flights from
Guam.
</P>
<P>
   As a senator in 1989, Cohen derided the idea of using the B-2
against terrorists. ``It's the equivalent of saying we're going to
send a Rolls-Royce down into a combat zone to pick up groceries,''
he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force Air Combat Command said the six bombers would
carry only conventional weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes only two days after North Korea tested an
advanced medium-range missile by firing it over Japan. The test has
inflamed tensions, but a military official discounted the link
between the deployment and North Korea's test.
</P>
</TEXT>
