r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX     09-02 1987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE SAKE OF ARGUMENT, JUST WRITE ABOUT JEFF GORDON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The more Jeff Gordon wins on the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit, the
harder he is making my job. Because it seems that there is just no
right way to write about Jeff Gordon anymore.
</P>
<P>
   After Gordon won the Brickyard 400 last month, an anonymous
woman caller left a message on my voice mail at the office. This
fan chastised me for writing a story about offers made to Gordon to
race in Formula One and the CART open-wheeled series. Instead, the
woman suggested that I should be investigating the illegal chassis
she is convinced Gordon is using to cheat his way into Victory
Lane.
</P>
<P>
   This was a veiled reference to the ``T-Rex'' Chevrolet Gordon
drove to victory in The Winston all-star race at Charlotte Motor
Speedway in May 1997. That chassis was so slick out of the box that
NASCAR officials ``suggested'' to the management at Hendrick
Motorsports that they not bring it back without modifications.
</P>
<P>
   The recent paranoia surrounding Gordon, the Winston Cup points
leader, continued the week after the Brickyard 400 when the series
visited Watkins Glen, N.Y., for the second road-course race of the
season. My Sunday advance story on the viability of road racing in
NASCAR included a line that stated Gordon ``whines'' on his in-car
radio during conversations with crew chief Ray Evernham. A Gordon
fan in Arlington criticized me in a letter for that observation,
which he took as a huge slap at a nice young man.
</P>
<P>
   I did not write, or suggest, that Gordon could not drive a stock
car. Hey, the guy whines in his race car. That doesn't mean I have
an agenda either for or against Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   But now NASCAR is having an independent laboratory investigate
Gordon's racing tires. What should we all make of this?
</P>
<P>
   Led by rival Ford team owner Jack Roush, some competitors
believe that someone at Team Hendrick is illegally ``soaking''
their allotted Goodyear Eagle radials in some kind of undetectable
chemical. Or maybe a secret bearnaise sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that softer tires have more grip, especially
through the corners, which is where the winners are separated from
the whiners in Winston Cup. The alleged soaked tires supposedly are
allowing Gordon to take on only right-side hides late in a race and
still whip the quarter-panels off cars that have taken on four
fresh tires.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's victory in the CMT 300 at New Hampshire International
Speedway on Sunday _ his ninth of the season and fifth in the past
six races _ prompted NASCAR's decision to impound his tires for
postrace examination.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the Cup champion in two of the past three years,
addressed the issue on the radio show ``NASCAR Live'' on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to stir up all this controversy, but all we're trying
to do is win races,'' said Gordon, who has 38 victories in 179
career Cup starts _ or a victory every 4.71 starts. ``I have a lot
of respect for (runner-up) Mark Martin and all the guys on the
Valvoline team. They race us hard. I feel like they're within the
rules, and we're within the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only disappointing thing to me is Jack Roush kind of took
away from our win. I lost a lot of respect for Jack. I hope he'll
apologize to our team. They don't deserve that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardon Roush if he waits until the results are in.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR rules stipulate a minimum fine of $200 a tire if a
violation is found. That's chump change to anybody competing in
Winston Cup today. But a driver could be thrown out of an event if
found to be fudging on the rules, and the loss of any precious
race-day points should serve as a deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that in 1995 Evernham and the team were fined after the
Coca-Cola 600, where a ``non-approved'' wheel hub was found on the
car by NASCAR after Gordon crashed. Racers traditionally have
interpreted the NASCAR rule book to their specifications. But even
the tenacious Martin, who trails Gordon by 67 points, said he did
not see any big deal in NASCAR's decision to impound and inspect
his tires. Or Gordon's tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'll find anything,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do I, because I don't think Gordon's team is cheating. I
don't think Gordon has misled people. I doubt anyone will find a
bottle of androstenedione in his motorhome. I hope that Jeff
flosses daily.
</P>
<P>
   But just for the sake of argument, whatever happened to the
T-Rex? &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
NASCAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Jack Roush's ire over the alleged tire-soaking going
on at Hendrick Motorsports is interesting in light of comments he
and ace driver Mark Martin made before the running of The Bud at
The Glen last month. Recall that Gordon was coming off his
Brickyard 400 victory over the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor
Speedway, where Martin finished second. Martin had this observation
about Gordon's No. 24 DuPont Refinishes Monte Carlo: ``They're on
top of their game on their engine program. They've got that (SB2)
cylinder head working for them right now, which is what we
expected. They started off the year with some things to learn about
it and looks like they've learned their lessons well.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Roush, a guru of the Ford V-8 engine, said his powerplants have
been durable and have produced good fuel mileage. ``But
historically, we haven't dazzled the field with speed,'' Roush
said. ``The SB2 engine, the cylinder head is better than anything
I've seen. If they haven't found all the power, certainly it's
there for it. I've had a chance to look at all the components and
the airflow and build an (SB2) engine, and there's areas GM has
left for the teams to develop. In Jack's world, that will give it
15 more horsepower over anything that Ford has until we get a new
cylinder head and manifold.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Four consecutive top-five finishes have allowed Dale Jarrett to
remain in third place in the Cup points chase, 238 behind Gordon
and 171 behind runner-up Martin. During that period, Jarrett has
dropped 39 points to Gordon. After 23 races last year, Jarrett also
was in third place behind leader Gordon and runner-up Martin. But
Jarrett was 143 points behind Martin and 168 in back of Gordon.
With nine races remaining, Jarrett is plugging himself into the
``win-win'' mode heading into the Pepsi Southern 500 at Darlington
(S.C.) Raceway. ``What we have to do is just race to win,'' said
Jarrett, winner of spring races at Darlington in 1997 and 1998.
``Winning the race is the only way that we can ensure ourselves of
gaining points, so things are no different than what they've been
the last two years for us. We've put ourselves in this position of
being behind and playing catch-up, so we just have to go try to
win.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Heilig-Meyers Co. will not renew its sponsorship contract with
team owner W.C. ``Junie'' Donleavy in 1999. Veteran Dick Trickle is
27th in Cup points in the No. 90 Heilig-Meyers Ford Taurus. ...
Kenny Wallace started fourth and finished sixth at New Hampshire
International Speedway on Sunday, his best Winston Cup results in
the No. 81 Square D Ford during an otherwise abysmal season. &QL; 
CART  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Retiring three-time CART champion Bobby Rahal believes his
hand-selected replacement, Max Papis, is a victory waiting to
happen. That factor, Rahal said, was significant in why the Italian
landed the ride in the No. 7 Miller Lite Ford/Cosworth beginning in
1999. Papis won out over a list of candidates that included
Americans Jimmy Vasser, a former Championship Auto Racing Teams
champion, and Indy Racing League long shot Greg Ray of Plano.
``Really, the single biggest criteria that we were looking for is
we needed somebody that we felt was capable of winning,
irrespective of nationality or what have you,'' said Rahal, whose
24 CART victories are exactly 24 more than scored by Team Rahal
proteges Papis and holdover Bryan Herta. Papis, 28, has recorded a
best finish of eighth in 34 career CART starts for Arciero-Wells
Racing, where he has been developing the Toyota RV8C engine. It
remains the only American-built and designed engine in the FedEx
Championship Series. ``Any development situation is a tough one. I
know that first-hand,'' said Rahal, 45, who took on a series of
engine and chassis projects throughout his 17-year career. ``I
think one of the things that also struck me about Max is the fact
that amid all the difficulties that development situations entail,
you never heard him once be critical. He was definitely a team
player.'' &QL; 
NHRA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Anderson's family-based drag racing team will necessarily
be taking a genteel approach to the 44th annual U.S. Nationals at
Indianapolis Raceway Park this weekend. The National Hot Rod
Association's oldest and most prestigious race is scheduled to be
Anderson's first outing since she suffered burns and injuries in a
crash during the Autolite Nationals at Sears Point Raceway in
Sonoma, Calif., on July 24. Anderson received medical clearance to
drive last week, but is only allowed to walk two hours a day for
the next two weeks. Her burns required two sets of skin grafts to
both ankles, her hand and left arm. Because those areas still are
tender, she has not been able to put on a fire suit and test-drive.
Tomorrow night's opening round of qualifications will be her first
time down the track since the crash. ``Safety has been my dad's and
my crew's No. 1 concern,'' said Anderson, 32, driver of the Parts
America Dragster. ``My dad (Brad) bought Kenny Bernstein's new
McKinney car as a backup, put that together, and put an on-board
fire extinguisher in the driver's compartment. It's not mandatory
in Top Fuel, but it is in Funny Car. Also, they've made a different
type of seat. The fire had melted the carbon fiber seat and it
trapped me in the car so that I couldn't get out. They've actually
put a different seat in between the roll bar and the carbon fiber
seat, so the seat won't be exposed to flames if there is a fire.''
Anderson also plans to wear a new pair of specially made Funny
Car-style boots, to further protect her ankles. &QL; 
FAST LAPS &QL; 
CUP SCHEDULE SHAPES UP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's 1999 Winston Cup schedule will grow to 34 dates today,
when the Miami-Dade Homestead Motorsports Complex in Florida will
officially be added to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, NASCAR's vice president of competition, is set to
preside over a news conference scheduled to include reigning Cup
champion Jeff Gordon and former champion Rusty Wallace. The entire
schedule might be announced today, or held for a big splash during
the running of the Pepsi Southern 500 at Darlington Raceway this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A tentative copy of the schedule compiled by Knight Ridder
Tribune has NASCAR retaining all venues from last year, and none of
those tracks has lost or added a date. The new schedule features
five open dates designed to keep the teams fresh. According to
Knight Ridder, the new race in Florida is scheduled for Nov. 14 _ a
week later than the 1998 season ender at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
The 1999 season will end at AMS on Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, vice president and general manager of Texas Motor
Speedway, announced in July that the Primestar 500 would run in
Fort Worth on March 28, 1999. Gossage said there was no surprise
that TMS will operate with one Cup date for the third consecutive
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said it publicly we'd only have one Winston Cup date in
1999,'' Gossage said. ``We're not through with surprises though.
We've got something up our sleeve (with regard to 1999). But it's
not a second Winston Cup date.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said that will not prevent him and the management of
Speedway Motorsports Inc. from lobbying NASCAR president Bill
France Jr. for a second date.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as getting a date for 2000, I don't know how to
handicap it,'' Gossage said. ``I don't have a clue. I have been
told by NASCAR that Texas Motor Speedway will have a second date. I
don't know when.''
</P>
</TEXT>
