<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DOUBTS ABOUT FIREWALL TACTIC TO CONTAIN CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inside the Treasury Department, some of the
strategists desperately seeking to contain spreading outbreaks of
financial chaos once called their approach the ``firewall
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea was straightforward and born of U.S. success in
containing the Mexican peso crisis in 1995. As foreign currencies
plummeted and investors fled _ first from Thailand, then Indonesia,
then Korea and now Russia _ the Treasury and the International
Monetary Fund would stitch together a bailout that insisted on
far-reaching reforms, which would rebuild national economies in
America's image.
</P>
<P>
   The hope was that the emergency support from the IMF would buy
some time, and the promise of change _ cleaning up failing banks,
imposing austerity and ending corruption and crony capitalism _
would lure back investors and protect the United States and other
countries from economic contagion.
</P>
<P>
   But now firewall strategy is coming undone. It has collided,
some Clinton administration officials concede, with the inability _
or unwillingess _ of weak or inexperienced foreign governments to
give stock and currency markets what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political price of complying with the markets' demands are
finally hitting home,'' said Robert Hormats, vice chairman of
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which was an investor in Asia and has been
deeply involved in the bailouts of South Korea and Russia. ``And
they simply seem too high.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, firewall strategy has never amounted to more than a
few haphazardly placed bricks. The Parliament has refused to enact
many of the IMF's conditions; the central bank has virtually run
out of dollars to defend the ruble, and the Western aid that was
sent in late July _ $4.8 billion _ has seemed to vanish. .
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich drove the point home Wednesday in
demanding that the Clinton administration explain why Congress
should give $18 billion more to the IMF. ``Where has all this money
gone?'' he asked Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin in a letter. ``How
much of this money has left Russia? How much of this money is in
the hands of corrupt officials or their corrupt business
associates?''
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, the firewall was built of straw and was
immediately ignited. Now, with a government barely hanging on,
rioters targeting the Chinese minority, which brought much foreign
investment into the country, and the army reeling, the IMF's
program is at a virtual standstill.
</P>
<P>
   And this week Malaysia became the first country to reject the
IMF's advice _ and Rubin's _ in explicit terms, deciding to turn
its back on the free market and virtually halt currency trading.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been told that the country's currency cannot be
traded outside the country _ all of it must be returned to Malaysia
by Oct. 1 or it will be declared worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad dismissed
his presumed successor, Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim, who has
been an advocate of free-market strategies and a champion of
financial modernization in Asia. Anwar's house has been cordoned
off by police, and there is widespread speculation that he may soon
be arrested for sedition.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Clinton administration official Wednesday called the
turn of events in Malaysia _ a country where firms like Intel,
Motorola and Matsushita have built huge factories _ ``a tragedy.''
Others said it was the inevitable clash between the power of
government and the power of markets, and they predicted that
Mahathir's effort to isolate Malaysia from world financial markets
would be a spectacular failure.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir saw it differently. ``Malaysia is facing terrible
problems because of the Western capitalist system, which has gone
wild,'' he said on Saturday. ``Financial instruments have become as
good as gunboats for colonizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir has always ranked among the most vocal critics of what
he views as Western efforts to dominate Asia, and in brighter times
he was a leading advocate of promoting ``Asian values.'' But the
Asian values debate was largely about cultural and legal issues _
the U.S. emphasis on individual rights, for example, versus an
Asian insistence on the importance of stability and the good of the
community.
</P>
<P>
   The current argument, while couched in terms of IMF plans and
currency conversions, is an offshoot of that debate. In Russia,
Malaysia and even Japan, the United States is insisting on reforms
that would essentially give power to investors to move their money
across borders at will, instead of to governments seeking to
control their destinies.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, a man trained on the trading room floor, has cast this
choice in stark terms: countries that try to interfere with the
freedom of markets will be cut off by international investors and
starved for lack of international capital. His speeches and
President Clinton's stiffly worded speech in Moscow on Tuesday make
it clear that the United States and the IMF will only aid countries
that adopt reforms along the lines the IMF has prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time Rubin has had to face a series of
political revolts to his plans,'' one White House official observed
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's team insists that the country-by-country approach _
getting the fundamental economics right, forcing the disclosure of
more financial information _ still works. Thailand and Korea, his
aides say, recently managed to lower interest rates, and there is
hope that this will help spur their economies in 1999. In Latin
America, they argue, countries like Brazil have taken preventive
measures, which have helped ward off the kinds of disasters that
struck Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin's deputy, Lawrence Summers, has said many times in
recent months, ``We can't want reform in any country more than its
government and its people do.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is essentially what is beginning to happen now. The
United States is virtually screaming at Japan to end seven years of
economic paralysis, and it will repeat the message Friday night
when Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan meet in San
Francisco with Kiichi Miyazawa, Japan's finance minister and a
40-year veteran of U.S.-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
   But dragging Japan, the world's second-largest economy, toward
politically painful reforms has been almost as difficult as
dragging Russia and Indonesia in that direction. And, increasingly,
there is a sense inside the Treasury that, in the words of one top
official: ``We don't have much time,'' Japan could touch off
another, far more serious round of financial crises if it fails to
deal with its problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
