<SLUG> BC-MARKET-AT&AMP;T-TCI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURMOIL HAS TRADERS CONFUSED ABOUT FUTURE OF AT&AMP;T-TCI MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chaotic stock market has pummeled arbitragers this summer as
fears that merger deals would fall apart have sent prices of some
takeover companies tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps no deal is causing more confusion among traders, who
make their fortunes betting on takeovers, than the pending AT&AMP;T
Corp. acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. On June 24, AT&AMP;T
agreed to acquire Tele-Communications for 0.7757 share of AT&AMP;T
stock for each TCI share, or a total of $31.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced, however, Tele-Communications stock
has fallen 15 percent, to $33.9375, while shares of AT&AMP;T have
fallen 13 percent to close Wednesday at $60. The dramatic decline
of TCI has some arbitragers worried that TCI's mercurial Chairman
John C. Malone may not go through with the deal. It was his
constant tinkering with the terms of the company's 1994 planned
merger with Bell Atlantic that finally ended that deal.
</P>
<P>
   However, a TCI spokeswoman said Wednesday that the merger was
proceeding as planned and was expected to be concluded in the first
half of 1999. And Ray Katz, an analyst at Bear, Stearns, sent out a
note to clients Wednesday saying he believed the deal would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that gave little comfort to one arbitrager Wednesday.
What has made him and others nervous is the recent near collapse of
a planned merger in which Tellabs was set to buy the Ciena Corp. in
a one-for-one swap in June that valued Ciena at $65.88 a share, or
$7.1 billion.The deal nearly came unraveled largely after Ciena
warned that its third-quarter earnings would be less than half the
estimates and that AT&AMP;T would not give it the business that the
company had anticipated. Now the deal has been reduced, so Tellabs
will pay $4.74 billion, or $46.25 a share,
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until the last minute, traders were getting comfort from
the companies that the deal was on track, '' said one arbitrager,
who requested anonymity. ``That has really spooked them.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbitragers who bought the stock of Ciena at a high price have
been hurt. At the same time they had shorted the stock of Tellabs,
but that stock has not fallen nearly as much, so that the ratios on
which their initial investment was premised have changed
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   But of all the deals announced in recent months, the ones that
have been damaged the most by the decline in the stock market are
cash buyouts, said George Kellner, a partner at Kellner DiLeo, a
merger and convertible arbitrage firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spreads all over the place are wider than you can get a
truck through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fear connected to cash deals is more obvious. ``Cash
deals have been hurt more because the stocks decline in tandem in a
falling market,'' Kellner said. As a result the buyout ratios do
not change. ``But in a cash buyout, the cash consideration was set
in more optimistic times. There is a fear that the buyer will see
what is going on and attempt to renegotiate and buy the target
company at a cheaper price,'' DiLeo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
