<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      09-02 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Bay Area's High-Tech Trade Publishers Feeling the Squeeze   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Some of the same factors spooking Silicon Valley _ the Asian flu
and the stock market jitters _ are also slowing the growth of the
advertising manna that feeds the Bay Area's high-tech trade
publishing world.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With more than 2,200 local scribes covering every aspect of
technology, from chip-making to home PCs to the corporate
enterprise, writing about the industry is practically an industry
in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-tech pubs had gotten use to double-digit growth in ad
pages and revenues, but in the first half of this year the market
has stalled,'' said Sheila Craven, president of Adscope, which
tracks high-tech print ads.
</P>
<P>
   Although advertising pages were flat, rate increases boosted
total ad revenues 9 percent, to $1.3 billion, in the 250 magazines
Adscope tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The page slowdown, though slight, seems to have caused a slight
shift in the balance of advertising power among the trade press'
Big Three: IDG Corp., Ziff-Davis and CMP Media. ``For the first
time, CMP topped Ziff in total ad page count,'' Craven said.
</P>
<P>
   CMP President Michael Leeds said one reason for the shift was
that CMP pubs like Information Week and Computer Reseller News
focus on corporate computing whereas Ziff has more of a consumer
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done better in a tough time to hold advertising,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis president Claude Sheer offered a different
perspective. First off, he noted that CMP's page count includes
advertising it bought when it acquired several McGraw-Hill pubs,
while Ziff ``lost'' pages this year because it spun off two Mac
magazines into a jointly owned subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, he said even if it lost ground in the page
battle, Ziff pubs like PC Magazine are still winning the dollar
wars, with $324 million in total revenues versus $267 million for
CMP, according to Adscope.
</P>
<P>
   IDG President Kelly Conlin brushed aside the fact that his firm
is a distant third in U.S. ad pages and revenues. Noting that the
``I'' in IDG stands for International, he said IDG is tops in
high-tech publishing when its overseas revenues get counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike our competitors, who operate primarily in the U.S.,
we're in 75 countries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, despite the ad slowdown in the United States, employment
in the Bay Area tech trades has continued to grow, with IDG
founding new magazines, like the Industry Standard, and Ziff
growing new pubs like its forthcoming joint venture with Excite.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ad drought isn't broken in the second half, the job
picture could change. Earlier this year, for instance, CMP cut 50
jobs at its Long Island headquarters, blaming it on the ad
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Nesting strategy:  &LR; CNet Television is set to leapfrog its
rival, San Francisco's ZDTV, in the battle to become the national
network for computer shows.
</P>
<P>
   CNet TV manager Dan Sexton said starting September 20, CNet will
begin airing two hours of computer TV, every Sunday beginning at 6
a.m., on the USA Network.
</P>
<P>
   Although that early bird slot isn't prime time, being on USA
will give CNet access to 73 million households nationwide,
including millions of Bay Area cable viewers who still can't see
ZDTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to really expand the CNet brand name, and our
talent,'' said Sexton, starting with Richard Hart, co-host of CNet
Central, the company's flagship show.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, CNet Central has aired mainly on the Sci-Fi Channel.
It will keep that slot even after it joins the USA schedule along
with three other CNet shows: ``The Web,'' hosted by Australian star
Sofie Formica, ``The New Edge,'' starring Ryan Seacrest and ``Cool
Tech'' with Daphne Brogdon and Desmond Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sexton downplayed the rivalry with ZDTV, CNet has
clearly shifted its strategy in an attempt to get a national
audience for computer television before its cross-town rival.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when CNet TV started, the company wanted to
create a 24-hour cable network. But Sexton said TV production costs
and the task of getting the shows carried on thousands of separate
cable franchises convinced CNet to take a different tack.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, it has become a production house, turning out TV
shows that it sells to established cable networks like Barry
Diller's USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this a nesting strategy,'' he said, adding that CNet's
50-person TV operation now turns a small profit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ZDTV _ which aims to be a network _ is spending money
like mad to create enough shows to fill a schedule while it
persuades more cable operators to give them a channel. So far ZDTV
reaches 8 million households, but its biggest markets are in
Louisville, Nashville and the New England region.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
