A6123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-ASSESS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-02 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-ASSESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: RENO SHIFT A CHANGE OF HEART OR BID TO BLUNT GOP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Reno is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Buffeted for 18 months by Republicans in Congress
over her refusal to allow an independent counsel to examine how
Democrats financed President Clinton's re-election, Attorney
General Janet Reno has abruptly reversed herself, opening two
preliminary inquiries in a week that could lead to the appointment
of an outside prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some law-enforcement officials said that within the
next week Reno would decide whether to begin another preliminary
inquiry into whether an independent prosecutor should investigate
how the Democratic National Committee funneled money to state
parties to indirectly help the Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A shift in the attorney general's approach does appear to be
under way. But what is uncertain is whether she has changed her
mind about the need for an independent counsel or, as some in
Congress suspect, is trying to blunt the fierce attacks by the
lawmakers on her competence and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Reno has ordered two 90-day preliminary investigations,
one focused on Vice President Al Gore, and the other on former
White House aide Harold M. Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden decisions to begin the inquiries suggested that
Reno's resistance could be weakening.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for the changes was a report sent to Reno in late
July by Charles La Bella, the former head of the Justice
Department's campaign finance unit. La Bella's report set off a
bitter fight within the Justice Department and reignited Republican
criticism of Reno for, in effect, standing by the Clinton White
House in the face of a recommendation of a career prosecutor
closest to the evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Reno tried to dampen the furor in Congress by meeting
with lawmakers who had demanded that she turn over a copy of La
Bella's report along with one given to Reno last fall by FBI
Director Louis Freeh, who also urged Reno to seek the appointment
of an independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Reno allowed the lawmakers to read a version of La Bella's
report on the understanding that they would not discuss it
contents. The version was edited by La Bella to remove references
to evidence presented to a federal grand jury and passages that
discussed the direction in which the inquiry was likely to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella's memorandum, according to people who have read it,
concludes that Reno misinterpreted the law. Like some members of
Congress, he urged her to invoke the statute's discretionary
provision, which allows Reno to apply the independent counsel law
if the subject of the inquiry poses a personal, financial or
political conflict of interest for the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella has argued that an outside counsel with a broad charter
could determine whether top Clinton White House officials illegally
conspired to evade federal election laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reno seemed to heed his advice for the first time in the
campaign finance case Tuesday when she used the discretionary
provision to open the inquiry into statements made by Ickes, who is
not automatically covered by the statute as are top officials like
Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her actions over the past week, including her efforts to
assuage Republican critics by sharing parts of the memorandums
Wednesday, did not seem to temper their demands for her to step
aside and let an independent investigation proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said after the meeting that while the discussion was
positive, Reno had not convinced him that she was moving
aggressively enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reviewing redacted versions of the memos prepared by Mr.
La Bella and Mr. Freeh, it is clear that both gentlemen have
advanced strong, convincing arguments in support of a broad-based
independent counsel,'' said Hatch, who had convened the meeting.
``Importantly, when I asked the attorney general and her top
advisers why those recommendations have, thus far, been rejected,
the answers I received were vague, insufficient or unconvincing.''
</P>
<P>
   One lawmaker refused to accept Reno's terms for the meeting.
Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., chairman of the governmental Affairs
Committee, which investigated the campaign finance issue last year.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said, ``There is no valid reason for keeping
confidential the redacted version of the La Bella and Freeh memos,
and no basis for keeping their legal theories and arguments secret
from the public except to reduce the embarrassment of the attorney
general.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno appeared to fail to mollify her main critic in the House,
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the Government Reform and
Oversight Committee, which voted to hold Reno in contempt of
Congress for refusing to turn over La Bella's memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said his reading of the memo ``reinforced my view that
the attorney general appears to be trying the protect the president
and vice president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Reno's advisers said that her decisions in recent days
marked an important shift in her legal thinking that resulted, at
least in part, from a realization that her obstinacy had eroded her
own credibility and damaged the standing of the Justice Department.
They predicted that she will ask for an outside prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But that is still unclear. Republican critics suggest that by
opening the three-month inquiries, she had postponed a final
decision about Ickes and Gore until after the November elections,
and by tightly defining the issues in each case, she could keep an
independent counsel inquiry away from Clinton. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
