<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRSHOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING WILL USE LONDON AIRSHOW TO FLEX ITS MUSCLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the world's biggest and most important airshows kicks off
Monday outside London, England, with Airbus Industrie strutting in
on the heels of recent headline-grabbing victories over The Boeing
Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based aerospace giant, on the other hand, arrives at
the biannual Farnborough International show with its image
tarnished after one of its worst years ever, its reputation on the
line and a new management team taking over the company's core
business of building commercial airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   But if an animal is most dangerous when wounded, look out for
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year at the Paris Air Show, where Boeing
deliberately kept a low profile because of European concerns over
its then-impending merger with defense powerhouse McDonnell
Douglas, Boeing will use the Farnborough stage to flex its
considerable military, space and commercial muscles. The world's
largest aerospace company also will showcase many of its products,
from the new 777-300 to its stealthy RAH-66 Comanche scout and
attack helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to Farnborough, Boeing and Airbus
convince customers to hold off announcing new orders until the
show, then both companies try and out duel the other for the
attention of the world's aerospace press, who every two years flock
to Farnborough, the home of British Aerospace some 30 miles outside
of London. It will be no different this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is expected to announce major orders for two of its
planes that are flying for the first time this week.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is the Boeing Business Jet, a corporate version of
the 737. So far, Boeing has 29 firm orders, including one from
professional golfer Greg Norman.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently decided that it needed more room for
production of its next generation 737 in Renton and is moving final
assembly of the business jet from Renton to the former Douglas
plant in Long Beach, Calif. But any new orders for the business jet
will also be good news for workers in Renton, who build the wings.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly of the Boeing Business Jet in Long Beach should get
under way next month, with an initial production rate of 3 planes a
month by next year.
</P>
<P>
   The business jet, which will compete in a market now dominated
by Gulfstream and Bombardier, will make its inaugural flight Friday
from Renton.
</P>
<P>
   The other new Boeing plane that could find customers at
Farnborough is the 717, which made its first flight Wednesday in
advance of the airshow.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-passenger 717, Boeing smallest commercial jet, took off
on its maiden flight from the Long Beach plant where it is built
and later landed at Boeing's flight test center in Yuma, Ariz. The
flight had been delayed from earlier this summer because of
problems with a new engine developed for the 717. After a test
program and certification, the first of 50 planes is scheduled to
be delivered to launch customer AirTran Airlines in the third
quarter next year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only AirTran, formerly ValueJet, has placed any
significant order for the 717.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is expected to announce at the airshow that it, too, has
decided to develop its own 100-seat jet to compete with the 717.
The Airbus plane will be a smaller version of its A319.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to announcing several commercial aircraft orders,
Boeing will also hold press briefings throughout the week-long show
on everything from its plans to eventually build a bigger 747 to
its battle with Lockheed Martin to win what could be a $200 billion
Pentagon contract for the next generation Joint Strike Fighter.
</P>
<P>
   But missing from this year's show will be the imposing figure of
Boeing's Ron Woodard, the plain-speaking, 6-foot-5 master airplane
salesman who until Monday headed the company's Commercial Airplane
Group.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most significant management shakeups in Boeing's
history, Chairman Phil Condit sacked Woodard because of continuing
production problems. Woodard was replaced as group president by
Alan Mulally, the former 777 program manager who has been heading
the company's defense and space business.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing has offered Woodard another position within the
commercial group, he has not yet decided he wants to remain with
the company, a Boeing spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two other executives in the commercial group were ousted in the
shakeup and several were moved to different jobs as Boeing
struggles to recover from production snarls that resulted in the
company's first annual loss in 50 years in 1997 and a decline of
almost 50 percent in the company's stock price over the past 14
months.
</P>
<P>
   With Woodard out, Boeing has had to play a musical-chairs game
with its executives as it prepares for the important Farnborough
show.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the opening day, Boeing and Airbus take center stage
with back-to-back news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Until Woodard was removed, the plan was to have him give the
presentation on the company's commercial business, with Boeing
President Harry Stonecipher talking about defense and space as a
substitute for Mulally, who is skipping Farnborough because of a
family reunion that has been planned for many months.
</P>
<P>
   The task of talking about Boeing's ailing commercial division
has fallen to Bruce Dennis, the group's vice president of
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The news conferences will take place against the backdrop of a
changing European aerospace industry, in which the Airbus
consortium of four separate companies will soon to be transformed
into a single corporate entity to better compete with Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Though Boeing still dominates commercial aviation, Airbus has
become a much more formidable opponent in the last two years. And
it arrives at Farnborough fresh off a major coup over Boeing. Last
week, British Airways, one of Boeing's most loyal customers,
decided it will buy planes from Airbus for the first time. Some
analysts believe this could be the year Airbus lands as many new
airplane orders as Boeing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
