r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEPAGE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-02 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEPAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Home Sweet Home Pages   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Forget push technology. Forget portals. Forget e-commerce.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest things on the Internet _ this week at least _ are
community home pages.
</P>
<P>
   These virtual neighborhoods are a cross between chat rooms,
where strangers message each other online _ and personal home
pages, those Web sites that let people show off themselves, their
pets and their hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual communities let a group of people _ friends, family, a
Little League team, a college alumni association _ set up an
interactive home page.
</P>
<P>
   Members can go to the site to communicate in chat rooms or by
e-mail. They can post schedules or photos and set up a contact list
with everyone's phone number and address.
</P>
<P>
   The creators can restrict access to the site or open it to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Major Internet companies such as Yahoo, America Online and
Excite are providing the free service as a way to draw and retain
visitors. They plan to make money by selling ads on the Web pages
where people create their virtual communities _ but not on the
community pages themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``As users become more Net savvy, they increasingly find chat
rooms are too noisy and crowded with strangers,'' said Tim Brady,
executive producer of Yahoo Clubs. ``A personalized Web community
page gives them a noise filter, a place with a fair amount of
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A chat room is like a cocktail party of a thousand people; Web
communities are like an intimate dinner party of a dozen close
friends,'' said Joe Kraus, co-founder of Excite, which is readying
a new service called Excite Communities this fall.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Yahoo Clubs is the only virtual neighborhood that's
operating. Excite and AOL plan to launch theirs in the fall,
followed by Netscape Communications, Lycos and Infoseek next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a new fad on the block,'' said Tom Taulli, an analyst
with IPO Monitor in Woodland Hills (Los Angeles County).
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at three community home page services:
</P>
<P>
   _Yahoo Clubs ( &LR; clubs.yahoo.com &LR; ), which has been up for only two
weeks and has not been consistently accessible, offers a convenient
way to create a community site with just a few mouse clicks.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can create a new community or join an existing one, if
it's open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers choose one topic from a list of 16 such as computers,
sports, sex and romance and hobbies. Within each of those
categories, there are subcategories that are even more specific _
such as African foods or horror movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gathering place where a group of knowledgeable people
can post information on a topic they know and like,'' said Pete
Challinger, a member of DVD (Digital Video Disk) Developers Club,
one of many communities already created on Yahoo Clubs. ``It's a
nice alternative to searching the Net for DVD bulletin boards and
it's different from a typical home page, where one-way
communication rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't found many travel places online where I can have a
meaningful, intellectual conversation about cultural exploration,''
said Suzanne Hornwood, founder of Discovery Travel, another
community page on Yahoo Clubs. The 22-member site recently has
posted discussions on tombs in China, dance in Brazil and
architecture in Jaipur, India.
</P>
<P>
   _Excite Communities ( &LR; www. &LR;   &LR; excite.com/comm/new &LR; ) plans to
offer a more comprehensive service.
</P>
<P>
   While Yahoo lets clubs post only one photo, Excite will let them
display many. It also will offer a calendar for event listings;
Yahoo doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   _Hometown AOL ( &LR; hometown.aol.com &LR; ), part of the Aol.com revamp,
will offer a format similar to Yahoo's. Available to non-AOL
subscribers, it will be divided into about a dozen categories such
as entertainment and sports and family and home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We call it a nice retention product,'' said Katherine
Borsecnik, AOL's vice president of network programming. ``It's
another way to drive traffic and gain eyeballs. And it plays into
the Internet's concept of people being part of an online community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more targeted the user base and the more we know about
users, the higher the value this is to advertisers,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
