<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6126 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-CARTEL-TEX     09-02 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-CARTEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN DRUG GANGS THRIVE ON INTRIGUE, BLOOD
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARISA TAYLOR 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amado Carrillo Fuentes used his smooth talking to ascend from
laboring in Mexico's opium fields to operating a $23 billion drug
empire, U.S. authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   But when all else failed, Carrillo Fuentes traded his
negotiating skills for an AK-47 assault rifle. His path to being
``patron'' of a vast drug territory, based in the Mexican border
city Ciudad Juarez, is splattered with the blood of rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Since Carrillo Fuentes died at age 41 in July 1997, when he had
plastic surgery to disguise his appearance, frenzied violence has
swept the city as drug traffickers battle for control of the
empire, or plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the blood stops flowing, we'll see who's in charge,''
said Travis Kuykendall, director of the High Intensity Drug
Trafficking Area in El Paso and a retired U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration agent. ``This plaza has been important in the
smuggling underworld for the last 50 years, and that's not going to
change with Carrillo Fuentes' death.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials attribute at least 60 homicides in the six months
after Carrillo Fuentes' death to rivalry for the drug empire, which
stretches at least 200 miles through Chihuahua, Mexico, and into
Presidio, Texas. In mid-August, seven men were found slain, three
of them in a black 1998 Ford Thunderbird. The three had been
tortured and strangled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the violence has started up again,'' said a U.S.
government official in Washington, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``Who knows when it will ever stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The new generation of Mexican drug traffickers learned their
vicious tactics from their Colombian counterparts, who became known
in the 1980s for carving up their adversaries with chain saws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, no trafficker would have killed the family
member of a rival,'' Kuykendall said. ``Now they take out five at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrillo Fuentes gained notoriety as ``Lord of the Skies'' with
his use of Cessna airplanes to transport heroin, cocaine and
marijuana into the United States. The key in the struggle for
control of the Ciudad Juarez cartel is who can prove they are the
new patrons capable of carrying out a deal with the Colombian
cartels to deliver their cocaine in exchange for half of each load.
</P>
<P>
   After taking over a cartel, a patron forms alliances with other
organizations to avoid violent sabotage of the drug transportation.
Drug cartels typically are not highly structured organizations like
the Mafia, with several levels of workers answering to one
godfather. Instead, a ``fluid system of geographical alliances and
working unions are the key to success of the major Mexican
traffickers,'' one DEA document states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably 50 people who could move 50 kilos of heroin
on the border,'' Kuykendall said. ``There has to be some level of
internal organization within each group, but as a whole, drug
trafficking is very chaotic and very disorganized, which makes it
so difficult to attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Three major players are vying for control, according to U.S.
officials. They are Carrillo Fuentes' brother, Vicente; Rafael
Munoz-Talavera, known as ``El Orejon,'' or Big Ears; and Juan Jose
Esparragosa-Moreno, known as ``El Azul,'' or the Blue-Eyed One.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Carrillo Fuentes has been seen spending lavishly since
his brother's death and is believed by some U.S. officials to be
living in an extravagant estate across the border from El Paso. He
would be a natural successor because of the importance of familial
ties in drug cartels, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   According to sensitive DEA documents obtained by the
Star-Telegram, Munoz-Talavera is a powerful drug trafficker who in
1989 supervised the funneling of 250 tons of cocaine worth more
than $1 billion from Mexico through El Paso into Sylmar, Calif.,
aligning him with Amado Carrillo Fuentes. Several attempts by the
U.S. government to pressure the Mexican government to prosecute or
extradite Munoz-Talavera after a 1992 indictment in El Paso have
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz-Talavera, who is believed to be living in Ciudad Juarez,
published a full-page advertisement last year in a Mexican daily
newspaper, denying allegations of being involved in drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Esparragosa-Moreno, who is believed to have been Amado Carrillo
Fuentes' top lieutenant, has been valued in the drug underworld for
``his ability to bring peace among warring traffickers,'' according
to a DEA document.] ]Mexican media have reported that
Esparragosa-Moreno is the head of the Ciudad Juarez cartel, but
U.S. officials said that is still unclear, judging from the amount
of blood being spilled.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Mexican government indicted Esparragosa-Moreno
on charges of drug trafficking. He is believed to be in hiding in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
