<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BIG12-BACKS-HNS &LR;      09-02 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG12-BACKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Unless you happen to be Ricky Williams of the University of Texas,
being a top running back in the Big 12 this season is sort of like
being a power hitter in a year when Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
make home-run history.
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may be one of the best around, but nobody seems to care.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has graced the cover of almost every newspaper and
magazine in the nation that covers college football. He is a clear
favorite to win the 1998 Heisman Trophy, playing at a big school in
a major conference that brings him plenty of media attention.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma running back De'Mond Parker said he doesn't mind if
Williams gets the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the hype,'' Parker said. ``I like being myself.
I'm friendly with people I know, but I'm no big talker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky can have all that stuff. That's all political. The only
reason why I would want to win (the Heisman) is it would mean we
had a great year. The best player on one of the best teams in the
country usually wins it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams may win despite being on a team that isn't expected to
be one of the best, but he is not the only player in the Big 12 who
can carry the football and make things happen. Talented running
backs are the staple of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Darren Davis of Iowa State were 1,000-yard rushers
last season, even though each missed three games with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M and Oklahoma State each had a tailback duo that
combined for more than 1,500 yards rushing. Dante Hall and Sirr
Parker totaled 1,773 yards on the ground for the Aggies, and Nathan
Simmons split time with Jamaal Fobbs to gain 1,557 yards for the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Having a tailback duo works for those schools, but it doesn't
help an individual put up the kind of numbers that make people
notice.
</P>
<P>
   A few running backs in the Big 12 last year earned some notice
as freshmen by proving they could run hard and gain big yards,
including Fobbs, Darrell Bush of Baylor and Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   That is, Ricky Williams of Texas Tech. Having the same name as
UT's star has enabled the Tech sophomore to gain a little more
attention than some of the other backs.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is more than just a name. He rushed for 894 yards
last season, breaking the Tech freshman record set by former Doak
Walker Award winner Byron Hanspard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is an outstanding young running back,'' Tech coach Spike
Dykes said. ``He continues to amaze me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor fans, and coach Dave Roberts, were amazed at what
Bush did when he got a chance to play. The Jersey Village product
became the first freshman in school history to rush for at least
100 yards in three games, along with surpassing the freshman
rushing record of Walter Abercrombie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell doesn't always look like the best guy in practice,''
Roberts said. ``But he would come over to me and say, `Just put me
in, coach, and I'll show you what I can do.' When you break the
records he did last year, that says something.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying in school for his senior season says something about
UT's Williams. But De'Mond Parker made a similar decision, and he
would be the Big 12 back getting most of the attention this season
had Williams left for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-10, 190-pound junior from Tulsa is the first OU back since
former Heisman winner Billy Sims (1978-79) to rush for 1,000 yards
in back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Parker considered leaving for the NFL after last season, but an
injury, a change in the offense and the urging of his mother
convinced Parker to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I needed another year to get stronger and show I
could be durable,'' Parker said. ``I think that injury may end up
being the best thing for me in the long run. If I had stayed
healthy, I probably would have turned pro and I might not have been
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker suffered a tear to a lower abdominal muscle that limited
him in the second half of last season. His 1,143 yards rushing look
even more impressive when you consider he gained only 17 yards on
13 carries in OU's last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to see my baby hurt,'' Parker's mother, Carol, told
the Tulsa World. ``But it kept him from going pro; I was glad. I
want him to stay in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker will have a new offense to display his skills this year
because OU has returned to the wishbone and the option attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why the option went away,'' OU coach John Blake
said. ``I think that has been part of our problem. We shouldn't
have gotten away from it, and it won't happen again. I believe in
it 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake also believes in Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know De'Mond is the feature back for us,'' Blake said. ``He
is a very special player. We need him to touch the ball 25 to 30
times a game. That's our main focus. I think this offense will be
easier on him because the defenses will have to key on the fullback
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``De'Mond has worked really hard in the weight room. He wants to
put his body in a situation where it can take the punishment. He's
ready to carry the load for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker has seven touchdown runs of 30 yards or more in his two
seasons at OU. He also has played his best games in head-to-head
matchups with Williams and the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   He outgained Williams 107-99 in 1996 and had a career-best 291
yards last year against Texas when Williams rushed for 223 yards.
But Texas won the game 27-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always dreamed my best game would be with us winning,''
Parker said. ``Maybe that will happen this year. I had a talk with
(running-backs coach) Joe (Dickinson), and he told me I was going
to get the ball more.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Heisman, Parker said he would be happier to take home
the award for the best running back in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather win the Doak Walker Award,'' Parker said. ``That's
more about what you did on the field. But mainly, I just want to
win and go to a bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for the talented backs at A&AMP;M and Oklahoma
State, who share time without complaining in hopes of winning the
Big 12 South Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good about those guys,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum
said of his running backs. ``They aren't very big, but they are
very talented and they're better receivers than we've had in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who also returns punts and kickoffs, just missed a
1,000-yard season last year when he rushed for 973 yards. But the
most impressive stat for the Nimitz High product was his 7.3 yards
per carry.
</P>
<P>
   There's no break for the defense when Sirr Parker takes the
field. His 4.2 speed is the best in school history, but it didn't
help him much against Florida State on Monday. He had eight carries
for 22 yards, and Hall had seven carries for 13 yards behind an
offensive line that has three new starters.
</P>
<P>
   OSU has a couple of all-conference candidates on the line in
center Jeremy Offutt and guard Adam Davis, which should keep things
rolling for the tandem of Simmons and Fobbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both kids will play an important role for us this season,''
said OSU coach Bob Simmons, Nathan's dad. ``When we need an inside
guy who is physical and makes cuts, Nathan is that kind of runner.
He's got the kind of legs and type of style to get you the tough
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamaal is a guy who can be a sensational back. I just have to
get him to grow up and mature. Right now, he is playing on athletic
ability alone. What he has to get better at is his work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people in college athletics have a better work ethic than
Simmons, who graduated with honors last May and is working on his
master's in psychology. He completed 44 credit hours as a freshman,
more than any student-athlete in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``God blessed me with two parents who had me focus on
academics,'' Simmons said. ``It was hard at times to take so many
hours so quickly, but I pushed through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons has that same attitude about playing in a conference
where most of the acclaim seems to go to one player.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't feel like the rest of us are overlooked,'' Simmons
said. ``It doesn't matter anyway. We know our talent, and we're
going to keep running as hard as we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
