</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME OLD STYLE FOR NEW DEVILS' COACH? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The playing surface at National Hockey League rinks will have
different dimensions this season in an attempt to increase the
goal-scoring and attacking excitement that have dwindled in recent
years. The Devils will have a new head coach who is replacing the
defensive-oriented one who helped stifle opposing attacks by
perfecting the neutral-zone trap.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has taken over for Jacques Lemaire, does Robbie
Ftorek expect more scoring chances because the goal lines have been
moved out two feet from the end boards, from 11 feet to 13 feet?
Not necessarily. Ftorek noted Wednesday that the space added behind
the goal lines will be taken away from the neutral zones, between
the blue lines. This, he said, might increase the effectiveness of
the 1-2-2 forechecking system that the Devils use to set up their
neutral-zone trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1-2-2 is designed to turn over the puck in the neutral
zone,'' Ftorek said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the smaller neutral zone, Ftorek said: ``I would think it
would enhance the ability of the 1-2-2 to work better.''
</P>
<P>
   So does that mean Ftorek will stick with Lemaire's 1-2-2 system
that some people found both effective and boring? ``That's
obviously one of the ways we'll play,'' Ftorek said during a
luncheon with reporters near the team's practice facility in West
Orange, N.J. Although training camp doesn't officially begin for
veterans until Sept. 13, many are working out informally. Among
several issues raised Wednesday, Ftorek said that he was
unconcerned about his four unsigned players who are restricted free
agents of the Group 2 category. Two are centers: Petr Sykora and
Denis Pederson, and the team needs to replace center Doug Gilmour,
who left for Chicago as an unrestricted free agent. The other two
are defensemen: Scott Niedermayer and Sheldon Souray. Only Souray
is thought to be near contract terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned,'' Ftorek said. ``You like to see everyone
here. My job is to coach the players we have.'' One of the players
sure to report is a free agent named Sam Ftorek, the coach's son. A
23-year-old right wing, he played the last four seasons in college
at St. Anselm in the ECAC. The coach said he will let other members
of the staff evaluate him. But will other players rough him up to
test his grit in training-camp scrimmages, the way they would with
most free-agent rookies?
</P>
<P>
   BOWMAN CONTEMPLATES FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 18, as teams begin their exhibition schedules, Detroit
Red Wings Coach Scotty Bowman will celebrate his 65th birthday. The
oldest coach in the league and the most successful, Bowman could
return this season in an attempt to lead his Wings to their third
consecutive Stanley Cup championship and the ninth over all of his
long and remarkable career. Since the Islanders won four from 1980
through 1983, no team has won more than two in succession. Should
Bowman win again, he will break a tie with Toe Blake. Both have
eight.
</P>
<P>
   But will Bowman be back? Probably not for training camp or the
start of the regular season. Shortly after the Wings won last June,
Bowman's younger brother, Jack Bowman, a Buffalo Sabres scout, died
of complications during heart surgery. Following a physical
examination, Scotty Bowman underwent an angioplasty to correct a
partly blocked artery near his heart. He also had surgery to
replace his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotty is rehabilitating; it's coming along, it's a slow
process,'' said Ken Holland, the Detroit general manager. ``We'll
take it week by week. There is every indication he is coming back.
But he has not said to me outright: `I'm coming back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Holland said Bowman has lost weight and is determined to make
life-style changes to keep the pounds off while lowering blood
pressure and cholesterol. Holland said Bowman will find time to
work out after practice and will eat fruit instead of pizza on the
team airplane after games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going into this with determination _ full bore ahead,''
Holland said. Bowman's assistants, Dave Lewis and Barry Smith, will
run the team until Bowman's return
</P>
<P>
   NEW STYLE FOR KARIYA
</P>
<P>
   After missing the second half of last season with a concussion,
Anaheim's Paul Kariya has said this summer that he plans to play a
rougher style to protect himself from heavy hits. This could
involve raising his stick to discourage opponents from charging
toward him. Kariya, a small superstar generously listed as 5 feet
11 inches, 175 pounds, twice won the Lady Byng trophy for
sportsmanship. If he needs a bodyguard, the Ducks have acquired Stu
Grimson in a trade with Carolina. Known as the Grim Reaper, Grimson
_ 6-5 and 227 pounds _ is one of hockey's largest and most
accomplished fistfighters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
