<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6131 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-CLINTON-SPI &LR;      09-02 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-CLINTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `HURT' SEN. MURRAY WANTS FURTHER EXPLANATION FROM CLINTON ON
AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Patty Murray, under fire from Washington state
Republicans for her restrained reaction to President Clinton's
sexual relationship with a White House intern, said Wednesday she
is angry and hurt by the president's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that she does not believe the president has acknowledged
how deeply painful his behavior has been for his supporters, Murray
called on Clinton to make another public statement explaining
himself. And Murray said she does not know whether she would want
the president to campaign for her anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow Wednesday, Clinton insisted he had acknowledged ``a
mistake'' and had asked ``to be forgiven'' in his much-criticized
explanation of his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the matter at a news conference with Boris Yeltsin,
Clinton said he had gone back and reread his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was clear that I was expressing my profound
regret to all who were hurt and to all who were involved and my
desire not to see any more people hurt by this process and caught
up in it,'' he said. ``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake,
said that I regretted it, asked to be forgiven, spent a lot of very
valuable time with my family in the last couple of weeks and said I
was going back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments clearly were not enough for Murray, who had read a
transcript of them before speaking with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks, at a briefing for reporters in her office, were her
most extensive since Clinton acknowledged a relationship that was
``not appropriate'' with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt I am very hurt and angered and really
dismayed by what he has done, and it is up to him now, clearly, to
show us that we can trust him,'' said Murray, who has been a strong
Clinton supporter. ``Does he fully understand the pain and anger
that has been caused by this, and the distrust that is out there?
I'm waiting for him to make a statement to let us know where he is
on that, and I will judge him when he makes that statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray is under fire from one of her leading re-election
challengers, Rep. Linda Smith, R-Wash., for her restraint in her
comments about Clinton's behavior. Previously, Murray has said she
was ``disappointed'' by the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   During a speech Aug. 22 to thousands of Republicans at the King
County GOP picnic, Smith offered her own history of Murray's
reaction over time to the accusations against Clinton, saying:
``First there was Paula Jones, and Patty said nothing. Then there
was Kathleen Willey, and Patty said nothing. Now our president has
admitted that he used the power of his office and took advantage of
a 21-year-old intern, and Patty is saying virtually nothing. Is
this the same Patty Murray who ran in 1992 saying that abuse of
power and sexual harassment were the reasons she was running?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith accused Murray of applying a different standard to Clinton
than she applied to two other public figures accused of sexual
misconduct _ former Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., and Supreme Court
nominee Clarence Thomas _ because Clinton has helped Murray raise
campaign cash. Mocking Murray's moniker as a ``mom in tennis
shoes,'' Smith said that Murray's relative silence about Clinton
suggested that ``she seems to have traded in her tennis shoes for a
pair of Hush Puppies.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray Wednesday rejected any charge of inconsistency, saying
that she has always simply demanded that a legal process be
followed in which accusations of sexual misconduct can be aired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely consistent with everything I have done in the
past,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's behavior clearly has the potential to become an
issue in Murray's re-election campaign. John Carlson, a Republican
commentator in Washington, mocked Murray at the GOP picnic, saying
``Don't you think Patty Murray should demand the same
accountability from Bill Clinton that she demanded from Bob
Packwood? ... A little consistency never hurt anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although national GOP leaders have been somewhat circumspect in
their comments about Clinton, Washington state GOP Chairman Dale
Foreman has called for Clinton's impeachment, saying `his behavior
is so despicable, it is so immoral, he is beneath contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of how male politicians have treated their female
subordinates has played a major role in Murray's political career.
She was elected in 1992, the so-called Year of the Woman, motivated
in part by anger over how the all-male Senate Judiciary Committee
had handled Anita Hill's sexual harassment allegations against
Supreme Court nominee Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   That year Murray had been one of few Washington state Democrats
willing to run against Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., who was accused
by eight women of abuses ranging from sexual harassment to rape.
Once elected, Murray was one of the leading critics of Packwood
when he was accused of groping numerous female employees. Murray
accused Packwood of ``manipulating'' the Senate, and she demanded
public hearings about the sexual allegations against the Republican
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's comments about Clinton generally have been restrained,
and even Wednesday, she did not go as far as House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who called Clinton's behavior
``reprehensible,'' or Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif, who within
minutes of the president's admission said ``my trust in his
credibility has been badly shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what the topic, Murray has always favored
unusually mild language for an elected official _ she doesn't try
to compete with the sharp tongue of Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., for
example _ and her comments Wednesday were clearly as far as she is
willing to go at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said some of her supporters want the Clinton sex scandal
simply to go away. In a statement just after Clinton's admission of
wrongdoing, Murray called for an end to the media frenzy over
Clinton's sexual behavior. But Wednesday she indicated she is no
longer seeking to turn attention from this topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to wait for the independent counsel's
report, and when that comes, Congress will have the ability to act
on that,'' she said. ``We need to see what the independent
counsel's report is before we make a determination about what needs
to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton said Wednesday that he has no intention of
elaborating, Murray called on the president to make a further
public statement expressing regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he needs to show us clearly that he understands the
full impact of what his actions have done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And, asked whether she would allow Clinton to campaign for her,
as he has in the past, Murray said ``I haven't made that decision.
I think that he has said he's focusing on repairing his family, and
obviously he's dealing with international issues that are extremely
important, and when he gets through that and we see what comes,
I'll make that decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
