<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC NOTES
 &HT;    Norman Arey AND Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEMSON vs. Furman, Saturday, 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve quarterback Woody Dantzler, who will play in two or
three series behind Brandon Streeter on Saturday, has been showing
some flashes akin to the departed Nealon Greene. Dantzler, a
redshirt freshman and former Mr. Football in South Carolina, has
been dubbed ``Mr. Excitement'' by teammates for his work in recent
scrimmages. He's had two runs of 40 yards or more, and has
demonstrated a stronger throwing arm than Greene. ... Wide receiver
Brian Wofford returned to practice this week after missing the last
two weeks with a sprained foot. He's currently listed behind Mal
Lawyer. ... Reserve outside linebacker O.J. Childress has been
moved to a starting spot on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE vs. W. Carolina, Saturday, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   If you wonder if the Blue Devils ever are going to get better,
this could be the year. ``This is the best preseason session we've
had since I've been here,'' said coach Fred Goldsmith. ``This is
the best team we've had since 1994.'' The '94 team was the one that
began the season 7-0, finished 8-3 and went to a bowl game. Since
then, Duke's fortunes have nose-dived and the Blue Devils have
compiled a 5-29 mark. Still, senior guard Lennie Freidman sees the
light at the end of the tunnel. ``We were involved in a lot of
close games last year,'' he said. ``Virginia and Clemson are two
very good teams that we had beaten and let it get away. We didn't
graduate that many people _ most people are back from last year.
The thing is, we don't want to shoot ourselves in the foot and make
mistakes and mental errors.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE at N.C. State, Sept. 12
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Bowden said the most significant thing to come out
of FSU's 23-14 win over Texas A&AMP;M Monday night, other than winning,
was the way his team responded to being down at the half. ``Here
wewere favored, but when we went in at halftime, they (Texas A&AMP;M)
got the lead and the momentum,'' said Bowden. ``They were all fired
up and jumping up and down, but our kids didn't lose our poise. We
took the ball in for a score and then scored again. We had talked
to them about adversity before the game. A lot of people say that's
negative, but to heck with that. They need to know about adversity
and about things not going right.'' Bowden said he was pleased,
overall, with the play of 26-year-old QB Chris Weinke, who was
starting his first college game. MARYLAND vs. James Madison,
Saturday, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   With a recent foot injury to starting tailback LaMont Jordan,
one of the rare bright lights for the Terrapins, Maryland has been
taking a close look at 5-foot-7 junior Harold Wheatley, who coaches
say is the fastest player coming out of the backfield. Jordan, who
had 689 yards as a true freshman, is still listed as the starter.
... With Trey Evans out with knee surgery, the Terps have an even
slimmer list of quarterback candidates to back up little-used
starter Ken Mastrole. The only other QBs listed on the depth chart
are redshirt freshmen Gil Harris and Erik Lipton. ... Former head
coach Mark Duffner, who filed a lawsuit this week seeking
compensation for TV and consulting services as part of his Maryland
contract, probably is entitled to less than $100,000 should he win.
NORTH CAROLINA vs. Miami-Ohio, Saturday, 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Domonique Williams, slated to start at tailback for North
Carolina before a preseason injury sidelined him, was declared
academically ineligible by the Tar Heels Wednesday. ... Junior
cornerback Dre Bly's assessment of the Carolina defensive unit is
bad news for the rest of the ACC. ``We feel we're just as good as
we were last year,'' he said. ``I know you think I'm crazy because
we had three first-rounders (in the NFL draft), but we're good. Our
front four can put the pressure on them.'' Bly also admitted he's
asked coach Carl Torbush about adding to his responsibilities. ``I
want to play receiver,'' the 5-foot-10, 190-pound All-ACC performer
said. ``I'm bored at cornerback. There's nobody throwing that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   N.C. STATE vs. Ohio University, today, 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio University has a chance to slay another ACC team tonight
when it meets the Wolfpack in Raleigh. Last year, the Bobcats upset
Maryland in the season opener 21-14, sending the Terps on a 2-9
slide. But former Valdosta High QB Kareem Wilson might not be in
the lineup for Ohio after getting pushed in preseason practice by
more mobile rivals. ... The loss of Tremayne Stephens overshadowed
the departure of his chief blocker, valuable fullback Carlos King,
and it's a position that State has had trouble filling in the
preseason. While Rahshon Spikes has nailed down Stephens' slot at
tailback, King will be succeeded by senior Jeff Butler or junior
Kevin Hubbard. Between them, they have rushed for fewer than 100
yards.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA at Auburn, today, 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Crawford, perhaps the top tight end in the ACC, says the
fact that his Cavaliers open tonight against Auburn on national
television has helped Virginia prepare for the Tigers. ``We're a
lot further along this year than we were last year,'' said the
6-foot-6, 250-pounder. ``The fact we're starting off with Auburn on
TV has helped keep our team focused this year. Our practices have
been very intense.'' ... Defensive tackle Antonio Dingle has never
had a problem staying intense. The 6-foot-3, 302-pound pre-season
All-ACC player had a ring put in his tongue over the summer. The
out-spoken native of Fayetteville, N.C., also has let his hair grow
long and has a pair of red contact lenses that he wears on certain
occasions. WAKE FOREST at Air Force, Saturday, 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Deacons' starting quarterback, Brian Kuklick, says he
started playing sports because of shyness. ``My parents pushed me
into sports at an early age because I was so quiet and shy,'' he
said. ``I started off playing Little League baseball and soccer and
moved into other sports.'' The plan obviously worked because the
Hatboro, Pa. native is as articulate as any player in the league.
``It's still hard for me (to talk),'' he said, ``but I'm getting
better.'' Kuklick also knows his value. ``I've been told by some of
the pro football people that I'm anywhere from a late first-rounder
to an early third-rounder (in the NFL draft),'' he said. So does he
consider himself the best quarterback in the ACC? ``Not the best,
but one of the best,'' he said, ``one of the best in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
