<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virginia seeks payback for '97 loss to Auburn
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ The way Auburn coach Terry Bowden figures it, two
very angry entities are coming to Jordan-Hare Stadium tonight when
Auburn opens the 1998 college football season. They are named
Virginia and Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia arrives for tonight's nationally televised game _ 8
p.m., ESPN _ as a team on a mission. The Cavaliers were 7-4 a year
ago, missing out on a bowl for the first time since 1992.
Virginia's players strongly believe they would not have been passed
over had they not lost to Auburn 28-17 in the 1997 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get down there, because I know that losing to
Auburn kept us out of a bowl,'' said Anthony Poindexter, Virginia's
All-America strong safety. ``This team and this program want to be
taken seriously. We want to make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden certainly takes this Virginia team seriously. The
Cavaliers return 15 starters, including nine from a Top 25 defense
a year ago. His father, Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, already
had made the telephone call to say, ``Look out for these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has had our attention since last spring,'' said
Terry Bowden, who begins his sixth season at Auburn. ``We know that
we're going to have to be hitting on all cylinders if we're going
to win. One thing's for sure. We'll know a lot more about our
football team after this.''
</P>
<P>
   The angry Earl comes in the form of a tropical storm that is
supposed to dump rain into Auburn as it moves through the South
today. Bowden was clinging to one report that said the rain would
clear out before the 8 p.m. kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it hurts is the home-field advantage that you get,''
Bowden said. ``The game is already on Thursday, so not everybody
can get here. If the travel conditions are bad, that only makes it
more difficult, and so people will just stay at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the weather, it will be a sweaty palms night for
sophomore Ben Leard, who makes his first start as Auburn's
quarterback. The Hartwell, Ga., native threw only two passes last
season as Dameyune Craig's backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ben's nervousness will be over after the first snap,''
Bowden said. ``We just have to work him through the first series
and he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn will try to run the ball with sophomore Demontray Carter
and senior Rusty Williams to try to take the pressure off Leard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
