<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLACKCOLLEGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter teammate starts at FAMU
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Quincy Carter was locked in a quarterback battle in the
final days before Georgia's season opener, his backup on Southwest
DeKalb's 1995 state championship team earned the starting job at
Florida A&AMP;M several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Michael Morand will start for FAMU at home Saturday
against Hampton University in an important early season contest
involving historically black colleges. The 6-foot-1, 205-pound
Morand beat out Division I transfers Jose Laureano of North
Carolina State and Patrick Bonner of Temple to earn the starting
job.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rattlers' spring game, Morand passed for 447 yards and
three touchdowns. Quarterbacks are common in the Morand family:
Mitchell Morand, Michael's father, and Elroy Morand, his uncle,
were starting quarterbacks at Alabama A&AMP;M and FAMU, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Giant showdown
</P>
<P>
   The Hampton-Florida A&AMP;M showdown matches the No. 1 and No. 3
teams in the Sheridan Broadcasting Network preseason poll. Many
have wondered why the two MEAC giants are meeting at the top of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly wasn't my idea to play this game so early in the
season,'' said Hampton coach Joe Taylor, whose team won the 1997
MEAC title and was crowned SBN national champion after posting a
10-2 record. ``Originally, we were to play this game the first
weekend in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Because some MEAC teams had scheduled games for Aug. 29, which
did not meet the approval of the NCAA, the league's composite
schedule had to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching debuts
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dickerson, who was fired at Temple last year after compiling
a record of 8-47 in five years, will coach his first game at the
I-AA level Saturday when his Alabama State team faces Troy State in
Troy, Ala. Dickerson, 52, wants to put his Temple experience in the
past, as he prepares for his first season in the SWAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't dwell on the facts of the good, the bad and the ugly
that occurred at Temple University,'' Dickerson said. ``I have to
put all my energies into Alabama State.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama A&AMP;M will be led by a former Division I-A coach when it
takes on Jacksonville State in Huntsville Saturday at 8 p.m. Ron
Cooper, fired at Louisville after the Cardinals posted a 1-10
record in his third year, looks toward better days at the
first-year SWAC school in his home town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to a great year,'' said Cooper, 37. ``We
aren't going to make any promises, but we're just going to put a
team out there that's going to play hard for 60 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   A lot of eyes will turn toward Grambling University at 8 p.m.
Saturday, when Doug Williams becomes only the second head coach in
57 years on the Tigers' sideline. Williams, a former Super Bowl
MVP, replaces legendary coach Eddie Robinson. ...Howard quarterback
Ted White, a 6-4, 220-pound passing machine, expected to be among
the top three or four draftable candidates from historically black
colleges, will get a chance to display his prowess on Fox Sports
South at noon Saturday against Jackson State in D.C. The past two
seasons, White has passed for a total of 5,455 yards and 54
touchdowns. . . . In addition to Sunday's 7 p.m. showdown between
Clark Atlanta and Morris Brown at Herndon Stadium, another Labor
Classic will unfold that day, Tuskegee-Benedict at 8 p.m. at Legion
Field in Birmingham . . . Virginia State, picked to win its third
CIAA title in the last four years, faces Norfolk State for the time
since Norfolk moved from the CIAA to the MEAC. The game will be
played in Norfolk at 6:30 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
