<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGAQBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs to start freshman Carter at QB
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ Quincy Carter learned about 2 p.m. Wednesday that he
will be the Bulldogs' starting quarterback in Saturday's opener
against Kent. The freshman was nearly sworn to secrecy, but Carter
couldn't have told the woman he wanted to tell first anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Montgomery Carter, his 82-year-old maternal grandmother,
died in Chicago Aug. 20 after a lengthy illness. After tearful
discussions with his mother, Sherry Carter-Embree of Decatur,
Carter decided not to attend her funeral to remain in Athens for
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like it was what my grandmother wanted me to do,''
Carter said. ``She always wanted me to achieve in life. She was the
most important person to me, except for my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   While Carter-Embree buried her mother Aug. 26, her son competed
in Georgia' final full-contact scrimmage in Sanford Stadium. His
performance that night would go a long way in earning him the
starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He visited her on her sick bed just before practice started,''
Carter-Embree said. ``I didn't hear all of the words, but she told
him that's what she wanted him to do. She prayed for him everyday.
She wanted him to make it and she gave him words of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She supported his decision to go back to school and play
football all the way. She would have wanted him to stay there and
fight for his position. Those were my last words to him before I
left for Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Donnan's announcement that Carter would start
over three other contenders is just the latest chapter in the
storybook career of the Southwest DeKalb High product. After less
than a month on campus, Carter, a Parade All-American in 1995, has
been handed the reigns of the 19th-ranked Bulldogs, despite a
two-year layoff from football.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a 6-foot-3, 225-pounder, will be the first true freshman
to start at quarterback in a season-opener for Georgia in more than
50 years. The last was John Rauch, who started 45 straight games
for the Bulldogs from1945 to1948 and finished his career as the
NCAA's career passing leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider (Carter) a true freshman because of all that
he has done athletically,'' Donnan said. ``Any time a guy comes in
as a true freshman and is able to do that, it's a real compliment.
But he's a mature young man; he's almost 21 years old now. He's
been around and knows how to handle himself. He's the guy we picked
and it's obvious why we picked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter held off Jon England, last year's backup behind Mike
Bobo, for the starting job. England, a 6-foot-1, 205-pound junior
from Norcross, left spring drills as the No. 1 contender. That was
before the arrival of Carter, who signed with Georgia Tech in
February 1996, but later opted for a minor-league baseball contract
with the Chicago Cubs. He was later released from his letter of
intent with the Yellow Jackets, but wasn't allowed to practice at
Georgia until August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out every day and did the best I could,'' England said.
``I just keep doing the same thing, I guess. I just went out in
this camp and did the best I could. Coach Donnan has his thoughts
on who should be the quarterback and I guess that's what's best for
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan said sophomore Mike Usry of Tallahassee was much-improved
in preseason camp and was ``involved a lot more in this decision
than everybody gave him credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   The player who could be most affected by the decision, though,
is true freshman Nate Hybl of Colbert, who graduated early from
Jeff Davis High in Hazelhurst to enroll at Georgia this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Hybl was perhaps Georgia's most impressive quarterback during
spring drills, but he was hampered by an ailing back for nearly the
last two weeks of preseason camp. If Carter is successful, the
highly regarded Hybl, who turned down scholarship offers from
Florida, Georgia Tech and Vanderbilt, now faces the possiblity of
being a backup at Georgia for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's written in stone yet,'' Hybl said. ``I'm still very
young in this whole deal. It's all new to me. I thought I was still
in there until this week. ... I knew there was a possibility
(Carter) was coming. I did take it into consideration, but it
wasn't a big factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard (to be a backup). That's not what I'm looking
to do, obviously. I don't feel left out at all. No one wants to
walk in someone else's shadow, but who couldn't use a redshirt
year? It's kind of murky, as far as my immediate future.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Georgia's players said they were surprised by
Wednesday's announcement. Donnan met with the candidates
individually, then Carter worked with the first-team offense
throughout Wednesday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Donnan) really didn't tell anyone,'' senior tight end
Jermaine Wiggins said. ``(Carter) was just out there with the first
team, so we all kind of got the feeling that he was the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great athlete and I think he's going to be a great
player. He brings the threat of the run and can throw on the run,
which is hard for quarterbacks to do. I'm just going to wait and
see what he does Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   1948 and finished his career as the NCAA's career passing
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider (Carter) a true freshman because of all that
he has done athletically,'' Donnan said. ``Any time a guy comes in
as a true freshman and is able to do that, it's a real compliment.
But he's a mature young man; he's almost 21 years old now. He's
been around and knows how to handle himself. He's the guy we picked
and it's obvious why we picked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter held off Jon England, last year's backup behind Mike
Bobo, for the starting job. England, a 6-foot-1, 205-pound junior
from Norcross, left spring drills as the No. 1 contender. That was
before the arrival of Carter, who signed with Georgia Tech in
February 1996 but later opted for a minor-league baseball contract
with the Chicago Cubs. He was released from his letter of intent
with the Yellow Jackets, but wasn't allowed to practice at Georgia
until August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out every day and did the best I could,'' England said.
``I just keep doing the same thing, I guess. I just went out in
this camp and did the best I could. Coach Donnan has his thoughts
on who should be the quarterback and I guess that's what's best for
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan said sophomore Mike Usry of Tallahassee was much improved
in preseason camp and was ``involved a lot more in this decision
than everybody gave him credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   The player who could be most affected by the decision, though,
is true freshman Nate Hybl of Colbert.
</P>
<P>
   Hybl was perhaps Georgia's most impressive quarterback during
spring drills, but he was hampered by an ailing back for nearly the
last two weeks of preseason camp. The highly regarded Hybl, who
turned down scholarships from Florida, Georgia Tech and Vanderbilt,
now faces the possibility of being a backup at Georgia for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's written in stone yet,'' Hybl said. ``I'm still very
