</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-WEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rams begin with grim '98 outlook
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past three years, prognosticators have examined the
young talent on the St. Louis Rams roster, rated several of the
kids among the NFL's top young performers and concluded that the
team will get over the hump. Invariably, the Rams finish much
closer to the sump pump than the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of being so wrong so often, and tired of waiting for the
Rams' youngsters to play up to their potential, no one is making
the same mistake this season. A Rams club that remains one of the
league's top teases figures to torture its fans once again.
</P>
<P>
   Even the eternally optimistic Dick Vermeil, who could hie back
to the broadcast booth if this season is anything like 1997,
appears resigned to another poor campaign. The Rams haven't had a
nonlosing season or made the playoffs since 1989. The club's most
recent NFC West championship came in '85. All those streaks will
likely continue in '98.
</P>
<P>
   As he demonstrated with troubled tailback Lawrence Phillips last
year, Vermeil is the Father Flanagan of coaches, always seeing the
positive side of players. After the coach's gut-wrenching
experience with Phillips, he now knows that incorrigibles exist.
``For whatever reason, a lot of the young players there never seem
to realize just what kind of commitment is necessary to play at the
NFL level,'' recently retired Rams center Bern Brostek said. ``The
talent isn't a problem, (because) from that standpoint they're not
far off. But as a team, they have to grow and realize talent isn't
always enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Enigmatic quarterback Tony Banks, entering his third year as the
starter, symbolizes the problems with St. Louis' nucleus of young
veterans. Banks, 25, has the stature and arm strength all NFL teams
covet, and in 30 starts has flashed playmaking skill at times. But
for every 50-yard touchdown pass to wide receiver Isaac Bruce, he
makes twice as many physical errors and untold mental miscues.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, after a brilliant practice session, Vermeil, who
for the first time since 1982 will call the offensive plays, told
friends that he thought Banks might have turned a corner. But a day
later, the staff again had lost patience with the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' Banks said, ``I'm making progress. Maybe not everyone
sees it, but I know what I feel in terms of my growth. I've come a
pretty long way in a short time.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks got a bad break when Phillips went bust on the Rams last
fall. Without a running game, Banks and receivers Bruce, Ricky
Proehl and Eddie Kennison feel far more pressure to carry the
offense. But even the enhanced preseason play of former first-round
tackles Orlando Pace and Wayne Gandy might not help a ground game
that was No. 24 in 1997 and still has unheralded Jerald Moore at
tailback.
</P>
<P>
   The return of cornerback Ryan McNeil, who signed a one-year
contract on Monday after a camp-long dispute, should solidify the
secondary. McNeil led the NFL in interceptions in 1997 and with
Todd Lyght gives the Rams a respectable tandem.
</P>
<P>
   ``(There's) no question we're immediately better now that Ryan
is in here,'' free safety Keith Lyle said.
</P>
<P>
   But questions persist over St. Louis' toothless pass rush.
First-round defensive end Grant Wistrom, who has trouble getting
off blocks, looks to be just a situational player for now. For the
league's oldest coaching staff, it could be another season that
adds to the gray they've already accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
