<SLUG> BC-PORN-BUST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENTS RAID CHILD-PORN SUSPECTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Texas) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Customs Service agents raided the homes of
suspected child pornographers in 32 U.S. cities in a crackdown
Wednesday on an international ring accused of trafficking in
computer images of children being raped and abused.
</P>
<P>
   The raids included Texas houses in the Conroe area, north of
Houston, Dallas and Allen, north of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   They were coordinated with law enforcement officials in 21 other
states and 13 other countries. Investigators said they tracked the
cyberspace images to about 200 suspects worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the targets ... have in common _ both here and abroad _
is membership in a perverse network,'' Customs Service Commissioner
Raymond Kelly said at a Washington news conference. ``They trade in
the most vile child pornography imaginable over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to imagine anything more repulsive than the sexual
exploitation of children,'' Kelly said, describing the images
swapped by traffickers as ranging from ``sexual abuse to the actual
rape of children.''
</P>
<P>
   In Montgomery County, north of Houston, customs agents executing
search and seizure warrants seized a pair of computers and hundreds
of diskettes from an undisclosed residence, customs spokesman Judy
Turner of confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No arrests were made at the Montgomery County home, nor at a
residence raided in Allen near Dallas, Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County raid netted two computer systems and 400
diskettes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Guy Williams acknowledged that deputies assisted federal
agents in the raid, but he referred questions to Turner.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the address and the name of the Montgomery County
resident whose home was raided cannot be disclosed because the
warrant remains under seal by a federal court order.
</P>
<P>
   The raids followed a two-year investigation that began after
officials in San Jose, Calif., found a group known as the Orchid
Club forcing children as young as 10 to perform sexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   The performances were being broadcast live over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation led to England, where investigators with the
British National Crime Squad found a second, larger organization
called ``Wonderland Club,'' which had a database of more than
100,000 pornographic images of children.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said that group was then linked to others in the United
States, Europe and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most extensive ring of child pornographers ever
uncovered,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to England, Australia and the United States, raids
were conducted in Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany,
Italy, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Texas locations, customs agents and local law
enforcement agencies in the United States served search warrants on
suspected child-porn traffickers in Broken Arrow, Okla.; Grand
Haven, Mich.; Jacksonville, Fla.; Halifax, Pa.; National City,
Calif.; St. Charles, Mo.; Lawrence, Kan.; Greenville, N.C.; Salt
Lake City; Brooklyn, N.Y.; Chapel Hill, N.C.; Miami; St. Paul,
Minn.; Kennebunk, Maine; Salem, Mass.; Fort Collins, Colo.;
Chesapeake, Va.; Braintree, Mass.; West Orange, N.J.; Skowhegan,
Maine.; Alpharetta, Ga.; Glen Carbon, Ill.; Augusta, Ga.;
Blacksburg, Va.; New Britain, Conn.; Santa Ana, Calif.;
Knightstown, Ind.; Columbus, Miss.; and Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, customs investigators worked with the
British National Crime Squad _ an operation code-named
``Cathedral'' _ to follow porn traffickers across state and
national borders through computer chat rooms and Internet clubs.
</P>
<P>
   To join, members were required to share multiple images of
children engaged in sexual acts, and some members had collected as
many as 10,000 images, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The content would turn the stomach of any right-minded person.
It's really disgusting,'' said Detective Superintendent John
Stewardson, who led the operation in London.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects were tracked ``through cyberspace as they hid
behind a maze of Internet providers, servers, files and screen
names,'' Kelly said. ``The people who exploit children in this way
think they can hide in cyberspace, but the are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal computers were seized at most of the homes, and more
than two dozen people were arrested overseas, mostly in England,
Germany and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Four were arrested in the United States. Another 100 remain
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Customs Service spokesman Bill Anthony said successfully
conducting the raids was complicated by the computer network
linking the suspects, which would allow individuals to alert each
other once agents arrived at the first location.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am unaware of another police operation that has ever pulled
together so many law enforcement agencies worldwide to effect
simultaneous raids and arrests,'' said Bob Packham, deputy director
general of the British National Crime Squad.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities involved in the raids confiscated ``boxes of
pornography, various software materials and hardware that were part
and parcel'' of the ring during the raids, said Special Agent Dick
Weart.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that, once information from the computers is
accessed by agency investigators, more people likely will be linked
to the porn traffickers and will be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law prohibits making or owning images of children under 18
involved in sexually explicit behavior. Anyone convicted of
possession or distributing banned material faces up to 10 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation and Wednesday raids were conducted as Congress
wrestles with proposals to tighten restrictions for transmitting
pornography on the Internet, legislation prompted by a 1997 Supreme
Court decision striking down restrictions in the Communications
Decency Act.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
