</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTORS-HANGON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL INVESTORS AVOIDING PANIC BUTTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Small investors may have been battered and
bruised by the market this week, but many are determined to hold on
to their stock investments without making any major adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   They remain calm while institutional investors largely have been
driving market volatility in the face of economic turmoil in Russia
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to jump in and jump out,'' said Norman Puls, a
62-year-old, semiretired engineer in suburban Woodland Hills. ``You
can't time the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Puls' comments came amid a mixed performance by the stock market
Wednesday. The Dow Jones industrial average rose as much as 125
points before a late sell-off left it down 45.06 on the day at
7,782.37. The Dow failed to build on Tuesday's 288-point rebound
from the previous day's 512-point plunge.
</P>
<P>
   After four decades of investing, Puls knows it's almost
impossible to pick the tops and bottoms of markets and time buys
and sells accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   While he has sold and bought a few stocks in the past month, his
investment portfolio overall has remained relatively unchanged. He
believes the market will bounce up for a little while, then test
new lows before surging upward again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of (mutual fund) money out there,'' Puls
said, ``and that has to go somewhere. It cannot lie in the bank, it
cannot lie in bonds because the yields are low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fund managers are measured by their performance. If they put
it in cash, they have no performance. They have to get back into
the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he can't time the movement back into stocks, Puls believes
it's better not to leave the equity market in the first place. ``I
don't want to be the last one in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Alexander, director of business development at Trim
Tabs.Com, a Santa Rosa, Calif., firm that tracks stock market
liquidity, said few individual investors are cashing out stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Cash inflows into stock mutual funds are estimated to be flat
for August, he said, after declining by $19.3 billion in July. That
means ``individual investors have not panicked. They have held on
to what they bought and neither liquidated them nor added to
them,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true with retirement accounts such as 401(k)
plans, where redemptions have been low, said a spokesman at
American Century Investments, a mutual fund company in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Tobias, an accountant from suburban Van Nuys, is not
touching his retirement account. However, he plans to whittle down
his exposure to stocks in his taxable accounts by selling a little
at a time as his stocks recover.
</P>
<P>
   But a decision to sell by individual investors like Tobias is
not the main driver of stock market volatility. It's institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said institutional investors -- mutual funds, pension
funds, banks and insurance companies -- that are exposed to
volatile emerging markets such as Russia's and Asia's are the ones
doing most of the selling.
</P>
<P>
   That's because they have to raise money to meet margin calls by
lenders who gave them money to buy emerging market government debt,
such as Russian bonds, Alexander said. When a lender makes a margin
call, the institutional investor has to put up more money to cover
the loan.
</P>
<P>
   How do they raise money quickly? Alexander said they sell their
most valuable holdings -- U.S. stocks. As the market drops, other
managers may sell more stock to hold on to gains they have made
this year and look good to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers look at the portfolio differently than individual
investors,'' said Ken Janke, chief executive officer of the
National Association of Investors Corp., an association of
investment clubs in Madison Heights, Mich. ``They are very
concerned about short-term swings (in the market) because they have
to report to their shareholders'' -- people who invest in their
funds.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't faze Rebekah Fleischaker of Van Nuys. The mechanic
not only is not selling, she has been shopping for bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unrealized loss if you don't sell,'' Fleischaker said.
``In the course of 10 years, you're going to get your money back.
This is the time to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
