<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-NAFTA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAFTA COMMERCE BOOSTS DRUG TRADE, REPORT STATES
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARISA TAYLOR and SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mexican drug traffickers are exploiting the North American Free
Trade Agreement, the pact that has reduced trade barriers among the
United States, Mexico and Canada, warns a confidential report by
federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Since NAFTA was adopted in 1994, drug traffickers have invested
in improving Mexico's roads, railways, airports and points of
entry, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful Mexican drug organizations are also buying some of the
country's largest trucking and railroad companies and have
interests in a large Colombian shipping company, according to the
report, Drug Trafficking, Commercial Trade and NAFTA on the
Southwest Border. It was conducted by Operation Alliance, an El
Paso agency that helps coordinate federal, state and local efforts
against drug smuggling along the Southwestern U.S. border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commercial trade increases have brought about significant
expansion of opportunity for drug trafficking organizations. This,
in large part, is because of the excellent `cover' commercial trade
activity provides,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   With eight rail lines, 43 airports, 24 ports of entry, three
nearby seaports, multiple highway links and remote, unguarded
areas, the Southwest border is ideal for drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Only 25 percent of commercial trucks crossing the border are
officially checked for narcotics, which requires that 20 percent of
the cargo be unloaded and examined, and that the walls of the truck
be inspected, along with its fuel tank, underbelly, tires and cab.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's physically impossible to check every vehicle, and that's
why NAFTA has been a blessing for drug traffickers,'' said Phil
Jordan, who headed the Drug Enforcement Administration's Dallas
division for a decade until retiring in 1995. ``Instead of
traffickers having loads intercepted once every 100 times, now it's
one in a thousand.''
</P>
<P>
   But some say that NAFTA, which by 2008 will remove most
restrictions on border trade, has had no proven effect on illegal
drug traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting NAFTA and the drug trade is ``totally unrealistic,''
said Vick Hines, legislative aide for state Sen. Carlos F. Truan,
D-Corpus Christi, who is chairman of the Texas Senate committee on
international relations, trade and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no evidence whatsoever that the rate of trade is
related in any degree whatsoever to the amount of drugs passing the
border,'' Hines said. ``I would just love for someone to show me
that, because no one has done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorough inspection of rail cars, containers and semi-trailers
on flat rail cars coming from Mexico has been impossible because
there are few inspection sites and personnel. Inspectors cannot
check inside tank cars because they can carry hazardous or
corrosive materials, according to the Operation Alliance report.
But railroad inspectors allow up to a 5,000-pound discrepancy in
cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Railroad plans to open a $1.5 million inspection
building in September at the border in Laredo, with areas for the
U.S. Customs Service and the U.S. Department of Agriculture, said
Mark Davis, spokesman for the Omaha, Neb.-based railway. Union
Pacific is the American train line with the most traffic from
Mexico, and Laredo is its busiest crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The building will have space for inspections of up to 16 rail
cars and eight trailers at a time. The Customs Service, the
Agriculture Department, the Border Patrol and Union Pacific
Railroad police personnel will have offices, and there will be six
dog kennels for federal and Union Pacific canine units.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps twofold,'' Davis said. ``It helps the federal
agencies have a place to secure the cars they want to inspect, and
it gives them one location. Prior to this, they would do the
inspection in the rail yard, and that would slow things down.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with the U.S. Defense Department, Operation Alliance is
arranging loans of high-tech military gadgetry and troops to assist
with drug interdiction efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any given day, some agency along the border is going to be
working with the military,'' said Mike Connell, chief Border Patrol
agent and coordinator of Operation Alliance in El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on the Operation Alliance report, saying
that it is an internal document.
</P>
<P>
   The most common vehicle provided by the military is the
Blackhawk helicopter. Blackhawks have a long flight capacity,
sophisticated navigation systems, platforms to mount night-vision
devices, infrared scopes and powerful ground lighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need them all the time,'' Connell said. ``And we
don't have that kind of money _ thousands of dollars an hour _ to
get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell said he gets about 1,200 requests a year from agencies
but is able to get military support for less than half. One reason
is cost.
</P>
<P>
   Another is government bureaucracy. If a drug trafficker wants
high-tech equipment, he drives to a store and buys it, Connell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to buy them, I have to go through a long process as
a government employee to justify it and go through bids,'' he said.
``By the time I've got it, we're six to eight months down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
