<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-EMILY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERING HEROIN ADDICT STILL STRUGGLES TO BREAK DRUG'S BOND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Emily, 19, was a heroin addict for more than a
year until entering a rehabilitation program. She says she has been
clean since March, attends a 12-step recovery program daily and
attends cosmetology school. Emily is keeping a diary for the
Star-Telegram of her thoughts about addiction and her continuing
struggle to break free of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   EMILY'S NOTES: I was in a meeting at the 12-step program I
attend when the using thought came upon me. I was just sitting
there playing the whole scenario in my mind _ of getting it out,
laying it on the table, opening up the cap and getting that one big
whiff, that first smell. It just made me gag. I was like ``Whoa,''
because it was so real. I'll make myself go through the act of
snorting, trying to taste it, even though I didn't like it. I can't
control it. If I'm sitting there and I'm bored, that's what I get
in deep thought about, about using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Then I think, ``Can I afford to start all over again?'' I'm not
sure if I went back it would be a one-nighter. I love it, but the
results I don't like.
</P>
<P>
   I heard story after story of people I knew getting caught.
Everybody either got caught or ran into the cops about it. It's
like, either throw up and you're shaking and you're having
withdrawals, or you're thinking of the chances of getting caught by
a cop. I didn't care. I didn't think it would happen to me. When I
would have withdrawals and I would go get it, just having it in my
hand would make me feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Using thoughts often occur when I am mad or something is not
going the way I want it. It's kind of a passing thought. It comes
down to dealing with life on its own terms. I thought I would have
to deal with using thoughts occurring only when stuff isn't going
my way and when bad things are happening to me. But there have been
plenty of days when everything is going great, and I still want to
use heroin.
</P>
<P>
   I have used many drugs, but heroin has not detached itself from
me. I still think how good that high feels. I forget all my
problems, and I am in my own world. How much better can life get?
Well, there is the problem: It's all a lie. Life on heroin sucks,
and it just gets worse. I have to tell myself that over and over
until the thought passes, or I talk to someone or I keep myself
occupied.
</P>
<P>
   I know I can't use and have everything be OK. My life will fall
apart, because there is no such thing as one time for me. I look at
it this way: There is no problem or excuse big enough for me to
use.
</P>
<P>
   I often think about if I were to go back out and use, how much
would it take for me to get a good high? The thought that follows
is: What if I don't make it? What if I die? I may not get another
chance to try life again. It scares me that it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   There is truly another way of living that is better. Not
everything goes my way. Not everybody does what I think they should
do. That's the beauty of it. Walking through life like that, clean,
and being OK with that.
</P>
<P>
   I had a choice in my addiction to live in misery and become
nothing. And the other choice, I had no idea existed. That is what
kills me inside today, to think I actually thought there was no way
out; I would be a junkie for the rest of my life. There's a way to
get clean, and there are people who care that are just like me. I
don't have to do it alone. If there weren't, I could be dead or in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
