<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YALE-STERN-ARCHITECTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT A.M. STERN TO BE YALE'S ARCHITECTURE DEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIE IOVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert A.M. Stern, who has designed notable buildings for
Berlin, New York's Battery Park City and Walt Disney Co., is
expected to be named Wednesday as the new dean of the Yale School
of Architecture. He will replace Fred Koetter, who has been dean
for the past five and a half years and who will return to private
practice while remaining a part-time adjunct professor.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, the founding principal of Robert A.M. Stern &AMP; Associates
in Manhattan, is known as a traditionalist architect. He is also an
author, a teacher, a preservationist and a member of the Disney
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's best-known buildings include the Walt Disney World
Castingslot Center in Lake Buena Vista, Fla; a master plan,
prepared with Jaquelin Robertson, for Celebration, the new town
founded by Walt Disney Co. in Orlando, Fla.; apartment houses in
Berlin; a dining hall for the University of Virginia and numerous
residences throughout the country, including one in Colorado for
Disney chairman Michael Eisner. His first residential apartment
building in New York will be completed in Battery Park City by the
end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Scully, the architectural historian and mentor of Stern
since his student days, commented in anticipation of the
appointment that ``Of all the many distinguished graduates of the
Yale School of Architecture, Robert Stern best understands its
history and values its special traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Stern both fits the school's reputation as a
school that has been led by active practitioners and unsettles its
long history of pushing the envelope of modern architecture. Past
deans have included Charles Moore, Cesar Pelli and Paul Rudolph,
whose iconoclastic modern design for Yale's Art and Architecture
building was came as a shock to the students of the 1960s. Stern,
along with artist Richard Serra, was a member of the first class to
study in the new building, where architects and artists worked side
by side, a legacy of cooperation that the school still champions.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York in 1939, Stern received degrees from both
Columbia University and Yale University, where he graduated from
the School of Architecture in 1965. He has continued to teach at
both universities, and his course on the history of American
architecture at Columbia has attracted hundreds of students over
the years. He is also the author of ``New York 1930,'' ``New York
1960'' and, most recently, ``New York 1880.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stern belongs to the last generation of hero architects that
includes Michael Graves, Charles Gwathmey and Richard Meier,'' said
Steven Harris a faculty member for 14 years and a member of the
search committee. ``The model no longer exists.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment came as a surprise to some members of the
architectural community who had received a letter from Yale
president Richard Levin in July stating that the search for a new
dean would not be completed until early fall. ``It's good move for
Yale to have completed its search,'' said Ralph Lerner, dean of the
Princeton School of Architecture. ``The course is now set with Bob
and will be a clear reflection of where Bob stands in
architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   While Stern's residential architecture tends in style to range
from the early American to the late Deco, as a preservationist he
has supported the landmark status of numerous modern buildings,
including the 1960s Huntington Hartford building on Columbus
Circle, deemed by some to be an eyesore. Bernard Tschumi, dean of
the Columbia School of Architecture, said, ``Bob has his
ideological preferences but at the end of the day, he will cast
them aside for the greater good of the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for a new dean lasted over one and a half years,
starting with a list of 400 names, according to Harris. The final
list included both architects and academics, but initially not
Stern. Among the finalists were Dana Cuff, a professor at UCLA;
Mark Robbins, the curator of architecture at the Wexner Center for
the Arts at Ohio State University, and Marilyn Taylor, an architect
at Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
