<SLUG> BC-BOXOFFICE-SUMMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BOX OFFICE POSTS RECORD DESPITE LACK OF MAJOR HIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hollywood stayed hot this summer, even without a
blockbuster hit.
</P>
<P>
   Final U.S. movie ticket sales for the period between Memorial
Day weekend and Labor Day will wind up around $2.5 billion,
tracking services Exhibitor Relations and ACNielsen EDI said
Wednesday. That equates to an 11 percent gain over last summer's
record-setting total of $2.22 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nine films topped $100 million, but none reached $200 million,
making this summer only the third of the past decade to finish
without a movie topping that milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sort of an unexpected record summer,'' said Paul
Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations Co. ``Usually, you
have two or three event movies dominate, but that didn't happen.
What went right was there were a lot of good films that people went
to over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marks, senior vice president of ACNielsen EDI, agreed. ``No
matter how you draw the comparisons, it was a great summer because
of the terrific breadth and depth,'' he said. ``There were movies
for all appetites. Every demographic had a movie to satisfy its
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of this year's late Labor Day, the 1998 season has one
more week than the summer of 1997. But even if this week were
excluded, box-office revenues would be up 8 percent, and admissions
would have risen 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A successful summer, representing more than one-third of this
year's expected box office, is crucial because of Hollywood's
soaring budgets. Analysts believe costs have continued to escalate
even beyond numbers posted in 1997, when production costs jumped 34
percent to $53.4 million, while marketing costs rose 12 percent to
$22.2 million, according to the Motion Picture Association of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' was the clear summer winner and could wind up
with $195 million by the end of its run. Disney's disaster flick
was labeled a major disappointment when it opened below
expectations over the Fourth of July weekend, but then showed
surprising staying power and is now the 27th-highest domestic
grosser of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With `Armageddon,' people made immediate comparisons with `Men
in Black' and `Independence Day,' but it's now Disney's most
successful live-action movie,'' noted Prudential Securities analyst
Kathy Styponias.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Armageddon'' carried an estimated $150 million budget
plus the costs of an enormous marketing campaign, so it's not close
to being the summer's most profitable movie. That title goes to
either 20th Century Fox's ``There's Something About Mary,'' made
for a mere $25 million, or DreamWorks SKG's ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' with a $65 million cost.
</P>
<P>
   ```There's Something About Mary' and `Saving Private Ryan' were
both successful due to strong word-of-mouth from audiences,''
Dergarabedian said. ``Audiences have become very sophisticated. You
can't fool them with hype for more than the first weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The staying power of popular films is particularly impressive
because it comes at a time when studios and theater chains are
increasingly likely to pull a poorly performing film. ``As long as
there are a lot of films, there is extraordinarily high pressure
for exhibitors to show films that gross well and push out films
that don't,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sony's ``Godzilla'' took in $74 million in its
first week and then only a little more than $60 million during the
rest of its run. By late July, it was in fewer than 200 theaters,
and analysts were saying that the studio had overhyped the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting good word-of-mouth is always elusive,'' Marks said.
``You never know you have it until it comes. And with so many
movies, ones that previously might have developed that buzz have a
hard time hanging around.''
</P>
<P>
   The summer saw both Disney and Fox crack the $500 million in
summer grosses, marking the first time two studios have done so.
Sony became the first to cross the milestone last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Disney managed the feat with solid performances from
``Armageddon,'' ``Mulan,'' ``The Parent Trap,'' ``The Horse
Whisperer'' and ``Six Days, Seven Nights.'' Fox started by
stumbling with ``Bulworth,'' which grossed only $26 million, before
clicking with most of its slate -- ``Hope Floats,'' ``The
X-Files,'' ``Dr. Dolittle,'' ``There's Something About Mary'' and
``Ever After.''
</P>
<P>
   For Disney, the performance represents a continuation of its
status as Hollywood's most consistent studio, while Fox has posted
a stunning rebound from its dismal summer of 1997, when it flopped
with ``Speed 2'' and was forced to delay ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also say the summer's strong performance reflects the
increased popularity of megaplexes, those giant 20- and 30-screen
complexes replete with lavish snack bars and state-of-the-art
screens, sound systems and seats. Nearly all new screens will be
part of megaplexes in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have this many good movies, a megaplex allows
customers to have multiple options,'' Dergarabedian said. ``If the
big hit is sold out, it's a matter of, `Let's go see something
else.' It gives moviegoers the chance to be the kid in the candy
store.''
</P>
<P>
   Marks agrees that megaplexes clearly helped keep moviegoers
coming this summer. ``The public loves them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
