<HEADER>
A6152 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-STREETS-TEX     09-02 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-STREETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFORMATION IS KEY TO BUSTING THE STREET DEALERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY and SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The faces had to be familiar, or Eddie wouldn't sell heroin to
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth dealer used caution and cunning to avoid
detection. He used code names to identify meeting places; drugs and
the quantity being sought were never mentioned on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who survive are very cagey,'' Eddie said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eddie, investigators say, typifies area heroin dealers. They
deal in small quantities of the lucrative drug. They sell to young
users who protect their own kind. And the major dealers don't deal
with strangers.
</P>
<P>
   That creates impossible odds for investigators, who must rely on
informants and undercover agents to infiltrate drug dealers'
circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only as good as our informants,'' said Grapevine police
Sgt. Sam Gladney, who is assigned to the Northeast Tarrant County
Drug Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   The barriers to getting that information on the deadly dealers
of heroin are many:
</P>
<P>
   The legion of today's heroin users are young, making it
difficult for undercover agents to blend in.
</P>
<P>
   Heroin use is growing in suburban areas, where its use is more
clandestine than in urban areas, and suburban users more likely can
afford quick, savvy legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and friends are not willing to turn in a teen-ager or to
call for an outside official's guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Even when investigators make a bust, they often don't find
enough heroin to press significant charges.
</P>
<P>
   Local, state and federal law enforcement agencies only now are
beginning to work together on the same cases.
</P>
<P>
   Heroin's spread beyond the inner city has changed the dynamics
of law enforcement and resulted in many of the new barriers, police
say.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban areas, users are much younger than the traditional
inner-city addicts, impeding police in their efforts to infiltrate
heroin circles and to go up the dope chain to find the dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The young users ``just don't want to give up the friends,'' said
Bedford police Lt. Larry Romines, commander of the Northeast
Tarrant County Drug Task Force. ``That's the problem with this
drug. It's kind of like a cliquish thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Most parents won't call Crime Stoppers, task forces or area
police departments to report that someone is a heroin user or a
dealer, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, some parents ``past the denial stage will say,
`Here's who he's talking to' and pass it on,'' Plano police officer
Rick Moore said. ``Occasionally, we'll talk to neighbors and
they'll give us license plate numbers of people they suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Heroin deals might be made on the streets of Fort Worth and
Dallas, but in Northeast Tarrant County they are cloistered behind
closed doors and are more difficult for police to track, officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Jason M., a 21-year-old recovering heroin addict from Haltom
City, said that when he was dealing, users came to his place or he
went to theirs. When he made deliveries, he put the heroin in
bubble wrap and placed it inside a container of coffee beans to
mask the odor. Even a drug-sniffing dog missed it once.
</P>
<P>
   When suburban users are busted, they usually have a gram or less
of heroin, which likely means a probated sentence, prosecutors say.
A private attorney will usually be at their side quickly, said
Margaret Beaudry, director of research with Drug Strategies in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that lawyer is not going to let them turn over dealers,''
Beaudry said. ``It's just a very different demographic. These are
sharp, sharp attorneys that they're getting. These are the kids of
doctors and lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say that they usually arrest young heroin users as soon
as they catch them, rather than dragging out the investigations and
risking overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They buy what they're going to use,'' Gladney said. ``As soon
as they buy it, they want to get it in their arms or up their nose.
They can't wait until they drive back over here.''
</P>
<P>
   To overcome the secrecy protecting heroin use, police are
searching for new tactics and alliances.
</P>
<P>
   In Denton, drug agents work with informants who know dealers of
other drugs, said Denton County Sheriff's Department Lt. Richard
Mankoff, commander of the North Central Texas Narcotics Task Force,
which serves Denton, Grayson and Wise counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those sources, they've heard about it and they lead us to
others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some fear that pressuring young people to inform may backfire
and cause users not to seek medical help or treatment.
</P>
<P>
   George Malina's 20-year-old son, Milan, died of a heroin
overdose in June 1997. Friends who were with Milan when he
overdosed kept an eye on him but were too afraid to call an
ambulance because they also had been doing the drug, Malina said.
By the time the friends took Milan to the hospital, it was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   A no-questions-asked policy for anyone who takes an overdose
victim to a hospital could keep more young people from dying,
Malina said.
</P>
<P>
   Collaboration by law enforcement agencies is vital, Beaudry
said. Although authorities at all levels have communicated with one
another for years, they focused on avoiding duplication of efforts
so that no two agencies were working the same case.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently have suburban, city, state and federal law
enforcement agencies come together on cases.
</P>
<P>
   One such endeavor is the Northeast Tarrant County Drug Task
Force, part of a countywide narcotics intelligence group. When task
force agents get a tip and follow a user outside the county _ to
Dallas, for example _ police there are notified.
</P>
<P>
   There are gaps in the coverage, though. Although most area
cities dedicate an officer to the effort, Colleyville, Keller and
Southlake have not, citing staff!chortages and the need to tend to
their home turf first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been convinced that I can do that right now,''
Colleyville Police Chief John Young said. ``I can't take someone
out of a shift and put him over there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Plano, where heroin has taken the lives of more than a dozen
young people in the past two years, local, state and federal
authorities combined forces to root out a major heroin distribution
ring.
</P>
<P>
   In late July, five Guerrero, Mexico, natives and 24 others,
including some Plano youths, were indicted on federal charges of
distributing heroin. Authorities have also accused some members of
the group of selling heroin that killed four people, a step that
could bring a longer prison sentence for anyone convicted.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement can be in only so many plaqes to try to
quell the heroin problem. The eyes and ears of others _ parents,
siblings, teachers and friends _ are needed to help spotlight users
and dealers, police say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can either be part of the problem or part of the
solution,'' said David Flory, Bedford's interim police chief. ``I
think they have a responsibility to society not to turn their
backs. If everyone took that attitude, I don't know where we'd end
up.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit$44e Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
