<HEADER>
A6153 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-1STL     09-02 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-835(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHWEST LAYS OFF HALF OF WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Eds: Rewrites 1st 2 grafs. Changes percentages and last sentence
in graf that begins ``The major issues.'' Changes percentages in
the 2 successive grafs that each begin ``In addition.'' Changes
``saved'' to ``helped save'' in graf that begins ``The Northwest
pilots say.'' No other changes.) 
 (ATTN: Ill., Mich., Minn., Tenn.)  (lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines laid off more than half of its 51,000 workers
Wednesday, spreading the economic disruption created by a 5-day-old
strike of its pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The move signals that the airline is preparing for a protracted
battle while at the same time increasing pressure on President
Clinton to order the pilots back to work, an intervention that the
company has been quietly seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said that with its 1,700 daily flights grounded since
Saturday by the walkout, it had no work for a full work force. The
27,500 employees being laid off, including mechanics, flight
attendants and customer-service representatives, are also in
contract negotiations with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, as Northwest canceled all its flights through
the Labor Day weekend, the Department of Transportation said that
two commuter airlines affiliated with Northwest had violated
federal law by suspending service to 17 small cities in 11 states.
</P>
<P>
   The department ordered the airlines, Mesaba Airlines and Express
Airlines I, which connect the cities with Northwest's hub airports
in Detroit, Minneapolis and Memphis, Tenn., to resume flying
Thursday. The commuter airlines' pilots are not on strike.
</P>
<P>
   The large layoff means that Northwest, which is the United
States' fourth-largest carrier and dominates much of the Midwest,
will not be flying again anytime soon, even if it reaches a
settlement with the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier estimated that it would take eight to 10 days to get
all its planes back in the air once the pilots returned to the
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed Wednesday to meet with a federal mediator on
Saturday, though it was not certain that negotiations would resume.
</P>
<P>
   The major issues in the strike are pay and job security. Before
negotiations broke off on Friday, the union was seeking a 14
percent raise over three years. Northwest's last offer was a 9
percent raise over four years. The union says the pilots' yearly
average salary is $120,000; the company says it is $133,000.
</P>
<P>
   Magdalena Jacobsen, the chairwoman of the National Mediation
Board, who is supervising the negotiations, invited the two sides
to meet with her in Chicago on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Armshaw, a spokesman for the board, which is an independent
federal agency that supervises the airline and rail industries,
said that the meeting was not a resumption of negotiations but an
attempt to see whether there was enough movement on either side for
new talks to be productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an exploratory meeting,'' Armshaw said. ``If it can go
beyond that, it will.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was announced a day after Rodney Slater, the
secretary of the Department of Transportation, met with the chief
executive of Northwest, John Dasburg, and the president of the Air
Line Pilots' Association, Randolph Babbitt, separately and together
for nearly five hours in his Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   Slater seemed to believe the two sides showed some willingness
to compromise, but neither the company nor the pilots indicated
that on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Foley, Northwest's vice president for communications,
said: ``Dasburg made it very clear that ALPA's position on pay is
unachievable.They gave no indication that they will move on that.
Until they do, we can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots reiterated their position that they were waiting for
Northwest to make a move. ``It has always been our preference to
negotiate,'' said Paul Omodt, the union's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first strike to cripple a major airline since flight
attendants went on strike at American Airlines five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest pilots say that they helped save the airline from
bankruptcy in 1993 when they accepted a 15.5 percent wage cut in
exchange for stock along with the other unions.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Northwest has registered four years of record
profits and the airline's executives have cashed in stock options
worth tens of millions of dollars, while the pilots' salaries have
merely returned to the pay levels before their concessions. After
two years of negotiations, the pilots say they are seeking an
``industry-leading'' contract that would vault them over their
counterparts at American Airlines, United Airlines and Delta
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said that it cannot afford to pay the pilots
more than its three competitors, which are much larger, pay their
pilots,
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 14 percent raise, the pilots are seeking a
lump sum of $86 million to make up for the past two years, an end
to a two-tier wage scale in which newly hired pilots are paid less
than those who have been at the airline more than five years, and
limits on the number of small, regional jets Northwest can add to
its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 9 percent wage increase, Northwest has
offered a lump sum of $57 million, a reduction of the two-tier wage
scale to three years from five, profit sharing and improved pension
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots say the difference between the two offers amounts to
$70 million a year; the company estimates the difference at $170
million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Northwest is also in the midst of negotiating new contracts
with its five other unions. The airline has said that if it meets
the pilots' demands, it will be forced to be equally generous with
its other workers, saddling it with high costs at a time when a
weakening global economy threatens to end the current boom in the
airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the strike has caused fewer problems than many had
predicted. Under the Railway Labor Act, which also governs union
contracts in the airline industry, the federal mediator must
declare a 30-day cooling-off period before an airline union can
strike. That gave businesses and consumers more than a month to
prepare for life without Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   But if the strike drags on beyond the Labor Day holiday, a heavy
travel period, it promises to cause increasing disruption as
business people resume heavier travel schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has repeatedly warned of the disastrous effects of a
strike in the hope of convincing Clinton to intervene. The White
House has the power to force the pilots back to work for 60 days
while a special emergency board tried to negotiate a compromise
acceptable to both sides. But Clinton, who ended a pilots strike at
American Airlines last year, has declined to step in.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said Wednesday that it regretted having to lay off its
workers. ``This is a sad day for Northwest Airlines,'' said Dwayne
Tucker, Northwest's vice president for human resources. ``We hoped
never to have to exercise this option.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pilots accused the company of exaggerating the impact of
the strike in order to get Clinton to intervene. The union said the
layoffs were ``simply the next step in a carefully contrived plan
by management to inflict pain on everyone _ the traveling public,
the pilots, and indeed, all Northwest workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The union has also said that there was no reason for Mesaba and
Express to stop flying just because Northwest was grounded.
</P>
<P>
   In its order Wednesday, the Transportation Department said that
under a federal program that pays subsidies to airlines to fly to
underserved areas, Mesaba and Express are prohibited from
suspending service below a minimum of two round trips a day to a
major hub airport six days a week without first giving 90 days
notice.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how many passengers would be affected by the
order, though it is probably small.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Wilkinson, a spokesman for Mesaba, which is effectively
controlled by Northwest, said that it made no economic sense for
the airline to fly without being able to connect passengers to
Northwest. He added that Northwest also provides many essential
services to Mesaba, such as its reservation system, scheduling and
ground handling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northwest just furloughed 27,000 employees,'' he said. ``There
is no one to provide these services.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing their own negotiations with the company, Northwest's
other unions have supported the pilots. ``We do stand behind
them,'' said Kathy Jo Smith, a business agent for Local 2000 of the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters, which represents
Northwest's 11,000 flight attendants. ``They're sort of paving the
way for us. We want them to stand hard and firm.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that thousands of workers are losing their jobs, the
pressure on both the union and the company to reach a settlement is
sure to increase. Few Northwest workers make anywhere near the
pilots' average yearly salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time alone changes these things,'' said one person involved in
the talks who insisted on anonymity. ``But it is important that
neither side be too far ahead of its troops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
