<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIN-SWALLOW-TEX     09-02 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIN-SWALLOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPORTING HEROIN INTERNALLY A DEADLY RISK FOR COURIERS TO
SWALLOW
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: One of 22 stories (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON DICKSON and SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The moment a smuggler slathers a heroin-filled balloon with
cooking oil, pops it in his mouth and swallows hard, his life is on
the clock.
</P>
<P>
   If anything goes wrong _ a flight delay, a lengthy interrogation
by the U.S. Customs Service _ the balloon could rupture and the
smuggler could face instant death.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extraordinary risk, swallowing is an increasingly
popular method of heroin smuggling because it is relatively simple
to get past federal authorities and even drug-sniffing dogs,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The couriers who swallow say to themselves, `This is an easy
way, it's good money and a free trip,' '' said Roberto Medina,]
associate special agent in charge of U.S. customs investigations in
El Paso. ``They think it's almost impossible to detect.''
</P>
<P>
   At Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, customs officials acknowledge that
they are usually wrong when they suspect that someone has swallowed
drug-filled balloons or condoms or bags. In the past five years,
only five of the 36 suspects escorted by customs officials to
Baylor Medical Center at Grapevine for X-rays had anything other
than food in their stomachs, U.S. customs records show.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. customs seizures of ``internally concealed''
heroin increased significantly in 1996 _ 642 pounds, compared with
508 in 1995 _ officials say they are seizing only a fraction of the
incoming drug.
</P>
<P>
   Swallowers usually arrive by plane, but they also walk or drive
across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're seeing swallowers show up at Laredo, Eagle Pass and
El Paso,'' said Judy Turner, a customs spokeswoman in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso and Laredo, Texas, were among the leading cities for
internally concealed heroin from Mexico from 1994 to 1996. Houston
was among the leading cities for internally concealed heroin
seizures from flights out of Panama and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   One swallower can ingest as much as $3 million worth of heroin,
a lure that is tempting more people to try, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug traffickers have no problems recruiting swallowers. Many
live in poverty where the heroin originates: Mexico, Colombia,
Ecuador, Peru and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Swallowers who are physically able to handle more balloons are
being asked to carry 2 to 3 pounds across the border at a time,
said Paul Rimmer, port director for customs in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It limits your exposure without limiting your profit,'' Rimmer
said. ``Several years ago, 2 pounds was unusual, but now it's much
more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In early August, a Salvadoran man arrested at Bush
Intercontinental Airport in Houston had swallowed 100 balloons
filled with about 3 pounds of heroin _ a load that had a potential
street value of up to $3 million, customs officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That's almost twice the typical load of 1.7 pounds for
swallowers from 1994 to 1996, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   New technology makes it possible to install easy-to-use X-ray
equipment at points of entry to try to identify more swallowers.
But customs officials are not planning to install the technology,
saying that role is for medical experts. And the American Civil
Liberties Union has said it will oppose any routine use of such
equipment at U.S. airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airport is not a no-privacy zone. The Fourth Amendment is
fully applicable,'' ACLU legislative counsel Gregory T. Nojeim told
the White House Commission on Aviation Safety and Security in
September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, federal officials say they are focusing primarily on
improving how they question suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Their main advantage is time.
</P>
<P>
   If a balloon is expelled prematurely, the smuggler risks a
lengthy prison sentence if discovered by authorities _ or quick
execution by the traffickers if any of the drug is missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people expel them prematurely and they swallow them
again,'' Turner said. ``It's unpleasant, but what else are they
going to do? If they show up missing two pellets when they make
their connection, they are going to get shot. It's an amazing
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   If a balloon ruptures in the carrier's body, the smuggler can
suffer a horrifying stomach explosion. Death is quick but
excruciating as the heroin makes its way to the intestinal walls,
where it is quickly absorbed into the bloodstream. Within a few
heartbeats, the heroin is pumped into the heart, stopping it cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your body will jerk and go rigid,'' said Larry Alexander, an
emergency room physician at Baylor Medical Center at Irving who has
treated several heroin overdoses. ``Once it's in the bloodstream
... it's like somebody turning the lights out. It takes one beat of
the heart to circulate it through the entire body.''
</P>
<P>
   If customs officials suspect that someone is a swallower, the
interrogation is usually slow-paced.
</P>
<P>
   They look for signs of nervousness as minutes tick by. They also
look in the suspect's luggage for laxatives or for medicine to
prevent premature bowel movements. They check whether the suspect's
breath smells like latex, or whether the suspect refused airplane
food.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the clues are more subtle. Last year, federal
authorities at D/FW Airport became suspicious about two Colombian
men traveling from Lima, Peru, to Japan. The two said they were
businessmen, but they weren't carrying briefcases and had dirty
fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we looked at them, they began to get nervous,'' said
customs inspector Renee Nunn, who worked the case. ``One was
shaking a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Each had swallowed 100 balloons of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, swallowers are generally less likely to travel to D/FW
than to drug-trafficking hot spots in Miami or New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit longer flight to here and a little more
difficult to hold that in all that time,'' said Fred Waters, a
chief customs inspector at D/FW.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
