<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton Hints at Offer to Russia of Financial Aid
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton suggested that the West would increase its aid
to Russia if that country continued its tough economic reforms. His
message was intended to encourage the Yeltsin government to stick
with its pro-capitalist course despite the nation's deepening
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has told his aides that the United States should be
prepared to lead a new international aid effort, which could draw
on the Group of Seven industrialized nations and international
organizations, such as the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Bank and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette announced
losses on their business in Russia. Chase said it expects to take a
$200 million charge in the third quarter, primarily for losses in
Russia and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   FDA Panel Backs Tamoxifen
</P>
<P>
   An advisory committee to the FDA voted unanimously to approve
the use of the drug tamoxifen to reduce women's risk of developing
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Zeneca, which makes the drug tamoxifen, and Barr
Laboratories, which sells its generic form, rose sharply. Also
increasing were shares of Genentech, which received approval from
an FDA panel for Herceptin, the brand name for a biological drug to
treat metastatic breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   More Northwest Workers Laid Off
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines laid off 27,500 workers, including mechanics,
flight attendants and customer service representatives, and
canceled all its 1,700 daily flights through the Labor Day weekend,
a move that could extend the disruption caused by the five-day old
pilots' strike for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysian Finance Minister Ousted
</P>
<P>
   Anwar Ibrahim was dismissed as deputy prime minister and finance
minister of Malaysia. His dismissal came one day after the prime
minister imposed controls on the sale of the currency, the ringgit,
and fixed its exchange rate. These steps followed a July stimulus
package that overturned Anwar's tight fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Suspends Short Sales
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government bolstered the stock market again by
suspending short-selling of shares many companies.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Brokerage Firms Down
</P>
<P>
   Shares of brokerage firms have been battered in recent weeks, in
some cases falling more than 40 percent. Analysts say that if the
market stabilizes and builds on its fledgling recovery, these
stocks might increase, but then again, if the market's slide
continues, they might decline.
</P>
<P>
   Livent Names Artistic Director
</P>
<P>
   Livent hired Todd Haimes, artistic director of the Roundabout
Theater Company, as artistic director, effectively supplanting
Garth Drabinsky, Livent's co-founder and the producer of
``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Bond's Yield Edges Down
</P>
<P>
   Prices of most Treasury securities slipped slightly, with
investors feeling less need to seek a haven, as stock markets
worldwide stabilized and the dollar weakened. The yield on the
30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.33 percent, from 5.34 percent on
Tuesday. With yields at a 30-year low, the lure for some investors
is not as strong as it was a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   A Finance Minister's Lament
</P>
<P>
   Investors have sold Latin securities because of worries
generated by Russia and Japan, without bothering to examine
conditions in individual nations, lamented Finance Minister Jose
Angel Gurria of Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
