<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 9-2 --
Removing dents from soft metal is not difficult. The only tools
required are a hammer or mallet and an anvil. Metal smiths use a
hammer with a smooth polished face called a planishing hammer to
tamp metal, but you can use a lightweight (eight ounce) ballpeen
hammer or a wooden mallet. Use these to tap dents in flat pieces
like plates or trays. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times
Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1998 -- NY-FRESH-WATER-POND-2, 9-2
-- The Rev. Hattie Smith Davis, center, with Sari Weissman and Sean
Andrews at Eib's Pond on Staten Island. The pond falls under the
Parks Council's Green Neighborhoods program, which Andrews, the
program's director, says requires strong local partners. ``It's a
place to listen to quietness,'' Ms. Davis says. ``When troubled
kids ran away from home, they would head in there. But they'd tell
me where they were going.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 1998 -- NY-FRESH-WATER-POND-1, 9-2
-- Eib's Pond on Staten Island. Most New York City wetlands are
salt marshes; Eib's Pond (pronounced eyebz) is a rarity: a
freshwater pond. Covering three acres, it is the largest in the
five boroughs of the kettle ponds that were scooped out by the
retreat of the Wisconsin glacier 12,000 years ago. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEWPORT, N.H. -- Sept. 2, 1998 -- NH-DRUGS-BOS, 9-2 --
Inside the Machine Tool Exhibit, where she works as an
administrator. Patryc Wiggins tells how she lost her brother,
Peter, to heroin. ``When someone dies in a small community, it's
like a whole web, and everyone has a thread to the family or person
it's affecting.'' Authorities blame Lidia Nunez, a convicted drug
dealer from Massachusetts, and her three sons for the death of
Peter and proliferation of heroin in this small town. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ROCKPORT, Mass. -- Sept. 2, 1998 -- CAPE-ANN-ARTIST-BOS,
9-2 -- Harold Rotenberg, 93, puts brush to paper as he overlooks
the harbor in Rockport. Rotenberg, who's work hands in the Israeli
parliament and Boston Museum of Fine Arts, lives outside Orlando,
Fla., but he and his dog, Popcorn, come to Rockport for a few weeks
each summer. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WOODSTOCK, Conn. -- Sept. 2, 1998 -- NUDIST-RESORT-BOS,
9-2 -- A family enjoys the water at Solaire Recreation League. The
idea of Solair, which has been a family nudist resort since 1937,
is to be naked. Most of the nearly 300 full-time members, who pay
$1333.50 a season (per couple) are social nudists year-round. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
