<SLUG> BC-FLYCATCHER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONGBIRD'S FUTURE IN PERIL, GROUP SAYS; U.S. BLAMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tiny songbird likely will become extinct despite its listing
as endangered because of the federal government's failure to
enforce the Endangered Species Act, an environmental group charged
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Southwestern willow flycatcher was declared endangered
in 1995, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has approved
destruction of habitats for nearly 20 percent of the remaining
population of this tiny migratory songbird, according to a report
by the Southwest Center for Biological Diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fish and Wildlife resisted listing the flycatcher, tooth
and nail, and ever since has continued to stonewall protection for
this graceful bird,'' said Noah Greenwald, who wrote the report for
the Tucson-based environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Humphrey, Phoenix spokesman for Fish and Wildlife, said his
agency shares concerns for the flycatcher, and is doing everything
possible to avoid issuing any additional ``take'' permits, which
legally allow the destruction of endangered species and their
habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists were especially critical of decisions by Fish
and Wildlife to allow the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation to raise water
levels at three lakes, drowning or potentially drowning the trees
that the flycatchers use to nest.
</P>
<P>
   Those lakes _ Roosevelt in Arizona, Isabella in California and
Mead on the Arizona-Nevada line _ represent half of the remaining
locations where at least 20 pairs of songbirds nest.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists filed lawsuits in each case. They lost the
decision to raise water levels at Lake Mead, which since has
flooded flycatcher trees. Federal court decisions are pending in
lawsuits involving Roosevelt and Isabella.
</P>
<P>
   According to an internal Fish and Wildlife memo made public in
the Mead lawsuit: Former federal biologist Rob Marshall said of his
own agency: ``The Southwestern willow flycatcher is being
piecemealed to extinction; the service is turning a blind eye to
the aggregate effects of its own (actions).''
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey said that his agency is sensitive to such criticism,
and that all decisions regarding the flycatcher now are being
collectively monitored by the agency's regional office in
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're doing everything in our power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, federal and local officials recently worked out a
way to provide water to a flycatcher nesting site when the repairs
for flood damage to the Kearny airport were planned.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Mead, the Bureau of Reclamation has pledged to
replace the destroyed habitat with new habitat along the Colorado
River, though the replacement habitat is yet to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   For Roosevelt, which was enlarged in 1996 to provide more
storage and more flood control for the Valley, the Bureau of
Reclamation pledged $4.4 million over 20 years so the Nature
Conservancy could buy 820 acres of former ranch land along the San
Pedro River for a preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald of the Southwest Center said this is hardly a fair
trade-off, because there have been up to 45 nesting territories
surrounding Roosevelt, and only three flycatcher territories at the
Dudleyville Crossing site run by the Nature Conservancy. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
