<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME, MATCH, OPEN AND OUT FOR KORDA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add art note) 
 (ART ADV: Three photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There will be no more cartoonish scissors kicks, no
reprisal of last year's epic U.S. Open dethroning of top-ranked
Pete Sampras, no encores to the Grand Slam breakthrough he made
last winter when he won the Australian Open at the ripe old age of
29.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Korda kissed all those scenarios goodbye Wednesday when he
became the first major casualty at Flushing Meadows when Germany's
Bernd Karbacher, a 155th-ranked qualifier whose own career was
threatened by myocarditis last year, recovered from a slow start
and went on to trample Korda, 2-6, 6-3, 6-2, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very tired at the moment, mentally, everything; I was not
pumped at all today,'' said the fourth-seeded Korda, who was
out-aced, 15-2, produced 57 unforced errors and felt everything go
downhill from the second set on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to hit it and I miss it, I was trying to come in
and he made good pass,'' Korda added. ``Whatever I did today, I did
wrong,'' Korda admitted he was also suffering from homesickness
that stemmed from his having to leave home just five days after the
birth of a second daughter on July 28th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really depend on my family, and I haven't had a chance to
see them since the baby was born,'' said Korda, who married Regina
Rajchrtova, a former WTA Tour player, in 1992 and has credited her
with helping him rebound from a series of surgeries and rekindle
his love for tennis.
</P>
<P>
   The playing conditions were amenable enough at Arthur Ashe
Stadium, and the opponent was one he had crushed in both prior
meetings, but Korda simply forgot how to play his game. Once that
happened, he was summarily ousted by the somewhat stunned
Karbacher, a 30-year-old journeyman who could not even remember the
last time he made life miserable for a member of the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Michael Chang, who encountered little resistance from
the qualifier he faced, 271st-ranked Eyal Erlich of Israel, could
have warned Korda about Karbacher's potential for creating chaos in
Grand Slam situations: Karbacher knocked him out of the second
round at the French Open, the only Slam where Chang has bragging
rights to a championship, in 1993. But Chang had other hurdles to
overcome: At 26, he has not only been Slam-less since capturing
that Roland Garros title in 1989, he came into this Slam, the one
where he was seeded second last year and became the odds-on
favorite to win the title after Korda's ambush of Sampras, unseeded
for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But Chang is nothing if not dogged, and after handling Eyal 6-1,
6-3, 6-1 in just 88 minutes, he donned a T-shirt with a ``Jesus
Loves You'' message and announced that, on the basis of this
first-round victory and the hardcourts title he won in Boston on
Sunday, he believes himself capable of tackling this title along
with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My injuries and stuff are headed in the right direction,''
said the 22nd-ranked Chang, who has battled foot, wrist, stomach
and knee trouble this season. ``I'm still left in the draw, so why
not have the attitude that I can come out and play great tennis and
maybe even win this tournament,'' said Chang, who confirmed that
his energized attitude toward the game does not include his
volunteering for Davis Cup singles duty in the semifinals against
Italy later this month in Milwaukee. ``It is not in my best
interest to play at this time. My major concern is getting back to
where I'd like to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Chang would like to be is back in the top 10 and
contending for titles like this one, but his immediate path is
complicated by his unseeded status, a predicament that advanced him
into a difficult second-round encounter against the reigning French
Open champion, 10th-seeded Carlos Moya of Spain. Moya escaped from
a potentially lengthy first-round duel with Mariano Puerta of
Argentina on Wednesday after the 58th-ranked teen-ager was felled
by hip flexor cramps with Moya ahead, 6-1, 7-6 (7-4), 6-7 (3-7),
4-4.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like Korda, the second-seeded Marcelo Rios has had ample
opportunities in 1998 to wrestle the No. 1 ranking away from Pete
Sampras, and unlike Korda, he has succeeded twice. But Rios has not
been quite the same since Moya sent him packing this spring at
Roland Garros, the Slam in which the Chilean had hopes to validate
his No. 1 ranking by capturing a major title.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Rios got revenge for a straight-sets loss to Daniel
Vacek in Cincinnati by demolishing the Czech, 6-4, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing really bad, not having a lot of fun,'' Rios
said, ``but I come to this tournament with a lot of energy, trying
to do good, get the No. 1 ranking again and win a Slam _ the last
Slam of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
