<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WRIGLEY FIELD BLEACHER BUMS, SOSA'S THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sammy Sosa responded to Mark McGwire, or at least to
Barbara Reichert. ``We need just one run, Sammy, hit me one,'' she
yelled Wednesday from the first row in the right-field bleachers at
Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   And Sosa did, leading off the Cubs' sixth inning with his 56th
home run, off a Jason Bere fastball that landed in Reichert's
college softball glove. The home run gave the Cubs a 1-0 lead over
the Reds in a game they would win, 4-2, assuring that they would
finish the day still ahead of the Mets in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   And that homer temporarily put Sosa one behind Mark McGwire of
St. Louis in the race to break Roger Maris' record of 61 home runs
in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had entered the night with 57 homers after his two
blasts Tuesday in Florida. But he connected on his 58th and 59th
Wednesday night, both two-run shots, again against the Marlins.
After Wednesday night, McGwire has 23 games remaining and Sosa has
22.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great day,'' said Sosa, a right-handed batter, who
had struck out three times the night before. ``Every time I'm
thinking about going to right field, I'm a much, much, much better
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   So the home run race has become a sprint to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   It was a glorious afternoon to be in right field at Wrigley,
where the serious baseball fans sit. It's warm on cold days in the
sun. The players are nearby. And the faces are familiar.
</P>
<P>
   They arrive early to argue over statistics and trades and the
batting order. They argue whether Wrigley will ever be torn down.
They opine: ``Fifty-seven is a dumb uniform number for an
outfielder,'' referring to Cincinnati right fielder Roberto
Petagine's jersey.
</P>
<P>
   They swap news: The pennant flags for the Western Division
teams, which show the standings, aren't flying above the scoreboard
Wednesday. ``Why not?'' ``The cable is frayed.'' The fans in right
field know these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here they come!'' Sherwin Esterman, the man in the painter's
cap, announces as the Cubs emerge from the dugout for the first
inning. He's not sure why he says that, but he always does. He's
been in the right-field bleachers since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   And here comes Sosa, not trotting as the other players do, but
sprinting 368 feet to the ivy-covered wall in right field. He takes
a left turn in front of the cheering bleachers, his right hand
cupped to his ear in the universal sign for ``I can't hear you.''
</P>
<P>
   The bleacher bums are Sammy's fans now, as they were Andre
Dawson's from 1987 to 1992. Sosa pats his chest to give heart
kisses to the crowd. They tell him to play a little deeper or to
the left. Wednesday he rewarded them with a fine running catch in
the corner, just before his home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right-field bleachers is something I'll never forget,''
Sosa said after Wednesday's game. ``When I play hard, they like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The bums agreed with Sosa that it was a bad idea for the Cubs to
announce Tuesday night that McGwire had hit two home runs. It made
him think home run, Sosa said. The Cubs say they won't make any
more announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's home run Wednesday gave the Cubs a 1-0 lead in a game
they would hang on to win on another home run by the veteran Gary
Gaetti, and an insurance homer by catcher Scott Servais. Sosa's
56th also tied the Cubs' record for a season, set by Hack Wilson in
1930. That was the National League record until McGwire's efforts
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the talk is of Sosa and McGwire, the bleacher bums
are most excited by the prospect of the Cubs' best finish since
1989. One theory is that a tie for the wild-card spot would help
Sosa pass McGwire. ``The Cubs will finish in a three-way tie for
the wild card,'' said Dave Alm, 53, who has been in the bleachers
since 1958. ``They'll play a playoff, and Sosa will hit two more.''
</P>
<P>
   The bums gamble on ``mound ball,'' in which the game is won or
lost depending on where the baseball is left by the players between
innings. And they stand reverently with 36,000 others for the
singing of ``Take Me Out to the Ballgame.'' Wednesday's guest
conductor, filling in for the late Harry Caray, is Cardinal Francis
George, archbishop of Chicago, who threatens to sing it in Latin.
That would match the sign across Sheffield Avenue, where more fans
fill still more bleachers built on top of a brick three-flat. The
sign urges ``Eamus Catuli,'' ballpark Latin for ``Go, Cubs!''
</P>
<P>
   Behind right field, the El train rumbles by and a ball roars
overhead. Dave Davidson had played Lance Johnson perfectly,
fielding his long foul off a taxi on Sheffield. Davidson gets his
signs from Mel Romanek in the back row. ``Uncle Mel,'' 59, has been
sitting in the bleachers since 1953. ``When a left-hander is up, I
tap my left shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   The bums can be brutal, perhaps hardened by years of
disappointment. Their favorite play this year was when a Phillies
right fielder, who had made one bad play, was heckled mercilessly.
Finally he turned to give the crowd a shrug, and missed a ball hit
down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fenway's OK, but this is it right here,'' said Trish Hollard,
32, a lawyer. She joins in the chant of ``MVP!'' for the most
valuable player award that the bums think will be Sosa's.
</P>
<P>
   The ivy-covered wall of right field became a 10th player itself
this week for the Cubs. A long fly to right by Jose Hernandez
appeared to be a home run, and the Reds' right fielder turned to
watch it land in the seats. But the serpentine wall curves at that
point, making the outfield a few feet deeper. The ball landed safe
on the warning track for a double.
</P>
<P>
   Fights are fewer now in the bleachers since beer sales were
discontinued a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reichert stayed in her seat when Sosa was up. A copy editor for
The Chicago Tribune, she might be editing a story with her name in
it. She held a sign: ``Hit Us No. 56 and we'll give it back free.''
And she offered to do just that. But if the ball were to go to the
Cubs, owned by Tribune Co., ``They'll have to pay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
