<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVER-FATIGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL HELP FOR SLEEPY DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sleepy drivers can cruise along the highway with
the window wide open, pinching or slapping themselves, chewing gum
or tuning the radio to a call-in host whose politics they detest,
but none of that will keep them awake, the AAA Foundation for
Traffic Safety and a prominent sleep researcher said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their advice for a Labor Day weekend drive is this: Go to bed
early on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can do,'' said David Willis, president of
the AAA Foundation, ``is spend your time running around like mad
getting ready for that big drive to Grandmother's house, and get
only a few hours' sleep the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three million drivers will hit the road this weekend,
Willis said, many of them right after work on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year study by the University of Pennsylvania medical
school surveyed 283 sleep researchers and transportation safety
experts. David Dinges, head of the division of sleep and
chronobiology at the school, said the study debunked a variety of
folk remedies, including driving with one shoe off, playing mind
games, eating snacks or arguing with someone on a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Dinges advised getting enough rest the night before. Taking a
nap, even for as little as 20 minutes, could provide an hour or
more of alert driving time afterward, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dinges and Willis recommended that after a nap, someone who
would be driving should do about two minutes of jumping jacks,
running or marching in place, and stretches, to get the blood
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Official statistics attribute about 3.2 percent of the crashes
in which someone is killed to driver fatigue, Willis said, but a
dozen states report no accidents from that cause because the report
forms that officers fill out do not have a space to list fatigue as
a factor. In addition, he said, few surviving drivers will admit
that they fell asleep, and if the driver dies, it is even harder to
pinpoint the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Dinges said that caffeine could be effective, and that people
who planned a long drive on Friday night should drink more then,
and less during the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
