<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA WILDFIRE LEAVES AREA IN RUIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story, eliminated earlier, is now restored.)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMET, Calif. _ A wildfire started by lightning and driven by 40
mph winds burned 34 homes and 6,000 acres near here on Monday and
Tuesday, leaving little but blackened barren hills and the pungent
smell of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 firefighters from around the state battled the
flames in Juniper Flats, about 85 miles east of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters contended with 12-foot flames, heat in excess of
110 degrees and a fire that did not burn in a clear pattern,
because of shifting winds. A preliminary assessment put the damage
at $2.9 million in homes, livestock, and buildings like barns,
greenhouses and sheds.
</P>
<P>
   As the flames advanced toward their homes, several residents
said they had little time to prepare or even to grab anything.
</P>
<P>
   Tod Chatlousky, a 40-year-old stone polisher and silversmith,
was having dinner at his mother's house when he heard news of the
fire. By the time he saw his house, everything was gone: his
collections of turtles and tarantulas, his laying hens, his mobile
home and his English furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the surface of the moon,'' Chatlousky said at a
Red Cross emergency shelter set up in a school cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   To the list of weather problems attributed to El Nino this year,
add hazardous fire conditions. Heavy rains caused thick growth this
year, leaving grass 8 feet tall in some parts of the state, said
Lisa Boyd, a spokeswoman for the California Department of Forestry
and Fire Protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
