<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES EXPECTS COOL PLAY AFTER BUM SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If nothing else, at least the longest and
hottest of summers is over for the Cowboys. Which, of course,
doesn't involve North Texas' record heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the walls at Valley Ranch, the Cowboys are parched and
barren in areas other than landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Just since the opening of training camp in mid-July, the image
of the Cowboys has dried up and died, both on the field and off.
</P>
<P>
   What do other people think of this bunch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad team,'' for starters. ``Still bad actors,'' for the
kicker.
</P>
<P>
   From a football standpoint, not since 1990 has the prevailing
national perception of the Cowboys been so low. This has been
fueled by a combo of 1997's December dog act and an August of
alarming preseason misery.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, Jerry Jones' carefully crafted and sincere
clean-up-the-Cowboys campaign suddenly took a serious beating. The
dorm-room neck slashing in Wichita Falls, and then the Larry Allen
incident, destroyed what had become some deserved credibility on
this front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I think in both cases those are fair
evaluations, at least based on the current general perception,''
Jones said yesterday, with the 1998 season opener just a few days
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here was a case where a negative fed on a negative. Our
two off-the-field instances were compounded by going 0-and-5 in the
preseason, and vice versa. Again, just in my opinion, it made both
look worse than they really were. But when dealing with perception,
and certainly when it's the Dallas Cowboys, it's a loss in both
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his Valley Ranch office, surrounded by five Lombardi
trophies, Jones spoke candidly, but didn't retreat from his normal
upbeat mood. Never-let-'em-see-you-sweat is a Jerry trademark, plus
yesterday had him in a general manager frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was juggling a legitimate attempt to sign free-agent
linebacker Quentin Coryatt (great idea) with some crazy scheme to
bring back Charles Haley (awful idea) from retirement. With Jerry,
it's always something.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones' obvious eagerness for the arrival of Sunday's kickoff
seemed to go beyond normal circumstances this time of year. Mainly,
he has convinced himself that Chan Gailey and Co. have the
on-the-field capabilities to quickly put a bad summer behind one
and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Dallas Cowboys, and we are constantly faced with
too high expectations and a too low benefit of the doubt,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit I have more unanswered questions about this team than
at any time since we became a (Super Bowl) contender. What I also
have, however, is the advantage of sitting in on so many of the
offensive meetings, be it before training camp, training camp, and
now. As a fly on the wall, and that's what I've been in these
meetings, I have regained that confident feeling that this is an
offense that is going to be very productive. If the offense is
productive again, then look out for the Dallas Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   See there. Jones is being Jones, even if his high hopes seem
totally unreasonable, given where the Cowboys are as a team.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry, would you take 8-and-8 right now and call 1998 a success?
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, every team starts off a season with the premise it can
be 8-and-8,'' Jones said. ``What takes a certain amount of those
teams to the 9-7 mark, the 10-6 mark, or beyond, is the caliber of
the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us a full season of health for Troy Aikman, playing in
Chan Gailey's offense, and we are a playoff team. If you're a
playoff team, you are a (Super Bowl) contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine wins for these Cowboys? Then file that under ``great
season.'' Ten wins would deserve a ``miracle'' tag. But to Jones,
my thinking, and the thinking of most others, is based on ``six
wins last season when there is no way we should have been that bad,
and also based on our preseason, when our emphasis was on veterans
staying healthy. I see a lot of things changing, and that starts on
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of change, the Cowboys' image hasn't, due to
off-the-field incidents this summer involving Michael Irvin and
Larry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that once again there has to be doubt,'' Jones said.
``But all I can say is we will continue to work very hard in this
area. We have had our setbacks, and there may be more. But we
aren't going to pack up and go home. We will continue to be
diligent as an organization, and it's going to get better and
better under Chan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad we have Chan. How bad would this have looked if
Barry (Switzer) were still here? Yes, things have changed, and we
will continue to work very hard for more positive change.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, at least the Cowboys' hottest of football summers
will end Sunday. And it couldn't have come soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
