</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK DEMOCRATS ANGRY ABOUT CLINTON FUND-RAISER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan fund-raising appearance by President
Clinton scheduled for the night before the New York Democratic
primary is stirring resentment among candidates and their aides,
who are worried that Clinton will steal attention from their
contests and undercut their own fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints seemed to represent a near-consensus among the
major New York campaigns as Clinton's appearance at the Sept. 14
national Democratic fund-raiser approaches. The state's three major
candidates for U.S. Senate _ Geraldine Ferraro, Charles Schumer and
Mark Green _ have called the White House in an unsuccessful effort
to persuade Clinton to delay the fund-raiser, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales for the event, a performance of ``The Lion King''
to benefit the national congressional campaigns, have been heavy
and are expected to raise at least $3.5 million. That would make it
the most lucrative fund-raiser the party has ever staged, said
Steven Grossman, chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The objections raised by Democrats in New York in a series of
interviews offered a discordant counterpoint to Democrats in
Washington. National party leaders pointed to the evident success
of the ``Lion King'' fund-raiser, which Grossman described
Wednesday as ``the political event of the decade,'' as an
indication that Clinton had not been hurt, at least among
contributors to the Democratic Party, by his admission of an
improper relationship with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than viewing the event's success as testimony to
Clinton's political strength, New York officials described it as
the latest instance in which national Democrats had put their
fortunes ahead of New York, where the party is engaged in difficult
races to unseat Sen. Alfonse D'Amato and Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign and state party officials said the very success of the
fund-raiser, whose top ticket goes for $100,000, would complicate
the already formidable task the party's nominees for senate and
governor will face in raising money after the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is unfortunate,'' said James Larocca, a Democrat
seeking the nomination for governor. ``It can't help but overshadow
whatever last-minute attention the primary may be getting.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser is to be attended by Clinton, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Tipper Gore. It will be the
first visit by the Clintons to a major city since he acknowledged
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, the former intern.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, New York candidates and their aides said Wednesday
night, they were now resigned, after a campaign in which they had
struggled to win public attention, to seeing the final hours of
their contests eclipsed by what is likely to be an unusually
prominent presidential visit.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Smith, the White House political director, said he had
fielded a series of calls from New York candidates upset about the
event. ``I told them that while we understood their concerns, the
same concerns get raised in every state in the country,'' Smith
said. ``You can't just shut down the fund-raising of these
committees. You just can't do it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Green said Clinton's fund-raiser would directly compete with and
overwhelm a campaign fund-raiser he had planned for the same night
at the Upper West Side home of folk singer Peter Yarrow, of Peter,
Paul and Mary. The Democratic candidate for Senate did not attempt
to hide his exasperation when asked his reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Green sighed,'' Green said, speaking of himself in the third
person, ``and then said, given the number of Democrats with dollars
in the five boroughs, it's awkward but inevitable. It is not
perfect that the Clinton `Lion King' party is happening at the same
moment as my Peter, Paul and Mary party.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's assessment was echoed in harsher terms by aides in most
of the gubernatorial and senate campaigns, all of whom would speak
only on the condition of anonymity, out of fear of angering the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why the hell are they holding a fund-raiser the night before
the primary?'' one said. ``Why do you want a story in the next
day's paper about Democrats raising money? We were shocked when we
heard this was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager of another statewide campaign said: ``This is not a
good development for anyone running statewide in New York. People
are very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   A state Democratic Party official added: ``It's the most
unbelievable, awful thing that you can imagine. It's a travesty. It
is everything that is wrong with politics in 1998. I don't think
the Republican National Committee would even consider doing
something like this.'
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's event is a joint fund-raiser involving the Democratic
National Committee, the Democratic Campaign Congressional Committee
and the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee. It is one of a
series of 12 to be held nationwide to raise money for the fall
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeds will be divided equally among the three committees
and, presumably, some of that money will come back to New York. In
addition, because of complaints by Judith Hope, the New York
Democratic Chairwoman, the Democratic National Committee has agreed
to give the state committee 7.5 percent of the net proceeds from
fund-raisers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   National party leaders said the concerns voiced by New York
Democrats were unfounded, but they tried to minimize the fallout.
White House officials said the Clintons and the Gores had agreed to
return to New York in the months ahead to campaign on behalf of New
York candidates. Grossman said the Democratic National Committee
planned to give $300,000 in proceeds from the event immediately to
New York campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said the party had settled on Sept. 14 because that was
the date that was offered them; it is a Monday, a night when
theaters are usually dark. ``This is one of the hottest shows of
the last decade,'' Grossman said. ``You take the date that they
give you and you work with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
