<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-ENVIRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. LEAGUE OF CONSERVATION VOTERS TO ENDORSE PATAKI 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York League of Conservation Voters, a
political action group that focuses on environmental issues, has
decided to back Gov. George Pataki in his re-election bid this
fall, the organization's leader said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group's decision to endorse the Republican incumbent before
a Democratic rival has been chosen was criticized by some of the
Democrats vying for the governorship. But Paul Elston, the chairman
of the directors of the conservation league, said Pataki's record
was ``so fantastic'' that there was no need to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last four years, he's just delivered on one
environmental initiative after the other,'' Elston said Wednesday,
citing Pataki's support for the $1.75 billion Clean Water-Clean Air
Bond Act, a park on Manhattan's Hudson River shoreline and state
purchases of forested tracts upstate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the League of Conservation Voters endorsed Gov. Mario
Cuomo, while criticizing Pataki's record in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The league, which is scheduled to formally announce its
endorsement Thursday in Manhattan, is a private political action
group that grades the environmental records of elected officials
and candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups have had a mixed relationship with Pataki,
with those focused on preserving open space closest to him, and
those focused on strengthening regulation of polluters more
critical.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has come under the sharpest criticism for shrinking the
budget of the Department of Environmental Conservation and reducing
the agency's emphasis on pollution enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The New York chapter of the Sierra Club has not decided to
endorse any candidate yet, said John Stouffer, the chief Albany
lobbyist for the group, adding that Pataki's mixed record made it
unlikely that he would receive the group's support. ``At this point
an endorsement of Pataki would be very difficult,'' Stouffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Elston said the conservation league's decision to support Pataki
was prompted by the governor's strong stand on issues like
requiring car manufacturers to offer some models that produce no
air pollution, and his commitment to expanding the state superfund
program.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ragone, a spokesman for New York City Council Speaker
Peter Vallone, a Democratic candidate for governor, said Pataki's
environmental record did not deserve such praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the league is a fine organization, it's troubling that
they chose to ignore the sad reality of the Pataki administration's
environmental policies, such as the 51 percent decline in
enforcement penalties for environmental violations,'' Ragone said.
He was referring to a recent audit of the Department of
Environmental Conservation by Richard Brodsky, chairman of the
state Assembly Environmental Conservation Committee, who has been
at odds with Pataki on many issues.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky also received an early endorsement from the League of
Conservation Voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
