<SLUG> BC-HOMEPRICES-SURGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
 
L.A. COUNTY HOME VALUES UP 11 PERCENT TO SET '90s RECORD, SURVEY(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A resurgent real estate market pushed Los Angeles
County's home values to their highest level of the decade during
this year's second quarter, a just-released survey showed.
</P>
<P>
   Values in the county jumped 11 percent from the 1997 quarter,
said First American Real Estate Solutions, formerly Experian, an
Anaheim-based market tracker.
</P>
<P>
   The region is now among the nation's best markets, reflecting
its increased attractiveness to home buyers. ``Eleven percent is a
very respectable performance,'' said Nima Nattagh, First American's
research director.
</P>
<P>
   The local results helped boost home values in the nation's major
metropolitan areas by 9.5 percent during the April-June period, the
biggest jump this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The company's assessment of home values is based on a ``repeat
sales model,'' which tracks the resale value of homes that have
sold at least twice. Some analysts consider this method a more
accurate measure of the marketplace than focusing on average or
median prices recorded by real estate trade associations.
</P>
<P>
   The strong performance by Los Angeles County came amid a surge
in values in other areas of California. Six of the eight areas in
which values jumped 10 percent or more are in the state, with
neighboring Orange County leading the way at 17.9 percent. First
American surveyed 36 markets.
</P>
<P>
   New York City and the Seattle area were the only non-California
markets to post double-digit growth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the California picture was not entirely rosy. Although
the state's major urban centers have emerged as the nation's
hottest real estate markets, the state's housing recovery is spotty
and home values in some areas have not recovered ground lost during
the recession.
</P>
<P>
   Values in the Riverside-San Bernardino area and Sacramento also
have not yet shaken off the effects of the recession. The regions
are, respectively, 24 percent and 12 percent under their
pre-recession peaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if today's trends continue, then I think it is just a
matter of time before homeowners who bought at the peak of the
market recoup the equity losses they incurred throughout the
1990s,'' Nattagh said.
</P>
<P>
   This is good news for the state's homeowners because for much of
the decade home values barely kept pace with inflation. But
double-digit gains in some parts of California have been the norm
since the last half of 1996, First American said.
</P>
<P>
   The steep gains in appreciation are being fueled by a strong
economy, with some key components being low unemployment, increases
in personal income and low interest rates. They have added up to a
buoyant housing market during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   And now the supply of homes for sale is tightening, especially
in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley area, which will put more upward
pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Gibson, chief economist for the California Department of
Finance, believes the gains in value could stimulate home building.
``It's a very strong signal that it's time to gear up the
home-building industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 130,000 new units will be built this year in California,
up 17 percent from 1997. Gibson said this figure could jump to
about 160,000 units next year, although that will not be enough to
satisfy demand and is far short of the 245,000 units built annually
between 1985 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
   However, the current building pace is ``a massive improvement''
from 1993 and 1995, when only 84,000 units were built each year,
Gibson noted. Even in the late 1970s and early 1980s, when mortgage
rates approached 14 percent, home-building activity did not descend
to those levels.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
