<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DOCTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REJECTED HMO CLAIMS, LATE PAYMENTS THREATEN DOCTORS' SOLVENCY,
GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (bl)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A group of doctors and consumer advocates said
Wednesday that the company that processes claims of more than half
the state's 2.3 million health maintenance organization subscribers
has endangered the solvency of doctors and hospitals in the state
by denying claims and delaying payments.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, they said that through a loophole in state law,
these companies that do nothing but process claims are not
themselves considered insurers and therefore are out of the reach
of state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the company that was the main target of the
anger, Allied Specialty Services, denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The criticisms of such companies, called ``third-party
administrators,'' came from an unlikely assemblage that included
doctors involved in the year-old effort to unionize physicians in
the state, leaders of the state's more traditional, 222-year-old
medical society and members of Citizen Action, the consumer group
that is usually critical of the profession's treatment of its
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But these groups seemed unified in their criticism of the
practices of Allied Specialty Services, the Florida-based company
that reviews, adjusts and pays claims for a range of medical
specialties.
</P>
<P>
   ``HMOs have been practicing medicine without a license for years
through their interference with medical decisions made by
doctors,'' said Dr. Anthony Tonzola, president of the 700-member
Physicians Union, an affiliate of the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers. ``With Allied Specialty Services,
they have gone one step further _ they're running an insurance
company without a license because of a loophole in state law.''
</P>
<P>
   The group announced its support of pending legislation that
would bring the third-party administrators under the orbit of state
regulators and insure prompt payment.
</P>
<P>
   However, on Sept. 8, new state regulations take effect that will
for the first time put teeth into enforcement of a prompt-payment
law that has been on the books since 1991, said Tom Breslin, a
spokesman for the state Department of Health and Senior Services.
Those regulations were the outgrowth of meetings last year with
critics of the current system.
</P>
<P>
   But those who participated in the meetings insisted that new
legislation is still needed to stiffen the resolve of state
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Tonzola and others charged that Allied Specialty Services had an
incentive to delay and deny claims because doing so allowed them to
invest, for longer periods of time, the money that the HMOs give
them to satisfy claims and thereby earn more on those investments.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Allied Specialty Services as well as the
association representing the state's 11 HMOs denied the charges,
saying that the doctors were either misinformed about the
arrangements between the HMOs and their claims processors or
blindly intent upon returning to the imperfect and costly practices
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   In the new world of health cost containment, said Dr. Lawrence
Schimmel, one of the founders of Allied Specialty Services,
improper billing is rife and the company has developed
sophisticated computer programs to weed out such mistakes and
possibly fraudulent claims.
</P>
<P>
   Schimmel also said that his company operated on a
fee-for-service basis in its contracts with four of the state's
largest HMOs and therefore did not benefit financially from holding
on to money from the insurers. It was the insurers themselves who
held the money until the claims were approved and checks cut, he
said. The company operates in 12 states processing 4 million claims
a year, Schimmel said.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, there had been a number of complaints over the
last year from medical specialists, he said, who were claiming
higher fees for consultations than were allowed by the Health Care
Financing Administration, the federal agency whose fee codes set
the standard for the industry. The HMOs serviced by Allied are HMO
Blue, Prudential HMO, Cigna HMO and NYLCare HMO.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened is that the doctors in New Jersey don't like
the fact that we downgrade them when they can't submit
documentation supporting a higher level of payment,'' Schimmel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the HMOs, Paul Langenvin, president of the New
Jersey HMO Association, said that the charges by the groups were
without foundation. He said that the HMOs took full responsibility
and were subject to punishment based on the actions of the claims
processors with which they contract. Under the new regulations, he
said, they will have to pay properly documented claims in 60 days
or face a penalty of 10 percent a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
