<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST STAYING WITH LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ There will be no sabbaticals for Jerry West,
nor a premature retirement for the Lakers' chief architect. In
fact, he'll be guiding the team's fortunes well into the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   West, the Lakers' top basketball executive for 16 seasons, has
agreed to a contract extension in the four- to five-year range. The
upcoming season would have been the last under his current deal.
</P>
<P>
   West and team owner Jerry Buss were ironing out the final
details of the new pact Wednesday, and an announcement is expected
as soon as today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're close to getting it done,'' Lakers spokesman John
Black said. ``Jerry West is definitely coming back next year. He
and Jerry Buss are discussing an extension that will be addressed
if and when it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifics of the extension were not available, but the Riverside
Press-Enterprise reported Wednesday that West would earn $3.5
million a year _ about a $2 million raise.
</P>
<P>
   Just four months ago, West contemplated leaving the team, citing
stress. He insisted at the time money had nothing to do with his
decision, although there were reports Buss owed West $4 million in
bonuses that had been deferred but have since been paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a wonderful year, but I can tell you that every
game I watched is like going to the dentist,'' West said in April.
``Sometimes, I say this is not good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old Hall of Famer said he would not make any
decision until the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the NBA's lockout, West spent most of August
vacationing in Europe and on the East Coast. When he returned last
week, the new deal was quickly hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has implications far beyond the Lakers merely keeping
one of the top executives in pro sports under contract. It could
also guarantee that the Lakers' franchise players, Shaquille O'Neal
and Kobe Bryant, remain with the team for the rest of their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, whose contract is up next summer, and O'Neal, who can
opt out of his deal next year, had both said West's departure would
have an impact on their decisions. O'Neal, who has a close
relationship with West, said during the season that he would be
``upset... to the highest degree of upsetivity'' if West left for
any reason other than health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's agent Leonard Armato said West's new contract is good
news for the Lakers and his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted he's signed a long-term extension that
stabilizes the future of the Lakers quite a bit... and that a
master captain is going to be at the head of the ship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armato declined to speculate how West's possible departure would
have affected O'Neal, but noted, ``Jerry means a lot to him. And
they both have tremendous respect for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   West, a Laker for most of his life, followed a 14-year,
Hall-of-Fame career as a player with a storied run as coach,
special consultant, general manager and executive vice president,
overseeing three NBA championships and seven Finals appearances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
