<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' LETT BACK ON FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys defensive tackle Leon Lett practiced
yesterday for the first time in more than three weeks and probably
will be in the starting lineup when the Cowboys meet the Arizona
Cardinals in Sunday's season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said he is 95 percent certain that
Lett, who sprained his left knee in a scrimmage against New Orleans
on Aug. 11, will play against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he felt good,'' Gailey said. ``Let us make the
decision on Sunday, but I'm optimistic he will play well over 50
percent of the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Lett is listed as questionable for the game. Second-year tackle
Antonio Anderson also will see time at Lett's tackle spot.
</P>
<P>
   Kavika Pittman also returned to practice yesterday. Pittman, who
has been hobbled the past three weeks by a sprained right ankle,
will start at weakside defensive end Sunday. Gonzalez is back The
Cowboys re-signed rookie free-agent Daniel Gonzalez to be the
team's third quarterback for Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who was the No. 3 quarterback in training camp, was
released Saturday. His return became necessary when former Oilers
quarterback James Ritchey, whom the Cowboys claimed off waivers,
failed his physical.
</P>
<P>
   The turn of events made for an interesting two days for
Gonzalez, who drove home to Chesapeake, Va., Tuesday and had to
drive back to Irving yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hectic, but I'm glad to be back,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Gonzalez's spot is guaranteed only for this weekend
since the team will re-evaluate the third quarterback spot next
week. Briefly The Cowboys added center/guard Earl Scott to the
practice squad yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said that Kevin Mathis will be the team's primary kickoff
returner against the Cardinals and that cornerback Deion Sanders
will handle punt returns. Either Billy Davis or Jeff Ogden will be
the other deep man on kickoff returns.
</P>
<P>
   Safety George Teague, who will start in the nickel defense,
strained his left hamstring in practice yesterday and is listed as
day-to-day _ though the Cowboys' training staff won't have a
prognosis for Sunday's game until they re-evaluate Teague today.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones confirmed that he has talked to former Cowboys
running back Herschel Walker, but said no decision has been made on
whether Walker will return to the team. Jones said Walker would not
be signed before Sunday's game with the Cardinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
