u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN03-COX     09-02 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson, Astros tough on Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy Johnson held up his end of the bargain. Greg Maddux had
his right arm gnawed off at the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros bashed Maddux for 10 hits, including three
home runs, to take a 4-2 victory over the Braves Wednesday night in
a game billed for pitching brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in his first start against Atlanta since being acquired
by Houston July 31, gave up a run in the first and shut out of the
Braves on three hits through eight innings, striking out 10, to
improve to 6-1. He left with leg cramps in his left leg after
batting in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux (17-7) gave up 10 hits for the second time in three
starts to fall to 5-5 in the second half. He threw only one hitless
inning before exiting after the seventh with three strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner pitched the 9th for Houston, allowing Andruw Jones'
25th homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won the season series against Atlanta five games to
four, the first time they've taken the Braves since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's third homer belonged to Sean Berry, who hit Maddux's
first pitch of the seventh inning over the center field wall for a
4-1 lead. Maddux had gone the first 392 starts of his career
without giving up a three-homer game and now has done it twice in
three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio gave Houston a 3-1 lead in the fifth, when he
homered to left with Brad Ausmus on second. The homer was Biggio's
19th of the season but the first of his career against Maddux in 83
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell tied it 1-1 with a lead-off homer in the second,
when the Astros recorded four hits but scored just once. Maddux
received a huge break when Moises Alou, who had doubled behind
Bagwell, was hit by Berry's grounder as he attempted to take third
base.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones was Maddux's greatest ally in the early going. When
Ricky Gutierrez sent a sinking single into center in the first
inning, Jones missed with a diving attempt, but still got up in
time to throw out Gutierrez when he attempted to take second. Jones
then assisted on a double play in the third, when Biggio took off
on a hit and run with Derek Bell at the plate. Jones ran down
Bell's line drive and then rifled a throw back to first to
double-off Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson might have gift-wrapped the Braves first run, when he
walked Gerald Williams on four pitches in the first. Williams stole
second, made third on a passed ball by catcher Ausmus and then came
in for a 1-0 lead on Javy Lopez's RBI single. The single gave Lopez
a career-high 11-game hitting streak and gave him eight RBI in five
games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
