<SLUG> BC-BBN-McGWIRE-RESTAURANT-LADN </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE'S CAP PUTS RESTAURANT ON MAP 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest thing on the grill at The Abbey, a small restaurant
in Seal Beach, Calif., is Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Not a ``Mark McGwire Sandwich'' or ``Mark McGwire Special'' or
dare we say? ``Big Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Mark McGwire himself, whose dramatic pursuit of Roger
Maris' home run record has put The Abbey (306 Main St.) squarely on
the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been absolutely amazing,'' said Rob Burdick, manager of
The Abbey, which his brother, Mike, opened only little more than a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's all because McGwire, when he sits down to face the press
night after night, has taken to wearing caps emblazoned with ``The
Abbey, Seal Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard from people all over the country,'' said Burdick.
``I've had hundreds of calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lady from Johnson City, Tenn., called (Wednesday) morning.
She wanted to buy some caps. A guy from New York called. He'd been
to Seal Beach and he wanted a cap. A fellow from St. Louis had been
out here on vacation. He wanted a cap. I even got a call from a guy
on a ship who was on his way here and wanted to make sure I saved
him a cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day we had caps we sold out, all 50. I had to order
some more.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what is it with Mark McGwire, soon-to-be (?) home run king,
and The Abbey?
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to know Mark at our other restaurant, Tsunami (17236
Pacific Coast Highway), in Seal Beach,'' Burdick said. ``Robb Nen
(a relief pitcher with the Giants who grew up in neighboring Los
Alamitos) is a good friend of mine and, through him, I got to know
Mark, who lives close by (in Huntington Harbour). We talk, maybe,
one, two times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started with Mark wearing a Tsunami cap ... but that's
all that's on it, Tsunami. So, when I was in Chicago a couple of
weeks ago, when the Cardinals were there, I brought along a whole
supply of caps from The Abbey.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, The Abbey is keeping close tabs on McGwire's home run
pace. Sometimes it's a little taxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a `Big Mac Meter' in the front window,'' Burdick
said, ``and (Tuesday night), when he hit those two homers, I'd just
put up No. 56 and - bang - he hit No. 57. Fifty-six wasn't up there
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, it couldn't happen to a nicer guy,'' Burdick
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who could sitting there in front of millions
(watching on television) wearing a Nike cap, but instead he's
wearing one from a little restaurant in Seal Beach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
