r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     09-02 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORYATT, HALEY ON JONES' LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
and CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Charles Haley is talking to the Cowboys about
coming out of retirement, and Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said he
would expand his checkbook in an attempt to sign former Colts
linebacker Quentin Coryatt.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Haley, who would still have to pass a physical, nor
Coryatt, who was released by the Colts last week, would be signed
in time for the Cowboys' season opener against the Arizona
Cardinals on Sunday, Jones said. But Jones is expected to talk with
both players before the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles has definitely decided to play,'' Jones said of Haley,
who retired because of back injuries in July 1997, but would come
back as a pass-rush specialist. ``This is interesting. I'm anxious
to sit down and see what his thoughts are. I'd like to sort through
(Haley's thoughts) a little more and see what's best for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys would be the second team to consider adding Haley to
their roster. Haley worked out with the San Francisco 49ers on
Tuesday, but the 49ers decided not to sign the defensive end who
played with them from 1986-91.
</P>
<P>
   After looking at a magnetic resonance imaging exam of Haley's
back, 49ers vice president Dwight Clark told the San Francisco-area
media during a news conference yesterday that, ``his back looked
pretty bad. It didn't look like he'd be able to practice much, or
play the 15 plays a game that we would want. His workout was a lot
better than his exam. But we decided the best thing for us is if we
pass at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the situation said Haley did not flunk the
49ers' physical, but other factors led to the club passing on him.
Haley had a rancorous relationship with the 49ers in his six
seasons there.
</P>
<P>
   In going after Coryatt, Jones also confirmed that he would be
getting into a bidding war with several teams and was prepared to
make him the highest-paid linebacker in club history. Coryatt
worked out with the Chicago Bears yesterday and also has received
interest from the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we signed (Coryatt), we would break the mold for what we've
traditionally paid linebackers,'' Jones said of Coryatt, who was
scheduled to make $2.3 million in 1998. In terms of base salary,
the Cowboys have never paid a linebacker more than the $750,000
they paid Darrin Smith in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt, who was a roommate of Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith at
Texas A&AMP;M, worked out at Valley Ranch during the off-season and
knows many Cowboys players. Jones said the club would use Smith's
relationship with Coryatt to woo the seventh-year linebacker, who
was the second overall pick of the 1992 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes it here,'' said Smith, who spoke with Coryatt
yesterday. ``He just wants to be in a good situation. But our
friendship won't be the deciding factor.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to sign Haley, 34, began last weekend. Haley told
Cowboys officials that he wants to play again and asked Jones to
officially release his rights. The Cowboys, Jones said, did not
immediately show an interest in Haley, who was the club's most
consistent pass rusher from 1992 until back problems sacked him for
much of the 1996 season. He had 34 sacks during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Haley flew to San Francisco on Tuesday, when he worked out for
49ers coaches and scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked pretty good,'' 49ers defensive coordinator John
Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   If he passes a physical and the Cowboys sign him, Haley would
probably be used in obvious passing situations. The Cowboys have
struggled rushing the passer this summer. Defensive ends Greg Ellis
and Kavika Pittman did not have a sack during five exhibition
games.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt, meanwhile, would likely be an every-down player. He
played primarily strong-side linebacker in Indianapolis, and his
presence probably would allow Cowboys coaches to move Randall
Godfrey inside to compete with starting middle linebacker Fred
Strickland. The team had considered moving Godfrey to middle
linebacker in training camp until Broderick Thomas suffered a
season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys restructured quarterback Troy Aikman's contract
Tuesday to help the club get under the league-limit $52,388,000
salary cap. Of the Coryatt and Haley deals, Jones said, ``One
wouldn't effect the other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
