<HEADLINE>
JAYHAWKS' COACH LOOKING TO PROVE HIMSELF OFFENSIVELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Allen proved he could make the transition from coaching
Division I-AA to Division I-A. Now, he hopes to get the chance to
demonstrate his ability as an offensive coach.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Northern Iowa, Allen took over at Kansas last
season. He inherited a team few thought was capable of a winning
record. The Jayhawks finished 5-6, losing their final two games to
fall out of contention for a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sophomore years can be scary years,'' Allen said. ``I'm not
trying to stab anybody in the back, but we weren't left with a
plethora of players. Now, we're just trying to get the ball moving
with the guys we recruited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be a better football team, but whether our record will
be better, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   At Northern Iowa, Allen's teams were known for their
high-scoring offense. Last season, the Jayhawks finished last in
the nation in total offense with 241.4 yards per game. Kansas won
five games despite averaging 16.1 points per game. The offensive
output was the Jayhawks' worst in more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 112 is a motivation for us,'' running back Mitch Bowles
said. ``It affects our pride. We want to go out and prove it won't
happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen is counting on 10 returning starters on offense, a
stronger offensive line and junior quarterback Zac Wegner to boost
the team's offense. In their last three games, the Jayhawks
averaged 353 yards and 27 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You finish last in the nation and nobody has expectations for
you. That can be a positive thing,'' wide receiver Michael Chandler
said. ``The offense was new for us last year. We had young guys.
But if you look at it, our stats improved late in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who replaced Glen Mason who took the job at Minnesota,
has, if nothing else, improved the Jayhawks' attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is together,'' offensive lineman Justin Glasgow
said. ``It used to be hard to get in touch with (coach Mason.) It
seems coach Allen is always around a lot of places and
communicating with the players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Allen is a players' coach who can motivate people and
get them ready to play,'' linebacker Pat Brown said. ``He's always
talking with the players and asks us to let him know how we're
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Kansas won four of its first five games. This
season, the Jayhawks need another fast start. They open the season
Saturday against Oklahoma State, and then play at rival Missouri on
Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's biggest concern is a lack of depth, so he decided it was
best to play two conference games at the beginning of the season
when his team was most likely to be at full strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled at the end of the season, so we might have lost
some of the confidence we might have had,'' Allen said. ``But I
think we've got some confidence going into the second year. We're
light years ahead of where we were a year ago at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we all got to know each other. What we expect in
certain situations, what dictates success and failure. I think all
the players are headed in the same direction, and that's a big
positive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
