<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UNT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGH ROAD FAMILIAR POSITION FOR NORTH TEXAS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ Looking back, Darrell Dickey had the world at
his fingertips in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   He only had to sign his name to grab hold.
</P>
<P>
   A letter of intent lay before him, a pledge to follow his dad
and play for Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about to become the quarterback for a football team that
wasn't winning very many games, that my father was the head coach
of,'' Dickey said, ``and I don't think I had any idea how hard that
would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 20 years later, Dickey is the first-year head coach of a
North Texas team that hasn't won very many games lately, 11-of-33
since moving up to Division I-A in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time around, Dickey knows exactly how hard it is going
to be, and still he says, it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say that knowing everybody is going to laugh and think `He's
crazy,' '' Dickey said. ``Well, when I arrived at Kansas State, if
I said that, I'd have been crazy, too, and now, they're talking
about having a shot at a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   UNT has smaller goals, trying to win any games it can against a
brutal schedule, invigorating a stagnant alumni base and generating
revenue. To do so, Dickey has borrowed from a plan his father
implemented upon his arrival at Kansas State _ recruit locally,
think long term and improve every year.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels between Kansas State and North Texas are
startling.
</P>
<P>
   When Dickey's father, Jim, was hired as the head coach at Kansas
State in 1978, the program recently had been through two
probations, never been to a bowl game and hadn't won a Big Eight
Conference game in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Dickey said he figured he'd change all of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the good things about Darrell, he wasn't
afraid of anything,'' recalls TCU coach Dennis Franchione, then, an
assistant at Kansas State under Jim Dickey. ``Sometimes we felt he
needed to be afraid of some things. He wasn't afraid of a challenge
though, and certainly Kansas State didn't have a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who can say they knew Dickey when he was just Darrell
Ray, they would expect nothing less. He was the kid afraid of
nothing. The quarterback from North Carolina with the curly
golden-blond hair, and a golden arm to match, wasn't afraid of a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Was there a better example than the Missouri game in 1979?
Dickey was just a redshirt freshman, and he got his first start for
Kansas State on a cool, autumn day in Columbia. He led a 27-point
underdog Wildcats squad to a 19-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that day Dickey made his first big impression on
current UNT athletic director Craig Helwig, who would choose him as
head coach nearly 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about that game a lot when I decided on a coach,''
said Helwig, who was an assistant AD at Kansas State when Dickey
played. ``I think the thing that always stands out in my mind is he
always found a way to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey threw for 4,098 yards and 23 touchdowns in four years at
Kansas State, saving his best for his final season. He passed for a
personal-best 1,225 yards and eight touchdowns, and led Kansas
State to an Independence Bowl berth in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was vindication. We were the whipping boys of the Big Eight
for a long time. There were a lot of 58-6s and 48-0s getting
there,'' said Rusty Hill, the backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   They held a party for him recently, 40 or 50 former Kansas State
teammates from all over the country who came to Kansas City to
celebrate Dickey becoming UNT's coach.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody was there. Steve Willis showed, the kicker who to this
day can see the look on Dickey's face as he returned to the huddle
after being drilled by Arizona State linebacker Vernon Maxwell in
1982. Oh, and offensive lineman Amos Donaldson was there, too. He
was Dickey's first roommate in college, the one who helped him ring
up almost $300 in cheeseburgers on Jim Dickey's country-club tab
one month.
</P>
<P>
   And the one thing they agreed on was that Dickey is a perfect
fit for UNT, because he has been there before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Darrell Ray (took the job) because he has been in that
situation before, and he knows what it takes,'' former Wildcats
teammate Mark Mackey said. ``He has a way of making everybody
believe the impossible can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the guys hadn't seen Dickey since those days, although
they had kept up with his career. They knew he had held assistant
positions at UT-El Paso, Louisiana State, Mississippi State and
Memphis through the years. He spent last season as the offensive
coordinator at SMU, helping a struggling Mustangs program to its
first winning season since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not coached any place where you walk in and they were
like `Are y'all going to the Orange Bowl or the Rose Bowl?' ''
Dickey said. ``I haven't been there. Where I've been is: `Let's get
on our feet. Let's get over the hump.' ''
</P>
<P>
   UNT has a huge hurdle to overcome, and that's Dickey's
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun, and I say that knowing everybody knows
the odds are stacked against me,'' Dickey said. ``If you make the
decision to do it, you better let it rip and approach it like you
are not scared, because if people sense you are scared they become
scared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
