<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT EXTENSION CLOSE FOR HITCHCOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said yesterday that he
is close to terms on a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which would likely keep him under contract with the
team for the next three years, would increase his tenure as one of
the most senior coaches in the NHL with the same team. Hitchcock
will soon begin his third full season as head coach, ranking fifth
behind Scotty Bowman of Detroit, Ron Low of Edmonton, Larry
Robinson of Los Angeles and Paul Maurice of Carolina in the 29-team
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful it will get done in the next day or two, and that
would be something that for myself and my family would be
fantastic,'' Hitchcock said. ``There are a lot of good coaches in
the NHL who have been a good coach for three or four teams. But I
always wanted to see myself as a good coach of one team.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over for general manager Bob Gainey, who gave up
his dual roles, on Jan. 8, 1996, Hitchcock has a 112-71-24 record
in the regular season. Last season, he led the Stars to the
Presidents' Trophy for best regular-season record in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   He finished second in the voting for the Jack Adams Award (NHL
coach of the year) in 1996-97 and finished third last season. He
was voted coach of the year by ``The Sporting News'' and ``The
Hockey News'' in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, 46, got into coaching at the midget ranks in
Edmonton, Alberta, and has worked himself up through the lower
levels before coaching the Stars' minor-league affiliate in
Kalamazoo, Mich. He said spending five years in the Stars'
organization has helped him appreciate what Gainey and owner Tom
Hicks are building.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's being built here is a commitment to winning, and you
always want to be a part of that,'' he said. ``This means a lot to
me. It means they believe in me as a coach and as a person.'' &QL; 
LIND GONE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left winger Juha Lind is close to signing a contract in Europe
and will not play for the Stars this season, his agent, Don
Baizley, said.
</P>
<P>
   Lind, 23, played in 15 of the Stars' 17 playoff games last
season and had seemingly worked himself into a regular position on
the team. But when the Stars refused to offer the restricted free
agent a ``one-way'' contract that would help keep him from playing
in the minor leagues, Lind decided it would be best to stay in
Europe, Baizley said.
</P>
<P>
   Lind is talking with Jokerit in his native Finland, as well as
teams in the Swedish and German leagues. As a restricted free
agent, he remains the Stars' property in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that he stays over there for only one year and
returns to the NHL,'' Baizley said. ``We'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have an abundance of left wingers fighting for a
regular spot, including Jamie Langenbrunner, Dave Reid, Brent
Severyn, Jamie Wright, Dave Roberts and either Brett Hull or Jere
Lehtinen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
