<HEADLINE>
REPORTERS EXPLAIN LEWINSKY QUESTIONS IN KREMLIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The two reporters who questioned President Clinton on
the Lewinsky matter Wednesday at the Kremlin both said that they
had raised the matter because they were frustrated by the lack of
opportunity to question Clinton about it since his speech to the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Santos, 40, who has covered the White House for 10 years
for United Press International, said she felt compelled to question
Clinton because it was her first chance since the Aug. 17
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen him,'' Ms. Santos said. ``We have not had the
opportunity to seek amplification. But we also wanted to know his
reaction to the fallout from his televised address and whether he
felt it was inhibiting his ability to govern.''
</P>
<P>
   The other reporter, Laurence McQuillan, 53, a Reuters
correspondent who has covered the White House for most of the past
22 years, said he had been considering a Lewinsky-related question
to the president for several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case,'' he said, ``I really wanted to ask a question
about Russia, but when I heard his response to the first question
about Lewinsky I thought it was so inadequate that I had to ask
mine. One, because we knew the press conference was going to be
short. And there was no one who can tell you when the next time
reporters will be near Bill Clinton again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
