<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-ATLANTIC-CITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR TOWNS: DEATH STOPS AT LAST RESORT FOR GAMBLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ The clerk at the Golden Island
cash-for-gold shop peered at the front door from behind
bullet-proof glass for a long minute before buzzing in the small,
solitary woman waiting outside. It was 2:30 in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes? What do you want?'' he said in a thick Russian accent,
when his potential customer walked in the door. A short man, he
strained to give the walk-in the once-over from behind the counter.
``Buy?'' he asked. ``Or sell?''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be little tolerance for browsing at the
cash-for-gold stores around the casinos. The cash-for-gold stores
are just about the only local businesses that have thrived since
the city started tearing down buildings to make way for gambling 20
years ago, and they are braced for the worst kind of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 cash-for-gold shops on Atlantic and Pacific Avenues, the
resort's main streets, all keep their doors locked and their gold
and their clerks sealed away behind windows. Many of the stores
have a public space no bigger than a bathroom stall. They allow one
customer in at a time, making desperate gamblers wait outside in
the thick of night even though all the cash and gold in the little
stores are behind half-inch-thick Plexiglas and steel partitions.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, after two attacks on storekeepers, it looks as though
the worst trouble has arrived. Three weeks ago, there was an
attempted robbery at City Jewelers, a cash-for-gold store on
Pacific Avenue. The 21-year-old proprietor, Alex Kotlyarenko, was
stabbed several times in the chest, neck and stomach. He lived to
tell about it, and the police have a warrant for a suspect, Huy T.
Luong, 30, of Jersey City. But on Friday, there was another
assault, believed to be unrelated, and Andrei Dvoriantchikov, the
38-year-old owner of Resort Jewelers on Atlantic Avenue, didn't
pull through.
</P>
<P>
   He was shot three times, in the mouth, heart and stomach, by
someone he had let into his inner office.
</P>
<P>
   The police say robbery may be a motive in that case, too. But by
Tuesday afternoon, rumors had spread that Dvoriantchikov had been
executed in classic Russian mob fashion. The police will not
discuss that possibility, and in any case it appears to have done
little to ease the anxieties of the mostly Russian and Asian
immigrant shopkeepers in the cash-for-gold stores.
</P>
<P>
   Five shopkeepers who were approached along Atlantic Avenue
refused to talk about the latest killing. At one, the clerk, who
was from Russia, brandished a copy of the local newspaper, The
Press of Atlantic City. He gestured to an article that suggested
the shooting of Dvoriantchikov was a mob hit. ``You don't worry,''
he said. ``The story is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it isn't. Even if the assailants in both incidents
are caught, what has happened has cast a new spotlight on the shady
world of jewelry buyers. No one paid much attention to the stores
before; they were just another consequence of gambling. But now,
they look like real problems. They have raised questions about
whether the Russian mob might be involved in the cash-for-gold
business. They also have other shopkeepers publicly worrying about
getting caught in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   The recent crimes have also pointed out the distinction between
pawnbrokers and cash-for-gold shops (which are listed under
``jewelry buyers'' in the Yellow Pages). Most people think they are
the same, which bothers pawnbrokers no end.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional pawnshops, which lend customers money and hold their
valuables as collateral, charging 3 percent interest a month, are
``bankers to the poor,'' says Martin Wood, owner of Wood's Money to
Loan on Atlantic Avenue. ``Cash-for-gold stores, on the other hand,
buy a customer's jewelry outright, and sell them back to them at a
20 percent markup or, after 15 days, to whoever cares to buy
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The moral distinction may be lost to most people. ``But it's a
big difference,'' said Wood, a fourth-generation broker. ``Once a
cash-for-gold store buys your jewelry,'' he said, ``you have no
claim to it.''
</P>
<P>
   His store, one of two pawnshops in Atlantic City, is much larger
than the cubicles the cash-for-gold stores operate, but no less
secure. He and his assistant sit behind bulletproof glass. Signs on
the front windows warn people they are being videotaped. Inside,
there are more cameras and a sign warning ``Guard Dogs on Duty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been security conscious,'' Wood said, ``but I'm
not too worried about what's happened recently. I'm a 9 to 5
business. Those cash-for-gold places run till 2 a.m. That's their
world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
