<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
59 DOWN, 2 TO GO FOR MCGWIRE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Mark McGwire, who hit two home runs on Tuesday night,
made it Nos. 58 and 59 against the Florida Marlins on Wednesday
night, putting him only two short of tying Roger Maris'
single-season record.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit No. 58 in the seventh inning. It came on a low,
inside 2-1 curveball from right-hander Brian Edmondson, the ball
sailing over the left-field fence and carrying an estimated 497
feet.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire knew it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals first baseman took several steps out of
the batter's box, then pumped his right arm as he watched yet
another home run fly out of Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third-longest home run at this stadium, behind Andres
Galarraga's 529-footer and McGwire's 500-footer, both last season.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, McGwire hit Rob Stanifer's first pitch, a
fastball, into the left-center-field seats, an estimated 458 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Both homers Wednesday came with one man on base and brought
standing ovations from the crowd of 45,170 _ the largest of the
season here _ and curtain calls from McGwire as the Cards trounced
the Marlins, 14-4.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, the Cubs' Sammy Sosa hit homer No. 56 at Wrigley
Field in Chicago's 4-2 win over the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire moved past Jimmie Foxx, who hit 58 homers in 1932, and
Hank Greenberg, who hit 58 in 1938, and McGwire eclipsed the 58
that he hit last season, 34 for Oakland and 24 for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And he pulled even with Babe Ruth, who had 59 homers in 1921. He
is now one behind Ruth's 60-homer season of 1927 as he takes aim at
Maris' mark of 61, set in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three plate appearances, McGwire grounded into a
double play and walked twice.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday marked McGwire's eighth multihomer game of the season.
The team has 23 games left to play, and McGwire seemed to
understand that he was now an odds-on favorite to break Maris'
mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole month of the season left,'' he said. ``There's
a great, great possibility that there's going to be two or three
guys. I wouldn't rule out Ken Griffey. I mean, this man is going to
get hot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
