<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE'S GOLDEN RISES ABOVE TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Jeremy Golden wears his tribute to his
father on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   That's where he has a tattoo of an eagle, but it doesn't
resemble an eagle. Instead, it's a sketch, and you have to use your
mind to fill in the blanks.
</P>
<P>
   This is significant. Golden, a Cal State Northridge defensive
back, lost his father, Mike, in a construction accident when he was
6. Golden's memories are sketchy 13 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a way to remember his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have someone watching over my shoulder,'' he said.
``I wouldn't mind my dad watching with eagle eyes. Those are the
best eyes to have, right?''
</P>
<P>
   And Golden really needs someone to watch over him. He seeks
thrills in BMX bicycle racing, skateboarding, snowboarding,
waterskiing and wakeboarding. Next up is motorcycling, rugby and
surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic Mountain is lame now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's into zanier things, as he has a pierced tongue. Out of
respect for his mother's wishes, Golden waited until he was 18 to
have his tongue pierced and shoulder tattooed.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Kim Bourdon, suspects Mike wouldn't have approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom wouldn't let me,'' Jeremy said. ``I do everything that
keeps me on the edge. I love all the extracurricular activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorite pastimes is football. While he is the first
in his family to play, he goes at it with a gusto that would make
his father proud.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot, 180-pound sophomore will be one of four returning
defensive starters in the Matadors' season opener Saturday at Boise
State. Last year as a freshman, he started the second game, at
Hawaii, and returned an interception 65 yards for a touchdown _
after he dislocated a shoulder. He finished the season with 65
unassisted tackles, 19 assisted tackles and four interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was the Hawaii game that earned him attention. Only then
did everyone become aware of his off-the-field antics. Couple that
with his frame and it's easy to see why Northridge coach Ron
Ponciano says Golden ``is not your prototype at that position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at (wide receiver James) Maldonado. He's built,''
Ponciano said. ``(Fellow DB) Vito Clemente's got some bumps on his
body. He passes the eyeball test. Jeremy doesn't pass the eyeball
test. For one, he rides skateboards.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ponciano discovered Golden recently broke his board, he
said, ``I bet it's a devastating thing in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden laughed, but it's clear losing his father was the
toughest. Mike was crushed when beams 11 stories high came crashing
down with him on it.
</P>
<P>
   Golden stayed away from school for three weeks and didn't want
to return because he feared everyone asking him about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea why my teacher asked me to stand up and talk
about it because I was bawling,'' he said. ``I asked why it had to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the man who used to let Golden take off his
construction boots after a long day. Jeremy said Mike always
promised his feet smelled like strawberries. Instead, they smelled
like sweaty feet.
</P>
<P>
   Never again would Mike be around to walk his son to a finish
line after little Jeremy had spilled off his BMX bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want me to quit,'' Jeremy said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many families, they went forward. Kim remarried and Jeremy
grew up and watched out for his younger brother, Josh (now a junior
at Westlake). But somewhere along the way, Kim said, Golden
discovered a need to revisit his father's memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be a need now,'' she said. ``Maybe he's trying to
find his way. You have to make your own life. Maybe he's trying to
find himself. We all go through different turning points.''
</P>
<P>
   When he turned 18, Golden got the eagle. He now feels like Mike
is near again, and it gives him a sense of safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy,'' he said. ``I have fun every day. I wake up in
the morning happy where I'm at. If I died today, I'd say I lived a
full life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
