<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMEN-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED IN 1 MURDER, SUSPECTED IN 7 OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-WOMEN-SLAIN-KIN) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police investigators wearing face masks and white jumpsuits
found the bodies of two women and the decaying remains of others
Wednesday in a ramshackle wooden house a block from prestigious
Vassar College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   They charged Kendall Francois, a 27-year-old unemployed school
aide who lived in the house, with strangling one of the women to
death and said they thought he was responsible for killing seven
others, most of them prostitutes, who have been missing for up to
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reason to believe that ultimately eight bodies will be
recovered from our search of the house based on our conversations
with him,'' said William Grady, the district attorney of Dutchess
County.
</P>
<P>
   The house, where Francois lived with his parents and sister, is
on a quiet tree-shaded block of gracious Victorians and doctors'
offices one block from Vassar. But it is also two blocks in the
opposite direction from a stretch of Poughkeepsie's Main Street
used by prostitutes, including some who were drug users, to solicit
customers.
</P>
<P>
   What made the case particularly eerie is that Francois' parents
and sister continued to live in the house where the bodies and the
remains of the women were found, yet law enforcement officials said
they were surprised when told of the murders. Neighbors and a
postal carrier said the stench coming from the disheveled and dirty
house had long been unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   Late into the evening, investigators continued to search the
Francois house for remains of the other women. Grady said at least
one body was found in the basement, but he would not disclose other
locations in the house that he said Francois had mentioned when
interrogated about the missing women Tuesday night and Wednesday.
Grady said there was no indication that the women had been
dismembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had something to say about all of the missing women,''
Grady said of the suspect. Grady would not say what led police to
Francois, although other law enforcement officials said Francois
was jailed for 15 days last winter on charges of assaulting a
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the latest in a sequence of serial murders of street
prostitutes during the last two decades. It bore strong
similarities to the case of Joel Rifkin, who confessed to killing
17 women he said were prostitutes in Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The string of missing women has unsettled both the city of
Poughkeepsie, a Hudson River manufacturing center with 28,844
residents, and the surrounding township, also named Poughkeepsie,
which has a population of 40,143 people. The economic vitality of
the area has been battered by the closing of a nearby IBM plant and
the flight of business from the city's downtown. Some relatives of
the victims complained that until last week, when a task force
focusing on the disappearance was formed, police were not paying
enough attention to the disappearances because the victims were
prostitutes and drug users.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been this much press before, I don't think it
would have gone this far,'' said James DeSalvo, the brother of
Kathleen Hurley, who vanished in January of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The only body identified Wednesday was that of Catina Newmaster,
a 25-year-old drug user who had tattoos on her right hip and right
arm and a nose ring. She was last seen on Aug. 25 by a boyfriend in
nearby Pleasant Valley, who found out that she had traveled to
Poughkeepsie.
</P>
<P>
   The first woman reported missing was Wendy Meyers, 30, who was
last seen on Oct. 24, 1996, at a motel in nearby Highland. Her
disappearance was followed by that of Catherine Marsh, 31, who was
pregnant, on Nov. 12, 1996; Gina Barone, 29, on Dec. 9, 1996; Ms.
Hurley on Jan. 12, 1997; Michelle Eason, 27, on Oct. 9, 1997; Mary
Healey Giaccone, 29, on Nov. 13, 1997; Sandra Jean French, 51, on
June 11, 1998, and Ms. Newmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Although some lived in the rural towns outside urban
Poughkeepsie, four of the women were last seen in the meaner
stretches of the city of Poughkeepsie. All except Ms. Hurley had
been arrested on prostitution charges. Seven of the women were
white; one was black. Francois is black, but Grady and other law
enforcement officials said the kilings did not appear to be
racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Francois, who is 6 feet 4 inches tall and weighs more than 300
pounds, was arraigned Wednesday morning before Judge Ira Pergament
of the Town of Poughkeepsie court and charged with one count of
second-degree murder. He pleaded not guilty and was assigned a
lawyer from the state's Capital Defender Office, which handles
cases that might result in a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Francois was born in Poughkeepsie, graduated from high school in
the Arlington School District, made up of the town of Poughkeepsie
and seven other towns, and served in the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   He began working at the Arlington Middle School in 1994 as an
occasional custodial worker, and then from April 1996 to January
1997 he worked full time as a hall monitor at Arlington, making
sure halls and the cafeteria were not unruly. When he left, he told
school administrators that he was going to work for the Anderson
School, a school for mentally retarded and other developmentally
disabled children in Staatsburg, a 20-minute ride from the city of
Poughkeepsie. Officials of that school would not confirm or deny
that he had worked there.
</P>
</TEXT>
