<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS &LR;      09-02 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
For the better part of a week, the Comets fought the Phoenix
Mercury with their backs pinned firmly against the proverbial wall
in defense of a WNBA championship.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, they are back-to-back champions of the 2-year-old league.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' voyage from the brink of elimination to repeat
winners was completed Tuesday night with an 80-71 triumph over the
Mercury in the decisive game of the best-of-three WNBA Championship
Series before a sellout crowd of 16,285 at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, a blizzard of confetti showered the arena
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper stood in the midst of the frenzied atmosphere
receiving her second consecutive finals Most Valuable Player
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson and Sheryl Swoopes hugged. Swoopes grabbed
year-old son Jordan Eric Jackson from her husband and held him
aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Perrot ambled from center court to one corner of the arena
and back shouting and signaling to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cooper and Swoopes, who have endured an uneasy truce
throughout the summer of '98, exchanged pleasantries, if only
briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Their teammates found a variety of methods to celebrate amid
blaring music and the crescendo of noise from an adoring public,
friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year Van Chancellor, his '98 WNBA championship cap
tugged firmly down on his head, sought out Cooper for an embrace of
thanks, friendship, admiration and congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy this one more than last year's
(championship) because Saturday I thought we were dead in the water
(in Game 2),'' Chancellor said Wednesday. ``There was no way we
were supposed to win that one. It was a miracle, simply a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Tuesday, man, what a ballgame. It had everything. Boy, did
we play defense when we needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   But where does this dynasty-in-the-making go from here?
</P>
<P>
   Will this team nobody could beat simply beat itself through a
postseason fit of petty jealousies and rage that quietly ripped at
its heart through a record 27-3 regular season?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely important that we try to keep this team
together,'' said Perrot, the 5-5 heroine who played her best game
of the series Tuesday. ``But some people have to make decisions to
better themselves. For me, personally, I hope this team can stay
together. I think we have great talent, and when we all put our
talent and character together, we're a winning team all around.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the Comets become free agents once an elite team of
WNBA players competes in a foreign exhibition tour that spans
September and October.
</P>
<P>
   Among the eight are Cooper, named league MVP for the second year
in a row, and fellow All-WNBA first-teamers Swoopes and Tina
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever feud existed between Cooper and Swoopes was thought to
have been squelched in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   They complemented each other on the court thereafter as the
Comets tied a franchise record for victories at the start of a
season (five in a row) and later put together a WNBA-record 15-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   But the day after that string was snapped by Cleveland 74-71 in
overtime at Compaq Center, Cooper let loose in the locker room,
offering a fiery climax to the Comets' 77-61 victory over
Sacramento. She fumed over what she perceived to be a team-wide
lapse into individualistic play. She ranted about Chancellor's
inability to control a team on the brink of splintering.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time Coach of the Year was able to grab the reins and
get the Comets back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The problems between Swoopes and Cooper aren't the only ones
with which Chancellor has had to cope.
</P>
<P>
   A practice session before the Comets faced the Charlotte Sting
in the first round of the playoffs had to be halted when another
two players were at odds over assignments. That clash simmered for
two days but was handled gently though deliberately by Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the night the Comets wrapped up their second straight
WNBA title, according to a source who requested anonymity, there
was at least one major player ``who was not happy'' about her role.
</P>
<P>
   It has become quite evident the only team capable of beating the
Comets may be the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor is amazed at the level of success the two-time
champions can achieve when petty jealousies, envy, ego and greed
are set aside for the good of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt that we need to keep this team
together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the issue of a team filled with turmoil, Chancellor
said, ``It's been my experience that when things are going good,
they're not going as good as you think. When things are going bad,
they're never as bad as you might seem to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what next year will bring. In eight months' time,
a lot of things can change. My whole thought process is, let's go a
few months, see how things look three or four months from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being frank about it, it's awfully difficult to see right
here, right after the season's over with, just what is next year
about.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to argue about what the Comets have
accomplished, problems or no.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, this year's been a struggle,'' said Chancellor.
``But as I reflect on it, a lot of parties involved in this
situation had to give for the good of the team. And as you see that
championship unfold, it makes it worthwhile. From my point of view,
I'd love to try it again this way next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I suffered through that much. We won 30
games overall. Any way you slice that up, it ain't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot has a philosophy about 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never predict the future,'' she said. ``But I have about
eight more fingers with no rings on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
