<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS' KIN HAVE BITTERSWEET MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-WOMEN-SLAIN) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ In the fall of 1996, Catherine Marsh, a
longtime prostitute and drug addict, repeatedly begged her mother
to let her come home.
</P>
<P>
   She had recently turned her life around, her mother said
Wednesday, completing a rehabilitation program, reuniting with her
two children and pursuing a college degree. Still, her mother,
Marguerite Marsh, was hesitant. ``I was afraid if she came up here
she was going to continue with her habit,'' Mrs. Marsh said. ``But
she kept calling and calling and finally I said, `OK, come.' That
was the last I ever heard from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they believed that Ms. Marsh, 29, was one of eight
women _ all involved with drugs and most with prostitution _ who
were murdered here by Kendall Francois in the last 22 months. On
Wednesday, after the arrest of Francois, 27, in the strangling
death of one of the women, police began removing bodies from the
home he lived in with his family on a stately, tree-lined street
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm praying she's not in there,'' Mrs. Marsh, her voice thin
and strained, said of her daughter in a telephone interview from
her home in Schenectady. ``Cathy was a beautiful, gifted woman. She
loved music and she was very, very bright. But she was caught up in
a powerful illness, addiction, and it took her places she didn't
want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The first body to be removed from Francois' home was identified
as that of Catina Newmaster, 25, who was last seen on Aug. 25,
police said. Her boyfriend, Christopher Briggs, said Wednesday that
he was trying to keep his mind focused on the woman he loved, a
mother of five who adored flowers and dreamed of being near the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to straighten out her life and be with her kids,''
he said. ``But Catina had a very bad drug problem. She cried on my
shoulder about it a lot. People in Dutchess County have said the
cops shouldn't have even bothered looking for these women, that it
was just one less crackhead or prostitute on the street. But these
people all had families, and they shouldn't be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the missing women have also criticized the news
media for concentrating on the dark side of the women's lives. Each
said the missing women had close ties to their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women, Sandra Jean French, 51, who was once a horse
trainer, was busy buying baby clothes in June _ for a granddaughter
who was born only a few days after she disappeared that same month.
She would call her expectant daughter, Heidi Cramer, at least three
times a day and bring meals over regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cramer said she had been realistic about her mother's
longtime struggle with drugs but never imagined it would end with
her death. Now she must tell her younger sister Nicole exactly what
police believe happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in shock,'' Ms. Cramer said of her sister. ``One minute
she's talking to her mother and it's, `OK Nicole, I love you, I'll
see you soon.' The next minute her mother's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Patricia Barone will be searching for an answer to
satisfy her granddaughter, whom she has been raising since her
daughter, Gina Barone, 25, was reported missing in 1996. An addict
since the age of 12, Ms. Barone never had a chance to develop much
individual talent or skill, her mother said. But, when sober, she
was a dedicated mother to her daughter, Nikki, now 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, you know, it was, `Where's my mommy?''' Mrs.
Barone said of her granddaughter's pleas. ``And I'd tell her, `Your
mommy doesn't feel well. Mommy went away for a while.' Then we'd
say, `We're looking for your mommy and we can't find her.' Now it's
going to be, `Your mommy's not coming back.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
