</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TOMS-RIVER-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY OF CELEBRATION IN MANHATTAN FOR TEAM FROM TOMS RIVER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the calendar, at least, Wednesday should have been
a normal day in school for a group of 12-year-olds from Toms River,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the boys of the Toms River East baseball team,
which won the Little League World Series Championship on Saturday,
were once again basking in the glow of celebrity, as the talk show
hostess Rosie O'Donnell showered them with gifts and the Official
All Star Cafe rolled out the feast of choice among many young
champions: burgers, fries and ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, they met Yogi Berra at the site of his
new museum, which is to open next month on the campus of Montclair
State University in Montclair, N.J..
</P>
<P>
   In fact, precious little has been normal for the boys since the
world first began paying attention to them, only a week ago.
Tuesday morning, on the first day of school, cameras followed their
every step. After school, the team boarded a bus for Yankee
Stadium, where they frolicked in George Steinbrenner's private
suite and took the field with the home team. There were even
autographs from Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   For the boys, all the attention has been the stuff of dreams.
But for their parents, well, they say it is time that life returns
to the way it was before their sons became heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants a piece of them right now; it's crazy, like
you wouldn't believe,'' said George Gardner, the father of the
team's third baseman, Gabe Gardner. Since the team won the
championship, the Gardners' telephone has rung incessantly and
there has been little time for things his family craves the most:
sleep and a quiet dinner away from all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   When Lucy Cardone, a first-grade teacher in Toms River, returned
to the classroom on Tuesday, her new students had only one thing on
their minds: her son Chris, a reserve outfielder who smacked two
home runs in the championship game, including one in the final
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-grade girls made a special trip to her classroom to ask
about the Toms River East boys. ``It's overwhelming,'' she said.
``On the one hand, my husband and I want to do as much as possible
to see that Chris has a chance to savor this moment. But I don't
want the situation to become so out of control that he's let down
when it finally ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cardone said that she and her son have had long talks about
what would happen when the cameras stop flashing. ``I've told him
that he should see what he and the team accomplished as a
once-in-a-lifetime thrill, not his life's greatest
accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys appeared to be handling their newfound fame with a
poise well beyond their years, though a few conceded to being a
little tired. ``Signing all the autographs kind of makes my hand
hurt,'' said Joey Franceschini, the smallest player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gaynor, the team's manager and the father of Casey Gaynor,
a team pitcher, said the trip to New York would probably be the
team's last big adventure, although another hometown parade is
planned for this weekend. ``We've told them that school is the No.
1 priority now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fame has brought at least one unusual moment. The first stop
Wednesday was the set of the ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show'' at the
NBC studios in Rockefeller Center, where they joined Cindy Crawford
in taping Monday's season premiere.
</P>
<P>
   But the boys seemed less interested in the supermodel than in
their moment with Ms. O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   First, Ms. O'Donnell joked with the boys. ``Are you like rock
stars at school?'' she asked Chris Cardone. Smiling shyly, he
replied, ``Nah.'' Trying to elicit a little more response, she
said, ``I hear all the girls want to marry you.'' This time Chris
had more to say: ``There was one girl with a sign when we got home.
But she was 7.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys' biggest thrill came when Ms. O'Donnell gave them a few
tokens of thanks: personalized championship baseball jackets, a
shopping cart full of new bats and balls, and a promise that she
would foot the bill for a new batting cage. That will come in
handy, as the league prepares to try out a practice facility that
will allow the boys to play baseball year-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a real cool lady,'' said Gabe Gardner, loading his arms
with piles of gifts, including a Rosie doll that Ms. O'Donnell
autographed for his mom. ``This was the best.''
</P>
<P>
   After the show, the team was off to a private party at the
Official All Star Cafe in Times Square, where the actor Stephen
Baldwin, a fan and a former Little League catcher, dropped by to
say hello. For a couple dozen boys and girls having lunch at the
cafe Wednesday, the team's visit was an unexpected surprise.
Grabbing napkins and any other piece of loose paper they could
find, the children lined the entryway of the reception area set up
for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dreamed of signing autographs in the pros,'' said Gabe
Gardner, who was surrounded by a group of autograph-seeking
8-year-olds from upstate New York. ``I never dreamed of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the parents who were being forced by sons and daughters to
wait as they got autographs, Bob Fisher, father of pitcher Scott
Fisher, looked on with a mix of excitement and disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' Fisher said, ``for other kids to see them
and to appreciate the accomplishment of being a group of ordinary
kids who worked hard and realized their dream. But for us, it's
also important for them to start getting back to a more routine
life. We're not complaining, but this pace can't continue. They're
just kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
