<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ELECTION-COMMISSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ELECTION COMMISSION GOES ASTRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 3:
</P>
<P>
   With limited resources and no shortage of serious campaign
finance abuses to pursue, the Federal Election Commission has made
the peculiar decision to target Forbes magazine for publishing
columns written by Steve Forbes while campaigning for president in
1996. In doing so, the commission has managed to trespass on the
First Amendment and call into question the agency's sense of
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit filed by the Election Commission last week contends
that the columns, which were published while Forbes was running for
the Republican presidential nomination, amounted to an illegal
corporate campaign contribution by Forbes magazine. The panel
values the columns at $94,900.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, news articles and commentary appearing in newspapers
and magazines are exempt from scrutiny under the Federal Election
Campaign Act. But under a constitutionally dubious provision such
articles may be deemed a ``contribution'' if the outlet is
controlled by the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to prevent candidates like Forbes, who own press
vehicles, from using them to gain unfair electoral advantage. The
trouble is, it ignores a basic First Amendment principle. The
government has no business trying to dictate the contents of a
magazine by potentially subjecting editorial decisions to civil
sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
