<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHANGING BANK REGULATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 3:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Banking Committee today takes up the financial
services regulatory reform bill, which passed the House earlier
this year by a one-vote margin. It is good legislation that sets up
fair rules as banks, insurers and brokerage firms expand into each
other's business. But two provisions in the House-passed bill need
to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The first provision concerns who will regulate banking companies
that choose to engage in expanded activities in insurance and
securities. The House bill would restrict that to the Federal
Reserve, while the Treasury Department is pressing for an amendment
that would also allow banks to structure their activities in such a
way as to allow the Comptroller of the Currency _ an official in
the Treasury Department _ to be their chief regulator.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the country has been well served by what amounted
to competing regulatory jurisdictions, a flexible arrangement that
has given the country the strongest banking system in the world.
There is no reason to cut out the comptroller now.
</P>
<P>
   The other provision concerns mutual insurance companies, which
are owned by their policyholders. Some states have enacted
legislation that allows such companies to be taken from their
policyholders without adequate compensation, while others,
including New York, have wisely rejected such legislation. But the
House-passed bill would effectively override laws such as the one
in New York. That provision should be deleted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-98 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
