<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL SUMMATION  
 BUILDING ON A STAMP 
SKATING COMMISSIONER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with JANE H. LII   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He spent a lifetime arguing some of the toughest cases before
some of the most demanding tribunals in the land, but Arthur Liman,
who died in July 1997, has presented his final summation as a
posthumous author.
</P>
<P>
   His new book, ``Lawyer: A Life of Counsel and Controversy''
(Public Affairs), chronicles his work as a partner at Paul, Weiss,
Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison; his investigation of the 1971 Attica
prison uprising, and his most public role, the face of the
prosecution in the Iran-Contra hearings.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Ellen Liman, said Wednesday that her husband had begun
writing the book shortly after bladder cancer was diagnosed in
1996. He finished the manuscript _ scribbled on yellow legal pads _
just months before he died.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Liman said the book was intended to be both an heirloom for
future generations of Limans and an inspiration to law school
students who may be interested in straddling the world of public
and private law. Starting next week, in fact, each incoming
first-year class at Liman's alma mater, Yale Law School, will
receive a free copy of the book as part of its orientation, Mrs.
Liman said.
</P>
<P>
   But the students won't be the first to get copies. A couple of
weeks ago, while vacationing on Martha's Vineyard, Mrs. Liman
presented a copy to Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton, members of the
Class of '73.
</P>
<P>
   The Empire State Is Nationalized
</P>
<P>
   It has been the backdrop for movies, out-of-focus tourist photos
and even a terrorist attack. Now, the Empire State Building has
something that few other private buildings can claim: its own
postage stamp.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service introduced an embossed likeness of the
landmark Wednesday as one of 15 stamps saluting the 1930s. The
series includes the Golden Gate Bridge, Jesse Owens, ``Gone With
the Wind'' and the game Monopoly. The stamps go on sale next
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's perfect,'' said Lydia Ruth, a spokeswoman for the
building. ``No people, no King Kong, just the building.''
</P>
<P>
   A Commissioner Is Staying In-Line
</P>
<P>
   It's barely a minute of film, but there he is, the no-nonsense
police commissioner of New York City, Howard Safir, wearing navy
blue shorts and a navy blue NYPD T-shirt, rolling confidently
toward the camera on a pair of in-line skates. He's wearing a
helmet, too.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not alone. His skating buddies are among the stars of a
documentary film called ``It's All Good,'' a 90-minute feature its
promoters call a look at the ``underground world of aggressive
in-line skating.''
</P>
<P>
   In the segment featuring Safir, skaters swoop down sidewalks and
do daring loops off the handrails outside a large Manhattan
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty impressive,'' the commissioner says, while pointing out
that wreaking pedestrian havoc on private property poses public
safety problems at least and a law-and-order problem at worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too sure the New York Mercantile Exchange would be too
crazy about it,'' he tells one young man sizing up the building's
stone steps for an obstacle course.
</P>
<P>
   Is Safir out of character? Not really, said his spokeswoman,
Marilyn Mode. She said the commissioner made an appearance at the
request of the filmmaker, David Hoffman, who is an old friend and
whose company, Varied Productions, is still seeking a distributor.
Safir has been skating since 1992, when his wife gave him a pair of
skates for his 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Although police departments elsewhere have skating units, Ms.
Mode said there were no plans to put New York's Finest on skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had Rollerblades in Central Park and the perpetrator
runs on the grass, it's hard to catch him,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
