<SLUG> BC-NY-STUCK-SHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND TOWN RUSHES TO SAVE TALL SHIP CAUGHT IN MUD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLEN COVE, N.Y. _ Volunteers rushed Wednesday to the rescue of
the Regina Maris, a 90-year-old three-masted barkentine that became
stuck in the mud at low tide and later filled with water, only a
few boat lengths away from her new home here.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Glen Cove were not about to let the 140-foot-long
ship _ a survivor of nearly a century of adventure on the high
seas, including the smuggling of Jewish refugees out of Europe
during World War II _ break apart in a murky tidal pool.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began when the ship's keel settled into the mud at
the end of Glen Cove Creek and the ship tilted on her side with her
masts at a 35-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to have some problems with the old ship, but not
quite this soon,'' said Mayor Thomas Suozzi, who only last week
welcomed the Regina Maris to Hempstead Harbor and declared her the
symbol of his efforts to revitalize the city's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   The ship foundered Tuesday afternoon as she was towed about a
mile to the marina, where she was to be permanently tied up near
the Steam Boat Landing Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Today, heavy pumps spewed hundreds of gallons of water from the
vessel, which had been unable to right herself and become flooded
at high tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``She almost made it, but got caught in shallow water when the
tide ran out,'' Suozzi said.
</P>
<P>
   The Regina Maris was towed to Glen Cove last week from
Greenport, 90 nautical miles east of here on the North Fork of Long
Island. Officials of Greenport had threatened to take the Regina
Maris out to sea and scuttle her because, they said, the town could
no longer afford to keep her. They said the aging vessel and her
rotting rigging presented a public safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the ship was in trouble brought hundreds of curious
onlookers to the marina. ``She's a beautiful ship, even when she's
stuck in the mud,'' said Samuel Schwartz, who watched with his
11-year-old son, Michael.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
