<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-PORN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS SEIZE COMPUTERS, SOFTWARE IN CHILD PORN PROBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Federal agents investigating an international
child pornography ring raided a suburban home, seizing computers
and software, in one of a series of search warrants served across
the nation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No arrests were made Wednesday when 10 U.S. Customs Service
agents, backed up by members of a child-abuse task force, searched
the Canoga Park home about 7 p.m. Tuesday, said Customs Service
spokesman Mike Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   With the warrant still under seal, Fleming said he could not
reveal the location of the house or other details, including the
nature of the evidence seized.
</P>
<P>
   The federal warrant was one of 32 served in 22 states in two
days, resulting in four arrests, said Customs Service spokesman
Bill Anthony. In all, investigators in 14 countries have identified
more than 100 suspects, most in the United States, who allegedly
use the Internet to trade child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who exploit children in this way think they can
hide in cyberspace,'' Customs Service Commissioner Raymond W. Kelly
said in a statement. ``They are wrong. We will find them and bring
them to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the speed of Internet communications, the searches in the
United States were done at the same time so the suspects could not
tip each other off, Anthony said. Investigators in other countries
also coordinated their raids, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unprecedented international scope of this investigation is
immensely significant in terms of the number of countries involved
and the level of law enforcement cooperation,'' Fleming said. ``If
you transmit, via the Internet, images of child pornography from
one country into the United States, then that's a federal crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation grew out of a similar case in 1996 in which
the Customs Service identified an international child porn ring
with members in the United States, England, Australia, Canada and
Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Arrests of British suspects in the last year led police in that
country to an even larger and more sophisticated international ring
whose members had to meet certain guidelines to join, such as
possessing multiple images of child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   In Canoga Park, agents took two computers and floppy disks.
Fleming said the evidence would be analyzed and that it was too
early to say if any arrests would follow.
</P>
<P>
   The only other raid in California was in National City, in San
Diego County, where agents took computer gear and files from the
home of a 38-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   The Customs Service, enforcing laws against trading child
pornography across the U.S. border, opened its first investigation
into the illicit trade on the Internet in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months ending July 31, agents have arrested 183
people on charges relating to possessing, manufacturing or
distributing child pornography, eventually resulting in convictions
against 189 people.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
