<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DOWN TIGERS, 5-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ This is the way it's supposed to work.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitcher goes six, seven innings. The setup reliever
holds the lead. The All-Star closer finishes it off.
</P>
<P>
   Simple. Effective. Painless ... especially for the manager.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of pitching the Rangers are hoping for as they
chase the Anaheim Angels for the American League West title, and
they got it last night in a 5-3 victory against the Detroit Tigers
at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Helling showed why manager Johnny Oates is considering
adjusting other starters' schedules and allowing him to pitch every
fifth day down the stretch. Helling survived some early control
troubles to pitch 6 1/3 tough innings for his club-leading 17th
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy who has been the workhorse for us all year,''
Oates said. ``He's pitched innings, he's struck people out and he's
won some big ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what's going through Oates' mind when he thinks about his
rotation for the final four weeks of the season. As the rotation
stands now, Helling would not pitch against the Angels in the
Rangers' two remaining series with the division leaders later this
month. Oates could change that by bumping both John Burkett and
Esteban Loiaza by just one day in the next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Oates would also like to see more of Xavier Hernandez, his most
dependable setup reliever, and All-Star closer John Wetteland.
Those two finished off the Tigers after Helling had thrown 133
pitches, and the Rangers remained 2 1/2 games behind the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to keep battling and keep winning games,'' said
Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who broke open the game with a
two-run home run off Tigers starter Brian Moehler in the sixth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd certainly like to have done better this road trip (4-3),
but there's nothing we can do about it now,'' Oates said. ``We're
still in striking distance. We go home for six days; we just need
to win. We need to get people out and continue to score runs. You
can make up two games in a hurry if you're playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allowed one unearned run in 1 2/3 innings, and while
other Rangers middle relievers have had their problems lately, he
has a 1.26 earned-run average in his past 27 outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel all right,'' Hernandez said. ``I've been keeping the
ball down for the most part and making them hit my pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland has been excellent all year, and last night he
recorded his 39th save, second-most in a season in Rangers history.
It was also the 250th save of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitching was pretty good tonight,'' Rodriguez said.
``That's what we need from the starter, six-seven good innings and
the bullpen can take care of the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling allowed six hits and walked four but survived because
the Tigers were 1-for-9 against him with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first inning or two my control wasn't pinpoint, but I made
enough good pitches to get out of some jams,'' said Helling, who
walked four of the first 15 batters he faced. ``This is one of the
flattest mounds in the leagues, and a high fastball pitcher like
me, it takes a little longer to get the ball down. But once I made
the adjustment, everything was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tigers manager Larry Parrish: ``It seems like a couple of
times, when he needed it, he had a little better fastball. He
pitches a little like Palmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish was referring to Jim Palmer, a three-time Cy Young Award
winner who is now in the Hall of Fame. That's an impressive
comparison for a guy who is in his first full year as a starter.
But Helling has come fast this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes back to getting a chance,'' Helling said. ``Who's
to say what I could have done a few years ago if I had gotten the
chance. You have to give Johnny and (general manager) Doug Melvin
credit for giving me that chance this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The chances apparently will increase as the Rangers head down
the stretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
