<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUZUKI SPLENDID, BUT MARINER BULLPEN BLOWS LEAD, GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mac Suzuki barely had time to put on his warmup jacket
Wednesday night before the seventh-inning lead he handed the
Mariner bullpen disappeared into the screen above the Green Monster
at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches. One swing. Two runs. Tie game.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Suzuki's splendid regular-season debut against
the Boston Red Sox produced a kiss-your-sister feeling as the
Mariners ended their nine-game road trip with a 7-3 loss before
25,813 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Benjamin smacked a game-tying homer off right-hander Jose
Paniagua on a 1-and-0 pitch to cap a three-run seventh inning and
pull the American League wild-card-leading Red Sox even.
</P>
<P>
   They won it in the ninth on Nomar Garciaparra's grand slam off
Bobby Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's infield single off third baseman Russ Davis' glove
led off the inning. A sacrifice bunt and two walks preceded
Garciaparra's 30th homer of the season, coming on the first pitch
Ayala fed him.
</P>
<P>
   The towering drive would have won the game regardless because
there was one out. But the slam added some gusto to the Red Sox's
42nd come-from-behind win this season _ the second time they beat
Seattle with a ninth-inning slam.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn did it on April 10 when Boston scored seven
ninth-inning runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see what happened with their side and our side,''
manager Lou Piniella said. ``It was a parallel for both teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are headed to the playoffs and the Mariners are not.
</P>
<P>
   Without a playoff berth to chase in September, the Mariners are
using the month to examine potential roster players for next
season. Suzuki warranted a look-see after finishing the Class AAA
season at Tacoma with a 2-1 record and 1.55 ERA in six August
starts.
</P>
<P>
   What worked in the minors also was working Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He held the Red Sox to two hits over six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed a lot of poise out there and a good arm,'' Piniella
said. ``He is vastly improved and it was exciting watching him
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander wobbled in the first inning, when he walked two
batters with two outs. He struggled again in the second when the
Red Sox put two more runners on base and again in the third when
ex-Mariner Darren Bragg led off with a double to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   But Suzuki retired the next three batters and by the time he
pitched from the stretch again, the Mariners led, 3-0. They should
have been ahead by many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances to score tons of runs,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners accumulated 15 hits, but stranded 14 runners.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had six hits and stranded eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke,'' said hitting coach Jesse Barfield of the missed
scoring opportunities. ``I've said it all year and I'll say it
again, you have to beat guys by going to the opposite field. You
can't hook (pull) the ball all the time, especially against good
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's put 11 runners in scoring position. Two scored.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner produced the other run with a titanic solo homer to
left-center in the sixth inning. The ball cleared the wall, the
screen, the street and landed on the roof of a building.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle led 2-0 at the time and made it a three-run lead in the
seventh when they loaded the bases with none out but had to settle
for one run.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki went to work in the seventh inning with a string of 12
straight outs. Then he walked Mike Stanley, got an out, and
surrendered a run-scoring double to pinch-hitting Mandy Romero.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, who has been solid as a setup reliever since being
promoted from Tacoma last month, twice shook off signs from catcher
John Marzano. Paniagua threw Benjamin a fastball and yanked his
head to watch the flight of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fault for letting (Paniagua) shake me off,'' Marzano
said. ``I usually don't let a young pitcher do that, but this time
I did. I wanted to throw (Benjamin) a slider. Then I called for a
splitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only pitch Benjamin can hit out is a four-seam fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua threw a four-seamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as he threw it, I thought `Oh, no,''' Marzano said.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki threw what Marzano wanted and carried a nifty two-hitter
into the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is I went 61/3 innings,'' Suzuki said. ``The
bad thing is I walked the leadoff guy in the seventh. Then
everything got screwed up. I shouldn't have walked that guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
